var P_HTM = [];
P_HTM[1]="*Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa* **";
P_HTM[2]="*Majjhimanikāyo* **";
P_HTM[3]="*Uparipaṇṇāsapāḷi* **";
P_HTM[4]="*5. Saḷāyatanavaggo* **";
P_HTM[5]="*101. Devadahasutta**At Devadaha*";
P_HTM[6]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[7]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati devadahaṃ nāma sakyānaṃ nigamo.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans, near the Sakyan town named Devadaha.*";
P_HTM[8]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[9]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[10]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[11]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[12]="*“santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**“Mendicants, there are some ascetics and brahmins who have this doctrine and view:*";
P_HTM[13]="*‘yaṃ kiñcāyaṃ purisapuggalo paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā, sabbaṃ taṃ pubbekatahetu.**‘Everything this individual experiences—pleasurable, painful, or neutral—is because of past deeds.*";
P_HTM[14]="*Iti purāṇānaṃ kammānaṃ tapasā byantībhāvā, navānaṃ kammānaṃ akaraṇā, āyatiṃ anavassavo;**So, due to eliminating past deeds by mortification, and not doing any new deeds, there’s nothing to come up in the future.*";
P_HTM[15]="*āyatiṃ anavassavā kammakkhayo; kammakkhayā dukkhakkhayo; dukkhakkhayā vedanākkhayo; vedanākkhayā sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**With nothing to come up in the future, deeds end. With the ending of deeds, suffering ends. With the ending of suffering, feeling ends. And with the ending of feeling, all suffering will have been worn away.’*";
P_HTM[16]="*Evaṃvādino, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhā.**Such is the doctrine of the Jain ascetics.*";
P_HTM[17]="*Evaṃvādāhaṃ, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhe upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:**I’ve gone up to the Jain ascetics who say this and said,*";
P_HTM[18]="*‘saccaṃ kira tumhe, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino—**‘Is it really true that this is the venerables’ view?’*";
P_HTM[19]="*yaṃ kiñcāyaṃ purisapuggalo paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā, sabbaṃ taṃ pubbekatahetu.* **";
P_HTM[20]="*Iti purāṇānaṃ kammānaṃ tapasā byantībhāvā, navānaṃ kammānaṃ akaraṇā, āyatiṃ anavassavo;* **";
P_HTM[21]="*āyatiṃ anavassavā kammakkhayo; kammakkhayā dukkhakkhayo; dukkhakkhayā vedanākkhayo; vedanākkhayā sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti?* **";
P_HTM[22]="*Te ca me, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhā evaṃ puṭṭhā ‘āmā’ti paṭijānanti.**They admitted that it is.*";
P_HTM[23]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**I said to them,*";
P_HTM[24]="*‘kiṃ pana tumhe, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, jānātha—**‘But reverends, do you know*";
P_HTM[25]="*ahuvamheva mayaṃ pubbe, na nāhuvamhā’ti?**for sure that you existed in the past, and it is not the case that you didn’t exist?’*";
P_HTM[26]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No we don’t, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[27]="*‘Kiṃ pana tumhe, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, jānātha—**‘But reverends, do you know*";
P_HTM[28]="*akaramheva mayaṃ pubbe pāpakammaṃ, na nākaramhā’ti?**for sure that you did bad deeds in the past?’*";
P_HTM[29]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No we don’t, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[30]="*‘Kiṃ pana tumhe, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, jānātha—**‘But reverends, do you know*";
P_HTM[31]="*evarūpaṃ vā evarūpaṃ vā pāpakammaṃ akaramhā’ti?**that you did such and such bad deeds?’*";
P_HTM[32]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No we don’t, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[33]="*‘Kiṃ pana tumhe, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, jānātha—**‘But reverends, do you know*";
P_HTM[34]="*ettakaṃ vā dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ, ettakaṃ vā dukkhaṃ nijjīretabbaṃ, ettakamhi vā dukkhe nijjiṇṇe sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti?**that so much suffering has already been worn away? Or that so much suffering still remains to be worn away? Or that when so much suffering is worn away all suffering will have been worn away?’*";
P_HTM[35]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No we don’t, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[36]="*‘Kiṃ pana tumhe, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, jānātha—**‘But reverends, do you know*";
P_HTM[37]="*diṭṭheva dhamme akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānaṃ, kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadan’ti?**about giving up unskillful qualities in the present life and embracing skillful qualities?’*";
P_HTM[38]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No we don’t, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[39]="*‘Iti kira tumhe, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, na jānātha—**‘So it seems that you don’t know any of these things.*";
P_HTM[40]="*ahuvamheva mayaṃ pubbe, na nāhuvamhāti, na jānātha—* **";
P_HTM[41]="*akaramheva mayaṃ pubbe pāpakammaṃ, na nākaramhāti, na jānātha—* **";
P_HTM[42]="*evarūpaṃ vā evarūpaṃ vā pāpakammaṃ akaramhāti, na jānātha—* **";
P_HTM[43]="*ettakaṃ vā dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ, ettakaṃ vā dukkhaṃ nijjīretabbaṃ, ettakamhi vā dukkhe nijjiṇṇe sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatīti, na jānātha—* **";
P_HTM[44]="*diṭṭheva dhamme akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānaṃ, kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[45]="*evaṃ sante āyasmantānaṃ nigaṇṭhānaṃ na kallamassa veyyākaraṇāya:**In that case, it’s not appropriate for the Jain venerables to declare this.*";
P_HTM[46]="*“yaṃ kiñcāyaṃ purisapuggalo paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā, sabbaṃ taṃ pubbekatahetu.* **";
P_HTM[47]="*Iti purāṇānaṃ kammānaṃ tapasā byantībhāvā, navānaṃ kammānaṃ akaraṇā, āyatiṃ anavassavo;* **";
P_HTM[48]="*āyatiṃ anavassavā kammakkhayo; kammakkhayā dukkhakkhayo; dukkhakkhayā vedanākkhayo; vedanākkhayā sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[49]="*Sace pana tumhe, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, jāneyyātha—**Now, supposing you did know these things.*";
P_HTM[50]="*ahuvamheva mayaṃ pubbe, na nāhuvamhāti, jāneyyātha—* **";
P_HTM[51]="*akaramheva mayaṃ pubbe pāpakammaṃ, na nākaramhāti, jāneyyātha—* **";
P_HTM[52]="*evarūpaṃ vā evarūpaṃ vā pāpakammaṃ akaramhāti, jāneyyātha—* **";
P_HTM[53]="*ettakaṃ vā dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ, ettakaṃ vā dukkhaṃ nijjīretabbaṃ, ettakamhi vā dukkhe nijjiṇṇe sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatīti, jāneyyātha—* **";
P_HTM[54]="*diṭṭheva dhamme akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānaṃ, kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[55]="*evaṃ sante āyasmantānaṃ nigaṇṭhānaṃ kallamassa veyyākaraṇāya:**In that case, it would be appropriate for the Jain venerables to declare this.*";
P_HTM[56]="*“yaṃ kiñcāyaṃ purisapuggalo paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā, sabbaṃ taṃ pubbekatahetu.* **";
P_HTM[57]="*Iti purāṇānaṃ kammānaṃ tapasā byantībhāvā, navānaṃ kammānaṃ akaraṇā, āyatiṃ anavassavo;* **";
P_HTM[58]="*āyatiṃ anavassavā kammakkhayo; kammakkhayā dukkhakkhayo; dukkhakkhayā vedanākkhayo; vedanākkhayā sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[59]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, puriso sallena viddho assa savisena gāḷhūpalepanena;**Suppose a man was struck by an arrow thickly smeared with poison,*";
P_HTM[60]="*so sallassapi vedhanahetu dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyeyya.**causing painful feelings, sharp and severe.*";
P_HTM[61]="*Tassa mittāmaccā ñātisālohitā bhisakkaṃ sallakattaṃ upaṭṭhāpeyyuṃ.**Their friends and colleagues, relatives and kin would get a field surgeon to treat them.*";
P_HTM[62]="*Tassa so bhisakko sallakatto satthena vaṇamukhaṃ parikanteyya;**The surgeon would cut open the wound with a scalpel,*";
P_HTM[63]="*so satthenapi vaṇamukhassa parikantanahetu dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyeyya.**causing painful feelings, sharp and severe.*";
P_HTM[64]="*Tassa so bhisakko sallakatto esaniyā sallaṃ eseyya;**They’d probe for the arrow,*";
P_HTM[65]="*so esaniyāpi sallassa esanāhetu dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyeyya.**causing painful feelings, sharp and severe.*";
P_HTM[66]="*Tassa so bhisakko sallakatto sallaṃ abbuheyya;**They’d extract the arrow,*";
P_HTM[67]="*so sallassapi abbuhanahetu dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyeyya.**causing painful feelings, sharp and severe.*";
P_HTM[68]="*Tassa so bhisakko sallakatto agadaṅgāraṃ vaṇamukhe odaheyya;**They’d apply cauterizing medicine to the wound,*";
P_HTM[69]="*so agadaṅgārassapi vaṇamukhe odahanahetu dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyeyya.**causing painful feelings, sharp and severe.*";
P_HTM[70]="*So aparena samayena rūḷhena vaṇena sañchavinā arogo assa sukhī serī sayaṃvasī yena kāmaṅgamo.**After some time that wound would be healed and the skin regrown. They’d be healthy, happy, autonomous, master of themselves, able to go where they wanted.*";
P_HTM[71]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think,*";
P_HTM[72]="*“ahaṃ kho pubbe sallena viddho ahosiṃ savisena gāḷhūpalepanena.**“Earlier I was struck by an arrow thickly smeared with poison,*";
P_HTM[73]="*Sohaṃ sallassapi vedhanahetu dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyiṃ.**causing painful feelings, sharp and severe.*";
P_HTM[74]="*Tassa me mittāmaccā ñātisālohitā bhisakkaṃ sallakattaṃ upaṭṭhapesuṃ.**My friends and colleagues, relatives and kin got a field surgeon to treat me.*";
P_HTM[75]="*Tassa me so bhisakko sallakatto satthena vaṇamukhaṃ parikanti;**At each step, the treatment was painful.*";
P_HTM[76]="*sohaṃ satthenapi vaṇamukhassa parikantanahetu dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[77]="*Tassa me so bhisakko sallakatto esaniyā sallaṃ esi;* **";
P_HTM[78]="*so ahaṃ esaniyāpi sallassa esanāhetu dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[79]="*Tassa me so bhisakko sallakatto sallaṃ abbuhi;* **";
P_HTM[80]="*sohaṃ sallassapi abbuhanahetu dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[81]="*Tassa me so bhisakko sallakatto agadaṅgāraṃ vaṇamukhe odahi;* **";
P_HTM[82]="*sohaṃ agadaṅgārassapi vaṇamukhe odahanahetu dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[83]="*Somhi etarahi rūḷhena vaṇena sañchavinā arogo sukhī serī sayaṃvasī yena kāmaṅgamo”ti.**But these days that wound is healed and the skin regrown. I’m healthy, happy, autonomous, my own master, able to go where I want.”*";
P_HTM[84]="*Evameva kho, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, sace tumhe jāneyyātha—**In the same way, reverends, if you knew about these things,*";
P_HTM[85]="*ahuvamheva mayaṃ pubbe, na nāhuvamhāti, jāneyyātha—* **";
P_HTM[86]="*akaramheva mayaṃ pubbe pāpakammaṃ, na nākaramhāti, jāneyyātha—* **";
P_HTM[87]="*evarūpaṃ vā evarūpaṃ vā pāpakammaṃ akaramhāti, jāneyyātha—* **";
P_HTM[88]="*ettakaṃ vā dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ, ettakaṃ vā dukkhaṃ nijjīretabbaṃ, ettakamhi vā dukkhe nijjiṇṇe sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatīti, jāneyyātha—* **";
P_HTM[89]="*diṭṭheva dhamme akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānaṃ, kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[90]="*evaṃ sante āyasmantānaṃ nigaṇṭhānaṃ kallamassa veyyākaraṇāya:**it would be appropriate for the Jain venerables to declare this.*";
P_HTM[91]="*“yaṃ kiñcāyaṃ purisapuggalo paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā, sabbaṃ taṃ pubbekatahetu.* **";
P_HTM[92]="*Iti purāṇānaṃ kammānaṃ tapasā byantībhāvā, navānaṃ kammānaṃ akaraṇā, āyatiṃ anavassavo;* **";
P_HTM[93]="*āyatiṃ anavassavā kammakkhayo; kammakkhayā dukkhakkhayo; dukkhakkhayā vedanākkhayo; vedanākkhayā sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[94]="*Yasmā ca kho tumhe, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, na jānātha—**But since you don’t know any of these things,*";
P_HTM[95]="*ahuvamheva mayaṃ pubbe, na nāhuvamhāti, na jānātha—* **";
P_HTM[96]="*akaramheva mayaṃ pubbe pāpakammaṃ, na nākaramhāti, na jānātha—* **";
P_HTM[97]="*evarūpaṃ vā evarūpaṃ vā pāpakammaṃ akaramhāti, na jānātha—* **";
P_HTM[98]="*ettakaṃ vā dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ, ettakaṃ vā dukkhaṃ nijjīretabbaṃ, ettakamhi vā dukkhe nijjiṇṇe sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatīti, na jānātha—* **";
P_HTM[99]="*diṭṭheva dhamme akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānaṃ, kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[100]="*tasmā āyasmantānaṃ nigaṇṭhānaṃ na kallamassa veyyākaraṇāya:**it’s not appropriate for the Jain venerables to declare this.’*";
P_HTM[101]="*“yaṃ kiñcāyaṃ purisapuggalo paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā, sabbaṃ taṃ pubbekatahetu.* **";
P_HTM[102]="*Iti purāṇānaṃ kammānaṃ tapasā byantībhāvā, navānaṃ kammānaṃ akaraṇā, āyatiṃ anavassavo;* **";
P_HTM[103]="*āyatiṃ anavassavā kammakkhayo; kammakkhayā dukkhakkhayo; dukkhakkhayā vedanākkhayo; vedanākkhayā sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatī”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[104]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhikkhave, te nigaṇṭhā maṃ etadavocuṃ:**When I said this, those Jain ascetics said to me,*";
P_HTM[105]="*‘nigaṇṭho, āvuso, nāṭaputto sabbaññū sabbadassāvī, aparisesaṃ ñāṇadassanaṃ paṭijānāti.**‘Reverend, the Jain leader Nāṭaputta claims to be all-knowing and all-seeing, to know and see everything without exception, thus:*";
P_HTM[106]="*“Carato ca me tiṭṭhato ca suttassa ca jāgarassa ca satataṃ samitaṃ ñāṇadassanaṃ paccupaṭṭhitan”ti.**“Knowledge and vision are constantly and continually present to me, while walking, standing, sleeping, and waking.”*";
P_HTM[107]="*So evamāha:**He says:*";
P_HTM[108]="*“atthi kho vo, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, pubbeva pāpakammaṃ kataṃ, taṃ imāya kaṭukāya dukkarakārikāya nijjīretha,**“O reverend Jain ascetics, you have done bad deeds in a past life. Wear them away with these severe and grueling austerities.*";
P_HTM[109]="*yaṃ panettha etarahi kāyena saṃvutā vācāya saṃvutā manasā saṃvutā taṃ āyatiṃ pāpakammassa akaraṇaṃ.**And when you refrain from such deeds in the present by way of body, speech, and mind, you’re not doing any bad deeds for the future.*";
P_HTM[110]="*Iti purāṇānaṃ kammānaṃ tapasā byantībhāvā, navānaṃ kammānaṃ akaraṇā, āyatiṃ anavassavo;**So, due to eliminating past deeds by mortification, and not doing any new deeds, there’s nothing to come up in the future.*";
P_HTM[111]="*āyatiṃ anavassavā kammakkhayo; kammakkhayā dukkhakkhayo; dukkhakkhayā vedanākkhayo; vedanākkhayā sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatī”ti.**With nothing to come up in the future, deeds end. With the ending of deeds, suffering ends. With the ending of suffering, feeling ends. And with the ending of feeling, all suffering will have been worn away.”*";
P_HTM[112]="*Tañca panamhākaṃ ruccati ceva khamati ca, tena camhā attamanā’ti.**We like and accept this, and we are satisfied with it.’*";
P_HTM[113]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, bhikkhave, te nigaṇṭhe etadavocaṃ:**When they said this, I said to them,*";
P_HTM[114]="*‘pañca kho ime, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, dhammā diṭṭheva dhamme dvidhāvipākā.**‘These five things can be seen to turn out in two different ways.*";
P_HTM[115]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[116]="*Saddhā, ruci, anussavo, ākāraparivitakko, diṭṭhinijjhānakkhanti—**Faith, preference, oral tradition, reasoned contemplation, and acceptance of a view after consideration.*";
P_HTM[117]="*ime kho, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, pañca dhammā diṭṭheva dhamme dvidhāvipākā.**These are the five things that can be seen to turn out in two different ways.*";
P_HTM[118]="*Tatrāyasmantānaṃ nigaṇṭhānaṃ kā atītaṃse satthari saddhā, kā ruci, ko anussavo, ko ākāraparivitakko, kā diṭṭhinijjhānakkhantī’ti.**In this case, what faith in your teacher do you have when it comes to the past? What preference, oral tradition, reasoned contemplation, or acceptance of a view after consideration?’*";
P_HTM[119]="*Evaṃvādī kho ahaṃ, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhesu na kañci sahadhammikaṃ vādapaṭihāraṃ samanupassāmi.**When I said this, I did not see any legitimate defense of their doctrine from the Jains.*";
P_HTM[120]="*Puna caparāhaṃ, bhikkhave, te nigaṇṭhe evaṃ vadāmi:**Furthermore, I said to those Jain ascetics,*";
P_HTM[121]="*‘taṃ kiṃ maññatha, āvuso nigaṇṭhā.**‘What do you think, reverends?*";
P_HTM[122]="*Yasmiṃ vo samaye tibbo upakkamo hoti tibbaṃ padhānaṃ, tibbā tasmiṃ samaye opakkamikā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyetha;**At a time of intense exertion and striving do you experience painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings due to overexertion?*";
P_HTM[123]="*yasmiṃ pana vo samaye na tibbo upakkamo hoti na tibbaṃ padhānaṃ, na tibbā tasmiṃ samaye opakkamikā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyethā’ti?**Whereas at a time without intense exertion and striving do you not experience painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings due to overexertion?’*";
P_HTM[124]="*‘Yasmiṃ no, āvuso gotama, samaye tibbo upakkamo hoti tibbaṃ padhānaṃ, tibbā tasmiṃ samaye opakkamikā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyāma;**‘Reverend Gotama, at a time of intense exertion we experience painful, sharp feelings due to overexertion,*";
P_HTM[125]="*yasmiṃ pana no samaye na tibbo upakkamo hoti na tibbaṃ padhānaṃ, na tibbā tasmiṃ samaye opakkamikā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyāmā’ti.**not without intense exertion.’*";
P_HTM[126]="*‘Iti kira, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, yasmiṃ vo samaye tibbo upakkamo hoti tibbaṃ padhānaṃ, tibbā tasmiṃ samaye opakkamikā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyetha;**‘So it seems that only at a time of intense exertion do you experience painful, sharp feelings due to overexertion,*";
P_HTM[127]="*yasmiṃ pana vo samaye na tibbo upakkamo hoti na tibbaṃ padhānaṃ, na tibbā tasmiṃ samaye opakkamikā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyetha.**not without intense exertion.*";
P_HTM[128]="*Evaṃ sante āyasmantānaṃ nigaṇṭhānaṃ na kallamassa veyyākaraṇāya:**In that case, it’s not appropriate for the Jain venerables to declare:*";
P_HTM[129]="*“yaṃ kiñcāyaṃ purisapuggalo paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā, sabbaṃ taṃ pubbekatahetu.**“Everything this individual experiences—pleasurable, painful, or neutral—is because of past deeds. …”*";
P_HTM[130]="*Iti purāṇānaṃ kammānaṃ tapasā byantībhāvā, navānaṃ kammānaṃ akaraṇā, āyatiṃ anavassavo;* **";
P_HTM[131]="*āyatiṃ anavassavā kammakkhayo; kammakkhayā dukkhakkhayo; dukkhakkhayā vedanākkhayo; vedanākkhayā sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[132]="*Sace, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, yasmiṃ vo samaye tibbo upakkamo hoti tibbaṃ padhānaṃ, na tibbā tasmiṃ samaye opakkamikā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyetha;**If at a time of intense exertion you did not experience painful, sharp feelings due to overexertion,*";
P_HTM[133]="*yasmiṃ pana vo samaye na tibbo upakkamo hoti na tibbaṃ padhānaṃ, tibbā tasmiṃ samaye opakkamikā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyetha;**and if without intense exertion you did experience such feelings,*";
P_HTM[134]="*evaṃ sante āyasmantānaṃ nigaṇṭhānaṃ kallamassa veyyākaraṇāya:**it would be appropriate for the Jain venerables to declare this.*";
P_HTM[135]="*“yaṃ kiñcāyaṃ purisapuggalo paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā, sabbaṃ taṃ pubbekatahetu.* **";
P_HTM[136]="*Iti purāṇānaṃ kammānaṃ tapasā byantībhāvā, navānaṃ kammānaṃ akaraṇā, āyatiṃ anavassavo;* **";
P_HTM[137]="*āyatiṃ anavassavā kammakkhayo; kammakkhayā dukkhakkhayo; dukkhakkhayā vedanākkhayo; vedanākkhayā sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[138]="*Yasmā ca kho, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, yasmiṃ vo samaye tibbo upakkamo hoti tibbaṃ padhānaṃ, tibbā tasmiṃ samaye opakkamikā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyetha;**But since this is not the case,*";
P_HTM[139]="*yasmiṃ pana vo samaye na tibbo upakkamo hoti na tibbaṃ padhānaṃ, na tibbā tasmiṃ samaye opakkamikā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyetha;* **";
P_HTM[140]="*te tumhe sāmaṃyeva opakkamikā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vedayamānā avijjā aññāṇā sammohā vipaccetha:**aren’t you experiencing painful, sharp feelings due only to your own exertion, which out of ignorance, unknowing, and confusion you misconstrue to imply:*";
P_HTM[141]="*“yaṃ kiñcāyaṃ purisapuggalo paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā, sabbaṃ taṃ pubbekatahetu.**“Everything this individual experiences—pleasurable, painful, or neutral—is because of past deeds. …”?’*";
P_HTM[142]="*Iti purāṇānaṃ kammānaṃ tapasā byantībhāvā, navānaṃ kammānaṃ akaraṇā, āyatiṃ anavassavo;* **";
P_HTM[143]="*āyatiṃ anavassavā kammakkhayo; kammakkhayā dukkhakkhayo; dukkhakkhayā vedanākkhayo; vedanākkhayā sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ bhavissatī”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[144]="*Evaṃvādīpi kho ahaṃ, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhesu na kañci sahadhammikaṃ vādapaṭihāraṃ samanupassāmi.**When I said this, I did not see any legitimate defense of their doctrine from the Jains.*";
P_HTM[145]="*Puna caparāhaṃ, bhikkhave, te nigaṇṭhe evaṃ vadāmi:**Furthermore, I said to those Jain ascetics,*";
P_HTM[146]="*‘taṃ kiṃ maññathāvuso nigaṇṭhā, yamidaṃ kammaṃ diṭṭhadhammavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā samparāyavedanīyaṃ hotūti labbhametan’ti?**‘What do you think, reverends? If a deed is to be experienced in this life, can exertion make it be experienced in lives to come?’*";
P_HTM[147]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[148]="*‘Yaṃ panidaṃ kammaṃ samparāyavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā diṭṭhadhammavedanīyaṃ hotūti labbhametan’ti?**‘But if a deed is to be experienced in lives to come, can exertion make it be experienced in this life?’*";
P_HTM[149]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[150]="*‘Taṃ kiṃ maññathāvuso nigaṇṭhā, yamidaṃ kammaṃ sukhavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā dukkhavedanīyaṃ hotūti labbhametan’ti?**‘What do you think, reverends? If a deed is to be experienced as pleasure, can exertion make it be experienced as pain?’*";
P_HTM[151]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[152]="*‘Yaṃ panidaṃ kammaṃ dukkhavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā sukhavedanīyaṃ hotūti labbhametan’ti?**‘But if a deed is to be experienced as pain, can exertion make it be experienced as pleasure?’*";
P_HTM[153]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[154]="*‘Taṃ kiṃ maññathāvuso nigaṇṭhā, yamidaṃ kammaṃ paripakkavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā aparipakkavedanīyaṃ hotūti labbhametan’ti?**‘What do you think, reverends? If a deed is to be experienced when fully ripened, can exertion make it be experienced when not fully ripened?’*";
P_HTM[155]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[156]="*‘Yaṃ panidaṃ kammaṃ aparipakkavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā paripakkavedanīyaṃ hotūti labbhametan’ti?**‘But if a deed is to be experienced when not fully ripened, can exertion make it be experienced when fully ripened?’*";
P_HTM[157]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[158]="*‘Taṃ kiṃ maññathāvuso nigaṇṭhā, yamidaṃ kammaṃ bahuvedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā appavedanīyaṃ hotūti labbhametan’ti?**‘What do you think, reverends? If a deed is to be experienced strongly, can exertion make it be experienced weakly?’*";
P_HTM[159]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[160]="*‘Yaṃ panidaṃ kammaṃ appavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā bahuvedanīyaṃ hotūti labbhametan’ti?**‘But if a deed is to be experienced weakly, can exertion make it be experienced strongly?’*";
P_HTM[161]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[162]="*‘Taṃ kiṃ maññathāvuso nigaṇṭhā, yamidaṃ kammaṃ savedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā avedanīyaṃ hotūti labbhametan’ti?**‘What do you think, reverends? If a deed is to be experienced, can exertion make it not be experienced?’*";
P_HTM[163]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[164]="*‘Yaṃ panidaṃ kammaṃ avedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā savedanīyaṃ hotūti labbhametan’ti?**‘But if a deed is not to be experienced, can exertion make it be experienced?’*";
P_HTM[165]="*‘No hidaṃ, āvuso’.**‘No, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[166]="*‘Iti kira, āvuso nigaṇṭhā, yamidaṃ kammaṃ diṭṭhadhammavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā samparāyavedanīyaṃ hotūti alabbhametaṃ, yaṃ panidaṃ kammaṃ samparāyavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā diṭṭhadhammavedanīyaṃ hotūti alabbhametaṃ, yamidaṃ kammaṃ sukhavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā dukkhavedanīyaṃ hotūti alabbhametaṃ, yamidaṃ kammaṃ dukkhavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā sukhavedanīyaṃ hotūti alabbhametaṃ, yamidaṃ kammaṃ paripakkavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā aparipakkavedanīyaṃ hotūti alabbhametaṃ, yamidaṃ kammaṃ aparipakkavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā paripakkavedanīyaṃ hotūti alabbhametaṃ, yamidaṃ kammaṃ bahuvedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā appavedanīyaṃ hotūti alabbhametaṃ, yamidaṃ kammaṃ appavedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā bahuvedanīyaṃ hotūti alabbhametaṃ, yamidaṃ kammaṃ savedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā avedanīyaṃ hotūti alabbhametaṃ, yamidaṃ kammaṃ avedanīyaṃ taṃ upakkamena vā padhānena vā savedanīyaṃ hotūti alabbhametaṃ;**‘So it seems that exertion cannot change the way deeds are experienced in any of these ways.*";
P_HTM[167]="*evaṃ sante āyasmantānaṃ nigaṇṭhānaṃ aphalo upakkamo hoti, aphalaṃ padhānaṃ’.**This being so, your exertion and striving are fruitless.’*";
P_HTM[168]="*Evaṃvādī, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhā.**Such is the doctrine of the Jain ascetics.*";
P_HTM[169]="*Evaṃvādīnaṃ, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhānaṃ dasa sahadhammikā vādānuvādā gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchanti.**Saying this, the Jain ascetics deserve rebuke and criticism on ten legitimate grounds.*";
P_HTM[170]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā pubbekatahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti;**If sentient beings experience pleasure and pain because of past deeds,*";
P_HTM[171]="*addhā, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhā pubbe dukkaṭakammakārino yaṃ etarahi evarūpā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyanti.**clearly the Jains have done bad deeds in the past, since they now experience such intense pain.*";
P_HTM[172]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā issaranimmānahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti;**If sentient beings experience pleasure and pain because of the Lord God’s creation,*";
P_HTM[173]="*addhā, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhā pāpakena issarena nimmitā yaṃ etarahi evarūpā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyanti.**clearly the Jains were created by a bad God, since they now experience such intense pain.*";
P_HTM[174]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā saṅgatibhāvahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti;**If sentient beings experience pleasure and pain because of circumstance and nature,*";
P_HTM[175]="*addhā, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhā pāpasaṅgatikā yaṃ etarahi evarūpā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyanti.**clearly the Jains arise from bad circumstances, since they now experience such intense pain.*";
P_HTM[176]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā abhijātihetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti;**If sentient beings experience pleasure and pain because of the class of rebirth,*";
P_HTM[177]="*addhā, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhā pāpābhijātikā yaṃ etarahi evarūpā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyanti.**clearly the Jains have been reborn in a bad class, since they now experience such intense pain.*";
P_HTM[178]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā diṭṭhadhammūpakkamahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti;**If sentient beings experience pleasure and pain because of exertion in the present,*";
P_HTM[179]="*addhā, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhā evarūpā diṭṭhadhammūpakkamā yaṃ etarahi evarūpā dukkhā tibbā kaṭukā vedanā vediyanti.**clearly the Jains exert themselves badly in the present, since they now experience such intense pain.*";
P_HTM[180]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā pubbekatahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, gārayhā nigaṇṭhā;**The Jains deserve criticism whether or not sentient beings experience pleasure and pain because of past deeds,*";
P_HTM[181]="*no ce sattā pubbekatahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, gārayhā nigaṇṭhā.* **";
P_HTM[182]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā issaranimmānahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, gārayhā nigaṇṭhā;**or the Lord God’s creation,*";
P_HTM[183]="*no ce sattā issaranimmānahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, gārayhā nigaṇṭhā.* **";
P_HTM[184]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā saṅgatibhāvahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, gārayhā nigaṇṭhā;**or circumstance and nature,*";
P_HTM[185]="*no ce sattā saṅgatibhāvahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, gārayhā nigaṇṭhā.* **";
P_HTM[186]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā abhijātihetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, gārayhā nigaṇṭhā;**or class of rebirth,*";
P_HTM[187]="*no ce sattā abhijātihetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, gārayhā nigaṇṭhā.* **";
P_HTM[188]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā diṭṭhadhammūpakkamahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, gārayhā nigaṇṭhā;**or exertion in the present.*";
P_HTM[189]="*no ce sattā diṭṭhadhammūpakkamahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, gārayhā nigaṇṭhā.* **";
P_HTM[190]="*Evaṃvādī, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhā.**Such is the doctrine of the Jain ascetics.*";
P_HTM[191]="*Evaṃvādīnaṃ, bhikkhave, nigaṇṭhānaṃ ime dasa sahadhammikā vādānuvādā gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchanti.**The Jain ascetics who say this deserve rebuke and criticism on these ten legitimate grounds.*";
P_HTM[192]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, aphalo upakkamo hoti, aphalaṃ padhānaṃ.**That’s how exertion and striving is fruitless.*";
P_HTM[193]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, saphalo upakkamo hoti, saphalaṃ padhānaṃ?**And how is exertion and striving fruitful?*";
P_HTM[194]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu na heva anaddhabhūtaṃ attānaṃ dukkhena addhabhāveti, dhammikañca sukhaṃ na pariccajati, tasmiñca sukhe anadhimucchito hoti.**It’s when a mendicant doesn’t bring suffering upon themselves; and they don’t give up legitimate pleasure, but they’re not besotted with that pleasure.*";
P_HTM[195]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[196]="*‘imassa kho me dukkhanidānassa saṅkhāraṃ padahato saṅkhārappadhānā virāgo hoti, imassa pana me dukkhanidānassa ajjhupekkhato upekkhaṃ bhāvayato virāgo hotī’ti.**‘When I actively strive I become dispassionate towards this source of suffering. But when I develop equanimity I become dispassionate towards this other source of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[197]="*So yassa hi khvāssa dukkhanidānassa saṅkhāraṃ padahato saṅkhārappadhānā virāgo hoti, saṅkhāraṃ tattha padahati.**So they either actively strive or develop equanimity as appropriate.*";
P_HTM[198]="*Yassa panassa dukkhanidānassa ajjhupekkhato upekkhaṃ bhāvayato virāgo hoti, upekkhaṃ tattha bhāveti.* **";
P_HTM[199]="*Tassa tassa dukkhanidānassa saṅkhāraṃ padahato saṅkhārappadhānā virāgo hoti—**Through active striving they become dispassionate towards that specific source of suffering,*";
P_HTM[200]="*evampissa taṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ hoti.**and so that suffering is worn away.*";
P_HTM[201]="*Tassa tassa dukkhanidānassa ajjhupekkhato upekkhaṃ bhāvayato virāgo hoti—**Through developing equanimity they become dispassionate towards that other source of suffering,*";
P_HTM[202]="*evampissa taṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ hoti.**and so that suffering is worn away.*";
P_HTM[203]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso itthiyā sāratto paṭibaddhacitto tibbacchando tibbāpekkho.**Suppose a man is in love with a woman, full of intense desire and lust.*";
P_HTM[204]="*So taṃ itthiṃ passeyya aññena purisena saddhiṃ santiṭṭhantiṃ sallapantiṃ sañjagghantiṃ saṃhasantiṃ.**Then he sees her standing together with another man, chatting, giggling, and laughing.*";
P_HTM[205]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[206]="*api nu tassa purisassa amuṃ itthiṃ disvā aññena purisena saddhiṃ santiṭṭhantiṃ sallapantiṃ sañjagghantiṃ saṃhasantiṃ uppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassūpāyāsā”ti?**Would that give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress for him?”*";
P_HTM[207]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.*";
P_HTM[208]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[209]="*“Amu hi, bhante, puriso amussā itthiyā sāratto paṭibaddhacitto tibbacchando tibbāpekkho.**Because that man is in love that woman, full of intense desire and lust.”*";
P_HTM[210]="*Tasmā taṃ itthiṃ disvā aññena purisena saddhiṃ santiṭṭhantiṃ sallapantiṃ sañjagghantiṃ saṃhasantiṃ uppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassūpāyāsā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[211]="*“Atha kho, bhikkhave, tassa purisassa evamassa:**“Then that man might think:*";
P_HTM[212]="*‘ahaṃ kho amussā itthiyā sāratto paṭibaddhacitto tibbacchando tibbāpekkho.**‘I’m in love with that woman, full of intense desire and lust.*";
P_HTM[213]="*Tassa me amuṃ itthiṃ disvā aññena purisena saddhiṃ santiṭṭhantiṃ sallapantiṃ sañjagghantiṃ saṃhasantiṃ uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassūpāyāsā.**When I saw her standing together with another man, chatting, giggling, and laughing, it gave rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress for me.*";
P_HTM[214]="*Yannūnāhaṃ yo me amussā itthiyā chandarāgo taṃ pajaheyyan’ti.**Why don’t I give up that desire and lust for that woman?’*";
P_HTM[215]="*So yo amussā itthiyā chandarāgo taṃ pajaheyya.**So that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[216]="*So taṃ itthiṃ passeyya aparena samayena aññena purisena saddhiṃ santiṭṭhantiṃ sallapantiṃ sañjagghantiṃ saṃhasantiṃ.**Some time later he sees her again standing together with another man, chatting, giggling, and laughing.*";
P_HTM[217]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[218]="*api nu tassa purisassa amuṃ itthiṃ disvā aññena purisena saddhiṃ santiṭṭhantiṃ sallapantiṃ sañjagghantiṃ saṃhasantiṃ uppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassūpāyāsā”ti?**Would that give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress for him?”*";
P_HTM[219]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[220]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[221]="*“Amu hi, bhante, puriso amussā itthiyā virāgo.**Because he no longer desires that woman.”*";
P_HTM[222]="*Tasmā taṃ itthiṃ disvā aññena purisena saddhiṃ santiṭṭhantiṃ sallapantiṃ sañjagghantiṃ saṃhasantiṃ na uppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassūpāyāsā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[223]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu na heva anaddhabhūtaṃ attānaṃ dukkhena addhabhāveti, dhammikañca sukhaṃ na pariccajati, tasmiñca sukhe anadhimucchito hoti.**“In the same way, a mendicant doesn’t bring suffering upon themselves; and they don’t give up legitimate pleasure, but they’re not besotted with that pleasure.*";
P_HTM[224]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[225]="*‘imassa kho me dukkhanidānassa saṅkhāraṃ padahato saṅkhārappadhānā virāgo hoti, imassa pana me dukkhanidānassa ajjhupekkhato upekkhaṃ bhāvayato virāgo hotī’ti.**‘When I actively strive I become dispassionate towards this source of suffering. But when I develop equanimity I become dispassionate towards this other source of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[226]="*So yassa hi khvāssa dukkhanidānassa saṅkhāraṃ padahato saṅkhārappadhānā virāgo hoti, saṅkhāraṃ tattha padahati;**So they either actively strive or develop equanimity as appropriate.*";
P_HTM[227]="*yassa panassa dukkhanidānassa ajjhupekkhato upekkhaṃ bhāvayato virāgo hoti, upekkhaṃ tattha bhāveti.* **";
P_HTM[228]="*Tassa tassa dukkhanidānassa saṅkhāraṃ padahato saṅkhārappadhānā virāgo hoti—**Through active striving they become dispassionate towards that specific source of suffering,*";
P_HTM[229]="*evampissa taṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ hoti.**and so that suffering is worn away.*";
P_HTM[230]="*Tassa tassa dukkhanidānassa ajjhupekkhato upekkhaṃ bhāvayato virāgo hoti—**Through developing equanimity they become dispassionate towards that other source of suffering,*";
P_HTM[231]="*evampissa taṃ dukkhaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ hoti.**and so that suffering is worn away.*";
P_HTM[232]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, saphalo upakkamo hoti, saphalaṃ padhānaṃ.**That’s how exertion and striving is fruitful.*";
P_HTM[233]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Furthermore, a mendicant reflects:*";
P_HTM[234]="*‘yathāsukhaṃ kho me viharato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti;**‘When I live as I please, unskillful qualities grow and skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[235]="*dukkhāya pana me attānaṃ padahato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.**But when I strive painfully, unskillful qualities decline and skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[236]="*Yannūnāhaṃ dukkhāya attānaṃ padaheyyan’ti.**Why don’t I strive painfully?’*";
P_HTM[237]="*So dukkhāya attānaṃ padahati.**So that’s what they do,*";
P_HTM[238]="*Tassa dukkhāya attānaṃ padahato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.**and as they do so unskillful qualities decline and skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[239]="*So na aparena samayena dukkhāya attānaṃ padahati.**After some time, they no longer strive painfully.*";
P_HTM[240]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[241]="*Yassa hi so, bhikkhave, bhikkhu atthāya dukkhāya attānaṃ padaheyya svāssa attho abhinipphanno hoti.**Because they have accomplished the goal for which they strived painfully.*";
P_HTM[242]="*Tasmā na aparena samayena dukkhāya attānaṃ padahati.* **";
P_HTM[243]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, usukāro tejanaṃ dvīsu alātesu ātāpeti paritāpeti ujuṃ karoti kammaniyaṃ.**Suppose an arrowsmith was heating an arrow shaft between two firebrands, making it straight and fit for use.*";
P_HTM[244]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, usukārassa tejanaṃ dvīsu alātesu ātāpitaṃ hoti paritāpitaṃ ujuṃ kataṃ kammaniyaṃ, na so taṃ aparena samayena usukāro tejanaṃ dvīsu alātesu ātāpeti paritāpeti ujuṃ karoti kammaniyaṃ.**After it’s been made straight and fit for use, they’d no longer heat it to make it straight and fit for use.*";
P_HTM[245]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[246]="*Yassa hi so, bhikkhave, atthāya usukāro tejanaṃ dvīsu alātesu ātāpeyya paritāpeyya ujuṃ kareyya kammaniyaṃ svāssa attho abhinipphanno hoti.**Because they have accomplished the goal for which they heated it.*";
P_HTM[247]="*Tasmā na aparena samayena usukāro tejanaṃ dvīsu alātesu ātāpeti paritāpeti ujuṃ karoti kammaniyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[248]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu iti paṭisañcikkhati:**In the same way, a mendicant reflects:*";
P_HTM[249]="*‘yathāsukhaṃ kho me viharato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti;**‘When I live as I please, unskillful qualities grow and skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[250]="*dukkhāya pana me attānaṃ padahato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.**But when I strive painfully, unskillful qualities decline and skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[251]="*Yannūnāhaṃ dukkhāya attānaṃ padaheyyan’ti.**Why don’t I strive painfully?’ …*";
P_HTM[252]="*So dukkhāya attānaṃ padahati.* **";
P_HTM[253]="*Tassa dukkhāya attānaṃ padahato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.* **";
P_HTM[254]="*So na aparena samayena dukkhāya attānaṃ padahati.* **";
P_HTM[255]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[256]="*Yassa hi so, bhikkhave, bhikkhu atthāya dukkhāya attānaṃ padaheyya svāssa attho abhinipphanno hoti.* **";
P_HTM[257]="*Tasmā na aparena samayena dukkhāya attānaṃ padahati.**After some time, they no longer strive painfully.*";
P_HTM[258]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, saphalo upakkamo hoti, saphalaṃ padhānaṃ.**That too is how exertion and striving is fruitful.*";
P_HTM[259]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, idha tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā.**Furthermore, a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.*";
P_HTM[260]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti.**He has realized with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and he makes it known to others.*";
P_HTM[261]="*So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ, kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti.**He teaches Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he reveals a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[262]="*Taṃ dhammaṃ suṇāti gahapati vā gahapatiputto vā aññatarasmiṃ vā kule paccājāto.**A householder hears that teaching, or a householder’s child, or someone reborn in some clan.*";
P_HTM[263]="*So taṃ dhammaṃ sutvā tathāgate saddhaṃ paṭilabhati.**They gain faith in the Realized One,*";
P_HTM[264]="*So tena saddhāpaṭilābhena samannāgato iti paṭisañcikkhati:**and reflect:*";
P_HTM[265]="*‘sambādho gharāvāso rajāpatho, abbhokāso pabbajjā.**‘Living in a house is cramped and dirty, but the life of one gone forth is wide open.*";
P_HTM[266]="*Nayidaṃ sukaraṃ agāraṃ ajjhāvasatā ekantaparipuṇṇaṃ ekantaparisuddhaṃ saṅkhalikhitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ carituṃ.**It’s not easy for someone living at home to lead the spiritual life utterly full and pure, like a polished shell.*";
P_HTM[267]="*Yannūnāhaṃ kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajeyyan’ti.**Why don’t I shave off my hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness?’*";
P_HTM[268]="*So aparena samayena appaṃ vā bhogakkhandhaṃ pahāya mahantaṃ vā bhogakkhandhaṃ pahāya, appaṃ vā ñātiparivaṭṭaṃ pahāya mahantaṃ vā ñātiparivaṭṭaṃ pahāya kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati.**After some time they give up a large or small fortune, and a large or small family circle. They shave off hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[269]="*So evaṃ pabbajito samāno bhikkhūnaṃ sikkhāsājīvasamāpanno pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti nihitadaṇḍo nihitasattho, lajjī dayāpanno sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī viharati.**Once they’ve gone forth, they take up the training and livelihood of the mendicants. They give up killing living creatures, renouncing the rod and the sword. They’re scrupulous and kind, living full of compassion for all living beings.*";
P_HTM[270]="*Adinnādānaṃ pahāya adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti dinnādāyī dinnapāṭikaṅkhī, athenena sucibhūtena attanā viharati.**They give up stealing. They take only what’s given, and expect only what’s given. They keep themselves clean by not thieving.*";
P_HTM[271]="*Abrahmacariyaṃ pahāya brahmacārī hoti ārācārī virato methunā gāmadhammā.**They give up unchastity. They are celibate, set apart, avoiding the common practice of sex.*";
P_HTM[272]="*Musāvādaṃ pahāya musāvādā paṭivirato hoti saccavādī saccasandho theto paccayiko avisaṃvādako lokassa.**They give up lying. They speak the truth and stick to the truth. They’re honest and trustworthy, and don’t trick the world with their words.*";
P_HTM[273]="*Pisuṇaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti; ito sutvā na amutra akkhātā imesaṃ bhedāya, amutra vā sutvā na imesaṃ akkhātā amūsaṃ bhedāya—iti bhinnānaṃ vā sandhātā sahitānaṃ vā anuppadātā samaggārāmo samaggarato samagganandī samaggakaraṇiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā hoti.**They give up divisive speech. They don’t repeat in one place what they heard in another so as to divide people against each other. Instead, they reconcile those who are divided, supporting unity, delighting in harmony, loving harmony, speaking words that promote harmony.*";
P_HTM[274]="*Pharusaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti; yā sā vācā nelā kaṇṇasukhā pemanīyā hadayaṅgamā porī bahujanakantā bahujanamanāpā tathārūpiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā hoti.**They give up harsh speech. They speak in a way that’s mellow, pleasing to the ear, lovely, going to the heart, polite, likable and agreeable to the people.*";
P_HTM[275]="*Samphappalāpaṃ pahāya samphappalāpā paṭivirato hoti kālavādī bhūtavādī atthavādī dhammavādī vinayavādī, nidhānavatiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā kālena sāpadesaṃ pariyantavatiṃ atthasaṃhitaṃ.**They give up talking nonsense. Their words are timely, true, and meaningful, in line with the teaching and training. They say things at the right time which are valuable, reasonable, succinct, and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[276]="*So bījagāmabhūtagāmasamārambhā paṭivirato hoti.**They avoid injuring plants and seeds.*";
P_HTM[277]="*Ekabhattiko hoti rattūparato virato vikālabhojanā.**They eat in one part of the day, abstaining from eating at night and food at the wrong time.*";
P_HTM[278]="*Naccagītavāditavisūkadassanā paṭivirato hoti.**They avoid dancing, singing, music, and seeing shows.*";
P_HTM[279]="*Mālāgandhavilepanadhāraṇamaṇḍanavibhūsanaṭṭhānā paṭivirato hoti.**They avoid beautifying and adorning themselves with garlands, perfumes, and makeup.*";
P_HTM[280]="*Uccāsayanamahāsayanā paṭivirato hoti.**They avoid high and luxurious beds.*";
P_HTM[281]="*Jātarūparajatapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**They avoid receiving gold and money,*";
P_HTM[282]="*Āmakadhaññapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**raw grains,*";
P_HTM[283]="*Āmakamaṃsapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**raw meat,*";
P_HTM[284]="*Itthikumārikapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**women and girls,*";
P_HTM[285]="*Dāsidāsapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**male and female bondservants,*";
P_HTM[286]="*Ajeḷakapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**goats and sheep,*";
P_HTM[287]="*Kukkuṭasūkarapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**chickens and pigs,*";
P_HTM[288]="*Hatthigavassavaḷavapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**elephants, cows, horses, and mares,*";
P_HTM[289]="*Khettavatthupaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**and fields and land.*";
P_HTM[290]="*Dūteyyapahiṇagamanānuyogā paṭivirato hoti.**They avoid running errands and messages;*";
P_HTM[291]="*Kayavikkayā paṭivirato hoti.**buying and selling;*";
P_HTM[292]="*Tulākūṭakaṃsakūṭamānakūṭā paṭivirato hoti.**falsifying weights, metals, or measures;*";
P_HTM[293]="*Ukkoṭanavañcananikatisāciyogā paṭivirato hoti.**bribery, fraud, cheating, and duplicity;*";
P_HTM[294]="*Chedanavadhabandhanaviparāmosaālopasahasākārā paṭivirato hoti.**mutilation, murder, abduction, banditry, plunder, and violence.*";
P_HTM[295]="*So santuṭṭho hoti kāyaparihārikena cīvarena, kucchiparihārikena piṇḍapātena. So yena yeneva pakkamati samādāyeva pakkamati.**They’re content with robes to look after the body and alms-food to look after the belly. Wherever they go, they set out taking only these things.*";
P_HTM[296]="*Seyyathāpi nāma pakkhī sakuṇo yena yeneva ḍeti sapattabhārova ḍeti;**They’re like a bird: wherever it flies, wings are its only burden.*";
P_HTM[297]="*evameva bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti kāyaparihārikena cīvarena, kucchiparihārikena piṇḍapātena; so yena yeneva pakkamati samādāyeva pakkamati.**In the same way, a mendicant is content with robes to look after the body and alms-food to look after the belly. Wherever they go, they set out taking only these things.*";
P_HTM[298]="*So iminā ariyena sīlakkhandhena samannāgato ajjhattaṃ anavajjasukhaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**When they have this entire spectrum of noble ethics, they experience a blameless happiness inside themselves.*";
P_HTM[299]="*So cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā na nimittaggāhī hoti nānubyañjanaggāhī.**When they see a sight with their eyes, they don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[300]="*Yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ cakkhundriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjati, rakkhati cakkhundriyaṃ, cakkhundriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**If the faculty of sight were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, they practice restraint, protecting the faculty of sight, and achieving its restraint.*";
P_HTM[301]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**When they hear a sound with their ears …*";
P_HTM[302]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā … pe …**When they smell an odor with their nose …*";
P_HTM[303]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā … pe …**When they taste a flavor with their tongue …*";
P_HTM[304]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā … pe …**When they feel a touch with their body …*";
P_HTM[305]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya na nimittaggāhī hoti nānubyañjanaggāhī.**When they know a thought with their mind, they don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[306]="*Yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ manindriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjati, rakkhati manindriyaṃ, manindriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**If the faculty of mind were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, they practice restraint, protecting the faculty of mind, and achieving its restraint.*";
P_HTM[307]="*So iminā ariyena indriyasaṃvarena samannāgato ajjhattaṃ abyāsekasukhaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**When they have this noble sense restraint, they experience an unsullied bliss inside themselves.*";
P_HTM[308]="*So abhikkante paṭikkante sampajānakārī hoti, ālokite vilokite sampajānakārī hoti, samiñjite pasārite sampajānakārī hoti, saṅghāṭipattacīvaradhāraṇe sampajānakārī hoti, asite pīte khāyite sāyite sampajānakārī hoti, uccārapassāvakamme sampajānakārī hoti, gate ṭhite nisinne sutte jāgarite bhāsite tuṇhībhāve sampajānakārī hoti.**They act with situational awareness when going out and coming back; when looking ahead and aside; when bending and extending the limbs; when bearing the outer robe, bowl and robes; when eating, drinking, chewing, and tasting; when urinating and defecating; when walking, standing, sitting, sleeping, waking, speaking, and keeping silent.*";
P_HTM[309]="*So iminā ca ariyena sīlakkhandhena samannāgato, imāya ca ariyāya santuṭṭhiyā samannāgato, iminā ca ariyena indriyasaṃvarena samannāgato, iminā ca ariyena satisampajaññena samannāgato**When they have this noble spectrum of ethics, this noble sense restraint, and this noble mindfulness and situational awareness,*";
P_HTM[310]="*vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajati araññaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ pabbataṃ kandaraṃ giriguhaṃ susānaṃ vanapatthaṃ abbhokāsaṃ palālapuñjaṃ.**they frequent a secluded lodging—a wilderness, the root of a tree, a hill, a ravine, a mountain cave, a charnel ground, a forest, the open air, a heap of straw.*";
P_HTM[311]="*So pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto nisīdati pallaṅkaṃ ābhujitvā, ujuṃ kāyaṃ paṇidhāya, parimukhaṃ satiṃ upaṭṭhapetvā.**After the meal, they return from alms-round, sit down cross-legged with their body straight, and establish mindfulness right there.*";
P_HTM[312]="*So abhijjhaṃ loke pahāya vigatābhijjhena cetasā viharati, abhijjhāya cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up desire for the world, they meditate with a heart rid of desire, cleansing the mind of desire.*";
P_HTM[313]="*Byāpādapadosaṃ pahāya abyāpannacitto viharati sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī, byāpādapadosā cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up ill will and malevolence, they meditate with a mind rid of ill will, full of compassion for all living beings, cleansing the mind of ill will.*";
P_HTM[314]="*Thinamiddhaṃ pahāya vigatathinamiddho viharati ālokasaññī sato sampajāno, thinamiddhā cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up dullness and drowsiness, they meditate with a mind rid of dullness and drowsiness, perceiving light, mindful and aware, cleansing the mind of dullness and drowsiness.*";
P_HTM[315]="*Uddhaccakukkuccaṃ pahāya anuddhato viharati ajjhattaṃ vūpasantacitto, uddhaccakukkuccā cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up restlessness and remorse, they meditate without restlessness, their mind peaceful inside, cleansing the mind of restlessness and remorse.*";
P_HTM[316]="*Vicikicchaṃ pahāya tiṇṇavicikiccho viharati akathaṃkathī kusalesu dhammesu, vicikicchāya cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up doubt, they meditate having gone beyond doubt, not undecided about skillful qualities, cleansing the mind of doubt.*";
P_HTM[317]="*So ime pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe**They give up these five hindrances, corruptions of the heart that weaken wisdom.*";
P_HTM[318]="*vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Then, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, they enter and remain in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[319]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, saphalo upakkamo hoti, saphalaṃ padhānaṃ.**That too is how exertion and striving is fruitful.*";
P_HTM[320]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[321]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, saphalo upakkamo hoti, saphalaṃ padhānaṃ.**That too is how exertion and striving is fruitful.*";
P_HTM[322]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato ca sampajāno, sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti. Yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, with the fading away of rapture, a mendicant enters and remains in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[323]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, saphalo upakkamo hoti, saphalaṃ padhānaṃ.**That too is how exertion and striving is fruitful.*";
P_HTM[324]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā, pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā, adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[325]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, saphalo upakkamo hoti, saphalaṃ padhānaṃ.**That too is how exertion and striving is fruitful.*";
P_HTM[326]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte pubbenivāsānussatiñāṇāya cittaṃ abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it toward recollection of past lives.*";
P_HTM[327]="*So anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo dasapi jātiyo vīsampi jātiyo tiṃsampi jātiyo cattālīsampi jātiyo paññāsampi jātiyo jātisatampi jātisahassampi jātisatasahassampi anekepi saṃvaṭṭakappe anekepi vivaṭṭakappe anekepi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭakappe: ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**They recollect many kinds of past lives, that is, one, two, three, four, five, ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand rebirths; many eons of the world contracting, many eons of the world expanding, many eons of the world contracting and expanding. They remember: ‘There, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn somewhere else. There, too, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn here.’ And so they recollect their many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[328]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, saphalo upakkamo hoti, saphalaṃ padhānaṃ.**That too is how exertion and striving is fruitful.*";
P_HTM[329]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte sattānaṃ cutūpapātañāṇāya cittaṃ abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it toward knowledge of the death and rebirth of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[330]="*So dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe, sugate duggate yathākammūpage satte pajānāti: ‘ime vata bhonto sattā kāyaduccaritena samannāgatā vacīduccaritena samannāgatā manoduccaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ upavādakā micchādiṭṭhikā micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānā, te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannā. Ime vā pana bhonto sattā kāyasucaritena samannāgatā vacīsucaritena samannāgatā manosucaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ anupavādakā sammādiṭṭhikā sammādiṭṭhikammasamādānā, te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannā’ti. Iti dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe, sugate duggate yathākammūpage satte pajānāti.**With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understood how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds: ‘These dear beings did bad things by way of body, speech, and mind. They spoke ill of the noble ones; they had wrong view; and they chose to act out of that wrong view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell. These dear beings, however, did good things by way of body, speech, and mind. They never spoke ill of the noble ones; they had right view; and they chose to act out of that right view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.’ And so, with clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds.*";
P_HTM[331]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, saphalo upakkamo hoti, saphalaṃ padhānaṃ.**That too is how exertion and striving is fruitful.*";
P_HTM[332]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte āsavānaṃ khayañāṇāya cittaṃ abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it toward knowledge of the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[333]="*So ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**They truly understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[334]="*‘ime āsavā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ āsavasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ āsavanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ āsavanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand: ‘These are defilements’ … ‘This is the origin of defilements’ … ‘This is the cessation of defilements’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of defilements’.*";
P_HTM[335]="*Tassa evaṃ jānato evaṃ passato kāmāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, bhavāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, avijjāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati.**Knowing and seeing like this, their mind is freed from the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[336]="*Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[337]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[338]="*Evampi kho, bhikkhave, saphalo upakkamo hoti, saphalaṃ padhānaṃ.**That too is how exertion and striving is fruitful.*";
P_HTM[339]="*Evaṃvādī, bhikkhave, tathāgatā.**Such is the doctrine of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[340]="*Evaṃvādīnaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ dasa sahadhammikā pāsaṃsaṭṭhānā āgacchanti.**Saying this, the Realized One deserves praise on ten legitimate grounds.*";
P_HTM[341]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā pubbekatahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti;**If sentient beings experience pleasure and pain because of past deeds,*";
P_HTM[342]="*addhā, bhikkhave, tathāgato pubbe sukatakammakārī yaṃ etarahi evarūpā anāsavā sukhā vedanā vedeti.**clearly the Realized One has done good deeds in the past, since he now experiences such undefiled pleasure.*";
P_HTM[343]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā issaranimmānahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti;**If sentient beings experience pleasure and pain because of the Lord God’s creation,*";
P_HTM[344]="*addhā, bhikkhave, tathāgato bhaddakena issarena nimmito yaṃ etarahi evarūpā anāsavā sukhā vedanā vedeti.**clearly the Realized One was created by a good God, since he now experiences such undefiled pleasure.*";
P_HTM[345]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā saṅgatibhāvahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti;**If sentient beings experience pleasure and pain because of circumstance and nature,*";
P_HTM[346]="*addhā, bhikkhave, tathāgato kalyāṇasaṅgatiko yaṃ etarahi evarūpā anāsavā sukhā vedanā vedeti.**clearly the Realized One arises from good circumstances, since he now experiences such undefiled pleasure.*";
P_HTM[347]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā abhijātihetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti;**If sentient beings experience pleasure and pain because of the class of rebirth,*";
P_HTM[348]="*addhā, bhikkhave, tathāgato kalyāṇābhijātiko yaṃ etarahi evarūpā anāsavā sukhā vedanā vedeti.**clearly the Realized One was reborn in a good class, since he now experiences such undefiled pleasure.*";
P_HTM[349]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā diṭṭhadhammūpakkamahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti;**If sentient beings experience pleasure and pain because of exertion in the present,*";
P_HTM[350]="*addhā, bhikkhave, tathāgato kalyāṇadiṭṭhadhammūpakkamo yaṃ etarahi evarūpā anāsavā sukhā vedanā vedeti.**clearly the Realized One exerts himself well in the present, since he now experiences such undefiled pleasure.*";
P_HTM[351]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā pubbekatahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, pāsaṃso tathāgato;**The Realized One deserves praise whether or not sentient beings experience pleasure and pain because of past deeds,*";
P_HTM[352]="*no ce sattā pubbekatahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, pāsaṃso tathāgato.* **";
P_HTM[353]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā issaranimmānahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, pāsaṃso tathāgato;**or the Lord God’s creation,*";
P_HTM[354]="*no ce sattā issaranimmānahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, pāsaṃso tathāgato.* **";
P_HTM[355]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā saṅgatibhāvahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, pāsaṃso tathāgato;**or circumstance and nature,*";
P_HTM[356]="*no ce sattā saṅgatibhāvahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, pāsaṃso tathāgato.* **";
P_HTM[357]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā abhijātihetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, pāsaṃso tathāgato;**or class of rebirth,*";
P_HTM[358]="*no ce sattā abhijātihetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, pāsaṃso tathāgato.* **";
P_HTM[359]="*Sace, bhikkhave, sattā diṭṭhadhammūpakkamahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, pāsaṃso tathāgato;* **";
P_HTM[360]="*no ce sattā diṭṭhadhammūpakkamahetu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, pāsaṃso tathāgato.**or exertion in the present.*";
P_HTM[361]="*Evaṃvādī, bhikkhave, tathāgatā.**Such is the doctrine of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[362]="*Evaṃvādīnaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ ime dasa sahadhammikā pāsaṃsaṭṭhānā āgacchantī”ti.**Saying this, the Realized One deserves praise on these ten legitimate grounds.”*";
P_HTM[363]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[364]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[365]="*Devadahasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[366]="*102. Pañcattayasutta**The Five and Three*";
P_HTM[367]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[368]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[369]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[370]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[371]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[372]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[373]="*“santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā aparantakappikā aparantānudiṭṭhino aparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhivuttipadāni abhivadanti.**“Mendicants, there are some ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the future, and assert various hypotheses concerning the future.*";
P_HTM[374]="*‘Saññī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā’ti—**Some propose this: ‘The self is percipient and is sound after death.’*";
P_HTM[375]="*ittheke abhivadanti;* **";
P_HTM[376]="*‘asaññī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā’ti—**Some propose this: ‘The self is non-percipient and is sound after death.’*";
P_HTM[377]="*ittheke abhivadanti;* **";
P_HTM[378]="*‘nevasaññīnāsaññī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā’ti—**Some propose this: ‘The self is neither percipient nor non-percipient and is sound after death.’*";
P_HTM[379]="*ittheke abhivadanti;* **";
P_HTM[380]="*sato vā pana sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti, diṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ vā paneke abhivadanti.**But some assert the annihilation, eradication, and obliteration of an existing being, while others propose extinguishment in the present life.*";
P_HTM[381]="*Iti santaṃ vā attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, sato vā pana sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti, diṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ vā paneke abhivadanti.**Thus they assert an existent self that is sound after death; or they assert the annihilation of an existing being; or they propose extinguishment in the present life.*";
P_HTM[382]="*Iti imāni pañca hutvā tīṇi honti, tīṇi hutvā pañca honti—**In this way five become three, and three become five.*";
P_HTM[383]="*ayamuddeso pañcattayassa.**This is the passage for recitation of the five and three.*";
P_HTM[384]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, rūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, arūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, rūpiñca arūpiñca vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, nevarūpiṃ nārūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, ekattasaññiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, nānattasaññiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, parittasaññiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, appamāṇasaññiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, etaṃ vā panekesaṃ upātivattataṃ viññāṇakasiṇameke abhivadanti appamāṇaṃ āneñjaṃ.**Now, the ascetics and brahmins who assert a self that is percipient and sound after death describe it as having form, or being formless, or both having form and being formless, or neither having form nor being formless. Or they describe it as of unified perception, or of diverse perception, or of limited perception, or of limitless perception. Or some among those who go beyond this propose universal consciousness, limitless and imperturbable.*";
P_HTM[385]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato abhijānāti.**The Realized One understands this as follows.*";
P_HTM[386]="*Ye kho te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, rūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, arūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, rūpiñca arūpiñca vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, nevarūpiṃ nārūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, ekattasaññiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, nānattasaññiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, parittasaññiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, appamāṇasaññiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, yā vā panetāsaṃ saññānaṃ parisuddhā paramā aggā anuttariyā akkhāyati—**There are ascetics and brahmins who assert a self that is percipient and sound after death, describing it as having form, or being formless, or both having form and being formless, or neither having form nor being formless. Or they describe it as of unified perception, or of diverse perception, or of limited perception, or of limitless perception.*";
P_HTM[387]="*yadi rūpasaññānaṃ yadi arūpasaññānaṃ yadi ekattasaññānaṃ yadi nānattasaññānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[388]="*‘Natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanameke abhivadanti appamāṇaṃ āneñjaṃ.**Or some, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, propose the dimension of nothingness, limitless and imperturbable. They declare that this is the purest, highest, best, and supreme of all those perceptions, whether of form or of formlessness or of unity or of diversity.*";
P_HTM[389]="*‘Tayidaṃ saṅkhataṃ oḷārikaṃ atthi kho pana saṅkhārānaṃ nirodho atthetan’ti—**‘All that is conditioned and coarse. But there is the cessation of conditions—that is real.’*";
P_HTM[390]="*iti viditvā tassa nissaraṇadassāvī tathāgato tadupātivatto.**Understanding thus and seeing the escape from it, the Realized One has gone beyond all that.*";
P_HTM[391]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, rūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, arūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, rūpiñca arūpiñca vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, nevarūpiṃ nārūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā.**Now, the ascetics and brahmins who assert a self that is non-percipient and sound after death describe it as having form, or being formless, or both having form and being formless, or neither having form nor being formless.*";
P_HTM[392]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā tesamete paṭikkosanti.**So they reject those who assert a self that is percipient and sound after death.*";
P_HTM[393]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[394]="*Saññā rogo saññā gaṇḍo saññā sallaṃ, etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ yadidaṃ: ‘asaññan’ti.**Because they believe that perception is a disease, a boil, a dart, and that the state of non-perception is peaceful and sublime.*";
P_HTM[395]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato abhijānāti**The Realized One understands this as follows.*";
P_HTM[396]="*ye kho te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, rūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, arūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, rūpiñca arūpiñca vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, nevarūpiṃ nārūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā.**There are ascetics and brahmins who assert a self that is non-percipient and sound after death, describing it as having form, or being formless, or both having form and being formless, or neither having form nor being formless.*";
P_HTM[397]="*Yo hi koci, bhikkhave, samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā evaṃ vadeyya:**But if any ascetic or brahmin should say this:*";
P_HTM[398]="*‘ahamaññatra rūpā, aññatra vedanāya, aññatra saññāya, aññatra saṅkhārehi, viññāṇassa āgatiṃ vā gatiṃ vā cutiṃ vā upapattiṃ vā vuddhiṃ vā virūḷhiṃ vā vepullaṃ vā paññapessāmī’ti—**‘Apart from form, feeling, perception, and choices, I will describe the coming and going of consciousness, its passing away and reappearing, its growth, increase, and maturity.’*";
P_HTM[399]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[400]="*‘Tayidaṃ saṅkhataṃ oḷārikaṃ atthi kho pana saṅkhārānaṃ nirodho atthetan’ti—**‘All that is conditioned and coarse. But there is the cessation of conditions—that is real.’*";
P_HTM[401]="*iti viditvā tassa nissaraṇadassāvī tathāgato tadupātivatto.**Understanding this and seeing the escape from it, the Realized One has gone beyond all that.*";
P_HTM[402]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, rūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, arūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, rūpiñca arūpiñca vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, nevarūpiṃ nārūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā.**Now, the ascetics and brahmins who assert a self that is neither percipient nor non-percipient and sound after death describe it as having form, or being formless, or both having form and being formless, or neither having form nor being formless.*";
P_HTM[403]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā tesamete paṭikkosanti, yepi te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā tesamete paṭikkosanti.**So they reject those who assert a self that is percipient and sound after death, as well as those who assert a self that is non-percipient and sound after death.*";
P_HTM[404]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[405]="*Saññā rogo saññā gaṇḍo saññā sallaṃ, asaññā sammoho, etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ yadidaṃ:**Because they believe that perception is a disease, a boil, a dart, and that the state of neither perception nor non-perception is peaceful and sublime.*";
P_HTM[406]="*‘nevasaññānāsaññan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[407]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato abhijānāti.**The Realized One understands this as follows.*";
P_HTM[408]="*Ye kho te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, rūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, arūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, rūpiñca arūpiñca vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā, nevarūpiṃ nārūpiṃ vā te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā.**There are ascetics and brahmins who assert a self that is neither percipient nor non-percipient and sound after death, describing it as having form, or being formless, or both having form and being formless, or neither having form nor being formless.*";
P_HTM[409]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā diṭṭhasutamutaviññātabbasaṅkhāramattena etassa āyatanassa upasampadaṃ paññapenti, byasanañhetaṃ, bhikkhave, akkhāyati etassa āyatanassa upasampadāya.**Some ascetics or brahmins assert the embracing of that dimension merely through the conditioned phenomena of what is seen, heard, thought, and known. But that is said to be a disastrous approach.*";
P_HTM[410]="*Na hetaṃ, bhikkhave, āyatanaṃ saṅkhārasamāpattipattabbamakkhāyati;**For that dimension is said to be not attainable by means of conditioned phenomena,*";
P_HTM[411]="*saṅkhārāvasesasamāpattipattabbametaṃ, bhikkhave, āyatanamakkhāyati.**but only with a residue of conditioned phenomena.*";
P_HTM[412]="*‘Tayidaṃ saṅkhataṃ oḷārikaṃ atthi kho pana saṅkhārānaṃ nirodho atthetan’ti—**‘All that is conditioned and coarse. But there is the cessation of conditions—that is real.’*";
P_HTM[413]="*iti viditvā tassa nissaraṇadassāvī tathāgato tadupātivatto.**Understanding this and seeing the escape from it, the Realized One has gone beyond all that.*";
P_HTM[414]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti, tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā tesamete paṭikkosanti, yepi te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā tesamete paṭikkosanti, yepi te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti arogaṃ paraṃ maraṇā tesamete paṭikkosanti.**Now, the ascetics and brahmins who assert the annihilation, eradication, and obliteration of an existing being reject those who assert a self that is sound after death, whether percipient or non-percipient or neither percipient non-percipient.*";
P_HTM[415]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[416]="*Sabbepime bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhaṃ saraṃ āsattiṃyeva abhivadanti:**Because all of those ascetics and brahmins only assert their attachment to moving up to a higher realm:*";
P_HTM[417]="*‘iti pecca bhavissāma, iti pecca bhavissāmā’ti.**‘After death we shall be like this! After death we shall be like that!’*";
P_HTM[418]="*Seyyathāpi nāma vāṇijassa vāṇijjāya gacchato evaṃ hoti:**Suppose a trader was going to market, thinking:*";
P_HTM[419]="*‘ito me idaṃ bhavissati, iminā idaṃ lacchāmī’ti;**‘With this, that shall be mine! This way, I shall get that!’*";
P_HTM[420]="*evamevime bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā vāṇijūpamā maññe paṭibhanti:**In the same way, those ascetics and brahmins seem to be like traders when they say:*";
P_HTM[421]="*‘iti pecca bhavissāma, iti pecca bhavissāmā’ti.**‘After death we shall be like this! After death we shall be like that!’*";
P_HTM[422]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato abhijānāti.**The Realized One understands this as follows.*";
P_HTM[423]="*Ye kho te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti te sakkāyabhayā sakkāyaparijegucchā sakkāyaññeva anuparidhāvanti anuparivattanti.**The ascetics and brahmins who assert the annihilation, eradication, and obliteration of an existing being; from fear and disgust with identity, they just keep running and circling around identity.*";
P_HTM[424]="*Seyyathāpi nāma sā gaddulabaddho daḷhe thambhe vā khile vā upanibaddho, tameva thambhaṃ vā khilaṃ vā anuparidhāvati anuparivattati;**Suppose a dog on a leash was tethered to a strong post or pillar. It would just keeping running and circling around that post or pillar.*";
P_HTM[425]="*evamevime bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā sakkāyabhayā sakkāyaparijegucchā sakkāyaññeva anuparidhāvanti anuparivattanti.**In the same way, those ascetics and brahmins, from fear and disgust with identity, just keep running and circling around identity.*";
P_HTM[426]="*‘Tayidaṃ saṅkhataṃ oḷārikaṃ atthi kho pana saṅkhārānaṃ nirodho atthetan’ti—**‘All that is conditioned and coarse. But there is the cessation of conditions—that is real.’*";
P_HTM[427]="*iti viditvā tassa nissaraṇadassāvī tathāgato tadupātivatto.**Understanding this and seeing the escape from it, the Realized One has gone beyond all that.*";
P_HTM[428]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā aparantakappikā aparantānudiṭṭhino aparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhivuttipadāni abhivadanti, sabbe te imāneva pañcāyatanāni abhivadanti etesaṃ vā aññataraṃ.**Whatever ascetics and brahmins theorize about the future, and propose various hypotheses concerning the future, all of them propose one or other of these five theses.*";
P_HTM[429]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā pubbantānudiṭṭhino pubbantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhivuttipadāni abhivadanti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past, and propose various hypotheses concerning the past. They propose the following, each insisting that theirs is the only truth and that everything else is wrong.*";
P_HTM[430]="*‘Sassato attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos are eternal.’*";
P_HTM[431]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘asassato attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos are not eternal.’*";
P_HTM[432]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘sassato ca asassato ca attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos are both eternal and not eternal.’*";
P_HTM[433]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘nevasassato nāsassato attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos are neither eternal nor not eternal.’*";
P_HTM[434]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘antavā attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos are finite.’*";
P_HTM[435]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘anantavā attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos are infinite.’*";
P_HTM[436]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘antavā ca anantavā ca attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos are both finite and infinite.’*";
P_HTM[437]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘nevantavā nānantavā attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos are neither finite nor infinite.’*";
P_HTM[438]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘ekattasaññī attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos are unified in perception.’*";
P_HTM[439]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘nānattasaññī attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos are diverse in perception.’*";
P_HTM[440]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘parittasaññī attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos have limited perception.’*";
P_HTM[441]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘appamāṇasaññī attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos have limitless perception.’*";
P_HTM[442]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘ekantasukhī attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos experience nothing but happiness.’*";
P_HTM[443]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘ekantadukkhī attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos experience nothing but suffering.’*";
P_HTM[444]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘sukhadukkhī attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos experience both happiness and suffering.’*";
P_HTM[445]="*ittheke abhivadanti, ‘adukkhamasukhī attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti—**‘The self and the cosmos experience neither happiness nor suffering.’*";
P_HTM[446]="*ittheke abhivadanti.* **";
P_HTM[447]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**Now, consider the ascetics and brahmins whose view is as follows.*";
P_HTM[448]="*‘sassato attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti, tesaṃ vata aññatreva saddhāya aññatra ruciyā aññatra anussavā aññatra ākāraparivitakkā aññatra diṭṭhinijjhānakkhantiyā paccattaṃyeva ñāṇaṃ bhavissati parisuddhaṃ pariyodātanti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**‘The self and the cosmos are eternal. This is the only truth, other ideas are silly.’ It’s simply not possible for them to have purified and clear personal knowledge of this, apart from faith, preference, oral tradition, reasoned contemplation, or acceptance of a view after consideration.*";
P_HTM[449]="*Paccattaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, ñāṇe asati parisuddhe pariyodāte yadapi te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā tattha ñāṇabhāgamattameva pariyodapenti tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ upādānamakkhāyati.**And in the absence of such knowledge, even the partial knowledge that they are clear about is said to be grasping on their part.*";
P_HTM[450]="*‘Tayidaṃ saṅkhataṃ oḷārikaṃ atthi kho pana saṅkhārānaṃ nirodho atthetan’ti—**‘All that is conditioned and coarse. But there is the cessation of conditions—that is real.’*";
P_HTM[451]="*iti viditvā tassa nissaraṇadassāvī tathāgato tadupātivatto.**Understanding this and seeing the escape from it, the Realized One has gone beyond all that.*";
P_HTM[452]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**Now, consider the ascetics and brahmins whose view is as follows.*";
P_HTM[453]="*‘asassato attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti … pe …**The self and the cosmos are not eternal,*";
P_HTM[454]="*sassato ca asassato ca attā ca loko ca …**or both eternal and not eternal,*";
P_HTM[455]="*nevasassato nāsassato attā ca loko ca …**or neither eternal nor not-eternal,*";
P_HTM[456]="*antavā attā ca loko ca …**or finite,*";
P_HTM[457]="*anantavā attā ca loko ca …**or infinite,*";
P_HTM[458]="*antavā ca anantavā ca attā ca loko ca …**or both finite and infinite,*";
P_HTM[459]="*nevantavā nānantavā attā ca loko ca …**or neither finite nor infinite,*";
P_HTM[460]="*ekattasaññī attā ca loko ca …**or of unified perception,*";
P_HTM[461]="*nānattasaññī attā ca loko ca …**or of diverse perception,*";
P_HTM[462]="*parittasaññī attā ca loko ca …**or of limited perception,*";
P_HTM[463]="*appamāṇasaññī attā ca loko ca …**or of limitless perception,*";
P_HTM[464]="*ekantasukhī attā ca loko ca …**or experience nothing but happiness,*";
P_HTM[465]="*ekantadukkhī attā ca loko ca …**or experience nothing but suffering,*";
P_HTM[466]="*sukhadukkhī attā ca loko ca …**or experience both happiness and suffering,*";
P_HTM[467]="*adukkhamasukhī attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññanti, tesaṃ vata aññatreva saddhāya aññatra ruciyā aññatra anussavā aññatra ākāraparivitakkā aññatra diṭṭhinijjhānakkhantiyā paccattaṃyeva ñāṇaṃ bhavissati parisuddhaṃ pariyodātanti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**or experience neither happiness nor suffering. It’s simply not possible for them to have purified and clear personal knowledge of this, apart from faith, preference, oral tradition, reasoned contemplation, or acceptance of a view after consideration.*";
P_HTM[468]="*Paccattaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, ñāṇe asati parisuddhe pariyodāte yadapi te bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā tattha ñāṇabhāgamattameva pariyodapenti tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ upādānamakkhāyati.**And in the absence of such knowledge, even the partial knowledge that they are clear about is said to be grasping on their part.*";
P_HTM[469]="*‘Tayidaṃ saṅkhataṃ oḷārikaṃ atthi kho pana saṅkhārānaṃ nirodho atthetan’ti—**‘All that is conditioned and coarse. But there is the cessation of conditions—that is real.’*";
P_HTM[470]="*iti viditvā tassa nissaraṇadassāvī tathāgato tadupātivatto.**Understanding this and seeing the escape from it, the Realized One has gone beyond all that.*";
P_HTM[471]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā pubbantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, aparantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, sabbaso kāmasaṃyojanānaṃ anadhiṭṭhānā, pavivekaṃ pītiṃ upasampajja viharati:**Now, some ascetics and brahmins, letting go of theories about the past and the future, shedding the fetters of sensuality, enter and remain in the rapture of seclusion:*";
P_HTM[472]="*‘etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ yadidaṃ pavivekaṃ pītiṃ upasampajja viharāmī’ti.**‘This is peaceful, this is sublime, that is, entering and remaining in the rapture of seclusion.’*";
P_HTM[473]="*Tassa sā pavivekā pīti nirujjhati.**But that rapture of seclusion of theirs ceases.*";
P_HTM[474]="*Pavivekāya pītiyā nirodhā uppajjati domanassaṃ, domanassassa nirodhā uppajjati pavivekā pīti.**When the rapture of seclusion ceases, sadness arises; and when sadness ceases, the rapture of seclusion arises.*";
P_HTM[475]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yaṃ chāyā jahati taṃ ātapo pharati, yaṃ ātapo jahati taṃ chāyā pharati;**It’s like how the sunlight fills the space when the shadow leaves, or the shadow fills the space when the sunshine leaves.*";
P_HTM[476]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, pavivekāya pītiyā nirodhā uppajjati domanassaṃ, domanassassa nirodhā uppajjati pavivekā pīti.**In the same way, when the rapture of seclusion ceases, sadness arises; and when sadness ceases, the rapture of seclusion arises.*";
P_HTM[477]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato abhijānāti.**The Realized One understands this as follows.*";
P_HTM[478]="*Ayaṃ kho bhavaṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā pubbantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, aparantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, sabbaso kāmasaṃyojanānaṃ anadhiṭṭhānā, pavivekaṃ pītiṃ upasampajja viharati:**This good ascetic or brahmin, letting go of theories about the past and the future, shedding the fetters of sensuality, enters and remains in the rapture of seclusion:*";
P_HTM[479]="*‘etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ yadidaṃ pavivekaṃ pītiṃ upasampajja viharāmī’ti.**‘This is peaceful, this is sublime, that is, entering and remaining in the rapture of seclusion.’*";
P_HTM[480]="*Tassa sā pavivekā pīti nirujjhati.**But that rapture of seclusion of theirs ceases.*";
P_HTM[481]="*Pavivekāya pītiyā nirodhā uppajjati domanassaṃ, domanassassa nirodhā uppajjati pavivekā pīti.**When the rapture of seclusion ceases, sadness arises; and when sadness ceases, the rapture of seclusion arises.*";
P_HTM[482]="*‘Tayidaṃ saṅkhataṃ oḷārikaṃ atthi kho pana saṅkhārānaṃ nirodho atthetan’ti—**‘All that is conditioned and coarse. But there is the cessation of conditions—that is real.’*";
P_HTM[483]="*iti viditvā tassa nissaraṇadassāvī tathāgato tadupātivatto.**Understanding this and seeing the escape from it, the Realized One has gone beyond all that.*";
P_HTM[484]="*Idha pana, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā pubbantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, aparantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, sabbaso kāmasaṃyojanānaṃ anadhiṭṭhānā, pavivekāya pītiyā samatikkamā nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ upasampajja viharati:**Now, some ascetics and brahmins, letting go of theories about the past and the future, shedding the fetters of sensuality, going beyond the rapture of seclusion, enter and remain in spiritual bliss.*";
P_HTM[485]="*‘etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ yadidaṃ nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ upasampajja viharāmī’ti.**‘This is peaceful, this is sublime, that is, entering and remaining in spiritual bliss.’*";
P_HTM[486]="*Tassa taṃ nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ nirujjhati.**But that spiritual bliss of theirs ceases.*";
P_HTM[487]="*Nirāmisassa sukhassa nirodhā uppajjati pavivekā pīti, pavivekāya pītiyā nirodhā uppajjati nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ.**When spiritual bliss ceases, the rapture of seclusion arises; and when the rapture of seclusion ceases, spiritual bliss arises.*";
P_HTM[488]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yaṃ chāyā jahati taṃ ātapo pharati, yaṃ ātapo jahati taṃ chāyā pharati;**It’s like how the sunlight fills the space when the shadow leaves, or the shadow fills the space when the sunshine leaves. …*";
P_HTM[489]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, nirāmisassa sukhassa nirodhā uppajjati pavivekā pīti, pavivekāya pītiyā nirodhā uppajjati nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[490]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato abhijānāti.**The Realized One understands this as follows.*";
P_HTM[491]="*Ayaṃ kho bhavaṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā pubbantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, aparantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, sabbaso kāmasaṃyojanānaṃ anadhiṭṭhānā, pavivekāya pītiyā samatikkamā, nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ upasampajja viharati:**This good ascetic or brahmin, letting go of theories about the past and the future, shedding the fetters of sensuality, going beyond the rapture of seclusion, enters and remains in spiritual bliss.*";
P_HTM[492]="*‘etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ yadidaṃ nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ upasampajja viharāmī’ti.**‘This is peaceful, this is sublime, that is, entering and remaining in spiritual bliss.’*";
P_HTM[493]="*Tassa taṃ nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ nirujjhati.**But that spiritual bliss of theirs ceases.*";
P_HTM[494]="*Nirāmisassa sukhassa nirodhā uppajjati pavivekā pīti, pavivekāya pītiyā nirodhā uppajjati nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ.**When spiritual bliss ceases, the rapture of seclusion arises; and when the rapture of seclusion ceases, spiritual bliss arises.*";
P_HTM[495]="*‘Tayidaṃ saṅkhataṃ oḷārikaṃ atthi kho pana saṅkhārānaṃ nirodho atthetan’ti—**‘All that is conditioned and coarse. But there is the cessation of conditions—that is real.’*";
P_HTM[496]="*iti viditvā tassa nissaraṇadassāvī tathāgato tadupātivatto.**Understanding this and seeing the escape from it, the Realized One has gone beyond all that.*";
P_HTM[497]="*Idha pana, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā pubbantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, aparantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, sabbaso kāmasaṃyojanānaṃ anadhiṭṭhānā, pavivekāya pītiyā samatikkamā, nirāmisassa sukhassa samatikkamā, adukkhamasukhaṃ vedanaṃ upasampajja viharati:**Now, some ascetics and brahmins, letting go of theories about the past and the future, shedding the fetters of sensuality, going beyond the rapture of seclusion and spiritual bliss, enter and remain in neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[498]="*‘etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ yadidaṃ adukkhamasukhaṃ vedanaṃ upasampajja viharāmī’ti.**‘This is peaceful, this is sublime, that is, entering and remaining in neutral feeling.’*";
P_HTM[499]="*Tassa sā adukkhamasukhā vedanā nirujjhati.**Then that neutral feeling ceases.*";
P_HTM[500]="*Adukkhamasukhāya vedanāya nirodhā uppajjati nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ, nirāmisassa sukhassa nirodhā uppajjati adukkhamasukhā vedanā.**When neutral feeling ceases, spiritual bliss arises; and when spiritual bliss ceases, neutral feelings arises.*";
P_HTM[501]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yaṃ chāyā jahati taṃ ātapo pharati, yaṃ ātapo jahati taṃ chāyā pharati;**It’s like how the sunlight fills the space when the shadow leaves, or the shadow fills the space when the sunshine leaves. …*";
P_HTM[502]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, adukkhamasukhāya vedanāya nirodhā uppajjati nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ, nirāmisassa sukhassa nirodhā uppajjati adukkhamasukhā vedanā.* **";
P_HTM[503]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato abhijānāti.**The Realized One understands this as follows.*";
P_HTM[504]="*Ayaṃ kho bhavaṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā pubbantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, aparantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, sabbaso kāmasaṃyojanānaṃ anadhiṭṭhānā, pavivekāya pītiyā samatikkamā, nirāmisassa sukhassa samatikkamā, adukkhamasukhaṃ vedanaṃ upasampajja viharati:**This good ascetic or brahmin, letting go of theories about the past and the future, shedding the fetters of sensuality, going beyond the rapture of seclusion and spiritual bliss, enters and remains in neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[505]="*‘etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ yadidaṃ adukkhamasukhaṃ vedanaṃ upasampajja viharāmī’ti.**‘This is peaceful, this is sublime, that is, entering and remaining in neutral feeling.’*";
P_HTM[506]="*Tassa sā adukkhamasukhā vedanā nirujjhati.**Then that neutral feeling ceases.*";
P_HTM[507]="*Adukkhamasukhāya vedanāya nirodhā uppajjati nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ, nirāmisassa sukhassa nirodhā uppajjati adukkhamasukhā vedanā.**When neutral feeling ceases, spiritual bliss arises; and when spiritual bliss ceases, neutral feelings arises.*";
P_HTM[508]="*‘Tayidaṃ saṅkhataṃ oḷārikaṃ atthi kho pana saṅkhārānaṃ nirodho atthetan’ti—**‘All that is conditioned and coarse. But there is the cessation of conditions—that is real.’*";
P_HTM[509]="*iti viditvā tassa nissaraṇadassāvī tathāgato tadupātivatto.**Understanding this and seeing the escape from it, the Realized One has gone beyond all that.*";
P_HTM[510]="*Idha pana, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā pubbantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, aparantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, sabbaso kāmasaṃyojanānaṃ anadhiṭṭhānā, pavivekāya pītiyā samatikkamā, nirāmisassa sukhassa samatikkamā, adukkhamasukhāya vedanāya samatikkamā:**Now, some ascetics and brahmins, letting go of theories about the past and the future, shedding the fetters of sensuality, go beyond the rapture of seclusion, spiritual bliss, and neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[511]="*‘santohamasmi, nibbutohamasmi, anupādānohamasmī’ti samanupassati.**They regard themselves like this: ‘I am at peace; I am extinguished; I am free of grasping.’*";
P_HTM[512]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato abhijānāti.**The Realized One understands this as follows.*";
P_HTM[513]="*Ayaṃ kho bhavaṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā pubbantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, aparantānudiṭṭhīnañca paṭinissaggā, sabbaso kāmasaṃyojanānaṃ anadhiṭṭhānā, pavivekāya pītiyā samatikkamā, nirāmisassa sukhassa samatikkamā, adukkhamasukhāya vedanāya samatikkamā:**This good ascetic or brahmin, letting go of theories about the past and the future, shedding the fetters of sensuality, goes beyond the rapture of seclusion, spiritual bliss, and neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[514]="*‘santohamasmi, nibbutohamasmi, anupādānohamasmī’ti samanupassati;**They regard themselves like this: ‘I am at peace; I am extinguished; I am free of grasping.’*";
P_HTM[515]="*addhā ayamāyasmā nibbānasappāyaṃyeva paṭipadaṃ abhivadati.**Clearly this venerable speaks of a practice that’s conducive to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[516]="*Atha ca panāyaṃ bhavaṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā pubbantānudiṭṭhiṃ vā upādiyamāno upādiyati, aparantānudiṭṭhiṃ vā upādiyamāno upādiyati, kāmasaṃyojanaṃ vā upādiyamāno upādiyati, pavivekaṃ vā pītiṃ upādiyamāno upādiyati, nirāmisaṃ vā sukhaṃ upādiyamāno upādiyati, adukkhamasukhaṃ vā vedanaṃ upādiyamāno upādiyati.**Nevertheless, they still grasp at theories about the past or the future, or the fetters of sensuality, or the rapture of seclusion, or spiritual bliss, or neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[517]="*Yañca kho ayamāyasmā:**And when they regard themselves like this:*";
P_HTM[518]="*‘santohamasmi, nibbutohamasmi, anupādānohamasmī’ti samanupassati tadapi imassa bhoto samaṇassa brāhmaṇassa upādānamakkhāyati.**‘I am at peace; I am extinguished; I am free of grasping,’ that’s also said to be grasping on their part.*";
P_HTM[519]="*‘Tayidaṃ saṅkhataṃ oḷārikaṃ atthi kho pana saṅkhārānaṃ nirodho atthetan’ti—**‘All that is conditioned and coarse. But there is the cessation of conditions—that is real.’*";
P_HTM[520]="*iti viditvā tassa nissaraṇadassāvī tathāgato tadupātivatto.**Understanding this and seeing the escape from it, the Realized One has gone beyond all that.*";
P_HTM[521]="*Idaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, tathāgatena anuttaraṃ santivarapadaṃ abhisambuddhaṃ yadidaṃ—**But the Realized One has awakened to the supreme state of sublime peace, that is,*";
P_HTM[522]="*channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimokkho”ti.**liberation by not grasping after truly understanding these six sense fields’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.”*";
P_HTM[523]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[524]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[525]="*Pañcattayasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[526]="*103. Kintisutta**Is This What You Think Of Me?*";
P_HTM[527]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[528]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā pisinārāyaṃ viharati baliharaṇe vanasaṇḍe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Kusināra, in the Forest of Offerings.*";
P_HTM[529]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[530]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[531]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[532]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[533]="*“kinti vo, bhikkhave, mayi hoti:**“Mendicants, is this what you think of me?*";
P_HTM[534]="*‘cīvarahetu vā samaṇo gotamo dhammaṃ deseti, piṇḍapātahetu vā samaṇo gotamo dhammaṃ deseti, senāsanahetu vā samaṇo gotamo dhammaṃ deseti, itibhavābhavahetu vā samaṇo gotamo dhammaṃ desetī’”ti?**‘The ascetic Gotama teaches the Dhamma for the sake of robes, alms-food, lodgings, or rebirth in this or that state.’”*";
P_HTM[535]="*“Na kho no, bhante, bhagavati evaṃ hoti:**“No sir, we don’t think of you that way.”*";
P_HTM[536]="*‘cīvarahetu vā samaṇo gotamo dhammaṃ deseti, piṇḍapātahetu vā samaṇo gotamo dhammaṃ deseti, senāsanahetu vā samaṇo gotamo dhammaṃ deseti, itibhavābhavahetu vā samaṇo gotamo dhammaṃ desetī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[537]="*“Na ca kira vo, bhikkhave, mayi evaṃ hoti:**“If you don’t think of me that way,*";
P_HTM[538]="*‘cīvarahetu vā samaṇo gotamo dhammaṃ deseti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[539]="*itibhavābhavahetu vā samaṇo gotamo dhammaṃ desetī’ti;* **";
P_HTM[540]="*atha kinti carahi vo, bhikkhave, mayi hotī”ti?**then what exactly do you think of me?”*";
P_HTM[541]="*“Evaṃ kho no, bhante, bhagavati hoti:**“We think of you this way:*";
P_HTM[542]="*‘anukampako bhagavā hitesī;**‘The Buddha is compassionate and wants what’s best for us.*";
P_HTM[543]="*anukampaṃ upādāya dhammaṃ desetī’”ti.**He teaches out of compassion.’”*";
P_HTM[544]="*“Evañca kira vo, bhikkhave, mayi hoti:**“So it seems you think*";
P_HTM[545]="*‘anukampako bhagavā hitesī;* **";
P_HTM[546]="*anukampaṃ upādāya dhammaṃ desetī’ti.**that I teach out of compassion.*";
P_HTM[547]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ye vo mayā dhammā abhiññā desitā, seyyathidaṃ—**In that case, each and every one of you should train in the things I have taught from my direct knowledge, that is:*";
P_HTM[548]="*cattāro satipaṭṭhānā cattāro sammappadhānā cattāro iddhipādā pañcindriyāni pañca balāni satta bojjhaṅgā ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, tattha sabbeheva samaggehi sammodamānehi avivadamānehi sikkhitabbaṃ.**the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, the four right efforts, the four bases of psychic power, the five faculties, the five powers, the seven awakening factors, and the noble eightfold path. You should train in these things in harmony, appreciating each other, without quarreling.*";
P_HTM[549]="*Tesañca vo, bhikkhave, samaggānaṃ sammodamānānaṃ avivadamānānaṃ sikkhataṃ siyaṃsu dve bhikkhū abhidhamme nānāvādā.**As you do so, it may happen that two mendicants disagree about the teaching.*";
P_HTM[550]="*Tatra ce tumhākaṃ evamassa:**Now, you might think,*";
P_HTM[551]="*‘imesaṃ kho āyasmantānaṃ atthato ceva nānaṃ byañjanato ca nānan’ti, tattha yaṃ bhikkhuṃ suvacataraṃ maññeyyātha so upasaṅkamitvā evamassa vacanīyo:**‘These two venerables disagree on both the meaning and the phrasing.’ So you should approach whichever mendicant you think is most amenable and say to them:*";
P_HTM[552]="*‘āyasmantānaṃ kho atthato ceva nānaṃ, byañjanato ca nānaṃ.**‘The venerables disagree on the meaning and the phrasing.*";
P_HTM[553]="*Tadamināpetaṃ āyasmanto jānātha—**But the venerables should know that this is how*";
P_HTM[554]="*yathā atthato ceva nānaṃ, byañjanato ca nānaṃ.**such disagreement on the meaning and the phrasing comes to be.*";
P_HTM[555]="*Māyasmanto vivādaṃ āpajjitthā’ti.**Please don’t get into a fight about this.’*";
P_HTM[556]="*Athāparesaṃ ekatopakkhikānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ yaṃ bhikkhuṃ suvacataraṃ maññeyyātha so upasaṅkamitvā evamassa vacanīyo:**Then they should approach whichever mendicant they think is most amenable among those who side with the other party and say to them:*";
P_HTM[557]="*‘āyasmantānaṃ kho atthato ceva nānaṃ, byañjanato ca nānaṃ.**‘The venerables disagree on the meaning and the phrasing.*";
P_HTM[558]="*Tadamināpetaṃ āyasmanto jānātha—**But the venerables should know that this is how*";
P_HTM[559]="*yathā atthato ceva nānaṃ, byañjanato ca nānaṃ.**such disagreement on the meaning and the phrasing comes to be.*";
P_HTM[560]="*Māyasmanto vivādaṃ āpajjitthā’ti.**Please don’t get into a fight about this.’*";
P_HTM[561]="*Iti duggahitaṃ duggahitato dhāretabbaṃ, suggahitaṃ suggahitato dhāretabbaṃ.**So you should remember what has been incorrectly memorized as incorrectly memorized and what has been correctly memorized as correctly memorized.*";
P_HTM[562]="*Duggahitaṃ duggahitato dhāretvā suggahitaṃ suggahitato dhāretvā yo dhammo yo vinayo so bhāsitabbo.**Remembering this, you should speak on the teaching and the training.*";
P_HTM[563]="*Tatra ce tumhākaṃ evamassa:**Now, you might think,*";
P_HTM[564]="*‘imesaṃ kho āyasmantānaṃ atthato hi kho nānaṃ, byañjanato sametī’ti, tattha yaṃ bhikkhuṃ suvacataraṃ maññeyyātha so upasaṅkamitvā evamassa vacanīyo:**‘These two venerables disagree on the meaning but agree on the phrasing.’ So you should approach whichever mendicant you think is most amenable and say to them:*";
P_HTM[565]="*‘āyasmantānaṃ kho atthato hi nānaṃ, byañjanato sameti.**‘The venerables disagree on the meaning but agree on the phrasing.*";
P_HTM[566]="*Tadamināpetaṃ āyasmanto jānātha—**But the venerables should know that this is how*";
P_HTM[567]="*yathā atthato hi kho nānaṃ, byañjanato sameti.**such disagreement on the meaning and agreement on the phrasing comes to be.*";
P_HTM[568]="*Māyasmanto vivādaṃ āpajjitthā’ti.**Please don’t get into a fight about this.’*";
P_HTM[569]="*Athāparesaṃ ekatopakkhikānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ yaṃ bhikkhuṃ suvacataraṃ maññeyyātha so upasaṅkamitvā evamassa vacanīyo:**Then they should approach whichever mendicant they think is most amenable among those who side with the other party and say to them:*";
P_HTM[570]="*‘āyasmantānaṃ kho atthato hi kho nānaṃ, byañjanato sameti.**‘The venerables disagree on the meaning but agree on the phrasing.*";
P_HTM[571]="*Tadamināpetaṃ āyasmanto jānātha—**But the venerables should know that this is how*";
P_HTM[572]="*yathā atthato hi kho nānaṃ, byañjanato sameti.**such disagreement on the meaning and agreement on the phrasing comes to be.*";
P_HTM[573]="*Māyasmanto vivādaṃ āpajjitthā’ti.**Please don’t get into a fight about this.’*";
P_HTM[574]="*Iti duggahitaṃ duggahitato dhāretabbaṃ, suggahitaṃ suggahitato dhāretabbaṃ.**So you should remember what has been incorrectly memorized as incorrectly memorized and what has been correctly memorized as correctly memorized.*";
P_HTM[575]="*Duggahitaṃ duggahitato dhāretvā suggahitaṃ suggahitato dhāretvā yo dhammo yo vinayo so bhāsitabbo.**Remembering this, you should speak on the teaching and the training.*";
P_HTM[576]="*Tatra ce tumhākaṃ evamassa:**Now, you might think,*";
P_HTM[577]="*‘imesaṃ kho āyasmantānaṃ atthato hi kho sameti, byañjanato nānan’ti, tattha yaṃ bhikkhuṃ suvacataraṃ maññeyyātha so upasaṅkamitvā evamassa vacanīyo:**‘These two venerables agree on the meaning but disagree on the phrasing.’ So you should approach whichever mendicant you think is most amenable and say to them:*";
P_HTM[578]="*‘āyasmantānaṃ kho atthato hi sameti, byañjanato nānaṃ.**‘The venerables agree on the meaning but disagree on the phrasing.*";
P_HTM[579]="*Tadamināpetaṃ āyasmanto jānātha—**But the venerables should know that this is how*";
P_HTM[580]="*yathā atthato hi kho sameti, byañjanato nānaṃ.**such agreement on the meaning and disagreement on the phrasing comes to be.*";
P_HTM[581]="*Appamattakaṃ kho panetaṃ yadidaṃ—byañjanaṃ.**But the phrasing is a minor matter.*";
P_HTM[582]="*Māyasmanto appamattake vivādaṃ āpajjitthā’ti.**Please don’t get into a fight about something so minor.’*";
P_HTM[583]="*Athāparesaṃ ekatopakkhikānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ yaṃ bhikkhuṃ suvacataraṃ maññeyyātha so upasaṅkamitvā evamassa vacanīyo:**Then they should approach whichever mendicant they think is most amenable among those who side with the other party and say to them:*";
P_HTM[584]="*‘āyasmantānaṃ kho atthato hi sameti, byañjanato nānaṃ.**‘The venerables agree on the meaning but disagree on the phrasing.*";
P_HTM[585]="*Tadamināpetaṃ āyasmanto jānātha—**But the venerables should know that this is how*";
P_HTM[586]="*yathā atthato hi kho sameti, byañjanato nānaṃ.**such agreement on the meaning and disagreement on the phrasing comes to be.*";
P_HTM[587]="*Appamattakaṃ kho panetaṃ yadidaṃ—byañjanaṃ.**But the phrasing is a minor matter.*";
P_HTM[588]="*Māyasmanto appamattake vivādaṃ āpajjitthā’ti.**Please don’t get into a fight about something so minor.’*";
P_HTM[589]="*Iti suggahitaṃ suggahitato dhāretabbaṃ, duggahitaṃ duggahitato dhāretabbaṃ.**So you should remember what has been correctly memorized as correctly memorized and what has been incorrectly memorized as incorrectly memorized.*";
P_HTM[590]="*Suggahitaṃ suggahitato dhāretvā duggahitaṃ duggahitato dhāretvā yo dhammo yo vinayo so bhāsitabbo.**Remembering this, you should speak on the teaching and the training.*";
P_HTM[591]="*Tatra ce tumhākaṃ evamassa:**Now, you might think,*";
P_HTM[592]="*‘imesaṃ kho āyasmantānaṃ atthato ceva sameti byañjanato ca sametī’ti, tattha yaṃ bhikkhuṃ suvacataraṃ maññeyyātha so upasaṅkamitvā evamassa vacanīyo:**‘These two venerables agree on both the meaning and the phrasing.’ So you should approach whichever mendicant you think is most amenable and say to them:*";
P_HTM[593]="*‘āyasmantānaṃ kho atthato ceva sameti, byañjanato ca sameti.**‘The venerables agree on both the meaning and the phrasing.*";
P_HTM[594]="*Tadamināpetaṃ āyasmanto jānātha—**But the venerables should know that this is how*";
P_HTM[595]="*yathā atthato ceva sameti byañjanato ca sameti.**they come to agree on the meaning and the phrasing.*";
P_HTM[596]="*Māyasmanto vivādaṃ āpajjitthā’ti.**Please don’t get into a fight about this.’*";
P_HTM[597]="*Athāparesaṃ ekatopakkhikānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ yaṃ bhikkhuṃ suvacataraṃ maññeyyātha so upasaṅkamitvā evamassa vacanīyo:**Then they should approach whichever mendicant they think is most amenable among those who side with the other party and say to them:*";
P_HTM[598]="*‘āyasmantānaṃ kho atthato ceva sameti byañjanato ca sameti.**‘The venerables agree on both the meaning and the phrasing.*";
P_HTM[599]="*Tadamināpetaṃ āyasmanto jānātha—**But the venerables should know that this is how*";
P_HTM[600]="*yathā atthato ceva sameti byañjanato ca sameti.**they come to agree on the meaning and the phrasing.*";
P_HTM[601]="*Māyasmanto vivādaṃ āpajjitthā’ti.**Please don’t get into a fight about this.’*";
P_HTM[602]="*Iti suggahitaṃ suggahitato dhāretabbaṃ.**So you should remember what has been correctly memorized as correctly memorized.*";
P_HTM[603]="*Suggahitaṃ suggahitato dhāretvā yo dhammo yo vinayo so bhāsitabbo.**Remembering this, you should speak on the teaching and the training.*";
P_HTM[604]="*Tesañca vo, bhikkhave, samaggānaṃ sammodamānānaṃ avivadamānānaṃ sikkhataṃ siyā aññatarassa bhikkhuno āpatti siyā vītikkamo,**As you train in harmony, appreciating each other, without quarreling, one of the mendicants might commit an offense or transgression.*";
P_HTM[605]="*tatra, bhikkhave, na codanāya taritabbaṃ. Puggalo upaparikkhitabbo:**In such a case, you should not be in a hurry to accuse them. The individual should be examined like this:*";
P_HTM[606]="*‘iti mayhañca avihesā bhavissati parassa ca puggalassa anupaghāto, paro hi puggalo akkodhano anupanāhī adaḷhadiṭṭhī suppaṭinissaggī, sakkomi cāhaṃ etaṃ puggalaṃ akusalā vuṭṭhāpetvā kusale patiṭṭhāpetun’ti.**‘I won’t be troubled and the other individual won’t be hurt, for they’re not irritable and hostile. They don’t hold fast to their views, but let them go easily. I can draw them away from the unskillful and establish them in the skillful.’*";
P_HTM[607]="*Sace, bhikkhave, evamassa, kallaṃ vacanāya.**If that’s what you think, then it’s appropriate to speak to them.*";
P_HTM[608]="*Sace pana, bhikkhave, evamassa:**But suppose you think this:*";
P_HTM[609]="*‘mayhaṃ kho avihesā bhavissati parassa ca puggalassa upaghāto, paro hi puggalo kodhano upanāhī adaḷhadiṭṭhī suppaṭinissaggī, sakkomi cāhaṃ etaṃ puggalaṃ akusalā vuṭṭhāpetvā kusale patiṭṭhāpetuṃ.**‘I will be troubled and the other individual will be hurt, for they’re irritable and hostile. However, they don’t hold fast to their views, but let them go easily. I can draw them away from the unskillful and establish them in the skillful.*";
P_HTM[610]="*Appamattakaṃ kho panetaṃ yadidaṃ—parassa puggalassa upaghāto.**But for the other individual to get hurt is a minor matter.*";
P_HTM[611]="*Atha kho etadeva bahutaraṃ—**It’s more important*";
P_HTM[612]="*svāhaṃ sakkomi etaṃ puggalaṃ akusalā vuṭṭhāpetvā kusale patiṭṭhāpetun’ti.**that I can draw them away from the unskillful and establish them in the skillful.’*";
P_HTM[613]="*Sace, bhikkhave, evamassa, kallaṃ vacanāya.**If that’s what you think, then it’s appropriate to speak to them.*";
P_HTM[614]="*Sace pana, bhikkhave, evamassa:**But suppose you think this:*";
P_HTM[615]="*‘mayhaṃ kho vihesā bhavissati parassa ca puggalassa anupaghāto. Paro hi puggalo akkodhano anupanāhī daḷhadiṭṭhī duppaṭinissaggī, sakkomi cāhaṃ etaṃ puggalaṃ akusalā vuṭṭhāpetvā kusale patiṭṭhāpetuṃ.**‘I will be troubled but the other individual won’t be hurt, for they’re not irritable and hostile. However, they hold fast to their views, refusing to let go. Nevertheless, I can draw them away from the unskillful and establish them in the skillful.*";
P_HTM[616]="*Appamattakaṃ kho panetaṃ yadidaṃ—mayhaṃ vihesā.**But for me to be troubled is a minor matter.*";
P_HTM[617]="*Atha kho etadeva bahutaraṃ—**It’s more important*";
P_HTM[618]="*svāhaṃ sakkomi etaṃ puggalaṃ akusalā vuṭṭhāpetvā kusale patiṭṭhāpetun’ti.**that I can draw them away from the unskillful and establish them in the skillful.’*";
P_HTM[619]="*Sace, bhikkhave, evamassa, kallaṃ vacanāya.**If that’s what you think, then it’s appropriate to speak to them.*";
P_HTM[620]="*Sace pana, bhikkhave, evamassa:**But suppose you think this:*";
P_HTM[621]="*‘mayhañca kho vihesā bhavissati parassa ca puggalassa upaghāto. Paro hi puggalo kodhano upanāhī daḷhadiṭṭhī duppaṭinissaggī, sakkomi cāhaṃ etaṃ puggalaṃ akusalā vuṭṭhāpetvā kusale patiṭṭhāpetuṃ.**‘I will be troubled and the other individual will be hurt, for they’re irritable and hostile. And they hold fast to their views, refusing to let go. Nevertheless, I can draw them away from the unskillful and establish them in the skillful.*";
P_HTM[622]="*Appamattakaṃ kho panetaṃ yadidaṃ—mayhañca vihesā bhavissati parassa ca puggalassa upaghāto.**But for me to be troubled and the other individual to get hurt is a minor matter.*";
P_HTM[623]="*Atha kho etadeva bahutaraṃ—**It’s more important*";
P_HTM[624]="*svāhaṃ sakkomi etaṃ puggalaṃ akusalā vuṭṭhāpetvā kusale patiṭṭhāpetun’ti.**that I can draw them away from the unskillful and establish them in the skillful.’*";
P_HTM[625]="*Sace, bhikkhave, evamassa, kallaṃ vacanāya.**If that’s what you think, then it’s appropriate to speak to them.*";
P_HTM[626]="*Sace pana, bhikkhave, evamassa:**But suppose you think this:*";
P_HTM[627]="*‘mayhañca kho vihesā bhavissati parassa ca puggalassa upaghāto. Paro hi puggalo kodhano upanāhī daḷhadiṭṭhī duppaṭinissaggī, na cāhaṃ sakkomi etaṃ puggalaṃ akusalā vuṭṭhāpetvā kusale patiṭṭhāpetun’ti.**‘I will be troubled and the other individual will be hurt, for they’re irritable and hostile. And they hold fast to their views, refusing to let go. I cannot draw them away from the unskillful and establish them in the skillful.’*";
P_HTM[628]="*Evarūpe, bhikkhave, puggale upekkhā nātimaññitabbā.**Don’t underestimate the value of equanimity for such a person.*";
P_HTM[629]="*Tesañca vo, bhikkhave, samaggānaṃ sammodamānānaṃ avivadamānānaṃ sikkhataṃ aññamaññassa vacīsaṃhāro uppajjeyya diṭṭhipaḷāso cetaso āghāto appaccayo anabhiraddhi.**As you train in harmony, appreciating each other, without quarreling, mutual tale-bearing might come up, with contempt for each other’s views, resentful, bitter, and exasperated.*";
P_HTM[630]="*Tattha ekatopakkhikānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ yaṃ bhikkhuṃ suvacataraṃ maññeyyātha so upasaṅkamitvā evamassa vacanīyo:**In this case you should approach whichever mendicant you think is most amenable among those who side with one party and say to them:*";
P_HTM[631]="*‘yaṃ no, āvuso, amhākaṃ samaggānaṃ sammodamānānaṃ avivadamānānaṃ sikkhataṃ aññamaññassa vacīsaṃhāro uppanno diṭṭhipaḷāso cetaso āghāto appaccayo anabhiraddhi, taṃ jānamāno samaṇo garaheyyā’ti.**‘Reverend, as we were training, mutual tale-bearing came up. If the Ascetic knew about this, would he rebuke it?’*";
P_HTM[632]="*Sammā byākaramāno, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃ byākareyya:**Answering rightly, the mendicant should say:*";
P_HTM[633]="*‘yaṃ no, āvuso, amhākaṃ samaggānaṃ sammodamānānaṃ avivadamānānaṃ sikkhataṃ aññamaññassa vacīsaṃhāro uppanno diṭṭhipaḷāso cetaso āghāto appaccayo anabhiraddhi, taṃ jānamāno samaṇo garaheyyāti.**‘Yes, reverend, he would.’*";
P_HTM[634]="*Etaṃ panāvuso, dhammaṃ appahāya nibbānaṃ sacchikareyyā’ti.**‘But without giving that up, reverend, can one realize extinguishment?’*";
P_HTM[635]="*Sammā byākaramāno, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃ byākareyya:**Answering rightly, the mendicant should say:*";
P_HTM[636]="*‘etaṃ, āvuso, dhammaṃ appahāya na nibbānaṃ sacchikareyyā’ti.**‘No, reverend, one cannot.’*";
P_HTM[637]="*Athāparesaṃ ekatopakkhikānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ yaṃ bhikkhuṃ suvacataraṃ maññeyyātha, so upasaṅkamitvā evamassa vacanīyo:**Then they should approach whichever mendicant they think is most amenable among those who side with the other party and say to them:*";
P_HTM[638]="*‘yaṃ no, āvuso, amhākaṃ samaggānaṃ sammodamānānaṃ avivadamānānaṃ sikkhataṃ aññamaññassa vacīsaṃhāro uppanno diṭṭhipaḷāso cetaso āghāto appaccayo anabhiraddhi, taṃ jānamāno samaṇo garaheyyā’ti.**‘Reverend, as we were training, mutual tale-bearing came up. If the Ascetic knew about this, would he rebuke it?’*";
P_HTM[639]="*Sammā byākaramāno, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃ byākareyya:**Answering rightly, the mendicant should say:*";
P_HTM[640]="*‘yaṃ no, āvuso, amhākaṃ samaggānaṃ sammodamānānaṃ avivadamānānaṃ sikkhataṃ aññamaññassa vacīsaṃhāro uppanno diṭṭhipaḷāso cetaso āghāto appaccayo anabhiraddhi taṃ jānamāno samaṇo garaheyyāti.**‘Yes, reverend, he would.’*";
P_HTM[641]="*Etaṃ panāvuso, dhammaṃ appahāya nibbānaṃ sacchikareyyā’ti.**‘But without giving that up, reverend, can one realize extinguishment?’*";
P_HTM[642]="*Sammā byākaramāno, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃ byākareyya:**Answering rightly, the mendicant should say:*";
P_HTM[643]="*‘etaṃ kho, āvuso, dhammaṃ appahāya na nibbānaṃ sacchikareyyā’ti.**‘No, reverend, one cannot.’*";
P_HTM[644]="*Tañce, bhikkhave, bhikkhuṃ pare evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**If others should ask that mendicant:*";
P_HTM[645]="*‘āyasmatā no ete bhikkhū akusalā vuṭṭhāpetvā kusale patiṭṭhāpitā’ti?**‘Were you the venerable who drew those mendicants away from the unskillful and established them in the skillful?’*";
P_HTM[646]="*Sammā byākaramāno, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃ byākareyya:**Answering rightly, the mendicant should say:*";
P_HTM[647]="*‘idhāhaṃ, āvuso, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃ, tassa me bhagavā dhammaṃ desesi, tāhaṃ dhammaṃ sutvā tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ abhāsiṃ.**‘Well, reverends, I approached the Buddha. He taught me the Dhamma. After hearing that teaching I explained it to those mendicants.*";
P_HTM[648]="*Taṃ te bhikkhū dhammaṃ sutvā akusalā vuṭṭhahiṃsu, kusale patiṭṭhahiṃsū’ti.**When those mendicants heard that teaching they were drawn away from the unskillful and established in the skillful.’*";
P_HTM[649]="*Evaṃ byākaramāno kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu na ceva attānaṃ ukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākaroti, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchatī”ti.**Answering in this way, that mendicant doesn’t glorify themselves or put others down. They answer in line with the teaching, with no legitimate grounds for rebuke and criticism.”*";
P_HTM[650]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[651]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[652]="*Kintisuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[653]="*104. Sāmagāmasutta**At Sāmagāma*";
P_HTM[654]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[655]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati sāmagāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying among the Sakyans near the village of Sāma.*";
P_HTM[656]="*Tena kho pana samayena nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto pāvāyaṃ adhunākālaṅkato hoti.**Now at that time the Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta had recently passed away at Pāvā.*";
P_HTM[657]="*Tassa kālaṃkiriyāya bhinnā nigaṇṭhā dvedhikajātā bhaṇḍanajātā kalahajātā vivādāpannā aññamaññaṃ mukhasattīhi vitudantā viharanti:**With his passing the Jain ascetics split, dividing into two factions, arguing, quarreling, and fighting, continually wounding each other with barbed words:*";
P_HTM[658]="*“na tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāsi, ahaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāmi. Kiṃ tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānissasi. Micchāpaṭipanno tvamasi, ahamasmi sammāpaṭipanno. Sahitaṃ me, asahitaṃ te. Purevacanīyaṃ pacchā avaca, pacchāvacanīyaṃ pure avaca. Adhiciṇṇaṃ te viparāvattaṃ. Āropito te vādo. Niggahitosi, cara vādappamokkhāya; nibbeṭhehi vā sace pahosī”ti.**‘You don’t understand this teaching and training. I understand this teaching and training. What, you understand this teaching and training? You’re practicing wrong. I’m practicing right. I stay on topic, you don’t. You said last what you should have said first. You said first what you should have said last. What you’ve thought so much about has been disproved. Your doctrine is refuted. Go on, save your doctrine! You’re trapped; get yourself out of this—if you can!’*";
P_HTM[659]="*Vadhoyeva kho maññe nigaṇṭhesu nāṭaputtiyesu vattati.**You’d think there was nothing but slaughter going on among the Jain ascetics.*";
P_HTM[660]="*Yepi nigaṇṭhassa nāṭaputtassa sāvakā gihī odātavasanā tepi nigaṇṭhesu nāṭaputtiyesu nibbinnarūpā virattarūpā paṭivānarūpā yathā taṃ durakkhāte dhammavinaye duppavedite aniyyānike anupasamasaṃvattanike asammāsambuddhappavedite bhinnathūpe appaṭisaraṇe.**And the Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta’s white-clothed lay disciples were disillusioned, dismayed, and disappointed in the Jain ascetics. They were equally disappointed with a teaching and training so poorly explained and poorly propounded, not emancipating, not leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is not a fully awakened Buddha, with broken monument and without a refuge.*";
P_HTM[661]="*Atha kho cundo samaṇuddeso pāvāyaṃ vassaṃvuṭṭho yena sāmagāmo yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho cundo samaṇuddeso āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**And then, after completing the rainy season residence near Pāvā, the novice Cunda went to see Venerable Ānanda at Sāma village. He bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened.*";
P_HTM[662]="*“nigaṇṭho, bhante, nāṭaputto pāvāyaṃ adhunākālaṅkato.* **";
P_HTM[663]="*Tassa kālaṃkiriyāya bhinnā nigaṇṭhā dvedhikajātā … pe … bhinnathūpe appaṭisaraṇe”ti.* **";
P_HTM[664]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando cundaṃ samaṇuddesaṃ etadavoca:**Ānanda said to him,*";
P_HTM[665]="*“atthi kho idaṃ, āvuso cunda, kathāpābhataṃ bhagavantaṃ dassanāya.**“Reverend Cunda, we should see the Buddha about this matter.*";
P_HTM[666]="*Āyāma, āvuso cunda, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamissāma; upasaṅkamitvā etamatthaṃ bhagavato ārocessāmā”ti.**Come, let’s go to the Buddha and inform him about this.”*";
P_HTM[667]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho cundo samaṇuddeso āyasmato ānandassa paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Cunda.*";
P_HTM[668]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca ānando cundo ca samaṇuddeso yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Ānanda and Cunda went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and Ānanda informed him of what Cunda had said. He went on to say,*";
P_HTM[669]="*“ayaṃ, bhante, cundo samaṇuddeso evamāha:* **";
P_HTM[670]="*‘nigaṇṭho, bhante, nāṭaputto pāvāyaṃ adhunākālaṅkato.* **";
P_HTM[671]="*Tassa kālaṃkiriyāya bhinnā nigaṇṭhā dvedhikajātā … pe … bhinnathūpe appaṭisaraṇe’ti.* **";
P_HTM[672]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, evaṃ hoti:**“Sir, it occurs to me:*";
P_HTM[673]="*‘mā heva bhagavato accayena saṃghe vivādo uppajji;**‘When the Buddha has passed away, let no dispute arise in the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[674]="*svāssa vivādo bahujanāhitāya bahujanāsukhāya bahuno janassa anatthāya ahitāya dukkhāya devamanussānan’”ti.**For such a dispute would be for the hurt and unhappiness of the people, for the harm, hurt, and suffering of gods and humans.’”*";
P_HTM[675]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ānanda,**“What do you think, Ānanda?*";
P_HTM[676]="*ye vo mayā dhammā abhiññā desitā, seyyathidaṃ—**Do you see even two mendicants who disagree regarding the things I have taught from my direct knowledge, that is,*";
P_HTM[677]="*cattāro satipaṭṭhānā cattāro sammappadhānā cattāro iddhipādā pañcindriyāni pañca balāni satta bojjhaṅgā ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, passasi no tvaṃ, ānanda, imesu dhammesu dvepi bhikkhū nānāvāde”ti?**the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, the four right efforts, the four bases of psychic power, the five faculties, the five powers, the seven awakening factors, and the noble eightfold path?”*";
P_HTM[678]="*“Ye me, bhante, dhammā bhagavatā abhiññā desitā, seyyathidaṃ—**“No, sir, I do not.*";
P_HTM[679]="*cattāro satipaṭṭhānā cattāro sammappadhānā cattāro iddhipādā pañcindriyāni pañca balāni satta bojjhaṅgā ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, nāhaṃ passāmi imesu dhammesu dvepi bhikkhū nānāvāde.* **";
P_HTM[680]="*Ye ca kho, bhante, puggalā bhagavantaṃ patissayamānarūpā viharanti tepi bhagavato accayena saṃghe vivādaṃ janeyyuṃ ajjhājīve vā adhipātimokkhe vā.**Nevertheless, there are some individuals who appear to live obedient to the Buddha, but when the Buddha has passed away they might create a dispute in the Saṅgha regarding livelihood or the monastic code.*";
P_HTM[681]="*Svāssa vivādo bahujanāhitāya bahujanāsukhāya bahuno janassa anatthāya ahitāya dukkhāya devamanussānan”ti.**Such a dispute would be for the hurt and unhappiness of the people, for the harm, hurt, and suffering of gods and humans.”*";
P_HTM[682]="*“Appamattako so, ānanda, vivādo yadidaṃ—ajjhājīve vā adhipātimokkhe vā.**“Ānanda, dispute about livelihood or the monastic code is a minor matter.*";
P_HTM[683]="*Magge vā hi, ānanda, paṭipadāya vā saṅghe vivādo uppajjamāno uppajjeyya; svāssa vivādo bahujanāhitāya bahujanāsukhāya bahuno janassa anatthāya ahitāya dukkhāya devamanussānaṃ.**But should a dispute arise in the Saṅgha concerning the path or the practice, that would be for the hurt and unhappiness of the people, for the harm, hurt, and suffering of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[684]="*Chayimāni, ānanda, vivādamūlāni.**Ānanda, there are these six roots of disputes.*";
P_HTM[685]="*Katamāni cha?**What six?*";
P_HTM[686]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu kodhano hoti upanāhī.**Firstly, a mendicant is irritable and hostile.*";
P_HTM[687]="*Yo so, ānanda, bhikkhu kodhano hoti upanāhī so sattharipi agāravo viharati appatisso, dhammepi agāravo viharati appatisso, saṃghepi agāravo viharati appatisso, sikkhāyapi na paripūrakārī hoti.**Such a mendicant lacks respect and reverence for the teacher, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, and they don’t fulfill the training.*";
P_HTM[688]="*Yo so, ānanda, bhikkhu satthari agāravo viharati appatisso, dhamme … saṃghe agāravo viharati appatisso, sikkhāya na paripūrakārī hoti, so saṃghe vivādaṃ janeti; yo hoti vivādo bahujanāhitāya bahujanāsukhāya, bahuno janassa anatthāya ahitāya dukkhāya devamanussānaṃ.**They create a dispute in the Saṅgha, which is for the hurt and unhappiness of the people, for the harm, hurt, and suffering of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[689]="*Evarūpañce tumhe, ānanda, vivādamūlaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā samanupasseyyātha, tatra tumhe, ānanda, tasseva pāpakassa vivādamūlassa pahānāya vāyameyyātha.**If you see such a root of disputes in yourselves or others, you should try to give up this bad thing.*";
P_HTM[690]="*Evarūpañce tumhe, ānanda, vivādamūlaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā na samanupasseyyātha. Tatra tumhe, ānanda, tasseva pāpakassa vivādamūlassa āyatiṃ anavassavāya paṭipajjeyyātha.**If you don’t see it, you should practice so that it doesn’t come up in the future.*";
P_HTM[691]="*Evametassa pāpakassa vivādamūlassa pahānaṃ hoti, evametassa pāpakassa vivādamūlassa āyatiṃ anavassavo hoti.**That’s how to give up this bad root of quarrels, so it doesn’t come up in the future.*";
P_HTM[692]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu makkhī hoti paḷāsī … pe …**Furthermore, a mendicant is offensive and contemptuous …*";
P_HTM[693]="*issukī hoti maccharī … pe …**They’re jealous and stingy …*";
P_HTM[694]="*saṭho hoti māyāvī … pe …**They’re devious and deceitful …*";
P_HTM[695]="*pāpiccho hoti micchādiṭṭhi … pe …**They have wicked desires and wrong view …*";
P_HTM[696]="*sandiṭṭhiparāmāsī hoti ādhānaggāhī duppaṭinissaggī.**They’re attached to their own views, holding them tight, and refusing to let go.*";
P_HTM[697]="*Yo so, ānanda, bhikkhu sandiṭṭhiparāmāsī hoti ādhānaggāhī duppaṭinissaggī so sattharipi agāravo viharati appatisso, dhammepi agāravo viharati appatisso, saṃghepi agāravo viharati appatisso, sikkhāyapi na paripūrakārī hoti.**Such a mendicant lacks respect and reverence for the teacher, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, and they don’t fulfill the training.*";
P_HTM[698]="*Yo so, ānanda, bhikkhu satthari agāravo viharati appatisso, dhamme … saṃghe … sikkhāya na paripūrakārī hoti so saṃghe vivādaṃ janeti; yo hoti vivādo bahujanāhitāya bahujanāsukhāya, bahuno janassa anatthāya ahitāya dukkhāya devamanussānaṃ.**They create a dispute in the Saṅgha, which is for the hurt and unhappiness of the people, for the harm, hurt, and suffering of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[699]="*Evarūpañce tumhe, ānanda, vivādamūlaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā samanupasseyyātha. Tatra tumhe, ānanda, tasseva pāpakassa vivādamūlassa pahānāya vāyameyyātha.**If you see such a root of quarrels in yourselves or others, you should try to give up this bad thing.*";
P_HTM[700]="*Evarūpañce tumhe, ānanda, vivādamūlaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā na samanupasseyyātha, tatra tumhe, ānanda, tasseva pāpakassa vivādamūlassa āyatiṃ anavassavāya paṭipajjeyyātha.**If you don’t see it, you should practice so that it doesn’t come up in the future.*";
P_HTM[701]="*Evametassa pāpakassa vivādamūlassa pahānaṃ hoti, evametassa pāpakassa vivādamūlassa āyatiṃ anavassavo hoti.**That’s how to give up this bad root of quarrels, so it doesn’t come up in the future.*";
P_HTM[702]="*Imāni kho, ānanda, cha vivādamūlāni.**These are the six roots of quarrels.*";
P_HTM[703]="*Cattārimāni, ānanda, adhikaraṇāni.**There are four kinds of disciplinary issues.*";
P_HTM[704]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[705]="*Vivādādhikaraṇaṃ, anuvādādhikaraṇaṃ, āpattādhikaraṇaṃ, kiccādhikaraṇaṃ—**Disciplinary issues due to disputes, accusations, offenses, or proceedings.*";
P_HTM[706]="*imāni kho, ānanda, cattāri adhikaraṇāni.**These are the four kinds of disciplinary issues.*";
P_HTM[707]="*Satta kho panime, ānanda, adhikaraṇasamathā—**There are seven methods for the settlement of any disciplinary issues that might arise.*";
P_HTM[708]="*uppannuppannānaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ samathāya vūpasamāya sammukhāvinayo dātabbo, sativinayo dātabbo, amūḷhavinayo dātabbo, paṭiññāya kāretabbaṃ, yebhuyyasikā, tassapāpiyasikā, tiṇavatthārako.**Removal in the presence of those concerned is applicable. Removal by accurate recollection is applicable. Removal due to recovery from madness is applicable. The offense should be acknowledged. The decision of a majority. A verdict of aggravated misconduct. Covering over with grass.*";
P_HTM[709]="*Kathañcānanda, sammukhāvinayo hoti?**And how is there removal in the presence of those concerned?*";
P_HTM[710]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhū vivadanti dhammoti vā adhammoti vā vinayoti vā avinayoti vā.**It’s when mendicants are disputing: ‘This is the teaching,’ ‘This is not the teaching,’ ‘This is the training,’ ‘This is not the training.’*";
P_HTM[711]="*Tehānanda, bhikkhūhi sabbeheva samaggehi sannipatitabbaṃ.**Those mendicants should all sit together in harmony*";
P_HTM[712]="*Sannipatitvā dhammanetti samanumajjitabbā.**and thoroughly go over the guidelines of the teaching.*";
P_HTM[713]="*Dhammanettiṃ samanumajjitvā yathā tattha sameti tathā taṃ adhikaraṇaṃ vūpasametabbaṃ.**They should settle that disciplinary issue in agreement with the guidelines.*";
P_HTM[714]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, sammukhāvinayo hoti;**That’s how there is removal in the presence of those concerned.*";
P_HTM[715]="*evañca panidhekaccānaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ vūpasamo hoti yadidaṃ—**And that’s how certain disciplinary issues are settled, that is,*";
P_HTM[716]="*sammukhāvinayena. (1)**by removal in the presence of those concerned.*";
P_HTM[717]="*Kathañcānanda, yebhuyyasikā hoti?**And how is there the decision of a majority?*";
P_HTM[718]="*Te ce, ānanda, bhikkhū na sakkonti taṃ adhikaraṇaṃ tasmiṃ āvāse vūpasametuṃ.**If those mendicants are not able to settle that issue in that monastery,*";
P_HTM[719]="*Tehānanda, bhikkhūhi yasmiṃ āvāse bahutarā bhikkhū so āvāso gantabbo.**they should go to another monastery with more mendicants.*";
P_HTM[720]="*Tattha sabbeheva samaggehi sannipatitabbaṃ.**There they should all sit together in harmony*";
P_HTM[721]="*Sannipatitvā dhammanetti samanumajjitabbā.**and thoroughly go over the guidelines of the teaching.*";
P_HTM[722]="*Dhammanettiṃ samanumajjitvā yathā tattha sameti tathā taṃ adhikaraṇaṃ vūpasametabbaṃ.**They should settle that disciplinary issue in agreement with the guidelines.*";
P_HTM[723]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, yebhuyyasikā hoti, evañca panidhekaccānaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ vūpasamo hoti yadidaṃ—**That’s how there is the decision of a majority. And that’s how certain disciplinary issues are settled, that is,*";
P_HTM[724]="*yebhuyyasikāya. (2)**by decision of a majority.*";
P_HTM[725]="*Kathañcānanda, sativinayo hoti?**And how is there removal by accurate recollection?*";
P_HTM[726]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhū bhikkhuṃ evarūpāya garukāya āpattiyā codenti pārājikena vā pārājikasāmantena vā:**It’s when mendicants accuse a mendicant of a serious offense; one entailing expulsion, or close to it:*";
P_HTM[727]="*‘saratāyasmā evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā’ti?**‘Venerable, do you recall committing the kind of serious offense that entails expulsion or close to it?’*";
P_HTM[728]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[729]="*‘na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, sarāmi evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā’ti.**‘No, reverends, I don’t recall committing such an offense.’*";
P_HTM[730]="*Tassa kho, ānanda, bhikkhuno sativinayo dātabbo.**The removal by accurate recollection is applicable to them.*";
P_HTM[731]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, sativinayo hoti, evañca panidhekaccānaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ vūpasamo hoti yadidaṃ—**That’s how there is the removal by accurate recollection. And that’s how certain disciplinary issues are settled, that is,*";
P_HTM[732]="*sativinayena. (3)**by removal by accurate recollection.*";
P_HTM[733]="*Kathañcānanda, amūḷhavinayo hoti?**And how is there removal by recovery from madness?*";
P_HTM[734]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhū bhikkhuṃ evarūpāya garukāya āpattiyā codenti pārājikena vā pārājikasāmantena vā:**It’s when mendicants accuse a mendicant of the kind of serious offense that entails expulsion, or close to it:*";
P_HTM[735]="*‘saratāyasmā evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā’ti?**‘Venerable, do you recall committing the kind of serious offense that entails expulsion or close to it?’*";
P_HTM[736]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[737]="*‘na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, sarāmi evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā’ti.**‘No, reverends, I don’t recall committing such an offense.’*";
P_HTM[738]="*Tamenaṃ so nibbeṭhentaṃ ativeṭheti:**But though they try to get out of it, the mendicants pursue the issue:*";
P_HTM[739]="*‘iṅghāyasmā sādhukameva jānāhi yadi sarasi evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā’ti.**‘Surely the venerable must know perfectly well if you recall committing an offense that entails expulsion or close to it!’*";
P_HTM[740]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[741]="*‘ahaṃ kho, āvuso, ummādaṃ pāpuṇiṃ cetaso vipariyāsaṃ.**‘Reverends, I had gone mad, I was out of my mind.*";
P_HTM[742]="*Tena me ummattakena bahuṃ assāmaṇakaṃ ajjhāciṇṇaṃ bhāsitaparikkantaṃ.**And while I was mad I did and said many things that are not proper for an ascetic.*";
P_HTM[743]="*Nāhaṃ taṃ sarāmi.**I don’t remember any of that,*";
P_HTM[744]="*Mūḷhena me etaṃ katan’ti.**I was mad when I did it.’*";
P_HTM[745]="*Tassa kho, ānanda, bhikkhuno amūḷhavinayo dātabbo.**The removal by recovery from madness is applicable to them.*";
P_HTM[746]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, amūḷhavinayo hoti, evañca panidhekaccānaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ vūpasamo hoti yadidaṃ—**That’s how there is the removal by recovery from madness. And that’s how certain disciplinary issues are settled, that is,*";
P_HTM[747]="*amūḷhavinayena. (4)**by recovery from madness.*";
P_HTM[748]="*Kathañcānanda, paṭiññātakaraṇaṃ hoti?**And how is there the acknowledging of an offense?*";
P_HTM[749]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu codito vā acodito vā āpattiṃ sarati, vivarati uttānīkaroti.**It’s when a mendicant, whether accused or not, recalls an offense and clarifies it and reveals it.*";
P_HTM[750]="*Tena, ānanda, bhikkhunā vuḍḍhataraṃ bhikkhuṃ upasaṅkamitvā ekaṃsaṃ cīvaraṃ katvā pāde vanditvā ukkuṭikaṃ nisīditvā añjaliṃ paggahetvā evamassa vacanīyo:**After approaching a more senior mendicant, that mendicant should arrange his robe over one shoulder, bow to that mendicant’s feet, squat on their heels, raise their joined palms, and say:*";
P_HTM[751]="*‘ahaṃ, bhante, itthannāmaṃ āpattiṃ āpanno, taṃ paṭidesemī’ti.**‘Sir, I have fallen into such-and-such an offense. I confess it.’*";
P_HTM[752]="*So evamāha:**The senior mendicant says:*";
P_HTM[753]="*‘passasī’ti?**‘Do you see it?’*";
P_HTM[754]="*‘Āma passāmī’ti.**‘Yes, I see it.’*";
P_HTM[755]="*‘Āyatiṃsaṃvareyyāsī’ti.**‘Then restrain yourself in future.’*";
P_HTM[756]="*‘Saṃvarissāmī’ti.**‘I shall restrain myself.’*";
P_HTM[757]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, paṭiññātakaraṇaṃ hoti, evañca panidhekaccānaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ vūpasamo hoti yadidaṃ—**That’s how there is the acknowledging of an offense. And that’s how certain disciplinary issues are settled, that is,*";
P_HTM[758]="*paṭiññātakaraṇena. (5)**by acknowledging an offense.*";
P_HTM[759]="*Kathañcānanda, tassapāpiyasikā hoti?**And how is there a verdict of aggravated misconduct?*";
P_HTM[760]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu bhikkhuṃ evarūpāya garukāya āpattiyā codeti pārājikena vā pārājikasāmantena vā:**It’s when a mendicant accuses a mendicant of the kind of serious offense that entails expulsion, or close to it:*";
P_HTM[761]="*‘saratāyasmā evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā’ti?**‘Venerable, do you recall committing the kind of serious offense that entails expulsion or close to it?’*";
P_HTM[762]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[763]="*‘na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, sarāmi evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā’ti.**‘No, reverends, I don’t recall committing such an offense.’*";
P_HTM[764]="*Tamenaṃ so nibbeṭhentaṃ ativeṭheti:**But though they try to get out of it, the mendicants pursue the issue:*";
P_HTM[765]="*‘iṅghāyasmā sādhukameva jānāhi yadi sarasi evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā’ti.**‘Surely the venerable must know perfectly well if you recall committing an offense that entails expulsion or close to it!’*";
P_HTM[766]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[767]="*‘na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, sarāmi evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā;**‘Reverends, I don’t recall committing a serious offense of that nature.*";
P_HTM[768]="*sarāmi ca kho ahaṃ, āvuso, evarūpiṃ appamattikaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā’ti.**But I do recall committing a light offense.’*";
P_HTM[769]="*Tamenaṃ so nibbeṭhentaṃ ativeṭheti:**But though they try to get out of it, the mendicants pursue the issue:*";
P_HTM[770]="*‘iṅghāyasmā sādhukameva jānāhi yadi sarasi evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā’ti?**‘Surely the venerable must know perfectly well if you recall committing an offense that entails expulsion or close to it!’*";
P_HTM[771]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[772]="*‘imañhi nāmāhaṃ, āvuso, appamattikaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitvā apuṭṭho paṭijānissāmi.**‘Reverends, I’ll go so far as to acknowledge this light offense even when not asked.*";
P_HTM[773]="*Kiṃ panāhaṃ evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitvā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā puṭṭho na paṭijānissāmī’ti?**Why wouldn’t I acknowledge a serious offense when asked?’*";
P_HTM[774]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[775]="*‘imañhi nāma tvaṃ, āvuso, appamattikaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitvā apuṭṭho na paṭijānissasi, kiṃ pana tvaṃ evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitvā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā puṭṭho paṭijānissasi?**‘You wouldn’t have acknowledged that light offense without being asked, so why would you acknowledge a serious offense?*";
P_HTM[776]="*Iṅghāyasmā sādhukameva jānāhi yadi sarasi evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā’ti.**Surely the venerable must know perfectly well if you recall committing an offense that entails expulsion or close to it!’*";
P_HTM[777]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[778]="*‘sarāmi kho ahaṃ, āvuso, evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā.**‘Reverend, I do recall committing the kind of serious offense that entails expulsion or close to it.*";
P_HTM[779]="*Davā me etaṃ vuttaṃ, ravā me etaṃ vuttaṃ—**I spoke too hastily when I said*";
P_HTM[780]="*nāhaṃ taṃ sarāmi evarūpiṃ garukaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjitā pārājikaṃ vā pārājikasāmantaṃ vā’ti.**that I didn’t recall it.’*";
P_HTM[781]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, tassapāpiyasikā hoti, evañca panidhekaccānaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ vūpasamo hoti yadidaṃ—**That’s how there is a verdict of aggravated misconduct. And that’s how certain disciplinary issues are settled, that is,*";
P_HTM[782]="*tassapāpiyasikāya. (6)**by a verdict of aggravated misconduct.*";
P_HTM[783]="*Kathañcānanda, tiṇavatthārako hoti?**And how is there the covering over with grass?*";
P_HTM[784]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhūnaṃ bhaṇḍanajātānaṃ kalahajātānaṃ vivādāpannānaṃ viharataṃ bahuṃ assāmaṇakaṃ ajjhāciṇṇaṃ hoti bhāsitaparikkantaṃ.**It’s when the mendicants continually argue, quarrel, and fight, doing and saying many things that are not proper for an ascetic.*";
P_HTM[785]="*Tehānanda, bhikkhūhi sabbeheva samaggehi sannipatitabbaṃ.**Those mendicants should all sit together in harmony.*";
P_HTM[786]="*Sannipatitvā ekatopakkhikānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ byattena bhikkhunā uṭṭhāyāsanā ekaṃsaṃ cīvaraṃ katvā añjaliṃ paṇāmetvā saṃgho ñāpetabbo—**A competent mendicant of one party, having got up from their seat, arranged their robe over one shoulder, and raised their joined palms, should inform the Saṅgha:*";
P_HTM[787]="*Suṇātu me, bhante, saṅgho.**‘Sir, let the Saṅgha listen to me.*";
P_HTM[788]="*Idaṃ amhākaṃ bhaṇḍanajātānaṃ kalahajātānaṃ vivādāpannānaṃ viharataṃ bahuṃ assāmaṇakaṃ ajjhāciṇṇaṃ bhāsitaparikkantaṃ.**We have been continually arguing, quarreling, and fighting, doing and saying many things that are not proper for an ascetic.*";
P_HTM[789]="*Yadi saṅghassa pattakallaṃ, ahaṃ yā ceva imesaṃ āyasmantānaṃ āpatti yā ca attano āpatti, imesañceva āyasmantānaṃ atthāya attano ca atthāya, saṅghamajjhe tiṇavatthārakena deseyyaṃ, ṭhapetvā thullavajjaṃ ṭhapetvā gihipaṭisaṃyuttan’ti.**If it seems appropriate to the Saṅgha, then—for the benefit of these venerables and myself—I disclose in the middle of the Saṅgha by means of covering over with grass any offenses committed by these venerables and by myself, excepting only those that are gravely blameworthy and those connected with laypeople.’*";
P_HTM[790]="*Athāparesaṃ ekatopakkhikānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ byattena bhikkhunā uṭṭhāyāsanā ekaṃsaṃ cīvaraṃ katvā añjaliṃ paṇāmetvā saṅgho ñāpetabbo:**Then a competent mendicant of the other party, having got up from their seat, arranged their robe over one shoulder, and raising their joined palms, should inform the Saṅgha:*";
P_HTM[791]="*‘Suṇātu me, bhante, saṅgho.**‘Sir, let the Saṅgha listen to me.*";
P_HTM[792]="*Idaṃ amhākaṃ bhaṇḍanajātānaṃ kalahajātānaṃ vivādāpannānaṃ viharataṃ bahuṃ assāmaṇakaṃ ajjhāciṇṇaṃ bhāsitaparikkantaṃ.**We have been continually arguing, quarreling, and fighting, doing and saying many things that are not proper for an ascetic.*";
P_HTM[793]="*Yadi saṅghassa pattakallaṃ, ahaṃ yā ceva imesaṃ āyasmantānaṃ āpatti yā ca attano āpatti, imesañceva āyasmantānaṃ atthāya attano ca atthāya, saṅghamajjhe tiṇavatthārakena deseyyaṃ, ṭhapetvā thullavajjaṃ ṭhapetvā gihipaṭisaṃyuttan’ti.**If it seems appropriate to the Saṅgha, then—for the benefit of these venerables and myself—I disclose in the middle of the Saṅgha by means of covering over with grass any offenses committed by these venerables and by myself, excepting only those that are gravely blameworthy and those connected with laypeople.’*";
P_HTM[794]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, tiṇavatthārako hoti, evañca panidhekaccānaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ vūpasamo hoti yadidaṃ—**That’s how there is the covering over with grass. And that’s how certain disciplinary issues are settled, that is,*";
P_HTM[795]="*tiṇavatthārakena. (7)**by covering over with grass.*";
P_HTM[796]="*Chayime, ānanda, dhammā sāraṇīyā piyakaraṇā garukaraṇā saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattanti.**Ānanda, these six warm-hearted qualities make for fondness and respect, conducing to inclusion, harmony, and unity, without quarreling.*";
P_HTM[797]="*Katame cha?**What six?*";
P_HTM[798]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhuno mettaṃ kāyakammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti sabrahmacārīsu āvi ceva raho ca.**Firstly, a mendicant consistently treats their spiritual companions with bodily kindness, both in public and in private.*";
P_HTM[799]="*Ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (1)**This warm-hearted quality makes for fondness and respect, conducing to inclusion, harmony, and unity, without quarreling.*";
P_HTM[800]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhuno mettaṃ vacīkammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti sabrahmacārīsu āvi ceva raho ca.**Furthermore, a mendicant consistently treats their spiritual companions with verbal kindness …*";
P_HTM[801]="*Ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (2)**This too is a warm-hearted quality.*";
P_HTM[802]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhuno mettaṃ manokammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti sabrahmacārīsu āvi ceva raho ca.**Furthermore, a mendicant consistently treats their spiritual companions with mental kindness …*";
P_HTM[803]="*Ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (3)**This too is a warm-hearted quality.*";
P_HTM[804]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu—ye te lābhā dhammikā dhammaladdhā antamaso pattapariyāpannamattampi tathārūpehi lābhehi—apaṭivibhattabhogī hoti, sīlavantehi sabrahmacārīhi sādhāraṇabhogī.**Furthermore, a mendicant shares without reservation any material possessions they have gained by legitimate means, even the food placed in the alms-bowl, using them in common with their ethical spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[805]="*Ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (4)**This too is a warm-hearted quality.*";
P_HTM[806]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu—yāni tāni sīlāni akhaṇḍāni acchiddāni asabalāni akammāsāni bhujissāni viññuppasatthāni aparāmaṭṭhāni samādhisaṃvattanikāni tathārūpesu sīlesu—sīlasāmaññagato viharati sabrahmacārīhi āvi ceva raho ca.**Furthermore, a mendicant lives according to the precepts shared with their spiritual companions, both in public and in private. Those precepts are unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[807]="*Ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (5)**This too is a warm-hearted quality.*";
P_HTM[808]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu—yāyaṃ diṭṭhi ariyā niyyānikā niyyāti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāya tathārūpāya diṭṭhiyā—diṭṭhisāmaññagato viharati sabrahmacārīhi āvi ceva raho ca.**Furthermore, a mendicant lives according to the view shared with their spiritual companions, both in public and in private. That view is noble and emancipating, and leads one who practices it to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[809]="*Ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (6)**This too is a warm-hearted quality.*";
P_HTM[810]="*Ime kho, ānanda, cha sāraṇīyā dhammā piyakaraṇā garukaraṇā saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattanti.**These six warm-hearted qualities make for fondness and respect, conducing to inclusion, harmony, and unity, without quarreling.*";
P_HTM[811]="*Ime ce tumhe, ānanda, cha sāraṇīye dhamme samādāya vatteyyātha, passatha no tumhe, ānanda, taṃ vacanapathaṃ aṇuṃ vā thūlaṃ vā yaṃ tumhe nādhivāseyyāthā”ti?**If you should undertake and follow these six warm-hearted qualities, do you see any criticism, large or small, that you could not endure?”*";
P_HTM[812]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[813]="*“Tasmātihānanda, ime cha sāraṇīye dhamme samādāya vattatha.**“That’s why, Ānanda, you should undertake and follow these six warm-hearted qualities.*";
P_HTM[814]="*Taṃ vo bhavissati dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā”ti.**That will be for your lasting welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[815]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[816]="*Attamano āyasmā ānando bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Ānanda was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[817]="*Sāmagāmasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[818]="*105. Sunakkhattasutta**With Sunakkhatta*";
P_HTM[819]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[820]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[821]="*Tena kho pana samayena sambahulehi bhikkhūhi bhagavato santike aññā byākatā hoti:**Now at that time several mendicants had declared their enlightenment in the Buddha’s presence:*";
P_HTM[822]="*“‘khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāmā”ti.**“We understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[823]="*Assosi kho sunakkhatto licchaviputto:**Sunakkhatta the Licchavi heard about this.*";
P_HTM[824]="*“sambahulehi kira bhikkhūhi bhagavato santike aññā byākatā hoti:* **";
P_HTM[825]="*‘khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāmā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[826]="*Atha kho sunakkhatto licchaviputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho sunakkhatto licchaviputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**He went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[827]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante:**“Sir, I have heard that*";
P_HTM[828]="*‘sambahulehi kira bhikkhūhi bhagavato santike aññā byākatā—**several mendicants have declared their enlightenment in the Buddha’s presence.*";
P_HTM[829]="*khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāmā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[830]="*Ye te, bhante, bhikkhū bhagavato santike aññaṃ byākaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[831]="*‘khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāmā’ti, kacci te, bhante, bhikkhū sammadeva aññaṃ byākaṃsu udāhu santetthekacce bhikkhū adhimānena aññaṃ byākaṃsū”ti?**I trust they did so rightly—or are there some who declared enlightenment out of overestimation?”*";
P_HTM[832]="*“Ye te, sunakkhatta, bhikkhū mama santike aññaṃ byākaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[833]="*‘khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāmā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[834]="*Santetthekacce bhikkhū sammadeva aññaṃ byākaṃsu, santi panidhekacce bhikkhū adhimānenapi aññaṃ byākaṃsu.**“Some of them did so rightly, Sunakkhatta, while others did so out of overestimation.*";
P_HTM[835]="*Tatra, sunakkhatta, ye te bhikkhū sammadeva aññaṃ byākaṃsu tesaṃ taṃ tatheva hoti;**Now, when mendicants declare enlightenment rightly, that’s how it is for them.*";
P_HTM[836]="*ye pana te bhikkhū adhimānena aññaṃ byākaṃsu tatra, sunakkhatta, tathāgatassa evaṃ hoti:**But when mendicants declare enlightenment out of overestimation, the Realized One thinks:*";
P_HTM[837]="*‘dhammaṃ nesaṃ desessan’ti.**‘I should teach them the Dhamma.’*";
P_HTM[838]="*Evañcettha, sunakkhatta, tathāgatassa hoti:**If the Realized One thinks*";
P_HTM[839]="*‘dhammaṃ nesaṃ desessan’ti.**he should teach them the Dhamma,*";
P_HTM[840]="*Atha ca panidhekacce moghapurisā pañhaṃ abhisaṅkharitvā abhisaṅkharitvā tathāgataṃ upasaṅkamitvā pucchanti.**but then certain foolish men, having carefully planned a question, approach the Realized One and ask it,*";
P_HTM[841]="*Tatra, sunakkhatta, yampi tathāgatassa evaṃ hoti:**then the Realized One*";
P_HTM[842]="*‘dhammaṃ nesaṃ desessan’ti tassapi hoti aññathattan”ti.**changes his mind.”*";
P_HTM[843]="*“Etassa bhagavā kālo, etassa sugata kālo,**“Now is the time, Blessed One! Now is the time, Holy One!*";
P_HTM[844]="*yaṃ bhagavā dhammaṃ deseyya. Bhagavato sutvā bhikkhū dhāressantī”ti.**Let the Buddha teach the Dhamma. The mendicants will listen and remember it.”*";
P_HTM[845]="*“Tena hi, sunakkhatta, suṇāhi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, Sunakkhatta, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[846]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho sunakkhatto licchaviputto bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Sunakkhatta.*";
P_HTM[847]="*Bhagavā etadavoca—**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[848]="*Pañca kho ime, sunakkhatta, kāmaguṇā.**“Sunakkhatta, there are these five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[849]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[850]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā,**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[851]="*sotaviññeyyā saddā … pe …**Sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[852]="*ghānaviññeyyā gandhā …**Smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[853]="*jivhāviññeyyā rasā …**Tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[854]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā—**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[855]="*ime kho, sunakkhatta, pañca kāmaguṇā.**These are the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[856]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, sunakkhatta, vijjati yaṃ idhekacco purisapuggalo lokāmisādhimutto assa.**It’s possible that a certain individual may be intent on material pleasures.*";
P_HTM[857]="*Lokāmisādhimuttassa kho, sunakkhatta, purisapuggalassa tappatirūpī ceva kathā saṇṭhāti, tadanudhammañca anuvitakketi, anuvicāreti, tañca purisaṃ bhajati, tena ca vittiṃ āpajjati;**Such an individual engages in pertinent conversation, thinking and considering in line with that. They associate with that kind of person, and they find it satisfying.*";
P_HTM[858]="*āneñjapaṭisaṃyuttāya ca pana kathāya kacchamānāya na sussūsati, na sotaṃ odahati, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhāpeti, na ca taṃ purisaṃ bhajati, na ca tena vittiṃ āpajjati.**But when talk connected with the imperturbable is going on they don’t want to listen. They don’t lend an ear or apply their minds to understand it. They don’t associate with that kind of person, and they don’t find it satisfying.*";
P_HTM[859]="*Seyyathāpi, sunakkhatta, puriso sakamhā gāmā vā nigamā vā ciravippavuttho assa.**Suppose a person had left their own village or town long ago,*";
P_HTM[860]="*So aññataraṃ purisaṃ passeyya tamhā gāmā vā nigamā vā acirapakkantaṃ.**and they saw another person who had only recently left there.*";
P_HTM[861]="*So taṃ purisaṃ tassa gāmassa vā nigamassa vā khematañca subhikkhatañca appābādhatañca puccheyya;**They would ask about whether their village was safe, with plenty of food and little disease,*";
P_HTM[862]="*tassa so puriso tassa gāmassa vā nigamassa vā khematañca subhikkhatañca appābādhatañca saṃseyya.**and the other person would tell them the news.*";
P_HTM[863]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, sunakkhatta,**What do you think, Sunakkhatta?*";
P_HTM[864]="*api nu so puriso tassa purisassa sussūseyya, sotaṃ odaheyya, aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhāpeyya, tañca purisaṃ bhajeyya, tena ca vittiṃ āpajjeyyā”ti?**Would that person want to listen to that other person? Would they lend an ear and apply their minds to understand? Would they associate with that person, and find it satisfying?”*";
P_HTM[865]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[866]="*“Evameva kho, sunakkhatta, ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ idhekacco purisapuggalo lokāmisādhimutto assa.**“In the same way, it’s possible that a certain individual may be intent on material pleasures.*";
P_HTM[867]="*Lokāmisādhimuttassa kho, sunakkhatta, purisapuggalassa tappatirūpī ceva kathā saṇṭhāti, tadanudhammañca anuvitakketi, anuvicāreti, tañca purisaṃ bhajati, tena ca vittiṃ āpajjati;**Such an individual engages in pertinent conversation, thinking and considering in line with that. They associate with that kind of person, and they find it satisfying.*";
P_HTM[868]="*āneñjapaṭisaṃyuttāya ca pana kathāya kacchamānāya na sussūsati, na sotaṃ odahati, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhāpeti, na ca taṃ purisaṃ bhajati, na ca tena vittiṃ āpajjati.**But when talk connected with the imperturbable is going on they don’t want to listen. They don’t lend an ear or apply their minds to understand it. They don’t associate with that kind of person, and they don’t find it satisfying.*";
P_HTM[869]="*So evamassa veditabbo:**You should know of them:*";
P_HTM[870]="*‘āneñjasaṃyojanena hi kho visaṃyutto lokāmisādhimutto purisapuggalo’ti.**‘That individual is intent on material pleasures, for they’re detached from things connected with the imperturbable.’*";
P_HTM[871]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, sunakkhatta, vijjati yaṃ idhekacco purisapuggalo āneñjādhimutto assa.**It’s possible that a certain individual may be intent on the imperturbable.*";
P_HTM[872]="*Āneñjādhimuttassa kho, sunakkhatta, purisapuggalassa tappatirūpī ceva kathā saṇṭhāti, tadanudhammañca anuvitakketi, anuvicāreti, tañca purisaṃ bhajati, tena ca vittiṃ āpajjati;**Such an individual engages in pertinent conversation, thinking and considering in line with that. They associate with that kind of person, and they find it satisfying.*";
P_HTM[873]="*lokāmisapaṭisaṃyuttāya ca pana kathāya kacchamānāya na sussūsati, na sotaṃ odahati, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhāpeti, na ca taṃ purisaṃ bhajati, na ca tena vittiṃ āpajjati.**But when talk connected with material pleasures is going on they don’t want to listen. They don’t lend an ear or apply their minds to understand it. They don’t associate with that kind of person, and they don’t find it satisfying.*";
P_HTM[874]="*Seyyathāpi, sunakkhatta, paṇḍupalāso bandhanā pavutto abhabbo haritattāya;**Suppose there was a fallen, withered leaf. It’s incapable of becoming green again.*";
P_HTM[875]="*evameva kho, sunakkhatta, āneñjādhimuttassa purisapuggalassa ye lokāmisasaṃyojane se pavutte.**In the same way, an individual intent on the imperturbable has dropped the connection with material pleasures.*";
P_HTM[876]="*So evamassa veditabbo:**You should know of them:*";
P_HTM[877]="*‘lokāmisasaṃyojanena hi kho visaṃyutto āneñjādhimutto purisapuggalo’ti.**‘That individual is intent on the imperturbable, for they’re detached from things connected with material pleasures.’*";
P_HTM[878]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, sunakkhatta, vijjati yaṃ idhekacco purisapuggalo ākiñcaññāyatanādhimutto assa.**It’s possible that a certain individual may be intent on the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[879]="*Ākiñcaññāyatanādhimuttassa kho, sunakkhatta, purisapuggalassa tappatirūpī ceva kathā saṇṭhāti, tadanudhammañca anuvitakketi, anuvicāreti, tañca purisaṃ bhajati, tena ca vittiṃ āpajjati;**Such an individual engages in pertinent conversation, thinking and considering in line with that. They associate with that kind of person, and they find it satisfying.*";
P_HTM[880]="*āneñjapaṭisaṃyuttāya ca pana kathāya kacchamānāya na sussūsati, na sotaṃ odahati, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhāpeti, na ca taṃ purisaṃ bhajati, na ca tena vittiṃ āpajjati.**But when talk connected with the imperturbable is going on they don’t want to listen. They don’t lend an ear or apply their minds to understand it. They don’t associate with that kind of person, and they don’t find it satisfying.*";
P_HTM[881]="*Seyyathāpi, sunakkhatta, puthusilā dvedhābhinnā appaṭisandhikā hoti;**Suppose there was a broad rock that had been broken in half, so that it could not be put back together again.*";
P_HTM[882]="*evameva kho, sunakkhatta, ākiñcaññāyatanādhimuttassa purisapuggalassa ye āneñjasaṃyojane se bhinne.**In the same way, an individual intent on the dimension of nothingness has broken the connection with the imperturbable.*";
P_HTM[883]="*So evamassa veditabbo:**You should know of them:*";
P_HTM[884]="*‘āneñjasaṃyojanena hi kho visaṃyutto ākiñcaññāyatanādhimutto purisapuggalo’ti.**‘That individual is intent on the dimension of nothingness, for they’re detached from things connected with the imperturbable.’*";
P_HTM[885]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, sunakkhatta, vijjati yaṃ idhekacco purisapuggalo nevasaññānāsaññāyatanādhimutto assa.**It’s possible that a certain individual may be intent on the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[886]="*Nevasaññānāsaññāyatanādhimuttassa kho, sunakkhatta, purisapuggalassa tappatirūpī ceva kathā saṇṭhāti, tadanudhammañca anuvitakketi, anuvicāreti, tañca purisaṃ bhajati, tena ca vittiṃ āpajjati;**Such an individual engages in pertinent conversation, thinking and considering in line with that. They associate with that kind of person, and they find it satisfying.*";
P_HTM[887]="*ākiñcaññāyatanapaṭisaṃyuttāya ca pana kathāya kacchamānāya na sussūsati, na sotaṃ odahati, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhāpeti, na ca taṃ purisaṃ bhajati, na ca tena vittiṃ āpajjati.**But when talk connected with the dimension of nothingness is going on they don’t want to listen. They don’t lend an ear or apply their minds to understand it. They don’t associate with that kind of person, and they don’t find it satisfying.*";
P_HTM[888]="*Seyyathāpi, sunakkhatta, puriso manuññabhojanaṃ bhuttāvī chaḍḍeyya.**Suppose someone had eaten some delectable food and thrown it up.*";
P_HTM[889]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, sunakkhatta,**What do you think, Sunakkhatta?*";
P_HTM[890]="*api nu tassa purisassa tasmiṃ bhatte puna bhottukamyatā assā”ti?**Would that person want to eat that food again?”*";
P_HTM[891]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[892]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[893]="*“Aduñhi, bhante, bhattaṃ paṭikūlasammatan”ti.**Because that food is considered repulsive.”*";
P_HTM[894]="*“Evameva kho, sunakkhatta, nevasaññānāsaññāyatanādhimuttassa purisapuggalassa ye ākiñcaññāyatanasaṃyojane se vante.**“In the same way, an individual intent on the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception has vomited the connection with the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[895]="*So evamassa veditabbo:**You should know of them:*";
P_HTM[896]="*‘ākiñcaññāyatanasaṃyojanena hi kho visaṃyutto nevasaññānāsaññāyatanādhimutto purisapuggalo’ti.**‘That individual is intent on the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, for they’re detached from things connected with the dimension of nothingness.’*";
P_HTM[897]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, sunakkhatta, vijjati yaṃ idhekacco purisapuggalo sammā nibbānādhimutto assa.**It’s possible that a certain individual may be rightly intent on extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[898]="*Sammā nibbānādhimuttassa kho, sunakkhatta, purisapuggalassa tappatirūpī ceva kathā saṇṭhāti, tadanudhammañca anuvitakketi, anuvicāreti, tañca purisaṃ bhajati, tena ca vittiṃ āpajjati;**Such an individual engages in pertinent conversation, thinking and considering in line with that. They associate with that kind of person, and they find it satisfying.*";
P_HTM[899]="*nevasaññānāsaññāyatanapaṭisaṃyuttāya ca pana kathāya kacchamānāya na sussūsati, na sotaṃ odahati, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhāpeti, na ca taṃ purisaṃ bhajati, na ca tena vittiṃ āpajjati.**But when talk connected with the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception is going on they don’t want to listen. They don’t lend an ear or apply their minds to understand it. They don’t associate with that kind of person, and they don’t find it satisfying.*";
P_HTM[900]="*Seyyathāpi, sunakkhatta, tālo matthakacchinno abhabbo puna viruḷhiyā;**Suppose there was a palm tree with its crown cut off. It’s incapable of further growth.*";
P_HTM[901]="*evameva kho, sunakkhatta, sammā nibbānādhimuttassa purisapuggalassa ye nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasaṃyojane se ucchinnamūle tālāvatthukate anabhāvaṃkate āyatiṃ anuppādadhamme.**In the same way, an individual rightly intent on extinguishment has cut off the connection with the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception at the root, made it like a palm stump, obliterated it, so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[902]="*So evamassa veditabbo:**You should know of them:*";
P_HTM[903]="*‘nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasaṃyojanena hi kho visaṃyutto sammā nibbānādhimutto purisapuggalo’ti.**‘That individual is rightly intent on extinguishment, for they’re detached from things connected with the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.’*";
P_HTM[904]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, sunakkhatta, vijjati yaṃ idhekaccassa bhikkhuno evamassa:**It’s possible that a certain mendicant might think:*";
P_HTM[905]="*‘taṇhā kho sallaṃ samaṇena vuttaṃ, avijjāvisadoso, chandarāgabyāpādena ruppati.**‘The Ascetic has said that craving is a dart; and that the poison of ignorance is inflicted by desire and ill will.*";
P_HTM[906]="*Taṃ me taṇhāsallaṃ pahīnaṃ, apanīto avijjāvisadoso, sammā nibbānādhimuttohamasmī’ti.**I have given up the dart of craving and expelled the poison of ignorance; I am rightly intent on extinguishment.’*";
P_HTM[907]="*Evaṃmāni assa atathaṃ samānaṃ.**Having such conceit, though it’s not based in fact,*";
P_HTM[908]="*So yāni sammā nibbānādhimuttassa asappāyāni tāni anuyuñjeyya; asappāyaṃ cakkhunā rūpadassanaṃ anuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ sotena saddaṃ anuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ ghānena gandhaṃ anuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ jivhāya rasaṃ anuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ anuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ manasā dhammaṃ anuyuñjeyya.**they would engage in things unconducive to extinguishment: unsuitable sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[909]="*Tassa asappāyaṃ cakkhunā rūpadassanaṃ anuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ sotena saddaṃ anuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ ghānena gandhaṃ anuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ jivhāya rasaṃ anuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ anuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ manasā dhammaṃ anuyuttassa rāgo cittaṃ anuddhaṃseyya.**Doing so, lust infects their mind,*";
P_HTM[910]="*So rāgānuddhaṃsitena cittena maraṇaṃ vā nigaccheyya maraṇamattaṃ vā dukkhaṃ.**resulting in death or deadly pain.*";
P_HTM[911]="*Seyyathāpi, sunakkhatta, puriso sallena viddho assa savisena gāḷhūpalepanena.**Suppose a man was struck by an arrow thickly smeared with poison.*";
P_HTM[912]="*Tassa mittāmaccā ñātisālohitā bhisakkaṃ sallakattaṃ upaṭṭhāpeyyuṃ.**Their friends and colleagues, relatives and kin would get a field surgeon to treat them.*";
P_HTM[913]="*Tassa so bhisakko sallakatto satthena vaṇamukhaṃ parikanteyya.**The surgeon would cut open the wound with a scalpel,*";
P_HTM[914]="*Satthena vaṇamukhaṃ parikantitvā esaniyā sallaṃ eseyya.**probe for the arrow,*";
P_HTM[915]="*Esaniyā sallaṃ esitvā sallaṃ abbuheyya, apaneyya visadosaṃ saupādisesaṃ.**extract it, and expel the poison, leaving some residue behind.*";
P_HTM[916]="*Saupādisesoti jānamāno so evaṃ vadeyya:**Thinking that no residue remained, the surgeon would say:*";
P_HTM[917]="*‘ambho purisa, ubbhataṃ kho te sallaṃ, apanīto visadoso saupādiseso.**‘My good man, the dart has been extracted and the poison expelled without residue.*";
P_HTM[918]="*Analañca te antarāyāya.**It’s not capable of harming you.*";
P_HTM[919]="*Sappāyāni ceva bhojanāni bhuñjeyyāsi, mā te asappāyāni bhojanāni bhuñjato vaṇo assāvī assa.**Eat only suitable food. Don’t eat unsuitable food, or else the wound may get infected.*";
P_HTM[920]="*Kālena kālañca vaṇaṃ dhoveyyāsi, kālena kālaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ ālimpeyyāsi, mā te na kālena kālaṃ vaṇaṃ dhovato na kālena kālaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ ālimpato pubbalohitaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ pariyonandhi.**Regularly wash the wound and anoint the opening, or else it’ll get covered with pus and blood.*";
P_HTM[921]="*Mā ca vātātape cārittaṃ anuyuñji, mā te vātātape cārittaṃ anuyuttassa rajosūkaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ anuddhaṃsesi.**Don’t walk too much in the wind and sun, or else dust and dirt will infect the wound.*";
P_HTM[922]="*Vaṇānurakkhī ca, ambho purisa, vihareyyāsi vaṇasāropī’ti.**Take care of the wound, my good sir, heal it.’*";
P_HTM[923]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think:*";
P_HTM[924]="*‘ubbhataṃ kho me sallaṃ, apanīto visadoso anupādiseso.**‘The dart has been extracted and the poison expelled without residue.*";
P_HTM[925]="*Analañca me antarāyāyā’ti.**It’s not capable of harming me.’*";
P_HTM[926]="*So asappāyāni ceva bhojanāni bhuñjeyya. Tassa asappāyāni bhojanāni bhuñjato vaṇo assāvī assa.**They’d eat unsuitable food, and the wound would get infected.*";
P_HTM[927]="*Na ca kālena kālaṃ vaṇaṃ dhoveyya, na ca kālena kālaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ ālimpeyya. Tassa na kālena kālaṃ vaṇaṃ dhovato, na kālena kālaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ ālimpato pubbalohitaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ pariyonandheyya.**And they wouldn’t regularly wash and anoint the opening, so it would get covered in pus and blood.*";
P_HTM[928]="*Vātātape ca cārittaṃ anuyuñjeyya. Tassa vātātape cārittaṃ anuyuttassa rajosūkaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ anuddhaṃseyya.**And they’d walk too much in the wind and sun, so dust and dirt infected the wound.*";
P_HTM[929]="*Na ca vaṇānurakkhī vihareyya na vaṇasāropī.**And they wouldn’t take care of the wound or heal it.*";
P_HTM[930]="*Tassa imissā ca asappāyakiriyāya, asuci visadoso apanīto saupādiseso tadubhayena vaṇo puthuttaṃ gaccheyya.**Then both because they did what was unsuitable, and because of the residue of unclean poison, the wound would spread,*";
P_HTM[931]="*So puthuttaṃ gatena vaṇena maraṇaṃ vā nigaccheyya maraṇamattaṃ vā dukkhaṃ.**resulting in death or deadly pain.*";
P_HTM[932]="*Evameva kho, sunakkhatta, ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ idhekaccassa bhikkhuno evamassa:**In the same way, it’s possible that a certain mendicant might think:*";
P_HTM[933]="*‘taṇhā kho sallaṃ samaṇena vuttaṃ, avijjāvisadoso chandarāgabyāpādena ruppati.**‘The Ascetic has said that craving is a dart; and that the poison of ignorance is inflicted by desire and ill will.*";
P_HTM[934]="*Taṃ me taṇhāsallaṃ pahīnaṃ, apanīto avijjāvisadoso, sammā nibbānādhimuttohamasmī’ti.**I have given up the dart of craving and expelled the poison of ignorance; I am rightly intent on extinguishment.’*";
P_HTM[935]="*Evaṃmāni assa atathaṃ samānaṃ.**Having such conceit, though it’s not based in fact,*";
P_HTM[936]="*So yāni sammā nibbānādhimuttassa asappāyāni tāni anuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ cakkhunā rūpadassanaṃ anuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ sotena saddaṃ anuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ ghānena gandhaṃ anuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ jivhāya rasaṃ anuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ anuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ manasā dhammaṃ anuyuñjeyya.**they would engage in things unconducive to extinguishment: unsuitable sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[937]="*Tassa asappāyaṃ cakkhunā rūpadassanaṃ anuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ sotena saddaṃ anuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ ghānena gandhaṃ anuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ jivhāya rasaṃ anuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ anuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ manasā dhammaṃ anuyuttassa rāgo cittaṃ anuddhaṃseyya.**Doing so, lust infects their mind,*";
P_HTM[938]="*So rāgānuddhaṃsitena cittena maraṇaṃ vā nigaccheyya maraṇamattaṃ vā dukkhaṃ.**resulting in death or deadly pain.*";
P_HTM[939]="*Maraṇañhetaṃ, sunakkhatta, ariyassa vinaye yo sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattati;**For it is death in the training of the noble one to reject the training and return to a lesser life.*";
P_HTM[940]="*maraṇamattañhetaṃ, sunakkhatta, dukkhaṃ yaṃ aññataraṃ saṅkiliṭṭhaṃ āpattiṃ āpajjati.**And it is deadly pain to commit one of the corrupt offenses.*";
P_HTM[941]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, sunakkhatta, vijjati yaṃ idhekaccassa bhikkhuno evamassa:**It’s possible that a certain mendicant might think:*";
P_HTM[942]="*‘taṇhā kho sallaṃ samaṇena vuttaṃ, avijjāvisadoso chandarāgabyāpādena ruppati.**‘The Ascetic has said that craving is a dart; and that the poison of ignorance is inflicted by desire and ill will.*";
P_HTM[943]="*Taṃ me taṇhāsallaṃ pahīnaṃ, apanīto avijjāvisadoso, sammā nibbānādhimuttohamasmī’ti.**I have given up the dart of craving and expelled the poison of ignorance; I am rightly intent on extinguishment.’*";
P_HTM[944]="*Sammā nibbānādhimuttasseva sato so yāni sammā nibbānādhimuttassa asappāyāni tāni nānuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ cakkhunā rūpadassanaṃ nānuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ sotena saddaṃ nānuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ ghānena gandhaṃ nānuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ jivhāya rasaṃ nānuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ nānuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ manasā dhammaṃ nānuyuñjeyya.**Being rightly intent on extinguishment, they wouldn’t engage in things unconducive to extinguishment: unsuitable sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[945]="*Tassa asappāyaṃ cakkhunā rūpadassanaṃ nānuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ sotena saddaṃ nānuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ ghānena gandhaṃ nānuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ jivhāya rasaṃ nānuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ nānuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ manasā dhammaṃ nānuyuttassa rāgo cittaṃ nānuddhaṃseyya.**Doing so, lust wouldn’t infect their mind,*";
P_HTM[946]="*So na rāgānuddhaṃsitena cittena neva maraṇaṃ vā nigaccheyya na maraṇamattaṃ vā dukkhaṃ.**so no death or deadly pain would result.*";
P_HTM[947]="*Seyyathāpi, sunakkhatta, puriso sallena viddho assa savisena gāḷhūpalepanena.**Suppose a man was struck by an arrow thickly smeared with poison.*";
P_HTM[948]="*Tassa mittāmaccā ñātisālohitā bhisakkaṃ sallakattaṃ upaṭṭhāpeyyuṃ.**Their friends and colleagues, relatives and kin would get a field surgeon to treat them.*";
P_HTM[949]="*Tassa so bhisakko sallakatto satthena vaṇamukhaṃ parikanteyya.**The surgeon would cut open the wound with a scalpel,*";
P_HTM[950]="*Satthena vaṇamukhaṃ parikantitvā esaniyā sallaṃ eseyya.**probe for the arrow,*";
P_HTM[951]="*Esaniyā sallaṃ esitvā sallaṃ abbuheyya, apaneyya visadosaṃ anupādisesaṃ.**extract it, and expel the poison, leaving no residue behind.*";
P_HTM[952]="*Anupādisesoti jānamāno so evaṃ vadeyya:**Knowing that no residue remained, the surgeon would say:*";
P_HTM[953]="*‘ambho purisa, ubbhataṃ kho te sallaṃ, apanīto visadoso anupādiseso.**‘My good man, the dart has been extracted and the poison expelled without residue.*";
P_HTM[954]="*Analañca te antarāyāya.**It’s not capable of harming you.*";
P_HTM[955]="*Sappāyāni ceva bhojanāni bhuñjeyyāsi, mā te asappāyāni bhojanāni bhuñjato vaṇo assāvī assa.**Eat only suitable food. Don’t eat unsuitable food, or else the wound may get infected.*";
P_HTM[956]="*Kālena kālañca vaṇaṃ dhoveyyāsi, kālena kālaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ ālimpeyyāsi. Mā te na kālena kālaṃ vaṇaṃ dhovato na kālena kālaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ ālimpato pubbalohitaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ pariyonandhi.**Regularly wash the wound and anoint the opening, or else it’ll get covered with pus and blood.*";
P_HTM[957]="*Mā ca vātātape cārittaṃ anuyuñji, mā te vātātape cārittaṃ anuyuttassa rajosūkaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ anuddhaṃsesi.**Don’t walk too much in the wind and sun, or else dust and dirt will infect the wound.*";
P_HTM[958]="*Vaṇānurakkhī ca, ambho purisa, vihareyyāsi vaṇasāropī’ti.**Take care of the wound, my good sir, heal it.’*";
P_HTM[959]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think:*";
P_HTM[960]="*‘ubbhataṃ kho me sallaṃ, apanīto visadoso anupādiseso.**‘The dart has been extracted and the poison expelled without residue.*";
P_HTM[961]="*Analañca me antarāyāyā’ti.**It’s not capable of harming me.’*";
P_HTM[962]="*So sappāyāni ceva bhojanāni bhuñjeyya. Tassa sappāyāni bhojanāni bhuñjato vaṇo na assāvī assa.**They’d eat suitable food, and the wound wouldn’t get infected.*";
P_HTM[963]="*Kālena kālañca vaṇaṃ dhoveyya, kālena kālaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ ālimpeyya. Tassa kālena kālaṃ vaṇaṃ dhovato kālena kālaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ ālimpato na pubbalohitaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ pariyonandheyya.**And they’d regularly wash and anoint the opening, so it wouldn’t get covered in pus and blood.*";
P_HTM[964]="*Na ca vātātape cārittaṃ anuyuñjeyya. Tassa vātātape cārittaṃ ananuyuttassa rajosūkaṃ vaṇamukhaṃ nānuddhaṃseyya.**And they wouldn’t walk too much in the wind and sun, so dust and dirt wouldn’t infect the wound.*";
P_HTM[965]="*Vaṇānurakkhī ca vihareyya vaṇasāropī.**And they’d take care of the wound and heal it.*";
P_HTM[966]="*Tassa imissā ca sappāyakiriyāya asu ca visadoso apanīto anupādiseso tadubhayena vaṇo viruheyya.**Then both because they did what was suitable, and the unclean poison had left no residue, the wound would heal,*";
P_HTM[967]="*So ruḷhena vaṇena sañchavinā neva maraṇaṃ vā nigaccheyya na maraṇamattaṃ vā dukkhaṃ.**and no death or deadly pain would result.*";
P_HTM[968]="*Evameva kho, sunakkhatta, ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ idhekaccassa bhikkhuno evamassa:**In the same way, it’s possible that a certain mendicant might think:*";
P_HTM[969]="*‘taṇhā kho sallaṃ samaṇena vuttaṃ, avijjāvisadoso chandarāgabyāpādena ruppati.**‘The Ascetic has said that craving is a dart; and that the poison of ignorance is inflicted by desire and ill will.*";
P_HTM[970]="*Taṃ me taṇhāsallaṃ pahīnaṃ, apanīto avijjāvisadoso, sammā nibbānādhimuttohamasmī’ti.**I have given up the dart of craving and expelled the poison of ignorance; I am rightly intent on extinguishment.’*";
P_HTM[971]="*Sammā nibbānādhimuttasseva sato so yāni sammā nibbānādhimuttassa asappāyāni tāni nānuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ cakkhunā rūpadassanaṃ nānuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ sotena saddaṃ nānuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ ghānena gandhaṃ nānuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ jivhāya rasaṃ nānuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ nānuyuñjeyya, asappāyaṃ manasā dhammaṃ nānuyuñjeyya.**Being rightly intent on extinguishment, they wouldn’t engage in things unconducive to extinguishment: unsuitable sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[972]="*Tassa asappāyaṃ cakkhunā rūpadassanaṃ nānuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ sotena saddaṃ nānuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ ghānena gandhaṃ nānuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ jivhāya rasaṃ nānuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ nānuyuttassa, asappāyaṃ manasā dhammaṃ nānuyuttassa, rāgo cittaṃ nānuddhaṃseyya.**Doing so, lust wouldn’t infect their mind,*";
P_HTM[973]="*So na rāgānuddhaṃsitena cittena neva maraṇaṃ vā nigaccheyya na maraṇamattaṃ vā dukkhaṃ.**so no death or deadly pain would result.*";
P_HTM[974]="*Upamā kho me ayaṃ, sunakkhatta, katā atthassa viññāpanāya.**I’ve made up this simile to make a point.*";
P_HTM[975]="*Ayaṃyevettha attho—**And this is the point:*";
P_HTM[976]="*vaṇoti kho, sunakkhatta, channetaṃ ajjhattikānaṃ āyatanānaṃ adhivacanaṃ;**‘Wound’ is a term for the six interior sense fields.*";
P_HTM[977]="*visadosoti kho, sunakkhatta, avijjāyetaṃ adhivacanaṃ;**‘Poison’ is a term for ignorance.*";
P_HTM[978]="*sallanti kho, sunakkhatta, taṇhāyetaṃ adhivacanaṃ;**‘Dart’ is a term for craving.*";
P_HTM[979]="*esanīti kho, sunakkhatta, satiyāyetaṃ adhivacanaṃ;**‘Probing’ is a term for mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[980]="*satthanti kho, sunakkhatta, ariyāyetaṃ paññāya adhivacanaṃ;**‘Scalpel’ is a term for noble wisdom.*";
P_HTM[981]="*bhisakko sallakattoti kho, sunakkhatta, tathāgatassetaṃ adhivacanaṃ arahato sammāsambuddhassa.**‘Field surgeon’ is a term for the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[982]="*So vata, sunakkhatta, bhikkhu chasu phassāyatanesu saṃvutakārī ‘upadhi dukkhassa mūlan’ti—**Truly, Sunakkhatta, that mendicant practices restraint regarding the six fields of contact.*";
P_HTM[983]="*iti viditvā nirupadhi upadhisaṅkhaye vimutto upadhismiṃ vā kāyaṃ upasaṃharissati cittaṃ vā uppādessatīti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Understanding that attachment is the root of suffering, they are freed with the ending of attachments. It’s not possible that they would apply their body or interest their mind in any attachment.*";
P_HTM[984]="*Seyyathāpi, sunakkhatta, āpānīyakaṃso vaṇṇasampanno gandhasampanno rasasampanno;**Suppose there was a bronze cup of beverage that had a nice color, aroma, and flavor.*";
P_HTM[985]="*so ca kho visena saṃsaṭṭho.**But it was mixed with poison.*";
P_HTM[986]="*Atha puriso āgaccheyya jīvitukāmo amaritukāmo sukhakāmo dukkhapaṭikūlo.**Then a person would come along who wants to live and doesn’t want to die, who wants to be happy and recoils from pain.*";
P_HTM[987]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, sunakkhatta,**What do you think, Sunakkhatta?*";
P_HTM[988]="*api nu so puriso amuṃ āpānīyakaṃsaṃ piveyya yaṃ jaññā:**Would that person drink that beverage knowing that*";
P_HTM[989]="*‘imāhaṃ pivitvā maraṇaṃ vā nigacchāmi maraṇamattaṃ vā dukkhan’”ti?**it would result in death or deadly suffering?”*";
P_HTM[990]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[991]="*“Evameva kho, sunakkhatta, so vata bhikkhu chasu phassāyatanesu saṃvutakārī ‘upadhi dukkhassa mūlan’ti—**“In the same way, Sunakkhatta, that mendicant practices restraint regarding the six fields of contact.*";
P_HTM[992]="*iti viditvā nirupadhi upadhisaṅkhaye vimutto upadhismiṃ vā kāyaṃ upasaṃharissati cittaṃ vā uppādessatīti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Understanding that attachment is the root of suffering, they are freed with the ending of attachments. It’s not possible that they would apply their body or interest their mind in any attachment.*";
P_HTM[993]="*Seyyathāpi, sunakkhatta, āsīviso ghoraviso.**Suppose there was a lethal viper.*";
P_HTM[994]="*Atha puriso āgaccheyya jīvitukāmo amaritukāmo sukhakāmo dukkhapaṭikūlo.**Then a person would come along who wants to live and doesn’t want to die, who wants to be happy and recoils from pain.*";
P_HTM[995]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, sunakkhatta,**What do you think, Sunakkhatta?*";
P_HTM[996]="*api nu so puriso amussa āsīvisassa ghoravisassa hatthaṃ vā aṅguṭṭhaṃ vā dajjā yaṃ jaññā:**Would that person give that lethal viper their hand or finger knowing that*";
P_HTM[997]="*‘imināhaṃ daṭṭho maraṇaṃ vā nigacchāmi maraṇamattaṃ vā dukkhan’”ti?**it would result in death or deadly suffering?”*";
P_HTM[998]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[999]="*“Evameva kho, sunakkhatta, so vata bhikkhu chasu phassāyatanesu saṃvutakārī ‘upadhi dukkhassa mūlan’ti—**“In the same way, Sunakkhatta, that mendicant practices restraint regarding the six fields of contact.*";
P_HTM[1000]="*iti viditvā nirupadhi upadhisaṅkhaye vimutto upadhismiṃ vā kāyaṃ upasaṃharissati cittaṃ vā uppādessatīti—**Understanding that attachment is the root of suffering, they are freed with the ending of attachments. It’s not possible that they would apply their body or interest their mind in any attachment.”*";
P_HTM[1001]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1002]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1003]="*Attamano sunakkhatto licchaviputto bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Sunakkhatta of the Licchavi clan was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1004]="*Sunakkhattasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1005]="*106. Āneñjasappāyasutta**Conducive to the Imperturbable*";
P_HTM[1006]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1007]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kurūsu viharati kammāsadhammaṃ nāma kurūnaṃ nigamo.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Kurus, near the Kuru town named Kammāsadamma.*";
P_HTM[1008]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[1009]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[1010]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1011]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1012]="*“Aniccā, bhikkhave, kāmā tucchā musā mosadhammā.**“Mendicants, sensual pleasures are impermanent, hollow, false, and deceptive,*";
P_HTM[1013]="*Māyākatametaṃ, bhikkhave, bālalāpanaṃ.**made by illusion, cooed over by fools.*";
P_HTM[1014]="*Ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmā, ye ca samparāyikā kāmā;**Sensual pleasures in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1015]="*yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā kāmasaññā—**sensual perceptions in this life and in lives to come;*";
P_HTM[1016]="*ubhayametaṃ māradheyyaṃ, mārassesa visayo, mārassesa nivāpo, mārassesa gocaro.**both of these are Māra’s sovereignty, Māra’s domain, and Māra’s territory.*";
P_HTM[1017]="*Etthete pāpakā akusalā mānasā abhijjhāpi byāpādāpi sārambhāpi saṃvattanti.**They conduce to bad, unskillful qualities such as desire, ill will, and aggression.*";
P_HTM[1018]="*Teva ariyasāvakassa idhamanusikkhato antarāyāya sambhavanti.**And they create an obstacle for a noble disciple training here.*";
P_HTM[1019]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati:**A noble disciple reflects on this:*";
P_HTM[1020]="*‘ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmā, ye ca samparāyikā kāmā;**‘Sensual pleasures in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1021]="*yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā kāmasaññā—**sensual perceptions in this life and in lives to come;*";
P_HTM[1022]="*ubhayametaṃ māradheyyaṃ, mārassesa visayo, mārassesa nivāpo, mārassesa gocaro.**both of these are Māra’s sovereignty, Māra’s domain, and Māra’s territory.*";
P_HTM[1023]="*Etthete pāpakā akusalā mānasā abhijjhāpi byāpādāpi sārambhāpi saṃvattanti,**They conduce to bad, unskillful qualities such as desire, ill will, and aggression.*";
P_HTM[1024]="*teva ariyasāvakassa idhamanusikkhato antarāyāya sambhavanti.**And they create an obstacle for a noble disciple training here.*";
P_HTM[1025]="*Yannūnāhaṃ vipulena mahaggatena cetasā vihareyyaṃ abhibhuyya lokaṃ adhiṭṭhāya manasā.**Why don’t I meditate with an abundant, expansive heart, having mastered the world and stabilized the mind?*";
P_HTM[1026]="*Vipulena hi me mahaggatena cetasā viharato abhibhuyya lokaṃ adhiṭṭhāya manasā ye pāpakā akusalā mānasā abhijjhāpi byāpādāpi sārambhāpi te na bhavissanti.**Then I will have no more bad, unskillful qualities such as desire, ill will, and aggression.*";
P_HTM[1027]="*Tesaṃ pahānā aparittañca me cittaṃ bhavissati appamāṇaṃ subhāvitan’ti.**And by giving them up my mind, no longer limited, will become limitless and well developed.’*";
P_HTM[1028]="*Tassa evaṃpaṭipannassa tabbahulavihārino āyatane cittaṃ pasīdati.**Practicing in this way and meditating on it often their mind becomes confident in this dimension.*";
P_HTM[1029]="*Sampasāde sati etarahi vā āneñjaṃ samāpajjati paññāya vā adhimuccati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā.**Being confident, they either attain the imperturbable now, or are freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1030]="*Ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ taṃsaṃvattanikaṃ viññāṇaṃ assa āneñjūpagaṃ.**When their body breaks up, after death, it’s possible that the consciousness headed that way will be reborn in the imperturbable.*";
P_HTM[1031]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamā āneñjasappāyā paṭipadā akkhāyati.**This is said to be the first way of practice suitable for attaining the imperturbable.*";
P_HTM[1032]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Furthermore, a noble disciple reflects:*";
P_HTM[1033]="*‘ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmā, ye ca samparāyikā kāmā;**‘Sensual pleasures in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1034]="*yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā kāmasaññā;**sensual perceptions in this life and in lives to come;*";
P_HTM[1035]="*yaṃ kiñci rūpaṃ sabbaṃ rūpaṃ cattāri ca mahābhūtāni, catunnañca mahābhūtānaṃ upādāyarūpan’ti.**whatever is form, all form is the four primary elements, or form derived from the four primary elements.’*";
P_HTM[1036]="*Tassa evaṃpaṭipannassa tabbahulavihārino āyatane cittaṃ pasīdati.**Practicing in this way and meditating on it often their mind becomes confident in this dimension.*";
P_HTM[1037]="*Sampasāde sati etarahi vā āneñjaṃ samāpajjati paññāya vā adhimuccati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā.**Being confident, they either attain the imperturbable now, or are freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1038]="*Ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ taṃsaṃvattanikaṃ viññāṇaṃ assa āneñjūpagaṃ.**When their body breaks up, after death, it’s possible that the consciousness headed that way will be reborn in the imperturbable.*";
P_HTM[1039]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyā āneñjasappāyā paṭipadā akkhāyati.**This is said to be the second way of practice suitable for attaining the imperturbable.*";
P_HTM[1040]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Furthermore, a noble disciple reflects:*";
P_HTM[1041]="*‘ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmā, ye ca samparāyikā kāmā;**‘Sensual pleasures in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1042]="*yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā kāmasaññā;**sensual perceptions in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1043]="*ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā rūpā, ye ca samparāyikā rūpā;**visions in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1044]="*yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā rūpasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā rūpasaññā—**perceptions of visions in this life and in lives to come;*";
P_HTM[1045]="*ubhayametaṃ aniccaṃ.**all of these are impermanent.*";
P_HTM[1046]="*Yadaniccaṃ taṃ nālaṃ abhinandituṃ, nālaṃ abhivadituṃ, nālaṃ ajjhositun’ti.**And what’s impermanent is not worth approving, welcoming, or clinging to.’*";
P_HTM[1047]="*Tassa evaṃpaṭipannassa tabbahulavihārino āyatane cittaṃ pasīdati.**Practicing in this way and meditating on it often their mind becomes confident in this dimension.*";
P_HTM[1048]="*Sampasāde sati etarahi vā āneñjaṃ samāpajjati paññāya vā adhimuccati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā.**Being confident, they either attain the imperturbable now, or are freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1049]="*Ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ taṃsaṃvattanikaṃ viññāṇaṃ assa āneñjūpagaṃ.**When their body breaks up, after death, it’s possible that the consciousness headed that way will be reborn in the imperturbable.*";
P_HTM[1050]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyā āneñjasappāyā paṭipadā akkhāyati.**This is said to be the third way of practice suitable for attaining the imperturbable.*";
P_HTM[1051]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Furthermore, a noble disciple reflects:*";
P_HTM[1052]="*‘ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmā, ye ca samparāyikā kāmā;**‘Sensual pleasures in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1053]="*yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā kāmasaññā;**sensual perceptions in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1054]="*ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā rūpā, ye ca samparāyikā rūpā;**visions in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1055]="*yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā rūpasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā rūpasaññā;**perceptions of visions in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1056]="*yā ca āneñjasaññā—**and perceptions of the imperturbable;*";
P_HTM[1057]="*sabbā saññā.**all are perceptions.*";
P_HTM[1058]="*Yatthetā aparisesā nirujjhanti etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ—**Where they cease without anything left over, that is peaceful, that is sublime,*";
P_HTM[1059]="*yadidaṃ ākiñcaññāyatanan’ti.**namely the dimension of nothingness.’*";
P_HTM[1060]="*Tassa evaṃpaṭipannassa tabbahulavihārino āyatane cittaṃ pasīdati.**Practicing in this way and meditating on it often their mind becomes confident in this dimension.*";
P_HTM[1061]="*Sampasāde sati etarahi vā ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samāpajjati paññāya vā adhimuccati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā.**Being confident, they either attain the dimension of nothingness now, or are freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1062]="*Ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ taṃsaṃvattanikaṃ viññāṇaṃ assa ākiñcaññāyatanūpagaṃ.**When their body breaks up, after death, it’s possible that the consciousness headed that way will be reborn in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1063]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamā ākiñcaññāyatanasappāyā paṭipadā akkhāyati.**This is said to be the first way of practice suitable for attaining the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1064]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako araññagato vā rukkhamūlagato vā suññāgāragato vā iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Furthermore, a noble disciple has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, and reflects like this:*";
P_HTM[1065]="*‘suññamidaṃ attena vā attaniyena vā’ti.**‘This is empty of a self or what belongs to a self.’*";
P_HTM[1066]="*Tassa evaṃpaṭipannassa tabbahulavihārino āyatane cittaṃ pasīdati.**Practicing in this way and meditating on it often their mind becomes confident in this dimension.*";
P_HTM[1067]="*Sampasāde sati etarahi vā ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samāpajjati paññāya vā adhimuccati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā.**Being confident, they either attain the dimension of nothingness now, or are freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1068]="*Ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ taṃsaṃvattanikaṃ viññāṇaṃ assa ākiñcaññāyatanūpagaṃ.**When their body breaks up, after death, it’s possible that the consciousness headed that way will be reborn in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1069]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyā ākiñcaññāyatanasappāyā paṭipadā akkhāyati.**This is said to be the second way of practice suitable for attaining the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1070]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Furthermore, a noble disciple reflects:*";
P_HTM[1071]="*‘nāhaṃ kvacani kassaci kiñcanatasmiṃ, na ca mama kvacani kismiñci kiñcanaṃ natthī’ti.**‘I don’t belong to anyone anywhere! And nothing belongs to me anywhere!’*";
P_HTM[1072]="*Tassa evaṃpaṭipannassa tabbahulavihārino āyatane cittaṃ pasīdati.**Practicing in this way and meditating on it often their mind becomes confident in this dimension.*";
P_HTM[1073]="*Sampasāde sati etarahi vā ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samāpajjati paññāya vā adhimuccati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā.**Being confident, they either attain the dimension of nothingness now, or are freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1074]="*Ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ taṃsaṃvattanikaṃ viññāṇaṃ assa ākiñcaññāyatanūpagaṃ.**When their body breaks up, after death, it’s possible that the consciousness headed that way will be reborn in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1075]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyā ākiñcaññāyatanasappāyā paṭipadā akkhāyati.**This is said to be the third way of practice suitable for attaining the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1076]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Furthermore, a noble disciple reflects:*";
P_HTM[1077]="*‘ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmā, ye ca samparāyikā kāmā;**‘Sensual pleasures in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1078]="*yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā kāmasaññā;**sensual perceptions in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1079]="*ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā rūpā, ye ca samparāyikā rūpā;**visions in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1080]="*yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā rūpasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā rūpasaññā;**perceptions of visions in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1081]="*yā ca āneñjasaññā, yā ca ākiñcaññāyatanasaññā—**perceptions of the imperturbable, and perceptions of the dimension of nothingness;*";
P_HTM[1082]="*sabbā saññā.**all are perceptions.*";
P_HTM[1083]="*Yatthetā aparisesā nirujjhanti etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ—**Where they cease without anything left over, that is peaceful, that is sublime,*";
P_HTM[1084]="*yadidaṃ nevasaññānāsaññāyatanan’ti.**namely the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.’*";
P_HTM[1085]="*Tassa evaṃpaṭipannassa tabbahulavihārino āyatane cittaṃ pasīdati.**Practicing in this way and meditating on it often their mind becomes confident in this dimension.*";
P_HTM[1086]="*Sampasāde sati etarahi vā nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samāpajjati paññāya vā adhimuccati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā.**Being confident, they either attain the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception now, or are freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1087]="*Ṭhānametaṃ vijjati yaṃ taṃsaṃvattanikaṃ viññāṇaṃ assa nevasaññānāsaññāyatanūpagaṃ.**When their body breaks up, after death, it’s possible that the consciousness headed that way will be reborn in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[1088]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasappāyā paṭipadā akkhāyatī”ti.**This is said to be the way of practice suitable for attaining the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.”*";
P_HTM[1089]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Ānanda said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1090]="*“idha, bhante, bhikkhu evaṃ paṭipanno hoti:**“Sir, take a mendicant who practices like this:*";
P_HTM[1091]="*‘no cassa, no ca me siyā; na bhavissati, na me bhavissati; yadatthi yaṃ, bhūtaṃ—taṃ pajahāmī’ti.**‘It might not be, and it might not be mine. It will not be, and it will not be mine. I am giving up what exists, what has come to be.’*";
P_HTM[1092]="*Evaṃ upekkhaṃ paṭilabhati.**In this way they gain equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1093]="*Parinibbāyeyya nu kho so, bhante, bhikkhu na vā parinibbāyeyyā”ti?**Would that mendicant become extinguished or not?”*";
P_HTM[1094]="*“Apetthekacco, ānanda, bhikkhu parinibbāyeyya, apetthekacco bhikkhu na parinibbāyeyyā”ti.**“One such mendicant might become extinguished, Ānanda, while another might not.”*";
P_HTM[1095]="*“Ko nu kho, bhante, hetu ko paccayo yenapetthekacco bhikkhu parinibbāyeyya, apetthekacco bhikkhu na parinibbāyeyyā”ti?**“What is the cause, sir, what is the reason for this?”*";
P_HTM[1096]="*“Idhānanda, bhikkhu evaṃ paṭipanno hoti:**“Ānanda, take a mendicant who practices like this:*";
P_HTM[1097]="*‘no cassa, no ca me siyā; na bhavissati, na me bhavissati; yadatthi, yaṃ bhūtaṃ—taṃ pajahāmī’ti.**‘It might not be, and it might not be mine. It will not be, and it will not be mine. I am giving up what exists, what has come to be.’*";
P_HTM[1098]="*Evaṃ upekkhaṃ paṭilabhati.**In this way they gain equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1099]="*So taṃ upekkhaṃ abhinandati, abhivadati, ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**They approve, welcome, and keep clinging to that equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1100]="*Tassa taṃ upekkhaṃ abhinandato abhivadato ajjhosāya tiṭṭhato tannissitaṃ hoti viññāṇaṃ tadupādānaṃ.**Their consciousness relies on that and grasps it.*";
P_HTM[1101]="*Saupādāno, ānanda, bhikkhu na parinibbāyatī”ti.**A mendicant with grasping does not become extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[1102]="*“Kahaṃ pana so, bhante, bhikkhu upādiyamāno upādiyatī”ti?**“But sir, what is that mendicant grasping?”*";
P_HTM[1103]="*“Nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ, ānandā”ti.**“The dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.”*";
P_HTM[1104]="*“Upādānaseṭṭhaṃ kira so, bhante, bhikkhu upādiyamāno upādiyatī”ti?**“Sir, it seems that mendicant is grasping the best thing to grasp!”*";
P_HTM[1105]="*“Upādānaseṭṭhañhi so, ānanda, bhikkhu upādiyamāno upādiyati.**“Indeed, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[1106]="*Upādānaseṭṭhañhetaṃ, ānanda, yadidaṃ—**For the best thing to grasp is*";
P_HTM[1107]="*nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ.**the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[1108]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu evaṃ paṭipanno hoti:**Take a mendicant who practices like this:*";
P_HTM[1109]="*‘no cassa, no ca me siyā; na bhavissati, na me bhavissati; yadatthi, yaṃ bhūtaṃ—taṃ pajahāmī’ti.**‘It might not be, and it might not be mine. It will not be, and it will not be mine. I am giving up what exists, what has come to be.’*";
P_HTM[1110]="*Evaṃ upekkhaṃ paṭilabhati.**In this way they gain equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1111]="*So taṃ upekkhaṃ nābhinandati, nābhivadati, na ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**They don’t approve, welcome, or keep clinging to that equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1112]="*Tassa taṃ upekkhaṃ anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato na tannissitaṃ hoti viññāṇaṃ na tadupādānaṃ.**So their consciousness doesn’t rely on that and grasp it.*";
P_HTM[1113]="*Anupādāno, ānanda, bhikkhu parinibbāyatī”ti.**A mendicant free of grasping becomes extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[1114]="*“Acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante.**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing!*";
P_HTM[1115]="*Nissāya nissāya kira no, bhante, bhagavatā oghassa nittharaṇā akkhātā.**The Buddha has explained to us how to cross over the flood by relying on one support or the other.*";
P_HTM[1116]="*Katamo pana, bhante, ariyo vimokkho”ti?**But sir, what is noble liberation?”*";
P_HTM[1117]="*“Idhānanda, bhikkhu ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati:**“Ananda, it’s when a mendicant reflects like this:*";
P_HTM[1118]="*‘ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmā, ye ca samparāyikā kāmā;**‘Sensual pleasures in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1119]="*yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā kāmasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā kāmasaññā;**sensual perceptions in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1120]="*ye ca diṭṭhadhammikā rūpā, ye ca samparāyikā rūpā;**visions in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1121]="*yā ca diṭṭhadhammikā rūpasaññā, yā ca samparāyikā rūpasaññā;**perceptions of visions in this life and in lives to come,*";
P_HTM[1122]="*yā ca āneñjasaññā, yā ca ākiñcaññāyatanasaññā, yā ca nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasaññā—**perceptions of the imperturbable, perceptions of the dimension of nothingness, perceptions of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception;*";
P_HTM[1123]="*esa sakkāyo yāvatā sakkāyo.**that is identity as far as identity extends.*";
P_HTM[1124]="*Etaṃ amataṃ yadidaṃ anupādā cittassa vimokkho.**This is the deathless, namely the liberation of the mind through not grasping.*";
P_HTM[1125]="*Iti, kho, ānanda, desitā mayā āneñjasappāyā paṭipadā, desitā ākiñcaññāyatanasappāyā paṭipadā, desitā nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasappāyā paṭipadā, desitā nissāya nissāya oghassa nittharaṇā, desito ariyo vimokkho.**So, Ānanda, I have taught the ways of practice suitable for attaining the imperturbable, the dimension of nothingness, and the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception. I have taught how to cross the flood by relying on one support or the other, and I have taught noble liberation.*";
P_HTM[1126]="*Yaṃ kho, ānanda, satthārā karaṇīyaṃ sāvakānaṃ hitesinā anukampakena anukampaṃ upādāya, kataṃ vo taṃ mayā.**Out of compassion, I’ve done what a teacher should do who wants what’s best for their disciples.*";
P_HTM[1127]="*Etāni, ānanda, rukkhamūlāni, etāni suññāgārāni. Jhāyathānanda, mā pamādattha, mā pacchā vippaṭisārino ahuvattha. Ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī’”ti.**Here are these roots of trees, and here are these empty huts. Practice absorption, Ānanda! Don’t be negligent! Don’t regret it later! This is my instruction to you.”*";
P_HTM[1128]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1129]="*Attamano āyasmā ānando bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Ānanda was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1130]="*Āneñjasappāyasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1131]="*107. Gaṇakamoggallānasutta**With Moggallāna the Accountant*";
P_HTM[1132]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1133]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati pubbārāme migāramātupāsāde.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in the Eastern Monastery, the stilt longhouse of Migāra’s mother.*";
P_HTM[1134]="*Atha kho gaṇakamoggallāno brāhmaṇo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then the brahmin Moggallāna the Accountant went up to the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[1135]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho gaṇakamoggallāno brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1136]="*“Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, imassa migāramātupāsādassa dissati anupubbasikkhā anupubbakiriyā anupubbapaṭipadā yadidaṃ—**“Master Gotama, in this stilt longhouse we can see gradual progress*";
P_HTM[1137]="*yāva pacchimasopānakaḷevarā;**down to the last step of the staircase.*";
P_HTM[1138]="*imesampi hi, bho gotama, brāhmaṇānaṃ dissati anupubbasikkhā anupubbakiriyā anupubbapaṭipadā yadidaṃ—**Among the brahmins we can see gradual progress*";
P_HTM[1139]="*ajjhene;**in learning the chants.*";
P_HTM[1140]="*imesampi hi, bho gotama, issāsānaṃ dissati anupubbasikkhā anupubbakiriyā anupubbapaṭipadā yadidaṃ—**Among archers we can see gradual progress*";
P_HTM[1141]="*issatthe.**in archery.*";
P_HTM[1142]="*Amhākampi hi, bho gotama, gaṇakānaṃ gaṇanājīvānaṃ dissati anupubbasikkhā anupubbakiriyā anupubbapaṭipadā yadidaṃ—**Among us accountants, who earn a living by accounting, we can see gradual progress*";
P_HTM[1143]="*saṅkhāne.**in mathematics.*";
P_HTM[1144]="*Mayañhi, bho gotama, antevāsiṃ labhitvā paṭhamaṃ evaṃ gaṇāpema:**For when we get an apprentice we first make them count:*";
P_HTM[1145]="*‘ekaṃ ekakaṃ, dve dukā, tīṇi tikā, cattāri catukkā, pañca pañcakā, cha chakkā, satta sattakā, aṭṭha aṭṭhakā, nava navakā, dasa dasakā’ti;**‘One one, two twos, three threes, four fours, five fives, six sixes, seven sevens, eight eights, nine nines, ten tens.’*";
P_HTM[1146]="*satampi mayaṃ, bho gotama, gaṇāpema, bhiyyopi gaṇāpema.**We even make them count up to a hundred.*";
P_HTM[1147]="*Sakkā nu kho, bho gotama, imasmimpi dhammavinaye evameva anupubbasikkhā anupubbakiriyā anupubbapaṭipadā paññapetun”ti?**Is it possible to similarly describe a gradual training, gradual progress, and gradual practice in this teaching and training?”*";
P_HTM[1148]="*“Sakkā, brāhmaṇa, imasmimpi dhammavinaye anupubbasikkhā anupubbakiriyā anupubbapaṭipadā paññapetuṃ.**“It is possible, brahmin.*";
P_HTM[1149]="*Seyyathāpi, brāhmaṇa, dakkho assadammako bhaddaṃ assājānīyaṃ labhitvā paṭhameneva mukhādhāne kāraṇaṃ kāreti, atha uttariṃ kāraṇaṃ kāreti;**Suppose a deft horse trainer were to obtain a fine thoroughbred. First of all he’d make it get used to wearing the bit.*";
P_HTM[1150]="*evameva kho, brāhmaṇa, tathāgato purisadammaṃ labhitvā paṭhamaṃ evaṃ vineti:**In the same way, when the Realized One gets a person for training they first guide them like this:*";
P_HTM[1151]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, sīlavā hohi, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharāhi ācāragocarasampanno aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhassu sikkhāpadesū’ti.**‘Come, mendicant, be ethical and restrained in the monastic code, conducting yourself well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, keep the rules you’ve undertaken.’*";
P_HTM[1152]="*Yato kho, brāhmaṇa, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu, tamenaṃ tathāgato uttariṃ vineti:**When they have ethical conduct, the Realized One guides them further:*";
P_HTM[1153]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, indriyesu guttadvāro hohi, cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā mā nimittaggāhī hohi mānubyañjanaggāhī.**‘Come, mendicant, guard your sense doors. When you see a sight with your eyes, don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[1154]="*Yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ cakkhundriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjāhi; rakkhāhi cakkhundriyaṃ, cakkhundriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjāhi.**If the faculty of sight were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, practice restraint, protect the faculty of sight, and achieve restraint over it.*";
P_HTM[1155]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**When you hear a sound with your ears …*";
P_HTM[1156]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā … pe …**When you smell an odor with your nose …*";
P_HTM[1157]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā … pe …**When you taste a flavor with your tongue …*";
P_HTM[1158]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā … pe …**When you feel a touch with your body …*";
P_HTM[1159]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya mā nimittaggāhī hohi mānubyañjanaggāhī.**When you know a thought with your mind, don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[1160]="*Yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ manindriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjāhi; rakkhāhi manindriyaṃ, manindriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjāhī’ti.**If the faculty of mind were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, practice restraint, protect the faculty of mind, and achieve its restraint.’*";
P_HTM[1161]="*Yato kho, brāhmaṇa, bhikkhu indriyesu guttadvāro hoti, tamenaṃ tathāgato uttariṃ vineti:**When they guard their sense doors, the Realized One guides them further:*";
P_HTM[1162]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhojane mattaññū hohi.**‘Come, mendicant, eat in moderation.*";
P_HTM[1163]="*Paṭisaṅkhā yoniso āhāraṃ āhāreyyāsi—**Reflect properly on the food that you eat:*";
P_HTM[1164]="*neva davāya na madāya na maṇḍanāya na vibhūsanāya, yāvadeva imassa kāyassa ṭhitiyā yāpanāya vihiṃsūparatiyā brahmacariyānuggahāya—iti purāṇañca vedanaṃ paṭihaṅkhāmi, navañca vedanaṃ na uppādessāmi, yātrā ca me bhavissati anavajjatā ca phāsuvihāro cā’ti.**‘Not for fun, indulgence, adornment, or decoration, but only to sustain this body, to avoid harm, and to support spiritual practice. In this way, I shall put an end to old discomfort and not give rise to new discomfort, and I will live blamelessly and at ease.’*";
P_HTM[1165]="*Yato kho, brāhmaṇa, bhikkhu bhojane mattaññū hoti, tamenaṃ tathāgato uttariṃ vineti:**When they eat in moderation, the Realized One guides them further:*";
P_HTM[1166]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, jāgariyaṃ anuyutto viharāhi, divasaṃ caṅkamena nisajjāya āvaraṇīyehi dhammehi cittaṃ parisodhehi, rattiyā paṭhamaṃ yāmaṃ caṅkamena nisajjāya āvaraṇīyehi dhammehi cittaṃ parisodhehi, rattiyā majjhimaṃ yāmaṃ dakkhiṇena passena sīhaseyyaṃ kappeyyāsi pāde pādaṃ accādhāya sato sampajāno uṭṭhānasaññaṃ manasikaritvā, rattiyā pacchimaṃ yāmaṃ paccuṭṭhāya caṅkamena nisajjāya āvaraṇīyehi dhammehi cittaṃ parisodhehī’ti.**‘Come, mendicant, be committed to wakefulness. Practice walking and sitting meditation by day, purifying your mind from obstacles. In the evening, continue to practice walking and sitting meditation. In the middle of the night, lie down in the lion’s posture—on the right side, placing one foot on top of the other—mindful and aware, and focused on the time of getting up. In the last part of the night, get up and continue to practice walking and sitting meditation, purifying your mind from obstacles.’*";
P_HTM[1167]="*Yato kho, brāhmaṇa, bhikkhu jāgariyaṃ anuyutto hoti, tamenaṃ tathāgato uttariṃ vineti:**When they are committed to wakefulness, the Realized One guides them further:*";
P_HTM[1168]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, satisampajaññena samannāgato hohi, abhikkante paṭikkante sampajānakārī, ālokite vilokite sampajānakārī, samiñjite pasārite sampajānakārī, saṅghāṭipattacīvaradhāraṇe sampajānakārī, asite pīte khāyite sāyite sampajānakārī, uccārapassāvakamme sampajānakārī, gate ṭhite nisinne sutte jāgarite bhāsite tuṇhībhāve sampajānakārī’ti.**‘Come, mendicant, have mindfulness and situational awareness. Act with situational awareness when going out and coming back; when looking ahead and aside; when bending and extending the limbs; when bearing the outer robe, bowl and robes; when eating, drinking, chewing, and tasting; when urinating and defecating; when walking, standing, sitting, sleeping, waking, speaking, and keeping silent.’*";
P_HTM[1169]="*Yato kho, brāhmaṇa, bhikkhu satisampajaññena samannāgato hoti, tamenaṃ tathāgato uttariṃ vineti:**When they have mindfulness and situational awareness, the Realized One guides them further:*";
P_HTM[1170]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajāhi araññaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ pabbataṃ kandaraṃ giriguhaṃ susānaṃ vanapatthaṃ abbhokāsaṃ palālapuñjan’ti.**‘Come, mendicant, frequent a secluded lodging—a wilderness, the root of a tree, a hill, a ravine, a mountain cave, a charnel ground, a forest, the open air, a heap of straw.’*";
P_HTM[1171]="*So vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajati araññaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ pabbataṃ kandaraṃ giriguhaṃ susānaṃ vanapatthaṃ abbhokāsaṃ palālapuñjaṃ.**And they do so.*";
P_HTM[1172]="*So pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto nisīdati pallaṅkaṃ ābhujitvā, ujuṃ kāyaṃ paṇidhāya, parimukhaṃ satiṃ upaṭṭhapetvā.**After the meal, they return from alms-round, sit down cross-legged with their body straight, and establish mindfulness right there.*";
P_HTM[1173]="*So abhijjhaṃ loke pahāya vigatābhijjhena cetasā viharati, abhijjhāya cittaṃ parisodheti;**Giving up desire for the world, they meditate with a heart rid of desire, cleansing the mind of desire.*";
P_HTM[1174]="*byāpādapadosaṃ pahāya abyāpannacitto viharati sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī, byāpādapadosā cittaṃ parisodheti;**Giving up ill will and malevolence, they meditate with a mind rid of ill will, full of compassion for all living beings, cleansing the mind of ill will.*";
P_HTM[1175]="*thinamiddhaṃ pahāya vigatathinamiddho viharati ālokasaññī sato sampajāno, thinamiddhā cittaṃ parisodheti;**Giving up dullness and drowsiness, they meditate with a mind rid of dullness and drowsiness, perceiving light, mindful and aware, cleansing the mind of dullness and drowsiness.*";
P_HTM[1176]="*uddhaccakukkuccaṃ pahāya anuddhato viharati ajjhattaṃ vūpasantacitto, uddhaccakukkuccā cittaṃ parisodheti;**Giving up restlessness and remorse, they meditate without restlessness, their mind peaceful inside, cleansing the mind of restlessness and remorse.*";
P_HTM[1177]="*vicikicchaṃ pahāya tiṇṇavicikiccho viharati akathaṃkathī kusalesu dhammesu, vicikicchāya cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up doubt, they meditate having gone beyond doubt, not undecided about skillful qualities, cleansing the mind of doubt.*";
P_HTM[1178]="*So ime pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe**They give up these five hindrances, corruptions of the heart that weaken wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1179]="*vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Then, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, they enter and remain in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[1180]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ … pe … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[1181]="*Pītiyā ca virāgā … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**And with the fading away of rapture, they enter and remain in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[1182]="*Sukhassa ca pahānā … catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[1183]="*Ye kho te, brāhmaṇa, bhikkhū sekkhā apattamānasā anuttaraṃ yogakkhemaṃ patthayamānā viharanti tesu me ayaṃ evarūpī anusāsanī hoti.**That’s how I instruct the mendicants who are trainees—who haven’t achieved their heart’s desire, but live aspiring to the supreme sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[1184]="*Ye pana te bhikkhū arahanto khīṇāsavā vusitavanto katakaraṇīyā ohitabhārā anuppattasadatthā parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojanā sammadaññāvimuttā tesaṃ ime dhammā diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārāya ceva saṃvattanti, satisampajaññāya cā”ti.**But for those mendicants who are perfected—who have ended the defilements, completed the spiritual journey, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, achieved their own goal, utterly ended the fetters of rebirth, and are rightly freed through enlightenment—these things lead to blissful meditation in the present life, and to mindfulness and awareness.”*";
P_HTM[1185]="*Evaṃ vutte, gaṇakamoggallāno brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Moggallāna the Accountant said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1186]="*“kiṃ nu kho bhoto gotamassa sāvakā bhotā gotamena evaṃ ovadīyamānā evaṃ anusāsīyamānā sabbe accantaṃ niṭṭhaṃ nibbānaṃ ārādhenti udāhu ekacce nārādhentī”ti?**“When his disciples are instructed and advised like this by Master Gotama, do all of them achieve the ultimate goal, extinguishment, or do some of them fail?”*";
P_HTM[1187]="*“Appekacce kho, brāhmaṇa, mama sāvakā mayā evaṃ ovadīyamānā evaṃ anusāsīyamānā accantaṃ niṭṭhaṃ nibbānaṃ ārādhenti, ekacce nārādhentī”ti.**“Some succeed, while others fail.”*";
P_HTM[1188]="*“Ko nu kho, bho gotama, hetu ko paccayo yaṃ tiṭṭhateva nibbānaṃ, tiṭṭhati nibbānagāmī maggo, tiṭṭhati bhavaṃ gotamo samādapetā;**“What is the cause, Master Gotama, what is the reason why, though extinguishment is present, the path leading to extinguishment is present, and Master Gotama is present to encourage them,*";
P_HTM[1189]="*atha ca pana bhoto gotamassa sāvakā bhotā gotamena evaṃ ovadīyamānā evaṃ anusāsīyamānā appekacce accantaṃ niṭṭhaṃ nibbānaṃ ārādhenti, ekacce nārādhentī”ti?**still some succeed while others fail?”*";
P_HTM[1190]="*“Tena hi, brāhmaṇa, taṃyevettha paṭipucchissāmi. Yathā te khameyya tathā naṃ byākareyyāsi.**“Well then, brahmin, I’ll ask you about this in return, and you can answer as you like.*";
P_HTM[1191]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, brāhmaṇa,**What do you think, brahmin?*";
P_HTM[1192]="*kusalo tvaṃ rājagahagāmissa maggassā”ti?**Are you skilled in the road to Rājagaha?”*";
P_HTM[1193]="*“Evaṃ, bho, kusalo ahaṃ rājagahagāmissa maggassā”ti.**“Yes, I am.”*";
P_HTM[1194]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, brāhmaṇa,**“What do you think, brahmin?*";
P_HTM[1195]="*idha puriso āgaccheyya rājagahaṃ gantukāmo.**Suppose a person was to come along who wanted to go to Rājagaha.*";
P_HTM[1196]="*So taṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadeyya:**He’d approach you and say:*";
P_HTM[1197]="*‘icchāmahaṃ, bhante, rājagahaṃ gantuṃ;**‘Sir, I wish to go to Rājagaha.*";
P_HTM[1198]="*tassa me rājagahassa maggaṃ upadisā’ti.**Please point out the road to Rājagaha.’*";
P_HTM[1199]="*Tamenaṃ tvaṃ evaṃ vadeyyāsi:**Then you’d say to them:*";
P_HTM[1200]="*‘ehambho purisa, ayaṃ maggo rājagahaṃ gacchati.**‘Here, mister, this road goes to Rājagaha.*";
P_HTM[1201]="*Tena muhuttaṃ gaccha, tena muhuttaṃ gantvā dakkhissasi amukaṃ nāma gāmaṃ, tena muhuttaṃ gaccha, tena muhuttaṃ gantvā dakkhissasi amukaṃ nāma nigamaṃ;**Go along it for a while, and you’ll see a certain village. Go along a while further, and you’ll see a certain town.*";
P_HTM[1202]="*tena muhuttaṃ gaccha, tena muhuttaṃ gantvā dakkhissasi rājagahassa ārāmarāmaṇeyyakaṃ vanarāmaṇeyyakaṃ bhūmirāmaṇeyyakaṃ pokkharaṇīrāmaṇeyyakan’ti.**Go along a while further and you’ll see Rājagaha with its delightful parks, woods, meadows, and lotus ponds.’*";
P_HTM[1203]="*So tayā evaṃ ovadīyamāno evaṃ anusāsīyamāno ummaggaṃ gahetvā pacchāmukho gaccheyya.**Instructed like this by you, they might still take the wrong road, heading west.*";
P_HTM[1204]="*Atha dutiyo puriso āgaccheyya rājagahaṃ gantukāmo.**But a second person might come with the same question and receive the same instructions.*";
P_HTM[1205]="*So taṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[1206]="*‘icchāmahaṃ, bhante, rājagahaṃ gantuṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1207]="*tassa me rājagahassa maggaṃ upadisā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1208]="*Tamenaṃ tvaṃ evaṃ vadeyyāsi:* **";
P_HTM[1209]="*‘ehambho purisa, ayaṃ maggo rājagahaṃ gacchati.* **";
P_HTM[1210]="*Tena muhuttaṃ gaccha, tena muhuttaṃ gantvā dakkhissasi amukaṃ nāma gāmaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1211]="*tena muhuttaṃ gaccha, tena muhuttaṃ gantvā dakkhissasi amukaṃ nāma nigamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1212]="*tena muhuttaṃ gaccha, tena muhuttaṃ gantvā dakkhissasi rājagahassa ārāmarāmaṇeyyakaṃ vanarāmaṇeyyakaṃ bhūmirāmaṇeyyakaṃ pokkharaṇīrāmaṇeyyakan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1213]="*So tayā evaṃ ovadīyamāno evaṃ anusāsīyamāno sotthinā rājagahaṃ gaccheyya.**Instructed by you, they might safely arrive at Rājagaha.*";
P_HTM[1214]="*Ko nu kho, brāhmaṇa, hetu ko paccayo yaṃ tiṭṭhateva rājagahaṃ, tiṭṭhati rājagahagāmī maggo, tiṭṭhasi tvaṃ samādapetā;**What is the cause, brahmin, what is the reason why, though Rājagaha is present, the path leading to Rājagaha is present, and you are there to encourage them,*";
P_HTM[1215]="*atha ca pana tayā evaṃ ovadīyamāno evaṃ anusāsīyamāno eko puriso ummaggaṃ gahetvā pacchāmukho gaccheyya, eko sotthinā rājagahaṃ gaccheyyā”ti?**one person takes the wrong path and heads west, while another arrives safely at Rājagaha?”*";
P_HTM[1216]="*“Ettha kyāhaṃ, bho gotama, karomi?**“What can I do about that, Master Gotama?*";
P_HTM[1217]="*Maggakkhāyīhaṃ, bho gotamā”ti.**I am the one who shows the way.”*";
P_HTM[1218]="*“Evameva kho, brāhmaṇa, tiṭṭhateva nibbānaṃ, tiṭṭhati nibbānagāmī maggo, tiṭṭhāmahaṃ samādapetā;**“In the same way, though extinguishment is present, the path leading to extinguishment is present, and I am present to encourage them,*";
P_HTM[1219]="*atha ca pana mama sāvakā mayā evaṃ ovadīyamānā evaṃ anusāsīyamānā appekacce accantaṃ niṭṭhaṃ nibbānaṃ ārādhenti, ekacce nārādhenti.**still some of my disciples, instructed and advised like this, achieve the ultimate goal, extinguishment, while some of them fail.*";
P_HTM[1220]="*Ettha kyāhaṃ, brāhmaṇa, karomi?**What can I do about that, brahmin?*";
P_HTM[1221]="*Maggakkhāyīhaṃ, brāhmaṇa, tathāgato”ti.**The Realized One is the one who shows the way.”*";
P_HTM[1222]="*Evaṃ vutte, gaṇakamoggallāno brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Moggallāna the Accountant said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1223]="*“yeme, bho gotama, puggalā assaddhā jīvikatthā na saddhā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitā saṭhā māyāvino ketabino uddhatā unnaḷā capalā mukharā vikiṇṇavācā indriyesu aguttadvārā bhojane amattaññuno jāgariyaṃ ananuyuttā sāmaññe anapekkhavanto sikkhāya na tibbagāravā bāhulikā sāthalikā okkamane pubbaṅgamā paviveke nikkhittadhurā kusītā hīnavīriyā muṭṭhassatino asampajānā asamāhitā vibbhantacittā duppaññā eḷamūgā, na tehi bhavaṃ gotamo saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**“Master Gotama, there are those faithless people who went forth from the lay life to homelessness not out of faith but to earn a livelihood. They’re devious, deceitful, and sneaky. They’re restless, insolent, fickle, gossipy, and loose-tongued. They do not guard their sense doors or eat in moderation, and they are not committed to wakefulness. They don’t care about the ascetic life, and don’t keenly respect the training. They’re indulgent and slack, leaders in backsliding, neglecting seclusion, lazy, and lacking energy. They’re unmindful, lacking situational awareness and immersion, with straying minds, witless and stupid. Master Gotama doesn’t live together with these.*";
P_HTM[1224]="*Ye pana te kulaputtā saddhā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitā asaṭhā amāyāvino aketabino anuddhatā anunnaḷā acapalā amukharā avikiṇṇavācā indriyesu guttadvārā bhojane mattaññuno jāgariyaṃ anuyuttā sāmaññe apekkhavanto sikkhāya tibbagāravā nabāhulikā nasāthalikā okkamane nikkhittadhurā paviveke pubbaṅgamā āraddhavīriyā pahitattā upaṭṭhitassatino sampajānā samāhitā ekaggacittā paññavanto aneḷamūgā, tehi bhavaṃ gotamo saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**But there are those gentlemen who went forth from the lay life to homelessness out of faith. They’re not devious, deceitful, and sneaky. They’re not restless, insolent, fickle, gossipy, and loose-tongued. They guard their sense doors and eat in moderation, and they are committed to wakefulness. They care about the ascetic life, and keenly respect the training. They’re not indulgent or slack, nor are they leaders in backsliding, neglecting seclusion. They’re energetic and determined. They’re mindful, with situational awareness, immersion, and unified minds; wise, not stupid. Master Gotama does live together with these.*";
P_HTM[1225]="*Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, ye keci mūlagandhā, kālānusāri tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati;**Of all kinds of fragrant root, spikenard is said to be the best.*";
P_HTM[1226]="*ye keci sāragandhā, lohitacandanaṃ tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati;**Of all kinds of fragrant heartwood, red sandalwood is said to be the best.*";
P_HTM[1227]="*ye keci pupphagandhā, vassikaṃ tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati;**Of all kinds of fragrant flower, jasmine is said to be the best.*";
P_HTM[1228]="*evameva bhoto gotamassa ovādo paramajjadhammesu.**In the same way, Master Gotama’s advice is the best of contemporary teachings.*";
P_HTM[1229]="*Abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama, abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama.**Excellent, Master Gotama! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[1230]="*Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhotā gotamena anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, Master Gotama has made the Teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[1231]="*Esāhaṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[1232]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[1233]="*Gaṇakamoggallānasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1234]="*108. Gopakamoggallānasutta**With Moggallāna the Guardian*";
P_HTM[1235]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1236]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ānando rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe aciraparinibbute bhagavati.**At one time Venerable Ānanda was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground. It was not long after the Buddha had become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1237]="*Tena kho pana samayena rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto rājagahaṃ paṭisaṅkhārāpeti rañño pajjotassa āsaṅkamāno.**Now at that time King Ajātasattu Vedehiputta of Magadha, being suspicious of King Pajjota, was having Rājagaha fortified.*";
P_HTM[1238]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya rājagahaṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then Venerable Ānanda robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Rājagaha for alms.*";
P_HTM[1239]="*Atha kho āyasmato ānandassa etadahosi:**Then it occurred to him,*";
P_HTM[1240]="*“atippago kho tāva rājagahe piṇḍāya carituṃ.**“It’s too early to wander for alms in Rājagaha.*";
P_HTM[1241]="*Yannūnāhaṃ yena gopakamoggallānassa brāhmaṇassa kammanto, yena gopakamoggallāno brāhmaṇo tenupasaṅkameyyan”ti.**Why don’t I go to see the brahmin Moggallāna the Guardian at his place of work?”*";
P_HTM[1242]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena gopakamoggallānassa brāhmaṇassa kammanto, yena gopakamoggallāno brāhmaṇo tenupasaṅkami.**So that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[1243]="*Addasā kho gopakamoggallāno brāhmaṇo āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ dūratova āgacchantaṃ.**Moggallāna the Guardian saw Ānanda coming off in the distance*";
P_HTM[1244]="*Disvāna āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1245]="*“etu kho bhavaṃ ānando.**“Come, Master Ānanda!*";
P_HTM[1246]="*Svāgataṃ bhoto ānandassa.**Welcome, Master Ānanda!*";
P_HTM[1247]="*Cirassaṃ kho bhavaṃ ānando imaṃ pariyāyamakāsi yadidaṃ idhāgamanāya.**It’s been a long time since you took the opportunity to come here.*";
P_HTM[1248]="*Nisīdatu bhavaṃ ānando, idamāsanaṃ paññattan”ti.**Please, sir, sit down, this seat is ready.”*";
P_HTM[1249]="*Nisīdi kho āyasmā ānando paññatte āsane.**Ānanda sat down on the seat spread out,*";
P_HTM[1250]="*Gopakamoggallānopi kho brāhmaṇo aññataraṃ nīcaṃ āsanaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**while Moggallāna took a low seat and sat to one side.*";
P_HTM[1251]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho gopakamoggallāno brāhmaṇo āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**Then he said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1252]="*“atthi nu kho, bho ānanda, ekabhikkhupi tehi dhammehi sabbenasabbaṃ sabbathāsabbaṃ samannāgato yehi dhammehi samannāgato so bhavaṃ gotamo ahosi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho”ti?**“Master Ānanda, is there even a single mendicant who has all the same qualities in each and every way as possessed by Master Gotama, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha?”*";
P_HTM[1253]="*“Natthi kho, brāhmaṇa, ekabhikkhupi tehi dhammehi sabbenasabbaṃ sabbathāsabbaṃ samannāgato yehi dhammehi samannāgato so bhagavā ahosi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho.**“No, brahmin, there is not.*";
P_HTM[1254]="*So hi, brāhmaṇa, bhagavā anuppannassa maggassa uppādetā, asañjātassa maggassa sañjanetā, anakkhātassa maggassa akkhātā, maggaññū, maggavidū, maggakovido;**For the Blessed One gave rise to the unarisen path, gave birth to the unborn path, explained the unexplained path. He was the knower of the path, the discoverer of the path, the expert on the path.*";
P_HTM[1255]="*maggānugā ca pana etarahi sāvakā viharanti pacchā samannāgatā”ti.**And now the disciples live following the path; they acquire it later.”*";
P_HTM[1256]="*Ayañca hidaṃ āyasmato ānandassa gopakamoggallānena brāhmaṇena saddhiṃ antarākathā vippakatā ahosi.**But this conversation between Ānanda and Moggallāna the Guardian was left unfinished.*";
P_HTM[1257]="*Atha kho vassakāro brāhmaṇo magadhamahāmatto rājagahe kammante anusaññāyamāno yena gopakamoggallānassa brāhmaṇassa kammanto, yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā ānandena saddhiṃ sammodi.**For just then the brahmin Vassakāra, a chief minister of Magadha, while supervising the work at Rājagaha, approached Ānanda at Moggallāna’s place of work and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[1258]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho vassakāro brāhmaṇo magadhamahāmatto āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1259]="*“kāya nuttha, bho ānanda, etarahi kathāya sannisinnā, kā ca pana vo antarākathā vippakatā”ti?**“Master Ānanda, what were you sitting talking about just now? What conversation was unfinished?”*";
P_HTM[1260]="*“Idha maṃ, brāhmaṇa, gopakamoggallāno brāhmaṇo evamāha:**So Ānanda told him of the conversation that they were having when Vassakāra arrived. Vassakāra said:*";
P_HTM[1261]="*‘atthi nu kho, bho ānanda, ekabhikkhupi tehi dhammehi sabbenasabbaṃ sabbathāsabbaṃ samannāgato yehi dhammehi samannāgato so bhavaṃ gotamo ahosi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1262]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, gopakamoggallānaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ etadavocaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[1263]="*‘natthi kho, brāhmaṇa, ekabhikkhupi tehi dhammehi sabbenasabbaṃ sabbathāsabbaṃ samannāgato yehi dhammehi samannāgato so bhagavā ahosi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho.* **";
P_HTM[1264]="*So hi, brāhmaṇa, bhagavā anuppannassa maggassa uppādetā, asañjātassa maggassa sañjanetā, anakkhātassa maggassa akkhātā, maggaññū, maggavidū, maggakovido;* **";
P_HTM[1265]="*maggānugā ca pana etarahi sāvakā viharanti pacchā samannāgatā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1266]="*Ayaṃ kho no, brāhmaṇa, gopakamoggallānena brāhmaṇena saddhiṃ antarākathā vippakatā.* **";
P_HTM[1267]="*Atha tvaṃ anuppatto”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1268]="*“Atthi nu kho, bho ānanda, ekabhikkhupi tena bhotā gotamena ṭhapito:**“Master Ānanda, is there even a single mendicant who was appointed by Master Gotama, saying:*";
P_HTM[1269]="*‘ayaṃ vo mamaccayena paṭisaraṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti, yaṃ tumhe etarahi paṭipādeyyāthā”ti?**‘This one will be your refuge when I have passed away,’ to whom you now turn?”*";
P_HTM[1270]="*“Natthi kho, brāhmaṇa, ekabhikkhupi tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena ṭhapito:**“No, there is not.”*";
P_HTM[1271]="*‘ayaṃ vo mamaccayena paṭisaraṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti, yaṃ mayaṃ etarahi paṭipādeyyāmā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1272]="*“Atthi pana, bho ānanda, ekabhikkhupi saṃghena sammato, sambahulehi therehi bhikkhūhi ṭhapito:**“But is there even a single mendicant who has been elected to such a position by the Saṅgha and appointed by several senior mendicants?”*";
P_HTM[1273]="*‘ayaṃ no bhagavato accayena paṭisaraṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti, yaṃ tumhe etarahi paṭipādeyyāthā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1274]="*“Natthi kho, brāhmaṇa, ekabhikkhupi saṃghena sammato, sambahulehi therehi bhikkhūhi ṭhapito:**“No, there is not.”*";
P_HTM[1275]="*‘ayaṃ no bhagavato accayena paṭisaraṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti, yaṃ mayaṃ etarahi paṭipādeyyāmā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1276]="*“Evaṃ appaṭisaraṇe ca pana, bho ānanda, ko hetu sāmaggiyā”ti?**“But since you lack a refuge, Master Ānanda, what’s the reason for your harmony?”*";
P_HTM[1277]="*“Na kho mayaṃ, brāhmaṇa, appaṭisaraṇā;**“We don’t lack a refuge, brahmin,*";
P_HTM[1278]="*sappaṭisaraṇā mayaṃ, brāhmaṇa;**we have a refuge.*";
P_HTM[1279]="*dhammappaṭisaraṇā”ti.**The teaching is our refuge.”*";
P_HTM[1280]="*“‘Atthi nu kho, bho ānanda, ekabhikkhupi tena bhotā gotamena ṭhapito—**“But Master Ānanda, when asked whether there was even a single mendicant—either appointed by the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1281]="*ayaṃ vo mamaccayena paṭisaraṇaṃ bhavissatīti, yaṃ tumhe etarahi paṭipādeyyāthā’ti—* **";
P_HTM[1282]="*iti puṭṭho samāno ‘natthi kho, brāhmaṇa, ekabhikkhupi tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena ṭhapito—* **";
P_HTM[1283]="*ayaṃ vo mamaccayena paṭisaraṇaṃ bhavissatīti, yaṃ mayaṃ etarahi paṭipādeyyāmā’ti vadesi;* **";
P_HTM[1284]="*‘atthi pana, bho ānanda, ekabhikkhupi saṅghena sammato, sambahulehi therehi bhikkhūhi ṭhapito—**or elected by the Saṅgha and appointed by several senior mendicants—*";
P_HTM[1285]="*ayaṃ no bhagavato accayena paṭisaraṇaṃ bhavissatīti, yaṃ tumhe etarahi paṭipādeyyāthā’ti—**who serves as your refuge after the Buddha passed away, to whom you now turn,*";
P_HTM[1286]="*iti puṭṭho samāno ‘natthi kho, brāhmaṇa, ekabhikkhupi saṅghena sammato, sambahulehi therehi bhikkhūhi ṭhapito—**you replied, ‘No, there is not.’*";
P_HTM[1287]="*ayaṃ no bhagavato accayena paṭisaraṇaṃ bhavissatīti, yaṃ mayaṃ etarahi paṭipādeyyāmā’ti—* **";
P_HTM[1288]="*vadesi;* **";
P_HTM[1289]="*‘evaṃ appaṭisaraṇe ca pana, bho ānanda, ko hetu sāmaggiyā’ti iti puṭṭho samāno ‘na kho mayaṃ, brāhmaṇa, appaṭisaraṇā;**But you say that the reason for your harmony is that you have*";
P_HTM[1290]="*sappaṭisaraṇā mayaṃ, brāhmaṇa;* **";
P_HTM[1291]="*dhammappaṭisaraṇā’ti vadesi.**the teaching as a refuge.*";
P_HTM[1292]="*Imassa pana, bho ānanda, bhāsitassa kathaṃ attho daṭṭhabbo”ti?**How should I see the meaning of this statement?”*";
P_HTM[1293]="*“Atthi kho, brāhmaṇa, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena bhikkhūnaṃ sikkhāpadaṃ paññattaṃ, pātimokkhaṃ uddiṭṭhaṃ.**“The Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha laid down training rules and recited the monastic code for the mendicants.*";
P_HTM[1294]="*Te mayaṃ tadahuposathe yāvatikā ekaṃ gāmakhettaṃ upanissāya viharāma te sabbe ekajjhaṃ sannipatāma;**On the day of the sabbath all of us who live in dependence on one village district gather together as one.*";
P_HTM[1295]="*sannipatitvā yassa taṃ pavattati taṃ ajjhesāma.**We invite one who has freshly rehearsed the code to recite it.*";
P_HTM[1296]="*Tasmiñce bhaññamāne hoti bhikkhussa āpatti hoti vītikkamo taṃ mayaṃ yathādhammaṃ yathānusiṭṭhaṃ kāremāti.**If anyone remembers an offense or transgression while they’re reciting, we make them act in line with the teachings and in line with the instructions.*";
P_HTM[1297]="*Na kira no bhavanto kārenti;**It’s not the venerables that make us act,*";
P_HTM[1298]="*dhammo no kāreti”.**it’s the teaching that makes us act.”*";
P_HTM[1299]="*“Atthi nu kho, bho ānanda, ekabhikkhupi yaṃ tumhe etarahi sakkarotha garuṃ karotha mānetha pūjetha; sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya viharathā”ti?**“Master Ānanda, is there even a single mendicant who you honor, respect, revere, venerate, and rely on?”*";
P_HTM[1300]="*“Natthi kho, brāhmaṇa, ekabhikkhupi yaṃ mayaṃ etarahi sakkaroma garuṃ karoma mānema pūjema; sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya viharāmā”ti.**“There is, brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[1301]="*“‘Atthi nu kho, bho ānanda, ekabhikkhupi tena bhotā gotamena ṭhapito—**“But Master Ānanda, when asked whether there was even a single mendicant—either appointed by the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1302]="*ayaṃ vo mamaccayena paṭisaraṇaṃ bhavissatīti yaṃ tumhe etarahi paṭipādeyyāthā’ti—* **";
P_HTM[1303]="*iti puṭṭho samāno ‘natthi kho, brāhmaṇa, ekabhikkhupi tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena ṭhapito—* **";
P_HTM[1304]="*ayaṃ vo mamaccayena paṭisaraṇaṃ bhavissatīti yaṃ mayaṃ etarahi paṭipādeyyāmā’ti vadesi;* **";
P_HTM[1305]="*‘atthi pana, bho ānanda, ekabhikkhupi saṅghena sammato, sambahulehi therehi bhikkhūhi ṭhapito—**or elected by the Saṅgha and appointed by several senior mendicants—*";
P_HTM[1306]="*ayaṃ no bhagavato accayena paṭisaraṇaṃ bhavissatīti yaṃ tumhe etarahi paṭipādeyyāthā’ti—**who serves as your refuge after the Buddha passed away, to whom you now turn,*";
P_HTM[1307]="*iti puṭṭho samāno ‘natthi kho, brāhmaṇa, ekabhikkhupi saṅghena sammato, sambahulehi therehi bhikkhūhi ṭhapito—**you replied, ‘No, there is not.’*";
P_HTM[1308]="*ayaṃ no bhagavato accayena paṭisaraṇaṃ bhavissatīti yaṃ mayaṃ etarahi paṭipādeyyāmā’ti vadesi;* **";
P_HTM[1309]="*‘atthi nu kho, bho ānanda, ekabhikkhupi yaṃ tumhe etarahi sakkarotha garuṃ karotha mānetha pūjetha; sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya viharathā’ti—**But when asked whether there is even a single mendicant who you honor, respect, revere, venerate, and rely on,*";
P_HTM[1310]="*iti puṭṭho samāno ‘natthi kho, brāhmaṇa, ekabhikkhupi yaṃ mayaṃ etarahi sakkaroma garuṃ karoma mānema pūjema; sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya viharāmā’ti vadesi.**you replied, ‘There is.’*";
P_HTM[1311]="*Imassa pana, bho ānanda, bhāsitassa kathaṃ attho daṭṭhabbo”ti?**How should I see the meaning of this statement?”*";
P_HTM[1312]="*“Atthi kho, brāhmaṇa, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena dasa pasādanīyā dhammā akkhātā.**“There are ten inspiring things explained by the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1313]="*Yasmiṃ no ime dhammā saṃvijjanti taṃ mayaṃ etarahi sakkaroma garuṃ karoma mānema pūjema; sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya viharāma.**We honor anyone in whom these things are found.*";
P_HTM[1314]="*Katame dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1315]="*Idha, brāhmaṇa, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno, aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu. (1)**It’s when a mendicant is ethical, restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[1316]="*Bahussuto hoti sutadharo sutasannicayo.**They’re very learned, remembering and keeping what they’ve learned.*";
P_HTM[1317]="*Ye te dhammā ādikalyāṇā, majjhekalyāṇā, pariyosānakalyāṇā, sātthaṃ, sabyañjanaṃ, kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ abhivadanti tathārūpāssa dhammā bahussutā honti dhātā vacasā paricitā manasānupekkhitā diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā. (2)**These teachings are good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased, describing a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure. They are very learned in such teachings, remembering them, reinforcing them by recitation, mentally scrutinizing them, and comprehending them theoretically.*";
P_HTM[1318]="*Santuṭṭho hoti cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārehi. (3)**They’re content with robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick.*";
P_HTM[1319]="*Catunnaṃ jhānānaṃ ābhicetasikānaṃ diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārānaṃ nikāmalābhī hoti akicchalābhī akasiralābhī. (4)**They get the four absorptions—blissful meditations in the present life that belong to the higher mind—when they want, without trouble or difficulty.*";
P_HTM[1320]="*Anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti, bahudhāpi hutvā eko hoti; āvibhāvaṃ tirobhāvaṃ; tirokuṭṭaṃ tiropākāraṃ tiropabbataṃ asajjamāno gacchati, seyyathāpi ākāse; pathaviyāpi ummujjanimujjaṃ karoti, seyyathāpi udake; udakepi abhijjamāne gacchati, seyyathāpi pathaviyaṃ; ākāsepi pallaṅkena kamati, seyyathāpi pakkhī sakuṇo; imepi candimasūriye evaṃmahiddhike evaṃmahānubhāve pāṇinā parimasati parimajjati, yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti. (5)**They wield the many kinds of psychic power: multiplying themselves and becoming one again; appearing and disappearing; going unimpeded through a wall, a rampart, or a mountain as if through space; diving in and out of the earth as if it were water; walking on water as if it were earth; flying cross-legged through the sky like a bird; touching and stroking with the hand the sun and moon, so mighty and powerful. They control the body as far as the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[1321]="*Dibbāya sotadhātuyā visuddhāya atikkantamānusikāya ubho sadde suṇāti—dibbe ca mānuse ca, ye dūre santike ca. (6)**With clairaudience that is purified and superhuman, they hear both kinds of sounds, human and divine, whether near or far.*";
P_HTM[1322]="*Parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cetasā ceto paricca pajānāti. Sarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sarāgaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vītarāgaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, sadosaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sadosaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītadosaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vītadosaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, samohaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘samohaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītamohaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vītamohaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, saṅkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘saṅkhittaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vikkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vikkhittaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, mahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ ‘mahaggataṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, amahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ ‘amahaggataṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, sauttaraṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sauttaraṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, anuttaraṃ vā cittaṃ ‘anuttaraṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, samāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘samāhitaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, asamāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘asamāhitaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vimuttaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘avimuttaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti. (7)**They understand the minds of other beings and individuals, having comprehended them with their own mind. They understand mind with greed as ‘mind with greed’, and mind without greed as ‘mind without greed’. They understand mind with hate … mind without hate … mind with delusion … mind without delusion … constricted mind … scattered mind … expansive mind … unexpansive mind … mind that is not supreme … mind that is supreme … mind immersed in samādhi … mind not immersed in samādhi … freed mind … They understand unfreed mind as ‘unfreed mind’.*";
P_HTM[1323]="*Anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo dasapi jātiyo vīsampi jātiyo tiṃsampi jātiyo cattārīsampi jātiyo paññāsampi jātiyo jātisatampi jātisahassampi jātisatasahassampi anekepi saṃvaṭṭakappe anekepi vivaṭṭakappe anekepi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭakappe: ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati. (8)**They recollect many kinds of past lives. That is: one, two, three, four, five, ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand rebirths; many eons of the world contracting, many eons of the world expanding, many eons of the world contracting and expanding. They remember: ‘There, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn somewhere else. There, too, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn here.’ And so they recollect their many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[1324]="*Dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe, sugate duggate yathākammūpage satte pajānāti. (9)**With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds.*";
P_HTM[1325]="*Āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati. (10)**They realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[1326]="*Ime kho, brāhmaṇa, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena dasa pasādanīyā dhammā akkhātā.**These are the ten inspiring things explained by the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1327]="*Yasmiṃ no ime dhammā saṃvijjanti taṃ mayaṃ etarahi sakkaroma garuṃ karoma mānema pūjema; sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya viharāmā”ti.**We honor anyone in whom these things are found, and rely on them.”*";
P_HTM[1328]="*Evaṃ vutte, vassakāro brāhmaṇo magadhamahāmatto upanandaṃ senāpatiṃ āmantesi:**When he had spoken, Vassakāra addressed General Upananda,*";
P_HTM[1329]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññati bhavaṃ senāpati yadime bhonto sakkātabbaṃ sakkaronti, garuṃ kātabbaṃ garuṃ karonti,**“What do you think, general?*";
P_HTM[1330]="*mānetabbaṃ mānenti, pūjetabbaṃ pūjenti”?**Do these venerables honor, respect, revere, and venerate those who are worthy?”*";
P_HTM[1331]="*“Tagghime bhonto sakkātabbaṃ sakkaronti, garuṃ kātabbaṃ garuṃ karonti, mānetabbaṃ mānenti, pūjetabbaṃ pūjenti.**“Indeed they do.*";
P_HTM[1332]="*Imañca hi te bhonto na sakkareyyuṃ na garuṃ kareyyuṃ na māneyyuṃ na pūjeyyuṃ;**For if these venerables were not to honor, respect, revere, and venerate such a person,*";
P_HTM[1333]="*atha kiñcarahi te bhonto sakkareyyuṃ garuṃ kareyyuṃ māneyyuṃ pūjeyyuṃ, sakkatvā garuṃ katvā mānetvā pūjetvā upanissāya vihareyyun”ti?**then who exactly would they honor?”*";
P_HTM[1334]="*Atha kho vassakāro brāhmaṇo magadhamahāmatto āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**Then Vassakāra said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1335]="*“kahaṃ pana bhavaṃ ānando etarahi viharatī”ti?**“Where are you staying at present?”*";
P_HTM[1336]="*“Veḷuvane khohaṃ, brāhmaṇa, etarahi viharāmī”ti.**“In the Bamboo Grove, brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[1337]="*“Kacci pana, bho ānanda, veḷuvanaṃ ramaṇīyañceva appasaddañca appanigghosañca vijanavātaṃ manussarāhasseyyakaṃ paṭisallānasāruppan”ti?**“I hope the Bamboo Grove is delightful, quiet and still, far from the madding crowd, remote from human settlements, and fit for retreat?”*";
P_HTM[1338]="*“Taggha, brāhmaṇa, veḷuvanaṃ ramaṇīyañceva appasaddañca appanigghosañca vijanavātaṃ manussarāhasseyyakaṃ paṭisallānasāruppaṃ, yathā taṃ tumhādisehi rakkhakehi gopakehī”ti.**“Indeed it is, brahmin. And it is like that owing to such protectors and guardians as yourself.”*";
P_HTM[1339]="*“Taggha, bho ānanda, veḷuvanaṃ ramaṇīyañceva appasaddañca appanigghosañca vijanavātaṃ manussarāhasseyyakaṃ paṭisallānasāruppaṃ, yathā taṃ bhavantehi jhāyīhi jhānasīlīhi.**“Surely, Master Ānanda, it is owing to the venerables who meditate, making a habit of meditating.*";
P_HTM[1340]="*Jhāyino ceva bhavanto jhānasīlino ca.**For the venerables do in fact meditate and make a habit of meditating.*";
P_HTM[1341]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, bho ānanda, samayaṃ so bhavaṃ gotamo vesāliyaṃ viharati mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**This one time, Master Ānanda, Master Gotama was staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[1342]="*Atha khvāhaṃ, bho ānanda, yena mahāvanaṃ kūṭāgārasālā yena so bhavaṃ gotamo tenupasaṅkamiṃ.**So I went there to see him.*";
P_HTM[1343]="*Tatra ca pana so bhavaṃ gotamo anekapariyāyena jhānakathaṃ kathesi.**And there he spoke about meditation in many ways.*";
P_HTM[1344]="*Jhāyī ceva so bhavaṃ gotamo ahosi jhānasīlī ca.**He meditated, and made a habit of meditating.*";
P_HTM[1345]="*Sabbañca pana so bhavaṃ gotamo jhānaṃ vaṇṇesī”ti.**And he praised all kinds of meditation.”*";
P_HTM[1346]="*“Na ca kho, brāhmaṇa, so bhagavā sabbaṃ jhānaṃ vaṇṇesi, napi so bhagavā sabbaṃ jhānaṃ na vaṇṇesīti.**“No, brahmin, the Buddha did not praise all kinds of meditation, nor did he dispraise all kinds of meditation.*";
P_HTM[1347]="*Kathaṃ rūpañca, brāhmaṇa, so bhagavā jhānaṃ na vaṇṇesi?**And what kind of meditation did he not praise?*";
P_HTM[1348]="*Idha, brāhmaṇa, ekacco kāmarāgapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā viharati kāmarāgaparetena, uppannassa ca kāmarāgassa nissaraṇaṃ yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;**It’s when someone’s heart is overcome and mired in sensual desire, and they don’t truly understand the escape from sensual desire that has arisen.*";
P_HTM[1349]="*so kāmarāgaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā jhāyati pajjhāyati nijjhāyati apajjhāyati.**Harboring sensual desire within they meditate and concentrate and contemplate and ruminate.*";
P_HTM[1350]="*Byāpādapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā viharati byāpādaparetena, uppannassa ca byāpādassa nissaraṇaṃ yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;**Their heart is overcome and mired in ill will …*";
P_HTM[1351]="*so byāpādaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā jhāyati pajjhāyati nijjhāyati apajjhāyati.* **";
P_HTM[1352]="*Thinamiddhapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā viharati thinamiddhaparetena, uppannassa ca thinamiddhassa nissaraṇaṃ yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;**dullness and drowsiness …*";
P_HTM[1353]="*so thinamiddhaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā jhāyati pajjhāyati nijjhāyati apajjhāyati.* **";
P_HTM[1354]="*Uddhaccakukkuccapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā viharati uddhaccakukkuccaparetena, uppannassa ca uddhaccakukkuccassa nissaraṇaṃ yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;**restlessness and remorse …*";
P_HTM[1355]="*so uddhaccakukkuccaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā jhāyati pajjhāyati nijjhāyati apajjhāyati.* **";
P_HTM[1356]="*Vicikicchāpariyuṭṭhitena cetasā viharati vicikicchāparetena, uppannāya ca vicikicchāya nissaraṇaṃ yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti;**doubt, and they don’t truly know and see the escape from doubt that has arisen.*";
P_HTM[1357]="*so vicikicchaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā jhāyati pajjhāyati nijjhāyati apajjhāyati.**Harboring doubt within they meditate and concentrate and contemplate and ruminate.*";
P_HTM[1358]="*Evarūpaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, so bhagavā jhānaṃ na vaṇṇesi.**The Buddha didn’t praise this kind of meditation.*";
P_HTM[1359]="*Kathaṃ rūpañca, brāhmaṇa, so bhagavā jhānaṃ vaṇṇesi?**And what kind of meditation did he praise?*";
P_HTM[1360]="*Idha, brāhmaṇa, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[1361]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[1362]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**And with the fading away of rapture, they enter and remain in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[1363]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[1364]="*Evarūpaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, so bhagavā jhānaṃ vaṇṇesī”ti.**The Buddha praised this kind of meditation.”*";
P_HTM[1365]="*“Gārayhaṃ kira, bho ānanda, so bhavaṃ gotamo jhānaṃ garahi, pāsaṃsaṃ pasaṃsi.**“Well, Master Ānanda, it seems that Master Gotama criticized the kind of meditation that deserves criticism and praised that deserving of praise.*";
P_HTM[1366]="*Handa ca dāni mayaṃ, bho ānanda, gacchāma;**Well, now, Master Ānanda, I must go.*";
P_HTM[1367]="*bahukiccā mayaṃ bahukaraṇīyā”ti.**I have many duties, and much to do.”*";
P_HTM[1368]="*“Yassadāni tvaṃ, brāhmaṇa, kālaṃ maññasī”ti.**“Please, brahmin, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1369]="*Atha kho vassakāro brāhmaṇo magadhamahāmatto āyasmato ānandassa bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmi.**Then Vassakāra the brahmin, having approved and agreed with what Venerable Ānanda said, got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[1370]="*Atha kho gopakamoggallāno brāhmaṇo acirapakkante vassakāre brāhmaṇe magadhamahāmatte āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**Soon after he had left, Moggallāna the Guardian said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1371]="*“yaṃ no mayaṃ bhavantaṃ ānandaṃ apucchimhā taṃ no bhavaṃ ānando na byākāsī”ti.**“Master Ānanda, you still haven’t answered my question.”*";
P_HTM[1372]="*“Nanu te, brāhmaṇa, avocumhā:**“But brahmin, didn’t I say:*";
P_HTM[1373]="*‘natthi kho, brāhmaṇa, ekabhikkhupi tehi dhammehi sabbenasabbaṃ sabbathāsabbaṃ samannāgato yehi dhammehi samannāgato so bhagavā ahosi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho.**‘There is no single mendicant who has all the same qualities in each and every way as possessed by Master Gotama, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1374]="*So hi, brāhmaṇa, bhagavā anuppannassa maggassa uppādetā, asañjātassa maggassa sañjanetā, anakkhātassa maggassa akkhātā, maggaññū, maggavidū, maggakovido.**For the Blessed One gave rise to the unarisen path, gave birth to the unborn path, explained the unexplained path. He was the knower of the path, the discoverer of the path, the expert on the path.*";
P_HTM[1375]="*Maggānugā ca pana etarahi sāvakā viharanti pacchā samannāgatā’”ti.**And now the disciples live following the path; they acquire it later.’”*";
P_HTM[1376]="*Gopakamoggallānasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1377]="*109. Mahāpuṇṇamasutta**The Longer Discourse on the Full-Moon Night*";
P_HTM[1378]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1379]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati pubbārāme migāramātupāsāde.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in the Eastern Monastery, the stilt longhouse of Migāra’s mother.*";
P_HTM[1380]="*Tena kho pana samayena bhagavā tadahuposathe pannarase puṇṇāya puṇṇamāya rattiyā bhikkhusaṅghaparivuto abbhokāse nisinno hoti.**Now, at that time it was the sabbath—the full moon on the fifteenth day—and the Buddha was sitting in the open surrounded by the Saṅgha of monks.*";
P_HTM[1381]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu uṭṭhāyāsanā ekaṃsaṃ cīvaraṃ katvā yena bhagavā tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then one of the mendicants got up from their seat, arranged their robe over one shoulder, raised their joined palms toward the Buddha, and said,*";
P_HTM[1382]="*“Puccheyyāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ kiñcideva desaṃ, sace me bhagavā okāsaṃ karoti pañhassa veyyākaraṇāyā”ti.**“I’d like to ask the Buddha about a certain point, if you’d take the time to answer.”*";
P_HTM[1383]="*“Tena hi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, sake āsane nisīditvā puccha yadākaṅkhasī”ti.**“Well then, mendicant, take your own seat and ask what you wish.”*";
P_HTM[1384]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu sake āsane nisīditvā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**That mendicant took his seat and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1385]="*“ime nu kho, bhante, pañcupādānakkhandhā, seyyathidaṃ—**“Sir, are these the five grasping aggregates:*";
P_HTM[1386]="*rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho”ti?**form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[1387]="*“Ime kho, bhikkhu, pañcupādānakkhandhā, seyyathidaṃ—**“Yes, they are,” replied the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1388]="*rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1389]="*“Sādhu, bhante”ti kho so bhikkhu bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā bhagavantaṃ uttariṃ pañhaṃ pucchi:**Saying “Good, sir”, that mendicant approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. Then he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[1390]="*“ime pana, bhante, pañcupādānakkhandhā kiṃmūlakā”ti?**“But sir, what is the root of these five grasping aggregates?”*";
P_HTM[1391]="*“Ime kho, bhikkhu, pañcupādānakkhandhā chandamūlakā”ti.**“These five grasping aggregates are rooted in desire.”*";
P_HTM[1392]="*“Taṃyeva nu kho, bhante, upādānaṃ te pañcupādānakkhandhā, udāhu aññatra pañcahupādānakkhandhehi upādānan”ti?**“But sir, is that grasping the exact same thing as the five grasping aggregates? Or is grasping one thing and the five grasping aggregates another?”*";
P_HTM[1393]="*“Na kho, bhikkhu, taṃyeva upādānaṃ te pañcupādānakkhandhā, nāpi aññatra pañcahupādānakkhandhehi upādānaṃ.**“Neither.*";
P_HTM[1394]="*Yo kho, bhikkhu, pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu chandarāgo taṃ tattha upādānan”ti.**Rather, the desire and greed for them is the grasping there.”*";
P_HTM[1395]="*“Siyā pana, bhante, pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu chandarāgavemattatā”ti?**“But sir, can there be different kinds of desire and greed for the five grasping aggregates?”*";
P_HTM[1396]="*“Siyā, bhikkhū”ti bhagavā avoca**“There can,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1397]="*“idha, bhikkhu, ekaccassa evaṃ hoti:**“It’s when someone thinks:*";
P_HTM[1398]="*‘evaṃrūpo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃvedano siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃsañño siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃsaṅkhāro siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, evaṃviññāṇo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānan’ti.**‘In the future, may I be of such form, such feeling, such perception, such choices, and such consciousness!’*";
P_HTM[1399]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, siyā pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu chandarāgavemattatā”ti.**That’s how there be different kinds of desire and greed for the five grasping aggregates.”*";
P_HTM[1400]="*“Kittāvatā pana, bhante, khandhānaṃ khandhādhivacanaṃ hotī”ti?**“Sir, what is the scope of the term ‘aggregates’ as applied to the aggregates?”*";
P_HTM[1401]="*“Yaṃ kiñci, bhikkhu, rūpaṃ—atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā, oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā, hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā, yaṃ dūre santike vā—ayaṃ rūpakkhandho.**“Any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: this is called the aggregate of form.*";
P_HTM[1402]="*Yā kāci vedanā—atītānāgatapaccuppannā ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā, oḷārikā vā sukhumā vā, hīnā vā paṇītā vā, yā dūre santike vā—ayaṃ vedanākkhandho.**Any kind of feeling at all …*";
P_HTM[1403]="*Yā kāci saññā—atītānāgatapaccuppannā … pe … yā dūre santike vā—ayaṃ saññākkhandho.**Any kind of perception at all …*";
P_HTM[1404]="*Ye keci saṅkhārā—atītānāgatapaccuppannā ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā, oḷārikā vā sukhumā vā, hīnā vā paṇītā vā, ye dūre santike vā—ayaṃ saṅkhārakkhandho.**Any kind of choices at all …*";
P_HTM[1405]="*Yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ—atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā, oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā, hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā, yaṃ dūre santike vā—ayaṃ viññāṇakkhandho.**Any kind of consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: this is called the aggregate of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1406]="*Ettāvatā kho, bhikkhu, khandhānaṃ khandhādhivacanaṃ hotī”ti.**That’s the scope of the term ‘aggregates’ as applied to the aggregates.”*";
P_HTM[1407]="*“Ko nu kho, bhante, hetu ko paccayo rūpakkhandhassa paññāpanāya?**“What is the cause, sir, what is the reason why the aggregate of form is found?*";
P_HTM[1408]="*Ko hetu ko paccayo vedanākkhandhassa paññāpanāya?**What is the cause, what is the reason why the aggregate of feeling …*";
P_HTM[1409]="*Ko hetu ko paccayo saññākkhandhassa paññāpanāya?**perception …*";
P_HTM[1410]="*Ko hetu ko paccayo saṅkhārakkhandhassa paññāpanāya?**choices …*";
P_HTM[1411]="*Ko hetu ko paccayo viññāṇakkhandhassa paññāpanāyā”ti?**consciousness is found?”*";
P_HTM[1412]="*“Cattāro kho, bhikkhu, mahābhūtā hetu, cattāro mahābhūtā paccayo rūpakkhandhassa paññāpanāya.**“The four primary elements are the reason why the aggregate of form is found.*";
P_HTM[1413]="*Phasso hetu, phasso paccayo vedanākkhandhassa paññāpanāya.**Contact is the reason why the aggregates of feeling …*";
P_HTM[1414]="*Phasso hetu, phasso paccayo saññākkhandhassa paññāpanāya.**perception …*";
P_HTM[1415]="*Phasso hetu, phasso paccayo saṅkhārakkhandhassa paññāpanāya.**and choices are found.*";
P_HTM[1416]="*Nāmarūpaṃ kho, bhikkhu, hetu, nāmarūpaṃ paccayo viññāṇakkhandhassa paññāpanāyā”ti.**Name and form are the reasons why the aggregate of consciousness is found.”*";
P_HTM[1417]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, sakkāyadiṭṭhi hotī”ti?**“But sir, how does identity view come about?”*";
P_HTM[1418]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto**“It’s when an uneducated ordinary person has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[1419]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ attani vā rūpaṃ rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ;**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[1420]="*vedanaṃ attato samanupassati vedanāvantaṃ vā attānaṃ attani vā vedanaṃ vedanāya vā attānaṃ;**They regard feeling as self, self as having feeling, feeling in self, or self in feeling.*";
P_HTM[1421]="*saññaṃ attato samanupassati saññāvantaṃ vā attānaṃ attani vā saññaṃ saññāya vā attānaṃ;**They regard perception as self, self as having perception, perception in self, or self in perception.*";
P_HTM[1422]="*saṅkhāre attato samanupassati saṅkhāravantaṃ vā attānaṃ attani vā saṅkhāre saṅkhāresu vā attānaṃ;**They regard choices as self, self as having choices, choices in self, or self in choices.*";
P_HTM[1423]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ attani vā viññāṇaṃ viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1424]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, sakkāyadiṭṭhi hotī”ti.**That’s how identity view comes about.”*";
P_HTM[1425]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, sakkāyadiṭṭhi na hotī”ti?**“But sir, how does identity view not come about?”*";
P_HTM[1426]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, sutavā ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī ariyadhammassa kovido ariyadhamme suvinīto sappurisānaṃ dassāvī sappurisadhammassa kovido sappurisadhamme suvinīto**“It’s when an educated noble disciple has seen the noble ones, and is skilled and trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve seen good persons, and are skilled and trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[1427]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati na rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ na attani vā rūpaṃ na rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ;**They don’t regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[1428]="*na vedanaṃ attato samanupassati na vedanāvantaṃ vā attānaṃ na attani vā vedanaṃ na vedanāya vā attānaṃ;**They don’t regard feeling as self, self as having feeling, feeling in self, or self in feeling.*";
P_HTM[1429]="*na saññaṃ attato samanupassati na saññāvantaṃ vā attānaṃ na attani vā saññaṃ na saññāya vā attānaṃ;**They don’t regard perception as self, self as having perception, perception in self, or self in perception.*";
P_HTM[1430]="*na saṅkhāre attato samanupassati na saṅkhāravantaṃ vā attānaṃ na attani vā saṅkhāre na saṅkhāresu vā attānaṃ;**They don’t regard choices as self, self as having choices, choices in self, or self in choices.*";
P_HTM[1431]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati na viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ na attani vā viññāṇaṃ na viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1432]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, sakkāyadiṭṭhi na hotī”ti.**That’s how identity view does not come about.”*";
P_HTM[1433]="*“Ko nu kho, bhante, rūpe assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇaṃ?**“Sir, what’s the gratification, the drawback, and the escape when it comes to form,*";
P_HTM[1434]="*Ko vedanāya assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇaṃ?**feeling,*";
P_HTM[1435]="*Ko saññāya assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇaṃ?**perception,*";
P_HTM[1436]="*Ko saṅkhāresu assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇaṃ?**choices,*";
P_HTM[1437]="*Ko viññāṇe assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇan”ti?**and consciousness?”*";
P_HTM[1438]="*“Yaṃ kho, bhikkhu, rūpaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ, ayaṃ rūpe assādo.**“The pleasure and happiness that arise from form: this is its gratification.*";
P_HTM[1439]="*Yaṃ rūpaṃ aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, ayaṃ rūpe ādīnavo.**That form is impermanent, suffering, and perishable: this is its drawback.*";
P_HTM[1440]="*Yo rūpe chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ, idaṃ rūpe nissaraṇaṃ.**Removing and giving up desire and greed for form: this is its escape.*";
P_HTM[1441]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhu, vedanaṃ paṭicca …**The pleasure and happiness that arise from feeling …*";
P_HTM[1442]="*saññaṃ paṭicca …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1443]="*saṅkhāre paṭicca …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1444]="*viññāṇaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ, ayaṃ viññāṇe assādo.**consciousness: this is its gratification.*";
P_HTM[1445]="*Yaṃ viññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, ayaṃ viññāṇe ādīnavo.**That consciousness is impermanent, suffering, and perishable: this is its drawback.*";
P_HTM[1446]="*Yo viññāṇe chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ, idaṃ viññāṇe nissaraṇan”ti.**Removing and giving up desire and greed for consciousness: this is its escape.”*";
P_HTM[1447]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, jānato kathaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānānusayā na hontī”ti?**“Sir, how does one know and see so that there’s no ego, possessiveness, or underlying tendency to conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli?”*";
P_HTM[1448]="*“Yaṃ kiñci, bhikkhu, rūpaṃ—atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā—sabbaṃ rūpaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti—evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passati.**“One truly sees any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all form—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1449]="*Yā kāci vedanā …**One truly sees any kind of feeling …*";
P_HTM[1450]="*yā kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1451]="*ye keci saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1452]="*yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ—atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā—sabbaṃ viññāṇaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti—evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passati.**consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near, all consciousness—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1453]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, jānato evaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānānusayā na hontī”ti.**That’s how to know and see so that there’s no ego, possessiveness, or underlying tendency to conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli.”*";
P_HTM[1454]="*Atha kho aññatarassa bhikkhuno evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Now at that time one of the mendicants had the thought,*";
P_HTM[1455]="*“iti kira, bho, rūpaṃ anattā, vedanā anattā, saññā anattā, saṅkhārā anattā, viññāṇaṃ anattā;**“So it seems, good sir, that form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness are not-self.*";
P_HTM[1456]="*anattakatāni kammāni kamattānaṃ phusissantī”ti?**Then what self will the deeds done by not-self affect?”*";
P_HTM[1457]="*Atha kho bhagavā tassa bhikkhuno cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya bhikkhū āmantesi:**But the Buddha, knowing what that monk was thinking, addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1458]="*“ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, vijjati yaṃ idhekacco moghapuriso avidvā avijjāgato taṇhādhipateyyena cetasā satthu sāsanaṃ atidhāvitabbaṃ maññeyya:**“It’s possible that some foolish person here—unknowing and ignorant, their mind dominated by craving—thinks they can overstep the teacher’s instructions. They think:*";
P_HTM[1459]="*‘iti kira, bho, rūpaṃ anattā, vedanā anattā, saññā anattā, saṅkhārā anattā, viññāṇaṃ anattā;**‘So it seems, good sir, that form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness are not-self.*";
P_HTM[1460]="*anattakatāni kammāni kamattānaṃ phusissantī’ti.**Then what self will the deeds done by not-self affect?’*";
P_HTM[1461]="*Paṭivinītā kho me tumhe, bhikkhave, tatra tatra dhammesu.**Now, mendicants, you have been educated by me in questioning with regard to all these things in all such cases.*";
P_HTM[1462]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[1463]="*rūpaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is form permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1464]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1465]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1466]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1467]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1468]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1469]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1470]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**“What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[1471]="*vedanā …**Is feeling …*";
P_HTM[1472]="*saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1473]="*saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1474]="*viññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**consciousness permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1475]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1476]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1477]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1478]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1479]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1480]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1481]="*“Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, yaṃ kiñci rūpaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā sabbaṃ rūpaṃ: ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**“So you should truly see any kind of form at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near: all form—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1482]="*Yā kāci vedanā …**You should truly see any kind of feeling …*";
P_HTM[1483]="*yā kāci saññā …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1484]="*ye keci saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1485]="*yaṃ kiñci viññāṇaṃ atītānāgatapaccuppannaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā oḷārikaṃ vā sukhumaṃ vā hīnaṃ vā paṇītaṃ vā yaṃ dūre santike vā sabbaṃ viññāṇaṃ: ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**consciousness at all—past, future, or present; internal or external; coarse or fine; inferior or superior; far or near, all consciousness—with right understanding: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1486]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpasmimpi nibbindati, vedanāyapi nibbindati, saññāyapi nibbindati, saṅkhāresupi nibbindati, viññāṇasmimpi nibbindati;**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1487]="*nibbindaṃ virajjati, virāgā vimuccati. Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[1488]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1489]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1490]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1491]="*Imasmiñca pana veyyākaraṇasmiṃ bhaññamāne saṭṭhimattānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ anupādāya āsavehi cittāni vimucciṃsūti.**And while this discourse was being spoken, the minds of sixty mendicants were freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[1492]="*Mahāpuṇṇamasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1493]="*110. Cūḷapuṇṇamasutta**The Shorter Discourse on the Full-Moon Night*";
P_HTM[1494]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1495]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati pubbārāme migāramātupāsāde.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in the Eastern Monastery, the stilt longhouse of Migāra’s mother.*";
P_HTM[1496]="*Tena kho pana samayena bhagavā tadahuposathe pannarase puṇṇāya puṇṇamāya rattiyā bhikkhusaṅghaparivuto abbhokāse nisinno hoti.**Now, at that time it was the sabbath—the full moon on the fifteenth day—and the Buddha was sitting in the open surrounded by the Saṅgha of monks.*";
P_HTM[1497]="*Atha kho bhagavā tuṇhībhūtaṃ tuṇhībhūtaṃ bhikkhusaṅghaṃ anuviloketvā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha looked around the Saṅgha of monks, who were so very silent. He addressed them,*";
P_HTM[1498]="*“jāneyya nu kho, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisaṃ:**“Mendicants, could a bad person know of a bad person:*";
P_HTM[1499]="*‘asappuriso ayaṃ bhavan’”ti?**‘This fellow is a bad person’?”*";
P_HTM[1500]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1501]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhave;**“Good, mendicants!*";
P_HTM[1502]="*aṭṭhānametaṃ, bhikkhave, anavakāso yaṃ asappuriso asappurisaṃ jāneyya:**It’s impossible, it can’t happen, that a bad person could know of a bad person:*";
P_HTM[1503]="*‘asappuriso ayaṃ bhavan’ti.**‘This fellow is a bad person.’*";
P_HTM[1504]="*Jāneyya pana, bhikkhave, asappuriso sappurisaṃ:**But could a bad person know of a good person:*";
P_HTM[1505]="*‘sappuriso ayaṃ bhavan’”ti?**‘This fellow is a good person’?”*";
P_HTM[1506]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1507]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhave;**“Good, mendicants!*";
P_HTM[1508]="*etampi kho, bhikkhave, aṭṭhānaṃ anavakāso yaṃ asappuriso sappurisaṃ jāneyya:**That too is impossible.*";
P_HTM[1509]="*‘sappuriso ayaṃ bhavan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1510]="*Asappuriso, bhikkhave, assaddhammasamannāgato hoti, asappurisabhatti hoti, asappurisacintī hoti, asappurisamantī hoti, asappurisavāco hoti, asappurisakammanto hoti, asappurisadiṭṭhi hoti; asappurisadānaṃ deti.**A bad person has bad qualities, associates with bad people, and has the intentions, counsel, speech, actions, views, and giving of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1511]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, asappuriso assaddhammasamannāgato hoti?**And how does a bad person have bad qualities?*";
P_HTM[1512]="*Idha, bhikkhave, asappuriso assaddho hoti, ahiriko hoti, anottappī hoti, appassuto hoti, kusīto hoti, muṭṭhassati hoti, duppañño hoti.**It’s when a bad person is faithless, shameless, imprudent, uneducated, lazy, unmindful, and witless.*";
P_HTM[1513]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, asappuriso assaddhammasamannāgato hoti. (1)**That’s how a bad person has bad qualities.*";
P_HTM[1514]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisabhatti hoti?**And how does a bad person associate with bad people?*";
P_HTM[1515]="*Idha, bhikkhave, asappurisassa ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā assaddhā ahirikā anottappino appassutā kusītā muṭṭhassatino duppaññā tyāssa mittā honti te sahāyā.**It’s when a bad person is a friend and companion of ascetics and brahmins who are faithless, shameless, imprudent, uneducated, lazy, unmindful, and witless.*";
P_HTM[1516]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisabhatti hoti. (2)**That’s how a bad person associates with bad people.*";
P_HTM[1517]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisacintī hoti?**And how does a bad person have the intentions of a bad person?*";
P_HTM[1518]="*Idha, bhikkhave, asappuriso attabyābādhāyapi ceteti, parabyābādhāyapi ceteti, ubhayabyābādhāyapi ceteti.**It’s when a bad person intends to hurt themselves, hurt others, and hurt both.*";
P_HTM[1519]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisacintī hoti. (3)**That’s how a bad person has the intentions of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1520]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisamantī hoti?**And how does a bad person offer the counsel of a bad person?*";
P_HTM[1521]="*Idha, bhikkhave, asappuriso attabyābādhāyapi manteti, parabyābādhāyapi manteti, ubhayabyābādhāyapi manteti.**It’s when a bad person offers counsel that hurts themselves, hurts others, and hurts both.*";
P_HTM[1522]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisamantī hoti. (4)**That’s how a bad person offers the counsel of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1523]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisavāco hoti?**And how does a bad person have the speech of a bad person?*";
P_HTM[1524]="*Idha, bhikkhave, asappuriso musāvādī hoti, pisuṇavāco hoti, pharusavāco hoti, samphappalāpī hoti.**It’s when a bad person uses speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, and nonsensical.*";
P_HTM[1525]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisavāco hoti. (5)**That’s how a bad person has the speech of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1526]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisakammanto hoti?**And how does a bad person have the action of a bad person?*";
P_HTM[1527]="*Idha, bhikkhave, asappuriso pāṇātipātī hoti, adinnādāyī hoti, kāmesumicchācārī hoti.**It’s when a bad person kills living creatures, steals, and commits sexual misconduct.*";
P_HTM[1528]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisakammanto hoti. (6)**That’s how a bad person has the actions of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1529]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisadiṭṭhi hoti?**And how does a bad person have the view of a bad person?*";
P_HTM[1530]="*Idha, bhikkhave, asappuriso evaṃdiṭṭhi hoti:**It’s when a bad person has such a view:*";
P_HTM[1531]="*‘natthi dinnaṃ, natthi yiṭṭhaṃ, natthi hutaṃ, natthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko, natthi ayaṃ loko, natthi paro loko, natthi mātā, natthi pitā, natthi sattā opapātikā, natthi loke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sammaggatā sammāpaṭipannā, ye imañca lokaṃ parañca lokaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedentī’ti.**‘There’s no meaning in giving, sacrifice, or offerings. There’s no fruit or result of good and bad deeds. There’s no afterlife. There’s no obligation to mother and father. No beings are reborn spontaneously. And there’s no ascetic or brahmin who is well attained and practiced, and who describes the afterlife after realizing it with their own insight.’*";
P_HTM[1532]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisadiṭṭhi hoti. (7)**That’s how a bad person has the view of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1533]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisadānaṃ deti?**And how does a bad person give the gifts of a bad person?*";
P_HTM[1534]="*Idha, bhikkhave, asappuriso asakkaccaṃ dānaṃ deti, asahatthā dānaṃ deti, acittīkatvā dānaṃ deti, apaviṭṭhaṃ dānaṃ deti anāgamanadiṭṭhiko dānaṃ deti.**It’s when a bad person gives a gift carelessly, not with their own hand, and thoughtlessly. They give the dregs, and they give without consideration for consequences.*";
P_HTM[1535]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, asappuriso asappurisadānaṃ deti.**That’s how a bad person gives the gifts of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1536]="*So, bhikkhave, asappuriso evaṃ assaddhammasamannāgato, evaṃ asappurisabhatti, evaṃ asappurisacintī, evaṃ asappurisamantī, evaṃ asappurisavāco, evaṃ asappurisakammanto, evaṃ asappurisadiṭṭhi;**That bad person—who has such bad qualities, frequents bad people, and has the intentions, counsel, speech, actions, views, and giving of a bad person—*";
P_HTM[1537]="*evaṃ asappurisadānaṃ datvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā yā asappurisānaṃ gati tattha upapajjati.**when their body breaks up, after death, is reborn in the place where bad people are reborn.*";
P_HTM[1538]="*Kā ca, bhikkhave, asappurisānaṃ gati?**And what is the place where bad people are reborn?*";
P_HTM[1539]="*Nirayo vā tiracchānayoni vā.**Hell or the animal realm.*";
P_HTM[1540]="*Jāneyya nu kho, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisaṃ:**Mendicants, could a good person know of a good person:*";
P_HTM[1541]="*‘sappuriso ayaṃ bhavan’”ti?**‘This fellow is a good person’?”*";
P_HTM[1542]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1543]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhave;**“Good, mendicants!*";
P_HTM[1544]="*ṭhānametaṃ, bhikkhave, vijjati yaṃ sappuriso sappurisaṃ jāneyya:**It is possible that a good person could know of a good person:*";
P_HTM[1545]="*‘sappuriso ayaṃ bhavan’ti.**‘This fellow is a good person.’*";
P_HTM[1546]="*Jāneyya pana, bhikkhave, sappuriso asappurisaṃ:**But could a good person know of a bad person:*";
P_HTM[1547]="*‘asappuriso ayaṃ bhavan’”ti?**‘This fellow is a bad person’?”*";
P_HTM[1548]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1549]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhave;**“Good, mendicants!*";
P_HTM[1550]="*etampi kho, bhikkhave, ṭhānaṃ vijjati yaṃ sappuriso asappurisaṃ jāneyya:**That too is possible.*";
P_HTM[1551]="*‘asappuriso ayaṃ bhavan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1552]="*Sappuriso, bhikkhave, saddhammasamannāgato hoti, sappurisabhatti hoti, sappurisacintī hoti, sappurisamantī hoti, sappurisavāco hoti, sappurisakammanto hoti, sappurisadiṭṭhi hoti;**A good person has good qualities, associates with good people, and has the intentions, counsel, speech, actions, views, and giving of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1553]="*sappurisadānaṃ deti.* **";
P_HTM[1554]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sappuriso saddhammasamannāgato hoti?**And how does a good person have good qualities?*";
P_HTM[1555]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sappuriso saddho hoti, hirimā hoti, ottappī hoti, bahussuto hoti, āraddhavīriyo hoti, upaṭṭhitassati hoti, paññavā hoti.**It’s when a good person is faithful, conscientious, prudent, learned, energetic, mindful, and wise.*";
P_HTM[1556]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sappuriso saddhammasamannāgato hoti. (1)**That’s how a good person has good qualities.*";
P_HTM[1557]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisabhatti hoti?**And how does a good person associate with good people?*";
P_HTM[1558]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sappurisassa ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhā hirimanto ottappino bahussutā āraddhavīriyā upaṭṭhitassatino paññavanto tyāssa mittā honti, te sahāyā.**It’s when a good person is a friend and companion of ascetics and brahmins who are faithful, conscientious, prudent, learned, energetic, mindful, and wise.*";
P_HTM[1559]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisabhatti hoti. (2)**That’s how a good person associates with good people.*";
P_HTM[1560]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisacintī hoti?**And how does a good person have the intentions of a good person?*";
P_HTM[1561]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sappuriso nevattabyābādhāya ceteti, na parabyābādhāya ceteti, na ubhayabyābādhāya ceteti.**It’s when a good person doesn’t intend to hurt themselves, hurt others, and hurt both.*";
P_HTM[1562]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisacintī hoti. (3)**That’s how a good person has the intentions of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1563]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisamantī hoti?**And how does a good person offer the counsel of a good person?*";
P_HTM[1564]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sappuriso nevattabyābādhāya manteti, na parabyābādhāya manteti, na ubhayabyābādhāya manteti.**It’s when a good person offers counsel that doesn’t hurt themselves, hurt others, and hurt both.*";
P_HTM[1565]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisamantī hoti. (4)**That’s how a good person offers the counsel of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1566]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisavāco hoti?**And how does a good person have the speech of a good person?*";
P_HTM[1567]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sappuriso musāvādā paṭivirato hoti, pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti, pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti, samphappalāpā paṭivirato hoti.**It’s when a good person refrains from speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical.*";
P_HTM[1568]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisavāco hoti. (5)**That’s how a good person has the speech of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1569]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisakammanto hoti?**And how does a good person have the action of a good person?*";
P_HTM[1570]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sappuriso pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti, adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti, kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato hoti.**It’s when a good person refrains from killing living creatures, stealing, and committing sexual misconduct.*";
P_HTM[1571]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisakammanto hoti. (6)**That’s how a good person has the action of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1572]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisadiṭṭhi hoti?**And how does a good person have the view of a good person?*";
P_HTM[1573]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sappuriso evaṃdiṭṭhi hoti:**It’s when a good person has such a view:*";
P_HTM[1574]="*‘atthi dinnaṃ, atthi yiṭṭhaṃ, atthi hutaṃ, atthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko, atthi ayaṃ loko, atthi paro loko, atthi mātā, atthi pitā, atthi sattā opapātikā, atthi loke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sammaggatā sammāpaṭipannā ye imañca lokaṃ parañca lokaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedentī’ti.**‘There is meaning in giving, sacrifice, and offerings. There are fruits and results of good and bad deeds. There is an afterlife. There are duties to mother and father. There are beings reborn spontaneously. And there are ascetics and brahmins who are well attained and practiced, and who describe the afterlife after realizing it with their own insight.’*";
P_HTM[1575]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisadiṭṭhi hoti. (7)**That’s how a good person has the view of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1576]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisadānaṃ deti?**And how does a good person give the gifts of a good person?*";
P_HTM[1577]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sappuriso sakkaccaṃ dānaṃ deti, sahatthā dānaṃ deti, cittīkatvā dānaṃ deti, anapaviṭṭhaṃ dānaṃ deti, āgamanadiṭṭhiko dānaṃ deti.**It’s when a good person gives a gift carefully, with their own hand, and thoughtfully. They don’t give the dregs, and they give with consideration for consequences.*";
P_HTM[1578]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sappuriso sappurisadānaṃ deti. (8)**That’s how a good person gives the gifts of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1579]="*So, bhikkhave, sappuriso evaṃ saddhammasamannāgato, evaṃ sappurisabhatti, evaṃ sappurisacintī, evaṃ sappurisamantī, evaṃ sappurisavāco, evaṃ sappurisakammanto, evaṃ sappurisadiṭṭhi;**That good person—who has such good qualities, associates with good people, and has the intentions, counsel, speech, actions, views, and giving of a good person—*";
P_HTM[1580]="*evaṃ sappurisadānaṃ datvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā yā sappurisānaṃ gati tattha upapajjati.**when their body breaks up, after death, is reborn in the place where good people are reborn.*";
P_HTM[1581]="*Kā ca, bhikkhave, sappurisānaṃ gati?**And what is the place where good people are reborn?*";
P_HTM[1582]="*Devamahattatā vā manussamahattatā vā”ti.**A state of greatness among gods or humans.”*";
P_HTM[1583]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1584]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1585]="*Cūḷapuṇṇamasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1586]="*Devadahavaggo niṭṭhito paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[1587]="*Devadahaṃ pañcattayaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1588]="*Kinti sāma sunakkhattaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1589]="*Sappāya gaṇa gopaka—* **";
P_HTM[1590]="*Mahāpuṇṇa cūḷapuṇṇañcāti.* **";
P_HTM[1591]="*111. Anupadasutta**One by One*";
P_HTM[1592]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1593]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1594]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[1595]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[1596]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1597]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1598]="*“Paṇḍito, bhikkhave, sāriputto;**“Sāriputta is astute, mendicants.*";
P_HTM[1599]="*mahāpañño, bhikkhave, sāriputto;**He has great wisdom,*";
P_HTM[1600]="*puthupañño, bhikkhave, sāriputto;**widespread wisdom,*";
P_HTM[1601]="*hāsapañño, bhikkhave, sāriputto;**laughing wisdom,*";
P_HTM[1602]="*javanapañño, bhikkhave, sāriputto;**swift wisdom,*";
P_HTM[1603]="*tikkhapañño, bhikkhave, sāriputto;**sharp wisdom,*";
P_HTM[1604]="*nibbedhikapañño, bhikkhave, sāriputto;**and penetrating wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1605]="*sāriputto, bhikkhave, aḍḍhamāsaṃ anupadadhammavipassanaṃ vipassati.**For a fortnight he practiced discernment of phenomena one by one.*";
P_HTM[1606]="*Tatridaṃ, bhikkhave, sāriputtassa anupadadhammavipassanāya hoti.**And this is how he did it.*";
P_HTM[1607]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sāriputto vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, he entered and remained in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[1608]="*Ye ca paṭhame jhāne dhammā vitakko ca vicāro ca pīti ca sukhañca cittekaggatā ca, phasso vedanā saññā cetanā cittaṃ chando adhimokkho vīriyaṃ sati upekkhā manasikāro—tyāssa dhammā anupadavavatthitā honti.**And he distinguished the phenomena in the first absorption one by one: placing and keeping and rapture and bliss and unification of mind; contact, feeling, perception, intention, mind, enthusiasm, decision, energy, mindfulness, equanimity, and attention.*";
P_HTM[1609]="*Tyāssa dhammā viditā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**He knew those phenomena as they arose, as they remained, and as they went away.*";
P_HTM[1610]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**He understood:*";
P_HTM[1611]="*‘evaṃ kirame dhammā ahutvā sambhonti, hutvā paṭiventī’ti.**‘So it seems that these phenomena, not having been, come to be; and having come to be, they flit away.’*";
P_HTM[1612]="*So tesu dhammesu anupāyo anapāyo anissito appaṭibaddho vippamutto visaṃyutto vimariyādīkatena cetasā viharati.**And he meditated without attraction or repulsion for those phenomena; independent, untied, liberated, detached, his mind free of limits.*";
P_HTM[1613]="*So ‘atthi uttari nissaraṇan’ti pajānāti.**He understood: ‘There is an escape beyond.’*";
P_HTM[1614]="*Tabbahulīkārā atthitvevassa hoti. (1)**And by repeated practice he knew for sure that there is.*";
P_HTM[1615]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, sāriputto vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected were stilled, he entered and remained in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[1616]="*Ye ca dutiye jhāne dhammā—ajjhattaṃ sampasādo ca pīti ca sukhañca cittekaggatā ca, phasso vedanā saññā cetanā cittaṃ chando adhimokkho vīriyaṃ sati upekkhā manasikāro—tyāssa dhammā anupadavavatthitā honti.**And he distinguished the phenomena in the second absorption one by one: internal confidence and rapture and bliss and unification of mind; contact, feeling, perception, intention, mind, enthusiasm, decision, energy, mindfulness, equanimity, and attention.*";
P_HTM[1617]="*Tyāssa dhammā viditā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**He knew those phenomena as they arose, as they remained, and as they went away.*";
P_HTM[1618]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**He understood:*";
P_HTM[1619]="*‘evaṃ kirame dhammā ahutvā sambhonti, hutvā paṭiventī’ti.**‘So it seems that these phenomena, not having been, come to be; and having come to be, they flit away.’*";
P_HTM[1620]="*So tesu dhammesu anupāyo anapāyo anissito appaṭibaddho vippamutto visaṃyutto vimariyādīkatena cetasā viharati.**And he meditated without attraction or repulsion for those phenomena; independent, untied, liberated, detached, his mind free of limits.*";
P_HTM[1621]="*So ‘atthi uttari nissaraṇan’ti pajānāti.**He understood: ‘There is an escape beyond.’*";
P_HTM[1622]="*Tabbahulīkārā atthitvevassa hoti. (2)**And by repeated practice he knew for sure that there is.*";
P_HTM[1623]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, sāriputto pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato ca sampajāno, sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti. Yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, with the fading away of rapture, he entered and remained in the third absorption, where he meditated with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[1624]="*Ye ca tatiye jhāne dhammā—sukhañca sati ca sampajaññañca cittekaggatā ca, phasso vedanā saññā cetanā cittaṃ chando adhimokkho vīriyaṃ sati upekkhā manasikāro—**And he distinguished the phenomena in the third absorption one by one: bliss and mindfulness and awareness and unification of mind; contact, feeling, perception, intention, mind, enthusiasm, decision, energy, mindfulness, equanimity, and attention.*";
P_HTM[1625]="*tyāssa dhammā anupadavavatthitā honti, tyāssa dhammā viditā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**He knew those phenomena as they arose, as they remained, and as they went away.*";
P_HTM[1626]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**He understood:*";
P_HTM[1627]="*‘evaṃ kirame dhammā ahutvā sambhonti, hutvā paṭiventī’ti.**‘So it seems that these phenomena, not having been, come to be; and having come to be, they flit away.’*";
P_HTM[1628]="*So tesu dhammesu anupāyo anapāyo anissito appaṭibaddho vippamutto visaṃyutto vimariyādīkatena cetasā viharati.**And he meditated without attraction or repulsion for those phenomena; independent, untied, liberated, detached, his mind free of limits.*";
P_HTM[1629]="*So ‘atthi uttari nissaraṇan’ti pajānāti.**He understood: ‘There is an escape beyond.’*";
P_HTM[1630]="*Tabbahulīkārā atthitvevassa hoti. (3)**And by repeated practice he knew for sure that there is.*";
P_HTM[1631]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, sāriputto sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, with the giving up of pleasure and pain, and the ending of former happiness and sadness, he entered and remained in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[1632]="*Ye ca catutthe jhāne dhammā—upekkhā adukkhamasukhā vedanā passaddhattā cetaso anābhogo satipārisuddhi cittekaggatā ca, phasso vedanā saññā cetanā cittaṃ chando adhimokkho vīriyaṃ sati upekkhā manasikāro—tyāssa dhammā anupadavavatthitā honti.**And he distinguished the phenomena in the fourth absorption one by one: equanimity and neutral feeling and mental unconcern due to tranquility and pure mindfulness and unification of mind; contact, feeling, perception, intention, mind, enthusiasm, decision, energy, mindfulness, equanimity, and attention.*";
P_HTM[1633]="*Tyāssa dhammā viditā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**He knew those phenomena as they arose, as they remained, and as they went away.*";
P_HTM[1634]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**He understood:*";
P_HTM[1635]="*‘evaṃ kirame dhammā ahutvā sambhonti, hutvā paṭiventī’ti.**‘So it seems that these phenomena, not having been, come to be; and having come to be, they flit away.’*";
P_HTM[1636]="*So tesu dhammesu anupāyo anapāyo anissito appaṭibaddho vippamutto visaṃyutto vimariyādīkatena cetasā viharati.**And he meditated without attraction or repulsion for those phenomena; independent, untied, liberated, detached, his mind free of limits.*";
P_HTM[1637]="*So ‘atthi uttari nissaraṇan’ti pajānāti.**He understood: ‘There is an escape beyond.’*";
P_HTM[1638]="*Tabbahulīkārā atthitvevassa hoti. (4)**And by repeated practice he knew for sure that there is.*";
P_HTM[1639]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, sāriputto sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, he entered and remained in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[1640]="*Ye ca ākāsānañcāyatane dhammā—ākāsānañcāyatanasaññā ca cittekaggatā ca phasso vedanā saññā cetanā cittaṃ chando adhimokkho vīriyaṃ sati upekkhā manasikāro—tyāssa dhammā anupadavavatthitā honti.**And he distinguished the phenomena in the dimension of infinite space one by one: the perception of the dimension of infinite space and unification of mind; contact, feeling, perception, intention, mind, enthusiasm, decision, energy, mindfulness, equanimity, and attention.*";
P_HTM[1641]="*Tyāssa dhammā viditā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**He knew those phenomena as they arose, as they remained, and as they went away.*";
P_HTM[1642]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**He understood:*";
P_HTM[1643]="*‘evaṃ kirame dhammā ahutvā sambhonti, hutvā paṭiventī’ti.**‘So it seems that these phenomena, not having been, come to be; and having come to be, they flit away.’*";
P_HTM[1644]="*So tesu dhammesu anupāyo anapāyo anissito appaṭibaddho vippamutto visaṃyutto vimariyādīkatena cetasā viharati.**And he meditated without attraction or repulsion for those phenomena; independent, untied, liberated, detached, his mind free of limits.*";
P_HTM[1645]="*So ‘atthi uttari nissaraṇan’ti pajānāti.**He understood: ‘There is an escape beyond.’*";
P_HTM[1646]="*Tabbahulīkārā atthitvevassa hoti. (5)**And by repeated practice he knew for sure that there is.*";
P_HTM[1647]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, sāriputto sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, he entered and remained in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1648]="*Ye ca viññāṇañcāyatane dhammā—viññāṇañcāyatanasaññā ca cittekaggatā ca, phasso vedanā saññā cetanā cittaṃ chando adhimokkho vīriyaṃ sati upekkhā manasikāro—tyāssa dhammā anupadavavatthitā honti.**And he distinguished the phenomena in the dimension of infinite consciousness one by one: the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness and unification of mind; contact, feeling, perception, intention, mind, enthusiasm, decision, energy, mindfulness, equanimity, and attention.*";
P_HTM[1649]="*Tyāssa dhammā viditā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**He knew those phenomena as they arose, as they remained, and as they went away.*";
P_HTM[1650]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**He understood:*";
P_HTM[1651]="*‘evaṃ kirame dhammā ahutvā sambhonti, hutvā paṭiventī’ti.**‘So it seems that these phenomena, not having been, come to be; and having come to be, they flit away.’*";
P_HTM[1652]="*So tesu dhammesu anupāyo anapāyo anissito appaṭibaddho vippamutto visaṃyutto vimariyādīkatena cetasā viharati.**And he meditated without attraction or repulsion for those phenomena; independent, untied, liberated, detached, his mind free of limits.*";
P_HTM[1653]="*So ‘atthi uttari nissaraṇan’ti pajānāti.**He understood: ‘There is an escape beyond.’*";
P_HTM[1654]="*Tabbahulīkārā atthitvevassa hoti. (6)**And by repeated practice he knew for sure that there is.*";
P_HTM[1655]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, sāriputto sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, he entered and remained in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1656]="*Ye ca ākiñcaññāyatane dhammā—ākiñcaññāyatanasaññā ca cittekaggatā ca, phasso vedanā saññā cetanā cittaṃ chando adhimokkho vīriyaṃ sati upekkhā manasikāro—tyāssa dhammā anupadavavatthitā honti.**And he distinguished the phenomena in the dimension of nothingness one by one: the perception of the dimension of nothingness and unification of mind; contact, feeling, perception, intention, mind, enthusiasm, decision, energy, mindfulness, equanimity, and attention.*";
P_HTM[1657]="*Tyāssa dhammā viditā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**He knew those phenomena as they arose, as they remained, and as they went away.*";
P_HTM[1658]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**He understood:*";
P_HTM[1659]="*‘evaṃ kirame dhammā ahutvā sambhonti, hutvā paṭiventī’ti.**‘So it seems that these phenomena, not having been, come to be; and having come to be, they flit away.’*";
P_HTM[1660]="*So tesu dhammesu anupāyo anapāyo anissito appaṭibaddho vippamutto visaṃyutto vimariyādīkatena cetasā viharati.**And he meditated without attraction or repulsion for those phenomena; independent, untied, liberated, detached, his mind free of limits.*";
P_HTM[1661]="*So ‘atthi uttari nissaraṇan’ti pajānāti.**He understood: ‘There is an escape beyond.’*";
P_HTM[1662]="*Tabbahulīkārā atthitvevassa hoti. (7)**And by repeated practice he knew for sure that there is.*";
P_HTM[1663]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, sāriputto sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, he entered and remained in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[1664]="*So tāya samāpattiyā sato vuṭṭhahati.**And he emerged from that attainment with mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[1665]="*So tāya samāpattiyā sato vuṭṭhahitvā ye dhammā atītā niruddhā vipariṇatā te dhamme samanupassati:**Then he contemplated the phenomena in that attainment that had passed, ceased, and perished:*";
P_HTM[1666]="*‘evaṃ kirame dhammā ahutvā sambhonti, hutvā paṭiventī’ti.**‘So it seems that these phenomena, not having been, come to be; and having come to be, they flit away.’*";
P_HTM[1667]="*So tesu dhammesu anupāyo anapāyo anissito appaṭibaddho vippamutto visaṃyutto vimariyādīkatena cetasā viharati.**And he meditated without attraction or repulsion for those phenomena; independent, untied, liberated, detached, his mind free of limits.*";
P_HTM[1668]="*So ‘atthi uttari nissaraṇan’ti pajānāti.**He understood: ‘There is an escape beyond.’*";
P_HTM[1669]="*Tabbahulīkārā atthitvevassa hoti. (8)**And by repeated practice he knew for sure that there is.*";
P_HTM[1670]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, sāriputto sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati. Paññāya cassa disvā āsavā parikkhīṇā honti.**Furthermore, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, he entered and remained in the cessation of perception and feeling. And, having seen with wisdom, his defilements came to an end.*";
P_HTM[1671]="*So tāya samāpattiyā sato vuṭṭhahati.**And he emerged from that attainment with mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[1672]="*So tāya samāpattiyā sato vuṭṭhahitvā ye dhammā atītā niruddhā vipariṇatā te dhamme samanupassati:**Then he contemplated the phenomena in that attainment that had passed, ceased, and perished:*";
P_HTM[1673]="*‘evaṃ kirame dhammā ahutvā sambhonti, hutvā paṭiventī’ti.**‘So it seems that these phenomena, not having been, come to be; and having come to be, they flit away.’*";
P_HTM[1674]="*So tesu dhammesu anupāyo anapāyo anissito appaṭibaddho vippamutto visaṃyutto vimariyādīkatena cetasā viharati.**And he meditated without attraction or repulsion for those phenomena; independent, untied, liberated, detached, his mind free of limits.*";
P_HTM[1675]="*So ‘natthi uttari nissaraṇan’ti pajānāti.**He understood: ‘There is no escape beyond.’*";
P_HTM[1676]="*Tabbahulīkārā natthi tvevassa hoti.**And by repeated practice he knew for sure that there is not.*";
P_HTM[1677]="*Yaṃ kho taṃ, bhikkhave, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**And if there’s anyone of whom it may be rightly said that*";
P_HTM[1678]="*‘vasippatto pāramippatto ariyasmiṃ sīlasmiṃ, vasippatto pāramippatto ariyasmiṃ samādhismiṃ, vasippatto pāramippatto ariyāya paññāya, vasippatto pāramippatto ariyāya vimuttiyā’ti, sāriputtameva taṃ sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**they have attained mastery and perfection in noble ethics, immersion, wisdom, and freedom, it’s Sāriputta.*";
P_HTM[1679]="*‘vasippatto pāramippatto ariyasmiṃ sīlasmiṃ, vasippatto pāramippatto ariyasmiṃ samādhismiṃ, vasippatto pāramippatto ariyāya paññāya, vasippatto pāramippatto ariyāya vimuttiyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1680]="*Yaṃ kho taṃ, bhikkhave, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**And if there’s anyone of whom it may be rightly said that*";
P_HTM[1681]="*‘bhagavato putto oraso mukhato jāto dhammajo dhammanimmito dhammadāyādo no āmisadāyādo’ti, sāriputtameva taṃ sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**they’re the Buddha’s true-born child, born from his mouth, born of the teaching, created by the teaching, heir to the teaching, not the heir in material things, it’s Sāriputta.*";
P_HTM[1682]="*‘bhagavato putto oraso mukhato jāto dhammajo dhammanimmito dhammadāyādo no āmisadāyādo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1683]="*Sāriputto, bhikkhave, tathāgatena anuttaraṃ dhammacakkaṃ pavattitaṃ sammadeva anuppavattetī”ti.**Sāriputta rightly keeps rolling the supreme Wheel of Dhamma that was rolled forth by the Realized One.”*";
P_HTM[1684]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1685]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1686]="*Anupadasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1687]="*112. Chabbisodhanasutta**The Sixfold Purification*";
P_HTM[1688]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1689]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1690]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[1691]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[1692]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1693]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1694]="*“Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu aññaṃ byākaroti:**“Take a mendicant who declares enlightenment:*";
P_HTM[1695]="*‘khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāmī’ti.**‘I understand: “Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.”’*";
P_HTM[1696]="*Tassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno bhāsitaṃ neva abhinanditabbaṃ nappaṭikkositabbaṃ.**You should neither approve nor dismiss that mendicant’s statement.*";
P_HTM[1697]="*Anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā pañho pucchitabbo:**Rather, you should question them:*";
P_HTM[1698]="*‘cattārome, āvuso, vohārā tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena sammadakkhātā.**‘Reverend, these four kinds of expression have been rightly explained by the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1699]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1700]="*Diṭṭhe diṭṭhavāditā, sute sutavāditā, mute mutavāditā, viññāte viññātavāditā—**One speaks of the seen as seen, the heard as heard, the thought as thought, and the known as known.*";
P_HTM[1701]="*ime kho, āvuso, cattāro vohārā tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena sammadakkhātā.**These are the four kinds of expression rightly explained by the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1702]="*Kathaṃ jānato panāyasmato, kathaṃ passato imesu catūsu vohāresu anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuttan’ti?**How does the venerable know and see regarding these four kinds of expression so that your mind is freed from defilements by not grasping?’*";
P_HTM[1703]="*Khīṇāsavassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno vusitavato katakaraṇīyassa ohitabhārassa anuppattasadatthassa parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojanassa sammadaññāvimuttassa ayamanudhammo hoti veyyākaraṇāya:**For a mendicant with defilements ended—who has completed the spiritual journey, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, achieved their own goal, utterly ended the fetters of rebirth, and is rightly freed through enlightenment—it is in line with the teaching to answer:*";
P_HTM[1704]="*‘diṭṭhe kho ahaṃ, āvuso, anupāyo anapāyo anissito appaṭibaddho vippamutto visaṃyutto vimariyādīkatena cetasā viharāmi.**‘Reverends, I live without attraction or repulsion for what is seen; independent, untied, liberated, detached, my mind free of limits.*";
P_HTM[1705]="*Sute kho ahaṃ, āvuso … pe …**I live without attraction or repulsion for what is heard …*";
P_HTM[1706]="*mute kho ahaṃ, āvuso …**thought …*";
P_HTM[1707]="*viññāte kho ahaṃ, āvuso, anupāyo anapāyo anissito appaṭibaddho vippamutto visaṃyutto vimariyādīkatena cetasā viharāmi.**or known; independent, untied, liberated, detached, my mind free of limits.*";
P_HTM[1708]="*Evaṃ kho me, āvuso, jānato evaṃ passato imesu catūsu vohāresu anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuttan’ti.**That is how I know and see regarding these four kinds of expression so that my mind is freed from defilements by not grasping.’*";
P_HTM[1709]="*Tassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ‘sādhū’ti bhāsitaṃ abhinanditabbaṃ anumoditabbaṃ.**Saying ‘Good!’ you should applaud and cheer that mendicant’s statement,*";
P_HTM[1710]="*‘Sādhū’ti bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uttariṃ pañho pucchitabbo.**then ask a further question:*";
P_HTM[1711]="*‘Pañcime, āvuso, upādānakkhandhā tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena sammadakkhātā.**‘Reverend, these five grasping aggregates have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1712]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1713]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho—**That is: the grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1714]="*ime kho, āvuso, pañcupādānakkhandhā tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena sammadakkhātā.**These are the five grasping aggregates that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1715]="*Kathaṃ jānato panāyasmato, kathaṃ passato imesu pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuttan’ti?**How does the venerable know and see regarding these five grasping aggregates so that your mind is freed from defilements by not grasping?’*";
P_HTM[1716]="*Khīṇāsavassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno vusitavato katakaraṇīyassa ohitabhārassa anuppattasadatthassa parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojanassa sammadaññāvimuttassa ayamanudhammo hoti veyyākaraṇāya:**For a mendicant with defilements ended it is in line with the teaching to answer:*";
P_HTM[1717]="*‘rūpaṃ kho ahaṃ, āvuso, abalaṃ virāgunaṃ anassāsikanti viditvā ye rūpe upāyūpādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā tesaṃ khayā virāgā nirodhā cāgā paṭinissaggā vimuttaṃ me cittanti pajānāmi.**‘Reverends, knowing that form is powerless, fading, and unreliable, I understand that my mind is freed through the ending, fading away, cessation, giving away, and letting go of attraction, grasping, mental fixation, insistence, and underlying tendency for form.*";
P_HTM[1718]="*Vedanaṃ kho ahaṃ, āvuso … pe …**Knowing that feeling …*";
P_HTM[1719]="*saññaṃ kho ahaṃ, āvuso …**perception …*";
P_HTM[1720]="*saṅkhāre kho ahaṃ, āvuso …**choices …*";
P_HTM[1721]="*viññāṇaṃ kho ahaṃ, āvuso, abalaṃ virāgunaṃ anassāsikanti viditvā ye viññāṇe upāyūpādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā tesaṃ khayā virāgā nirodhā cāgā paṭinissaggā vimuttaṃ me cittanti pajānāmi.**consciousness is powerless, fading, and unreliable, I understand that my mind is freed through the ending, fading away, cessation, giving away, and letting go of attraction, grasping, mental fixation, insistence, and underlying tendency for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1722]="*Evaṃ kho me, āvuso, jānato evaṃ passato imesu pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuttan’ti.**That is how I know and see regarding these five grasping aggregates so that my mind is freed from defilements by not grasping.’*";
P_HTM[1723]="*Tassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ‘sādhū’ti bhāsitaṃ abhinanditabbaṃ, anumoditabbaṃ.**Saying ‘Good!’ you should applaud and cheer that mendicant’s statement,*";
P_HTM[1724]="*‘Sādhū’ti bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uttariṃ pañho pucchitabbo.**then ask a further question:*";
P_HTM[1725]="*‘Chayimā, āvuso, dhātuyo tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena sammadakkhātā.**‘Reverend, these six elements have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1726]="*Katamā cha?**What six?*";
P_HTM[1727]="*Pathavīdhātu, āpodhātu, tejodhātu, vāyodhātu, ākāsadhātu, viññāṇadhātu—**The elements of earth, water, fire, air, space, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1728]="*imā kho, āvuso, cha dhātuyo tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena sammadakkhātā.**These are the six elements that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1729]="*Kathaṃ jānato panāyasmato, kathaṃ passato imāsu chasu dhātūsu anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuttan’ti?**How does the venerable know and see regarding these six elements so that your mind is freed from defilements by not grasping?’*";
P_HTM[1730]="*Khīṇāsavassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno vusitavato katakaraṇīyassa ohitabhārassa anuppattasadatthassa parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojanassa sammadaññāvimuttassa ayamanudhammo hoti veyyākaraṇāya:**For a mendicant with defilements ended it is in line with the teaching to answer:*";
P_HTM[1731]="*‘pathavīdhātuṃ kho ahaṃ, āvuso, na attato upagacchiṃ, na ca pathavīdhātunissitaṃ attānaṃ.**‘Reverends, I’ve not taken the earth element as self, nor is there a self based on the earth element.*";
P_HTM[1732]="*Ye ca pathavīdhātunissitā upāyūpādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā tesaṃ khayā virāgā nirodhā cāgā paṭinissaggā vimuttaṃ me cittanti pajānāmi.**And I understand that my mind is freed through the ending, fading away, cessation, giving away, and letting go of attraction, grasping, mental fixation, insistence, and underlying tendency based on the earth element.*";
P_HTM[1733]="*Āpodhātuṃ kho ahaṃ, āvuso … pe …**I’ve not taken the water element …*";
P_HTM[1734]="*tejodhātuṃ kho ahaṃ, āvuso …**fire element …*";
P_HTM[1735]="*vāyodhātuṃ kho ahaṃ, āvuso …**air element …*";
P_HTM[1736]="*ākāsadhātuṃ kho ahaṃ, āvuso …**space element …*";
P_HTM[1737]="*viññāṇadhātuṃ kho ahaṃ, āvuso, na attato upagacchiṃ, na ca viññāṇadhātunissitaṃ attānaṃ.**consciousness element as self, nor is there a self based on the consciousness element.*";
P_HTM[1738]="*Ye ca viññāṇadhātunissitā upāyūpādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā tesaṃ khayā virāgā nirodhā cāgā paṭinissaggā vimuttaṃ me cittanti pajānāmi.**And I understand that my mind is freed through the ending of attraction based on the consciousness element.*";
P_HTM[1739]="*Evaṃ kho me, āvuso, jānato, evaṃ passato imāsu chasu dhātūsu anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuttan’ti.**That is how I know and see regarding these six elements so that my mind is freed from defilements by not grasping.’*";
P_HTM[1740]="*Tassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ‘sādhū’ti bhāsitaṃ abhinanditabbaṃ, anumoditabbaṃ.**Saying ‘Good!’ you should applaud and cheer that mendicant’s statement,*";
P_HTM[1741]="*‘Sādhū’ti bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uttariṃ pañho pucchitabbo.**then ask a further question:*";
P_HTM[1742]="*‘Cha kho panimāni, āvuso, ajjhattikabāhirāni āyatanāni tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena sammadakkhātāni.**‘Reverend, these six interior and exterior sense fields have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1743]="*Katamāni cha?**What six?*";
P_HTM[1744]="*Cakkhu ceva rūpā ca, sotañca saddā ca, ghānañca gandhā ca, jivhā ca rasā ca, kāyo ca phoṭṭhabbā ca, mano ca dhammā ca—**The eye and sights, the ear and sounds, the nose and smells, the tongue and tastes, the body and touches, and the mind and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1745]="*imāni kho, āvuso, cha ajjhattikabāhirāni āyatanāni tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena sammadakkhātāni.**These are the six interior and exterior sense fields that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1746]="*Kathaṃ jānato panāyasmato, kathaṃ passato imesu chasu ajjhattikabāhiresu āyatanesu anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuttan’ti?**How does the venerable know and see regarding these six interior and exterior sense fields so that your mind is freed from defilements by not grasping?’*";
P_HTM[1747]="*Khīṇāsavassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno vusitavato katakaraṇīyassa ohitabhārassa anuppattasadatthassa parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojanassa sammadaññāvimuttassa ayamanudhammo hoti veyyākaraṇāya:**For a mendicant with defilements ended it is in line with the teaching to answer:*";
P_HTM[1748]="*‘cakkhusmiṃ, āvuso, rūpe cakkhuviññāṇe cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbesu dhammesu yo chando yo rāgo yā nandī yā taṇhā ye ca upāyūpādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā tesaṃ khayā virāgā nirodhā cāgā paṭinissaggā vimuttaṃ me cittanti pajānāmi.**‘I understand that my mind is freed through the ending, fading away, cessation, giving away, and letting go of desire and greed and relishing and craving; attraction, grasping, mental fixation, insistence, and underlying tendency for the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and things knowable by eye consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1749]="*Sotasmiṃ, āvuso, sadde sotaviññāṇe … pe …**I understand that my mind is freed through the ending of desire for the ear …*";
P_HTM[1750]="*ghānasmiṃ, āvuso, gandhe ghānaviññāṇe …**nose …*";
P_HTM[1751]="*jivhāya, āvuso, rase jivhāviññāṇe …**tongue …*";
P_HTM[1752]="*kāyasmiṃ, āvuso, phoṭṭhabbe kāyaviññāṇe …**body …*";
P_HTM[1753]="*manasmiṃ, āvuso, dhamme manoviññāṇe manoviññāṇaviññātabbesu dhammesu yo chando yo rāgo yā nandī yā taṇhā ye ca upāyūpādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā tesaṃ khayā virāgā nirodhā cāgā paṭinissaggā vimuttaṃ me cittanti pajānāmi.**mind, thoughts, mind consciousness, and things knowable by mind consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1754]="*Evaṃ kho me, āvuso, jānato evaṃ passato imesu chasu ajjhattikabāhiresu āyatanesu anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuttan’ti.**That is how I know and see regarding these six interior and exterior sense fields so that my mind is freed from defilements by not grasping.’*";
P_HTM[1755]="*Tassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ‘sādhū’ti bhāsitaṃ abhinanditabbaṃ anumoditabbaṃ.**Saying ‘Good!’ you should applaud and cheer that mendicant’s statement,*";
P_HTM[1756]="*‘Sādhū’ti bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uttariṃ pañho pucchitabbo.**then ask a further question:*";
P_HTM[1757]="*‘Kathaṃ jānato panāyasmato, kathaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṃkāramamaṃkāramānānusayā samūhatā’ti?**‘Sir, how does the venerable know and see so that he has eradicated ego, possessiveness, and underlying tendency to conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli?’*";
P_HTM[1758]="*Khīṇāsavassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno vusitavato katakaraṇīyassa ohitabhārassa anuppattasadatthassa parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojanassa sammadaññāvimuttassa ayamanudhammo hoti veyyākaraṇāya:**For a mendicant with defilements ended it is in line with the teaching to answer:*";
P_HTM[1759]="*‘pubbe kho ahaṃ, āvuso, agāriyabhūto samāno aviddasu ahosiṃ.**‘Formerly, reverends, when I was still a layperson, I was ignorant.*";
P_HTM[1760]="*Tassa me tathāgato vā tathāgatasāvako vā dhammaṃ desesi.**Then the Realized One or one of his disciples taught me the Dhamma.*";
P_HTM[1761]="*Tāhaṃ dhammaṃ sutvā tathāgate saddhaṃ paṭilabhiṃ.**I gained faith in the Realized One,*";
P_HTM[1762]="*So tena saddhāpaṭilābhena samannāgato iti paṭisañcikkhiṃ:**and reflected:*";
P_HTM[1763]="*“sambādho gharāvāso rajāpatho, abbhokāso pabbajjā.**“Living in a house is cramped and dirty, but the life of one gone forth is wide open.*";
P_HTM[1764]="*Nayidaṃ sukaraṃ agāraṃ ajjhāvasatā ekantaparipuṇṇaṃ ekantaparisuddhaṃ saṅkhalikhitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ carituṃ.**It’s not easy for someone living at home to lead the spiritual life utterly full and pure, like a polished shell.*";
P_HTM[1765]="*Yannūnāhaṃ kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajeyyan”ti.**Why don’t I cut off my hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from lay life to homelessness?”*";
P_HTM[1766]="*So kho ahaṃ, āvuso, aparena samayena appaṃ vā bhogakkhandhaṃ pahāya mahantaṃ vā bhogakkhandhaṃ pahāya, appaṃ vā ñātiparivaṭṭaṃ pahāya mahantaṃ vā ñātiparivaṭṭaṃ pahāya kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajiṃ.**After some time I gave up a large or small fortune, and a large or small family circle. I shaved off hair and beard, dressed in ocher robes, and went forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[1767]="*So evaṃ pabbajito samāno bhikkhūnaṃ sikkhāsājīvasamāpanno pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato ahosiṃ nihitadaṇḍo nihitasattho, lajjī dayāpanno sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī vihāsiṃ.**Once I had gone forth, I took up the training and livelihood of the mendicants. I gave up killing living creatures, renouncing the rod and the sword. I was scrupulous and kind, living full of compassion for all living beings.*";
P_HTM[1768]="*Adinnādānaṃ pahāya adinnādānā paṭivirato ahosiṃ dinnādāyī dinnapāṭikaṅkhī, athenena sucibhūtena attanā vihāsiṃ.**I gave up stealing. I took only what’s given, and expected only what’s given. I kept myself clean by not thieving.*";
P_HTM[1769]="*Abrahmacariyaṃ pahāya brahmacārī ahosiṃ ārācārī virato methunā gāmadhammā.**I gave up unchastity. I became celibate, set apart, avoiding the common practice of sex.*";
P_HTM[1770]="*Musāvādaṃ pahāya musāvādā paṭivirato ahosiṃ saccavādī saccasandho theto paccayiko avisaṃvādako lokassa.**I gave up lying. I spoke the truth and stuck to the truth. I was honest and trustworthy, not tricking the world with my words.*";
P_HTM[1771]="*Pisuṇaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato ahosiṃ, ito sutvā na amutra akkhātā imesaṃ bhedāya, amutra vā sutvā na imesaṃ akkhātā amūsaṃ bhedāya; iti bhinnānaṃ vā sandhātā sahitānaṃ vā anuppadātā samaggārāmo samaggarato samagganandī samaggakaraṇiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā ahosiṃ.**I gave up divisive speech. I didn’t repeat in one place what I heard in another so as to divide people against each other. Instead, I reconciled those who are divided, supporting unity, delighting in harmony, loving harmony, speaking words that promote harmony.*";
P_HTM[1772]="*Pharusaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato ahosiṃ; yā sā vācā nelā kaṇṇasukhā pemanīyā hadayaṅgamā porī bahujanakantā bahujanamanāpā tathārūpiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā ahosiṃ.**I gave up harsh speech. I spoke in a way that’s mellow, pleasing to the ear, lovely, going to the heart, polite, likable and agreeable to the people.*";
P_HTM[1773]="*Samphappalāpaṃ pahāya samphappalāpā paṭivirato ahosiṃ; kālavādī bhūtavādī atthavādī dhammavādī vinayavādī nidhānavatiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā ahosiṃ kālena sāpadesaṃ pariyantavatiṃ atthasaṃhitaṃ.**I gave up talking nonsense. My words were timely, true, and meaningful, in line with the teaching and training. I said things at the right time which are valuable, reasonable, succinct, and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1774]="*So bījagāmabhūtagāmasamārambhā paṭivirato ahosiṃ, ekabhattiko ahosiṃ rattūparato virato vikālabhojanā.**I avoided injuring plants and seeds. I ate in one part of the day, abstaining from eating at night and food at the wrong time.*";
P_HTM[1775]="*Naccagītavāditavisūkadassanā paṭivirato ahosiṃ.**I avoided dancing, singing, music, and seeing shows.*";
P_HTM[1776]="*Mālāgandhavilepanadhāraṇamaṇḍanavibhūsanaṭṭhānā paṭivirato ahosiṃ.**I avoided beautifying and adorning myself with garlands, perfumes, and makeup.*";
P_HTM[1777]="*Uccāsayanamahāsayanā paṭivirato ahosiṃ.**I avoided high and luxurious beds.*";
P_HTM[1778]="*Jātarūparajatapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato ahosiṃ,**I avoided receiving gold and money,*";
P_HTM[1779]="*āmakadhaññapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato ahosiṃ,**raw grains,*";
P_HTM[1780]="*āmakamaṃsapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato ahosiṃ;**raw meat,*";
P_HTM[1781]="*itthikumārikapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato ahosiṃ,**women and girls,*";
P_HTM[1782]="*dāsidāsapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato ahosiṃ,**male and female bondservants,*";
P_HTM[1783]="*ajeḷakapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato ahosiṃ,**goats and sheep,*";
P_HTM[1784]="*kukkuṭasūkarapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato ahosiṃ,**chicken and pigs,*";
P_HTM[1785]="*hatthigavassavaḷavapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato ahosiṃ,**elephants, cows, horses, and mares,*";
P_HTM[1786]="*khettavatthupaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato ahosiṃ.**and fields and land.*";
P_HTM[1787]="*Dūteyyapahiṇagamanānuyogā paṭivirato ahosiṃ,**I avoided running errands and messages;*";
P_HTM[1788]="*kayavikkayā paṭivirato ahosiṃ,**buying and selling;*";
P_HTM[1789]="*tulākūṭakaṃsakūṭamānakūṭā paṭivirato ahosiṃ,**falsifying weights, metals, or measures;*";
P_HTM[1790]="*ukkoṭanavañcananikatisāciyogā paṭivirato ahosiṃ,**bribery, fraud, cheating, and duplicity;*";
P_HTM[1791]="*chedanavadhabandhanaviparāmosaālopasahasākārā paṭivirato ahosiṃ.**mutilation, murder, abduction, banditry, plunder, and violence.*";
P_HTM[1792]="*So santuṭṭho ahosiṃ kāyaparihārikena cīvarena, kucchiparihārikena piṇḍapātena. So yena yeneva pakkamiṃ samādāyeva pakkamiṃ.**I became content with robes to look after the body and alms-food to look after the belly. Wherever I went, I set out taking only these things.*";
P_HTM[1793]="*Seyyathāpi nāma pakkhī sakuṇo yena yeneva ḍeti sapattabhārova ḍeti;**Like a bird: wherever it flies, wings are its only burden.*";
P_HTM[1794]="*evameva kho ahaṃ, āvuso; santuṭṭho ahosiṃ kāyaparihārikena cīvarena, kucchiparihārikena piṇḍapātena. So yena yeneva pakkamiṃ samādāyeva pakkamiṃ.**In the same way, I became content with robes to look after the body and alms-food to look after the belly. Wherever I went, I set out taking only these things.*";
P_HTM[1795]="*So iminā ariyena sīlakkhandhena samannāgato ajjhattaṃ anavajjasukhaṃ paṭisaṃvedesiṃ.**When I had this entire spectrum of noble ethics, I experienced a blameless happiness inside myself.*";
P_HTM[1796]="*So cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā na nimittaggāhī ahosiṃ nānubyañjanaggāhī;**When I saw a sight with my eyes, I didn’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[1797]="*yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ cakkhundriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ, tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjiṃ; rakkhiṃ cakkhundriyaṃ, cakkhundriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjiṃ.**If the faculty of sight were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, I practiced restraint, protecting the faculty of sight, and achieving its restraint.*";
P_HTM[1798]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**When I heard a sound with my ears …*";
P_HTM[1799]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā … pe …**When I smelled an odor with my nose …*";
P_HTM[1800]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā … pe …**When I tasted a flavor with my tongue …*";
P_HTM[1801]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā … pe …**When I felt a touch with my body …*";
P_HTM[1802]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya na nimittaggāhī ahosiṃ nānubyañjanaggāhī;**When I knew a thought with my mind, I didn’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[1803]="*yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ manindriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ, tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjiṃ; rakkhiṃ manindriyaṃ, manindriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjiṃ.**If the faculty of the mind were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, I practiced restraint, protecting the faculty of the mind, and achieving its restraint.*";
P_HTM[1804]="*So iminā ariyena indriyasaṃvarena samannāgato ajjhattaṃ abyāsekasukhaṃ paṭisaṃvedesiṃ.**When I had this noble sense restraint, I experienced an unsullied bliss inside myself.*";
P_HTM[1805]="*So abhikkante paṭikkante sampajānakārī ahosiṃ, ālokite vilokite sampajānakārī ahosiṃ, samiñjite pasārite sampajānakārī ahosiṃ, saṅghāṭipattacīvaradhāraṇe sampajānakārī ahosiṃ, asite pīte khāyite sāyite sampajānakārī ahosiṃ, uccārapassāvakamme sampajānakārī ahosiṃ, gate ṭhite nisinne sutte jāgarite bhāsite tuṇhībhāve sampajānakārī ahosiṃ.**I acted with situational awareness when going out and coming back; when looking ahead and aside; when bending and extending the limbs; when bearing the outer robe, bowl and robes; when eating, drinking, chewing, and tasting; when urinating and defecating; when walking, standing, sitting, sleeping, waking, speaking, and keeping silent.*";
P_HTM[1806]="*So iminā ca ariyena sīlakkhandhena samannāgato, imāya ca ariyāya santuṭṭhiyā samannāgato, iminā ca ariyena indriyasaṃvarena samannāgato, iminā ca ariyena satisampajaññena samannāgato**When I had this noble spectrum of ethics, this noble sense restraint, and this noble mindfulness and situational awareness,*";
P_HTM[1807]="*vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajiṃ araññaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ pabbataṃ kandaraṃ giriguhaṃ susānaṃ vanapatthaṃ abbhokāsaṃ palālapuñjaṃ.**I frequented a secluded lodging—a wilderness, the root of a tree, a hill, a ravine, a mountain cave, a charnel ground, a forest, the open air, a heap of straw.*";
P_HTM[1808]="*So pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto nisīdiṃ pallaṅkaṃ ābhujitvā ujuṃ kāyaṃ paṇidhāya parimukhaṃ satiṃ upaṭṭhapetvā.**After the meal, I returned from alms-round, sat down cross-legged with my body straight, and established mindfulness right there.*";
P_HTM[1809]="*So abhijjhaṃ loke pahāya vigatābhijjhena cetasā vihāsiṃ, abhijjhāya cittaṃ parisodhesiṃ.**Giving up desire for the world, I meditated with a heart rid of desire, cleansing the mind of desire.*";
P_HTM[1810]="*Byāpādapadosaṃ pahāya abyāpannacitto vihāsiṃ sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī, byāpādapadosā cittaṃ parisodhesiṃ.**Giving up ill will and malevolence, I meditated with a mind rid of ill will, full of compassion for all living beings, cleansing the mind of ill will.*";
P_HTM[1811]="*Thinamiddhaṃ pahāya vigatathinamiddho vihāsiṃ ālokasaññī sato sampajāno, thinamiddhā cittaṃ parisodhesiṃ.**Giving up dullness and drowsiness, I meditated with a mind rid of dullness and drowsiness, perceiving light, mindful and aware, cleansing the mind of dullness and drowsiness.*";
P_HTM[1812]="*Uddhaccakukkuccaṃ pahāya anuddhato vihāsiṃ ajjhattaṃ, vūpasantacitto, uddhaccakukkuccā cittaṃ parisodhesiṃ.**Giving up restlessness and remorse, I meditated without restlessness, my mind peaceful inside, cleansing the mind of restlessness and remorse.*";
P_HTM[1813]="*Vicikicchaṃ pahāya tiṇṇavicikiccho vihāsiṃ akathaṅkathī kusalesu dhammesu, vicikicchāya cittaṃ parisodhesiṃ.**Giving up doubt, I meditated having gone beyond doubt, not undecided about skillful qualities, cleansing the mind of doubt.*";
P_HTM[1814]="*So ime pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe**I gave up these five hindrances, corruptions of the heart that weaken wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1815]="*vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja vihāsiṃ.**Then, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, I entered and remained in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[1816]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ … pe …**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected were stilled, I entered and remained in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[1817]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[1818]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja vihāsiṃ.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[1819]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte āsavānaṃ khayañāṇāya cittaṃ abhininnāmesiṃ.**When my mind had immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—I extended it toward knowledge of the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[1820]="*So idaṃ dukkhanti yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, ayaṃ dukkhasamudayoti yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, ayaṃ dukkhanirodhoti yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadāti yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ;**I truly understood: “This is suffering” … “This is the origin of suffering” … “This is the cessation of suffering” … “This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering”.*";
P_HTM[1821]="*ime āsavāti yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, ayaṃ āsavasamudayoti yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, ayaṃ āsavanirodhoti yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, ayaṃ āsavanirodhagāminī paṭipadāti yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ.**I truly understood: “These are defilements”… “This is the origin of defilements” … “This is the cessation of defilements” … “This is the practice that leads to the cessation of defilements”.*";
P_HTM[1822]="*Tassa me evaṃ jānato evaṃ passato kāmāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccittha, bhavāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccittha, avijjāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccittha.**Knowing and seeing like this, my mind was freed from the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[1823]="*Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ ahosi.**When it was freed, I knew it was freed.*";
P_HTM[1824]="*Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyāti abbhaññāsiṃ.**I understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[1825]="*Evaṃ kho me, āvuso, jānato evaṃ passato imasmiñca saviññāṇake kāye bahiddhā ca sabbanimittesu ahaṃkāramamaṃkāramānānusayā samūhatā’ti.**That is how I know and see so that I have eradicated ego, possessiveness, and underlying tendency to conceit for this conscious body and all external stimuli.’*";
P_HTM[1826]="*Tassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ‘sādhū’ti bhāsitaṃ abhinanditabbaṃ anumoditabbaṃ.**Saying ‘Good!’ you should applaud and cheer that mendicant’s statement,*";
P_HTM[1827]="*‘Sādhū’ti bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā evamassa vacanīyo:**and then say to them:*";
P_HTM[1828]="*‘lābhā no, āvuso, suladdhaṃ no, āvuso,**‘We are fortunate, reverend, so very fortunate*";
P_HTM[1829]="*ye mayaṃ āyasmantaṃ tādisaṃ sabrahmacāriṃ samanupassāmā’”ti.**to see a venerable such as yourself as one of our spiritual companions!’”*";
P_HTM[1830]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1831]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1832]="*Chabbisodhanasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1833]="*113. Sappurisasutta**A Good Person*";
P_HTM[1834]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1835]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1836]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[1837]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[1838]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1839]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1840]="*“sappurisadhammañca vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi asappurisadhammañca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the qualities of a good person and the qualities of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1841]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[1842]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1843]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1844]="*“Katamo ca, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo?**“And what is a quality of a bad person?*";
P_HTM[1845]="*Idha, bhikkhave, asappuriso uccākulā pabbajito hoti.**Take a bad person who has gone forth from an eminent family.*";
P_HTM[1846]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**They reflect:*";
P_HTM[1847]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi uccākulā pabbajito, ime panaññe bhikkhū na uccākulā pabbajitā’ti.**‘I have gone forth from an eminent family, unlike these other mendicants.’*";
P_HTM[1848]="*So tāya uccākulīnatāya attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.**And they glorify themselves and put others down on account of that.*";
P_HTM[1849]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.**This is a quality of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1850]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:**A good person reflects:*";
P_HTM[1851]="*‘na kho uccākulīnatāya lobhadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, dosadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, mohadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.**‘It’s not because of one’s eminent family that thoughts of greed, hate, or delusion come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1852]="*No cepi uccākulā pabbajito hoti;**Even if someone has not gone forth from an eminent family,*";
P_HTM[1853]="*so ca hoti dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tattha pujjo, so tattha pāsaṃso’ti.**if they practice in line with the teaching, practice properly, and live in line with the teaching, they are worthy of honor and praise for that.’*";
P_HTM[1854]="*So paṭipadaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā tāya uccākulīnatāya nevattānukkaṃseti na paraṃ vambheti.**Keeping only the practice close to their heart, they don’t glorify themselves and put others down on account of their eminent family.*";
P_HTM[1855]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (1)**This is a quality of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1856]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso mahākulā pabbajito hoti … pe …**Furthermore, take a bad person who has gone forth from a great family …*";
P_HTM[1857]="*mahābhogakulā pabbajito hoti … pe …**from a wealthy family …*";
P_HTM[1858]="*uḷārabhogakulā pabbajito hoti.**from an extremely wealthy family.*";
P_HTM[1859]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**They reflect:*";
P_HTM[1860]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi uḷārabhogakulā pabbajito, ime panaññe bhikkhū na uḷārabhogakulā pabbajitā’ti.**‘I have gone forth from an extremely wealthy family, unlike these other mendicants.’*";
P_HTM[1861]="*So tāya uḷārabhogatāya attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.**And they glorify themselves and put others down on account of that.*";
P_HTM[1862]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.**This too is a quality of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1863]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:**A good person reflects:*";
P_HTM[1864]="*‘na kho uḷārabhogatāya lobhadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, dosadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, mohadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.**‘It’s not because of one’s extremely wealthy family that thoughts of greed, hate, or delusion come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1865]="*No cepi uḷārabhogakulā pabbajito hoti;**Even if someone has not gone forth from an extremely wealthy family,*";
P_HTM[1866]="*so ca hoti dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tattha pujjo, so tattha pāsaṃso’ti.**if they practice in line with the teaching, practice properly, and live in line with the teaching, they are worthy of honor and praise for that.’*";
P_HTM[1867]="*So paṭipadaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā tāya uḷārabhogatāya nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.**Keeping only the practice close to their heart, they don’t glorify themselves and put others down on account of their extremely wealthy family.*";
P_HTM[1868]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (2–4.)**This too is a quality of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1869]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso ñāto hoti yasassī.**Furthermore, take a bad person who is well-known and famous.*";
P_HTM[1870]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**They reflect:*";
P_HTM[1871]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi ñāto yasassī, ime panaññe bhikkhū appaññātā appesakkhā’ti.**‘I’m well-known and famous. These other mendicants are obscure and insignificant.’*";
P_HTM[1872]="*So tena ñattena attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.**And they glorify themselves and put others down on account of that.*";
P_HTM[1873]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.**This too is a quality of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1874]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:**A good person reflects:*";
P_HTM[1875]="*‘na kho ñattena lobhadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, dosadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, mohadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.**‘It’s not because of one’s fame that thoughts of greed, hate, or delusion come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1876]="*No cepi ñāto hoti yasassī;**Even if someone is not well-known and famous,*";
P_HTM[1877]="*so ca hoti dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tattha pujjo, so tattha pāsaṃso’ti.**if they practice in line with the teaching, practice properly, and live in line with the teaching, they are worthy of honor and praise for that.’*";
P_HTM[1878]="*So paṭipadaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā tena ñattena nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.**Keeping only the practice close to their heart, they don’t glorify themselves and put others down on account of their fame.*";
P_HTM[1879]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (5)**This too is a quality of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1880]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso lābhī hoti cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārānaṃ.**Furthermore, take a bad person who receives robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick.*";
P_HTM[1881]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**They reflect:*";
P_HTM[1882]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi lābhī cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārānaṃ, ime panaññe bhikkhū na lābhino cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārānan’ti.**‘I receive robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick, unlike these other mendicants.’*";
P_HTM[1883]="*So tena lābhena attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.**And they glorify themselves and put others down on account of that.*";
P_HTM[1884]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.**This too is a quality of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1885]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:**A good person reflects:*";
P_HTM[1886]="*‘na kho lābhena lobhadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, dosadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, mohadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.**‘It’s not because of one’s material possessions that thoughts of greed, hate, or delusion come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1887]="*No cepi lābhī hoti cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārānaṃ;**Even if someone doesn’t receive robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick,*";
P_HTM[1888]="*so ca hoti dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tattha pujjo, so tattha pāsaṃso’ti.**if they practice in line with the teaching, practice properly, and live in line with the teaching, they are worthy of honor and praise for that.’*";
P_HTM[1889]="*So paṭipadaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā tena lābhena nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.**Keeping only the practice close to their heart, they don’t glorify themselves and put others down on account of their material possessions.*";
P_HTM[1890]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (6)**This too is a quality of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1891]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso bahussuto hoti.**Furthermore, take a bad person who is very learned …*";
P_HTM[1892]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1893]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi bahussuto, ime panaññe bhikkhū na bahussutā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1894]="*So tena bāhusaccena attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1895]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.* **";
P_HTM[1896]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1897]="*‘na kho bāhusaccena lobhadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, dosadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, mohadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.* **";
P_HTM[1898]="*No cepi bahussuto hoti;* **";
P_HTM[1899]="*so ca hoti dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tattha pujjo, so tattha pāsaṃso’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1900]="*So paṭipadaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā tena bāhusaccena nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1901]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (7)* **";
P_HTM[1902]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso vinayadharo hoti.**an expert in the texts on monastic training …*";
P_HTM[1903]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1904]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi vinayadharo, ime panaññe bhikkhū na vinayadharā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1905]="*So tena vinayadharattena attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1906]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.* **";
P_HTM[1907]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1908]="*‘na kho vinayadharattena lobhadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, dosadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, mohadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.* **";
P_HTM[1909]="*No cepi vinayadharo hoti;* **";
P_HTM[1910]="*so ca hoti dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tattha pujjo, so tattha pāsaṃso’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1911]="*So paṭipadaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā tena vinayadharattena nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1912]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (8)* **";
P_HTM[1913]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso dhammakathiko hoti.**a Dhamma teacher …*";
P_HTM[1914]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1915]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi dhammakathiko, ime panaññe bhikkhū na dhammakathikā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1916]="*So tena dhammakathikattena attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1917]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.* **";
P_HTM[1918]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1919]="*‘na kho dhammakathikattena lobhadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, dosadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, mohadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.* **";
P_HTM[1920]="*No cepi dhammakathiko hoti;* **";
P_HTM[1921]="*so ca hoti dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tattha pujjo, so tattha pāsaṃso’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1922]="*So paṭipadaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā tena dhammakathikattena nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1923]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (9)* **";
P_HTM[1924]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso āraññiko hoti.**who dwells in the wilderness …*";
P_HTM[1925]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1926]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi āraññiko ime panaññe bhikkhū na āraññikā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1927]="*So tena āraññikattena attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1928]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.* **";
P_HTM[1929]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1930]="*‘na kho āraññikattena lobhadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, dosadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, mohadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.* **";
P_HTM[1931]="*No cepi āraññiko hoti;* **";
P_HTM[1932]="*so ca hoti dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tattha pujjo, so tattha pāsaṃso’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1933]="*So paṭipadaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā tena āraññikattena nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1934]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (10)* **";
P_HTM[1935]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso paṃsukūliko hoti.**who is a rag robe wearer …*";
P_HTM[1936]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1937]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi paṃsukūliko, ime panaññe bhikkhū na paṃsukūlikā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1938]="*So tena paṃsukūlikattena attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1939]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.* **";
P_HTM[1940]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1941]="*‘na kho paṃsukūlikattena lobhadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, dosadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, mohadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.* **";
P_HTM[1942]="*No cepi paṃsukūliko hoti;* **";
P_HTM[1943]="*so ca hoti dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tattha pujjo, so tattha pāsaṃso’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1944]="*So paṭipadaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā tena paṃsukūlikattena nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1945]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (11)* **";
P_HTM[1946]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso piṇḍapātiko hoti.**who eats only alms-food …*";
P_HTM[1947]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1948]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi piṇḍapātiko, ime panaññe bhikkhū na piṇḍapātikā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1949]="*So tena piṇḍapātikattena attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1950]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.* **";
P_HTM[1951]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1952]="*‘na kho piṇḍapātikattena lobhadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, dosadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, mohadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.* **";
P_HTM[1953]="*No cepi piṇḍapātiko hoti;* **";
P_HTM[1954]="*so ca hoti dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tattha pujjo, so tattha pāsaṃso’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1955]="*So paṭipadaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā tena piṇḍapātikattena nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1956]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (12)* **";
P_HTM[1957]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso rukkhamūliko hoti.**who stays at the root of a tree …*";
P_HTM[1958]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1959]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi rukkhamūliko, ime panaññe bhikkhū na rukkhamūlikā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1960]="*So tena rukkhamūlikattena attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1961]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.* **";
P_HTM[1962]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[1963]="*‘na kho rukkhamūlikattena lobhadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, dosadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, mohadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.* **";
P_HTM[1964]="*No cepi rukkhamūliko hoti;* **";
P_HTM[1965]="*so ca hoti dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tattha pujjo, so tattha pāsaṃso’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1966]="*So paṭipadaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā tena rukkhamūlikattena nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[1967]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (13)* **";
P_HTM[1968]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso sosāniko hoti … pe …**who stays in a charnel ground …*";
P_HTM[1969]="*abbhokāsiko hoti …**who stays in the open air …*";
P_HTM[1970]="*nesajjiko hoti … pe …**who never lies down …*";
P_HTM[1971]="*yathāsanthatiko hoti … pe …**who sleeps wherever they lay their mat...*";
P_HTM[1972]="*ekāsaniko hoti.**who eats in one sitting per day.*";
P_HTM[1973]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**They reflect:*";
P_HTM[1974]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi ekāsaniko, ime panaññe bhikkhū na ekāsanikā’ti.**‘I eat in one sitting per day, unlike these other mendicants.’*";
P_HTM[1975]="*So tena ekāsanikattena attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.**And they glorify themselves and put others down on account of that.*";
P_HTM[1976]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.**This too is a quality of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1977]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:**A good person reflects:*";
P_HTM[1978]="*‘na kho ekāsanikattena lobhadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, dosadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, mohadhammā vā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.**‘It’s not because of eating in one sitting per day that thoughts of greed, hate, or delusion come to an end.*";
P_HTM[1979]="*No cepi ekāsaniko hoti;**Even if someone eats in more than one sitting per day,*";
P_HTM[1980]="*so ca hoti dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tattha pujjo, so tattha pāsaṃso’ti.**if they practice in line with the teaching, practice properly, and live in line with the teaching, they are worthy of honor and praise for that.’*";
P_HTM[1981]="*So paṭipadaṃyeva antaraṃ karitvā tena ekāsanikattena nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.**Keeping only the practice close to their heart, they don’t glorify themselves and put others down on account of their eating in one sitting per day.*";
P_HTM[1982]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (14–18.)**This too is a quality of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1983]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, take a bad person who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[1984]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**They reflect:*";
P_HTM[1985]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi paṭhamajjhānasamāpattiyā lābhī, ime panaññe bhikkhū paṭhamajjhānasamāpattiyā na lābhino’ti.**‘I have attained the first absorption, unlike these other mendicants.’*";
P_HTM[1986]="*So tāya paṭhamajjhānasamāpattiyā attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.**And they glorify themselves and put others down on account of that.*";
P_HTM[1987]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.**This too is a quality of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[1988]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:**A good person reflects:*";
P_HTM[1989]="*‘paṭhamajjhānasamāpattiyāpi kho atammayatā vuttā bhagavatā.**‘The Buddha has spoken of not identifying even with the attainment of the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[1990]="*Yena yena hi maññanti tato taṃ hoti aññathā’ti.**For whatever they think it is, it turns out to be something else.’*";
P_HTM[1991]="*So atammayataññeva antaraṃ karitvā tāya paṭhamajjhānasamāpattiyā nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.**Keeping only non-identification close to their heart, they don’t glorify themselves and put others down on account of their attainment of the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[1992]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (19)**This too is a quality of a good person.*";
P_HTM[1993]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, take a bad person who, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, enters and remains in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[1994]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[1995]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[1996]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**They reflect:*";
P_HTM[1997]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi catutthajjhānasamāpattiyā lābhī, ime panaññe bhikkhū catutthajjhānasamāpattiyā na lābhino’ti.**‘I have attained the fourth absorption, unlike these other mendicants.’*";
P_HTM[1998]="*So tāya catutthajjhānasamāpattiyā attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.**And they glorify themselves and put others down on account of that.*";
P_HTM[1999]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.**This too is a quality of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[2000]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:**A good person reflects:*";
P_HTM[2001]="*‘catutthajjhānasamāpattiyāpi kho atammayatā vuttā bhagavatā.**‘The Buddha has spoken of not identifying even with the attainment of the fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[2002]="*Yena yena hi maññanti tato taṃ hoti aññathā’ti.**For whatever they think it is, it turns out to be something else.’*";
P_HTM[2003]="*So atammayataññeva antaraṃ karitvā tāya catutthajjhānasamāpattiyā nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.**Keeping only non-identification close to their heart, they don’t glorify themselves and put others down on account of their attainment of the fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[2004]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (20–22.)**This too is a quality of a good person.*";
P_HTM[2005]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, take someone who, going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, enters and remains in the dimension of infinite space …*";
P_HTM[2006]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[2007]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi ākāsānañcāyatanasamāpattiyā lābhī, ime panaññe bhikkhū ākāsānañcāyatanasamāpattiyā na lābhino’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2008]="*So tāya ākāsānañcāyatanasamāpattiyā attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[2009]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.* **";
P_HTM[2010]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[2011]="*‘ākāsānañcāyatanasamāpattiyāpi kho atammayatā vuttā bhagavatā.* **";
P_HTM[2012]="*Yena yena hi maññanti tato taṃ hoti aññathā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2013]="*So atammayataññeva antaraṃ karitvā tāya ākāsānañcāyatanasamāpattiyā nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[2014]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (23)* **";
P_HTM[2015]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**the dimension of infinite consciousness …*";
P_HTM[2016]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[2017]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi viññāṇañcāyatanasamāpattiyā lābhī, ime panaññe bhikkhū viññāṇañcāyatanasamāpattiyā na lābhino’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2018]="*So tāya viññāṇañcāyatanasamāpattiyā attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[2019]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.* **";
P_HTM[2020]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[2021]="*‘viññāṇañcāyatanasamāpattiyāpi kho atammayatā vuttā bhagavatā.* **";
P_HTM[2022]="*Yena yena hi maññanti tato taṃ hoti aññathā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2023]="*So atammayataññeva antaraṃ karitvā tāya viññāṇañcāyatanasamāpattiyā nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[2024]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (24)* **";
P_HTM[2025]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**the dimension of nothingness …*";
P_HTM[2026]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[2027]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi ākiñcaññāyatanasamāpattiyā lābhī, ime panaññe bhikkhū ākiñcaññāyatanasamāpattiyā na lābhino’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2028]="*So tāya ākiñcaññāyatanasamāpattiyā attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[2029]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.* **";
P_HTM[2030]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:* **";
P_HTM[2031]="*‘ākiñcaññāyatanasamāpattiyāpi kho atammayatā vuttā bhagavatā.* **";
P_HTM[2032]="*Yena yena hi maññanti tato taṃ hoti aññathā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2033]="*So atammayataññeva antaraṃ karitvā tāya ākiñcaññāyatanasamāpattiyā nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[2034]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (25)* **";
P_HTM[2035]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, asappuriso sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[2036]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**They reflect:*";
P_HTM[2037]="*‘ahaṃ khomhi nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasamāpattiyā lābhī, ime panaññe bhikkhū nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasamāpattiyā na lābhino’ti.**‘I have attained the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, unlike these other mendicants.’*";
P_HTM[2038]="*So tāya nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasamāpattiyā attānukkaṃseti, paraṃ vambheti.**And they glorify themselves and put others down on account of that.*";
P_HTM[2039]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, asappurisadhammo.**This too is a quality of a bad person.*";
P_HTM[2040]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, iti paṭisañcikkhati:**A good person reflects:*";
P_HTM[2041]="*‘nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasamāpattiyāpi kho atammayatā vuttā bhagavatā.**‘The Buddha has spoken of not identifying even with the attainment of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[2042]="*Yena yena hi maññanti tato taṃ hoti aññathā’ti.**For whatever they think it is, it turns out to be something else.’*";
P_HTM[2043]="*So atammayataññeva antaraṃ karitvā tāya nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasamāpattiyā nevattānukkaṃseti, na paraṃ vambheti.**Keeping only non-identification close to their heart, they don’t glorify themselves and put others down on account of their attainment of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[2044]="*Ayampi, bhikkhave, sappurisadhammo. (26)**This too is a quality of a good person.*";
P_HTM[2045]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, sappuriso sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati. Paññāya cassa disvā āsavā parikkhīṇā honti.**Furthermore, take a good person who, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, enters and remains in the cessation of perception and feeling. And, having seen with wisdom, their defilements come to an end.*";
P_HTM[2046]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu na kiñci maññati, na kuhiñci maññati, na kenaci maññatī”ti. (27)**This is a mendicant who does not identify with anything, does not identify regarding anything, does not identify through anything.”*";
P_HTM[2047]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2048]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2049]="*Sappurisasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2050]="*114. Sevitabbāsevitabbasutta**What Should and Should Not Be Cultivated*";
P_HTM[2051]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2052]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[2053]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2054]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[2055]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2056]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2057]="*“sevitabbāsevitabbaṃ vo, bhikkhave, dhammapariyāyaṃ desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you an exposition of the teaching on what should and should not be cultivated.*";
P_HTM[2058]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[2059]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2060]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2061]="*“Kāyasamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**“I say that there are two kinds of bodily behavior:*";
P_HTM[2062]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2063]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ kāyasamācāraṃ.**And each of these is a kind of behavior.*";
P_HTM[2064]="*Vacīsamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two kinds of verbal behavior:*";
P_HTM[2065]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2066]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ vacīsamācāraṃ.**And each of these is a kind of behavior.*";
P_HTM[2067]="*Manosamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two kinds of mental behavior:*";
P_HTM[2068]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2069]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ manosamācāraṃ.**And each of these is a kind of behavior.*";
P_HTM[2070]="*Cittuppādampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two ways of giving rise to a thought:*";
P_HTM[2071]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2072]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ cittuppādaṃ.**And each of these is a way of giving rise to a thought.*";
P_HTM[2073]="*Saññāpaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two ways of acquiring perception:*";
P_HTM[2074]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2075]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ saññāpaṭilābhaṃ.**And each of these is a way of acquiring perception.*";
P_HTM[2076]="*Diṭṭhipaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two ways of acquiring views:*";
P_HTM[2077]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2078]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ diṭṭhipaṭilābhaṃ.**And each of these is a way of acquiring views.*";
P_HTM[2079]="*Attabhāvapaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two ways of reincarnating:*";
P_HTM[2080]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2081]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ attabhāvapaṭilābhan”ti.**And each of these is a way of reincarnating.”*";
P_HTM[2082]="*Evaṃ vutte āyasmā sāriputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Sāriputta said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2083]="*“imassa kho ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa, vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa, evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmi.**“Sir, this is how I understand the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement.*";
P_HTM[2084]="*‘Kāyasamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of bodily behavior:*";
P_HTM[2085]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2086]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ kāyasamācāran’ti—**And each of these is a kind of bodily behavior.’*";
P_HTM[2087]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.**That’s what the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[2088]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did he say it?*";
P_HTM[2089]="*Yathārūpaṃ, bhante, kāyasamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti, evarūpo kāyasamācāro na sevitabbo;**You should not cultivate the kind of bodily behavior which causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2090]="*yathārūpañca kho, bhante, kāyasamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, evarūpo kāyasamācāro sevitabbo.**And you should cultivate the kind of bodily behavior which causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2091]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, kāyasamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti?**And what kind of bodily behavior causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline?*";
P_HTM[2092]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco pāṇātipātī hoti luddo lohitapāṇi hatappahate niviṭṭho adayāpanno pāṇabhūtesu;**It’s when someone kills living creatures. They’re violent, bloody-handed, a hardened killer, merciless to living beings.*";
P_HTM[2093]="*adinnādāyī kho pana hoti, yaṃ taṃ parassa paravittūpakaraṇaṃ gāmagataṃ vā araññagataṃ vā taṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādātā hoti;**They steal. With the intention to commit theft, they take the wealth or belongings of others from village or wilderness.*";
P_HTM[2094]="*kāmesumicchācārī kho pana hoti, yā tā māturakkhitā piturakkhitā mātāpiturakkhitā bhāturakkhitā bhaginirakkhitā ñātirakkhitā gottarakkhitā dhammarakkhitā sassāmikā saparidaṇḍā antamaso mālāguḷaparikkhittāpi tathārūpāsu cārittaṃ āpajjitā hoti—**They commit sexual misconduct. They have sexual relations with women who have their mother, father, both mother and father, brother, sister, relatives, or clan as guardian. They have sexual relations with a woman who is protected on principle, or who has a husband, or whose violation is punishable by law, or even one who has been garlanded as a token of betrothal.*";
P_HTM[2095]="*evarūpaṃ, bhante, kāyasamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti.**That kind of bodily behavior causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2096]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, kāyasamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti?**And what kind of bodily behavior causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow?*";
P_HTM[2097]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti nihitadaṇḍo nihitasattho, lajjī dayāpanno sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī viharati;**It’s when someone gives up killing living creatures. They renounce the rod and the sword. They’re scrupulous and kind, living full of compassion for all living beings.*";
P_HTM[2098]="*adinnādānaṃ pahāya adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti, yaṃ taṃ parassa paravittūpakaraṇaṃ gāmagataṃ vā araññagataṃ vā taṃ nādinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādātā hoti;**They give up stealing. They don’t, with the intention to commit theft, take the wealth or belongings of others from village or wilderness.*";
P_HTM[2099]="*kāmesumicchācāraṃ pahāya kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato hoti, yā tā māturakkhitā piturakkhitā mātāpiturakkhitā bhāturakkhitā bhaginirakkhitā ñātirakkhitā gottarakkhitā dhammarakkhitā sassāmikā saparidaṇḍā antamaso mālāguḷaparikkhittāpi tathārūpāsu na cārittaṃ āpajjitā hoti—**They give up sexual misconduct. They don’t have sexual relations with women who have their mother, father, both mother and father, brother, sister, relatives, or clan as guardian. They don’t have sexual relations with a woman who is protected on principle, or who has a husband, or whose violation is punishable by law, or even one who has been garlanded as a token of betrothal.*";
P_HTM[2100]="*evarūpaṃ, bhante, kāyasamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.**That kind of bodily behavior causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2101]="*‘Kāyasamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of bodily behavior:*";
P_HTM[2102]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2103]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ kāyasamācāran’ti—**And each of these is a kind of bodily behavior.’*";
P_HTM[2104]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what the Buddha said, and this is why he said it.*";
P_HTM[2105]="*‘Vacīsamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of verbal behavior:*";
P_HTM[2106]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2107]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ vacīsamācāran’ti—**And each of these is a kind of verbal behavior.’*";
P_HTM[2108]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.**That’s what the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[2109]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did he say it?*";
P_HTM[2110]="*Yathārūpaṃ, bhante, vacīsamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti, evarūpo vacīsamācāro na sevitabbo;**You should not cultivate the kind of verbal behavior which causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2111]="*yathārūpañca kho, bhante, vacīsamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti evarūpo vacīsamācāro sevitabbo.**And you should cultivate the kind of verbal behavior which causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2112]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, vacīsamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti?**And what kind of verbal behavior causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline?*";
P_HTM[2113]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco musāvādī hoti. Sabhāgato vā parisāgato vā ñātimajjhagato vā pūgamajjhagato vā rājakulamajjhagato vā abhinīto sakkhipuṭṭho: ‘ehambho purisa, yaṃ jānāsi taṃ vadehī’ti so ajānaṃ vā āha: ‘jānāmī’ti, jānaṃ vā āha: ‘na jānāmī’ti; apassaṃ vā āha: ‘passāmī’ti, passaṃ vā āha: ‘na passāmī’ti—iti attahetu vā parahetu vā āmisakiñcikkhahetu vā sampajānamusā bhāsitā hoti;**It’s when someone lies. They’re summoned to a council, an assembly, a family meeting, a guild, or to the royal court, and asked to bear witness: ‘Please, mister, say what you know.’ Not knowing, they say ‘I know.’ Knowing, they say ‘I don’t know.’ Not seeing, they say ‘I see.’ And seeing, they say ‘I don’t see.’ So they deliberately lie for the sake of themselves or another, or for some trivial worldly reason.*";
P_HTM[2114]="*pisuṇavāco kho pana hoti, ito sutvā amutra akkhātā imesaṃ bhedāya, amutra vā sutvā imesaṃ akkhātā amūsaṃ bhedāya—iti samaggānaṃ vā bhettā, bhinnānaṃ vā anuppadātā, vaggārāmo, vaggarato, vagganandī, vaggakaraṇiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā hoti;**They speak divisively. They repeat in one place what they heard in another so as to divide people against each other. And so they divide those who are harmonious, supporting division, delighting in division, loving division, speaking words that promote division.*";
P_HTM[2115]="*pharusavāco kho pana hoti, yā sā vācā kaṇḍakā kakkasā pharusā parakaṭukā parābhisajjanī kodhasāmantā asamādhisaṃvattanikā, tathārūpiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā hoti;**They speak harshly. They use the kinds of words that are cruel, nasty, hurtful, offensive, bordering on anger, not leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[2116]="*samphappalāpī kho pana hoti akālavādī abhūtavādī anatthavādī adhammavādī avinayavādī, anidhānavatiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā hoti akālena anapadesaṃ apariyantavatiṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ—**They talk nonsense. Their speech is untimely, and is neither factual nor beneficial. It has nothing to do with the teaching or the training. Their words have no value, and are untimely, unreasonable, rambling, and pointless.*";
P_HTM[2117]="*evarūpaṃ, bhante, vacīsamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti.**That kind of verbal behavior causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2118]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, vacīsamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti?**And what kind of verbal behavior causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow?*";
P_HTM[2119]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco musāvādaṃ pahāya musāvādā paṭivirato hoti sabhāgato vā parisāgato vā ñātimajjhagato vā pūgamajjhagato vā rājakulamajjhagato vā abhinīto sakkhipuṭṭho: ‘ehambho purisa, yaṃ jānāsi taṃ vadehī’ti so ajānaṃ vā āha: ‘na jānāmī’ti, jānaṃ vā āha: ‘jānāmī’ti, apassaṃ vā āha: ‘na passāmī’ti, passaṃ vā āha: ‘passāmī’ti—iti attahetu vā parahetu vā āmisakiñcikkhahetu vā na sampajānamusā bhāsitā hoti;**It’s when a certain person gives up lying. They’re summoned to a council, an assembly, a family meeting, a guild, or to the royal court, and asked to bear witness: ‘Please, mister, say what you know.’ Not knowing, they say ‘I don’t know.’ Knowing, they say ‘I know.’ Not seeing, they say ‘I don’t see.’ And seeing, they say ‘I see.’ So they don’t deliberately lie for the sake of themselves or another, or for some trivial worldly reason.*";
P_HTM[2120]="*pisuṇaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti, ito sutvā na amutra akkhātā imesaṃ bhedāya, amutra vā sutvā na imesaṃ akkhātā amūsaṃ bhedāya—iti bhinnānaṃ vā sandhātā sahitānaṃ vā anuppadātā samaggārāmo samaggarato samagganandī samaggakaraṇiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā hoti;**They give up divisive speech. They don’t repeat in one place what they heard in another so as to divide people against each other. Instead, they reconcile those who are divided, supporting unity, delighting in harmony, loving harmony, speaking words that promote harmony.*";
P_HTM[2121]="*pharusaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti, yā sā vācā nelā kaṇṇasukhā pemanīyā hadayaṅgamā porī bahujanakantā bahujanamanāpā tathārūpiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā hoti;**They give up harsh speech. They speak in a way that’s mellow, pleasing to the ear, lovely, going to the heart, polite, likable and agreeable to the people.*";
P_HTM[2122]="*samphappalāpaṃ pahāya samphappalāpā paṭivirato hoti kālavādī bhūtavādī atthavādī dhammavādī vinayavādī, nidhānavatiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā hoti kālena sāpadesaṃ pariyantavatiṃ atthasaṃhitaṃ—**They give up talking nonsense. Their words are timely, true, and meaningful, in line with the teaching and training. They say things at the right time which are valuable, reasonable, succinct, and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[2123]="*evarūpaṃ, bhante, vacīsamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.**That kind of verbal behavior causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2124]="*‘Vacīsamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of verbal behavior:*";
P_HTM[2125]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2126]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ vacīsamācāran’ti—**And each of these is a kind of verbal behavior.’*";
P_HTM[2127]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what the Buddha said, and this is why he said it.*";
P_HTM[2128]="*‘Manosamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of mental behavior:*";
P_HTM[2129]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2130]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ manosamācāran’ti—**And each of these is a kind of mental behavior.’*";
P_HTM[2131]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.**That’s what the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[2132]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did he say it?*";
P_HTM[2133]="*Yathārūpaṃ, bhante, manosamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpo manosamācāro na sevitabbo;**You should not cultivate the kind of mental behavior which causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2134]="*yathārūpañca kho, bhante, manosamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti evarūpo manosamācāro sevitabbo.**And you should cultivate the kind of mental behavior which causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2135]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, manosamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti?**And what kind of mental behavior causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline?*";
P_HTM[2136]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco abhijjhālu hoti, yaṃ taṃ parassa paravittūpakaraṇaṃ taṃ abhijjhātā hoti: ‘aho vata yaṃ parassa taṃ mamassā’ti;**It’s when someone is covetous. They covet the wealth and belongings of others: ‘Oh, if only their belongings were mine!’*";
P_HTM[2137]="*byāpannacitto kho pana hoti paduṭṭhamanasaṅkappo: ‘ime sattā haññantu vā vajjhantu vā ucchijjantu vā vinassantu vā mā vā ahesun’ti—**They have ill will and hateful intentions: ‘May these sentient beings be killed, slaughtered, slain, destroyed, or annihilated!’*";
P_HTM[2138]="*evarūpaṃ, bhante, manosamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti.**That kind of mental behavior causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2139]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, manosamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti?**And what kind of mental behavior causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow?*";
P_HTM[2140]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco anabhijjhālu hoti, yaṃ taṃ parassa paravittūpakaraṇaṃ taṃ nābhijjhātā hoti: ‘aho vata yaṃ parassa taṃ mamassā’ti;**It’s when someone is content. They don’t covet the wealth and belongings of others: ‘Oh, if only their belongings were mine!’*";
P_HTM[2141]="*abyāpannacitto kho pana hoti appaduṭṭhamanasaṅkappo: ‘ime sattā averā abyābajjhā anīghā sukhī attānaṃ pariharantū’ti—**They have a kind heart and loving intentions: ‘May these sentient beings live free of enmity and ill will, untroubled and happy!’*";
P_HTM[2142]="*evarūpaṃ, bhante, manosamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.**That kind of mental behavior causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2143]="*‘Manosamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of mental behavior:*";
P_HTM[2144]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2145]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ manosamācāran’ti—**And each of these is a kind of mental behavior.’*";
P_HTM[2146]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what the Buddha said, and this is why he said it.*";
P_HTM[2147]="*‘Cittuppādampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two ways of giving rise to a thought:*";
P_HTM[2148]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2149]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ cittuppādan’ti—**And each of these is a way of giving rise to a thought.’*";
P_HTM[2150]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.**That’s what the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[2151]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did he say it?*";
P_HTM[2152]="*Yathārūpaṃ, bhante, cittuppādaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpo cittuppādo na sevitabbo;**You should not cultivate the way of giving rise to a thought which causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2153]="*yathārūpañca kho, bhante, cittuppādaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti evarūpo cittuppādo sevitabbo.**And you should cultivate the way of giving rise to a thought which causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2154]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, cittuppādaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti?**And what way of giving rise to a thought causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline?*";
P_HTM[2155]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco abhijjhālu hoti, abhijjhāsahagatena cetasā viharati;**It’s when someone is covetous, and lives with their heart full of covetousness.*";
P_HTM[2156]="*byāpādavā hoti, byāpādasahagatena cetasā viharati;**They are malicious, and live with their heart full of ill will.*";
P_HTM[2157]="*vihesavā hoti, vihesāsahagatena cetasā viharati—**They’re hurtful, and live with their heart intent on harm.*";
P_HTM[2158]="*evarūpaṃ, bhante, cittuppādaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti.**That way of giving rise to a thought causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2159]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, cittuppādaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti?**And what way of giving rise to a thought causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow?*";
P_HTM[2160]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco anabhijjhālu hoti, anabhijjhāsahagatena cetasā viharati;**It’s when someone is content, and lives with their heart full of contentment.*";
P_HTM[2161]="*abyāpādavā hoti, abyāpādasahagatena cetasā viharati;**They have good will, and live with their heart full of good will.*";
P_HTM[2162]="*avihesavā hoti, avihesāsahagatena cetasā viharati—**They’re kind, and live with their heart full of kindness.*";
P_HTM[2163]="*evarūpaṃ, bhante, cittuppādaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.**That way of giving rise to a thought causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2164]="*‘Cittuppādampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two ways of giving rise to a thought:*";
P_HTM[2165]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2166]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ cittuppādan’ti—**And each of these is a way of giving rise to a thought.’*";
P_HTM[2167]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what the Buddha said, and this is why he said it.*";
P_HTM[2168]="*‘Saññāpaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two ways of acquiring perception:*";
P_HTM[2169]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2170]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ saññāpaṭilābhan’ti—**And each of these is a way of acquiring perception.’*";
P_HTM[2171]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.**That’s what the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[2172]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did he say it?*";
P_HTM[2173]="*Yathārūpaṃ, bhante, saññāpaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpo saññāpaṭilābho na sevitabbo;**You should not cultivate the way of acquiring perception which causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2174]="*yathārūpañca kho, bhante, saññāpaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti evarūpo saññāpaṭilābho sevitabbo.**And you should cultivate the way of acquiring perception which causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2175]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, saññāpaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti?**And what way of acquiring perception causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline?*";
P_HTM[2176]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco abhijjhālu hoti, abhijjhāsahagatāya saññāya viharati;**It’s when someone is covetous, and lives with their perception full of covetousness.*";
P_HTM[2177]="*byāpādavā hoti, byāpādasahagatāya saññāya viharati;**They are malicious, and live with their perception full of ill will.*";
P_HTM[2178]="*vihesavā hoti, vihesāsahagatāya saññāya viharati—**They’re hurtful, and live with their perception intent on harm.*";
P_HTM[2179]="*evarūpaṃ, bhante, saññāpaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti.**That way of acquiring perception causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2180]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, saññāpaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti?**And what way of acquiring perception causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow?*";
P_HTM[2181]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco anabhijjhālu hoti, anabhijjhāsahagatāya saññāya viharati;**It’s when someone is content, and lives with their perception full of contentment.*";
P_HTM[2182]="*abyāpādavā hoti, abyāpādasahagatāya saññāya viharati;**They have good will, and live with their perception full of good will.*";
P_HTM[2183]="*avihesavā hoti, avihesāsahagatāya saññāya viharati—**They’re kind, and live with their perception full of kindness.*";
P_HTM[2184]="*evarūpaṃ, bhante, saññāpaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.**That way of acquiring perception causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2185]="*‘Saññāpaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two ways of acquiring perception:*";
P_HTM[2186]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2187]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ saññāpaṭilābhan’ti—**And each of these is a way of acquiring perception.’*";
P_HTM[2188]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what the Buddha said, and this is why he said it.*";
P_HTM[2189]="*‘Diṭṭhipaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two ways of acquiring views:*";
P_HTM[2190]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2191]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ diṭṭhipaṭilābhan’ti—**And each of these is a way of acquiring views.’*";
P_HTM[2192]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.**That’s what the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[2193]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did he say it?*";
P_HTM[2194]="*Yathārūpaṃ, bhante, diṭṭhipaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpo diṭṭhipaṭilābho na sevitabbo;**You should not cultivate the way of acquiring views which causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2195]="*yathārūpañca kho, bhante, diṭṭhipaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti—evarūpo diṭṭhipaṭilābho sevitabbo.**And you should cultivate the way of acquiring views which causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2196]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, diṭṭhipaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti?**And what way of acquiring views causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline?*";
P_HTM[2197]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco evaṃdiṭṭhiko hoti:**It’s when someone has such a view:*";
P_HTM[2198]="*‘natthi dinnaṃ, natthi yiṭṭhaṃ, natthi hutaṃ, natthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko, natthi ayaṃ loko, natthi paro loko, natthi mātā, natthi pitā, natthi sattā opapātikā, natthi loke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sammaggatā sammāpaṭipannā ye imañca lokaṃ parañca lokaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedentī’ti—**‘There’s no meaning in giving, sacrifice, or offerings. There’s no fruit or result of good and bad deeds. There’s no afterlife. There are no duties to mother and father. No beings are reborn spontaneously. And there’s no ascetic or brahmin who is well attained and practiced, and who describes the afterlife after realizing it with their own insight.’*";
P_HTM[2199]="*evarūpaṃ, bhante, diṭṭhipaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti.**That way of acquiring views causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2200]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, diṭṭhipaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti?**And what way of acquiring views causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow?*";
P_HTM[2201]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco evaṃdiṭṭhiko hoti:**It’s when someone has such a view:*";
P_HTM[2202]="*‘atthi dinnaṃ, atthi yiṭṭhaṃ, atthi hutaṃ, atthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko, atthi ayaṃ loko, atthi paro loko, atthi mātā, atthi pitā, atthi sattā opapātikā, atthi loke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sammaggatā sammāpaṭipannā ye imañca lokaṃ parañca lokaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedentī’ti—**‘There is meaning in giving, sacrifice, and offerings. There are fruits and results of good and bad deeds. There is an afterlife. There are duties to mother and father. There are beings reborn spontaneously. And there are ascetics and brahmins who are well attained and practiced, and who describe the afterlife after realizing it with their own insight.’*";
P_HTM[2203]="*evarūpaṃ, bhante, diṭṭhipaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.**That way of acquiring views causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2204]="*‘Diṭṭhipaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two ways of acquiring views:*";
P_HTM[2205]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2206]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ diṭṭhipaṭilābhan’ti—**And each of these is a way of acquiring views.’*";
P_HTM[2207]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what the Buddha said, and this is why he said it.*";
P_HTM[2208]="*‘Attabhāvapaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two ways of reincarnating:*";
P_HTM[2209]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2210]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ attabhāvapaṭilābhan’ti—**And each of these is a way of reincarnating.’*";
P_HTM[2211]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.**That’s what the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[2212]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did he say it?*";
P_HTM[2213]="*Yathārūpaṃ, bhante, attabhāvapaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti—**The way of reincarnating that causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline:*";
P_HTM[2214]="*evarūpo attabhāvapaṭilābho na sevitabbo;**you should not cultivate that way of reincarnating.*";
P_HTM[2215]="*yathārūpañca kho, bhante, attabhāvapaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti—**The way of reincarnating that causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow:*";
P_HTM[2216]="*evarūpo attabhāvapaṭilābho sevitabbo.**you should cultivate that way of reincarnating.*";
P_HTM[2217]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, bhante, attabhāvapaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti?**And what way of reincarnating causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline?*";
P_HTM[2218]="*Sabyābajjhaṃ, bhante, attabhāvapaṭilābhaṃ abhinibbattayato apariniṭṭhitabhāvāya akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti;**Generating rebirth in a hurtful reincarnation, which because of its unpreparedness causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2219]="*abyābajjhaṃ, bhante, attabhāvapaṭilābhaṃ abhinibbattayato pariniṭṭhitabhāvāya akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.**And what way of reincarnating causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow? Generating rebirth in a pleasing reincarnation, which because of its preparedness causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2220]="*‘Attabhāvapaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two ways of reincarnating:*";
P_HTM[2221]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2222]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ attabhāvapaṭilābhan’ti—**And each of these is a way of reincarnating.’*";
P_HTM[2223]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what the Buddha said, and this is why he said it.*";
P_HTM[2224]="*Imassa kho ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa, vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa, evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmī”ti.**Sir, that’s how I understand the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement.”*";
P_HTM[2225]="*“Sādhu sādhu, sāriputta.**“Good, good, Sāriputta!*";
P_HTM[2226]="*Sādhu kho tvaṃ, sāriputta, imassa mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa, vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa, evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāsi.**It’s good that you understand the detailed meaning of my brief statement in this way.”*";
P_HTM[2227]="*‘Kāyasamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**And the Buddha went on to repeat and endorse Venerable Sāriputta’s explanation in full. Then he went on to explain further:*";
P_HTM[2228]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;* **";
P_HTM[2229]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ kāyasamācāran’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2230]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ mayā.* **";
P_HTM[2231]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[2232]="*Yathārūpaṃ, sāriputta, kāyasamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpo kāyasamācāro na sevitabbo;* **";
P_HTM[2233]="*yathārūpañca kho, sāriputta, kāyasamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti—* **";
P_HTM[2234]="*evarūpo kāyasamācāro sevitabbo.* **";
P_HTM[2235]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, sāriputta, kāyasamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti?* **";
P_HTM[2236]="*Idha, sāriputta, ekacco pāṇātipātī hoti luddo lohitapāṇi hatappahate niviṭṭho adayāpanno pāṇabhūtesu;* **";
P_HTM[2237]="*adinnādāyī kho pana hoti, yaṃ taṃ parassa paravittūpakaraṇaṃ gāmagataṃ vā araññagataṃ vā taṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādātā hoti;* **";
P_HTM[2238]="*kāmesumicchācārī kho pana hoti, yā tā māturakkhitā piturakkhitā mātāpiturakkhitā bhāturakkhitā bhaginirakkhitā ñātirakkhitā gottarakkhitā dhammarakkhitā sassāmikā saparidaṇḍā antamaso mālāguḷaparikkhittāpi tathārūpāsu cārittaṃ āpajjitā hoti—* **";
P_HTM[2239]="*evarūpaṃ, sāriputta, kāyasamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti.* **";
P_HTM[2240]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, sāriputta, kāyasamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti?* **";
P_HTM[2241]="*Idha, sāriputta, ekacco pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti nihitadaṇḍo nihitasattho, lajjī dayāpanno sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī viharati;* **";
P_HTM[2242]="*adinnādānaṃ pahāya adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti, yaṃ taṃ parassa paravittūpakaraṇaṃ gāmagataṃ vā araññagataṃ vā taṃ nādinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādātā hoti;* **";
P_HTM[2243]="*kāmesumicchācāraṃ pahāya kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato hoti, yā tā māturakkhitā piturakkhitā mātāpiturakkhitā bhāturakkhitā bhaginirakkhitā ñātirakkhitā gottarakkhitā dhammarakkhitā sassāmikā saparidaṇḍā antamaso mālāguḷaparikkhittāpi tathārūpāsu na cārittaṃ āpajjitā hoti—* **";
P_HTM[2244]="*evarūpaṃ, sāriputta, kāyasamācāraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.* **";
P_HTM[2245]="*‘Kāyasamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—* **";
P_HTM[2246]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;* **";
P_HTM[2247]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ kāyasamācāran’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2248]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ mayā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2249]="*Vacīsamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2250]="*manosamācārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2251]="*cittuppādampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2252]="*saññāpaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2253]="*diṭṭhipaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[2254]="*‘Attabhāvapaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—* **";
P_HTM[2255]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;* **";
P_HTM[2256]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ attabhāvapaṭilābhan’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2257]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ mayā.* **";
P_HTM[2258]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[2259]="*Yathārūpaṃ, sāriputta, attabhāvapaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpo attabhāvapaṭilābho na sevitabbo;* **";
P_HTM[2260]="*yathārūpañca kho, sāriputta, attabhāvapaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti—* **";
P_HTM[2261]="*evarūpo attabhāvapaṭilābho sevitabbo.* **";
P_HTM[2262]="*Kathaṃrūpaṃ, sāriputta, attabhāvapaṭilābhaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti?* **";
P_HTM[2263]="*Sabyābajjhaṃ, sāriputta, attabhāvapaṭilābhaṃ abhinibbattayato apariniṭṭhitabhāvāya akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti;* **";
P_HTM[2264]="*abyābajjhaṃ, sāriputta, attabhāvapaṭilābhaṃ abhinibbattayato pariniṭṭhitabhāvāya akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti.* **";
P_HTM[2265]="*‘Attabhāvapaṭilābhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—* **";
P_HTM[2266]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;* **";
P_HTM[2267]="*tañca aññamaññaṃ attabhāvapaṭilābhan’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2268]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ mayā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2269]="*Imassa kho, sāriputta, mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo.* **";
P_HTM[2270]="*Cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**“I say that there are two kinds of sight known by the eye:*";
P_HTM[2271]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2272]="*sotaviññeyyaṃ saddampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two kinds of sound known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[2273]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampi;* **";
P_HTM[2274]="*ghānaviññeyyaṃ gandhampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**two kinds of smell known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[2275]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;* **";
P_HTM[2276]="*jivhāviññeyyaṃ rasampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**two kinds of taste known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[2277]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;* **";
P_HTM[2278]="*kāyaviññeyyaṃ phoṭṭhabbampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**two kinds of touch known by the body …*";
P_HTM[2279]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi;* **";
P_HTM[2280]="*manoviññeyyaṃ dhammampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**two kinds of thought known by the mind:*";
P_HTM[2281]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī”ti.**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.”*";
P_HTM[2282]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā sāriputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Sāriputta said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[2283]="*“imassa kho ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa, vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa, evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmi.**“Sir, this is how I understand the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement.*";
P_HTM[2284]="*‘Cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of sight known by the eye:*";
P_HTM[2285]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.’*";
P_HTM[2286]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.**That’s what the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[2287]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did he say it?*";
P_HTM[2288]="*Yathārūpaṃ, bhante, cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpaṃ cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpaṃ na sevitabbaṃ;**You should not cultivate the kind of sight known by the eye which causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2289]="*yathārūpañca kho, bhante, cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti evarūpaṃ cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpaṃ sevitabbaṃ.**And you should cultivate the kind of sight known by the eye which causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2290]="*‘Cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of sight known by the eye:*";
P_HTM[2291]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.’*";
P_HTM[2292]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what the Buddha said, and this is why he said it.*";
P_HTM[2293]="*Sotaviññeyyaṃ saddampāhaṃ, sāriputta … pe …**‘I say that there are two kinds of sound known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[2294]="*evarūpo sotaviññeyyo saddo na sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2295]="*evarūpo sotaviññeyyo saddo sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2296]="*evarūpo ghānaviññeyyo gandho na sevitabbo …**two kinds of smell known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[2297]="*evarūpo ghānaviññeyyo gandho sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2298]="*evarūpo jivhāviññeyyo raso na sevitabbo …**two kinds of taste known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[2299]="*evarūpo jivhāviññeyyo raso sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2300]="*kāyaviññeyyaṃ phoṭṭhabbampāhaṃ, sāriputta …**two kinds of touch known by the body …*";
P_HTM[2301]="*evarūpo kāyaviññeyyo phoṭṭhabbo na sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2302]="*evarūpo kāyaviññeyyo phoṭṭhabbo sevitabbo.* **";
P_HTM[2303]="*‘Manoviññeyyaṃ dhammampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**two kinds of thought known by the mind:*";
P_HTM[2304]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.’*";
P_HTM[2305]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.**That’s what the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[2306]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did he say it?*";
P_HTM[2307]="*Yathārūpaṃ, bhante, manoviññeyyaṃ dhammaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpo manoviññeyyo dhammo na sevitabbo;**You should not cultivate the kind of thought known by the mind which causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2308]="*yathārūpañca kho, bhante, manoviññeyyaṃ dhammaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti evarūpo manoviññeyyo dhammo sevitabbo.**And you should cultivate the kind of thought known by the mind which causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2309]="*‘Manoviññeyyaṃ dhammampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of thought known by the mind:*";
P_HTM[2310]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.’*";
P_HTM[2311]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what the Buddha said, and this is why he said it.*";
P_HTM[2312]="*Imassa kho ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa, vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa, evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmī”ti.**Sir, that’s how I understand the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement.”*";
P_HTM[2313]="*“Sādhu sādhu, sāriputta.**“Good, good, Sāriputta!*";
P_HTM[2314]="*Sādhu kho tvaṃ, sāriputta, imassa mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa, vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa, evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāsi.**It’s good that you understand the detailed meaning of my brief statement in this way.”*";
P_HTM[2315]="*‘Cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**And the Buddha went on to repeat and endorse Venerable Sāriputta’s explanation in full. Then he went on to explain further:*";
P_HTM[2316]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2317]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ mayā.* **";
P_HTM[2318]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[2319]="*Yathārūpaṃ, sāriputta, cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpaṃ cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpaṃ na sevitabbaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[2320]="*yathārūpañca kho, sāriputta, cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti evarūpaṃ cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpaṃ sevitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2321]="*‘Cakkhuviññeyyaṃ rūpampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—* **";
P_HTM[2322]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2323]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ mayā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2324]="*Sotaviññeyyaṃ saddampāhaṃ, sāriputta … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2325]="*evarūpo sotaviññeyyo saddo na sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2326]="*evarūpo sotaviññeyyo saddo sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2327]="*evarūpo ghānaviññeyyo gandho na sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2328]="*evarūpo ghānaviññeyyo gandho sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2329]="*evarūpo jivhāviññeyyo raso na sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2330]="*evarūpo jivhāviññeyyo raso sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2331]="*evarūpo kāyaviññeyyo phoṭṭhabbo na sevitabbo …* **";
