P_HTM[2335]="*evarūpo manoviññeyyo dhammo sevitabbo.* **";
P_HTM[2336]="*‘Manoviññeyyaṃ dhammampāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—* **";
P_HTM[2337]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2338]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ mayā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2339]="*Imassa kho, sāriputta, mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo.* **";
P_HTM[2340]="*Cīvaraṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**“I say that there are two kinds of robes:*";
P_HTM[2341]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampi … pe …**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.*";
P_HTM[2342]="*piṇḍapātaṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta …**I say that there are two kinds of alms-food …*";
P_HTM[2343]="*senāsanaṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta …**lodging …*";
P_HTM[2344]="*gāmampāhaṃ, sāriputta …**village …*";
P_HTM[2345]="*nigamampāhaṃ, sāriputta …**town …*";
P_HTM[2346]="*nagarampāhaṃ, sāriputta …**city …*";
P_HTM[2347]="*janapadampāhaṃ, sāriputta …**country …*";
P_HTM[2348]="*puggalaṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**person:*";
P_HTM[2349]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī”ti.**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.”*";
P_HTM[2350]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā sāriputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Sāriputta said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[2351]="*“imassa kho ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa, vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa, evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmi.**“Sir, this is how I understand the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement.*";
P_HTM[2352]="*‘Cīvaraṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of robes …*";
P_HTM[2353]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2354]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.* **";
P_HTM[2355]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[2356]="*Yathārūpaṃ, bhante, cīvaraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpaṃ cīvaraṃ na sevitabbaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[2357]="*yathārūpañca kho, bhante, cīvaraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti evarūpaṃ cīvaraṃ sevitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2358]="*‘Cīvaraṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—* **";
P_HTM[2359]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2360]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2361]="*Piṇḍapātaṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta … pe …**alms-food …*";
P_HTM[2362]="*evarūpo piṇḍapāto na sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2363]="*evarūpo piṇḍapāto sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2364]="*senāsanaṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta … pe …**lodging …*";
P_HTM[2365]="*evarūpaṃ senāsanaṃ na sevitabbaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2366]="*evarūpaṃ senāsanaṃ sevitabbaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2367]="*gāmampāhaṃ, sāriputta … pe …**village …*";
P_HTM[2368]="*evarūpo gāmo na sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2369]="*evarūpo gāmo sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2370]="*evarūpo nigamo na sevitabbo …**town …*";
P_HTM[2371]="*evarūpo nigamo sevitabbo …* **";
P_HTM[2372]="*evarūpaṃ nagaraṃ na sevitabbaṃ …**city …*";
P_HTM[2373]="*evarūpaṃ nagaraṃ sevitabbaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2374]="*evarūpo janapado na sevitabbo …**country …*";
P_HTM[2375]="*evarūpo janapado sevitabbo.* **";
P_HTM[2376]="*‘Puggalaṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**person:*";
P_HTM[2377]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—**that which you should cultivate, and that which you should not cultivate.’*";
P_HTM[2378]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.**That’s what the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[2379]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did he say it?*";
P_HTM[2380]="*Yathārūpaṃ, bhante, puggalaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpo puggalo na sevitabbo;**You should not cultivate the kind of person who causes unskillful qualities to grow while skillful qualities decline.*";
P_HTM[2381]="*yathārūpañca kho, bhante, puggalaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti evarūpo puggalo sevitabbo.**And you should cultivate the kind of person who causes unskillful qualities to decline while skillful qualities grow.*";
P_HTM[2382]="*‘Puggalaṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of person:*";
P_HTM[2383]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—**those who you should cultivate, and those who you should not cultivate.’*";
P_HTM[2384]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttanti.**That’s what the Buddha said, and this is why he said it.*";
P_HTM[2385]="*Imassa kho ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa, vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmī”ti.**Sir, that’s how I understand the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement.”*";
P_HTM[2386]="*“Sādhu sādhu, sāriputta.**“Good, good, Sāriputta!*";
P_HTM[2387]="*Sādhu kho tvaṃ, sāriputta, imassa mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa, vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāsi.**It’s good that you understand the detailed meaning of my brief statement in this way.”*";
P_HTM[2388]="*‘Cīvaraṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—**And the Buddha went on to repeat and endorse Venerable Sāriputta’s explanation in full. Then he added:*";
P_HTM[2389]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2390]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ mayā.* **";
P_HTM[2391]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[2392]="*Yathārūpaṃ, sāriputta, cīvaraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpaṃ cīvaraṃ na sevitabbaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[2393]="*yathārūpañca kho, sāriputta, cīvaraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti evarūpaṃ cīvaraṃ sevitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2394]="*‘Cīvaraṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—* **";
P_HTM[2395]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2396]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ mayā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2397]="*(Yathā paṭhamaṃ tathā vitthāretabbaṃ)* **";
P_HTM[2398]="*Evarūpo piṇḍapāto …* **";
P_HTM[2399]="*evarūpaṃ senāsanaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2400]="*evarūpo gāmo …* **";
P_HTM[2401]="*evarūpo nigamo …* **";
P_HTM[2402]="*evarūpaṃ nagaraṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2403]="*evarūpo janapado.* **";
P_HTM[2404]="*‘Puggalaṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—* **";
P_HTM[2405]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2406]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ mayā.* **";
P_HTM[2407]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[2408]="*Yathārūpaṃ, sāriputta, puggalaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyanti evarūpo puggalo na sevitabbo;* **";
P_HTM[2409]="*yathārūpañca kho, sāriputta, puggalaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti evarūpo puggalo sevitabbo.* **";
P_HTM[2410]="*‘Puggalaṃpāhaṃ, sāriputta, duvidhena vadāmi—* **";
P_HTM[2411]="*sevitabbampi, asevitabbampī’ti—* **";
P_HTM[2412]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ mayā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2413]="*Imassa kho, sāriputta, mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo.* **";
P_HTM[2414]="*Sabbepi ce, sāriputta, khattiyā imassa mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājāneyyuṃ, sabbesānampissa khattiyānaṃ dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāya.**“If all the aristocrats, brahmins, merchants, and workers were to understand the detailed meaning of my brief statement in this way, it would be for their lasting welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[2415]="*Sabbepi ce, sāriputta, brāhmaṇā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2416]="*sabbepi ce, sāriputta, vessā …* **";
P_HTM[2417]="*sabbepi ce, sāriputta, suddā imassa mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājāneyyuṃ, sabbesānampissa suddānaṃ dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāya.* **";
P_HTM[2418]="*Sadevakopi ce, sāriputta, loko samārako sabrahmako sassamaṇabrāhmaṇī pajā sadevamanussā imassa mayā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājāneyya, sadevakassapissa lokassa samārakassa sabrahmakassa sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā”ti.**If the whole world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—was to understand the detailed meaning of my brief statement in this way, it would be for the whole world’s lasting welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[2419]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2420]="*Attamano āyasmā sāriputto bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Sāriputta was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2421]="*Sevitabbāsevitabbasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2422]="*115. Bahudhātukasutta**Many Elements*";
P_HTM[2423]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2424]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[2425]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2426]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[2427]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2428]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2429]="*“Yāni kānici, bhikkhave, bhayāni uppajjanti sabbāni tāni bālato uppajjanti, no paṇḍitato;**“Whatever dangers there are, all come from the foolish, not from the astute.*";
P_HTM[2430]="*ye keci upaddavā uppajjanti sabbe te bālato uppajjanti, no paṇḍitato;**Whatever perils there are, all come from the foolish, not from the astute.*";
P_HTM[2431]="*ye keci upasaggā uppajjanti sabbe te bālato uppajjanti, no paṇḍitato.**Whatever hazards there are, all come from the foolish, not from the astute.*";
P_HTM[2432]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, naḷāgārā vā tiṇāgārā vā aggi mutto kūṭāgārānipi dahati ullittāvalittāni nivātāni phusitaggaḷāni pihitavātapānāni;**It’s like a fire that spreads from a hut made of reeds or grass, and burns down even a bungalow, plastered inside and out, draft-free, with latches fastened and windows shuttered.*";
P_HTM[2433]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, yāni kānici bhayāni uppajjanti sabbāni tāni bālato uppajjanti, no paṇḍitato;**In the same way, whatever dangers there are, all come from the foolish, not from the astute.*";
P_HTM[2434]="*ye keci upaddavā uppajjanti sabbe te bālato uppajjanti, no paṇḍitato;**Whatever perils there are, all come from the foolish, not from the astute.*";
P_HTM[2435]="*ye keci upasaggā uppajjanti sabbe te bālato uppajjanti, no paṇḍitato.**Whatever hazards there are, all come from the foolish, not from the astute.*";
P_HTM[2436]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, sappaṭibhayo bālo, appaṭibhayo paṇḍito;**So, the fool is dangerous, but the astute person is safe.*";
P_HTM[2437]="*saupaddavo bālo, anupaddavo paṇḍito;**The fool is perilous, but the astute person is not.*";
P_HTM[2438]="*saupasaggo bālo, anupasaggo paṇḍito.**The fool is hazardous, but the astute person is not.*";
P_HTM[2439]="*Natthi, bhikkhave, paṇḍitato bhayaṃ, natthi paṇḍitato upaddavo, natthi paṇḍitato upasaggo.**There’s no danger, peril, or hazard that comes from the astute.*";
P_HTM[2440]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘paṇḍitā bhavissāma vīmaṃsakā’ti—**So you should train like this: ‘We shall be astute, we shall be inquirers.’”*";
P_HTM[2441]="*evañhi vo, bhikkhave, sikkhitabban”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2442]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Ānanda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2443]="*“kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, paṇḍito bhikkhu ‘vīmaṃsako’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**“Sir, how is a mendicant qualified to be called ‘astute, an inquirer’?”*";
P_HTM[2444]="*“Yato kho, ānanda, bhikkhu dhātukusalo ca hoti, āyatanakusalo ca hoti, paṭiccasamuppādakusalo ca hoti, ṭhānāṭhānakusalo ca hoti—**“Ānanda, it’s when a mendicant is skilled in the elements, in the sense fields, in dependent origination, and in the possible and the impossible.*";
P_HTM[2445]="*ettāvatā kho, ānanda, paṇḍito bhikkhu ‘vīmaṃsako’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti.**That’s how a mendicant is qualified to be called ‘astute, an inquirer’.”*";
P_HTM[2446]="*“Kittāvatā pana, bhante, ‘dhātukusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**“But sir, how is a mendicant qualified to be called ‘skilled in the elements’?”*";
P_HTM[2447]="*“Aṭṭhārasa kho imā, ānanda, dhātuyo—**“There are, Ānanda, these eighteen elements:*";
P_HTM[2448]="*cakkhudhātu, rūpadhātu, cakkhuviññāṇadhātu;**the elements of the eye, sights, and eye consciousness;*";
P_HTM[2449]="*sotadhātu, saddadhātu, sotaviññāṇadhātu;**the ear, sounds, and ear consciousness;*";
P_HTM[2450]="*ghānadhātu, gandhadhātu, ghānaviññāṇadhātu;**the nose, smells, and nose consciousness;*";
P_HTM[2451]="*jivhādhātu, rasadhātu, jivhāviññāṇadhātu;**the tongue, tastes, and tongue consciousness;*";
P_HTM[2452]="*kāyadhātu, phoṭṭhabbadhātu, kāyaviññāṇadhātu;**the body, touches, and body consciousness;*";
P_HTM[2453]="*manodhātu, dhammadhātu, manoviññāṇadhātu.**the mind, thoughts, and mind consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2454]="*Imā kho, ānanda, aṭṭhārasa dhātuyo yato jānāti passati—**When a mendicant knows and sees these eighteen elements,*";
P_HTM[2455]="*ettāvatāpi kho, ānanda, ‘dhātukusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti. (1)**they’re qualified to be called ‘skilled in the elements’.”*";
P_HTM[2456]="*“Siyā pana, bhante, aññopi pariyāyo, yathā ‘dhātukusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**“But sir, could there be another way in which a mendicant is qualified to be called ‘skilled in the elements’?”*";
P_HTM[2457]="*“Siyā, ānanda.**“There could, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[2458]="*Chayimā, ānanda, dhātuyo—**There are these six elements:*";
P_HTM[2459]="*pathavīdhātu, āpodhātu, tejodhātu, vāyodhātu, ākāsadhātu, viññāṇadhātu.**the elements of earth, water, fire, air, space, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2460]="*Imā kho, ānanda, cha dhātuyo yato jānāti passati—**When a mendicant knows and sees these six elements,*";
P_HTM[2461]="*ettāvatāpi kho, ānanda, ‘dhātukusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti. (2)**they’re qualified to be called ‘skilled in the elements’.”*";
P_HTM[2462]="*“Siyā pana, bhante, aññopi pariyāyo, yathā ‘dhātukusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**“But sir, could there be another way in which a mendicant is qualified to be called ‘skilled in the elements’?”*";
P_HTM[2463]="*“Siyā, ānanda.**“There could, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[2464]="*Chayimā, ānanda, dhātuyo—**There are these six elements:*";
P_HTM[2465]="*sukhadhātu, dukkhadhātu, somanassadhātu, domanassadhātu, upekkhādhātu, avijjādhātu.**the elements of pleasure, pain, happiness, sadness, equanimity, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[2466]="*Imā kho, ānanda, cha dhātuyo yato jānāti passati—**When a mendicant knows and sees these six elements,*";
P_HTM[2467]="*ettāvatāpi kho, ānanda, ‘dhātukusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti. (3)**they’re qualified to be called ‘skilled in the elements’.”*";
P_HTM[2468]="*“Siyā pana, bhante, aññopi pariyāyo, yathā ‘dhātukusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**“But sir, could there be another way in which a mendicant is qualified to be called ‘skilled in the elements’?”*";
P_HTM[2469]="*“Siyā, ānanda.**“There could, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[2470]="*Chayimā, ānanda, dhātuyo—**There are these six elements:*";
P_HTM[2471]="*kāmadhātu, nekkhammadhātu, byāpādadhātu, abyāpādadhātu, vihiṃsādhātu, avihiṃsādhātu.**the elements of sensuality and renunciation, malice and good will, and cruelty and harmlessness.*";
P_HTM[2472]="*Imā kho, ānanda, cha dhātuyo yato jānāti passati—**When a mendicant knows and sees these six elements,*";
P_HTM[2473]="*ettāvatāpi kho, ānanda, ‘dhātukusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti. (4)**they’re qualified to be called ‘skilled in the elements’.”*";
P_HTM[2474]="*“Siyā pana, bhante, aññopi pariyāyo, yathā ‘dhātukusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**“But sir, could there be another way in which a mendicant is qualified to be called ‘skilled in the elements’?”*";
P_HTM[2475]="*“Siyā, ānanda.**“There could, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[2476]="*Tisso imā, ānanda, dhātuyo—**There are these three elements:*";
P_HTM[2477]="*kāmadhātu, rūpadhātu, arūpadhātu.**the elements of the sensual realm, the realm of luminous form, and the formless realm.*";
P_HTM[2478]="*Imā kho, ānanda, tisso dhātuyo yato jānāti passati—**When a mendicant knows and sees these three elements,*";
P_HTM[2479]="*ettāvatāpi kho, ānanda, ‘dhātukusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti. (5)**they’re qualified to be called ‘skilled in the elements’.”*";
P_HTM[2480]="*“Siyā pana, bhante, aññopi pariyāyo, yathā ‘dhātukusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**“But sir, could there be another way in which a mendicant is qualified to be called ‘skilled in the elements’?”*";
P_HTM[2481]="*“Siyā, ānanda.**“There could, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[2482]="*Dve imā, ānanda, dhātuyo—**There are these two elements:*";
P_HTM[2483]="*saṅkhatādhātu, asaṅkhatādhātu.**the conditioned element and the unconditioned element.*";
P_HTM[2484]="*Imā kho, ānanda, dve dhātuyo yato jānāti passati—**When a mendicant knows and sees these two elements,*";
P_HTM[2485]="*ettāvatāpi kho, ānanda, ‘dhātukusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti. (6)**they’re qualified to be called ‘skilled in the elements’.”*";
P_HTM[2486]="*“Kittāvatā pana, bhante, ‘āyatanakusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**“But sir, how is a mendicant qualified to be called ‘skilled in the sense fields’?”*";
P_HTM[2487]="*“Cha kho panimāni, ānanda, ajjhattikabāhirāni āyatanāni—**“There are these six interior and exterior sense fields:*";
P_HTM[2488]="*cakkhu ceva rūpā ca sotañca saddā ca ghānañca gandhā ca jivhā ca rasā ca kāyo ca phoṭṭhabbā ca mano ca dhammā ca.**the eye and sights, the ear and sounds, the nose and smells, the tongue and tastes, the body and touches, and the mind and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[2489]="*Imāni kho, ānanda, cha ajjhattikabāhirāni āyatanāni yato jānāti passati—**When a mendicant knows and sees these six interior and exterior sense fields,*";
P_HTM[2490]="*ettāvatā kho, ānanda, ‘āyatanakusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti.**they’re qualified to be called ‘skilled in the sense fields’.”*";
P_HTM[2491]="*“Kittāvatā pana, bhante, ‘paṭiccasamuppādakusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**“But sir, how is a mendicant qualified to be called ‘skilled in dependent origination’?”*";
P_HTM[2492]="*“Idhānanda, bhikkhu evaṃ pajānāti:**“It’s when a mendicant understands:*";
P_HTM[2493]="*‘imasmiṃ sati idaṃ hoti, imassuppādā idaṃ uppajjati,**‘When this exists, that is; due to the arising of this, that arises.*";
P_HTM[2494]="*imasmiṃ asati idaṃ na hoti, imassa nirodhā idaṃ nirujjhati, yadidaṃ—**When this doesn’t exist, that is not; due to the cessation of this, that ceases. That is:*";
P_HTM[2495]="*avijjāpaccayā saṅkhārā,**ignorance is a condition for choices.*";
P_HTM[2496]="*saṅkhārapaccayā viññāṇaṃ,**Choices are conditions for consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2497]="*viññāṇapaccayā nāmarūpaṃ,**Consciousness is a condition for name and form.*";
P_HTM[2498]="*nāmarūpapaccayā saḷāyatanaṃ,**Name and form are conditions for the six sense fields.*";
P_HTM[2499]="*saḷāyatanapaccayā phasso,**The six sense fields are conditions for contact.*";
P_HTM[2500]="*phassapaccayā vedanā,**Contact is a condition for feeling.*";
P_HTM[2501]="*vedanāpaccayā taṇhā,**Feeling is a condition for craving.*";
P_HTM[2502]="*taṇhāpaccayā upādānaṃ,**Craving is a condition for grasping.*";
P_HTM[2503]="*upādānapaccayā bhavo,**Grasping is a condition for continued existence.*";
P_HTM[2504]="*bhavapaccayā jāti,**Continued existence is a condition for rebirth.*";
P_HTM[2505]="*jātipaccayā jarāmaraṇaṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassūpāyāsā sambhavanti.**Rebirth is a condition for old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress to come to be.*";
P_HTM[2506]="*Evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa samudayo hoti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering originates.*";
P_HTM[2507]="*Avijjāya tveva asesavirāganirodhā saṅkhāranirodho,**When ignorance fades away and ceases with nothing left over, choices cease.*";
P_HTM[2508]="*saṅkhāranirodhā viññāṇanirodho,**When choices cease, consciousness ceases.*";
P_HTM[2509]="*viññāṇanirodhā nāmarūpanirodho,**When consciousness ceases, name and form cease.*";
P_HTM[2510]="*nāmarūpanirodhā saḷāyatananirodho,**When name and form cease, the six sense fields cease.*";
P_HTM[2511]="*saḷāyatananirodhā phassanirodho,**When the six sense fields cease, contact ceases.*";
P_HTM[2512]="*phassanirodhā vedanānirodho,**When contact ceases, feeling ceases.*";
P_HTM[2513]="*vedanānirodhā taṇhānirodho,**When feeling ceases, craving ceases.*";
P_HTM[2514]="*taṇhānirodhā upādānanirodho,**When craving ceases, grasping ceases.*";
P_HTM[2515]="*upādānanirodhā bhavanirodho,**When grasping ceases, continued existence ceases.*";
P_HTM[2516]="*bhavanirodhā jātinirodho,**When continued existence ceases, rebirth ceases.*";
P_HTM[2517]="*jātinirodhā jarāmaraṇaṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassūpāyāsā nirujjhanti.**When rebirth ceases, old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress cease.*";
P_HTM[2518]="*Evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa nirodho hoti’.**That is how this entire mass of suffering ceases.’*";
P_HTM[2519]="*Ettāvatā kho, ānanda, ‘paṭiccasamuppādakusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti.**That’s how a mendicant is qualified to be called ‘skilled in dependent origination’.”*";
P_HTM[2520]="*“Kittāvatā pana, bhante, ‘ṭhānāṭhānakusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**“But sir, how is a mendicant qualified to be called ‘skilled in the possible and impossible’?”*";
P_HTM[2521]="*“Idhānanda, bhikkhu ‘aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ diṭṭhisampanno puggalo kañci saṅkhāraṃ niccato upagaccheyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**“It’s when a mendicant understands: ‘It’s impossible for a person accomplished in view to take any condition as permanent. That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[2522]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ puthujjano kañci saṅkhāraṃ niccato upagaccheyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**But it’s possible for an ordinary person to take some condition as permanent. That is possible.’*";
P_HTM[2523]="*‘aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ diṭṭhisampanno puggalo kañci saṅkhāraṃ sukhato upagaccheyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for a person accomplished in view to take any condition as pleasant.*";
P_HTM[2524]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ puthujjano kañci saṅkhāraṃ sukhato upagaccheyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it’s possible for an ordinary person to take some condition as pleasant.’*";
P_HTM[2525]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ diṭṭhisampanno puggalo kañci dhammaṃ attato upagaccheyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti,**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for a person accomplished in view to take anything as self.*";
P_HTM[2526]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ puthujjano kañci dhammaṃ attato upagaccheyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it’s possible for an ordinary person to take something as self.’*";
P_HTM[2527]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ diṭṭhisampanno puggalo mātaraṃ jīvitā voropeyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for a person accomplished in view to murder their mother.*";
P_HTM[2528]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ puthujjano mātaraṃ jīvitā voropeyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it’s possible for an ordinary person to murder their mother.’*";
P_HTM[2529]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ diṭṭhisampanno puggalo pitaraṃ jīvitā voropeyya … pe …**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for a person accomplished in view to murder their father … or murder a perfected one.*";
P_HTM[2530]="*arahantaṃ jīvitā voropeyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**But it’s possible for an ordinary person to murder their father … or a perfected one.’*";
P_HTM[2531]="*‘aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ diṭṭhisampanno puggalo duṭṭhacitto tathāgatassa lohitaṃ uppādeyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for a person accomplished in view to injure a Realized One with malicious intent.*";
P_HTM[2532]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ puthujjano duṭṭhacitto tathāgatassa lohitaṃ uppādeyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it’s possible for an ordinary person to injure a Realized One with malicious intent.’*";
P_HTM[2533]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ diṭṭhisampanno puggalo saṅghaṃ bhindeyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for a person accomplished in view to cause a schism in the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2534]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ puthujjano saṅghaṃ bhindeyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it’s possible for an ordinary person to cause a schism in the Saṅgha.’*";
P_HTM[2535]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ diṭṭhisampanno puggalo aññaṃ satthāraṃ uddiseyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for a person accomplished in view to acknowledge another teacher.*";
P_HTM[2536]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ puthujjano aññaṃ satthāraṃ uddiseyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it’s possible for an ordinary person to acknowledge another teacher.’*";
P_HTM[2537]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ ekissā lokadhātuyā dve arahanto sammāsambuddhā apubbaṃ acarimaṃ uppajjeyyuṃ, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for two perfected ones, fully awakened Buddhas to arise in the same solar system at the same time.*";
P_HTM[2538]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ ekissā lokadhātuyā eko arahaṃ sammāsambuddho uppajjeyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it is possible for just one perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha, to arise in one solar system.’*";
P_HTM[2539]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ ekissā lokadhātuyā dve rājāno cakkavattino apubbaṃ acarimaṃ uppajjeyyuṃ, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for two wheel-turning monarchs to arise in the same solar system at the same time.*";
P_HTM[2540]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ ekissā lokadhātuyā eko rājā cakkavattī uppajjeyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it is possible for just one wheel-turning monarch to arise in one solar system.’*";
P_HTM[2541]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ itthī arahaṃ assa sammāsambuddho, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for a woman to be a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2542]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ puriso arahaṃ assa sammāsambuddho, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it is possible for a man to be a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha.’*";
P_HTM[2543]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ itthī rājā assa cakkavattī, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for a woman to be a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2544]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ puriso rājā assa cakkavattī, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it is possible for a man to be a wheel-turning monarch.’*";
P_HTM[2545]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ itthī sakkattaṃ kareyya … mārattaṃ kareyya … brahmattaṃ kareyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for a woman to perform the role of Sakka, Māra, or Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[2546]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ puriso sakkattaṃ kareyya … mārattaṃ kareyya … brahmattaṃ kareyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it is possible for a man to perform the role of Sakka, Māra, or Brahmā.’*";
P_HTM[2547]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ kāyaduccaritassa iṭṭho kanto manāpo vipāko nibbatteyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for a likable, desirable, agreeable result to come from bad conduct of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[2548]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ kāyaduccaritassa aniṭṭho akanto amanāpo vipāko nibbatteyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it is possible for an unlikable, undesirable, disagreeable result to come from bad conduct of body, speech, and mind.’*";
P_HTM[2549]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ vacīduccaritassa … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2550]="*yaṃ manoduccaritassa iṭṭho kanto manāpo vipāko nibbatteyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;* **";
P_HTM[2551]="*ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ vacīduccaritassa … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2552]="*yaṃ manoduccaritassa aniṭṭho akanto amanāpo vipāko nibbatteyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatīti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[2553]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ kāyasucaritassa aniṭṭho akanto amanāpo vipāko nibbatteyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible for an unlikable, undesirable, disagreeable result to come from good conduct of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[2554]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ kāyasucaritassa iṭṭho kanto manāpo vipāko nibbatteyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it is possible for a likable, desirable, agreeable result to come from good conduct of body, speech, and mind.’*";
P_HTM[2555]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ vacīsucaritassa … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2556]="*yaṃ manosucaritassa aniṭṭho akanto amanāpo vipāko nibbatteyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;* **";
P_HTM[2557]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ vacīsucaritassa … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2558]="*yaṃ manosucaritassa iṭṭho kanto manāpo vipāko nibbatteyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[2559]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ kāyaduccaritasamaṅgī taṃnidānā tappaccayā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjeyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible that someone who has engaged in bad conduct of body, speech, and mind, could for that reason alone, when their body breaks up, after death, be reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2560]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ kāyaduccaritasamaṅgī taṃnidānā tappaccayā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjeyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it is possible that someone who has engaged in bad conduct of body, speech, and mind could, for that reason alone, when their body breaks up, after death, be reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.’*";
P_HTM[2561]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ vacīduccaritasamaṅgī … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2562]="*yaṃ manoduccaritasamaṅgī taṃnidānā tappaccayā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjeyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;* **";
P_HTM[2563]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ vacīduccaritasamaṅgī … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2564]="*yaṃ manoduccaritasamaṅgī taṃnidānā tappaccayā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjeyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[2565]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ kāyasucaritasamaṅgī taṃnidānā tappaccayā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjeyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;**They understand: ‘It’s impossible that someone who has engaged in good conduct of body, speech, and mind could, for that reason alone, when their body breaks up, after death, be reborn in a place of loss, the underworld, a lower realm, hell.*";
P_HTM[2566]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ kāyasucaritasamaṅgī taṃnidānā tappaccayā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjeyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.**But it is possible that someone who has engaged in good conduct of body, speech, and mind could, for that reason alone, when their body breaks up, after death, be reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.’*";
P_HTM[2567]="*‘Aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ vacīsucaritasamaṅgī … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2568]="*yaṃ manosucaritasamaṅgī taṃnidānā tappaccayā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjeyya, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti;* **";
P_HTM[2569]="*‘ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ vacīsucaritasamaṅgī … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2570]="*yaṃ manosucaritasamaṅgī taṃnidānā tappaccayā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjeyya, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[2571]="*Ettāvatā kho, ānanda, ‘ṭhānāṭhānakusalo bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti.**That’s how a mendicant is qualified to be called ‘skilled in the possible and impossible’.”*";
P_HTM[2572]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Ānanda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2573]="*“acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante.**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing!*";
P_HTM[2574]="*Konāmo ayaṃ, bhante, dhammapariyāyo”ti?**What is the name of this exposition of the teaching?”*";
P_HTM[2575]="*“Tasmātiha tvaṃ, ānanda, imaṃ dhammapariyāyaṃ ‘bahudhātuko’tipi naṃ dhārehi, ‘catuparivaṭṭo’tipi naṃ dhārehi, ‘dhammādāso’tipi naṃ dhārehi, ‘amatadundubhī’tipi naṃ dhārehi, ‘anuttaro saṅgāmavijayo’tipi naṃ dhārehī”ti.**“In that case, Ānanda, you may remember this exposition of the teaching as ‘The Many Elements’, or else ‘The Four Cycles’, or else ‘The Mirror of the Teaching’, or else ‘The Drum of the Deathless’, or else ‘The Supreme Victory in Battle’.”*";
P_HTM[2576]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2577]="*Attamano āyasmā ānando bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Ānanda was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2578]="*Bahudhātukasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2579]="*116. Isigilisutta**At Isigili*";
P_HTM[2580]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2581]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati isigilismiṃ pabbate.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, on the Isigili Mountain.*";
P_HTM[2582]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2583]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[2584]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2585]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2586]="*“Passatha no tumhe, bhikkhave, etaṃ vebhāraṃ pabbatan”ti?**“Mendicants, do you see that Mount Vebhāra?”*";
P_HTM[2587]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2588]="*“Etassapi kho, bhikkhave, vebhārassa pabbatassa aññāva samaññā ahosi aññā paññatti.**“It used to have a different label and description.*";
P_HTM[2589]="*Passatha no tumhe, bhikkhave, etaṃ paṇḍavaṃ pabbatan”ti?**Do you see that Mount Paṇḍava?”*";
P_HTM[2590]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2591]="*“Etassapi kho, bhikkhave, paṇḍavassa pabbatassa aññāva samaññā ahosi aññā paññatti.**“It too used to have a different label and description.*";
P_HTM[2592]="*Passatha no tumhe, bhikkhave, etaṃ vepullaṃ pabbatan”ti?**Do you see that Mount Vepulla?”*";
P_HTM[2593]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2594]="*“Etassapi kho, bhikkhave, vepullassa pabbatassa aññāva samaññā ahosi aññā paññatti.**“It too used to have a different label and description.*";
P_HTM[2595]="*Passatha no tumhe, bhikkhave, etaṃ gijjhakūṭaṃ pabbatan”ti?**Do you see that Mount Vulture’s Peak?”*";
P_HTM[2596]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2597]="*“Etassapi kho, bhikkhave, gijjhakūṭassa pabbatassa aññāva samaññā ahosi aññā paññatti.**“It too used to have a different label and description.*";
P_HTM[2598]="*Passatha no tumhe, bhikkhave, imaṃ isigiliṃ pabbatan”ti?**Do you see that Mount Isigili?”*";
P_HTM[2599]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2600]="*“Imassa kho pana, bhikkhave, isigilissa pabbatassa esāva samaññā ahosi esā paññatti.**“It used to have exactly the same label and description.*";
P_HTM[2601]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, pañca paccekabuddhasatāni imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsino ahesuṃ.**Once upon a time, five hundred Buddhas awakened for themselves dwelt for a long time on this Isigili.*";
P_HTM[2602]="*Te imaṃ pabbataṃ pavisantā dissanti, paviṭṭhā na dissanti.**They were seen entering the mountain, but after entering were seen no more.*";
P_HTM[2603]="*Tamenaṃ manussā disvā evamāhaṃsu:**When people noticed this they said:*";
P_HTM[2604]="*‘ayaṃ pabbato ime isī gilatī’ti;**‘That mountain swallows these hermits!’*";
P_HTM[2605]="*‘isigili isigili’ tveva samaññā udapādi.**That’s how it came to be known as Isigili.*";
P_HTM[2606]="*Ācikkhissāmi, bhikkhave, paccekabuddhānaṃ nāmāni;**I shall declare the names of the Buddhas awakened for themselves;*";
P_HTM[2607]="*kittayissāmi, bhikkhave, paccekabuddhānaṃ nāmāni;**I shall extol the names of the Buddhas awakened for themselves;*";
P_HTM[2608]="*desessāmi, bhikkhave, paccekabuddhānaṃ nāmāni.**I shall teach the names of the Buddhas awakened for themselves.*";
P_HTM[2609]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[2610]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2611]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2612]="*“Ariṭṭho nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi;**“The Buddhas awakened for themselves who dwelt for a long time on this Isigili were named Ariṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[2613]="*upariṭṭho nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi;**Upariṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[2614]="*tagarasikhī nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi;**Tagarasikhin,*";
P_HTM[2615]="*yasassī nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi;**Yasassin,*";
P_HTM[2616]="*sudassano nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi;**Sudassana,*";
P_HTM[2617]="*piyadassī nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi;**Piyadassin,*";
P_HTM[2618]="*gandhāro nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi;**Gandhāra,*";
P_HTM[2619]="*piṇḍolo nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi;**Piṇḍola,*";
P_HTM[2620]="*upāsabho nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi;**Upāsabha,*";
P_HTM[2621]="*nīto nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi;**Nītha,*";
P_HTM[2622]="*tatho nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi,**Tatha,*";
P_HTM[2623]="*sutavā nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi;**Sutavā,*";
P_HTM[2624]="*bhāvitatto nāma, bhikkhave, paccekasambuddho imasmiṃ isigilismiṃ pabbate ciranivāsī ahosi.**and Bhāvitatta.*";
P_HTM[2625]="*Ye sattasārā anīghā nirāsā,**Those saintly beings, untroubled and free of hope,*";
P_HTM[2626]="*Paccekamevajjhagamaṃsu bodhiṃ;**who each achieved awakening by themselves;*";
P_HTM[2627]="*Tesaṃ visallāna naruttamānaṃ,**hear me extol their names,*";
P_HTM[2628]="*Nāmāni me kittayato suṇātha.**the supreme persons, free of thorns.*";
P_HTM[2629]="*Ariṭṭho upariṭṭho tagarasikhī yasassī,**Ariṭṭha, Upariṭṭha, Tagarasikhin, Yasassin,*";
P_HTM[2630]="*Sudassano piyadassī ca susambuddho;**Sudassana, and Piyadassin the awakened;*";
P_HTM[2631]="*Gandhāro piṇḍolo upāsabho ca,**Gandhāra, Piṇḍola, and Upāsabha,*";
P_HTM[2632]="*Nīto tatho sutavā bhāvitatto.**Nītha, Tatha, Sutavā, and Bhāvitatta.*";
P_HTM[2633]="*Sumbho subho matulo aṭṭhamo ca,**Sumbha, Subha, Methula, and Aṭṭhama,*";
P_HTM[2634]="*Athassumegho anīgho sudāṭho;**and Assumegha, Anīgha, and Sudāṭha,*";
P_HTM[2635]="*Paccekabuddhā bhavanettikhīṇā,**awakened for themselves, enders of the attachment to rebirth.*";
P_HTM[2636]="*Hiṅgū ca hiṅgo ca mahānubhāvā.**Hiṅgū, and Hiṅga the mighty.*";
P_HTM[2637]="*Dve jālino munino aṭṭhako ca,**Two sages named Jāli, and Aṭṭhaka.*";
P_HTM[2638]="*Atha kosallo buddho atho subāhu;**Then the Buddha Kosala and Subāhu;*";
P_HTM[2639]="*Upanemiso nemiso santacitto,**Upanemi, Nemi, and Santacitta,*";
P_HTM[2640]="*Sacco tatho virajo paṇḍito ca.**right and true, stainless and astute.*";
P_HTM[2641]="*Kāḷūpakāḷā vijito jito ca,**Kāḷa and Upakāḷa, Vijita and Jita,*";
P_HTM[2642]="*Aṅgo ca paṅgo ca guttijito ca;**Aṅga and Paṅga, and Guttijita too;*";
P_HTM[2643]="*Passi jahi upadhidukkhamūlaṃ,**Passin gave up attachment, suffering’s root,*";
P_HTM[2644]="*Aparājito mārabalaṃ ajesi.**while Aparājita defeated Māra’s power.*";
P_HTM[2645]="*Satthā pavattā sarabhaṅgo lomahaṃso,**Satthar, Pavattar, Sarabhaṅga, Lomahaṁsa,*";
P_HTM[2646]="*Uccaṅgamāyo asito anāsavo;**Uccaṅgamāya, Asita, Anāsava,*";
P_HTM[2647]="*Manomayo mānacchido ca bandhumā,**Manomaya, and Bandhumant the cutter of conceit,*";
P_HTM[2648]="*Tadādhimutto vimalo ca ketumā.**and Tadādhimutta the immaculate and resplendent.*";
P_HTM[2649]="*Ketumbharāgo ca mātaṅgo ariyo,**Ketumbarāga, Mātaṅga, and Ariya,*";
P_HTM[2650]="*Athaccuto accutagāmabyāmako;**then Accuta, Accutagāma, and Byāmaka,*";
P_HTM[2651]="*Sumaṅgalo dabbilo supatiṭṭhito,**Sumaṅgala, Dabbila, Supatiṭṭhita,*";
P_HTM[2652]="*Asayho khemābhirato ca sorato.**Asayha, Khemābhirata, and Sorata.*";
P_HTM[2653]="*Durannayo saṅgho athopi ujjayo,**Durannaya, Saṅgha, and also Ujjaya,*";
P_HTM[2654]="*Aparo muni sayho anomanikkamo;**another sage, Sayha of peerless effort.*";
P_HTM[2655]="*Ānando nando upanando dvādasa,**There are twelve Ānandas, Nandas, and Upanandas,*";
P_HTM[2656]="*Bhāradvājo antimadehadhārī.**and Bhāradvāja, bearing his final body.*";
P_HTM[2657]="*Bodhi mahānāmo athopi uttaro,**Bodhi, also Mahānāma the supreme,*";
P_HTM[2658]="*Kesī sikhī sundaro dvārabhājo;**Kesin, Sikhin, Sundara, and Bhāradvāja,*";
P_HTM[2659]="*Tissūpatissā bhavabandhanacchidā,**Tissa and Upatissa, who’ve both cut the bonds to rebirth,*";
P_HTM[2660]="*Upasikhi taṇhacchido ca sikhari.**Upasīdarin and Sīdarin, who’ve both cut off craving.*";
P_HTM[2661]="*Buddho ahu maṅgalo vītarāgo,**Maṅgala was awakened, free of greed,*";
P_HTM[2662]="*Usabhacchidā jāliniṃ dukkhamūlaṃ;**Usabha cut the net, the root of suffering,*";
P_HTM[2663]="*Santaṃ padaṃ ajjhagamopanīto,**Upanīta who attained the state of peace,*";
P_HTM[2664]="*Uposatho sundaro saccanāmo.**Uposatha, Sundara, and Saccanāma.*";
P_HTM[2665]="*Jeto jayanto padumo uppalo ca,**Jeta, Jayanta, Paduma, and Uppala;*";
P_HTM[2666]="*Padumuttaro rakkhito pabbato ca;**Padumuttara, Rakkhita, and Pabbata,*";
P_HTM[2667]="*Mānatthaddho sobhito vītarāgo,**Mānatthaddha, beautiful and free of greed,*";
P_HTM[2668]="*Kaṇho ca buddho suvimuttacitto.**and the Buddha Kaṇha, his mind well freed.*";
P_HTM[2669]="*Ete ca aññe ca mahānubhāvā,**These and other mighty ones awakened for themselves,*";
P_HTM[2670]="*Paccekabuddhā bhavanettikhīṇā;**enders of the attachment to rebirth—*";
P_HTM[2671]="*Te sabbasaṅgātigate mahesī,**honor these great hermits who are fully extinguished,*";
P_HTM[2672]="*Parinibbute vandatha appameyye”ti.**having got past all ties, limitless.”*";
P_HTM[2673]="*Isigilisuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2674]="*117. Mahācattārīsakasutta**The Great Forty*";
P_HTM[2675]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2676]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[2677]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2678]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[2679]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2680]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2681]="*“ariyaṃ vo, bhikkhave, sammāsamādhiṃ desessāmi saupanisaṃ saparikkhāraṃ.**“Mendicants, I will teach you noble right immersion with its vital conditions and its prerequisites.*";
P_HTM[2682]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[2683]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2684]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2685]="*“Katamo ca, bhikkhave, ariyo sammāsamādhi saupaniso saparikkhāro?**“And what is noble right immersion with its vital conditions and its prerequisites?*";
P_HTM[2686]="*Seyyathidaṃ—sammādiṭṭhi, sammāsaṅkappo, sammāvācā, sammākammanto, sammāājīvo, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati;**They are: right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, and right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2687]="*yā kho, bhikkhave, imehi sattahaṅgehi cittassa ekaggatā parikkhatā—**Unification of mind with these seven factors as prerequisites*";
P_HTM[2688]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ariyo sammāsamādhi saupaniso itipi, saparikkhāro itipi.**is called noble right immersion with its vital conditions and also with its prerequisites.*";
P_HTM[2689]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti.**In this context, right view comes first.*";
P_HTM[2690]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti?**And how does right view come first?*";
P_HTM[2691]="*Micchādiṭṭhiṃ ‘micchādiṭṭhī’ti pajānāti, sammādiṭṭhiṃ ‘sammādiṭṭhī’ti pajānāti—sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**When you understand wrong view as wrong view and right view as right view, that’s your right view.*";
P_HTM[2692]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, micchādiṭṭhi?**And what is wrong view?*";
P_HTM[2693]="*‘Natthi dinnaṃ, natthi yiṭṭhaṃ, natthi hutaṃ, natthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko, natthi ayaṃ loko, natthi paro loko, natthi mātā, natthi pitā, natthi sattā opapātikā, natthi loke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sammaggatā sammāpaṭipannā ye imañca lokaṃ parañca lokaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedentī’ti—**‘There’s no meaning in giving, sacrifice, or offerings. There’s no fruit or result of good and bad deeds. There’s no afterlife. There are no duties to mother and father. No beings are reborn spontaneously. And there’s no ascetic or brahmin who is well attained and practiced, and who describes the afterlife after realizing it with their own insight.’*";
P_HTM[2694]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, micchādiṭṭhi.**This is wrong view.*";
P_HTM[2695]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi?**And what is right view?*";
P_HTM[2696]="*Sammādiṭṭhimpahaṃ, bhikkhave, dvāyaṃ vadāmi—**Right view is twofold, I say.*";
P_HTM[2697]="*atthi, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi sāsavā puññabhāgiyā upadhivepakkā;**There is right view that is accompanied by defilements, has the attributes of good deeds, and ripens in attachment.*";
P_HTM[2698]="*atthi, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi ariyā anāsavā lokuttarā maggaṅgā.**And there is right view that is noble, undefiled, transcendent, a factor of the path.*";
P_HTM[2699]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi sāsavā puññabhāgiyā upadhivepakkā?**And what is right view that is accompanied by defilements, has the attributes of good deeds, and ripens in attachment?*";
P_HTM[2700]="*‘Atthi dinnaṃ, atthi yiṭṭhaṃ, atthi hutaṃ, atthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko, atthi ayaṃ loko, atthi paro loko, atthi mātā, atthi pitā, atthi sattā opapātikā, atthi loke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sammaggatā sammāpaṭipannā ye imañca lokaṃ parañca lokaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedentī’ti—**‘There is meaning in giving, sacrifice, and offerings. There are fruits and results of good and bad deeds. There is an afterlife. There are duties to mother and father. There are beings reborn spontaneously. And there are ascetics and brahmins who are well attained and practiced, and who describe the afterlife after realizing it with their own insight.’*";
P_HTM[2701]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi sāsavā puññabhāgiyā upadhivepakkā.**This is right view that is accompanied by defilements, has the attributes of good deeds, and ripens in attachment.*";
P_HTM[2702]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi ariyā anāsavā lokuttarā maggaṅgā?**And what is right view that is noble, undefiled, transcendent, a factor of the path?*";
P_HTM[2703]="*Yā kho, bhikkhave, ariyacittassa anāsavacittassa ariyamaggasamaṅgino ariyamaggaṃ bhāvayato paññā paññindriyaṃ paññābalaṃ dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgo sammādiṭṭhi maggaṅgaṃ—**It’s the wisdom—the faculty of wisdom, the power of wisdom, the awakening factor of investigation of principles, and right view as a factor of the path—in one of noble mind and undefiled mind, who possesses the noble path and develops the noble path.*";
P_HTM[2704]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi ariyā anāsavā lokuttarā maggaṅgā.**This is called right view that is noble, undefiled, transcendent, a factor of the path.*";
P_HTM[2705]="*So micchādiṭṭhiyā pahānāya vāyamati, sammādiṭṭhiyā, upasampadāya, svāssa hoti sammāvāyāmo.**They make an effort to give up wrong view and embrace right view: that’s their right effort.*";
P_HTM[2706]="*So sato micchādiṭṭhiṃ pajahati, sato sammādiṭṭhiṃ upasampajja viharati, sāssa hoti sammāsati.**Mindfully they give up wrong view and take up right view: that’s their right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2707]="*Itiyime tayo dhammā sammādiṭṭhiṃ anuparidhāvanti anuparivattanti, seyyathidaṃ—sammādiṭṭhi, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati.**So these three things keep running and circling around right view, namely: right view, right effort, and right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2708]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti.**In this context, right view comes first.*";
P_HTM[2709]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti?**And how does right view come first?*";
P_HTM[2710]="*Micchāsaṅkappaṃ ‘micchāsaṅkappo’ti pajānāti, sammāsaṅkappaṃ ‘sammāsaṅkappo’ti pajānāti, sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**When you understand wrong thought as wrong thought and right thought as right thought, that’s your right view.*";
P_HTM[2711]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, micchāsaṅkappo?**And what is wrong thought?*";
P_HTM[2712]="*Kāmasaṅkappo, byāpādasaṅkappo, vihiṃsāsaṅkappo—**Thoughts of sensuality, of malice, and of cruelty.*";
P_HTM[2713]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, micchāsaṅkappo.**This is wrong thought.*";
P_HTM[2714]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sammāsaṅkappo?**And what is right thought?*";
P_HTM[2715]="*Sammāsaṅkappampahaṃ, bhikkhave, dvāyaṃ vadāmi—**Right thought is twofold, I say.*";
P_HTM[2716]="*atthi, bhikkhave, sammāsaṅkappo sāsavo puññabhāgiyo upadhivepakko;**There is right thought that is accompanied by defilements, has the attributes of good deeds, and ripens in attachment.*";
P_HTM[2717]="*atthi, bhikkhave, sammāsaṅkappo ariyo anāsavo lokuttaro maggaṅgo.**And there is right thought that is noble, undefiled, transcendent, a factor of the path.*";
P_HTM[2718]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sammāsaṅkappo sāsavo puññabhāgiyo upadhivepakko?**And what is right thought that is accompanied by defilements, has the attributes of good deeds, and ripens in attachment?*";
P_HTM[2719]="*Nekkhammasaṅkappo, abyāpādasaṅkappo, avihiṃsāsaṅkappo:**Thoughts of renunciation, good will, and harmlessness.*";
P_HTM[2720]="*‘ayaṃ, bhikkhave, sammāsaṅkappo sāsavo puññabhāgiyo upadhivepakko’.**This is right thought that is accompanied by defilements.*";
P_HTM[2721]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sammāsaṅkappo ariyo anāsavo lokuttaro maggaṅgo?**And what is right thought that is noble, undefiled, transcendent, a factor of the path?*";
P_HTM[2722]="*Yo kho, bhikkhave, ariyacittassa anāsavacittassa ariyamaggasamaṅgino ariyamaggaṃ bhāvayato takko vitakko saṅkappo appanā byappanā cetaso abhiniropanā vacīsaṅkhāro—**It’s the thinking—the placing of the mind, thought, applying, application, implanting of the mind, verbal processes—in one of noble mind and undefiled mind, who possesses the noble path and develops the noble path.*";
P_HTM[2723]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, sammāsaṅkappo ariyo anāsavo lokuttaro maggaṅgo.**This is right thought that is noble.*";
P_HTM[2724]="*So micchāsaṅkappassa pahānāya vāyamati, sammāsaṅkappassa upasampadāya, svāssa hoti sammāvāyāmo.**They make an effort to give up wrong thought and embrace right thought: that’s their right effort.*";
P_HTM[2725]="*So sato micchāsaṅkappaṃ pajahati, sato sammāsaṅkappaṃ upasampajja viharati; sāssa hoti sammāsati.**Mindfully they give up wrong thought and take up right thought: that’s their right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2726]="*Itiyime tayo dhammā sammāsaṅkappaṃ anuparidhāvanti anuparivattanti, seyyathidaṃ—sammādiṭṭhi, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati.**So these three things keep running and circling around right thought, namely: right view, right effort, and right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2727]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti.**In this context, right view comes first.*";
P_HTM[2728]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti?**And how does right view come first?*";
P_HTM[2729]="*Micchāvācaṃ ‘micchāvācā’ti pajānāti, sammāvācaṃ ‘sammāvācā’ti pajānāti; sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**When you understand wrong speech as wrong speech and right speech as right speech, that’s your right view.*";
P_HTM[2730]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, micchāvācā?**And what is wrong speech?*";
P_HTM[2731]="*Musāvādo, pisuṇā vācā, pharusā vācā, samphappalāpo—**Speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical.*";
P_HTM[2732]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, micchāvācā.**This is wrong speech.*";
P_HTM[2733]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, sammāvācā?**And what is right speech?*";
P_HTM[2734]="*Sammāvācampahaṃ, bhikkhave, dvāyaṃ vadāmi—**Right speech is twofold, I say.*";
P_HTM[2735]="*atthi, bhikkhave, sammāvācā sāsavā puññabhāgiyā upadhivepakkā;**There is right speech that is accompanied by defilements, has the attributes of good deeds, and ripens in attachment.*";
P_HTM[2736]="*atthi, bhikkhave, sammāvācā ariyā anāsavā lokuttarā maggaṅgā.**And there is right speech that is noble, undefiled, transcendent, a factor of the path.*";
P_HTM[2737]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, sammāvācā sāsavā puññabhāgiyā upadhivepakkā?**And what is right speech that is accompanied by defilements, has the attributes of good deeds, and ripens in attachment?*";
P_HTM[2738]="*Musāvādā veramaṇī, pisuṇāya vācāya veramaṇī, pharusāya vācāya veramaṇī, samphappalāpā veramaṇī—**The refraining from lying, divisive speech, harsh speech, and talking nonsense.*";
P_HTM[2739]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, sammāvācā sāsavā puññabhāgiyā upadhivepakkā.**This is right speech that is accompanied by defilements.*";
P_HTM[2740]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, sammāvācā ariyā anāsavā lokuttarā maggaṅgā?**And what is right speech that is noble, undefiled, transcendent, a factor of the path?*";
P_HTM[2741]="*Yā kho, bhikkhave, ariyacittassa anāsavacittassa ariyamaggasamaṅgino ariyamaggaṃ bhāvayato catūhi vacīduccaritehi ārati virati paṭivirati veramaṇī—**It’s the desisting, abstaining, abstinence, and refraining from the four kinds of bad verbal conduct in one of noble mind and undefiled mind, who possesses the noble path and develops the noble path.*";
P_HTM[2742]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, sammāvācā ariyā anāsavā lokuttarā maggaṅgā.**This is right speech that is noble.*";
P_HTM[2743]="*So micchāvācāya pahānāya vāyamati, sammāvācāya upasampadāya; svāssa hoti sammāvāyāmo.**They make an effort to give up wrong speech and embrace right speech: that’s their right effort.*";
P_HTM[2744]="*So sato micchāvācaṃ pajahati, sato sammāvācaṃ upasampajja viharati; sāssa hoti sammāsati.**Mindfully they give up wrong speech and take up right speech: that’s their right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2745]="*Itiyime tayo dhammā sammāvācaṃ anuparidhāvanti anuparivattanti, seyyathidaṃ—sammādiṭṭhi, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati.**So these three things keep running and circling around right speech, namely: right view, right effort, and right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2746]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti.**In this context, right view comes first.*";
P_HTM[2747]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti?**And how does right view come first?*";
P_HTM[2748]="*Micchākammantaṃ ‘micchākammanto’ti pajānāti, sammākammantaṃ ‘sammākammanto’ti pajānāti; sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**When you understand wrong action as wrong action and right action as right action, that’s your right view.*";
P_HTM[2749]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, micchākammanto?**And what is wrong action?*";
P_HTM[2750]="*Pāṇātipāto, adinnādānaṃ, kāmesumicchācāro—**Killing living creatures, stealing, and sexual misconduct.*";
P_HTM[2751]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, micchākammanto.**This is wrong action.*";
P_HTM[2752]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sammākammanto?**And what is right action?*";
P_HTM[2753]="*Sammākammantampahaṃ, bhikkhave, dvāyaṃ vadāmi—**Right action is twofold, I say.*";
P_HTM[2754]="*atthi, bhikkhave, sammākammanto sāsavo puññabhāgiyo upadhivepakko;**There is right action that is accompanied by defilements, has the attributes of good deeds, and ripens in attachment.*";
P_HTM[2755]="*atthi, bhikkhave, sammākammanto ariyo anāsavo lokuttaro maggaṅgo.**And there is right action that is noble, undefiled, transcendent, a factor of the path.*";
P_HTM[2756]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sammākammanto sāsavo puññabhāgiyo upadhivepakko?**And what is right action that is accompanied by defilements, has the attributes of good deeds, and ripens in attachment?*";
P_HTM[2757]="*Pāṇātipātā veramaṇī, adinnādānā veramaṇī, kāmesumicchācārā veramaṇī—**Refraining from killing living creatures, stealing, and sexual misconduct.*";
P_HTM[2758]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, sammākammanto sāsavo puññabhāgiyo upadhivepakko.**This is right action that is accompanied by defilements.*";
P_HTM[2759]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sammākammanto ariyo anāsavo lokuttaro maggaṅgo?**And what is right action that is noble, undefiled, transcendent, a factor of the path?*";
P_HTM[2760]="*Yā kho, bhikkhave, ariyacittassa anāsavacittassa ariyamaggasamaṅgino ariyamaggaṃ bhāvayato tīhi kāyaduccaritehi ārati virati paṭivirati veramaṇī—**It’s the desisting, abstaining, abstinence, and refraining from the three kinds of bad bodily conduct in one of noble mind and undefiled mind, who possesses the noble path and develops the noble path.*";
P_HTM[2761]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, sammākammanto ariyo anāsavo lokuttaro maggaṅgo.**This is right action that is noble.*";
P_HTM[2762]="*So micchākammantassa pahānāya vāyamati, sammākammantassa upasampadāya; svāssa hoti sammāvāyāmo.**They make an effort to give up wrong action and embrace right action: that’s their right effort.*";
P_HTM[2763]="*So sato micchākammantaṃ pajahati, sato sammākammantaṃ upasampajja viharati; sāssa hoti sammāsati.**Mindfully they give up wrong action and take up right action: that’s their right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2764]="*Itiyime tayo dhammā sammākammantaṃ anuparidhāvanti anuparivattanti, seyyathidaṃ—sammādiṭṭhi, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati.**So these three things keep running and circling around right action, namely: right view, right effort, and right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2765]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti.**In this context, right view comes first.*";
P_HTM[2766]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti?**And how does right view come first?*";
P_HTM[2767]="*Micchāājīvaṃ ‘micchāājīvo’ti pajānāti, sammāājīvaṃ ‘sammāājīvo’ti pajānāti; sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**When you understand wrong livelihood as wrong livelihood and right livelihood as right livelihood, that’s your right view.*";
P_HTM[2768]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, micchāājīvo?**And what is wrong livelihood?*";
P_HTM[2769]="*Kuhanā, lapanā, nemittikatā, nippesikatā, lābhena lābhaṃ nijigīsanatā—**Deceit, flattery, hinting, and belittling, and using material possessions to pursue other material possessions.*";
P_HTM[2770]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, micchāājīvo.**This is wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[2771]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sammāājīvo?**And what is right livelihood?*";
P_HTM[2772]="*Sammāājīvampahaṃ, bhikkhave, dvāyaṃ vadāmi—**Right livelihood is twofold, I say.*";
P_HTM[2773]="*atthi, bhikkhave, sammāājīvo sāsavo puññabhāgiyo upadhivepakko;**There is right livelihood that is accompanied by defilements, has the attributes of good deeds, and ripens in attachment.*";
P_HTM[2774]="*atthi, bhikkhave, sammāājīvo ariyo anāsavo lokuttaro maggaṅgo.**And there is right livelihood that is noble, undefiled, transcendent, a factor of the path.*";
P_HTM[2775]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sammāājīvo sāsavo puññabhāgiyo upadhivepakko?**And what is right livelihood that is accompanied by defilements, has the attributes of good deeds, and ripens in attachment?*";
P_HTM[2776]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako micchāājīvaṃ pahāya sammāājīvena jīvikaṃ kappeti—**It’s when a noble disciple gives up wrong livelihood and earns a living by right livelihood.*";
P_HTM[2777]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, sammāājīvo sāsavo puññabhāgiyo upadhivepakko.**This is right livelihood that is accompanied by defilements.*";
P_HTM[2778]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sammāājīvo ariyo anāsavo lokuttaro maggaṅgo?**And what is right livelihood that is noble, undefiled, transcendent, a factor of the path?*";
P_HTM[2779]="*Yā kho, bhikkhave, ariyacittassa anāsavacittassa ariyamaggasamaṅgino ariyamaggaṃ bhāvayato micchāājīvā ārati virati paṭivirati veramaṇī—**It’s the desisting, abstaining, abstinence, and refraining from wrong livelihood in one of noble mind and undefiled mind, who possesses the noble path and develops the noble path.*";
P_HTM[2780]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, sammāājīvo ariyo anāsavo lokuttaro maggaṅgo.**This is right livelihood that is noble.*";
P_HTM[2781]="*So micchāājīvassa pahānāya vāyamati, sammāājīvassa upasampadāya; svāssa hoti sammāvāyāmo.**They make an effort to give up wrong livelihood and embrace right livelihood: that’s their right effort.*";
P_HTM[2782]="*So sato micchāājīvaṃ pajahati, sato sammāājīvaṃ upasampajja viharati; sāssa hoti sammāsati.**Mindfully they give up wrong livelihood and take up right livelihood: that’s their right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2783]="*Itiyime tayo dhammā sammāājīvaṃ anuparidhāvanti anuparivattanti, seyyathidaṃ—sammādiṭṭhi, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati.**So these three things keep running and circling around right livelihood, namely: right view, right effort, and right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2784]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti.**In this context, right view comes first.*";
P_HTM[2785]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti?**And how does right view come first?*";
P_HTM[2786]="*Sammādiṭṭhissa, bhikkhave, sammāsaṅkappo pahoti, sammāsaṅkappassa sammāvācā pahoti, sammāvācassa sammākammanto pahoti, sammākammantassa sammāājīvo pahoti, sammāājīvassa sammāvāyāmo pahoti, sammāvāyāmassa sammāsati pahoti, sammāsatissa sammāsamādhi pahoti, sammāsamādhissa sammāñāṇaṃ pahoti, sammāñāṇassa sammāvimutti pahoti.**Right view gives rise to right thought. Right thought gives rise to right speech. Right speech gives rise to right action. Right action gives rise to right livelihood. Right livelihood gives rise to right effort. Right effort gives rise to right mindfulness. Right mindfulness gives rise to right immersion. Right immersion gives rise to right knowledge. Right knowledge gives rise to right freedom.*";
P_HTM[2787]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, aṭṭhaṅgasamannāgato sekkho, dasaṅgasamannāgato arahā hoti.**So the trainee has eight factors, while the perfected one has ten factors.*";
P_HTM[2788]="*Tatrapi sammāñāṇena aneke pāpakā akusalā dhammā vigatā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti.**And here too, the eradication of many bad, unskillful qualities is fully developed due to right knowledge.*";
P_HTM[2789]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti.**In this context, right view comes first.*";
P_HTM[2790]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi pubbaṅgamā hoti?**And how does right view come first?*";
P_HTM[2791]="*Sammādiṭṭhissa, bhikkhave, micchādiṭṭhi nijjiṇṇā hoti.**For one of right view, wrong view is worn away.*";
P_HTM[2792]="*Ye ca micchādiṭṭhipaccayā aneke pāpakā akusalā dhammā sambhavanti te cassa nijjiṇṇā honti.**And the many bad, unskillful qualities that arise because of wrong view are worn away.*";
P_HTM[2793]="*Sammādiṭṭhipaccayā aneke kusalā dhammā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti.**And because of right view, many skillful qualities are fully developed.*";
P_HTM[2794]="*Sammāsaṅkappassa, bhikkhave, micchāsaṅkappo nijjiṇṇo hoti … pe …**For one of right thought, wrong thought is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[2795]="*sammāvācassa, bhikkhave, micchāvācā nijjiṇṇā hoti …**For one of right speech, wrong speech is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[2796]="*sammākammantassa, bhikkhave, micchākammanto nijjiṇṇo hoti …**For one of right action, wrong action is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[2797]="*sammāājīvassa, bhikkhave, micchāājīvo nijjiṇṇo hoti …**For one of right livelihood, wrong livelihood is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[2798]="*sammāvāyāmassa, bhikkhave, micchāvāyāmo nijjiṇṇo hoti …**For one of right effort, wrong effort is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[2799]="*sammāsatissa, bhikkhave, micchāsati nijjiṇṇā hoti …**For one of right mindfulness, wrong mindfulness is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[2800]="*sammāsamādhissa, bhikkhave, micchāsamādhi nijjiṇṇo hoti …**For one of right immersion, wrong immersion is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[2801]="*sammāñāṇassa, bhikkhave, micchāñāṇaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ hoti …**For one of right knowledge, wrong knowledge is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[2802]="*sammāvimuttassa, bhikkhave, micchāvimutti nijjiṇṇā hoti.**For one of right freedom, wrong freedom is worn away.*";
P_HTM[2803]="*Ye ca micchāvimuttipaccayā aneke pāpakā akusalā dhammā sambhavanti te cassa nijjiṇṇā honti.**And the many bad, unskillful qualities that arise because of wrong freedom are worn away.*";
P_HTM[2804]="*Sammāvimuttipaccayā ca aneke kusalā dhammā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti.**And because of right freedom, many skillful qualities are fully developed.*";
P_HTM[2805]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, vīsati kusalapakkhā, vīsati akusalapakkhā—**So there are twenty on the side of the skillful, and twenty on the side of the unskillful.*";
P_HTM[2806]="*mahācattārīsako dhammapariyāyo pavattito appaṭivattiyo samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ.**This exposition of the teaching on the Great Forty has been rolled forth. And it cannot be rolled back by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[2807]="*Yo hi koci, bhikkhave, samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā imaṃ mahācattārīsakaṃ dhammapariyāyaṃ garahitabbaṃ paṭikkositabbaṃ maññeyya tassa diṭṭheva dhamme dasasahadhammikā vādānuvādā gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchanti—**If any ascetic or brahmin imagines they can criticize and reject the exposition of the teaching on the Great Forty, they deserve rebuke and criticism on ten legitimate grounds in the present life.*";
P_HTM[2808]="*sammādiṭṭhiñce bhavaṃ garahati, ye ca micchādiṭṭhī samaṇabrāhmaṇā te bhoto pujjā, te bhoto pāsaṃsā;**If such a gentleman criticizes right view, they praise and honor the ascetics and brahmins who have wrong view.*";
P_HTM[2809]="*sammāsaṅkappañce bhavaṃ garahati, ye ca micchāsaṅkappā samaṇabrāhmaṇā te bhoto pujjā, te bhoto pāsaṃsā;**If they criticize right thought …*";
P_HTM[2810]="*sammāvācañce bhavaṃ garahati … pe …**right speech …*";
P_HTM[2811]="*sammākammantañce bhavaṃ garahati …**right action …*";
P_HTM[2812]="*sammāājīvañce bhavaṃ garahati …**right livelihood …*";
P_HTM[2813]="*sammāvāyāmañce bhavaṃ garahati …**right effort …*";
P_HTM[2814]="*sammāsatiñce bhavaṃ garahati …**right mindfulness …*";
P_HTM[2815]="*sammāsamādhiñce bhavaṃ garahati …**right immersion …*";
P_HTM[2816]="*sammāñāṇañce bhavaṃ garahati …**right knowledge …*";
P_HTM[2817]="*sammāvimuttiñce bhavaṃ garahati, ye ca micchāvimuttī samaṇabrāhmaṇā te bhoto pujjā, te bhoto pāsaṃsā.**right freedom, they praise and honor the ascetics and brahmins who have wrong freedom.*";
P_HTM[2818]="*Yo koci, bhikkhave, samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā imaṃ mahācattārīsakaṃ dhammapariyāyaṃ garahitabbaṃ paṭikkositabbaṃ maññeyya tassa diṭṭheva dhamme ime dasasahadhammikā vādānuvādā gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchanti.**If any ascetic or brahmin imagines they can criticize and reject the exposition of the teaching on the Great Forty, they deserve rebuke and criticism on these ten legitimate grounds in the present life.*";
P_HTM[2819]="*Yepi te, bhikkhave, ahesuṃ okkalā vassabhaññā ahetuvādā akiriyavādā natthikavādā tepi mahācattārīsakaṃ dhammapariyāyaṃ na garahitabbaṃ nappaṭikkositabbaṃ amaññiṃsu.**Even those wanderers of the past, Vassa and Bhañña of Ukkalā, who taught the doctrines of no-cause, inaction, and nihilism, didn’t imagine that the Great Forty should be criticized or rejected.*";
P_HTM[2820]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[2821]="*Nindābyārosaupārambhabhayā”ti.**For fear of being blamed, criticized, and faulted.”*";
P_HTM[2822]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2823]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2824]="*Mahācattārīsakasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2825]="*118. Ānāpānassatisutta**Mindfulness of Breathing*";
P_HTM[2826]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2827]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati pubbārāme migāramātupāsāde sambahulehi abhiññātehi abhiññātehi therehi sāvakehi saddhiṃ—**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in the Eastern Monastery, the stilt longhouse of Migāra’s mother, together with several well-known senior disciples, such as*";
P_HTM[2828]="*āyasmatā ca sāriputtena āyasmatā ca mahāmoggallānena āyasmatā ca mahākassapena āyasmatā ca mahākaccāyanena āyasmatā ca mahākoṭṭhikena āyasmatā ca mahākappinena āyasmatā ca mahācundena āyasmatā ca anuruddhena āyasmatā ca revatena āyasmatā ca ānandena, aññehi ca abhiññātehi abhiññātehi therehi sāvakehi saddhiṃ.**the venerables Sāriputta, Mahāmoggallāna, Mahākassapa, Mahākaccāna, Mahākoṭṭhita, Mahākappina, Mahācunda, Anuruddha, Revata, Ānanda, and others.*";
P_HTM[2829]="*Tena kho pana samayena therā bhikkhū nave bhikkhū ovadanti anusāsanti.**Now at that time the senior mendicants were advising and instructing the junior mendicants.*";
P_HTM[2830]="*Appekacce therā bhikkhū dasapi bhikkhū ovadanti anusāsanti, appekacce therā bhikkhū vīsampi bhikkhū ovadanti anusāsanti, appekacce therā bhikkhū tiṃsampi bhikkhū ovadanti anusāsanti, appekacce therā bhikkhū cattārīsampi bhikkhū ovadanti anusāsanti.**Some senior mendicants instructed ten mendicants, while some instructed twenty, thirty, or forty.*";
P_HTM[2831]="*Te ca navā bhikkhū therehi bhikkhūhi ovadiyamānā anusāsiyamānā uḷāraṃ pubbenāparaṃ visesaṃ jānanti.**Being instructed by the senior mendicants, the junior mendicants realized a higher distinction than they had before.*";
P_HTM[2832]="*Tena kho pana samayena bhagavā tadahuposathe pannarase pavāraṇāya puṇṇāya puṇṇamāya rattiyā bhikkhusaṃghaparivuto abbhokāse nisinno hoti.**Now, at that time it was the sabbath—the full moon on the fifteenth day—and the Buddha was sitting surrounded by the Saṅgha of monks for the invitation to admonish.*";
P_HTM[2833]="*Atha kho bhagavā tuṇhībhūtaṃ tuṇhībhūtaṃ bhikkhusaṃghaṃ anuviloketvā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha looked around the Saṅgha of monks, who were so very silent. He addressed them:*";
P_HTM[2834]="*“āraddhosmi, bhikkhave, imāya paṭipadāya;**“I am satisfied, mendicants, with this practice.*";
P_HTM[2835]="*āraddhacittosmi, bhikkhave, imāya paṭipadāya.**My heart is satisfied with this practice.*";
P_HTM[2836]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, bhiyyoso mattāya vīriyaṃ ārabhatha appattassa pattiyā, anadhigatassa adhigamāya, asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāya.**So you should rouse up even more energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.*";
P_HTM[2837]="*Idhevāhaṃ sāvatthiyaṃ komudiṃ cātumāsiniṃ āgamessāmī”ti.**I will wait here in Sāvatthī for the Komudi full moon of the fourth month.”*";
P_HTM[2838]="*Assosuṃ kho jānapadā bhikkhū:**Mendicants from around the country heard about this,*";
P_HTM[2839]="*“bhagavā kira tattheva sāvatthiyaṃ komudiṃ cātumāsiniṃ āgamessatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2840]="*Te jānapadā bhikkhū sāvatthiṃ osaranti bhagavantaṃ dassanāya.**and came down to Sāvatthī to see the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2841]="*Te ca kho therā bhikkhū bhiyyoso mattāya nave bhikkhū ovadanti anusāsanti.**And those senior mendicants instructed the junior mendicants even more.*";
P_HTM[2842]="*Appekacce therā bhikkhū dasapi bhikkhū ovadanti anusāsanti, appekacce therā bhikkhū vīsampi bhikkhū ovadanti anusāsanti, appekacce therā bhikkhū tiṃsampi bhikkhū ovadanti anusāsanti, appekacce therā bhikkhū cattārīsampi bhikkhū ovadanti anusāsanti.**Some senior mendicants instructed ten mendicants, while some instructed twenty, thirty, or forty.*";
P_HTM[2843]="*Te ca navā bhikkhū therehi bhikkhūhi ovadiyamānā anusāsiyamānā uḷāraṃ pubbenāparaṃ visesaṃ jānanti.**Being instructed by the senior mendicants, the junior mendicants realized a higher distinction than they had before.*";
P_HTM[2844]="*Tena kho pana samayena bhagavā tadahuposathe pannarase komudiyā cātumāsiniyā puṇṇāya puṇṇamāya rattiyā bhikkhusaṅghaparivuto abbhokāse nisinno hoti.**Now, at that time it was the sabbath—the Komudi full moon on the fifteenth day of the fourth month—and the Buddha was sitting in the open surrounded by the Saṅgha of monks.*";
P_HTM[2845]="*Atha kho bhagavā tuṇhībhūtaṃ tuṇhībhūtaṃ bhikkhusaṅghaṃ anuviloketvā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha looked around the Saṅgha of monks, who were so very silent. He addressed them:*";
P_HTM[2846]="*“Apalāpāyaṃ, bhikkhave, parisā; nippalāpāyaṃ, bhikkhave, parisā; suddhā sāre patiṭṭhitā.**“This assembly has no nonsense, mendicants, it’s free of nonsense. It consists purely of the essential core.*";
P_HTM[2847]="*Tathārūpo ayaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhusaṃgho; tathārūpā ayaṃ, bhikkhave, parisā**Such is this Saṅgha of monks, such is this assembly!*";
P_HTM[2848]="*yathārūpā parisā āhuneyyā pāhuneyyā dakkhiṇeyyā añjalikaraṇīyā anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassa.**An assembly such as this is worthy of offerings dedicated to the gods, worthy of hospitality, worthy of a religious donation, worthy of greeting with joined palms, and is the supreme field of merit for the world.*";
P_HTM[2849]="*Tathārūpo ayaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhusaṃgho; tathārūpā ayaṃ, bhikkhave, parisā**Such is this Saṅgha of monks, such is this assembly!*";
P_HTM[2850]="*yathārūpāya parisāya appaṃ dinnaṃ bahu hoti, bahu dinnaṃ bahutaraṃ.**Even a small gift to an assembly such as this is fruitful, while giving more is even more fruitful.*";
P_HTM[2851]="*Tathārūpo ayaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhusaṃgho; tathārūpā ayaṃ, bhikkhave, parisā**Such is this Saṅgha of monks, such is this assembly!*";
P_HTM[2852]="*yathārūpā parisā dullabhā dassanāya lokassa.**An assembly such as this is rarely seen in the world.*";
P_HTM[2853]="*Tathārūpo ayaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhusaṃgho; tathārūpā ayaṃ, bhikkhave, parisā**Such is this Saṅgha of monks, such is this assembly!*";
P_HTM[2854]="*yathārūpaṃ parisaṃ alaṃ yojanagaṇanāni dassanāya gantuṃ puṭosenāpi.**An assembly such as this is worth traveling many leagues to see, even if you have to carry your own provisions in a shoulder bag.*";
P_HTM[2855]="*Santi, bhikkhave, bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṃghe arahanto khīṇāsavā vusitavanto katakaraṇīyā ohitabhārā anuppattasadatthā parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojanā sammadaññāvimuttā—**For in this Saṅgha there are perfected mendicants, who have ended the defilements, completed the spiritual journey, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, achieved their own goal, utterly ended the fetters of rebirth, and are rightly freed through enlightenment.*";
P_HTM[2856]="*evarūpāpi, bhikkhave, santi bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṃghe.**There are such mendicants in this Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2857]="*Santi, bhikkhave, bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṃghe pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātikā tattha parinibbāyino anāvattidhammā tasmā lokā—**In this Saṅgha there are mendicants who, with the ending of the five lower fetters are reborn spontaneously. They are extinguished there, and are not liable to return from that world.*";
P_HTM[2858]="*evarūpāpi, bhikkhave, santi bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṃghe.**There are such mendicants in this Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2859]="*Santi, bhikkhave, bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṃghe tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā rāgadosamohānaṃ tanuttā sakadāgāmino sakideva imaṃ lokaṃ āgantvā dukkhassantaṃ karissanti—**In this Saṅgha there are mendicants who, with the ending of three fetters, and the weakening of greed, hate, and delusion, are once-returners. They come back to this world once only, then make an end of suffering.*";
P_HTM[2860]="*evarūpāpi, bhikkhave, santi bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṃghe.**There are such mendicants in this Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2861]="*Santi, bhikkhave, bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṃghe tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā sotāpannā avinipātadhammā niyatā sambodhiparāyanā—**In this Saṅgha there are mendicants who, with the ending of three fetters are stream-enterers, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[2862]="*evarūpāpi, bhikkhave, santi bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṃghe.**There are such mendicants in this Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2863]="*Santi, bhikkhave, bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṅghe catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvanānuyogamanuyuttā viharanti—**In this Saṅgha there are mendicants who are committed to developing the four kinds of mindfulness meditation …*";
P_HTM[2864]="*evarūpāpi, bhikkhave, santi bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṅghe.* **";
P_HTM[2865]="*Santi, bhikkhave, bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṅghe catunnaṃ sammappadhānānaṃ bhāvanānuyogamanuyuttā viharanti … pe …**the four right efforts …*";
P_HTM[2866]="*catunnaṃ iddhipādānaṃ …**the four bases of psychic power …*";
P_HTM[2867]="*pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ …**the five faculties …*";
P_HTM[2868]="*pañcannaṃ balānaṃ …**the five powers …*";
P_HTM[2869]="*sattannaṃ bojjhaṅgānaṃ …**the seven awakening factors …*";
P_HTM[2870]="*ariyassa aṭṭhaṅgikassa maggassa bhāvanānuyogamanuyuttā viharanti—**the noble eightfold path.*";
P_HTM[2871]="*evarūpāpi, bhikkhave, santi bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṅghe.**There are such mendicants in this Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2872]="*Santi, bhikkhave, bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṅghe mettābhāvanānuyogamanuyuttā viharanti …**In this Saṅgha there are mendicants who are committed to developing the meditation on love …*";
P_HTM[2873]="*karuṇābhāvanānuyogamanuyuttā viharanti …**compassion …*";
P_HTM[2874]="*muditābhāvanānuyogamanuyuttā viharanti …**rejoicing …*";
P_HTM[2875]="*upekkhābhāvanānuyogamanuyuttā viharanti …**equanimity …*";
P_HTM[2876]="*asubhabhāvanānuyogamanuyuttā viharanti …**ugliness …*";
P_HTM[2877]="*aniccasaññābhāvanānuyogamanuyuttā viharanti—**impermanence.*";
P_HTM[2878]="*evarūpāpi, bhikkhave, santi bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṅghe.**There are such mendicants in this Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2879]="*Santi, bhikkhave, bhikkhū imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṅghe ānāpānassatibhāvanānuyogamanuyuttā viharanti.**In this Saṅgha there are mendicants who are committed to developing the meditation on mindfulness of breathing.*";
P_HTM[2880]="*Ānāpānassati, bhikkhave, bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahapphalā hoti mahānisaṃsā.**Mendicants, when mindfulness of breathing is developed and cultivated it is very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[2881]="*Ānāpānassati, bhikkhave, bhāvitā bahulīkatā cattāro satipaṭṭhāne paripūreti.**Mindfulness of breathing, when developed and cultivated, fulfills the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[2882]="*Cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvitā bahulīkatā satta bojjhaṅge paripūrenti.**The four kinds of mindfulness meditation, when developed and cultivated, fulfill the seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[2883]="*Satta bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā bahulīkatā vijjāvimuttiṃ paripūrenti.**And the seven awakening factors, when developed and cultivated, fulfill knowledge and freedom.*";
P_HTM[2884]="*Kathaṃ bhāvitā ca, bhikkhave, ānāpānassati kathaṃ bahulīkatā mahapphalā hoti mahānisaṃsā?**And how is mindfulness of breathing developed and cultivated to be very fruitful and beneficial?*";
P_HTM[2885]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu araññagato vā rukkhamūlagato vā suññāgāragato vā nisīdati pallaṅkaṃ ābhujitvā ujuṃ kāyaṃ paṇidhāya parimukhaṃ satiṃ upaṭṭhapetvā.**It’s when a mendicant has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut. They sit down cross-legged, with their body straight, and establish mindfulness right there.*";
P_HTM[2886]="*So satova assasati satova passasati.**Just mindful, they breathe in. Mindful, they breathe out.*";
P_HTM[2887]="*Dīghaṃ vā assasanto ‘dīghaṃ assasāmī’ti pajānāti, dīghaṃ vā passasanto ‘dīghaṃ passasāmī’ti pajānāti;**When breathing in heavily they know: ‘I’m breathing in heavily.’ When breathing out heavily they know: ‘I’m breathing out heavily.’*";
P_HTM[2888]="*rassaṃ vā assasanto ‘rassaṃ assasāmī’ti pajānāti, rassaṃ vā passasanto ‘rassaṃ passasāmī’ti pajānāti;**When breathing in lightly they know: ‘I’m breathing in lightly.’ When breathing out lightly they know: ‘I’m breathing out lightly.’*";
P_HTM[2889]="*‘sabbakāyapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘sabbakāyapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**They practice breathing in experiencing the whole body. They practice breathing out experiencing the whole body.*";
P_HTM[2890]="*‘passambhayaṃ kāyasaṅkhāraṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘passambhayaṃ kāyasaṅkhāraṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati. (1)**They practice breathing in stilling the body’s motion. They practice breathing out stilling the body’s motion.*";
P_HTM[2891]="*‘Pītipaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘pītipaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**They practice breathing in experiencing rapture. They practice breathing out experiencing rapture.*";
P_HTM[2892]="*‘sukhapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘sukhapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**They practice breathing in experiencing bliss. They practice breathing out experiencing bliss.*";
P_HTM[2893]="*‘cittasaṅkhārapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘cittasaṅkhārapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**They practice breathing in experiencing these emotions. They practice breathing out experiencing these emotions.*";
P_HTM[2894]="*‘passambhayaṃ cittasaṅkhāraṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘passambhayaṃ cittasaṅkhāraṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati. (2)**They practice breathing in stilling these emotions. They practice breathing out stilling these emotions.*";
P_HTM[2895]="*‘Cittapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘cittapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**They practice breathing in experiencing the mind. They practice breathing out experiencing the mind.*";
P_HTM[2896]="*‘abhippamodayaṃ cittaṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘abhippamodayaṃ cittaṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**They practice breathing in gladdening the mind. They practice breathing out gladdening the mind.*";
P_HTM[2897]="*‘samādahaṃ cittaṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘samādahaṃ cittaṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**They practice breathing in immersing the mind in samādhi. They practice breathing out immersing the mind in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[2898]="*‘vimocayaṃ cittaṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘vimocayaṃ cittaṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati. (3)**They practice breathing in freeing the mind. They practice breathing out freeing the mind.*";
P_HTM[2899]="*‘Aniccānupassī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘aniccānupassī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**They practice breathing in observing impermanence. They practice breathing out observing impermanence.*";
P_HTM[2900]="*‘virāgānupassī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘virāgānupassī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**They practice breathing in observing fading away. They practice breathing out observing fading away.*";
P_HTM[2901]="*‘nirodhānupassī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘nirodhānupassī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**They practice breathing in observing cessation. They practice breathing out observing cessation.*";
P_HTM[2902]="*‘paṭinissaggānupassī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘paṭinissaggānupassī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati.**They practice breathing in observing letting go. They practice breathing out observing letting go.*";
P_HTM[2903]="*Evaṃ bhāvitā kho, bhikkhave, ānāpānassati evaṃ bahulīkatā mahapphalā hoti mahānisaṃsā. (4)**Mindfulness of breathing, when developed and cultivated in this way, is very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[2904]="*Kathaṃ bhāvitā ca, bhikkhave, ānāpānassati kathaṃ bahulīkatā cattāro satipaṭṭhāne paripūreti?**And how is mindfulness of breathing developed and cultivated so as to fulfill the four kinds of mindfulness meditation?*";
P_HTM[2905]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu dīghaṃ vā assasanto ‘dīghaṃ assasāmī’ti pajānāti, dīghaṃ vā passasanto ‘dīghaṃ passasāmī’ti pajānāti;**Whenever a mendicant knows that they breathe heavily,*";
P_HTM[2906]="*rassaṃ vā assasanto ‘rassaṃ assasāmī’ti pajānāti, rassaṃ vā passasanto ‘rassaṃ passasāmī’ti pajānāti;**or lightly,*";
P_HTM[2907]="*‘sabbakāyapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘sabbakāyapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**or experiencing the whole body,*";
P_HTM[2908]="*‘passambhayaṃ kāyasaṅkhāraṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘passambhayaṃ kāyasaṅkhāraṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**or stilling the body’s motion—*";
P_HTM[2909]="*kāye kāyānupassī, bhikkhave, tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**at that time they’re meditating by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2910]="*Kāyesu kāyaññatarāhaṃ, bhikkhave, evaṃ vadāmi yadidaṃ—assāsapassāsā.**For I say that the in-breaths and out-breaths are an aspect of the body.*";
P_HTM[2911]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, kāye kāyānupassī tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ. (1)**That’s why at that time a mendicant is meditating by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2912]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ‘pītipaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘pītipaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**Whenever a mendicant practices breathing while experiencing rapture,*";
P_HTM[2913]="*‘sukhapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘sukhapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**or experiencing bliss,*";
P_HTM[2914]="*‘cittasaṅkhārapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘cittasaṅkhārapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**or experiencing these emotions,*";
P_HTM[2915]="*‘passambhayaṃ cittasaṅkhāraṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘passambhayaṃ cittasaṅkhāraṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**or stilling these emotions—*";
P_HTM[2916]="*vedanāsu vedanānupassī, bhikkhave, tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**at that time they meditate observing an aspect of feelings—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2917]="*Vedanāsu vedanāññatarāhaṃ, bhikkhave, evaṃ vadāmi yadidaṃ—assāsapassāsānaṃ sādhukaṃ manasikāraṃ.**For I say that close attention to the in-breaths and out-breaths is an aspect of feelings.*";
P_HTM[2918]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, vedanāsu vedanānupassī tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ. (2)**That’s why at that time a mendicant is meditating by observing an aspect of feelings—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2919]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ‘cittapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘cittapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**Whenever a mendicant practices breathing while experiencing the mind,*";
P_HTM[2920]="*‘abhippamodayaṃ cittaṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘abhippamodayaṃ cittaṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**or gladdening the mind,*";
P_HTM[2921]="*‘samādahaṃ cittaṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘samādahaṃ cittaṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**or immersing the mind in samādhi,*";
P_HTM[2922]="*‘vimocayaṃ cittaṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘vimocayaṃ cittaṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**or freeing the mind—*";
P_HTM[2923]="*citte cittānupassī, bhikkhave, tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**at that time they meditate observing an aspect of the mind—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2924]="*Nāhaṃ, bhikkhave, muṭṭhassatissa asampajānassa ānāpānassatiṃ vadāmi.**There is no development of mindfulness of breathing for someone who is unmindful and lacks awareness, I say.*";
P_HTM[2925]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, citte cittānupassī tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ. (3)**That’s why at that time a mendicant is meditating by observing an aspect of the mind—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2926]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ‘aniccānupassī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘aniccānupassī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**Whenever a mendicant practices breathing while observing impermanence,*";
P_HTM[2927]="*‘virāgānupassī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘virāgānupassī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**or observing fading away,*";
P_HTM[2928]="*‘nirodhānupassī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘nirodhānupassī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**or observing cessation,*";
P_HTM[2929]="*‘paṭinissaggānupassī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘paṭinissaggānupassī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**or observing letting go—*";
P_HTM[2930]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī, bhikkhave, tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**at that time they meditate observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2931]="*So yaṃ taṃ abhijjhādomanassānaṃ pahānaṃ taṃ paññāya disvā sādhukaṃ ajjhupekkhitā hoti.**Having seen with wisdom the giving up of desire and aversion, they watch over closely with equanimity.*";
P_HTM[2932]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, dhammesu dhammānupassī tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ. (4)**That’s why at that time a mendicant is meditating by observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2933]="*Evaṃ bhāvitā kho, bhikkhave, ānāpānassati evaṃ bahulīkatā cattāro satipaṭṭhāne paripūreti.**That’s how mindfulness of breathing, when developed and cultivated, fulfills the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[2934]="*Kathaṃ bhāvitā ca, bhikkhave, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā kathaṃ bahulīkatā satta bojjhaṅge paripūrenti?**And how are the four kinds of mindfulness meditation developed and cultivated so as to fulfill the seven awakening factors?*";
P_HTM[2935]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ, upaṭṭhitāssa tasmiṃ samaye sati hoti asammuṭṭhā.**Whenever a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body, at that time their mindfulness is established and lucid.*";
P_HTM[2936]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno upaṭṭhitā sati hoti asammuṭṭhā, satisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti. Satisambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, satisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (1)**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of mindfulness; they develop it and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[2937]="*So tathāsato viharanto taṃ dhammaṃ paññāya pavicinati pavicayati parivīmaṃsaṃ āpajjati.**As they live mindfully in this way they investigate, explore, and inquire into that principle with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[2938]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu tathāsato viharanto taṃ dhammaṃ paññāya pavicinati pavicayati parivīmaṃsaṃ āpajjati, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (2)**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of investigation of principles; they develop it and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[2939]="*Tassa taṃ dhammaṃ paññāya pavicinato pavicayato parivīmaṃsaṃ āpajjato āraddhaṃ hoti vīriyaṃ asallīnaṃ.**As they investigate principles with wisdom in this way their energy is roused up and unflagging.*";
P_HTM[2940]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno taṃ dhammaṃ paññāya pavicinato pavicayato parivīmaṃsaṃ āpajjato āraddhaṃ hoti vīriyaṃ asallīnaṃ, vīriyasambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, vīriyasambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, vīriyasambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (3)**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of energy; they develop it and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[2941]="*Āraddhavīriyassa uppajjati pīti nirāmisā.**When they’re energetic, spiritual rapture arises.*";
P_HTM[2942]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno āraddhavīriyassa uppajjati pīti nirāmisā, pītisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, pītisambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, pītisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (4)**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of rapture; they develop it and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[2943]="*Pītimanassa kāyopi passambhati, cittampi passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body and mind become tranquil.*";
P_HTM[2944]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno pītimanassa kāyopi passambhati, cittampi passambhati, passaddhisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, passaddhisambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, passaddhisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (5)**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of tranquility; they develop it and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[2945]="*Passaddhakāyassa sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**When the body is tranquil and they feel bliss, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[2946]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno passaddhakāyassa sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati, samādhisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, samādhisambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, samādhisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (6)**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of immersion; they develop it and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[2947]="*So tathāsamāhitaṃ cittaṃ sādhukaṃ ajjhupekkhitā hoti.**They closely watch over that mind immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[2948]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu tathāsamāhitaṃ cittaṃ sādhukaṃ ajjhupekkhitā hoti, upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (7)**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of equanimity; they develop it and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[2949]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vedanāsu … pe …**Whenever a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[2950]="*citte …**mind …*";
P_HTM[2951]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ, upaṭṭhitāssa tasmiṃ samaye sati hoti asammuṭṭhā.**principles, at that time their mindfulness is established and lucid.*";
P_HTM[2952]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno upaṭṭhitā sati hoti asammuṭṭhā, satisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, satisambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, satisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (1)**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of mindfulness …*";
P_HTM[2953]="*So tathāsato viharanto taṃ dhammaṃ paññāya pavicinati pavicayati parivīmaṃsaṃ āpajjati.* **";
P_HTM[2954]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu tathāsato viharanto taṃ dhammaṃ paññāya pavicinati pavicayati parivīmaṃsaṃ āpajjati, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (2)**investigation of principles …*";
P_HTM[2955]="*Tassa taṃ dhammaṃ paññāya pavicinato pavicayato parivīmaṃsaṃ āpajjato āraddhaṃ hoti vīriyaṃ asallīnaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2956]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno taṃ dhammaṃ paññāya pavicinato pavicayato parivīmaṃsaṃ āpajjato āraddhaṃ hoti vīriyaṃ asallīnaṃ, vīriyasambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, vīriyasambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, vīriyasambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (3)**energy …*";
P_HTM[2957]="*Āraddhavīriyassa uppajjati pīti nirāmisā.* **";
P_HTM[2958]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno āraddhavīriyassa uppajjati pīti nirāmisā, pītisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, pītisambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, pītisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (4)**rapture …*";
P_HTM[2959]="*Pītimanassa kāyopi passambhati, cittampi passambhati.* **";
P_HTM[2960]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno pītimanassa kāyopi passambhati, cittampi passambhati, passaddhisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, passaddhisambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, passaddhisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (5)**tranquility …*";
P_HTM[2961]="*Passaddhakāyassa sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.* **";
P_HTM[2962]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno passaddhakāyassa sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati, samādhisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, samādhisambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, samādhisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati. (6)**immersion …*";
P_HTM[2963]="*So tathāsamāhitaṃ cittaṃ sādhukaṃ ajjhupekkhitā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2964]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu tathāsamāhitaṃ cittaṃ sādhukaṃ ajjhupekkhitā hoti, upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti, upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti, upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati.**equanimity.*";
P_HTM[2965]="*Evaṃ bhāvitā kho, bhikkhave, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā evaṃ bahulīkatā satta sambojjhaṅge paripūrenti. (7)**That’s how the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, when developed and cultivated, fulfill the seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[2966]="*Kathaṃ bhāvitā ca, bhikkhave, satta bojjhaṅgā kathaṃ bahulīkatā vijjāvimuttiṃ paripūrenti?**And how are the seven awakening factors developed and cultivated so as to fulfill knowledge and freedom?*";
P_HTM[2967]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ. Dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pe … vīriyasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pītisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … passaddhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … samādhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[2968]="*Evaṃ bhāvitā kho, bhikkhave, satta bojjhaṅgā evaṃ bahulīkatā vijjāvimuttiṃ paripūrentī”ti.**That’s how the seven awakening factors, when developed and cultivated, fulfill knowledge and freedom.”*";
P_HTM[2969]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2970]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2971]="*Ānāpānassatisuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2972]="*119. Kāyagatāsatisutta**Mindfulness of the Body*";
P_HTM[2973]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2974]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[2975]="*Atha kho sambahulānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantānaṃ upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ ayamantarākathā udapādi:**Then after the meal, on return from alms-round, several senior mendicants sat together in the pavilion and this discussion came up among them.*";
P_HTM[2976]="*“acchariyaṃ, āvuso, abbhutaṃ, āvuso.**“It’s incredible, reverends, it’s amazing,*";
P_HTM[2977]="*Yāvañcidaṃ tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena kāyagatāsati bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahapphalā vuttā mahānisaṃsā”ti.**how the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha has said that mindfulness of the body, when developed and cultivated, is very fruitful and beneficial.”*";
P_HTM[2978]="*Ayañca hidaṃ tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ antarākathā vippakatā hoti, atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yena upaṭṭhānasālā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**But their conversation was left unfinished when the Buddha came out of retreat and went to the pavilion. He sat on the seat spread out*";
P_HTM[2979]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**and addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2980]="*“kāya nuttha, bhikkhave, etarahi kathāya sannisinnā, kā ca pana vo antarākathā vippakatā”ti?**“Mendicants, what were you sitting talking about just now? What conversation was unfinished?”*";
P_HTM[2981]="*“Idha, bhante, amhākaṃ pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantānaṃ upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ ayamantarākathā udapādi:**So the mendicants told him what they had been talking about when the Buddha arrived. The Buddha said:*";
P_HTM[2982]="*‘acchariyaṃ, āvuso, abbhutaṃ, āvuso.* **";
P_HTM[2983]="*Yāvañcidaṃ tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena kāyagatāsati bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahapphalā vuttā mahānisaṃsā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2984]="*Ayaṃ kho no, bhante, antarākathā vippakatā, atha bhagavā anuppatto”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2985]="*“Kathaṃ bhāvitā ca, bhikkhave, kāyagatāsati kathaṃ bahulīkatā mahapphalā hoti mahānisaṃsā?**“And how, mendicants, is mindfulness of the body developed and cultivated to be very fruitful and beneficial?*";
P_HTM[2986]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu araññagato vā rukkhamūlagato vā suññāgāragato vā nisīdati pallaṅkaṃ ābhujitvā ujuṃ kāyaṃ paṇidhāya parimukhaṃ satiṃ upaṭṭhapetvā.**It’s when a mendicant has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut. They sit down cross-legged, with their body straight, and establish mindfulness right there.*";
P_HTM[2987]="*So satova assasati satova passasati;**Just mindful, they breathe in. Mindful, they breathe out.*";
P_HTM[2988]="*dīghaṃ vā assasanto ‘dīghaṃ assasāmī’ti pajānāti, dīghaṃ vā passasanto ‘dīghaṃ passasāmī’ti pajānāti;**When breathing in heavily they know: ‘I’m breathing in heavily.’ When breathing out heavily they know: ‘I’m breathing out heavily.’*";
P_HTM[2989]="*rassaṃ vā assasanto ‘rassaṃ assasāmī’ti pajānāti, rassaṃ vā passasanto ‘rassaṃ passasāmī’ti pajānāti;**When breathing in lightly they know: ‘I’m breathing in lightly.’ When breathing out lightly they know: ‘I’m breathing out lightly.’*";
P_HTM[2990]="*‘sabbakāyapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘sabbakāyapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati;**They practice breathing in experiencing the whole body. They practice breathing out experiencing the whole body.*";
P_HTM[2991]="*‘passambhayaṃ kāyasaṅkhāraṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati, ‘passambhayaṃ kāyasaṅkhāraṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati.**They practice breathing in stilling the body’s motion. They practice breathing out stilling the body’s motion.*";
P_HTM[2992]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato ye gehasitā sarasaṅkappā te pahīyanti.**As they meditate like this—diligent, keen, and resolute—memories and thoughts of the lay life are given up.*";
P_HTM[2993]="*Tesaṃ pahānā ajjhattameva cittaṃ santiṭṭhati sannisīdati ekodi hoti samādhiyati.**Their mind becomes stilled internally; it settles, unifies, and becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[2994]="*Evaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (1)**That’s how a mendicant develops mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[2995]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu gacchanto vā ‘gacchāmī’ti pajānāti, ṭhito vā ‘ṭhitomhī’ti pajānāti, nisinno vā ‘nisinnomhī’ti pajānāti, sayāno vā ‘sayānomhī’ti pajānāti.**Furthermore, when a mendicant is walking they know ‘I am walking’. When standing they know ‘I am standing’. When sitting they know ‘I am sitting’. And when lying down they know ‘I am lying down’.*";
P_HTM[2996]="*Yathā yathā vā panassa kāyo paṇihito hoti tathā tathā naṃ pajānāti.**Whatever posture their body is in, they know it.*";
P_HTM[2997]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato ye gehasitā sarasaṅkappā te pahīyanti.**As they meditate like this—diligent, keen, and resolute—memories and thoughts of the lay life are given up.*";
P_HTM[2998]="*Tesaṃ pahānā ajjhattameva cittaṃ santiṭṭhati sannisīdati ekodi hoti samādhiyati.**Their mind becomes stilled internally; it settles, unifies, and becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[2999]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (2)**That too is how a mendicant develops mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[3000]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu abhikkante paṭikkante sampajānakārī hoti, ālokite vilokite sampajānakārī hoti, samiñjite pasārite sampajānakārī hoti, saṅghāṭipattacīvaradhāraṇe sampajānakārī hoti, asite pīte khāyite sāyite sampajānakārī hoti, uccārapassāvakamme sampajānakārī hoti, gate ṭhite nisinne sutte jāgarite bhāsite tuṇhībhāve sampajānakārī hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant acts with situational awareness when going out and coming back; when looking ahead and aside; when bending and extending the limbs; when bearing the outer robe, bowl and robes; when eating, drinking, chewing, and tasting; when urinating and defecating; when walking, standing, sitting, sleeping, waking, speaking, and keeping silent.*";
P_HTM[3001]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato ye gehasitā sarasaṅkappā te pahīyanti.**As they meditate like this—diligent, keen, and resolute—memories and thoughts of the lay life are given up.*";
P_HTM[3002]="*Tesaṃ pahānā ajjhattameva cittaṃ santiṭṭhati sannisīdati ekodi hoti samādhiyati.**Their mind becomes stilled internally; it settles, unifies, and becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[3003]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (3)**That too is how a mendicant develops mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[3004]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ uddhaṃ pādatalā adho kesamatthakā tacapariyantaṃ pūraṃ nānappakārassa asucino paccavekkhati:**Furthermore, a mendicant examines their own body, up from the soles of the feet and down from the tips of the hairs, wrapped in skin and full of many kinds of filth.*";
P_HTM[3005]="*‘atthi imasmiṃ kāye kesā lomā nakhā dantā taco maṃsaṃ nhāru aṭṭhi aṭṭhimiñjaṃ vakkaṃ hadayaṃ yakanaṃ kilomakaṃ pihakaṃ papphāsaṃ antaṃ antaguṇaṃ udariyaṃ karīsaṃ pittaṃ semhaṃ pubbo lohitaṃ sedo medo assu vasā kheḷo siṅghāṇikā lasikā muttan’ti.**‘In this body there is head hair, body hair, nails, teeth, skin, flesh, sinews, bones, bone marrow, kidneys, heart, liver, diaphragm, spleen, lungs, intestines, mesentery, undigested food, feces, bile, phlegm, pus, blood, sweat, fat, tears, grease, saliva, snot, synovial fluid, urine.’*";
P_HTM[3006]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ubhatomukhā putoḷi pūrā nānāvihitassa dhaññassa, seyyathidaṃ—**It’s as if there were a bag with openings at both ends, filled with various kinds of grains, such as*";
P_HTM[3007]="*sālīnaṃ vīhīnaṃ muggānaṃ māsānaṃ tilānaṃ taṇḍulānaṃ,**fine rice, wheat, mung beans, peas, sesame, and ordinary rice.*";
P_HTM[3008]="*tamenaṃ cakkhumā puriso muñcitvā paccavekkheyya:**And someone with good eyesight were to open it and examine the contents:*";
P_HTM[3009]="*‘ime sālī ime vīhī ime muggā ime māsā ime tilā ime taṇḍulā’ti;**‘These grains are fine rice, these are wheat, these are mung beans, these are peas, these are sesame, and these are ordinary rice.’*";
P_HTM[3010]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ uddhaṃ pādatalā adho kesamatthakā tacapariyantaṃ pūraṃ nānappakārassa asucino paccavekkhati:**In the same way, a mendicant examines their own body, up from the soles of the feet and down from the tips of the hairs, wrapped in skin and full of many kinds of filth. …*";
P_HTM[3011]="*‘atthi imasmiṃ kāye kesā lomā nakhā dantā taco maṃsaṃ nhāru aṭṭhi aṭṭhimiñjaṃ vakkaṃ hadayaṃ yakanaṃ kilomakaṃ pihakaṃ papphāsaṃ antaṃ antaguṇaṃ udariyaṃ karīsaṃ pittaṃ semhaṃ pubbo lohitaṃ sedo medo assu vasā kheḷo siṅghāṇikā lasikā muttan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3012]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato ye gehasitā sarasaṅkappā te pahīyanti.**As they meditate like this—diligent, keen, and resolute—memories and thoughts of the lay life are given up.*";
P_HTM[3013]="*Tesaṃ pahānā ajjhattameva cittaṃ santiṭṭhati sannisīdati ekodi hoti samādhiyati.**Their mind becomes stilled internally; it settles, unifies, and becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[3014]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (4)**That too is how a mendicant develops mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[3015]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ yathāṭhitaṃ yathāpaṇihitaṃ dhātuso paccavekkhati:**Furthermore, a mendicant examines their own body, whatever its placement or posture, according to the elements:*";
P_HTM[3016]="*‘atthi imasmiṃ kāye pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū’ti.**‘In this body there is the earth element, the water element, the fire element, and the air element.’*";
P_HTM[3017]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, dakkho goghātako vā goghātakantevāsī vā gāviṃ vadhitvā catumahāpathe bilaso vibhajitvā nisinno assa;**It’s as if a deft butcher or butcher’s apprentice were to kill a cow and sit down at the crossroads with the meat cut into portions.*";
P_HTM[3018]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ yathāṭhitaṃ yathāpaṇihitaṃ dhātuso paccavekkhati:**In the same way, a mendicant examines their own body, whatever its placement or posture, according to the elements:*";
P_HTM[3019]="*‘atthi imasmiṃ kāye pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū’ti.**‘In this body there is the earth element, the water element, the fire element, and the air element.’*";
P_HTM[3020]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato ye gehasitā sarasaṅkappā te pahīyanti.**As they meditate like this—diligent, keen, and resolute—memories and thoughts of the lay life are given up.*";
P_HTM[3021]="*Tesaṃ pahānā ajjhattameva cittaṃ santiṭṭhati sannisīdati ekodi hoti samādhiyati.**Their mind becomes stilled internally; it settles, unifies, and becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[3022]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (5)**That too is how a mendicant develops mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[3023]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu seyyathāpi passeyya sarīraṃ sivathikāya chaḍḍitaṃ ekāhamataṃ vā dvīhamataṃ vā tīhamataṃ vā uddhumātakaṃ vinīlakaṃ vipubbakajātaṃ.**Furthermore, suppose a mendicant were to see a corpse discarded in a charnel ground. And it had been dead for one, two, or three days, bloated, livid, and festering.*";
P_HTM[3024]="*So imameva kāyaṃ upasaṃharati:**They’d compare it with their own body:*";
P_HTM[3025]="*‘ayampi kho kāyo evaṃdhammo evaṃbhāvī evaṃanatīto’ti.**‘This body is also of that same nature, that same kind, and cannot go beyond that.’*";
P_HTM[3026]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato ye gehasitā sarasaṅkappā te pahīyanti.**As they meditate like this—diligent, keen, and resolute—memories and thoughts of the lay life are given up.*";
P_HTM[3027]="*Tesaṃ pahānā ajjhattameva cittaṃ santiṭṭhati sannisīdati ekodi hoti samādhiyati.**Their mind becomes stilled internally; it settles, unifies, and becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[3028]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (6)**That too is how a mendicant develops mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[3029]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu seyyathāpi passeyya sarīraṃ sivathikāya chaḍḍitaṃ kākehi vā khajjamānaṃ kulalehi vā khajjamānaṃ gijjhehi vā khajjamānaṃ kaṅkehi vā khajjamānaṃ sunakhehi vā khajjamānaṃ byagghehi vā khajjamānaṃ dīpīhi vā khajjamānaṃ siṅgālehi vā khajjamānaṃ vividhehi vā pāṇakajātehi khajjamānaṃ.**Or suppose they were to see a corpse discarded in a charnel ground being devoured by crows, hawks, vultures, herons, dogs, tigers, leopards, jackals, and many kinds of little creatures.*";
P_HTM[3030]="*So imameva kāyaṃ upasaṃharati:**They’d compare it with their own body:*";
P_HTM[3031]="*‘ayampi kho kāyo evaṃdhammo evaṃbhāvī evaṃanatīto’ti.**‘This body is also of that same nature, that same kind, and cannot go beyond that.’*";
P_HTM[3032]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3033]="*evampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (7)**That too is how a mendicant develops mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[3034]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu seyyathāpi passeyya sarīraṃ sivathikāya chaḍḍitaṃ aṭṭhikasaṅkhalikaṃ samaṃsalohitaṃ nhārusambandhaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, suppose they were to see a corpse discarded in a charnel ground, a skeleton with flesh and blood, held together by sinews …*";
P_HTM[3035]="*aṭṭhikasaṅkhalikaṃ nimmaṃsalohitamakkhitaṃ nhārusambandhaṃ … pe …**A skeleton without flesh but smeared with blood, and held together by sinews …*";
P_HTM[3036]="*aṭṭhikasaṅkhalikaṃ apagatamaṃsalohitaṃ nhārusambandhaṃ … pe …**A skeleton rid of flesh and blood, held together by sinews …*";
P_HTM[3037]="*aṭṭhikāni apagatasambandhāni disāvidisāvikkhittāni aññena hatthaṭṭhikaṃ aññena pādaṭṭhikaṃ aññena gopphakaṭṭhikaṃ aññena jaṅghaṭṭhikaṃ aññena ūruṭṭhikaṃ aññena kaṭiṭṭhikaṃ aññena phāsukaṭṭhikaṃ aññena piṭṭhiṭṭhikaṃ aññena khandhaṭṭhikaṃ aññena gīvaṭṭhikaṃ aññena hanukaṭṭhikaṃ aññena dantaṭṭhikaṃ aññena sīsakaṭāhaṃ.**Bones without sinews scattered in every direction. Here a hand-bone, there a foot-bone, here a shin-bone, there a thigh-bone, here a hip-bone, there a rib-bone, here a back-bone, there an arm-bone, here a neck-bone, there a jaw-bone, here a tooth, there the skull …*";
P_HTM[3038]="*So imameva kāyaṃ upasaṃharati:* **";
P_HTM[3039]="*‘ayampi kho kāyo evaṃdhammo evaṃbhāvī evaṃanatīto’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3040]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3041]="*evampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (8–11.)* **";
P_HTM[3042]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu seyyathāpi passeyya sarīraṃ sivathikāya chaḍḍitaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[3043]="*aṭṭhikāni setāni saṅkhavaṇṇapaṭibhāgāni … pe …**White bones, the color of shells …*";
P_HTM[3044]="*aṭṭhikāni puñjakitāni terovassikāni … pe …**Decrepit bones, heaped in a pile …*";
P_HTM[3045]="*aṭṭhikāni pūtīni cuṇṇakajātāni.**Bones rotted and crumbled to powder.*";
P_HTM[3046]="*So imameva kāyaṃ upasaṃharati:**They’d compare it with their own body:*";
P_HTM[3047]="*‘ayampi kho kāyo evaṃdhammo evaṃbhāvī evaṃanatīto’ti.**‘This body is also of that same nature, that same kind, and cannot go beyond that.’*";
P_HTM[3048]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa …**As they meditate like this—diligent, keen, and resolute—memories and thoughts of the lay life are given up.*";
P_HTM[3049]="*pe …**Their mind becomes stilled internally; it settles, unifies, and becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[3050]="*evampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (12–14.)**That too is how a mendicant develops mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[3051]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[3052]="*So imameva kāyaṃ vivekajena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa vivekajena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**They drench, steep, fill, and spread their body with rapture and bliss born of seclusion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of seclusion.*";
P_HTM[3053]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, dakkho nhāpako vā nhāpakantevāsī vā kaṃsathāle nhānīyacuṇṇāni ākiritvā udakena paripphosakaṃ paripphosakaṃ sanneyya, sāyaṃ nhānīyapiṇḍi snehānugatā snehaparetā santarabāhirā phuṭā snehena na ca pagghariṇī;**It’s like when a deft bathroom attendant or their apprentice pours bath powder into a bronze dish, sprinkling it little by little with water. They knead it until the ball of bath powder is soaked and saturated with moisture, spread through inside and out; yet no moisture oozes out.*";
P_HTM[3054]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ vivekajena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati; nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa vivekajena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**In the same way, they drench, steep, fill, and spread their body with rapture and bliss born of seclusion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of seclusion.*";
P_HTM[3055]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa …**As they meditate like this—diligent, keen, and resolute—memories and thoughts of the lay life are given up.*";
P_HTM[3056]="*pe …**Their mind becomes stilled internally; it settles, unifies, and becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[3057]="*evampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (15)**That too is how a mendicant develops mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[3058]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā … pe … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, a mendicant enters and remains in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[3059]="*So imameva kāyaṃ samādhijena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati; nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa samādhijena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**They drench, steep, fill, and spread their body with rapture and bliss born of immersion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of immersion.*";
P_HTM[3060]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, udakarahado gambhīro ubbhidodako. Tassa nevassa puratthimāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ na pacchimāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ na uttarāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ na dakkhiṇāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ; devo ca na kālena kālaṃ sammā dhāraṃ anuppaveccheyya; atha kho tamhāva udakarahadā sītā vāridhārā ubbhijjitvā tameva udakarahadaṃ sītena vārinā abhisandeyya parisandeyya paripūreyya paripphareyya, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato udakarahadassa sītena vārinā apphuṭaṃ assa;**It’s like a deep lake fed by spring water. There’s no inlet to the east, west, north, or south, and no rainfall to replenish it from time to time. But the stream of cool water welling up in the lake drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads throughout the lake. There’s no part of the lake that’s not spread through with cool water.*";
P_HTM[3061]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ samādhijena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa samādhijena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**In the same way, a mendicant drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads their body with rapture and bliss born of immersion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of immersion.*";
P_HTM[3062]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3063]="*evampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (16)**That too is how a mendicant develops mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[3064]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā … pe … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, with the fading away of rapture, a mendicant enters and remains in the third absorption. They meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[3065]="*So imameva kāyaṃ nippītikena sukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa nippītikena sukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**They drench, steep, fill, and spread their body with bliss free of rapture. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with bliss free of rapture.*";
P_HTM[3066]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, uppaliniyaṃ vā paduminiyaṃ vā puṇḍarīkiniyaṃ vā appekaccāni uppalāni vā padumāni vā puṇḍarīkāni vā udake jātāni udake saṃvaḍḍhāni udakānuggatāni antonimuggaposīni, tāni yāva caggā yāva ca mūlā sītena vārinā abhisannāni parisannāni paripūrāni paripphuṭāni, nāssa kiñci sabbāvataṃ uppalānaṃ vā padumānaṃ vā puṇḍarīkānaṃ vā sītena vārinā apphuṭaṃ assa;**It’s like a pool with blue water lilies, or pink or white lotuses. Some of them sprout and grow in the water without rising above it, thriving underwater. From the tip to the root they’re drenched, steeped, filled, and soaked with cool water. There’s no part of them that’s not soaked with cool water.*";
P_HTM[3067]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ nippītikena sukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa nippītikena sukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**In the same way, a mendicant drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads their body with bliss free of rapture. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with bliss free of rapture.*";
P_HTM[3068]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3069]="*evampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (17)**That too is how a mendicant develops mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[3070]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā … pe … catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, a mendicant, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, enters and remains in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[3071]="*So imameva kāyaṃ parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena pharitvā nisinno hoti; nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**They sit spreading their body through with pure bright mind. There’s no part of the body that’s not filled with pure bright mind.*";
P_HTM[3072]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso odātena vatthena sasīsaṃ pārupitvā nisinno assa, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa odātena vatthena apphuṭaṃ assa;**It’s like someone sitting wrapped from head to foot with white cloth. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread over with white cloth.*";
P_HTM[3073]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena pharitvā nisinno hoti, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**In the same way, they sit spreading their body through with pure bright mind. There’s no part of the body that’s not filled with pure bright mind.*";
P_HTM[3074]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato ye gehasitā sarasaṅkappā te pahīyanti.**As they meditate like this—diligent, keen, and resolute—memories and thoughts of the lay life are given up.*";
P_HTM[3075]="*Tesaṃ pahānā ajjhattameva cittaṃ santiṭṭhati, sannisīdati ekodi hoti samādhiyati.**Their mind becomes stilled internally; it settles, unifies, and becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[3076]="*Evampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyagatāsatiṃ bhāveti. (18)**That too is how a mendicant develops mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[3077]="*Yassa kassaci, bhikkhave, kāyagatāsati bhāvitā bahulīkatā, antogadhāvāssa kusalā dhammā ye keci vijjābhāgiyā.**Anyone who has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body includes all of the skillful qualities that play a part in realization.*";
P_HTM[3078]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yassa kassaci mahāsamuddo cetasā phuṭo, antogadhāvāssa kunnadiyo yā kāci samuddaṅgamā;**Anyone who brings into their mind the great ocean includes all of the streams that run down into it.*";
P_HTM[3079]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, yassa kassaci kāyagatāsati bhāvitā bahulīkatā, antogadhāvāssa kusalā dhammā ye keci vijjābhāgiyā.**In the same way, anyone who has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body includes all of the skillful qualities that play a part in realization.*";
P_HTM[3080]="*Yassa kassaci, bhikkhave, kāyagatāsati abhāvitā abahulīkatā, labhati tassa māro otāraṃ, labhati tassa māro ārammaṇaṃ.**When a mendicant has not developed or cultivated mindfulness of the body, Māra finds a vulnerability and gets hold of them.*";
P_HTM[3081]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso garukaṃ silāguḷaṃ allamattikāpuñje pakkhipeyya.**Suppose a person were to throw a heavy stone ball on a mound of wet clay.*";
P_HTM[3082]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[3083]="*api nu taṃ garukaṃ silāguḷaṃ allamattikāpuñje labhetha otāran”ti?**Would that heavy stone ball find an entry into that mound of wet clay?”*";
P_HTM[3084]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3085]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yassa kassaci kāyagatāsati abhāvitā abahulīkatā, labhati tassa māro otāraṃ, labhati tassa māro ārammaṇaṃ.**“In the same way, when a mendicant has not developed or cultivated mindfulness of the body, Māra finds a vulnerability and gets hold of them.*";
P_HTM[3086]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, sukkhaṃ kaṭṭhaṃ koḷāpaṃ;**Suppose there was a dried up, withered log.*";
P_HTM[3087]="*atha puriso āgaccheyya uttarāraṇiṃ ādāya:**Then a person comes along with a drill-stick, thinking*";
P_HTM[3088]="*‘aggiṃ abhinibbattessāmi, tejo pātukarissāmī’ti.**to light a fire and produce heat.*";
P_HTM[3089]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[3090]="*api nu so puriso amuṃ sukkhaṃ kaṭṭhaṃ koḷāpaṃ uttarāraṇiṃ ādāya abhimanthento aggiṃ abhinibbatteyya, tejo pātukareyyā”ti?**By drilling the stick against that dried up, withered log on dry land far from water, could they light a fire and produce heat?”*";
P_HTM[3091]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3092]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yassa kassaci kāyagatāsati abhāvitā abahulīkatā, labhati tassa māro otāraṃ, labhati tassa māro ārammaṇaṃ.**“In the same way, when a mendicant has not developed or cultivated mindfulness of the body, Māra finds a vulnerability and gets hold of them.*";
P_HTM[3093]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, udakamaṇiko ritto tuccho ādhāre ṭhapito;**Suppose a water jar was placed on a stand, empty and hollow.*";
P_HTM[3094]="*atha puriso āgaccheyya udakabhāraṃ ādāya.**Then a person comes along with a load of water.*";
P_HTM[3095]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[3096]="*api nu so puriso labhetha udakassa nikkhepanan”ti?**Could that person pour water into the jar?”*";
P_HTM[3097]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3098]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yassa kassaci kāyagatāsati abhāvitā abahulīkatā, labhati tassa māro otāraṃ, labhati tassa māro ārammaṇaṃ.**“In the same way, when a mendicant has not developed or cultivated mindfulness of the body, Māra finds a vulnerability and gets hold of them.*";
P_HTM[3099]="*Yassa kassaci, bhikkhave, kāyagatāsati bhāvitā bahulīkatā, na tassa labhati māro otāraṃ, na tassa labhati māro ārammaṇaṃ.**When a mendicant has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body, Māra cannot find a vulnerability and doesn’t get hold of them.*";
P_HTM[3100]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso lahukaṃ suttaguḷaṃ sabbasāramaye aggaḷaphalake pakkhipeyya.**Suppose a person were to throw a light ball of string at a door-panel made entirely of hardwood.*";
P_HTM[3101]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[3102]="*api nu so puriso taṃ lahukaṃ suttaguḷaṃ sabbasāramaye aggaḷaphalake labhetha otāran”ti?**Would that light ball of string find an entry into that door-panel made entirely of hardwood?”*";
P_HTM[3103]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3104]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yassa kassaci kāyagatāsati bhāvitā bahulīkatā, na tassa labhati māro otāraṃ, na tassa labhati māro ārammaṇaṃ.**“In the same way, when a mendicant has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body, Māra cannot find a vulnerability and doesn’t get hold of them.*";
P_HTM[3105]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, allaṃ kaṭṭhaṃ sasnehaṃ;**Suppose there was a green, sappy log.*";
P_HTM[3106]="*atha puriso āgaccheyya uttarāraṇiṃ ādāya:**Then a person comes along with a drill-stick, thinking*";
P_HTM[3107]="*‘aggiṃ abhinibbattessāmi, tejo pātukarissāmī’ti.**to light a fire and produce heat.*";
P_HTM[3108]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[3109]="*api nu so puriso amuṃ allaṃ kaṭṭhaṃ sasnehaṃ uttarāraṇiṃ ādāya abhimanthento aggiṃ abhinibbatteyya, tejo pātukareyyā”ti?**By drilling the stick against that green, sappy log on dry land far from water, could they light a fire and produce heat?”*";
P_HTM[3110]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3111]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yassa kassaci kāyagatāsati bhāvitā bahulīkatā, na tassa labhati māro otāraṃ, na tassa labhati māro ārammaṇaṃ.**“In the same way, when a mendicant has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body, Māra cannot find a vulnerability and doesn’t get hold of them.*";
P_HTM[3112]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, udakamaṇiko pūro udakassa samatittiko kākapeyyo ādhāre ṭhapito;**Suppose a water jar was placed on a stand, full to the brim so a crow could drink from it.*";
P_HTM[3113]="*atha puriso āgaccheyya udakabhāraṃ ādāya.**Then a person comes along with a load of water.*";
P_HTM[3114]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[3115]="*api nu so puriso labhetha udakassa nikkhepanan”ti?**Could that person pour water into the jar?”*";
P_HTM[3116]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3117]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yassa kassaci kāyagatāsati bhāvitā bahulīkatā, na tassa labhati māro otāraṃ, na tassa labhati māro ārammaṇaṃ.**“In the same way, when a mendicant has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body, Māra cannot find a vulnerability and doesn’t get hold of them.*";
P_HTM[3118]="*Yassa kassaci, bhikkhave, kāyagatāsati bhāvitā bahulīkatā, so yassa yassa abhiññāsacchikaraṇīyassa dhammassa cittaṃ abhininnāmeti abhiññāsacchikiriyāya, tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati satiāyatane.**When a mendicant has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body, they become capable of realizing anything that can be realized by insight to which they extend the mind, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[3119]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, udakamaṇiko pūro udakassa samatittiko kākapeyyo ādhāre ṭhapito.**Suppose a water jar was placed on a stand, full to the brim so a crow could drink from it.*";
P_HTM[3120]="*Tamenaṃ balavā puriso yato yato āviñcheyya, āgaccheyya udakan”ti?**If a strong man was to pour it on any side, would water pour out?”*";
P_HTM[3121]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3122]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yassa kassaci kāyagatāsati bhāvitā bahulīkatā so, yassa yassa abhiññāsacchikaraṇīyassa dhammassa cittaṃ abhininnāmeti abhiññāsacchikiriyāya, tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati satiāyatane.**“In the same way, when a mendicant has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body, they become capable of realizing anything that can be realized by insight to which they extend the mind, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[3123]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, same bhūmibhāge caturassā pokkharaṇī assa āḷibandhā pūrā udakassa samatittikā kākapeyyā.**Suppose there was a square, walled lotus pond on level ground, full to the brim so a crow could drink from it.*";
P_HTM[3124]="*Tamenaṃ balavā puriso yato yato āḷiṃ muñceyya āgaccheyya udakan”ti?**If a strong man was to open the wall on any side, would water pour out?”*";
P_HTM[3125]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3126]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yassa kassaci kāyagatāsati bhāvitā bahulīkatā, so yassa yassa abhiññāsacchikaraṇīyassa dhammassa cittaṃ abhininnāmeti abhiññāsacchikiriyāya, tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati satiāyatane.**“In the same way, when a mendicant has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body, they become capable of realizing anything that can be realized by insight to which they extend the mind, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[3127]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, subhūmiyaṃ catumahāpathe ājaññaratho yutto assa ṭhito odhastapatodo;**Suppose a chariot stood harnessed to thoroughbreds at a level crossroads, with a goad ready.*";
P_HTM[3128]="*tamenaṃ dakkho yoggācariyo assadammasārathi abhiruhitvā vāmena hatthena rasmiyo gahetvā dakkhiṇena hatthena patodaṃ gahetvā yenicchakaṃ yadicchakaṃ sāreyyāpi paccāsāreyyāpi;**Then a deft horse trainer, a master charioteer, might mount the chariot, taking the reins in his right hand and goad in the left. He’d drive out and back wherever he wishes, whenever he wishes.*";
P_HTM[3129]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, yassa kassaci kāyagatāsati bhāvitā bahulīkatā, so yassa yassa abhiññāsacchikaraṇīyassa dhammassa cittaṃ abhininnāmeti abhiññāsacchikiriyāya, tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati satiāyatane.**In the same way, when a mendicant has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body, they become capable of realizing anything that can be realized by insight to which they extend the mind, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[3130]="*Kāyagatāya, bhikkhave, satiyā āsevitāya bhāvitāya bahulīkatāya yānīkatāya vatthukatāya anuṭṭhitāya paricitāya susamāraddhāya dasānisaṃsā pāṭikaṅkhā.**You can expect ten benefits when mindfulness of the body has been cultivated, developed, and practiced, made a vehicle and a basis, kept up, consolidated, and properly implemented.*";
P_HTM[3131]="*Aratiratisaho hoti, na ca taṃ arati sahati, uppannaṃ aratiṃ abhibhuyya viharati. (1)**They prevail over desire and discontent, and live having mastered desire and discontent whenever they arose.*";
P_HTM[3132]="*Bhayabheravasaho hoti, na ca taṃ bhayabheravaṃ sahati, uppannaṃ bhayabheravaṃ abhibhuyya viharati. (2)**They prevail over fear and dread, and live having mastered fear and dread whenever they arose.*";
P_HTM[3133]="*Khamo hoti sītassa uṇhassa jighacchāya pipāsāya ḍaṃsamakasavātātapasarīsapasamphassānaṃ duruttānaṃ durāgatānaṃ vacanapathānaṃ, uppannānaṃ sārīrikānaṃ vedanānaṃ dukkhānaṃ tibbānaṃ kharānaṃ kaṭukānaṃ asātānaṃ amanāpānaṃ pāṇaharānaṃ adhivāsakajātiko hoti. (3)**They endure cold, heat, hunger, and thirst; the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, sun, and reptiles; rude and unwelcome criticism; and put up with physical pain—sharp, severe, acute, unpleasant, disagreeable, and life-threatening.*";
P_HTM[3134]="*Catunnaṃ jhānānaṃ ābhicetasikānaṃ diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārānaṃ nikāmalābhī hoti akicchalābhī akasiralābhī. (4)**They get the four absorptions—blissful meditations in the present life that belong to the higher mind—when they want, without trouble or difficulty.*";
P_HTM[3135]="*So anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccānubhoti. Ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti, bahudhāpi hutvā eko hoti, āvibhāvaṃ … pe … yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti. (5)**They wield the many kinds of psychic power: multiplying themselves and becoming one again … They control the body as far as the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[3136]="*Dibbāya sotadhātuyā visuddhāya atikkantamānusikāya ubho sadde suṇāti dibbe ca mānuse ca, ye dūre santike ca … pe …. (6)**With clairaudience that is purified and superhuman, they hear both kinds of sounds, human and divine, whether near or far. …*";
P_HTM[3137]="*Parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cetasā ceto paricca pajānāti. Sarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sarāgaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ … pe … sadosaṃ vā cittaṃ … vītadosaṃ vā cittaṃ … samohaṃ vā cittaṃ … vītamohaṃ vā cittaṃ … saṅkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ … vikkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ … mahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ … amahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ … sauttaraṃ vā cittaṃ … anuttaraṃ vā cittaṃ … samāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ … asamāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ … vimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ … avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘avimuttaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti. (7)**They understand the minds of other beings and individuals, having comprehended them with their own mind. …*";
P_HTM[3138]="*So anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo … pe … iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati. (8)**They recollect many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[3139]="*Dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe, sugate duggate yathākammūpage satte pajānāti. (9)**With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds.*";
P_HTM[3140]="*Āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati. (10)**They realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[3141]="*Kāyagatāya, bhikkhave, satiyā āsevitāya bhāvitāya bahulīkatāya yānīkatāya vatthukatāya anuṭṭhitāya paricitāya susamāraddhāya ime dasānisaṃsā pāṭikaṅkhā”ti.**You can expect these ten benefits when mindfulness of the body has been cultivated, developed, and practiced, made a vehicle and a basis, kept up, consolidated, and properly implemented.”*";
P_HTM[3142]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3143]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3144]="*Kāyagatāsatisuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3145]="*120. Saṅkhārupapattisutta**Rebirth by Choice*";
P_HTM[3146]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3147]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[3148]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[3149]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[3150]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[3151]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[3152]="*“saṅkhārupapattiṃ vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi,**“I shall teach you rebirth by choice.*";
P_HTM[3153]="*taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[3154]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[3155]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[3156]="*“Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena samannāgato hoti, sutena samannāgato hoti, cāgena samannāgato hoti, paññāya samannāgato hoti.**“Take a mendicant who has faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3157]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[3158]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā khattiyamahāsālānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of well-to-do aristocrats!’*";
P_HTM[3159]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**They settle on that thought, stabilize it and develop it.*";
P_HTM[3160]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā ca vihārā ca evaṃ bhāvitā evaṃ bahulīkatā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattanti.**Those choices and meditations of theirs, developed and cultivated like this, lead to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3161]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattati.**This is the path and the practice that leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3162]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena samannāgato hoti, sutena samannāgato hoti, cāgena samannāgato hoti, paññāya samannāgato hoti.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who has faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3163]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[3164]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā brāhmaṇamahāsālānaṃ … pe …**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of well-to-do brahmins …*";
P_HTM[3165]="*gahapatimahāsālānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**well-to-do householders.’*";
P_HTM[3166]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**They settle on that thought, stabilize it and develop it.*";
P_HTM[3167]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā ca vihārā ca evaṃ bhāvitā evaṃ bahulīkatā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattanti.**Those choices and meditations of theirs, developed and cultivated like this, lead to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3168]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattati.**This is the path and the practice that leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3169]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena samannāgato hoti, sutena samannāgato hoti, cāgena samannāgato hoti, paññāya samannāgato hoti.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who has faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3170]="*Tassa sutaṃ hoti:**And they’ve heard:*";
P_HTM[3171]="*‘cātumahārājikā devā dīghāyukā vaṇṇavanto sukhabahulā’ti.**‘The Gods of the Four Great Kings are long-lived, beautiful, and very happy.’*";
P_HTM[3172]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[3173]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā cātumahārājikānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of the Gods of the Four Great Kings!’*";
P_HTM[3174]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**They settle on that thought, stabilize it and develop it.*";
P_HTM[3175]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā ca vihārā ca evaṃ bhāvitā evaṃ bahulīkatā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattanti.**Those choices and meditations of theirs, developed and cultivated like this, lead to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3176]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattati.**This is the path and the practice that leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3177]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena samannāgato hoti, sutena samannāgato hoti, cāgena samannāgato hoti, paññāya samannāgato hoti.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who has faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3178]="*Tassa sutaṃ hoti—**And they’ve heard:*";
P_HTM[3179]="*tāvatiṃsā devā … pe …**‘The Gods of the Thirty-Three …*";
P_HTM[3180]="*yāmā devā …**the Gods of Yama …*";
P_HTM[3181]="*tusitā devā …**the Joyful Gods …*";
P_HTM[3182]="*nimmānaratī devā …**the Gods Who Love to Create …*";
P_HTM[3183]="*paranimmitavasavattī devā dīghāyukā vaṇṇavanto sukhabahulāti.**the Gods Who Control the Creations of Others are long-lived, beautiful, and very happy.’*";
P_HTM[3184]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[3185]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā paranimmitavasavattīnaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of the Gods Who Control the Creations of Others!’*";
P_HTM[3186]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**They settle on that thought, stabilize it and develop it.*";
P_HTM[3187]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā ca vihārā ca evaṃ bhāvitā evaṃ bahulīkatā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattanti.**Those choices and meditations of theirs, developed and cultivated like this, lead to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3188]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattati.**This is the path and the practice that leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3189]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena samannāgato hoti, sutena samannāgato hoti, cāgena samannāgato hoti, paññāya samannāgato hoti.**Furthermore, take a mendicant who has faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3190]="*Tassa sutaṃ hoti:**And they’ve heard:*";
P_HTM[3191]="*‘sahasso brahmā dīghāyuko vaṇṇavā sukhabahulo’ti.**‘The Brahmā of a thousand is long-lived, beautiful, and very happy.’*";
P_HTM[3192]="*Sahasso, bhikkhave, brahmā sahassilokadhātuṃ pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**Now the Brahmā of a thousand meditates determined on pervading a galaxy of a thousand solar systems,*";
P_HTM[3193]="*Yepi tattha sattā upapannā tepi pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**as well as the sentient beings reborn there.*";
P_HTM[3194]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, cakkhumā puriso ekaṃ āmaṇḍaṃ hatthe karitvā paccavekkheyya;**As a person might pick up a gallnut in their hand and examine it,*";
P_HTM[3195]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, sahasso brahmā sahassilokadhātuṃ pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**so too the Brahmā of a thousand meditates determined on pervading a galaxy of a thousand solar systems,*";
P_HTM[3196]="*Yepi tattha sattā upapannā tepi pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**as well as the sentient beings reborn there.*";
P_HTM[3197]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[3198]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sahassassa brahmuno sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of the Brahmā of a thousand!’*";
P_HTM[3199]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**They settle on that thought, stabilize it and develop it.*";
P_HTM[3200]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā ca vihārā ca evaṃ bhāvitā evaṃ bahulīkatā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattanti.**Those choices and meditations of theirs, developed and cultivated like this, lead to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3201]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattati.**This is the path and the practice that leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3202]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena samannāgato hoti, sutena …**Furthermore, take a mendicant who has faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3203]="*cāgena …* **";
P_HTM[3204]="*paññāya samannāgato hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3205]="*Tassa sutaṃ hoti—**And they’ve heard:*";
P_HTM[3206]="*dvisahasso brahmā … pe …**‘The Brahmā of two thousand …*";
P_HTM[3207]="*tisahasso brahmā …**the Brahmā of three thousand …*";
P_HTM[3208]="*catusahasso brahmā …**the Brahmā of four thousand …*";
P_HTM[3209]="*pañcasahasso brahmā dīghāyuko vaṇṇavā sukhabahuloti.**the Brahmā of five thousand is long-lived, beautiful, and very happy.’*";
P_HTM[3210]="*Pañcasahasso, bhikkhave, brahmā pañcasahassilokadhātuṃ pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**Now the Brahmā of five thousand meditates determined on pervading a galaxy of five thousand solar systems,*";
P_HTM[3211]="*Yepi tattha sattā upapannā tepi pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**as well as the sentient beings reborn there.*";
P_HTM[3212]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, cakkhumā puriso pañca āmaṇḍāni hatthe karitvā paccavekkheyya;**As a person might pick up five gallnuts in their hand and examine them,*";
P_HTM[3213]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, pañcasahasso brahmā pañcasahassilokadhātuṃ pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**so too the Brahmā of five thousand meditates determined on pervading a galaxy of five thousand solar systems,*";
P_HTM[3214]="*Yepi tattha sattā upapannā tepi pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**as well as the sentient beings reborn there.*";
P_HTM[3215]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[3216]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā pañcasahassassa brahmuno sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of the Brahmā of five thousand!’*";
P_HTM[3217]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**They settle on that thought, stabilize it and develop it.*";
P_HTM[3218]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā ca vihārā ca evaṃ bhāvitā evaṃ bahulīkatā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattanti.**Those choices and meditations of theirs, developed and cultivated like this, lead to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3219]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattati.**This is the path and the practice that leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3220]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena samannāgato hoti, sutena …**Furthermore, take a mendicant who has faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3221]="*cāgena …* **";
P_HTM[3222]="*paññāya samannāgato hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3223]="*Tassa sutaṃ hoti:**And they’ve heard:*";
P_HTM[3224]="*‘dasasahasso brahmā dīghāyuko vaṇṇavā sukhabahulo’ti.**‘The Brahmā of ten thousand is long-lived, beautiful, and very happy.’*";
P_HTM[3225]="*Dasasahasso, bhikkhave, brahmā dasasahassilokadhātuṃ pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**Now the Brahmā of ten thousand meditates determined on pervading a galaxy of ten thousand solar systems,*";
P_HTM[3226]="*Yepi tattha sattā upapannā tepi pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**as well as the sentient beings reborn there.*";
P_HTM[3227]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, maṇi veḷuriyo subho jātimā aṭṭhaṃso suparikammakato paṇḍukambale nikkhitto bhāsate ca tapate ca virocati ca;**Suppose there was a beryl gem that was naturally beautiful, eight-faceted, well-worked. When placed on a cream rug it would shine and glow and radiate.*";
P_HTM[3228]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, dasasahasso brahmā dasasahassilokadhātuṃ pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**In the same way the Brahmā of ten thousand meditates determined on pervading a galaxy of ten thousand solar systems,*";
P_HTM[3229]="*Yepi tattha sattā upapannā tepi pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**as well as the sentient beings reborn there.*";
P_HTM[3230]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[3231]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā dasasahassassa brahmuno sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of the Brahmā of ten thousand!’*";
P_HTM[3232]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**They settle on that thought, stabilize it and develop it.*";
P_HTM[3233]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā ca vihārā ca evaṃ bhāvitā evaṃ bahulīkatā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattanti.**Those choices and meditations of theirs, developed and cultivated like this, lead to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3234]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattati.**This is the path and the practice that leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3235]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena …**Furthermore, take a mendicant who has faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3236]="*sutena …* **";
P_HTM[3237]="*cāgena …* **";
P_HTM[3238]="*paññāya samannāgato hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3239]="*Tassa sutaṃ hoti:**And they’ve heard:*";
P_HTM[3240]="*‘satasahasso brahmā dīghāyuko vaṇṇavā sukhabahulo’ti.**‘The Brahmā of a hundred thousand is long-lived, beautiful, and very happy.’*";
P_HTM[3241]="*Satasahasso, bhikkhave, brahmā satasahassilokadhātuṃ pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**Now the Brahmā of a hundred thousand meditates determined on pervading a galaxy of a hundred thousand solar systems,*";
P_HTM[3242]="*Yepi tattha sattā upapannā tepi pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**as well as the sentient beings reborn there.*";
P_HTM[3243]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, nikkhaṃ jambonadaṃ dakkhakammāraputtaukkāmukhasukusalasampahaṭṭhaṃ paṇḍukambale nikkhittaṃ bhāsate ca tapate ca virocati ca;**Suppose there was an ornament of rare gold, fashioned by an expert smith, well wrought in the forge. When placed on a cream rug it would shine and glow and radiate.*";
P_HTM[3244]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, satasahasso brahmā satasahassilokadhātuṃ pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**In the same way the Brahmā of a hundred thousand meditates determined on pervading a galaxy of a hundred thousand solar systems,*";
P_HTM[3245]="*Yepi tattha sattā upapannā tepi pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**as well as the sentient beings reborn there.*";
P_HTM[3246]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[3247]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā satasahassassa brahmuno sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of the Brahmā of a hundred thousand!’*";
P_HTM[3248]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**They settle on that thought, stabilize it and develop it.*";
P_HTM[3249]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā ca vihārā ca evaṃ bhāvitā evaṃ bahulīkatā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattanti.**Those choices and meditations of theirs, developed and cultivated like this, lead to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3250]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattati.**This is the path and the practice that leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3251]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena …**Furthermore, take a mendicant who has faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
