P_HTM[3287]="*sudassī devā …**the Fair Seeing Gods …*";
P_HTM[3288]="*akaniṭṭhā devā dīghāyukā vaṇṇavanto sukhabahulāti.**the Gods of Akaniṭṭha …*";
P_HTM[3289]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:* **";
P_HTM[3290]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā akaniṭṭhānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3291]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.* **";
P_HTM[3292]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā ca vihārā ca evaṃ bhāvitā evaṃ bahulīkatā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattanti.* **";
P_HTM[3293]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattati.* **";
P_HTM[3294]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena …* **";
P_HTM[3295]="*sutena …* **";
P_HTM[3296]="*cāgena …* **";
P_HTM[3297]="*paññāya samannāgato hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3298]="*Tassa sutaṃ hoti:* **";
P_HTM[3299]="*‘ākāsānañcāyatanūpagā devā dīghāyukā ciraṭṭhitikā sukhabahulā’ti.**the gods of the dimension of infinite space …*";
P_HTM[3300]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:* **";
P_HTM[3301]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā ākāsānañcāyatanūpagānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3302]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.* **";
P_HTM[3303]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā ca vihārā ca evaṃ bhāvitā evaṃ bahulīkatā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattanti.* **";
P_HTM[3304]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattati.* **";
P_HTM[3305]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena …* **";
P_HTM[3306]="*sutena …* **";
P_HTM[3307]="*cāgena …* **";
P_HTM[3308]="*paññāya samannāgato hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3309]="*Tassa sutaṃ hoti:* **";
P_HTM[3310]="*‘viññāṇañcāyatanūpagā devā dīghāyukā ciraṭṭhitikā sukhabahulā’ti.**the gods of the dimension of infinite consciousness …*";
P_HTM[3311]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:* **";
P_HTM[3312]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā viññāṇañcāyatanūpagānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3313]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.* **";
P_HTM[3314]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā ca vihārā ca evaṃ bhāvitā evaṃ bahulīkatā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattanti.* **";
P_HTM[3315]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattati.* **";
P_HTM[3316]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena …* **";
P_HTM[3317]="*sutena …* **";
P_HTM[3318]="*cāgena …* **";
P_HTM[3319]="*paññāya samannāgato hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3320]="*Tassa sutaṃ hoti—* **";
P_HTM[3321]="*ākiñcaññāyatanūpagā devā … pe …**the gods of the dimension of nothingness …*";
P_HTM[3322]="*nevasaññānāsaññāyatanūpagā devā dīghāyukā ciraṭṭhitikā sukhabahulāti.**the gods of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception are long-lived, beautiful, and very happy.’*";
P_HTM[3323]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[3324]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā nevasaññānāsaññāyatanūpagānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of the gods of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception!’*";
P_HTM[3325]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**They settle on that thought, stabilize it and develop it.*";
P_HTM[3326]="*Tassa te saṅkhārā ca vihārā ca evaṃ bhāvitā evaṃ bahulīkatā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattanti.**Those choices and meditations of theirs, developed and cultivated like this, lead to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3327]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā tatrupapattiyā saṃvattati.**This is the path and the practice that leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[3328]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddhāya samannāgato hoti, sīlena …**Furthermore, take a mendicant who has faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3329]="*sutena …* **";
P_HTM[3330]="*cāgena …* **";
P_HTM[3331]="*paññāya samannāgato hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3332]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[3333]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihareyyan’ti.**‘If only I might realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and live having realized it with my own insight due to the ending of defilements.’*";
P_HTM[3334]="*So āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**They realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[3335]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu na katthaci upapajjatī”ti.**And, mendicants, that mendicant is not reborn anywhere.”*";
P_HTM[3336]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3337]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3338]="*Saṅkhārupapattisuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3339]="*Anupadavaggo niṭṭhito dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[3340]="*Anupada sodhana porisadhammo,* **";
P_HTM[3341]="*Sevitabba bahudhātu vibhatti;* **";
P_HTM[3342]="*Buddhassa kittināma cattārīsena,* **";
P_HTM[3343]="*Ānāpāno kāyagato upapatti.* **";
P_HTM[3344]="*121. Cūḷasuññatasutta**The Shorter Discourse on Emptiness*";
P_HTM[3345]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3346]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati pubbārāme migāramātupāsāde.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in the Eastern Monastery, the stilt longhouse of Migāra’s mother.*";
P_HTM[3347]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then in the late afternoon, Venerable Ānanda came out of retreat and went to the Buddha. He bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3348]="*“Ekamidaṃ, bhante, samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati nagarakaṃ nāma sakyānaṃ nigamo.**“Sir, this one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans where they have a town named Nagaraka.*";
P_HTM[3349]="*Tattha me, bhante, bhagavato sammukhā sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**There I heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3350]="*‘suññatāvihārenāhaṃ, ānanda, etarahi bahulaṃ viharāmī’ti.**‘Ānanda, these days I usually practice the meditation on emptiness.’*";
P_HTM[3351]="*Kacci metaṃ, bhante, sussutaṃ suggahitaṃ sumanasikataṃ sūpadhāritan”ti?**I trust I properly heard, learned, attended, and remembered that from the Buddha?”*";
P_HTM[3352]="*“Taggha te etaṃ, ānanda, sussutaṃ suggahitaṃ sumanasikataṃ sūpadhāritaṃ.**“Indeed, Ānanda, you properly heard, learned, attended, and remembered that.*";
P_HTM[3353]="*Pubbepāhaṃ, ānanda, etarahipi suññatāvihārena bahulaṃ viharāmi.**Now, as before, I usually practice the meditation on emptiness.*";
P_HTM[3354]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, ayaṃ migāramātupāsādo suñño hatthigavassavaḷavena, suñño jātarūparajatena, suñño itthipurisasannipātena atthi cevidaṃ asuññataṃ yadidaṃ—**Consider this stilt longhouse of Migāra’s mother. It’s empty of elephants, cows, horses, and mares; of gold and money; and of gatherings of men and women.*";
P_HTM[3355]="*bhikkhusaṃghaṃ paṭicca ekattaṃ;**There is only this that is not emptiness, namely, the oneness dependent on the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[3356]="*evameva kho, ānanda, bhikkhu amanasikaritvā gāmasaññaṃ, amanasikaritvā manussasaññaṃ, araññasaññaṃ paṭicca manasi karoti ekattaṃ.**In the same way, a mendicant—ignoring the perception of the village and the perception of people—focuses on the oneness dependent on the perception of wilderness.*";
P_HTM[3357]="*Tassa araññasaññāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati adhimuccati.**Their mind becomes eager, confident, settled, and decided in that perception of wilderness.*";
P_HTM[3358]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[3359]="*‘ye assu darathā gāmasaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, ye assu darathā manussasaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, atthi cevāyaṃ darathamattā yadidaṃ—**‘Here there is no stress due to the perception of village or the perception of people.*";
P_HTM[3360]="*araññasaññaṃ paṭicca ekattan’ti.**There is only this modicum of stress, namely the oneness dependent on the perception of wilderness.’*";
P_HTM[3361]="*So ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ gāmasaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ manussasaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘atthi cevidaṃ asuññataṃ yadidaṃ—**They understand: ‘This field of perception is empty of the perception of the village. It is empty of the perception of people.*";
P_HTM[3362]="*araññasaññaṃ paṭicca ekattan’ti.**There is only this that is not emptiness, namely the oneness dependent on the perception of wilderness.’*";
P_HTM[3363]="*Iti yañhi kho tattha na hoti tena taṃ suññaṃ samanupassati, yaṃ pana tattha avasiṭṭhaṃ hoti taṃ ‘santamidaṃ atthī’ti pajānāti.**And so they regard it as empty of what is not there, but as to what remains they understand that it is present.*";
P_HTM[3364]="*Evampissa esā, ānanda, yathābhuccā avipallatthā parisuddhā suññatāvakkanti bhavati.**That’s how emptiness is born in them—genuine, undistorted, and pure.*";
P_HTM[3365]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu amanasikaritvā manussasaññaṃ, amanasikaritvā araññasaññaṃ, pathavīsaññaṃ paṭicca manasi karoti ekattaṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant—ignoring the perception of people and the perception of wilderness—focuses on the oneness dependent on the perception of earth.*";
P_HTM[3366]="*Tassa pathavīsaññāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati adhimuccati.**Their mind becomes eager, confident, settled, and decided in that perception of earth.*";
P_HTM[3367]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, āsabhacammaṃ saṅkusatena suvihataṃ vigatavalikaṃ;**As a bull’s hide is rid of folds when fully stretched out by a hundred pegs,*";
P_HTM[3368]="*evameva kho, ānanda, bhikkhu yaṃ imissā pathaviyā ukkūlavikkūlaṃ nadīviduggaṃ khāṇukaṇṭakaṭṭhānaṃ pabbatavisamaṃ taṃ sabbaṃ amanasikaritvā pathavīsaññaṃ paṭicca manasi karoti ekattaṃ.**so too, ignoring the hilly terrain, inaccessible riverlands, stumps and thorns, and rugged mountains, they focus on the oneness dependent on the perception of earth.*";
P_HTM[3369]="*Tassa pathavīsaññāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati adhimuccati.**Their mind becomes eager, confident, settled, and decided in that perception of earth.*";
P_HTM[3370]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[3371]="*‘ye assu darathā manussasaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, ye assu darathā araññasaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, atthi cevāyaṃ darathamattā yadidaṃ—**‘Here there is no stress due to the perception of people or the perception of wilderness.*";
P_HTM[3372]="*pathavīsaññaṃ paṭicca ekattan’ti.**There is only this modicum of stress, namely the oneness dependent on the perception of earth.’*";
P_HTM[3373]="*So ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ manussasaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ araññasaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘atthi cevidaṃ asuññataṃ yadidaṃ—**They understand: ‘This field of perception is empty of the perception of people. It is empty of the perception of wilderness.*";
P_HTM[3374]="*pathavīsaññaṃ paṭicca ekattan’ti.**There is only this that is not emptiness, namely the oneness dependent on the perception of earth.’*";
P_HTM[3375]="*Iti yañhi kho tattha na hoti tena taṃ suññaṃ samanupassati, yaṃ pana tattha avasiṭṭhaṃ hoti taṃ ‘santamidaṃ atthī’ti pajānāti.**And so they regard it as empty of what is not there, but as to what remains they understand that it is present.*";
P_HTM[3376]="*Evampissa esā, ānanda, yathābhuccā avipallatthā parisuddhā suññatāvakkanti bhavati.**That’s how emptiness is born in them—genuine, undistorted, and pure.*";
P_HTM[3377]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu amanasikaritvā araññasaññaṃ, amanasikaritvā pathavīsaññaṃ, ākāsānañcāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca manasi karoti ekattaṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant—ignoring the perception of wilderness and the perception of earth—focuses on the oneness dependent on the perception of the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[3378]="*Tassa ākāsānañcāyatanasaññāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati adhimuccati.**Their mind becomes eager, confident, settled, and decided in that perception of the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[3379]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[3380]="*‘ye assu darathā araññasaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, ye assu darathā pathavīsaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, atthi cevāyaṃ darathamattā yadidaṃ—**‘Here there is no stress due to the perception of wilderness or the perception of earth.*";
P_HTM[3381]="*ākāsānañcāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca ekattan’ti.**There is only this modicum of stress, namely the oneness dependent on the perception of the dimension of infinite space.’*";
P_HTM[3382]="*So ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ araññasaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ pathavīsaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘atthi cevidaṃ asuññataṃ yadidaṃ—**They understand: ‘This field of perception is empty of the perception of wilderness. It is empty of the perception of earth.*";
P_HTM[3383]="*ākāsānañcāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca ekattan’ti.**There is only this that is not emptiness, namely the oneness dependent on the perception of the dimension of infinite space.’*";
P_HTM[3384]="*Iti yañhi kho tattha na hoti tena taṃ suññaṃ samanupassati, yaṃ pana tattha avasiṭṭhaṃ hoti taṃ ‘santamidaṃ atthī’ti pajānāti.**And so they regard it as empty of what is not there, but as to what remains they understand that it is present.*";
P_HTM[3385]="*Evampissa esā, ānanda, yathābhuccā avipallatthā parisuddhā suññatāvakkanti bhavati.**That’s how emptiness is born in them—genuine, undistorted, and pure.*";
P_HTM[3386]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu amanasikaritvā pathavīsaññaṃ, amanasikaritvā ākāsānañcāyatanasaññaṃ, viññāṇañcāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca manasi karoti ekattaṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant—ignoring the perception of earth and the perception of the dimension of infinite space—focuses on the oneness dependent on the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3387]="*Tassa viññāṇañcāyatanasaññāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati adhimuccati.**Their mind becomes eager, confident, settled, and decided in that perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3388]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[3389]="*‘ye assu darathā pathavīsaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, ye assu darathā ākāsānañcāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, atthi cevāyaṃ darathamattā yadidaṃ—**‘Here there is no stress due to the perception of earth or the perception of the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[3390]="*viññāṇañcāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca ekattan’ti.**There is only this modicum of stress, namely the oneness dependent on the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[3391]="*So ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ pathavīsaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ ākāsānañcāyatanasaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘atthi cevidaṃ asuññataṃ yadidaṃ—**They understand: ‘This field of perception is empty of the perception of earth. It is empty of the perception of the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[3392]="*viññāṇañcāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca ekattan’ti.**There is only this modicum of stress, namely the oneness dependent on the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[3393]="*Iti yañhi kho tattha na hoti tena taṃ suññaṃ samanupassati, yaṃ pana tattha avasiṭṭhaṃ hoti taṃ ‘santamidaṃ atthī’ti pajānāti.**And so they regard it as empty of what is not there, but as to what remains they understand that it is present.*";
P_HTM[3394]="*Evampissa esā, ānanda, yathābhuccā avipallatthā parisuddhā suññatāvakkanti bhavati.**That’s how emptiness is born in them—genuine, undistorted, and pure.*";
P_HTM[3395]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu amanasikaritvā ākāsānañcāyatanasaññaṃ, amanasikaritvā viññāṇañcāyatanasaññaṃ, ākiñcaññāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca manasi karoti ekattaṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant—ignoring the perception of the dimension of infinite space and the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness—focuses on the oneness dependent on the perception of the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[3396]="*Tassa ākiñcaññāyatanasaññāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati adhimuccati.**Their mind becomes eager, confident, settled, and decided in that perception of the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[3397]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[3398]="*‘ye assu darathā ākāsānañcāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, ye assu darathā viññāṇañcāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, atthi cevāyaṃ darathamattā yadidaṃ—**‘Here there is no stress due to the perception of the dimension of infinite space or the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3399]="*ākiñcaññāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca ekattan’ti.**There is only this modicum of stress, namely the oneness dependent on the perception of the dimension of nothingness.’*";
P_HTM[3400]="*So ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ ākāsānañcāyatanasaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ viññāṇañcāyatanasaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘atthi cevidaṃ asuññataṃ yadidaṃ—**They understand: ‘This field of perception is empty of the perception of the dimension of infinite space. It is empty of the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[3401]="*ākiñcaññāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca ekattan’ti.**There is only this that is not emptiness, namely the oneness dependent on the perception of the dimension of nothingness.’*";
P_HTM[3402]="*Iti yañhi kho tattha na hoti tena taṃ suññaṃ samanupassati, yaṃ pana tattha avasiṭṭhaṃ hoti taṃ ‘santamidaṃ atthī’ti pajānāti.**And so they regard it as empty of what is not there, but as to what remains they understand that it is present.*";
P_HTM[3403]="*Evampissa esā, ānanda, yathābhuccā avipallatthā parisuddhā suññatāvakkanti bhavati.**That’s how emptiness is born in them—genuine, undistorted, and pure.*";
P_HTM[3404]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda bhikkhu amanasikaritvā viññāṇañcāyatanasaññaṃ, amanasikaritvā ākiñcaññāyatanasaññaṃ, nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca manasi karoti ekattaṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant—ignoring the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness and the perception of the dimension of nothingness—focuses on the oneness dependent on the perception of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[3405]="*Tassa nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasaññāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati adhimuccati.**Their mind becomes eager, confident, settled, and decided in that perception of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[3406]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[3407]="*‘ye assu darathā viññāṇañcāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, ye assu darathā ākiñcaññāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, atthi cevāyaṃ darathamattā yadidaṃ—**‘Here there is no stress due to the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness or the perception of the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[3408]="*nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca ekattan’ti.**There is only this modicum of stress, namely the oneness dependent on the perception of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.’*";
P_HTM[3409]="*So ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ viññāṇañcāyatanasaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ ākiñcaññāyatanasaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘atthi cevidaṃ asuññataṃ yadidaṃ—**They understand: ‘This field of perception is empty of the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness. It is empty of the perception of the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[3410]="*nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca ekattan’ti.**There is only this that is not emptiness, namely the oneness dependent on the perception of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.’*";
P_HTM[3411]="*Iti yañhi kho tattha na hoti tena taṃ suññaṃ samanupassati, yaṃ pana tattha avasiṭṭhaṃ hoti taṃ ‘santamidaṃ atthī’ti pajānāti.**And so they regard it as empty of what is not there, but as to what remains they understand that it is present.*";
P_HTM[3412]="*Evampissa esā, ānanda, yathābhuccā avipallatthā parisuddhā suññatāvakkanti bhavati.**That’s how emptiness is born in them—genuine, undistorted, and pure.*";
P_HTM[3413]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu amanasikaritvā ākiñcaññāyatanasaññaṃ, amanasikaritvā nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasaññaṃ, animittaṃ cetosamādhiṃ paṭicca manasi karoti ekattaṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant—ignoring the perception of the dimension of nothingness and the perception of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception—focuses on the oneness dependent on the signless immersion of the heart.*";
P_HTM[3414]="*Tassa animitte cetosamādhimhi cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati adhimuccati.**Their mind becomes eager, confident, settled, and decided in that signless immersion of the heart.*";
P_HTM[3415]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[3416]="*‘ye assu darathā ākiñcaññāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, ye assu darathā nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasaññaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, atthi cevāyaṃ darathamattā yadidaṃ—**‘Here there is no stress due to the perception of the dimension of nothingness or the perception of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[3417]="*imameva kāyaṃ paṭicca saḷāyatanikaṃ jīvitapaccayā’ti.**There is only this modicum of stress, namely that associated with the six sense fields dependent on this body and conditioned by life.’*";
P_HTM[3418]="*So ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ ākiñcaññāyatanasaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasaññāyā’ti pajānāti, ‘atthi cevidaṃ asuññataṃ yadidaṃ—**They understand: ‘This field of perception is empty of the perception of the dimension of nothingness. It is empty of the perception of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[3419]="*imameva kāyaṃ paṭicca saḷāyatanikaṃ jīvitapaccayā’ti.**There is only this that is not emptiness, namely that associated with the six sense fields dependent on this body and conditioned by life.’*";
P_HTM[3420]="*Iti yañhi kho tattha na hoti tena taṃ suññaṃ samanupassati, yaṃ pana tattha avasiṭṭhaṃ hoti taṃ ‘santamidaṃ atthī’ti pajānāti.**And so they regard it as empty of what is not there, but as to what remains they understand that it is present.*";
P_HTM[3421]="*Evampissa esā, ānanda, yathābhuccā avipallatthā parisuddhā suññatāvakkanti bhavati.**That’s how emptiness is born in them—genuine, undistorted, and pure.*";
P_HTM[3422]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu amanasikaritvā ākiñcaññāyatanasaññaṃ, amanasikaritvā nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasaññaṃ, animittaṃ cetosamādhiṃ paṭicca manasi karoti ekattaṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant—ignoring the perception of the dimension of nothingness and the perception of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception—focuses on the oneness dependent on the signless immersion of the heart.*";
P_HTM[3423]="*Tassa animitte cetosamādhimhi cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati adhimuccati.**Their mind becomes eager, confident, settled, and decided in that signless immersion of the heart.*";
P_HTM[3424]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[3425]="*‘ayampi kho animitto cetosamādhi abhisaṅkhato abhisañcetayito’.**‘Even this signless immersion of the heart is produced by choices and intentions.’*";
P_HTM[3426]="*‘Yaṃ kho pana kiñci abhisaṅkhataṃ abhisañcetayitaṃ tadaniccaṃ nirodhadhamman’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘But whatever is produced by choices and intentions is impermanent and liable to cessation.’*";
P_HTM[3427]="*Tassa evaṃ jānato evaṃ passato kāmāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, bhavāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, avijjāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati.**Knowing and seeing like this, their mind is freed from the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[3428]="*Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[3429]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[3430]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[3431]="*‘ye assu darathā kāmāsavaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, ye assu darathā bhavāsavaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, ye assu darathā avijjāsavaṃ paṭicca tedha na santi, atthi cevāyaṃ darathamattā yadidaṃ—**‘Here there is no stress due to the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, or ignorance.*";
P_HTM[3432]="*imameva kāyaṃ paṭicca saḷāyatanikaṃ jīvitapaccayā’ti.**There is only this modicum of stress, namely that associated with the six sense fields dependent on this body and conditioned by life.’*";
P_HTM[3433]="*So ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ kāmāsavenā’ti pajānāti, ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ bhavāsavenā’ti pajānāti, ‘suññamidaṃ saññāgataṃ avijjāsavenā’ti pajānāti, ‘atthi cevidaṃ asuññataṃ yadidaṃ—**They understand: ‘This field of perception is empty of the perception of the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[3434]="*imameva kāyaṃ paṭicca saḷāyatanikaṃ jīvitapaccayā’ti.**There is only this that is not emptiness, namely that associated with the six sense fields dependent on this body and conditioned by life.’*";
P_HTM[3435]="*Iti yañhi kho tattha na hoti tena taṃ suññaṃ samanupassati, yaṃ pana tattha avasiṭṭhaṃ hoti taṃ ‘santamidaṃ atthī’ti pajānāti.**And so they regard it as empty of what is not there, but as to what remains they understand that it is present.*";
P_HTM[3436]="*Evampissa esā, ānanda, yathābhuccā avipallatthā parisuddhā paramānuttarā suññatāvakkanti bhavati.**That’s how emptiness is born in them—genuine, undistorted, and pure.*";
P_HTM[3437]="*Yepi hi keci, ānanda, atītamaddhānaṃ samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā parisuddhaṃ paramānuttaraṃ suññataṃ upasampajja vihariṃsu, sabbe te imaṃyeva parisuddhaṃ paramānuttaraṃ suññataṃ upasampajja vihariṃsu.**Whatever ascetics and brahmins enter and remain in the pure, ultimate, supreme emptiness—whether in the past, future, or present—all of them enter and remain in this same pure, ultimate, supreme emptiness.*";
P_HTM[3438]="*Yepi hi keci, ānanda, anāgatamaddhānaṃ samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā parisuddhaṃ paramānuttaraṃ suññataṃ upasampajja viharissanti, sabbe te imaṃyeva parisuddhaṃ paramānuttaraṃ suññataṃ upasampajja viharissanti.* **";
P_HTM[3439]="*Yepi hi keci, ānanda, etarahi samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā parisuddhaṃ paramānuttaraṃ suññataṃ upasampajja viharanti, sabbe te imaṃyeva parisuddhaṃ paramānuttaraṃ suññataṃ upasampajja viharanti.* **";
P_HTM[3440]="*Tasmātiha, ānanda, ‘parisuddhaṃ paramānuttaraṃ suññataṃ upasampajja viharissāmā’ti—**So, Ānanda, you should train like this: ‘We will enter and remain in the pure, ultimate, supreme emptiness.’*";
P_HTM[3441]="*evañhi vo, ānanda, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train.”*";
P_HTM[3442]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3443]="*Attamano āyasmā ānando bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Ānanda was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3444]="*Cūḷasuññatasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3445]="*122. Mahāsuññatasutta**The Longer Discourse on Emptiness*";
P_HTM[3446]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3447]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati kapilavatthusmiṃ nigrodhārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans, near Kapilavatthu in the Banyan Tree Monastery.*";
P_HTM[3448]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya kapilavatthuṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Kapilavatthu for alms.*";
P_HTM[3449]="*Kapilavatthusmiṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto yena kāḷakhemakassa sakkassa vihāro tenupasaṅkami divāvihārāya.**He wandered for alms in Kapilavatthu. After the meal, on his return from alms-round, he went to the dwelling of Kāḷakhemaka the Sakyan for the day’s meditation.*";
P_HTM[3450]="*Tena kho pana samayena kāḷakhemakassa sakkassa vihāre sambahulāni senāsanāni paññattāni honti.**Now at that time several resting places had been spread out at Kāḷakhemaka’s dwelling.*";
P_HTM[3451]="*Addasā kho bhagavā kāḷakhemakassa sakkassa vihāre sambahulāni senāsanāni paññattāni.**The Buddha saw this,*";
P_HTM[3452]="*Disvāna bhagavato etadahosi:**and wondered,*";
P_HTM[3453]="*“sambahulāni kho kāḷakhemakassa sakkassa vihāre senāsanāni paññattāni.**“Several resting places have been spread out;*";
P_HTM[3454]="*Sambahulā nu kho idha bhikkhū viharantī”ti.**are there several mendicants living here?”*";
P_HTM[3455]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā ānando sambahulehi bhikkhūhi saddhiṃ ghaṭāya sakkassa vihāre cīvarakammaṃ karoti.**Now at that time Venerable Ānanda, together with several other mendicants, was making robes in Ghaṭa the Sakyan’s dwelling.*";
P_HTM[3456]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yena ghaṭāya sakkassa vihāro tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha came out of retreat and went to Ghaṭa’s dwelling, where he sat on the seat spread out*";
P_HTM[3457]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**and said to Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[3458]="*“sambahulāni kho, ānanda, kāḷakhemakassa sakkassa vihāre senāsanāni paññattāni.**“Several resting places have been spread out at Kāḷakhemaka’s dwelling;*";
P_HTM[3459]="*Sambahulā nu kho ettha bhikkhū viharantī”ti?**are several mendicants living there?”*";
P_HTM[3460]="*“Sambahulāni, bhante, kāḷakhemakassa sakkassa vihāre senāsanāni paññattāni.* **";
P_HTM[3461]="*Sambahulā bhikkhū ettha viharanti.**“Indeed there are, sir.*";
P_HTM[3462]="*Cīvarakārasamayo no, bhante, vattatī”ti.**It’s currently the time for making robes.”*";
P_HTM[3463]="*“Na kho, ānanda, bhikkhu sobhati saṅgaṇikārāmo saṅgaṇikarato saṅgaṇikārāmataṃ anuyutto gaṇārāmo gaṇarato gaṇasammudito.**“Ānanda, a mendicant doesn’t shine who enjoys company and groups, who loves them and likes to enjoy them.*";
P_HTM[3464]="*So vatānanda, bhikkhu saṅgaṇikārāmo saṅgaṇikarato saṅgaṇikārāmataṃ anuyutto gaṇārāmo gaṇarato gaṇasammudito yaṃ taṃ nekkhammasukhaṃ pavivekasukhaṃ upasamasukhaṃ sambodhisukhaṃ tassa sukhassa nikāmalābhī bhavissati akicchalābhī akasiralābhīti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**It’s simply not possible that such a mendicant will get the pleasure of renunciation, the pleasure of seclusion, the pleasure of peace, the pleasure of awakening when they want, without trouble or difficulty.*";
P_HTM[3465]="*Yo ca kho so, ānanda, bhikkhu eko gaṇasmā vūpakaṭṭho viharati tassetaṃ bhikkhuno pāṭikaṅkhaṃ yaṃ taṃ nekkhammasukhaṃ pavivekasukhaṃ upasamasukhaṃ sambodhisukhaṃ tassa sukhassa nikāmalābhī bhavissati akicchalābhī akasiralābhīti—ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**But you should expect that a mendicant who lives alone, withdrawn from the group, will get the pleasure of renunciation, the pleasure of seclusion, the pleasure of peace, the pleasure of awakening when they want, without trouble or difficulty. That is possible.*";
P_HTM[3466]="*So vatānanda, bhikkhu saṅgaṇikārāmo saṅgaṇikarato saṅgaṇikārāmataṃ anuyutto gaṇārāmo gaṇarato gaṇasammudito sāmāyikaṃ vā kantaṃ cetovimuttiṃ upasampajja viharissati asāmāyikaṃ vā akuppanti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Indeed, Ānanda, it is not possible that a mendicant who enjoys company will enter and remain in the freedom of heart—either that which is temporary and pleasant, or that which is irreversible and unshakable.*";
P_HTM[3467]="*Yo ca kho so, ānanda, bhikkhu eko gaṇasmā vūpakaṭṭho viharati tassetaṃ bhikkhuno pāṭikaṅkhaṃ sāmāyikaṃ vā kantaṃ cetovimuttiṃ upasampajja viharissati asāmāyikaṃ vā akuppanti—ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**But it is possible that a mendicant who lives alone, withdrawn from the group will enter and remain in the freedom of heart—either that which is temporary and pleasant, or that which is irreversible and unshakable.*";
P_HTM[3468]="*Nāhaṃ, ānanda, ekaṃ rūpampi samanupassāmi yattha rattassa yathābhiratassa rūpassa vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā na uppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassūpāyāsā.**Ānanda, I do not see even a single sight which, with its decay and perishing, would not give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress in someone who has desire and lust for it.*";
P_HTM[3469]="*Ayaṃ kho panānanda, vihāro tathāgatena abhisambuddho yadidaṃ—**But the Realized One woke up to this meditation, namely*";
P_HTM[3470]="*sabbanimittānaṃ amanasikārā ajjhattaṃ suññataṃ upasampajja viharituṃ.**to enter and remain in emptiness internally by not focusing on any signs.*";
P_HTM[3471]="*Tatra ce, ānanda, tathāgataṃ iminā vihārena viharantaṃ bhavanti upasaṅkamitāro bhikkhū bhikkhuniyo upāsakā upāsikāyo rājāno rājamahāmattā titthiyā titthiyasāvakā.**Now, suppose that while the Realized One is practicing this meditation, monks, nuns, laymen, laywomen, rulers and their ministers, founders of religious sects, and their disciples go to visit him.*";
P_HTM[3472]="*Tatrānanda, tathāgato vivekaninneneva cittena vivekapoṇena vivekapabbhārena vūpakaṭṭhena nekkhammābhiratena byantībhūtena sabbaso āsavaṭṭhānīyehi dhammehi aññadatthu uyyojanikapaṭisaṃyuttaṃyeva kathaṃ kattā hoti.**In that case, with a mind slanting, sloping, and inclining to seclusion, withdrawn, and loving renunciation, he invariably gives each of them a talk emphasizing the topic of dismissal.*";
P_HTM[3473]="*Tasmātihānanda, bhikkhu cepi ākaṅkheyya:**Therefore, if a mendicant might wish:*";
P_HTM[3474]="*‘ajjhattaṃ suññataṃ upasampajja vihareyyan’ti, tenānanda, bhikkhunā ajjhattameva cittaṃ saṇṭhapetabbaṃ sannisādetabbaṃ ekodi kātabbaṃ samādahātabbaṃ.**‘May I enter and remain in emptiness internally!’ So they should still, settle, unify, and immerse their mind in samādhi internally.*";
P_HTM[3475]="*Kathañcānanda, bhikkhu ajjhattameva cittaṃ saṇṭhapeti sannisādeti ekodiṃ karoti samādahati?**And how does a mendicant still, settle, unify, and immerse their mind in samādhi internally?*";
P_HTM[3476]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati … pe …**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption …*";
P_HTM[3477]="*dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**second absorption …*";
P_HTM[3478]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[3479]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[3480]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, bhikkhu ajjhattameva cittaṃ saṇṭhapeti sannisādeti ekodiṃ karoti samādahati.**That’s how a mendicant stills, settles, unifies, and immerses their mind in samādhi internally.*";
P_HTM[3481]="*So ajjhattaṃ suññataṃ manasi karoti.**They focus on emptiness internally,*";
P_HTM[3482]="*Tassa ajjhattaṃ suññataṃ manasikaroto suññatāya cittaṃ na pakkhandati nappasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati.**but their mind isn’t eager, confident, settled, and decided.*";
P_HTM[3483]="*Evaṃ santametaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu evaṃ pajānāti:**In that case, they understand:*";
P_HTM[3484]="*‘ajjhattaṃ suññataṃ kho me manasikaroto ajjhattaṃ suññatāya cittaṃ na pakkhandati nappasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccatī’ti.**‘I am focusing on emptiness internally, but my mind isn’t eager, confident, settled, and decided.’*";
P_HTM[3485]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3486]="*So bahiddhā suññataṃ manasi karoti … pe …**They focus on emptiness externally …*";
P_HTM[3487]="*so ajjhattabahiddhā suññataṃ manasi karoti … pe …**They focus on emptiness internally and externally …*";
P_HTM[3488]="*so āneñjaṃ manasi karoti.**They focus on the imperturbable,*";
P_HTM[3489]="*Tassa āneñjaṃ manasikaroto āneñjāya cittaṃ na pakkhandati nappasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati.**but their mind isn’t eager, confident, settled, and decided.*";
P_HTM[3490]="*Evaṃ santametaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu evaṃ pajānāti:**In that case, they understand:*";
P_HTM[3491]="*‘āneñjaṃ kho me manasikaroto āneñjāya cittaṃ na pakkhandati nappasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccatī’ti.**‘I am focusing on the imperturbable internally, but my mind isn’t eager, confident, settled, and decided.’*";
P_HTM[3492]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3493]="*Tenānanda, bhikkhunā tasmiṃyeva purimasmiṃ samādhinimitte ajjhattameva cittaṃ saṇṭhapetabbaṃ sannisādetabbaṃ ekodi kātabbaṃ samādahātabbaṃ.**Then that mendicant should still, settle, unify, and immerse their mind in samādhi internally using the same meditation subject as a basis of immersion that they used before.*";
P_HTM[3494]="*So ajjhattaṃ suññataṃ manasi karoti.**They focus on emptiness internally,*";
P_HTM[3495]="*Tassa ajjhattaṃ suññataṃ manasikaroto ajjhattaṃ suññatāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati.**and their mind is eager, confident, settled, and decided.*";
P_HTM[3496]="*Evaṃ santametaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu evaṃ pajānāti:**In that case, they understand:*";
P_HTM[3497]="*‘ajjhattaṃ suññataṃ kho me manasikaroto ajjhattaṃ suññatāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccatī’ti.**‘I am focusing on emptiness internally, and my mind is eager, confident, settled, and decided.’*";
P_HTM[3498]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3499]="*So bahiddhā suññataṃ manasi karoti … pe …**They focus on emptiness externally …*";
P_HTM[3500]="*so ajjhattabahiddhā suññataṃ manasi karoti … pe …**They focus on emptiness internally and externally …*";
P_HTM[3501]="*so āneñjaṃ manasi karoti.**They focus on the imperturbable,*";
P_HTM[3502]="*Tassa āneñjaṃ manasikaroto āneñjāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati.**and their mind is eager, confident, settled, and decided.*";
P_HTM[3503]="*Evaṃ santametaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu evaṃ pajānāti:**In that case, they understand:*";
P_HTM[3504]="*‘āneñjaṃ kho me manasikaroto āneñjāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccatī’ti.**‘I am focusing on the imperturbable, and my mind is eager, confident, settled, and decided.’*";
P_HTM[3505]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3506]="*Tassa ce, ānanda, bhikkhuno iminā vihārena viharato caṅkamāya cittaṃ namati, so caṅkamati:**While a mendicant is practicing such meditation, if their mind inclines to walking, they walk, thinking:*";
P_HTM[3507]="*‘evaṃ maṃ caṅkamantaṃ nābhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssavissantī’ti.**‘While I’m walking, bad, unskillful qualities of desire and aversion will not overwhelm me.’*";
P_HTM[3508]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3509]="*Tassa ce, ānanda, bhikkhuno iminā vihārena viharato ṭhānāya cittaṃ namati, so tiṭṭhati:**While a mendicant is practicing such meditation, if their mind inclines to standing, they stand, thinking:*";
P_HTM[3510]="*‘evaṃ maṃ ṭhitaṃ nābhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssavissantī’ti.**‘While I’m standing, bad, unskillful qualities of desire and aversion will not overwhelm me.’*";
P_HTM[3511]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3512]="*Tassa ce, ānanda, bhikkhuno iminā vihārena viharato nisajjāya cittaṃ namati, so nisīdati:**While a mendicant is practicing such meditation, if their mind inclines to sitting, they sit, thinking:*";
P_HTM[3513]="*‘evaṃ maṃ nisinnaṃ nābhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssavissantī’ti.**‘While I’m sitting, bad, unskillful qualities of desire and aversion will not overwhelm me.’*";
P_HTM[3514]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3515]="*Tassa ce, ānanda, bhikkhuno iminā vihārena viharato sayanāya cittaṃ namati, so sayati:**While a mendicant is practicing such meditation, if their mind inclines to lying down, they lie down, thinking:*";
P_HTM[3516]="*‘evaṃ maṃ sayantaṃ nābhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssavissantī’ti.**‘While I’m lying down, bad, unskillful qualities of desire and aversion will not overwhelm me.’*";
P_HTM[3517]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3518]="*Tassa ce, ānanda, bhikkhuno iminā vihārena viharato kathāya cittaṃ namati, so:**While a mendicant is practicing such meditation, if their mind inclines to talking, they think:*";
P_HTM[3519]="*‘yāyaṃ kathā hīnā gammā pothujjanikā anariyā anatthasaṃhitā na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattati, seyyathidaṃ—rājakathā corakathā mahāmattakathā senākathā bhayakathā yuddhakathā annakathā pānakathā vatthakathā sayanakathā mālākathā gandhakathā ñātikathā yānakathā gāmakathā nigamakathā nagarakathā janapadakathā itthikathā surākathā visikhākathā kumbhaṭṭhānakathā pubbapetakathā nānattakathā lokakkhāyikā samuddakkhāyikā itibhavābhavakathā iti vā iti—evarūpiṃ kathaṃ na kathessāmī’ti.**‘I will not engage in the kind of speech that is low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. Such speech doesn’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment. Namely: talk about kings, bandits, and ministers; talk about armies, threats, and wars; talk about food, drink, clothes, and beds; talk about garlands and fragrances; talk about family, vehicles, villages, towns, cities, and countries; talk about women and heroes; street talk and well talk; talk about the departed; motley talk; tales of land and sea; and talk about being reborn in this or that state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[3520]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3521]="*Yā ca kho ayaṃ, ānanda, kathā abhisallekhikā cetovinīvaraṇasappāyā ekantanibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati, seyyathidaṃ—appicchakathā santuṭṭhikathā pavivekakathā asaṃsaggakathā vīriyārambhakathā sīlakathā samādhikathā paññākathā vimuttikathā vimuttiñāṇadassanakathā iti: ‘evarūpiṃ kathaṃ kathessāmī’ti.**‘But I will engage in speech about self-effacement that helps open the heart and leads solely to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment. That is, talk about fewness of wishes, contentment, seclusion, aloofness, arousing energy, ethics, immersion, wisdom, freedom, and the knowledge and vision of freedom.’*";
P_HTM[3522]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3523]="*Tassa ce, ānanda, bhikkhuno iminā vihārena viharato vitakkāya cittaṃ namati, so:**While a mendicant is practicing such meditation, if their mind inclines to thinking, they think:*";
P_HTM[3524]="*‘ye te vitakkā hīnā gammā pothujjanikā anariyā anatthasaṃhitā na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattanti, seyyathidaṃ—kāmavitakko byāpādavitakko vihiṃsāvitakko iti evarūpe vitakke na vitakkessāmī’ti.**‘I will not think the kind of thought that is low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. Such thoughts don’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment. That is, sensual, malicious, or cruel thoughts.’*";
P_HTM[3525]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3526]="*Ye ca kho ime, ānanda, vitakkā ariyā niyyānikā niyyanti takkarassa sammādukkhakkhayāya, seyyathidaṃ—nekkhammavitakko abyāpādavitakko avihiṃsāvitakko iti: ‘evarūpe vitakke vitakkessāmī’ti.**‘But I will think the kind of thought that is noble and emancipating, and brings one who practices it to the complete ending of suffering. That is, thoughts of renunciation, good will, and harmlessness.’*";
P_HTM[3527]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3528]="*Pañca kho ime, ānanda, kāmaguṇā.**There are these five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[3529]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[3530]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā,**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[3531]="*sotaviññeyyā saddā …**Sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[3532]="*ghānaviññeyyā gandhā …**Smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[3533]="*jivhāviññeyyā rasā …**Tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[3534]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā—**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[3535]="*ime kho, ānanda, pañca kāmaguṇā.**These are the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[3536]="*Yattha bhikkhunā abhikkhaṇaṃ sakaṃ cittaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ:**So you should regularly check your own mind:*";
P_HTM[3537]="*‘atthi nu kho me imesu pañcasu kāmaguṇesu aññatarasmiṃ vā aññatarasmiṃ vā āyatane uppajjati cetaso samudācāro’ti?**‘Does my mind take an interest in any of these five kinds of sensual stimulation?’*";
P_HTM[3538]="*Sace, ānanda, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno evaṃ pajānāti:**Suppose that, upon checking, a mendicant knows this:*";
P_HTM[3539]="*‘atthi kho me imesu pañcasu kāmaguṇesu aññatarasmiṃ vā aññatarasmiṃ vā āyatane uppajjati cetaso samudācāro’ti,**‘My mind does take an interest.’*";
P_HTM[3540]="*evaṃ santametaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu evaṃ pajānāti:**In that case, they understand:*";
P_HTM[3541]="*‘yo kho imesu pañcasu kāmaguṇesu chandarāgo so me nappahīno’ti.**‘I have not given up desire and greed for the five kinds of sensual stimulation.’*";
P_HTM[3542]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3543]="*Sace panānanda, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno evaṃ pajānāti:**But suppose that, upon checking, a mendicant knows this:*";
P_HTM[3544]="*‘natthi kho me imesu pañcasu kāmaguṇesu aññatarasmiṃ vā aññatarasmiṃ vā āyatane uppajjati cetaso samudācāro’ti,**‘My mind does not take an interest.’*";
P_HTM[3545]="*evaṃ santametaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu evaṃ pajānāti:**In that case, they understand:*";
P_HTM[3546]="*‘yo kho imesu pañcasu kāmaguṇesu chandarāgo so me pahīno’ti.**‘I have given up desire and greed for the five kinds of sensual stimulation.’*";
P_HTM[3547]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3548]="*Pañca kho ime, ānanda, upādānakkhandhā yattha bhikkhunā udayabbayānupassinā vihātabbaṃ:**A mendicant should meditate observing rise and fall in these five grasping aggregates:*";
P_HTM[3549]="*‘iti rūpaṃ iti rūpassa samudayo iti rūpassa atthaṅgamo,**‘Such is form, such is the origin of form, such is the ending of form.*";
P_HTM[3550]="*iti vedanā …**Such is feeling …*";
P_HTM[3551]="*iti saññā …**Such is perception …*";
P_HTM[3552]="*iti saṅkhārā …**Such are choices …*";
P_HTM[3553]="*iti viññāṇaṃ iti viññāṇassa samudayo iti viññāṇassa atthaṅgamo’ti.**Such is consciousness, such is the origin of consciousness, such is the ending of consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[3554]="*Tassa imesu pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu udayabbayānupassino viharato yo pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu asmimāno so pahīyati.**As they do so, they give up the conceit ‘I am’ regarding the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[3555]="*Evaṃ santametaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu evaṃ pajānāti:**In that case, they understand:*";
P_HTM[3556]="*‘yo kho imesu pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu asmimāno so me pahīno’ti.**‘I have given up the conceit “I am” regarding the five grasping aggregates.’*";
P_HTM[3557]="*Itiha tattha sampajāno hoti.**In this way they are aware of the situation.*";
P_HTM[3558]="*Ime kho te, ānanda, dhammā ekantakusalā kusalāyātikā ariyā lokuttarā anavakkantā pāpimatā.**These principles are entirely skillful, with skillful outcomes; they are noble, transcendent, and inaccessible to the Wicked One.*";
P_HTM[3559]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ānanda,**What do you think, Ānanda?*";
P_HTM[3560]="*kaṃ atthavasaṃ sampassamāno arahati sāvako satthāraṃ anubandhituṃ api paṇujjamāno”ti?**For what reason would a disciple value following the Teacher, even if sent away?”*";
P_HTM[3561]="*“Bhagavaṃmūlakā no, bhante, dhammā bhagavaṃnettikā bhagavaṃpaṭisaraṇā. Sādhu vata, bhante, bhagavantaṃyeva paṭibhātu etassa bhāsitassa attho. Bhagavato sutvā bhikkhū dhāressantī”ti.**“Our teachings are rooted in the Buddha. He is our guide and our refuge. Sir, may the Buddha himself please clarify the meaning of this. The mendicants will listen and remember it.”*";
P_HTM[3562]="*“Na kho, ānanda, arahati sāvako satthāraṃ anubandhituṃ, yadidaṃ suttaṃ geyyaṃ veyyākaraṇaṃ tassa hetu.**“A disciple should not value following the Teacher for the sake of statements, songs, or discussions.*";
P_HTM[3563]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3564]="*Dīgharattassa hi te, ānanda, dhammā sutā dhātā vacasā paricitā manasānupekkhitā diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā.**Because for a long time you have learned the teachings, remembering them, reciting them, mentally scrutinizing them, and understanding them with right view.*";
P_HTM[3565]="*Yā ca kho ayaṃ, ānanda, kathā abhisallekhikā cetovinīvaraṇasappāyā ekantanibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati, seyyathidaṃ—appicchakathā santuṭṭhikathā pavivekakathā asaṃsaggakathā vīriyārambhakathā sīlakathā samādhikathā paññākathā vimuttikathā vimuttiñāṇadassanakathā—evarūpiyā kho, ānanda, kathāya hetu arahati sāvako satthāraṃ anubandhituṃ api paṇujjamāno.**But a disciple should value following the Teacher, even if asked to go away, for the sake of talk about self-effacement that helps open the heart and leads solely to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment. That is, talk about fewness of wishes, contentment, seclusion, aloofness, arousing energy, ethics, immersion, wisdom, freedom, and the knowledge and vision of freedom.*";
P_HTM[3566]="*Evaṃ sante kho, ānanda, ācariyūpaddavo hoti, evaṃ sante antevāsūpaddavo hoti, evaṃ sante brahmacārūpaddavo hoti.**This being so, Ānanda, there is a peril for the teacher, a peril for the student, and a peril for a spiritual practitioner.*";
P_HTM[3567]="*Kathañcānanda, ācariyūpaddavo hoti?**And how is there a peril for the teacher?*";
P_HTM[3568]="*Idhānanda, ekacco satthā vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajati araññaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ pabbataṃ kandaraṃ giriguhaṃ susānaṃ vanapatthaṃ abbhokāsaṃ palālapuñjaṃ.**It’s when some teacher frequents a secluded lodging—a wilderness, the root of a tree, a hill, a ravine, a mountain cave, a charnel ground, a forest, the open air, a heap of straw.*";
P_HTM[3569]="*Tassa tathāvūpakaṭṭhassa viharato anvāvattanti brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamā ceva jānapadā ca.**While meditating withdrawn, they’re visited by a stream of brahmins and householders of the city and country.*";
P_HTM[3570]="*So anvāvattantesu brāhmaṇagahapatikesu negamesu ceva jānapadesu ca mucchaṃ nikāmayati, gedhaṃ āpajjati, āvattati bāhullāya.**When this happens, they enjoy infatuation, fall into greed, and return to indulgence.*";
P_HTM[3571]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, upaddavo ācariyo.**This teacher is said to be imperiled by the teacher’s peril.*";
P_HTM[3572]="*Ācariyūpaddavena avadhiṃsu naṃ pāpakā akusalā dhammā saṃkilesikā ponobbhavikā sadarā dukkhavipākā āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇiyā.**They’re ruined by bad, unskillful qualities that are corrupted, leading to future lives, hurtful, resulting in suffering and future rebirth, old age, and death.*";
P_HTM[3573]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, ācariyūpaddavo hoti.**That’s how there is a peril for the teacher.*";
P_HTM[3574]="*Kathañcānanda, antevāsūpaddavo hoti?**And how is there a peril for the student?*";
P_HTM[3575]="*Tasseva kho panānanda, satthu sāvako tassa satthu vivekamanubrūhayamāno**It’s when the student of a teacher, emulating their teacher’s fostering of seclusion,*";
P_HTM[3576]="*vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajati araññaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ pabbataṃ kandaraṃ giriguhaṃ susānaṃ vanapatthaṃ abbhokāsaṃ palālapuñjaṃ.**frequents a secluded lodging—a wilderness, the root of a tree, a hill, a ravine, a mountain cave, a charnel ground, a forest, the open air, a heap of straw.*";
P_HTM[3577]="*Tassa tathāvūpakaṭṭhassa viharato anvāvattanti brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamā ceva jānapadā ca.**While meditating withdrawn, they’re visited by a stream of brahmins and householders of the city and country.*";
P_HTM[3578]="*So anvāvattantesu brāhmaṇagahapatikesu negamesu ceva jānapadesu ca mucchaṃ nikāmayati, gedhaṃ āpajjati, āvattati bāhullāya.**When this happens, they enjoy infatuation, fall into greed, and return to indulgence.*";
P_HTM[3579]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, upaddavo antevāsī.**This student is said to be imperiled by the student’s peril.*";
P_HTM[3580]="*Antevāsūpaddavena avadhiṃsu naṃ pāpakā akusalā dhammā saṅkilesikā ponobbhavikā sadarā dukkhavipākā āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇiyā.**They’re ruined by bad, unskillful qualities that are corrupted, leading to future lives, hurtful, resulting in suffering and future rebirth, old age, and death.*";
P_HTM[3581]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, antevāsūpaddavo hoti.**That’s how there is a peril for the student.*";
P_HTM[3582]="*Kathañcānanda, brahmacārūpaddavo hoti?**And how is there a peril for a spiritual practitioner?*";
P_HTM[3583]="*Idhānanda, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā.**It’s when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.*";
P_HTM[3584]="*So vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajati araññaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ pabbataṃ kandaraṃ giriguhaṃ susānaṃ vanapatthaṃ abbhokāsaṃ palālapuñjaṃ.**He frequents a secluded lodging—a wilderness, the root of a tree, a hill, a ravine, a mountain cave, a charnel ground, a forest, the open air, a heap of straw.*";
P_HTM[3585]="*Tassa tathāvūpakaṭṭhassa viharato anvāvattanti brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamā ceva jānapadā ca.**While meditating withdrawn, he’s visited by a stream of brahmins and householders of the city and country.*";
P_HTM[3586]="*So anvāvattantesu brāhmaṇagahapatikesu negamesu ceva jānapadesu ca na mucchaṃ nikāmayati, na gedhaṃ āpajjati, na āvattati bāhullāya.**When this happens, he doesn’t enjoy infatuation, fall into greed, and return to indulgence.*";
P_HTM[3587]="*Tasseva kho panānanda, satthu sāvako tassa satthu vivekamanubrūhayamāno**But a disciple of this teacher, emulating their teacher’s fostering of seclusion,*";
P_HTM[3588]="*vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajati araññaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ pabbataṃ kandaraṃ giriguhaṃ susānaṃ vanapatthaṃ abbhokāsaṃ palālapuñjaṃ.**frequents a secluded lodging—a wilderness, the root of a tree, a hill, a ravine, a mountain cave, a charnel ground, a forest, the open air, a heap of straw.*";
P_HTM[3589]="*Tassa tathāvūpakaṭṭhassa viharato anvāvattanti brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamā ceva jānapadā ca.**While meditating withdrawn, they’re visited by a stream of brahmins and householders of the city and country.*";
P_HTM[3590]="*So anvāvattantesu brāhmaṇagahapatikesu negamesu ceva jānapadesu ca mucchaṃ nikāmayati, gedhaṃ āpajjati, āvattati bāhullāya.**When this happens, they enjoy infatuation, fall into greed, and return to indulgence.*";
P_HTM[3591]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, upaddavo brahmacārī.**This spiritual practitioner is said to be imperiled by the spiritual practitioner’s peril.*";
P_HTM[3592]="*Brahmacārūpaddavena avadhiṃsu naṃ pāpakā akusalā dhammā saṅkilesikā ponobbhavikā sadarā dukkhavipākā āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇiyā.**They’re ruined by bad, unskillful qualities that are corrupted, leading to future lives, hurtful, resulting in suffering and future rebirth, old age, and death.*";
P_HTM[3593]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, brahmacārūpaddavo hoti.**That’s how there is a peril for the spiritual practitioner.*";
P_HTM[3594]="*Tatrānanda, yo cevāyaṃ ācariyūpaddavo, yo ca antevāsūpaddavo ayaṃ tehi brahmacārūpaddavo dukkhavipākataro ceva kaṭukavipākataro ca, api ca vinipātāya saṃvattati.**And in this context, Ānanda, as compared to the peril of the teacher or the student, the peril of the spiritual practitioner has more painful, bitter results, and even leads to the underworld.*";
P_HTM[3595]="*Tasmātiha maṃ, ānanda, mittavatāya samudācaratha, mā sapattavatāya.**So, Ānanda, treat me as a friend, not as an enemy.*";
P_HTM[3596]="*Taṃ vo bhavissati dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāya.**That will be for your lasting welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[3597]="*Kathañcānanda, satthāraṃ sāvakā sapattavatāya samudācaranti, no mittavatāya?**And how do disciples treat their Teacher as an enemy, not a friend?*";
P_HTM[3598]="*Idhānanda, satthā sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ deseti anukampako hitesī anukampaṃ upādāya:**It’s when the Teacher teaches the Dhamma out of kindness and compassion:*";
P_HTM[3599]="*‘idaṃ vo hitāya, idaṃ vo sukhāyā’ti.**‘This is for your welfare. This is for your happiness.’*";
P_HTM[3600]="*Tassa sāvakā na sussūsanti, na sotaṃ odahanti, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, vokkamma ca satthusāsanā vattanti.**But their disciples don’t want to listen. They don’t pay attention or apply their minds to understand. They proceed having turned away from the Teacher’s instruction.*";
P_HTM[3601]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, satthāraṃ sāvakā sapattavatāya samudācaranti, no mittavatāya.**That’s how the disciples treat their Teacher as an enemy, not a friend.*";
P_HTM[3602]="*Kathañcānanda, satthāraṃ sāvakā mittavatāya samudācaranti, no sapattavatāya?**And how do disciples treat their Teacher as a friend, not an enemy?*";
P_HTM[3603]="*Idhānanda, satthā sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ deseti anukampako hitesī anukampaṃ upādāya:**It’s when the Teacher teaches the Dhamma out of kindness and compassion:*";
P_HTM[3604]="*‘idaṃ vo hitāya, idaṃ vo sukhāyā’ti.**‘This is for your welfare. This is for your happiness.’*";
P_HTM[3605]="*Tassa sāvakā sussūsanti, sotaṃ odahanti, aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, na ca vokkamma satthusāsanā vattanti.**And their disciples want to listen. They pay attention and apply their minds to understand. They don’t proceed having turned away from the Teacher’s instruction.*";
P_HTM[3606]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, satthāraṃ sāvakā mittavatāya samudācaranti, no sapattavatāya.**That’s how the disciples treat their Teacher as a friend, not an enemy.*";
P_HTM[3607]="*Tasmātiha maṃ, ānanda, mittavatāya samudācaratha, mā sapattavatāya.**So, Ānanda, treat me as a friend, not as an enemy.*";
P_HTM[3608]="*Taṃ vo bhavissati dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāya.**That will be for your lasting welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[3609]="*Na vo ahaṃ, ānanda, tathā parakkamissāmi yathā kumbhakāro āmake āmakamatte.**I shall not mollycoddle you like a potter with their damp, unfired pots.*";
P_HTM[3610]="*Niggayha niggayhāhaṃ, ānanda, vakkhāmi;**I shall speak, pushing you again and again,*";
P_HTM[3611]="*pavayha pavayha, ānanda, vakkhāmi.**pressing you again and again.*";
P_HTM[3612]="*Yo sāro so ṭhassatī”ti.**The core will stand the test.”*";
P_HTM[3613]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3614]="*Attamano āyasmā ānando bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Ānanda was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3615]="*Mahāsuññatasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3616]="*123. Acchariyaabbhutasutta**Incredible and Amazing*";
P_HTM[3617]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3618]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[3619]="*Atha kho sambahulānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantānaṃ upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ ayamantarākathā udapādi:**Then after the meal, on return from alms-round, several senior mendicants sat together in the pavilion and this discussion came up among them:*";
P_HTM[3620]="*“acchariyaṃ, āvuso, abbhutaṃ, āvuso. Tathāgatassa mahiddhikatā mahānubhāvatā,**“It’s incredible, reverends, it’s amazing, the power and might of a Realized One!*";
P_HTM[3621]="*yatra hi nāma tathāgato atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivatte jānissati:**For he is able to know the Buddhas of the past who have become completely extinguished, cut off proliferation, cut off the track, finished off the cycle, and transcended suffering.*";
P_HTM[3622]="*‘evaṃjaccā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ itipi, ‘evaṃnāmā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ itipi, ‘evaṃgottā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ itipi, ‘evaṃsīlā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ itipi, ‘evaṃdhammā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ itipi, ‘evaṃpaññā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ itipi, ‘evaṃvihārī te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ itipi, ‘evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ itipī”ti.**He knows the caste they were born in, and also their names, clans, conduct, teaching, wisdom, meditation, and freedom.”*";
P_HTM[3623]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando te bhikkhū etadavoca:**When they said this, Venerable Ānanda said,*";
P_HTM[3624]="*“acchariyā ceva, āvuso, tathāgatā acchariyadhammasamannāgatā ca;**“The Realized Ones are incredible, reverends, and they have incredible qualities.*";
P_HTM[3625]="*abbhutā ceva, āvuso, tathāgatā abbhutadhammasamannāgatā cā”ti.**They’re amazing, and they have amazing qualities.”*";
P_HTM[3626]="*Ayañca hidaṃ tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ antarākathā vippakatā hoti.**But this conversation among those mendicants was left unfinished.*";
P_HTM[3627]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenupaṭṭhānasālā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha came out of retreat, went to the assembly hall, sat down on the seat spread out,*";
P_HTM[3628]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**and addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[3629]="*“kāya nuttha, bhikkhave, etarahi kathāya sannisinnā, kā ca pana vo antarākathā vippakatā”ti?**“Mendicants, what were you sitting talking about just now? What conversation was unfinished?”*";
P_HTM[3630]="*“Idha, bhante, amhākaṃ pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantānaṃ upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ ayamantarākathā udapādi:**So the mendicants told him what they had been talking about when the Buddha arrived. The Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[3631]="*‘acchariyaṃ, āvuso, abbhutaṃ, āvuso, tathāgatassa mahiddhikatā mahānubhāvatā, yatra hi nāma tathāgato atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivatte jānissati—* **";
P_HTM[3632]="*evaṃjaccā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃnāmā … evaṅgottā … evaṃsīlā … evaṃdhammā … evaṃpaññā … evaṃvihārī … evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipī’ti. Evaṃ vutte, bhante, āyasmā ānando amhe etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3633]="*‘acchariyā ceva, āvuso, tathāgatā acchariyadhammasamannāgatā ca;* **";
P_HTM[3634]="*abbhutā ceva, āvuso, tathāgatā abbhutadhammasamannāgatā cā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3635]="*Ayaṃ kho no, bhante, antarākathā vippakatā; atha bhagavā anuppatto”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3636]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:* **";
P_HTM[3637]="*“tasmātiha taṃ, ānanda, bhiyyoso mattāya paṭibhantu tathāgatassa acchariyā abbhutadhammā”ti.**“Well then, Ānanda, say some more about the incredible and amazing qualities of the Realized One.”*";
P_HTM[3638]="*“Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**“Sir, I have heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3639]="*‘sato sampajāno, ānanda, bodhisatto tusitaṃ kāyaṃ upapajjī’ti.**‘Mindful and aware, the being intent on awakening was reborn in the host of Joyful Gods.’*";
P_HTM[3640]="*Yampi, bhante, sato sampajāno bodhisatto tusitaṃ kāyaṃ upapajji idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (1)**This I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3641]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3642]="*‘sato sampajāno, ānanda, bodhisatto tusite kāye aṭṭhāsī’ti.**‘Mindful and aware, the being intent on awakening remained in the host of Joyful Gods.’*";
P_HTM[3643]="*Yampi, bhante, sato sampajāno bodhisatto tusite kāye aṭṭhāsi idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (2)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3644]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3645]="*‘yāvatāyukaṃ, ānanda, bodhisatto tusite kāye aṭṭhāsī’ti.**‘For the whole of that life, the being intent on awakening remained in the host of Joyful Gods.’*";
P_HTM[3646]="*Yampi, bhante, yāvatāyukaṃ bodhisatto tusite kāye aṭṭhāsi idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (3)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3647]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3648]="*‘sato sampajāno, ānanda, bodhisatto tusitā, kāyā cavitvā mātukucchiṃ okkamī’ti.**‘Mindful and aware, the being intent on awakening passed away from the host of Joyful Gods and was conceived in his mother’s womb.’*";
P_HTM[3649]="*Yampi, bhante, sato sampajāno bodhisatto tusitā kāyā cavitvā mātukucchiṃ okkami idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (4)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3650]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3651]="*‘yadā, ānanda, bodhisatto tusitā kāyā cavitvā mātukucchiṃ okkamati,**‘When the being intent on awakening passes away from the host of Joyful Gods, he is conceived in his mother’s womb.*";
P_HTM[3652]="*atha sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya appamāṇo uḷāro obhāso loke pātubhavati atikkammeva devānaṃ devānubhāvaṃ.**And then—in this world with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—an immeasurable, magnificent light appears, surpassing the glory of the gods.*";
P_HTM[3653]="*Yāpi tā lokantarikā aghā asaṃvutā andhakārā andhakāratimisā, yatthapime candimasūriyā evaṃmahiddhikā evaṃmahānubhāvā ābhāya nānubhonti tatthapi appamāṇo uḷāro obhāso loke pātubhavati atikkammeva devānaṃ devānubhāvaṃ.**Even in the boundless desolation of interstellar space—so utterly dark that even the light of the moon and the sun, so mighty and powerful, makes no impression—an immeasurable, magnificent light appears, surpassing the glory of the gods.*";
P_HTM[3654]="*Yepi tattha sattā upapannā tepi tenobhāsena aññamaññaṃ sañjānanti—aññepi kira, bho, santi sattā idhūpapannāti.**And even the sentient beings reborn there recognize each other by that light: “So, it seems other sentient beings have been reborn here!”*";
P_HTM[3655]="*Ayañca dasasahassī lokadhātu saṅkampati sampakampati sampavedhati appamāṇo ca uḷāro obhāso loke pātubhavati atikkammeva devānaṃ devānubhāvan’ti.**And this galaxy shakes and rocks and trembles. And an immeasurable, magnificent light appears in the world, surpassing the glory of the gods.’*";
P_HTM[3656]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (5)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3657]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3658]="*‘yadā, ānanda, bodhisatto mātukucchiṃ okkanto hoti, cattāro devaputtā catuddisaṃ ārakkhāya upagacchanti—mā naṃ bodhisattaṃ vā bodhisattamātaraṃ vā manusso vā amanusso vā koci vā viheṭhesī’ti.**‘When the being intent on awakening is conceived in his mother’s belly, four deities approach to guard the four directions, so that no human or non-human or anyone at all shall harm the being intent on awakening or his mother.’*";
P_HTM[3659]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (6)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3660]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3661]="*‘yadā, ānanda, bodhisatto mātukucchiṃ okkanto hoti, pakatiyā sīlavatī bodhisattamātā hoti viratā pāṇātipātā viratā adinnādānā viratā kāmesumicchācārā viratā musāvādā viratā surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhānā’ti.**‘When the being intent on awakening is conceived in his mother’s belly, she becomes naturally ethical. She refrains from killing living creatures, stealing, sexual misconduct, lying, and alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.’*";
P_HTM[3662]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (7)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3663]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3664]="*‘yadā, ānanda, bodhisatto mātukucchiṃ okkanto hoti, na bodhisattamātu purisesu mānasaṃ uppajjati kāmaguṇūpasaṃhitaṃ, anatikkamanīyā ca bodhisattamātā hoti kenaci purisena rattacittenā’ti.**‘When the being intent on awakening is conceived in his mother’s belly, she no longer feels sexual desire for men, and she cannot be violated by a man of lustful intent.’*";
P_HTM[3665]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (8)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3666]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3667]="*‘yadā, ānanda, bodhisatto mātukucchiṃ okkanto hoti, lābhinī bodhisattamātā hoti pañcannaṃ kāmaguṇānaṃ. Sā pañcahi kāmaguṇehi samappitā samaṅgībhūtā paricāretī’ti.**‘When the being intent on awakening is conceived in his mother’s belly, she obtains the five kinds of sensual stimulation and amuses herself, supplied and provided with them.’*";
P_HTM[3668]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (9)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3669]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3670]="*‘yadā, ānanda, bodhisatto mātukucchiṃ okkanto hoti, na bodhisattamātu kocideva ābādho uppajjati; sukhinī bodhisattamātā hoti akilantakāyā; bodhisattañca bodhisattamātā tirokucchigataṃ passati sabbaṅgapaccaṅgaṃ ahīnindriyaṃ.**‘When the being intent on awakening is conceived in his mother’s belly, no afflictions beset her. She’s happy and free of bodily fatigue. And she sees the being intent on awakening in her womb, complete with all his various parts, not deficient in any faculty.*";
P_HTM[3671]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, maṇi veḷuriyo subho jātimā aṭṭhaṃso suparikammakato. Tatrāssa suttaṃ āvutaṃ nīlaṃ vā pītaṃ vā lohitaṃ vā odātaṃ vā paṇḍusuttaṃ vā.**Suppose there was a beryl gem that was naturally beautiful, eight-faceted, well-worked. And it was strung with a thread of blue, yellow, red, white, or golden brown.*";
P_HTM[3672]="*Tamenaṃ cakkhumā puriso hatthe karitvā paccavekkheyya—ayaṃ kho maṇi veḷuriyo subho jātimā aṭṭhaṃso suparikammakato, tatridaṃ suttaṃ āvutaṃ nīlaṃ vā pītaṃ vā lohitaṃ vā odātaṃ vā paṇḍusuttaṃ vāti.**And someone with good eyesight were to take it in their hand and examine it: “This beryl gem is naturally beautiful, eight-faceted, well-worked. And it’s strung with a thread of blue, yellow, red, white, or golden brown.”*";
P_HTM[3673]="*Evameva kho, ānanda, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchiṃ okkanto hoti, na bodhisattamātu kocideva ābādho uppajjati; sukhinī bodhisattamātā hoti akilantakāyā; bodhisattañca bodhisattamātā tirokucchigataṃ passati sabbaṅgapaccaṅgaṃ ahīnindriyan’ti.**In the same way, when the being intent on awakening is conceived in his mother’s belly, no afflictions beset her. She’s happy and free of bodily fatigue. And she sees the being intent on awakening in her womb, complete with all his various parts, not deficient in any faculty.’*";
P_HTM[3674]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (10)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3675]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3676]="*‘sattāhajāte, ānanda, bodhisatte bodhisattamātā kālaṃ karoti, tusitaṃ kāyaṃ upapajjatī’ti.**‘Seven days after the being intent on awakening is born, his mother passes away and is reborn in the host of Joyful Gods.’*";
P_HTM[3677]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (11)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3678]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3679]="*‘yathā kho panānanda, aññā itthikā nava vā dasa vā māse gabbhaṃ kucchinā pariharitvā vijāyanti, na hevaṃ bodhisattaṃ bodhisattamātā vijāyati. Daseva māsāni bodhisattaṃ bodhisattamātā kucchinā pariharitvā vijāyatī’ti.**‘Other women carry the infant in the womb for nine or ten months before giving birth. Not so the mother of the being intent on awakening. She gives birth after exactly ten months.’*";
P_HTM[3680]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (12)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3681]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3682]="*‘yathā kho panānanda, aññā itthikā nisinnā vā nipannā vā vijāyanti, na hevaṃ bodhisattaṃ bodhisattamātā vijāyati. Ṭhitāva bodhisattaṃ bodhisattamātā vijāyatī’ti.**‘Other women give birth while sitting or lying down. Not so the mother of the being intent on awakening. She only gives birth standing up.’*";
P_HTM[3683]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (13)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3684]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3685]="*‘yadā, ānanda, bodhisatto mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, devā naṃ paṭhamaṃ paṭiggaṇhanti pacchā manussā’ti.**‘When the being intent on awakening emerges from his mother’s womb, gods receive him first, then humans.’*";
P_HTM[3686]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (14)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3687]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3688]="*‘yadā, ānanda, bodhisatto mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, appattova bodhisatto pathaviṃ hoti, cattāro naṃ devaputtā paṭiggahetvā mātu purato ṭhapenti—attamanā, devi, hohi; mahesakkho te putto uppanno’ti.**‘When the being intent on awakening emerges from his mother’s womb, before he reaches the ground, four deities receive him and place him before his mother, saying: “Rejoice, O Queen! An illustrious son is born to you.”’*";
P_HTM[3689]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (15)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3690]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3691]="*‘yadā, ānanda, bodhisatto mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, visadova nikkhamati amakkhito udena amakkhito semhena amakkhito ruhirena amakkhito kenaci asucinā suddho visado.**‘When the being intent on awakening emerges from his mother’s womb, he emerges already clean, unsoiled by waters, mucus, blood, or any other kind of impurity, pure and clean.*";
P_HTM[3692]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, maṇiratanaṃ kāsike vatthe nikkhittaṃ neva maṇiratanaṃ kāsikaṃ vatthaṃ makkheti nāpi kāsikaṃ vatthaṃ maṇiratanaṃ makkheti.**Suppose a jewel-treasure was placed on a cloth from Kāsī. The jewel would not soil the cloth, nor would the cloth soil the jewel.*";
P_HTM[3693]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3694]="*Ubhinnaṃ suddhattā.**Because of the cleanliness of them both.*";
P_HTM[3695]="*Evameva kho, ānanda, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, visadova nikkhamati amakkhito udena amakkhito semhena amakkhito ruhirena amakkhito kenaci asucinā suddho visado’ti.**In the same way, when the being intent on awakening emerges from his mother’s womb, he emerges already clean, unsoiled by waters, mucus, blood, or any other kind of impurity, pure and clean.’*";
P_HTM[3696]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (16)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3697]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3698]="*‘yadā, ānanda, bodhisatto mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, dve udakassa dhārā antalikkhā pātubhavanti—ekā sītassa, ekā uṇhassa; yena bodhisattassa udakakiccaṃ karonti mātu cā’ti.**‘When the being intent on awakening emerges from his mother’s womb, two streams of water appear in the sky, one cool, one warm, for bathing the being intent on awakening and his mother.’*";
P_HTM[3699]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (17)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3700]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3701]="*‘sampatijāto, ānanda, bodhisatto samehi pādehi pathaviyaṃ patiṭṭhahitvā uttarābhimukho sattapadavītihārena gacchati, setamhi chatte anudhāriyamāne, sabbā ca disā viloketi, āsabhiñca vācaṃ bhāsati—aggohamasmi lokassa, jeṭṭhohamasmi lokassa, seṭṭhohamasmi lokassa. Ayamantimā jāti, natthi dāni punabbhavo’ti.**‘As soon as he’s born, the being intent on awakening stands firm with his own feet on the ground. Facing north, he takes seven strides with a white parasol held above him, surveys all quarters, and makes this dramatic statement: “I am the foremost in the world! I am the eldest in the world! I am the best in the world! This is my last rebirth. Now there are no more future lives.”’*";
P_HTM[3702]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremi. (18)**This too I remember as an incredible quality of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3703]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3704]="*‘yadā, ānanda, bodhisatto mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, atha sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya appamāṇo uḷāro obhāso loke pātubhavati atikkammeva devānaṃ devānubhāvaṃ.**‘When the being intent on awakening emerges from his mother’s womb, then—in this world with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—an immeasurable, magnificent light appears, surpassing the glory of the gods.*";
P_HTM[3705]="*Yāpi tā lokantarikā aghā asaṃvutā andhakārā andhakāratimisā yatthapime candimasūriyā evaṃmahiddhikā evaṃmahānubhāvā ābhāya nānubhonti tatthapi appamāṇo uḷāro obhāso loke pātubhavati atikkammeva devānaṃ devānubhāvaṃ.**Even in the boundless desolation of interstellar space—so utterly dark that even the light of the moon and the sun, so mighty and powerful, makes no impression—an immeasurable, magnificent light appears, surpassing the glory of the gods.*";
P_HTM[3706]="*Yepi tattha sattā upapannā tepi tenobhāsena aññamaññaṃ sañjānanti—aññepi kira, bho, santi sattā idhūpapannāti.**And the sentient beings reborn there recognize each other by that light: “So, it seems other sentient beings have been reborn here!”*";
P_HTM[3707]="*Ayañca dasasahassī lokadhātu saṅkampati sampakampati sampavedhati, appamāṇo ca uḷāro obhāso loke pātubhavati atikkammeva devānaṃ devānubhāvan’ti.**And this galaxy shakes and rocks and trembles. And an immeasurable, magnificent light appears in the world, surpassing the glory of the gods.’*";
P_HTM[3708]="*Yampi, bhante … pe … idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremī”ti. (19)**This too I remember as an incredible and amazing quality of the Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[3709]="*“Tasmātiha tvaṃ, ānanda, idampi tathāgatassa acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhārehi.**“Well then, Ānanda, you should also remember this as an incredible and amazing quality of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[3710]="*Idhānanda, tathāgatassa viditā vedanā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti;**It’s that the Realized One knows feelings as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[3711]="*viditā saññā uppajjanti … pe …**He knows perceptions as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[3712]="*viditā vitakkā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**He knows thoughts as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[3713]="*Idampi kho tvaṃ, ānanda, tathāgatassa acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhārehī”ti.**This too you should remember as an incredible and amazing quality of the Realized One.”*";
P_HTM[3714]="*“Yampi, bhante, bhagavato viditā vedanā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti;**“Sir, the Buddha knows feelings as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[3715]="*viditā saññā …**He knows perceptions as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[3716]="*viditā vitakkā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**He knows thoughts as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[3717]="*Idampāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremī”ti. (20)**This too I remember as an incredible and amazing quality of the Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[3718]="*Idamavoca āyasmā ānando.**That’s what Ānanda said,*";
P_HTM[3719]="*Samanuñño satthā ahosi;**and the teacher approved.*";
P_HTM[3720]="*attamanā ca te bhikkhū āyasmato ānandassa bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, those mendicants were happy with what Venerable Ānanda said.*";
P_HTM[3721]="*Acchariyaabbhutasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3722]="*124. Bākulasutta**With Bakkula*";
P_HTM[3723]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3724]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā bākulo rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time Venerable Bakkula was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[3725]="*Atha kho acelakassapo āyasmato bākulassa purāṇagihisahāyo yenāyasmā bākulo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā bākulena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then the naked ascetic Kassapa, who had been a friend of Bakkula’s in the lay life, approached him, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[3726]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho acelakassapo āyasmantaṃ bākulaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Venerable Bakkula,*";
P_HTM[3727]="*“Kīvaciraṃ pabbajitosi, āvuso bākulā”ti?**“Reverend Bakkula, how long has it been since you went forth?”*";
P_HTM[3728]="*“Asīti me, āvuso, vassāni pabbajitassā”ti.**“It has been eighty years, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[3729]="*“Imehi pana te, āvuso bākula, asītiyā vassehi katikkhattuṃ methuno dhammo paṭisevito”ti?**“But in these eighty years, how many times have you had sex?”*";
P_HTM[3730]="*“Na kho maṃ, āvuso kassapa, evaṃ pucchitabbaṃ:**“You shouldn’t ask me such a question.*";
P_HTM[3731]="*‘imehi pana te, āvuso bākula, asītiyā vassehi katikkhattuṃ methuno dhammo paṭisevito’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3732]="*Evañca kho maṃ, āvuso kassapa, pucchitabbaṃ:**Rather, you should ask me this:*";
P_HTM[3733]="*‘imehi pana te, āvuso bākula, asītiyā vassehi katikkhattuṃ kāmasaññā uppannapubbā’”ti?**‘But in these eighty years, how many times have sensual perceptions ever arisen in you?’”*";
P_HTM[3734]="*()**“But in these eighty years, how many times have sensual perceptions ever arisen in you?”*";
P_HTM[3735]="*“Asīti me, āvuso, vassāni pabbajitassa nābhijānāmi kāmasaññaṃ uppannapubbaṃ”.**“In these eighty years, I don’t recall that any sensual perception has ever arisen in me.”*";
P_HTM[3736]="*“Yampāyasmā bākulo asītiyā vassehi nābhijānāti kāmasaññaṃ uppannapubbaṃ idampi mayaṃ āyasmato bākulassa acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhārema”. (1)**“This we remember as an incredible quality of Venerable Bakkula.”*";
P_HTM[3737]="*“Asīti me, āvuso, vassāni pabbajitassa nābhijānāmi byāpādasaññaṃ … pe …**“In these eighty years, I don’t recall that any perception of ill will …*";
P_HTM[3738]="*vihiṃsāsaññaṃ uppannapubbaṃ”.**or cruelty has ever arisen in me.”*";
P_HTM[3739]="*“Yampāyasmā bākulo asītiyā vassehi nābhijānāti vihiṃsāsaññaṃ uppannapubbaṃ, idampi mayaṃ āyasmato bākulassa acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhārema”. (2–3.)**“This too we remember as an incredible quality of Venerable Bakkula.”*";
P_HTM[3740]="*“Asīti me, āvuso, vassāni pabbajitassa nābhijānāmi kāmavitakkaṃ uppannapubbaṃ”.**“In these eighty years, I don’t recall that any thought of sensuality …*";
P_HTM[3741]="*“Yampāyasmā bākulo asītiyā vassehi nābhijānāti kāmavitakkaṃ uppannapubbaṃ, idampi mayaṃ āyasmato bākulassa acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhārema”. (4)* **";
P_HTM[3742]="*“Asīti me, āvuso, vassāni pabbajitassa nābhijānāmi byāpādavitakkaṃ … pe …**ill will …*";
P_HTM[3743]="*vihiṃsāvitakkaṃ uppannapubbaṃ”.**or cruelty has ever arisen in me.”*";
P_HTM[3744]="*“Yampāyasmā bākulo asītiyā vassehi nābhijānāti vihiṃsāvitakkaṃ uppannapubbaṃ, idampi mayaṃ āyasmato bākulassa acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhārema”. (5–6.)**“This too we remember as an incredible quality of Venerable Bakkula.”*";
P_HTM[3745]="*“Asīti me, āvuso, vassāni pabbajitassa nābhijānāmi gahapaticīvaraṃ sāditā”.**“In these eighty years, I don’t recall accepting a robe from a householder …*";
P_HTM[3746]="*“Yampāyasmā bākulo asītiyā vassehi nābhijānāti gahapaticīvaraṃ sāditā, idampi mayaṃ āyasmato bākulassa acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhārema”. (7)* **";
P_HTM[3747]="*“Asīti me, āvuso, vassāni pabbajitassa nābhijānāmi satthena cīvaraṃ chinditā”.**cutting a robe with a knife …*";
P_HTM[3748]="*“Yampāyasmā bākulo asītiyā vassehi nābhijānāti satthena cīvaraṃ chinditā … pe … dhārema”. (8)* **";
P_HTM[3749]="*“Asīti me, āvuso, vassāni pabbajitassa nābhijānāmi sūciyā cīvaraṃ sibbitā … pe …**sewing a robe with a needle …*";
P_HTM[3750]="*nābhijānāmi rajanena cīvaraṃ rajitā …**dying a robe …*";
P_HTM[3751]="*nābhijānāmi kathine cīvaraṃ sibbitā …**sewing a robe at kaṭhina time …*";
P_HTM[3752]="*nābhijānāmi sabrahmacārīnaṃ cīvarakamme vicāritā …**looking for robe material for my companions in the spiritual life when they are making robes …*";
P_HTM[3753]="*nābhijānāmi nimantanaṃ sāditā …**accepting an invitation …*";
P_HTM[3754]="*nābhijānāmi evarūpaṃ cittaṃ uppannapubbaṃ:**having such a thought:*";
P_HTM[3755]="*‘aho vata maṃ koci nimanteyyā’ti …**‘If only someone would invite me!’ …*";
P_HTM[3756]="*nābhijānāmi antaraghare nisīditā …**sitting down inside a house …*";
P_HTM[3757]="*nābhijānāmi antaraghare bhuñjitā …**eating inside a house …*";
P_HTM[3758]="*nābhijānāmi mātugāmassa anubyañjanaso nimittaṃ gahetā …**getting caught up in the details of female’s appearance …*";
P_HTM[3759]="*nābhijānāmi mātugāmassa dhammaṃ desitā antamaso catuppadampi gāthaṃ …**teaching a female, even so much as a four line verse …*";
P_HTM[3760]="*nābhijānāmi bhikkhunupassayaṃ upasaṅkamitā …**going to the nuns’ quarters …*";
P_HTM[3761]="*nābhijānāmi bhikkhuniyā dhammaṃ desitā …**teaching the nuns …*";
P_HTM[3762]="*nābhijānāmi sikkhamānāya dhammaṃ desitā …**teaching the trainee nuns …*";
P_HTM[3763]="*nābhijānāmi sāmaṇeriyā dhammaṃ desitā …**teaching the novice nuns …*";
P_HTM[3764]="*nābhijānāmi pabbājetā …**giving the going forth …*";
P_HTM[3765]="*nābhijānāmi upasampādetā …**giving the ordination …*";
P_HTM[3766]="*nābhijānāmi nissayaṃ dātā …**giving dependence …*";
P_HTM[3767]="*nābhijānāmi sāmaṇeraṃ upaṭṭhāpetā …**being looked after by a novice …*";
P_HTM[3768]="*nābhijānāmi jantāghare nhāyitā …**bathing in the sauna …*";
P_HTM[3769]="*nābhijānāmi cuṇṇena nhāyitā …**bathing with bath powder …*";
P_HTM[3770]="*nābhijānāmi sabrahmacārīgattaparikamme vicāritā …**looking for a massage from my companions in the spiritual life …*";
P_HTM[3771]="*nābhijānāmi ābādhaṃ uppannapubbaṃ, antamaso gaddūhanamattampi …**being ill, even for as long as it takes to pull a cow’s udder …*";
P_HTM[3772]="*nābhijānāmi bhesajjaṃ upaharitā, antamaso haritakikhaṇḍampi …**being presented with medicine, even as much as a bit of yellow myrobalan …*";
P_HTM[3773]="*nābhijānāmi apassenakaṃ apassayitā …**leaning on a headrest …*";
P_HTM[3774]="*nābhijānāmi seyyaṃ kappetā”.**preparing a cot …”*";
P_HTM[3775]="*“Yampāyasmā … pe … dhārema”. (9–33.)**“This too we remember as an incredible quality of Venerable Bakkula.”*";
P_HTM[3776]="*“Asīti me, āvuso, vassāni pabbajitassa nābhijānāmi gāmantasenāsane vassaṃ upagantā”.**“In these eighty years, I don’t recall commencing the rainy season residence in the neighborhood of a village.”*";
P_HTM[3777]="*“Yampāyasmā bākulo asītiyā vassehi nābhijānāti gāmantasenāsane vassaṃ upagantā, idampi mayaṃ āyasmato bākulassa acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhārema”. (34)**“This too we remember as an incredible quality of Venerable Bakkula.”*";
P_HTM[3778]="*“Sattāhameva kho ahaṃ, āvuso, saraṇo raṭṭhapiṇḍaṃ bhuñjiṃ;**“Reverend, for seven days I ate the nation’s alms-food as a debtor.*";
P_HTM[3779]="*atha aṭṭhamiyaṃ aññā udapādi.**Then on the eighth day I became enlightened.”*";
P_HTM[3780]="*Yampāyasmā bākulo sattāhameva saraṇo raṭṭhapiṇḍaṃ bhuñji; atha aṭṭhamiyaṃ aññā udapādi idampi mayaṃ āyasmato bākulassa acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhārema. (35)**“This too we remember as an incredible quality of Venerable Bakkula.*";
P_HTM[3781]="*Labheyyāhaṃ, āvuso bākula, imasmiṃ dhammavinaye pabbajjaṃ, labheyyaṃ upasampadan”ti.**Reverend Bakkula, may I receive the going forth, the ordination in this teaching and training?”*";
P_HTM[3782]="*Alattha kho acelakassapo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye pabbajjaṃ, alattha upasampadaṃ.**And the naked ascetic Kassapa received the going forth, the ordination in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[3783]="*Acirūpasampanno panāyasmā kassapo eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**Not long after his ordination, Venerable Kassapa, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[3784]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[3785]="*Aññataro kho panāyasmā kassapo arahataṃ ahosi.**And Venerable Kassapa became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[3786]="*Atha kho āyasmā bākulo aparena samayena avāpuraṇaṃ ādāya vihārena vihāraṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāha:**Then some time later Venerable Bakkula took a key and went from dwelling to dwelling, saying,*";
P_HTM[3787]="*“abhikkamathāyasmanto, abhikkamathāyasmanto. Ajja me parinibbānaṃ bhavissatī”ti.**“Come forth, venerables, come forth! Today will be my final extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[3788]="*“Yampāyasmā bākulo avāpuraṇaṃ ādāya vihārena vihāraṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāha: ‘abhikkamathāyasmanto, abhikkamathāyasmanto; ajja me parinibbānaṃ bhavissatī’ti, idampi mayaṃ āyasmato bākulassa acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhārema”. (36)**“This too we remember as an incredible quality of Venerable Bakkula.”*";
P_HTM[3789]="*Āyasmā bākulo majjhe bhikkhusaṅghassa nisinnakova parinibbāyi.**And Venerable Bakkula became fully extinguished while sitting right in the middle of the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[3790]="*“Yampāyasmā bākulo majjhe bhikkhusaṅghassa nisinnakova parinibbāyi, idampi mayaṃ āyasmato bākulassa acchariyaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ dhāremā”ti. (37)**“This too we remember as an incredible quality of Venerable Bakkula.”*";
P_HTM[3791]="*Bākulasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3792]="*125. Dantabhūmisutta**The Level of the Tamed*";
P_HTM[3793]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3794]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[3795]="*Tena kho pana samayena aciravato samaṇuddeso araññakuṭikāyaṃ viharati.**Now at that time the novice Aciravata was staying in a wilderness hut.*";
P_HTM[3796]="*Atha kho jayaseno rājakumāro jaṅghāvihāraṃ anucaṅkamamāno anuvicaramāno yena aciravato samaṇuddeso tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā aciravatena samaṇuddesena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then as Prince Jayasena was going for a walk he approached Aciravata, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[3797]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho jayaseno rājakumāro aciravataṃ samaṇuddesaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Aciravata,*";
P_HTM[3798]="*“Sutaṃ metaṃ, bho aggivessana:**“Master Aggivessana, I have heard that*";
P_HTM[3799]="*‘idha bhikkhu appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto phuseyya cittassa ekaggatan’”ti.**a mendicant who meditates diligently, keenly, and resolutely can experience unification of mind.”*";
P_HTM[3800]="*“Evametaṃ, rājakumāra, evametaṃ, rājakumāra.**“That’s so true, Prince! That’s so true!*";
P_HTM[3801]="*Idha bhikkhu appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto phuseyya cittassa ekaggatan”ti.**A mendicant who meditates diligently, keenly, and resolutely can experience unification of mind.”*";
P_HTM[3802]="*“Sādhu me bhavaṃ aggivessano yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ desetū”ti.**“Master Aggivessana, please teach me the Dhamma as you have learned and memorized it.”*";
P_HTM[3803]="*“Na kho te ahaṃ, rājakumāra, sakkomi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ desetuṃ.**“I’m not competent to do so, Prince.*";
P_HTM[3804]="*Ahañca hi te, rājakumāra, yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ deseyyaṃ, tvañca me bhāsitassa atthaṃ na ājāneyyāsi; so mamassa kilamatho, sā mamassa vihesā”ti.**For if I were to teach you the Dhamma as I have learned and memorized it, you might not understand the meaning, which would be wearying and troublesome for me.”*";
P_HTM[3805]="*“Desetu me bhavaṃ aggivessano yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ.**“Master Aggivessana, please teach me the Dhamma as you have learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[3806]="*Appevanāmāhaṃ bhoto aggivessanassa bhāsitassa atthaṃ ājāneyyan”ti.**Hopefully I will understand the meaning of what you say.”*";
P_HTM[3807]="*“Deseyyaṃ kho te ahaṃ, rājakumāra, yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ.**“Then I shall teach you.*";
P_HTM[3808]="*Sace me tvaṃ bhāsitassa atthaṃ ājāneyyāsi, iccetaṃ kusalaṃ;**If you understand the meaning of what I say, that’s good.*";
P_HTM[3809]="*no ce me tvaṃ bhāsitassa atthaṃ ājāneyyāsi, yathāsake tiṭṭheyyāsi, na maṃ tattha uttariṃ paṭipuccheyyāsī”ti.**If not, then leave each to his own, and do not question me about it further.”*";
P_HTM[3810]="*“Desetu me bhavaṃ aggivessano yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ.**“Master Aggivessana, please teach me the Dhamma as you have learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[3811]="*Sace ahaṃ bhoto aggivessanassa bhāsitassa atthaṃ ājānissāmi, iccetaṃ kusalaṃ;**If I understand the meaning of what you say, that’s good.*";
P_HTM[3812]="*no ce ahaṃ bhoto aggivessanassa bhāsitassa atthaṃ ājānissāmi, yathāsake tiṭṭhissāmi, nāhaṃ tattha bhavantaṃ aggivessanaṃ uttariṃ paṭipucchissāmī”ti.**If not, then I will leave each to his own, and not question you about it further.”*";
P_HTM[3813]="*Atha kho aciravato samaṇuddeso jayasenassa rājakumārassa yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ desesi.**Then the novice Aciravata taught Prince Jayasena the Dhamma as he had learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[3814]="*Evaṃ vutte, jayaseno rājakumāro aciravataṃ samaṇuddesaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Jayasena said to him,*";
P_HTM[3815]="*“aṭṭhānametaṃ, bho aggivessana, anavakāso yaṃ bhikkhu appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto phuseyya cittassa ekaggatan”ti.**“It is impossible, Master Aggivessana, it cannot happen that a mendicant who meditates diligently, keenly, and resolutely can experience unification of mind.”*";
P_HTM[3816]="*Atha kho jayaseno rājakumāro aciravatassa samaṇuddesassa aṭṭhānatañca anavakāsatañca pavedetvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmi.**Having declared that this was impossible, Jayasena got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[3817]="*Atha kho aciravato samaṇuddeso acirapakkante jayasene rājakumāre yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**Not long after he had left, Aciravata went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side,*";
P_HTM[3818]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho aciravato samaṇuddeso yāvatako ahosi jayasenena rājakumārena saddhiṃ kathāsallāpo taṃ sabbaṃ bhagavato ārocesi.**and informed the Buddha of all they had discussed.*";
P_HTM[3819]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhagavā aciravataṃ samaṇuddesaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, the Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[3820]="*“‘taṃ kutettha, aggivessana, labbhā.**“How could it possibly be otherwise, Aggivessana?*";
P_HTM[3821]="*Yaṃ taṃ nekkhammena ñātabbaṃ nekkhammena daṭṭhabbaṃ nekkhammena pattabbaṃ nekkhammena sacchikātabbaṃ taṃ vata jayaseno rājakumāro kāmamajjhe vasanto kāme paribhuñjanto kāmavitakkehi khajjamāno kāmapariḷāhena pariḍayhamāno kāmapariyesanāya ussuko ñassati vā dakkhati vā sacchi vā karissatī’ti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Prince Jayasena dwells in the midst of sensual pleasures, enjoying them, consumed by thoughts of them, burning with fever for them, and eagerly seeking more. It’s simply impossible for him to know or see or realize what can only be known, seen, and realized by renunciation.*";
P_HTM[3822]="*Seyyathāpissu, aggivessana, dve hatthidammā vā assadammā vā godammā vā sudantā suvinītā, dve hatthidammā vā assadammā vā godammā vā adantā avinītā.**Suppose there was a pair of elephants or horse or oxen in training who were well tamed and well trained. And there was a pair who were not tamed or trained.*";
P_HTM[3823]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, aggivessana,**What do you think, Aggivessana?*";
P_HTM[3824]="*ye te dve hatthidammā vā assadammā vā godammā vā sudantā suvinītā, api nu te dantāva dantakāraṇaṃ gaccheyyuṃ, dantāva dantabhūmiṃ sampāpuṇeyyun”ti?**Wouldn’t the pair that was well tamed and well trained perform the tasks of the tamed and reach the level of the tamed?”*";
P_HTM[3825]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3826]="*“Ye pana te dve hatthidammā vā assadammā vā godammā vā adantā avinītā, api nu te adantāva dantakāraṇaṃ gaccheyyuṃ, adantāva dantabhūmiṃ sampāpuṇeyyuṃ, seyyathāpi te dve hatthidammā vā assadammā vā godammā vā sudantā suvinītā”ti?**“But would the pair that was not tamed and trained perform the tasks of the tamed and reach the level of the tamed, just like the tamed pair?”*";
P_HTM[3827]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3828]="*“Evameva kho, aggivessana, ‘yaṃ taṃ nekkhammena ñātabbaṃ nekkhammena daṭṭhabbaṃ nekkhammena pattabbaṃ nekkhammena sacchikātabbaṃ taṃ vata jayaseno rājakumāro kāmamajjhe vasanto kāme paribhuñjanto kāmavitakkehi khajjamāno kāmapariḷāhena pariḍayhamāno kāmapariyesanāya ussuko ñassati vā dakkhati vā sacchi vā karissatī’ti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**“In the same way, Prince Jayasena dwells in the midst of sensual pleasures, enjoying them, consumed by thoughts of them, burning with fever for them, and eagerly seeking more. It’s simply impossible for him to know or see or realize what can only be known, seen, and realized by renunciation.*";
P_HTM[3829]="*Seyyathāpi, aggivessana, gāmassa vā nigamassa vā avidūre mahāpabbato.**Suppose there was a big mountain not far from a town or village.*";
P_HTM[3830]="*Tamenaṃ dve sahāyakā tamhā gāmā vā nigamā vā nikkhamitvā hatthavilaṅghakena yena so pabbato tenupasaṅkameyyuṃ; upasaṅkamitvā eko sahāyako heṭṭhā pabbatapāde tiṭṭheyya, eko sahāyako uparipabbataṃ āroheyya.**And two friends set out from that village or town, lending each other a hand up to the mountain. Once there, one friend would remain at the foot of the mountain, while the other would climb to the peak.*";
P_HTM[3831]="*Tamenaṃ heṭṭhā pabbatapāde ṭhito sahāyako uparipabbate ṭhitaṃ sahāyakaṃ evaṃ vadeyya:**Then the one standing at the foot would say to the one at the peak,*";
P_HTM[3832]="*‘yaṃ, samma, kiṃ tvaṃ passasi uparipabbate ṭhito’ti?**‘My friend, what do you see, standing there at the peak?’*";
P_HTM[3833]="*So evaṃ vadeyya:**They’d reply,*";
P_HTM[3834]="*‘passāmi kho ahaṃ, samma, uparipabbate ṭhito ārāmarāmaṇeyyakaṃ vanarāmaṇeyyakaṃ bhūmirāmaṇeyyakaṃ pokkharaṇīrāmaṇeyyakan’ti.**‘Standing at the peak, I see delightful parks, woods, meadows, and lotus ponds!’*";
P_HTM[3835]="*So evaṃ vadeyya:**But the other would say,*";
P_HTM[3836]="*‘aṭṭhānaṃ kho etaṃ, samma, anavakāso yaṃ tvaṃ uparipabbate ṭhito passeyyāsi ārāmarāmaṇeyyakaṃ vanarāmaṇeyyakaṃ bhūmirāmaṇeyyakaṃ pokkharaṇīrāmaṇeyyakan’ti.**‘It’s impossible, it cannot happen that, standing at the peak, you can see delightful parks, woods, meadows, and lotus ponds.’*";
P_HTM[3837]="*Tamenaṃ uparipabbate ṭhito sahāyako heṭṭhimapabbatapādaṃ orohitvā taṃ sahāyakaṃ bāhāyaṃ gahetvā uparipabbataṃ āropetvā muhuttaṃ assāsetvā evaṃ vadeyya:**So their friend would come down from the peak, take their friend by the arm, and make them climb to the peak. After giving them a moment to catch their breath, they’d say,*";
P_HTM[3838]="*‘yaṃ, samma, kiṃ tvaṃ passasi uparipabbate ṭhito’ti?**‘My friend, what do you see, standing here at the peak?’*";
P_HTM[3839]="*So evaṃ vadeyya:**They’d reply,*";
P_HTM[3840]="*‘passāmi kho ahaṃ, samma, uparipabbate ṭhito ārāmarāmaṇeyyakaṃ vanarāmaṇeyyakaṃ bhūmirāmaṇeyyakaṃ pokkharaṇīrāmaṇeyyakan’ti.**‘Standing at the peak, I see delightful parks, woods, meadows, and lotus ponds!’*";
P_HTM[3841]="*So evaṃ vadeyya:**They’d say,*";
P_HTM[3842]="*‘idāneva kho te, samma, bhāsitaṃ—mayaṃ evaṃ ājānāma—**‘Just now I understood you to say:*";
P_HTM[3843]="*aṭṭhānaṃ kho etaṃ samma, anavakāso yaṃ tvaṃ uparipabbate ṭhito passeyyāsi ārāmarāmaṇeyyakaṃ vanarāmaṇeyyakaṃ bhūmirāmaṇeyyakaṃ pokkharaṇīrāmaṇeyyakan’ti.**“It’s impossible, it cannot happen that, standing at the peak, you can see delightful parks, woods, meadows, and lotus ponds.”*";
P_HTM[3844]="*Idāneva ca pana te bhāsitaṃ mayaṃ evaṃ ājānāma:**But now you say:*";
P_HTM[3845]="*‘passāmi kho ahaṃ, samma, uparipabbate ṭhito ārāmarāmaṇeyyakaṃ vanarāmaṇeyyakaṃ bhūmirāmaṇeyyakaṃ pokkharaṇīrāmaṇeyyakan’ti.**“Standing at the peak, I see delightful parks, woods, meadows, and lotus ponds!”’*";
P_HTM[3846]="*So evaṃ vadeyya:**They’d say,*";
P_HTM[3847]="*‘tathā hi panāhaṃ, samma, iminā mahatā pabbatena āvuto daṭṭheyyaṃ nāddasan’ti.**‘But my friend, it was because I was obstructed by this big mountain that I didn’t see what could be seen.’*";
P_HTM[3848]="*Ato mahantatarena, aggivessana, ‘avijjākhandhena jayaseno rājakumāro āvuto nivuto ophuṭo pariyonaddho.**But bigger than that is the mass of ignorance by which Prince Jayasena is hindered, obstructed, covered, and engulfed.*";
P_HTM[3849]="*So vata yaṃ taṃ nekkhammena ñātabbaṃ nekkhammena daṭṭhabbaṃ nekkhammena pattabbaṃ nekkhammena sacchikātabbaṃ taṃ vata jayaseno rājakumāro kāmamajjhe vasanto kāme paribhuñjanto kāmavitakkehi khajjamāno kāmapariḷāhena pariḍayhamāno kāmapariyesanāya ussuko ñassati vā dakkhati vā sacchi vā karissatī’ti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Prince Jayasena dwells in the midst of sensual pleasures, enjoying them, consumed by thoughts of them, burning with fever for them, and eagerly seeking more. It’s simply impossible for him to know or see or realize what can only be known, seen, and realized by renunciation.*";
P_HTM[3850]="*Sace kho taṃ, aggivessana, jayasenassa rājakumārassa imā dve upamā paṭibhāyeyyuṃ, anacchariyaṃ te jayaseno rājakumāro pasīdeyya, pasanno ca te pasannākāraṃ kareyyā”ti.**It wouldn’t be surprising if, had these two similes occurred to you, Prince Jayasena would have gained confidence in you and shown his confidence.”*";
P_HTM[3851]="*“Kuto pana maṃ, bhante, jayasenassa rājakumārassa imā dve upamā paṭibhāyissanti anacchariyā pubbe assutapubbā, seyyathāpi bhagavantan”ti?**“But sir, how could these two similes have occurred to me as they did to the Buddha, since they were neither supernaturally inspired, nor learned before in the past?”*";
P_HTM[3852]="*“Seyyathāpi, aggivessana, rājā khattiyo muddhāvasitto nāgavanikaṃ āmanteti:**“Suppose, Aggivessana, an anointed king was to address his elephant tracker,*";
P_HTM[3853]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, samma nāgavanika, rañño nāgaṃ abhiruhitvā nāgavanaṃ pavisitvā āraññakaṃ nāgaṃ atipassitvā rañño nāgassa gīvāyaṃ upanibandhāhī’ti.**‘Please, my good elephant tracker, mount the royal bull elephant and enter the elephant wood. When you see a wild bull elephant, tether it by the neck to the royal elephant.’*";
P_HTM[3854]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, aggivessana, nāgavaniko rañño khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa paṭissutvā rañño nāgaṃ abhiruhitvā nāgavanaṃ pavisitvā āraññakaṃ nāgaṃ atipassitvā rañño nāgassa gīvāyaṃ upanibandhati.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ replied the elephant tracker, and did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[3855]="*Tamenaṃ rañño nāgo abbhokāsaṃ nīharati.**The royal elephant leads the wild elephant out into the open;*";
P_HTM[3856]="*Ettāvatā kho, aggivessana, āraññako nāgo abbhokāsaṃ gato hoti.**and it’s only then that it comes out into the open,*";
P_HTM[3857]="*Etthagedhā hi, aggivessana, āraññakā nāgā yadidaṃ—nāgavanaṃ.**for a wild bull elephant clings to the elephant wood.*";
P_HTM[3858]="*Tamenaṃ nāgavaniko rañño khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa ārocesi:**Then the elephant tracker informs the king,*";
P_HTM[3859]="*‘abbhokāsagato kho, deva, āraññako nāgo’ti.**‘Sire, the wild elephant has come out into the open.’*";
P_HTM[3860]="*Atha kho aggivessana, tamenaṃ rājā khattiyo muddhāvasitto hatthidamakaṃ āmantesi:**Then the king addresses his elephant trainer,*";
P_HTM[3861]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, samma hatthidamaka, āraññakaṃ nāgaṃ damayāhi āraññakānañceva sīlānaṃ abhinimmadanāya āraññakānañceva sarasaṅkappānaṃ abhinimmadanāya āraññakānañceva darathakilamathapariḷāhānaṃ abhinimmadanāya gāmante abhiramāpanāya manussakantesu sīlesu samādapanāyā’ti.**‘Please, my good elephant trainer, tame the wild bull elephant. Subdue its wild behaviors, its wild memories and thoughts, and its wild stress, weariness, and fever. Make it happy to be in the neighborhood of a village, and instill behaviors congenial to humans.’*";
P_HTM[3862]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, aggivessana, hatthidamako rañño khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa paṭissutvā mahantaṃ thambhaṃ pathaviyaṃ nikhaṇitvā āraññakassa nāgassa gīvāyaṃ upanibandhati āraññakānañceva sīlānaṃ abhinimmadanāya āraññakānañceva sarasaṅkappānaṃ abhinimmadanāya āraññakānañceva darathakilamathapariḷāhānaṃ abhinimmadanāya gāmante abhiramāpanāya manussakantesu sīlesu samādapanāya.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ replied the elephant trainer. He dug a large post into the earth and tethered the elephant to it by the neck, so as to subdue its wild behaviors, its wild memories and thoughts, and its wild stress, weariness, and fever, and to make it happy to be in the neighborhood of a village, and instill behaviors congenial to humans.*";
P_HTM[3863]="*Tamenaṃ hatthidamako yā sā vācā nelā kaṇṇasukhā pemanīyā hadayaṅgamā porī bahujanakantā bahujanamanāpā tathārūpāhi vācāhi samudācarati.**He spoke in a way that’s mellow, pleasing to the ear, lovely, going to the heart, polite, likable and agreeable to the people.*";
P_HTM[3864]="*Yato kho, aggivessana, āraññako nāgo hatthidamakassa yā sā vācā nelā kaṇṇasukhā pemanīyā hadayaṅgamā porī bahujanakantā bahujanamanāpā tathārūpāhi vācāhi samudācariyamāno sussūsati, sotaṃ odahati, aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhāpeti;**Spoken to in such a way by the elephant trainer, the wild elephant wanted to listen. It leant an ear and applied its mind to understand.*";
P_HTM[3865]="*tamenaṃ hatthidamako uttari tiṇaghāsodakaṃ anuppavecchati.**So the elephant trainer rewards it with grass, fodder, and water.*";
P_HTM[3866]="*Yato kho, aggivessana, āraññako nāgo hatthidamakassa tiṇaghāsodakaṃ paṭiggaṇhāti, tatra hatthidamakassa evaṃ hoti:**When the wild elephant accepts the grass, fodder, and water, the trainer knows,*";
P_HTM[3867]="*‘jīvissati kho dāni āraññako nāgo’ti.**‘Now the wild elephant will survive!’*";
P_HTM[3868]="*Tamenaṃ hatthidamako uttari kāraṇaṃ kāreti:**Then he sets it a further task:*";
P_HTM[3869]="*‘ādiya, bho, nikkhipa, bho’ti.**‘Pick it up, sir! Put it down, sir!’*";
P_HTM[3870]="*Yato kho, aggivessana, āraññako nāgo hatthidamakassa ādānanikkhepe vacanakaro hoti ovādappaṭikaro, tamenaṃ hatthidamako uttari kāraṇaṃ kāreti:**When the wild elephant picks up and puts down when the trainer says, following instructions, the trainer sets it a further task:*";
P_HTM[3871]="*‘abhikkama, bho, paṭikkama, bho’ti.**‘Forward, sir! Back, sir!’*";
P_HTM[3872]="*Yato kho, aggivessana, āraññako nāgo hatthidamakassa abhikkamapaṭikkamavacanakaro hoti ovādappaṭikaro, tamenaṃ hatthidamako uttari kāraṇaṃ kāreti:**When the wild elephant goes forward and back when the trainer says, following instructions, the trainer sets it a further task:*";
P_HTM[3873]="*‘uṭṭhaha, bho, nisīda, bho’ti.**‘Stand, sir! Sit, sir!’*";
P_HTM[3874]="*Yato kho, aggivessana, āraññako nāgo hatthidamakassa uṭṭhānanisajjāya vacanakaro hoti ovādappaṭikaro, tamenaṃ hatthidamako uttari āneñjaṃ nāma kāraṇaṃ kāreti, mahantassa phalakaṃ soṇḍāya upanibandhati, tomarahattho ca puriso uparigīvāya nisinno hoti, samantato ca tomarahatthā purisā parivāretvā ṭhitā honti, hatthidamako ca dīghatomarayaṭṭhiṃ gahetvā purato ṭhito hoti.**When the wild elephant stands and sits when the trainer says, following instructions, the trainer sets the task called imperturbability. He fastens a large plank to its trunk; a lancer sits on its neck; other lancers surround it on all sides; and the trainer himself stands in front with a long lance.*";
P_HTM[3875]="*So āneñjaṃ kāraṇaṃ kāriyamāno neva purime pāde copeti na pacchime pāde copeti, na purimakāyaṃ copeti na pacchimakāyaṃ copeti, na sīsaṃ copeti, na kaṇṇe copeti, na dante copeti, na naṅguṭṭhaṃ copeti, na soṇḍaṃ copeti.**While practicing this task, it doesn’t budge its fore-feet or hind-feet, its fore-quarters or hind-quarters, its head, ears, tusks, tail, or trunk.*";
P_HTM[3876]="*So hoti āraññako nāgo khamo sattippahārānaṃ asippahārānaṃ usuppahārānaṃ sarapattappahārānaṃ bheripaṇavavaṃsasaṅkhaḍiṇḍimaninnādasaddānaṃ sabbavaṅkadosanihitaninnītakasāvo rājāraho rājabhoggo rañño aṅganteva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**The wild bull elephant endures being struck by spears, swords, arrows, and axes; it endures the thunder of the drums, kettledrums, horns, and cymbals. Rid of all crooks and flaws, and purged of defects, it is worthy of a king, fit to serve a king, and considered a factor of kingship.*";
P_HTM[3877]="*Evameva kho, aggivessana, idha tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā.**In the same way, Aggivessana, a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.*";
P_HTM[3878]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti.**He realizes with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and he makes it known to others.*";
P_HTM[3879]="*So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ, kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti.**He teaches Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he reveals a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[3880]="*Taṃ dhammaṃ suṇāti gahapati vā gahapatiputto vā aññatarasmiṃ vā kule paccājāto.**A householder hears that teaching, or a householder’s child, or someone reborn in some clan.*";
P_HTM[3881]="*So taṃ dhammaṃ sutvā tathāgate saddhaṃ paṭilabhati.**They gain faith in the Realized One,*";
P_HTM[3882]="*So tena saddhāpaṭilābhena samannāgato iti paṭisañcikkhati:**and reflect,*";
P_HTM[3883]="*‘sambādho gharāvāso rajāpatho, abbhokāso pabbajjā.**‘Living in a house is cramped and dirty, but the life of one gone forth is wide open.*";
P_HTM[3884]="*Nayidaṃ sukaraṃ agāraṃ ajjhāvasatā ekantaparipuṇṇaṃ ekantaparisuddhaṃ saṅkhalikhitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ carituṃ.**It’s not easy for someone living at home to lead the spiritual life utterly full and pure, like a polished shell.*";
P_HTM[3885]="*Yannūnāhaṃ kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajeyyan’ti.**Why don’t I shave off my hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness?’*";
P_HTM[3886]="*So aparena samayena appaṃ vā bhogakkhandhaṃ pahāya mahantaṃ vā bhogakkhandhaṃ pahāya appaṃ vā ñātiparivaṭṭaṃ pahāya mahantaṃ vā ñātiparivaṭṭaṃ pahāya kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati.**After some time they give up a large or small fortune, and a large or small family circle. They shave off hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[3887]="*Ettāvatā kho, aggivessana, ariyasāvako abbhokāsagato hoti.**And it’s only then that a noble disciple comes out into the open,*";
P_HTM[3888]="*Etthagedhā hi, aggivessana, devamanussā yadidaṃ—pañca kāmaguṇā.**for gods and humans cling to the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[3889]="*Tamenaṃ tathāgato uttariṃ vineti:**Then the Realized One guides them further:*";
P_HTM[3890]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, sīlavā hohi, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharāhi ācāragocarasampanno, aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhassu sikkhāpadesū’ti.**‘Come, mendicant, be ethical and restrained in the monastic code, conducting yourself well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, keep the rules you’ve undertaken.’*";
P_HTM[3891]="*Yato kho, aggivessana, ariyasāvako sīlavā hoti, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu, tamenaṃ tathāgato uttariṃ vineti:**When they have ethical conduct, the Realized One guides them further:*";
P_HTM[3892]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, indriyesu guttadvāro hohi, cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā mā nimittaggāhī … pe …**‘Come, mendicant, guard your sense doors. When you see a sight with your eyes, don’t get caught up in the features and details. …*";
P_HTM[3893]="*(yathā gaṇakamoggallānasuttante, evaṃ vitthāretabbāni.)**(This should be expanded as in MN 107, the Discourse with Moggallāna the Accountant.)*";
P_HTM[3894]="*So ime pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe**They give up these five hindrances, corruptions of the heart that weaken wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3895]="*kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**Then they meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3896]="*Vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3897]="*citte …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3898]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3899]="*Seyyathāpi, aggivessana, hatthidamako mahantaṃ thambhaṃ pathaviyaṃ nikhaṇitvā āraññakassa nāgassa gīvāyaṃ upanibandhati āraññakānañceva sīlānaṃ abhinimmadanāya āraññakānañceva sarasaṅkappānaṃ abhinimmadanāya āraññakānañceva darathakilamathapariḷāhānaṃ abhinimmadanāya gāmante abhiramāpanāya manussakantesu sīlesu samādapanāya;**It’s like when the elephant trainer dug a large post into the earth and tethered the elephant to it by the neck, so as to subdue its wild behaviors, its wild memories and thoughts, and its wild stress, weariness, and fever, and to make it happy to be in the neighborhood of a village, and instill behaviors congenial to humans.*";
P_HTM[3900]="*evameva kho, aggivessana, ariyasāvakassa ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā cetaso upanibandhanā honti gehasitānañceva sīlānaṃ abhinimmadanāya gehasitānañceva sarasaṅkappānaṃ abhinimmadanāya gehasitānañceva darathakilamathapariḷāhānaṃ abhinimmadanāya ñāyassa adhigamāya nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya.**In the same way, a noble disciple has these four kinds of mindfulness meditation as tethers for the mind so as to subdue behaviors of the lay life, memories and thoughts of the lay life, the stress, weariness, and fever of the lay life, to end the cycle of suffering and to realize extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3901]="*Tamenaṃ tathāgato uttariṃ vineti:**Then the Realized One guides them further:*";
P_HTM[3902]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, kāye kāyānupassī viharāhi, mā ca kāmūpasaṃhitaṃ vitakkaṃ vitakkesi.**‘Come, mendicant, meditate observing an aspect of the body, but don’t think thoughts connected with sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[3903]="*Vedanāsu …**Meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3904]="*citte …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3905]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharāhi, mā ca kāmūpasaṃhitaṃ vitakkaṃ vitakkesī’ti.**principles, but don’t think thoughts connected with sensual pleasures.’*";
P_HTM[3906]="*So vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[3907]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[3908]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[3909]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte pubbenivāsānussatiñāṇāya cittaṃ abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it toward recollection of past lives.*";
P_HTM[3910]="*So anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo … pe … iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**They recollect many kinds of past lives. That is: one, two, three, four, five, ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand rebirths; many eons of the world contracting, many eons of the world expanding, many eons of the world contracting and expanding. And so they recollect their many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[3911]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte sattānaṃ cutūpapātañāṇāya cittaṃ abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it toward knowledge of the death and rebirth of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[3912]="*So dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe, sugate duggate … pe … yathākammūpage satte pajānāti.**With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds.*";
P_HTM[3913]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte āsavānaṃ khayañāṇāya cittaṃ abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it toward knowledge of the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[3914]="*So ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**They truly understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[3915]="*‘ime āsavā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ āsavasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ āsavanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ āsavanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand: ‘These are defilements’ … ‘This is the origin of defilements’ … ‘This is the cessation of defilements’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of defilements’.*";
P_HTM[3916]="*Tassa evaṃ jānato evaṃ passato kāmāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, bhavāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, avijjāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati.**Knowing and seeing like this, their mind is freed from the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[3917]="*Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[3918]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[3919]="*So hoti bhikkhu khamo sītassa uṇhassa jighacchāya pipāsāya ḍaṃsamakasavātātapasarīsapasamphassānaṃ duruttānaṃ durāgatānaṃ vacanapathānaṃ, uppannānaṃ sārīrikānaṃ vedanānaṃ dukkhānaṃ tibbānaṃ kharānaṃ kaṭukānaṃ asātānaṃ amanāpānaṃ pāṇaharānaṃ adhivāsakajātiko hoti**Such a mendicant endures cold, heat, hunger, and thirst; the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, sun, and reptiles; rude and unwelcome criticism; and puts up with physical pain—sharp, severe, acute, unpleasant, disagreeable, and life-threatening.*";
P_HTM[3920]="*sabbarāgadosamohanihitaninnītakasāvo āhuneyyo pāhuneyyo dakkhiṇeyyo añjalikaraṇīyo anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassa.**Rid of all greed, hate, and delusion, and purged of defects, they are worthy of offerings dedicated to the gods, worthy of hospitality, worthy of a religious donation, worthy of greeting with joined palms, and are the supreme field of merit for the world.*";
P_HTM[3921]="*Mahallako cepi, aggivessana, rañño nāgo adanto avinīto kālaṃ karoti, ‘adantamaraṇaṃ mahallako rañño nāgo kālaṅkato’tveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati;**If a royal bull elephant passes away untamed and untrained—whether in their old age, middle age, or youth—they’re considered a royal bull elephant who passed away untamed.*";
P_HTM[3922]="*majjhimo cepi, aggivessana, rañño nāgo.* **";
P_HTM[3923]="*Daharo cepi, aggivessana, rañño nāgo adanto avinīto kālaṃ karoti, ‘adantamaraṇaṃ daharo rañño nāgo kālaṅkato’tveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati;* **";
P_HTM[3924]="*evameva kho, aggivessana, thero cepi bhikkhu akhīṇāsavo kālaṃ karoti, ‘adantamaraṇaṃ thero bhikkhu kālaṅkato’tveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati;**In the same way, if a mendicant passes away without having ended the defilements—whether as a senior, middle, or junior—they’re considered as a mendicant who passed away untamed.*";
P_HTM[3925]="*majjhimo cepi, aggivessana, bhikkhu.* **";
P_HTM[3926]="*Navo cepi, aggivessana, bhikkhu akhīṇāsavo kālaṃ karoti, ‘adantamaraṇaṃ navo bhikkhu kālaṅkato’tveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.* **";
P_HTM[3927]="*Mahallako cepi, aggivessana, rañño nāgo sudanto suvinīto kālaṃ karoti, ‘dantamaraṇaṃ mahallako rañño nāgo kālaṅkato’tveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati;**If a royal bull elephant passes away tamed and trained—whether in their old age, middle age, or youth—they’re considered a royal bull elephant who passed away tamed.*";
P_HTM[3928]="*majjhimo cepi, aggivessana, rañño nāgo …* **";
P_HTM[3929]="*daharo cepi, aggivessana, rañño nāgo sudanto suvinīto kālaṃ karoti, ‘dantamaraṇaṃ daharo rañño nāgo kālaṅkato’tveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati;* **";
P_HTM[3930]="*evameva kho, aggivessana, thero cepi bhikkhu khīṇāsavo kālaṃ karoti, ‘dantamaraṇaṃ thero bhikkhu kālaṅkato’tveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati;**In the same way, if a mendicant passes away having ended the defilements—whether as a senior, middle, or junior—they’re considered as a mendicant who passed away tamed.”*";
P_HTM[3931]="*majjhimo cepi, aggivessana, bhikkhu.* **";
P_HTM[3932]="*Navo cepi, aggivessana, bhikkhu khīṇāsavo kālaṃ karoti, ‘dantamaraṇaṃ navo bhikkhu kālaṅkato’tveva saṅkhaṃ gacchatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3933]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3934]="*Attamano aciravato samaṇuddeso bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, the novice Aciravata was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3935]="*Dantabhūmisuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3936]="*126. Bhūmijasutta**With Bhūmija*";
P_HTM[3937]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3938]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[3939]="*Atha kho āyasmā bhūmijo pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena jayasenassa rājakumārassa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then Venerable Bhūmija robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the home of Prince Jayasena, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[3940]="*Atha kho jayaseno rājakumāro yenāyasmā bhūmijo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā bhūmijena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then Jayasena approached and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[3941]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho jayaseno rājakumāro āyasmantaṃ bhūmijaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Bhūmija:*";
P_HTM[3942]="*“santi, bho bhūmija, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**“Master Bhūmija, there are some ascetics and brahmins who have this doctrine and view:*";
P_HTM[3943]="*‘āsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**‘If you make a wish and lead the spiritual life, you can’t win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[3944]="*anāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**If you don’t make a wish and lead the spiritual life, you can’t win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[3945]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**If you both make a wish and don’t make a wish and lead the spiritual life, you can’t win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[3946]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāyā’ti.**If you neither make a wish nor don’t make a wish and lead the spiritual life, you can’t win the fruit.’*";
P_HTM[3947]="*Idha bhoto bhūmijassa satthā kiṃvādī kimakkhāyī”ti?**What does Master Bhūmija’s Teacher say about this? How does he explain it?”*";
P_HTM[3948]="*“Na kho metaṃ, rājakumāra, bhagavato sammukhā sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ.**“Prince, I haven’t heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3949]="*Ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ bhagavā evaṃ byākareyya:**But it’s possible that he might explain it like this:*";
P_HTM[3950]="*‘āsañcepi karitvā ayoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**‘If you lead the spiritual life irrationally, you can’t win the fruit, regardless of whether you make a wish,*";
P_HTM[3951]="*anāsañcepi karitvā ayoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**you don’t make a wish,*";
P_HTM[3952]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā ayoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**you both do and do not make a wish,*";
P_HTM[3953]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā ayoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya.**or you neither do nor don’t make a wish.*";
P_HTM[3954]="*Āsañcepi karitvā yoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**But if you lead the spiritual life rationally, you can win the fruit, regardless of whether you make a wish,*";
P_HTM[3955]="*anāsañcepi karitvā yoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**you don’t make a wish,*";
P_HTM[3956]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā yoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**you both do and do not make a wish,*";
P_HTM[3957]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā yoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāyā’ti.**or you neither do nor don’t make a wish.’*";
P_HTM[3958]="*Na kho me taṃ, rājakumāra, bhagavato sammukhā sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ.**I haven’t heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3959]="*Ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ bhagavā evaṃ byākareyyā”ti.**But it’s possible that he might explain it like that.”*";
P_HTM[3960]="*“Sace kho bhoto bhūmijassa satthā evaṃvādī evamakkhāyī, addhā bhoto bhūmijassa satthā sabbesaṃyeva puthusamaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ muddhānaṃ maññe āhacca tiṭṭhatī”ti.**“If that’s what your teacher says, Master Bhūmija, he clearly stands head and shoulders above all the various other ascetics and brahmins.”*";
P_HTM[3961]="*Atha kho jayaseno rājakumāro āyasmantaṃ bhūmijaṃ sakeneva thālipākena parivisi.**Then Prince Jayasena served Venerable Bhūmija from his own dish.*";
P_HTM[3962]="*Atha kho āyasmā bhūmijo pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā bhūmijo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then after the meal, on his return from alms-round, Bhūmija went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him all that had happened, adding:*";
P_HTM[3963]="*“idhāhaṃ, bhante, pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena jayasenassa rājakumārassa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃ; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3964]="*Atha kho, bhante, jayaseno rājakumāro yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā mayā saddhiṃ sammodi.* **";
P_HTM[3965]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho, bhante, jayaseno rājakumāro maṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3966]="*‘santi, bho bhūmija, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino—* **";
P_HTM[3967]="*āsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[3968]="*anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3969]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[3970]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3971]="*‘Idha bhoto bhūmijassa satthā kiṃvādī kimakkhāyī’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3972]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, bhante, jayasenaṃ rājakumāraṃ etadavocaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3973]="*‘na kho me taṃ, rājakumāra, bhagavato sammukhā sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3974]="*Ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ bhagavā evaṃ byākareyya—* **";
P_HTM[3975]="*āsañcepi karitvā ayoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[3976]="*anāsañcepi karitvā ayoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[3977]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā ayoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[3978]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā ayoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya.* **";
P_HTM[3979]="*Āsañcepi karitvā yoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[3980]="*anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3981]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3982]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā yoniso brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāyāti.* **";
P_HTM[3983]="*Na kho me taṃ, rājakumāra, bhagavato sammukhā sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3984]="*Ṭhānañca kho etaṃ vijjati yaṃ bhagavā evaṃ byākareyyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3985]="*‘Sace bhoto bhūmijassa satthā evaṃvādī evamakkhāyī, addhā bhoto bhūmijassa satthā sabbesaṃyeva puthusamaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ muddhānaṃ maññe āhacca tiṭṭhatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3986]="*‘Kaccāhaṃ, bhante, evaṃ puṭṭho evaṃ byākaramāno vuttavādī ceva bhagavato homi, na ca bhagavantaṃ abhūtena abbhācikkhāmi, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākaromi, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchatī’”ti?**“Answering this way, I trust that I repeated what the Buddha has said, and didn’t misrepresent him with an untruth. I trust my explanation was in line with the teaching, and that there are no legitimate grounds for rebuke or criticism.”*";
P_HTM[3987]="*“Taggha tvaṃ, bhūmija, evaṃ puṭṭho evaṃ byākaramāno vuttavādī ceva me hosi, na ca maṃ abhūtena abbhācikkhasi, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākarosi, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchati.**“Indeed, Bhūmija, in answering this way you repeated what I’ve said, and didn’t misrepresent me with an untruth. Your explanation was in line with the teaching, and there are no legitimate grounds for rebuke or criticism.*";
P_HTM[3988]="*Ye hi keci, bhūmija, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā micchādiṭṭhino micchāsaṅkappā micchāvācā micchākammantā micchāājīvā micchāvāyāmā micchāsatī micchāsamādhino te āsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**There are some ascetics and brahmins who have wrong view, wrong thought, wrong speech, wrong action, wrong livelihood, wrong effort, wrong mindfulness, and wrong immersion. If they lead the spiritual life, they can’t win the fruit, regardless of whether they make a wish,*";
P_HTM[3989]="*anāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**they don’t make a wish,*";
P_HTM[3990]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**they both do and do not make a wish,*";
P_HTM[3991]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya.**or they neither do nor don’t make a wish.*";
P_HTM[3992]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3993]="*Ayoni hesā, bhūmija, phalassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s an irrational way to win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[3994]="*Seyyathāpi, bhūmija, puriso telatthiko telagavesī telapariyesanaṃ caramāno vālikaṃ doṇiyā ākiritvā udakena paripphosakaṃ paripphosakaṃ pīḷeyya.**Suppose there was a person in need of oil. While wandering in search of oil, they tried heaping sand in a bucket, sprinkling it thoroughly with water, and pressing it out.*";
P_HTM[3995]="*Āsañcepi karitvā vālikaṃ doṇiyā ākiritvā udakena paripphosakaṃ paripphosakaṃ pīḷeyya, abhabbo telassa adhigamāya;**But by doing this, they couldn’t extract any oil, regardless of whether they made a wish,*";
P_HTM[3996]="*anāsañcepi karitvā vālikaṃ doṇiyā ākiritvā udakena paripphosakaṃ paripphosakaṃ pīḷeyya, abhabbo telassa adhigamāya;**didn’t make a wish,*";
P_HTM[3997]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā vālikaṃ doṇiyā ākiritvā udakena paripphosakaṃ paripphosakaṃ pīḷeyya, abhabbo telassa adhigamāya;**both did and did not make a wish,*";
P_HTM[3998]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā vālikaṃ doṇiyā ākiritvā udakena paripphosakaṃ paripphosakaṃ pīḷeyya, abhabbo telassa adhigamāya.**or neither did nor did not make a wish.*";
P_HTM[3999]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[4000]="*Ayoni hesā, bhūmija, telassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s an irrational way to extract oil.*";
P_HTM[4001]="*Evameva kho, bhūmija, ye hi keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā micchādiṭṭhino micchāsaṅkappā micchāvācā micchākammantā micchāājīvā micchāvāyāmā micchāsatī micchāsamādhino te āsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**And so it is for any ascetics and brahmins who have wrong view, wrong thought, wrong speech, wrong action, wrong livelihood, wrong effort, wrong mindfulness, and wrong immersion. If they lead the spiritual life, they can’t win the fruit, regardless of whether or not they make a wish.*";
P_HTM[4002]="*anāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[4003]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[4004]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya.* **";
P_HTM[4005]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[4006]="*Ayoni hesā, bhūmija, phalassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s an irrational way to win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[4007]="*Seyyathāpi, bhūmija, puriso khīratthiko khīragavesī khīrapariyesanaṃ caramāno gāviṃ taruṇavacchaṃ visāṇato āviñcheyya.**Suppose there was a person in need of milk. While wandering in search of milk, they tried pulling the horn of a newly-calved cow.*";
P_HTM[4008]="*Āsañcepi karitvā gāviṃ taruṇavacchaṃ visāṇato āviñcheyya, abhabbo khīrassa adhigamāya;**But by doing this, they couldn’t get any milk, regardless of whether they made a wish,*";
P_HTM[4009]="*anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …**didn’t make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4010]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …**both did and did not make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4011]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā gāviṃ taruṇavacchaṃ visāṇato āviñcheyya, abhabbo khīrassa adhigamāya.**or neither did nor did not make a wish.*";
P_HTM[4012]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[4013]="*Ayoni hesā, bhūmija, khīrassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s an irrational way to get milk.*";
P_HTM[4014]="*Evameva kho, bhūmija, ye hi keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā micchādiṭṭhino … pe …**And so it is for any ascetics and brahmins who have wrong view …*";
P_HTM[4015]="*micchāsamādhino te āsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[4016]="*anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[4017]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[4018]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya.* **";
P_HTM[4019]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[4020]="*Ayoni hesā, bhūmija, phalassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s an irrational way to win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[4021]="*Seyyathāpi, bhūmija, puriso navanītatthiko navanītagavesī navanītapariyesanaṃ caramāno udakaṃ kalase āsiñcitvā matthena āviñcheyya.**Suppose there was a person in need of butter. While wandering in search of butter, they tried pouring water into a pot and churning it with a stick.*";
P_HTM[4022]="*Āsañcepi karitvā udakaṃ kalase āsiñcitvā matthena āviñcheyya, abhabbo navanītassa adhigamāya;**But by doing this, they couldn’t produce any butter, regardless of whether they made a wish,*";
P_HTM[4023]="*anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …**didn’t make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4024]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …**both did and did not make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4025]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā udakaṃ kalase āsiñcitvā matthena āviñcheyya, abhabbo navanītassa adhigamāya.**or neither did nor did not make a wish.*";
P_HTM[4026]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[4027]="*Ayoni hesā, bhūmija, navanītassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s an irrational way to produce butter.*";
P_HTM[4028]="*Evameva kho, bhūmija, ye hi keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā micchādiṭṭhino … pe …**And so it is for any ascetics and brahmins who have wrong view …*";
P_HTM[4029]="*micchāsamādhino te āsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[4030]="*anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[4031]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[4032]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya.* **";
P_HTM[4033]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[4034]="*Ayoni hesā, bhūmija, phalassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s an irrational way to win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[4035]="*Seyyathāpi, bhūmija, puriso aggitthiko aggigavesī aggipariyesanaṃ caramāno allaṃ kaṭṭhaṃ sasnehaṃ uttarāraṇiṃ ādāya abhimantheyya.**Suppose there was a person in need of fire. While wandering in search of fire, they tried drilling a green, sappy log with a drill-stick.*";
P_HTM[4036]="*Āsañcepi karitvā allaṃ kaṭṭhaṃ sasnehaṃ uttarāraṇiṃ ādāya abhimantheyya, abhabbo aggissa adhigamāya;**But by doing this, they couldn’t start a fire, regardless of whether they made a wish,*";
P_HTM[4037]="*anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …**didn’t make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4038]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …**both did and did not make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4039]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā allaṃ kaṭṭhaṃ sasnehaṃ uttarāraṇiṃ ādāya abhimantheyya, abhabbo aggissa adhigamāya.**or neither did nor did not make a wish.*";
P_HTM[4040]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[4041]="*Ayoni hesā, bhūmija, aggissa adhigamāya.**Because that’s an irrational way to start a fire.*";
P_HTM[4042]="*Evameva kho, bhūmija, ye hi keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā micchādiṭṭhino … pe …**And so it is for any ascetics and brahmins who have wrong view …*";
P_HTM[4043]="*micchāsamādhino te āsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[4044]="*anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[4045]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[4046]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, abhabbā phalassa adhigamāya.* **";
P_HTM[4047]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[4048]="*Ayoni hesā, bhūmija, phalassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s an irrational way to win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[4049]="*Ye hi keci, bhūmija, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā sammādiṭṭhino sammāsaṅkappā sammāvācā sammākammantā sammāājīvā sammāvāyāmā sammāsatī sammāsamādhino te āsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**There are some ascetics and brahmins who have right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion. If they lead the spiritual life, they can win the fruit, regardless of whether they make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4050]="*anāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**they don’t make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4051]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;**they both do and do not make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4052]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya.**or they neither do nor do not make a wish.*";
P_HTM[4053]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[4054]="*Yoni hesā, bhūmija, phalassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s a rational way to win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[4055]="*Seyyathāpi, bhūmija, puriso telatthiko telagavesī telapariyesanaṃ caramāno tilapiṭṭhaṃ doṇiyā ākiritvā udakena paripphosakaṃ paripphosakaṃ pīḷeyya.**Suppose there was a person in need of oil. While wandering in search of oil, they tried heaping sesame flour in a bucket, sprinkling it thoroughly with water, and pressing it out.*";
P_HTM[4056]="*Āsañcepi karitvā tilapiṭṭhaṃ doṇiyā ākiritvā udakena paripphosakaṃ paripphosakaṃ pīḷeyya, bhabbo telassa adhigamāya;**By doing this, they could extract oil, regardless of whether they made a wish,*";
P_HTM[4057]="*anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …**didn’t make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4058]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …**both did and did not make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4059]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā tilapiṭṭhaṃ doṇiyā ākiritvā udakena paripphosakaṃ paripphosakaṃ pīḷeyya, bhabbo telassa adhigamāya.**or neither did nor did not make a wish.*";
P_HTM[4060]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[4061]="*Yoni hesā, bhūmija, telassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s a rational way to extract oil.*";
P_HTM[4062]="*Evameva kho, bhūmija, ye hi keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā sammādiṭṭhino … pe …**And so it is for any ascetics and brahmins who have right view …*";
P_HTM[4063]="*sammāsamādhino te āsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[4064]="*anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[4065]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[4066]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya.* **";
P_HTM[4067]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[4068]="*Yoni hesā, bhūmija, phalassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s a rational way to win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[4069]="*Seyyathāpi, bhūmija, puriso khīratthiko khīragavesī khīrapariyesanaṃ caramāno gāviṃ taruṇavacchaṃ thanato āviñcheyya.**Suppose there was a person in need of milk. While wandering in search of milk, they tried pulling the udder of a newly-calved cow.*";
P_HTM[4070]="*Āsañcepi karitvā gāviṃ taruṇavacchaṃ thanato āviñcheyya, bhabbo khīrassa adhigamāya;**By doing this, they could get milk, regardless of whether they made a wish,*";
P_HTM[4071]="*anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …**didn’t make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4072]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …**both did and did not make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4073]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā gāviṃ taruṇavacchaṃ thanato āviñcheyya, bhabbo khīrassa adhigamāya.**or neither did nor did not make a wish.*";
P_HTM[4074]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[4075]="*Yoni hesā, bhūmija, khīrassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s a rational way to get milk.*";
P_HTM[4076]="*Evameva kho, bhūmija, ye hi keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā sammādiṭṭhino … pe …**And so it is for any ascetics and brahmins who have right view …*";
P_HTM[4077]="*sammāsamādhino te āsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[4078]="*anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[4079]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[4080]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya.* **";
P_HTM[4081]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[4082]="*Yoni hesā, bhūmija, phalassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s a rational way to win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[4083]="*Seyyathāpi, bhūmija, puriso navanītatthiko navanītagavesī navanītapariyesanaṃ caramāno dadhiṃ kalase āsiñcitvā matthena āviñcheyya.**Suppose there was a person in need of butter. While wandering in search of butter, they tried pouring curds into a pot and churning them with a stick.*";
P_HTM[4084]="*Āsañcepi karitvā dadhiṃ kalase āsiñcitvā matthena āviñcheyya, bhabbo navanītassa adhigamāya;**By doing this, they could produce butter, regardless of whether they made a wish,*";
P_HTM[4085]="*anāsañcepi karitvā …**didn’t make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4086]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā …**both did and did not make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4087]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā dadhiṃ kalase āsiñcitvā matthena āviñcheyya, bhabbo navanītassa adhigamāya.**or neither did nor did not make a wish.*";
P_HTM[4088]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[4089]="*Yoni hesā, bhūmija, navanītassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s a rational way to produce butter.*";
P_HTM[4090]="*Evameva kho, bhūmija, ye hi keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā sammādiṭṭhino … pe …**And so it is for any ascetics and brahmins who have right view …*";
P_HTM[4091]="*sammāsamādhino te āsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[4092]="*anāsañcepi karitvā …* **";
P_HTM[4093]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā …* **";
P_HTM[4094]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya.* **";
P_HTM[4095]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[4096]="*Yoni hesā, bhūmija, phalassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s a rational way to win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[4097]="*Seyyathāpi, bhūmija, puriso aggitthiko aggigavesī aggipariyesanaṃ caramāno sukkhaṃ kaṭṭhaṃ koḷāpaṃ uttarāraṇiṃ ādāya abhimantheyya;**Suppose there was a person in need of fire. While wandering in search of fire, they tried drilling a dried up, withered log with a drill-stick.*";
P_HTM[4098]="*() āsañcepi karitvā …**By doing this, they could start a fire, regardless of whether they made a wish,*";
P_HTM[4099]="*anāsañcepi karitvā …**didn’t make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4100]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā …**both did and did not make a wish,*";
P_HTM[4101]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā sukkhaṃ kaṭṭhaṃ koḷāpaṃ uttarāraṇiṃ ādāya abhimantheyya, bhabbo aggissa adhigamāya.**or neither did nor did not make a wish.*";
P_HTM[4102]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[4103]="*Yoni hesā, bhūmija, aggissa adhigamāya.**Because that’s a rational way to start a fire.*";
P_HTM[4104]="*Evameva kho, bhūmija, ye hi keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā sammādiṭṭhino … pe …**And so it is for any ascetics and brahmins who have right view …*";
P_HTM[4105]="*sammāsamādhino te āsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[4106]="*anāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[4107]="*āsañca anāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya;* **";
P_HTM[4108]="*nevāsaṃ nānāsañcepi karitvā brahmacariyaṃ caranti, bhabbā phalassa adhigamāya.* **";
P_HTM[4109]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[4110]="*Yoni hesā, bhūmija, phalassa adhigamāya.**Because that’s a rational way to win the fruit.*";
P_HTM[4111]="*Sace kho taṃ, bhūmija, jayasenassa rājakumārassa imā catasso upamā paṭibhāyeyyuṃ anacchariyaṃ te jayaseno rājakumāro pasīdeyya, pasanno ca te pasannākāraṃ kareyyā”ti.**Bhūmija, it wouldn’t be surprising if, had these four similes occurred to you, Prince Jayasena would have gained confidence in you and shown his confidence.”*";
P_HTM[4112]="*“Kuto pana maṃ, bhante, jayasenassa rājakumārassa imā catasso upamā paṭibhāyissanti anacchariyā pubbe assutapubbā, seyyathāpi bhagavantan”ti?**“But sir, how could these four similes have occurred to me as they did to the Buddha, since they were neither supernaturally inspired, nor learned before in the past?”*";
P_HTM[4113]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[4114]="*Attamano āyasmā bhūmijo bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Bhūmija was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[4115]="*Bhūmijasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4116]="*127. Anuruddhasutta**With Anuruddha*";
P_HTM[4117]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[4118]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[4119]="*Atha kho pañcakaṅgo thapati aññataraṃ purisaṃ āmantesi:**And then the master builder Pañcakaṅga addressed a man,*";
P_HTM[4120]="*“ehi tvaṃ, ambho purisa, yenāyasmā anuruddho tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā mama vacanena āyasmato anuruddhassa pāde sirasā vandāhi:**“Please, mister, go to Venerable Anuruddha, and in my name bow with your head to his feet. Say to him,*";
P_HTM[4121]="*‘pañcakaṅgo, bhante, thapati āyasmato anuruddhassa pāde sirasā vandatī’ti;**‘Sir, the master builder Pañcakaṅga bows with his head to your feet.’*";
P_HTM[4122]="*evañca vadehi:**And then ask him whether he*";
P_HTM[4123]="*‘adhivāsetu kira, bhante, āyasmā anuruddho pañcakaṅgassa thapatissa svātanāya attacatuttho bhattaṃ;**might accept tomorrow’s meal from Pañcakaṅga together with the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[4124]="*yena ca kira, bhante, āyasmā anuruddho pagevataraṃ āgaccheyya;**And ask whether he might please come earlier than usual,*";
P_HTM[4125]="*pañcakaṅgo, bhante, thapati bahukicco bahukaraṇīyo rājakaraṇīyenā’”ti.**for Pañcakaṅga has many duties, and much work to do for the king.”*";
P_HTM[4126]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho so puriso pañcakaṅgassa thapatissa paṭissutvā yenāyasmā anuruddho tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so puriso āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” that man replied. He did as Pañcakaṅga asked, and*";
P_HTM[4127]="*“pañcakaṅgo, bhante, thapati āyasmato anuruddhassa pāde sirasā vandati, evañca vadeti:* **";
P_HTM[4128]="*‘adhivāsetu kira, bhante, āyasmā anuruddho pañcakaṅgassa thapatissa svātanāya attacatuttho bhattaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[4129]="*yena ca kira, bhante, āyasmā anuruddho pagevataraṃ āgaccheyya;* **";
P_HTM[4130]="*pañcakaṅgo, bhante, thapati bahukicco bahukaraṇīyo rājakaraṇīyenā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[4131]="*Adhivāsesi kho āyasmā anuruddho tuṇhībhāvena.**Venerable Anuruddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[4132]="*Atha kho āyasmā anuruddho tassā rattiyā accayena pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena pañcakaṅgassa thapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then when the night had passed, Anuruddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to Pañcakaṅga’s home, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[4133]="*Atha kho pañcakaṅgo thapati āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ paṇītena khādanīyena bhojanīyena sahatthā santappesi sampavāresi.**Then Pañcakaṅga served and satisfied Anuruddha with his own hands with a variety of delicious foods.*";
P_HTM[4134]="*Atha kho pañcakaṅgo thapati āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ bhuttāviṃ onītapattapāṇiṃ aññataraṃ nīcaṃ āsanaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**When Anuruddha had eaten and washed his hands and bowl, Pañcakaṅga took a low seat, sat to one side,*";
P_HTM[4135]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho pañcakaṅgo thapati āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him:*";
P_HTM[4136]="*“Idha maṃ, bhante, therā bhikkhū upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:**“Sir, some senior mendicants have come to me and said,*";
P_HTM[4137]="*‘appamāṇaṃ, gahapati, cetovimuttiṃ bhāvehī’ti.**‘Householder, develop the limitless release of heart.’*";
P_HTM[4138]="*Ekacce therā evamāhaṃsu:**Others have said,*";
P_HTM[4139]="*‘mahaggataṃ, gahapati, cetovimuttiṃ bhāvehī’ti.**‘Householder, develop the expansive release of heart.’*";
P_HTM[4140]="*Yā cāyaṃ, bhante, appamāṇā cetovimutti yā ca mahaggatā cetovimutti—**Now, the limitless release of the heart and the expansive release of the heart:*";
P_HTM[4141]="*ime dhammā nānatthā ceva nānābyañjanā ca, udāhu ekatthā byañjanameva nānan”ti?**do these things differ in both meaning and phrasing? Or do they mean the same thing, and differ only in the phrasing?”*";
P_HTM[4142]="*“Tena hi, gahapati, taṃyevettha paṭibhātu, apaṇṇakante ito bhavissatī”ti.**“Well then, householder, let me know what you think about this. Afterwards you’ll get it for sure.”*";
P_HTM[4143]="*“Mayhaṃ kho, bhante, evaṃ hoti:**“Sir, this is what I think.*";
P_HTM[4144]="*‘yā cāyaṃ appamāṇā cetovimutti yā ca mahaggatā cetovimutti ime dhammā ekatthā byañjanameva nānan’”ti.**The limitless release of the heart and the expansive release of the heart mean the same thing, and differ only in the phrasing.”*";
P_HTM[4145]="*“Yā cāyaṃ, gahapati, appamāṇā cetovimutti yā ca mahaggatā cetovimutti ime dhammā nānatthā ceva nānābyañjanā ca.**“The limitless release of the heart and the expansive release of the heart differ in both meaning and phrasing.*";
P_HTM[4146]="*Tadamināpetaṃ, gahapati, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ yathā ime dhammā nānatthā ceva nānābyañjanā ca.**This is a way to understand how these things differ in both meaning and phrasing.*";
P_HTM[4147]="*Katamā ca, gahapati, appamāṇā cetovimutti?**And what is the limitless release of the heart?*";
P_HTM[4148]="*Idha, gahapati, bhikkhu mettāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati, tathā dutiyaṃ tathā tatiyaṃ tathā catutthaṃ; iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ mettāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyābajjhena pharitvā viharati.**It’s when a mendicant meditates spreading a heart full of love to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of love to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[4149]="*Karuṇāsahagatena cetasā …**They meditate spreading a heart full of compassion …*";
P_HTM[4150]="*muditāsahagatena cetasā …**They meditate spreading a heart full of rejoicing …*";
P_HTM[4151]="*upekkhāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati, tathā dutiyaṃ tathā tatiyaṃ tathā catutthaṃ; iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ upekkhāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyābajjhena pharitvā viharati.**They meditate spreading a heart full of equanimity to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of equanimity to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[4152]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, gahapati, appamāṇā cetovimutti.**This is called the limitless release of the heart.*";
P_HTM[4153]="*Katamā ca, gahapati, mahaggatā cetovimutti?**And what is the expansive release of the heart?*";
P_HTM[4154]="*Idha, gahapati, bhikkhu yāvatā ekaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ mahaggatanti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**It’s when a mendicant meditates determined on pervading the extent of a single tree root as expansive.*";
P_HTM[4155]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, gahapati, mahaggatā cetovimutti.**This is called the expansive release of the heart.*";
P_HTM[4156]="*Idha pana, gahapati, bhikkhu yāvatā dve vā tīṇi vā rukkhamūlāni mahaggatanti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**Also, a mendicant meditates determined on pervading the extent of two or three tree roots …*";
P_HTM[4157]="*Ayampi vuccati, gahapati, mahaggatā cetovimutti.* **";
P_HTM[4158]="*Idha pana, gahapati, bhikkhu yāvatā ekaṃ gāmakkhettaṃ mahaggatanti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**a single village district …*";
P_HTM[4159]="*Ayampi vuccati, gahapati, mahaggatā cetovimutti.* **";
P_HTM[4160]="*Idha pana, gahapati, bhikkhu yāvatā dve vā tīṇi vā gāmakkhettāni mahaggatanti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**two or three village districts …*";
P_HTM[4161]="*Ayampi vuccati, gahapati, mahaggatā cetovimutti.* **";
P_HTM[4162]="*Idha pana, gahapati, bhikkhu yāvatā ekaṃ mahārajjaṃ mahaggatanti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**a single kingdom …*";
P_HTM[4163]="*Ayampi vuccati, gahapati, mahaggatā cetovimutti.* **";
P_HTM[4164]="*Idha pana, gahapati, bhikkhu yāvatā dve vā tīṇi vā mahārajjāni mahaggatanti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**two or three kingdoms …*";
P_HTM[4165]="*Ayampi vuccati, gahapati, mahaggatā cetovimutti.* **";
P_HTM[4166]="*Idha pana, gahapati, bhikkhu yāvatā samuddapariyantaṃ pathaviṃ mahaggatanti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**this land surrounded by ocean.*";
P_HTM[4167]="*Ayampi vuccati, gahapati, mahaggatā cetovimutti.**This too is called the expansive release of the heart.*";
P_HTM[4168]="*Iminā kho etaṃ, gahapati, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ yathā ime dhammā nānatthā ceva nānābyañjanā ca.**This is a way to understand how these things differ in both meaning and phrasing.*";
P_HTM[4169]="*Catasso kho imā gahapati, bhavūpapattiyo.**Householder, there are these four kinds of rebirth in a future life.*";
P_HTM[4170]="*Katamā catasso?**What four?*";
P_HTM[4171]="*Idha, gahapati, ekacco ‘parittābhā’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**Take someone who meditates determined on pervading ‘limited radiance’.*";
P_HTM[4172]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parittābhānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in the company of the gods of limited radiance.*";
P_HTM[4173]="*Idha pana, gahapati, ekacco ‘appamāṇābhā’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**Next, take someone who meditates determined on pervading ‘limitless radiance’.*";
P_HTM[4174]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā appamāṇābhānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in the company of the gods of limitless radiance.*";
P_HTM[4175]="*Idha pana, gahapati, ekacco ‘saṅkiliṭṭhābhā’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**Next, take someone who meditates determined on pervading ‘corrupted radiance’.*";
P_HTM[4176]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā saṅkiliṭṭhābhānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in the company of the gods of corrupted radiance.*";
P_HTM[4177]="*Idha pana, gahapati, ekacco ‘parisuddhābhā’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**Next, take someone who meditates determined on pervading ‘pure radiance’.*";
P_HTM[4178]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parisuddhābhānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in the company of the gods of pure radiance.*";
P_HTM[4179]="*Imā kho, gahapati, catasso bhavūpapattiyo.**These are the four kinds of rebirth in a future life.*";
P_HTM[4180]="*Hoti kho so, gahapati, samayo, yā tā devatā ekajjhaṃ sannipatanti, tāsaṃ ekajjhaṃ sannipatitānaṃ vaṇṇanānattañhi kho paññāyati no ca ābhānānattaṃ.**There comes a time, householder, when the deities gather together as one. When they do so, a difference in their color is evident, but not in their radiance.*";
P_HTM[4181]="*Seyyathāpi, gahapati, puriso sambahulāni telappadīpāni ekaṃ gharaṃ paveseyya.**It’s like when a person brings several oil lamps into one house.*";
P_HTM[4182]="*Tesaṃ ekaṃ gharaṃ pavesitānaṃ accinānattañhi kho paññāyetha, no ca ābhānānattaṃ;**You can detect a difference in their flames, but not in their radiance.*";
P_HTM[4183]="*evameva kho, gahapati, hoti kho so samayo, yā tā devatā ekajjhaṃ sannipatanti tāsaṃ ekajjhaṃ sannipatitānaṃ vaṇṇanānattañhi kho paññāyati, no ca ābhānānattaṃ.**In the same way, when the deities gather together as one, a difference in their color is evident, but not in their radiance.*";
P_HTM[4184]="*Hoti kho so, gahapati, samayo, yā tā devatā tato vipakkamanti, tāsaṃ tato vipakkamantīnaṃ vaṇṇanānattañceva paññāyati ābhānānattañca.**There comes a time when those deities go their separate ways. When they do so, a difference both in their color and also in their radiance is evident.*";
P_HTM[4185]="*Seyyathāpi, gahapati, puriso tāni sambahulāni telappadīpāni tamhā gharā nīhareyya.**It’s like when a person takes those several oil lamps out of that house.*";
P_HTM[4186]="*Tesaṃ tato nīhatānaṃ accinānattañceva paññāyetha ābhānānattañca;**You can detect a difference both in their flames and also in their radiance.*";
P_HTM[4187]="*evameva kho, gahapati, hoti kho so samayo, yā tā devatā tato vipakkamanti, tāsaṃ tato vipakkamantīnaṃ vaṇṇanānattañceva paññāyati ābhānānattañca.**In the same way, when the deities go their separate ways, a difference both in their color and also in their radiance is evident.*";
P_HTM[4188]="*Na kho, gahapati, tāsaṃ devatānaṃ evaṃ hoti:**It’s not that those deities think,*";
P_HTM[4189]="*‘idaṃ amhākaṃ niccanti vā dhuvanti vā sassatanti vā’, api ca yattha yattheva tā devatā abhinivisanti tattha tattheva tā devatā abhiramanti.**‘What we have is permanent, lasting, and eternal.’ Rather, wherever those deities cling, that’s where they take pleasure.*";
P_HTM[4190]="*Seyyathāpi, gahapati, makkhikānaṃ kājena vā piṭakena vā harīyamānānaṃ na evaṃ hoti:**It’s like when flies are being carried along on a carrying-pole or basket. It’s not that they think,*";
P_HTM[4191]="*‘idaṃ amhākaṃ niccanti vā dhuvanti vā sassatanti vā’, api ca yattha yattheva tā makkhikā abhinivisanti tattha tattheva tā makkhikā abhiramanti;**‘What we have is permanent, lasting, and eternal.’ Rather, wherever those flies cling, that’s where they take pleasure.*";
P_HTM[4192]="*evameva kho, gahapati, tāsaṃ devatānaṃ na evaṃ hoti:**In the same way, it’s not that those deities think,*";
P_HTM[4193]="*‘idaṃ amhākaṃ niccanti vā dhuvanti vā sassatanti vā’, api ca yattha yattheva tā devatā abhinivisanti tattha tattheva tā devatā abhiramantī”ti.**‘What we have is permanent, lasting, and eternal.’ Rather, wherever those deities cling, that’s where they take pleasure.”*";
P_HTM[4194]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā sabhiyo kaccāno āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Venerable Abhiya Kaccāna said to Venerable Anuruddha:*";
P_HTM[4195]="*“sādhu, bhante anuruddha.**“Good, Venerable Anuruddha!*";
P_HTM[4196]="*Atthi ca me ettha uttariṃ paṭipucchitabbaṃ.**I have a further question about this.*";
P_HTM[4197]="*Yā tā, bhante, devatā ābhā sabbā tā parittābhā udāhu santettha ekaccā devatā appamāṇābhā”ti?**Do all the radiant deities have limited radiance, or do some there have limitless radiance?”*";
P_HTM[4198]="*“Tadaṅgena kho, āvuso kaccāna, santettha ekaccā devatā parittābhā, santi panettha ekaccā devatā appamāṇābhā”ti.**“In that respect, Reverend Kaccāna, some deities there have limited radiance, while some have limitless radiance.”*";
P_HTM[4199]="*“Ko nu kho, bhante anuruddha, hetu ko paccayo yena tāsaṃ devatānaṃ ekaṃ devanikāyaṃ upapannānaṃ santettha ekaccā devatā parittābhā, santi panettha ekaccā devatā appamāṇābhā”ti?**“What is the cause, Venerable Anuruddha, what is the reason why, when those deities have been reborn in a single order of gods, some deities there have limited radiance, while some have limitless radiance?”*";
P_HTM[4200]="*“Tena hāvuso kaccāna, taṃyevettha paṭipucchissāmi. Yathā te khameyya tathā naṃ byākareyyāsi.**“Well then, Reverend Kaccāna, I’ll ask you about this in return, and you can answer as you like.*";
P_HTM[4201]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso kaccāna,**What do you think, Reverend Kaccāna?*";
P_HTM[4202]="*yvāyaṃ bhikkhu yāvatā ekaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati, yo cāyaṃ bhikkhu yāvatā dve vā tīṇi vā rukkhamūlāni ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati—**Which of these two kinds of mental development is more expansive: when a mendicant meditates determined on pervading as expansive the extent of a single tree root, or two or three tree roots?”*";
P_HTM[4203]="*imāsaṃ ubhinnaṃ cittabhāvanānaṃ katamā cittabhāvanā mahaggatatarā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[4204]="*“Yvāyaṃ, bhante, bhikkhu yāvatā dve vā tīṇi vā rukkhamūlāni ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati—**“When a mendicant meditates on two or three tree roots.”*";
P_HTM[4205]="*ayaṃ imāsaṃ ubhinnaṃ cittabhāvanānaṃ mahaggatatarā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[4206]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso kaccāna,**“What do you think, Reverend Kaccāna?*";
P_HTM[4207]="*yvāyaṃ bhikkhu yāvatā dve vā tīṇi vā rukkhamūlāni ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati, yo cāyaṃ bhikkhu yāvatā ekaṃ gāmakkhettaṃ ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati—**Which of these two kinds of mental development is more expansive: when a mendicant meditates determined on pervading as expansive the extent of two or three tree roots, or a single village district …*";
P_HTM[4208]="*imāsaṃ ubhinnaṃ cittabhāvanānaṃ katamā cittabhāvanā mahaggatatarā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[4209]="*“Yvāyaṃ, bhante, bhikkhu yāvatā ekaṃ gāmakkhettaṃ ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati—* **";
P_HTM[4210]="*ayaṃ imāsaṃ ubhinnaṃ cittabhāvanānaṃ mahaggatatarā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[4211]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso kaccāna, yvāyaṃ bhikkhu yāvatā ekaṃ gāmakkhettaṃ ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati, yo cāyaṃ bhikkhu yāvatā dve vā tīṇi vā gāmakkhettāni ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati—**two or three village districts …*";
P_HTM[4212]="*imāsaṃ ubhinnaṃ cittabhāvanānaṃ katamā cittabhāvanā mahaggatatarā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[4213]="*“Yvāyaṃ, bhante, bhikkhu yāvatā dve vā tīṇi vā gāmakkhettāni ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati—* **";
P_HTM[4214]="*ayaṃ imāsaṃ ubhinnaṃ cittabhāvanānaṃ mahaggatatarā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[4215]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso kaccāna, yvāyaṃ bhikkhu yāvatā dve vā tīṇi vā gāmakkhettāni ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati, yo cāyaṃ bhikkhu yāvatā ekaṃ mahārajjaṃ ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati—**a single kingdom …*";
P_HTM[4216]="*imāsaṃ ubhinnaṃ cittabhāvanānaṃ katamā cittabhāvanā mahaggatatarā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[4217]="*“Yvāyaṃ, bhante, bhikkhu yāvatā ekaṃ mahārajjaṃ ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati—* **";
P_HTM[4218]="*ayaṃ imāsaṃ ubhinnaṃ cittabhāvanānaṃ mahaggatatarā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[4219]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso kaccāna, yvāyaṃ bhikkhu yāvatā ekaṃ mahārajjaṃ ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati, yo cāyaṃ bhikkhu yāvatā dve vā tīṇi vā mahārajjāni ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati—**two or three kingdoms …*";
P_HTM[4220]="*imāsaṃ ubhinnaṃ cittabhāvanānaṃ katamā cittabhāvanā mahaggatatarā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[4221]="*“Yvāyaṃ, bhante, bhikkhu yāvatā dve vā tīṇi vā mahārajjāni ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati—* **";
P_HTM[4222]="*ayaṃ imāsaṃ ubhinnaṃ cittabhāvanānaṃ mahaggatatarā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[4223]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, āvuso kaccāna, yvāyaṃ bhikkhu yāvatā dve vā tīṇi vā mahārajjāni ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati, yo cāyaṃ bhikkhu yāvatā samuddapariyantaṃ pathaviṃ ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati—**this land surrounded by ocean?”*";
P_HTM[4224]="*imāsaṃ ubhinnaṃ cittabhāvanānaṃ katamā cittabhāvanā mahaggatatarā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[4225]="*“Yvāyaṃ, bhante, bhikkhu yāvatā samuddapariyantaṃ pathaviṃ ‘mahaggatan’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati—**“When a mendicant meditates on this land surrounded by ocean.”*";
P_HTM[4226]="*ayaṃ imāsaṃ ubhinnaṃ cittabhāvanānaṃ mahaggatatarā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[4227]="*“Ayaṃ kho, āvuso kaccāna, hetu ayaṃ paccayo, yena tāsaṃ devatānaṃ ekaṃ devanikāyaṃ upapannānaṃ santettha ekaccā devatā parittābhā, santi panettha ekaccā devatā appamāṇābhā”ti.**“This is the cause, Reverend Kaccāna, this is the reason why, when those deities have been reborn in a single order of gods, some deities there have limited radiance, while some have limitless radiance.”*";
P_HTM[4228]="*“Sādhu, bhante anuruddha.**“Good, Venerable Anuruddha!*";
P_HTM[4229]="*Atthi ca me ettha uttariṃ paṭipucchitabbaṃ.**I have a further question about this.*";
P_HTM[4230]="*Yāvatā, bhante, devatā ābhā sabbā tā saṃkiliṭṭhābhā udāhu santettha ekaccā devatā parisuddhābhā”ti?**Do all the radiant deities have corrupted radiance, or do some there have pure radiance?”*";
P_HTM[4231]="*“Tadaṅgena kho, āvuso kaccāna, santettha ekaccā devatā saṃkiliṭṭhābhā, santi panettha ekaccā devatā parisuddhābhā”ti.**“In that respect, Reverend Kaccāna, some deities there have corrupted radiance, while some have pure radiance.”*";
P_HTM[4232]="*“Ko nu kho, bhante, anuruddha, hetu ko paccayo, yena tāsaṃ devatānaṃ ekaṃ devanikāyaṃ upapannānaṃ santettha ekaccā devatā saṃkiliṭṭhābhā, santi panettha ekaccā devatā parisuddhābhā”ti?**“What is the cause, Venerable Anuruddha, what is the reason why, when those deities have been reborn in a single order of gods, some deities there have corrupted radiance, while some have pure radiance?”*";
P_HTM[4233]="*“Tena hāvuso kaccāna, upamaṃ te karissāmi.**“Well then, Reverend Kaccāna, I shall give you a simile.*";
P_HTM[4234]="*Upamāyapidhekacce viññū purisā bhāsitassa atthaṃ ājānanti.**For by means of a simile some sensible people understand the meaning of what is said.*";
P_HTM[4235]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso kaccāna, telappadīpassa jhāyato telampi aparisuddhaṃ vaṭṭipi aparisuddhā.**Suppose an oil lamp was burning with impure oil and impure wick.*";
P_HTM[4236]="*So telassapi aparisuddhattā vaṭṭiyāpi aparisuddhattā andhandhaṃ viya jhāyati;**Because of the impurity of the oil and the wick it burns dimly, as it were.*";
P_HTM[4237]="*evameva kho, āvuso kaccāna, idhekacco bhikkhu ‘saṃkiliṭṭhābhā’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati,**In the same way, take some mendicant who meditates determined on pervading ‘corrupted radiance’.*";
P_HTM[4238]="*tassa kāyaduṭṭhullampi na suppaṭippassaddhaṃ hoti, thinamiddhampi na susamūhataṃ hoti, uddhaccakukkuccampi na suppaṭivinītaṃ hoti.**Their physical discomfort is not completely settled, their dullness and drowsiness is not completely eradicated, and their restlessness and remorse is not completely eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4239]="*So kāyaduṭṭhullassapi na suppaṭippassaddhattā thinamiddhassapi na susamūhatattā uddhaccakukkuccassapi na suppaṭivinītattā andhandhaṃ viya jhāyati.**Because of this they practice absorption dimly, as it were.*";
P_HTM[4240]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā saṃkiliṭṭhābhānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in the company of the gods of corrupted radiance.*";
P_HTM[4241]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso kaccāna, telappadīpassa jhāyato telampi parisuddhaṃ vaṭṭipi parisuddhā.**Suppose an oil lamp was burning with pure oil and pure wick.*";
P_HTM[4242]="*So telassapi parisuddhattā vaṭṭiyāpi parisuddhattā na andhandhaṃ viya jhāyati;**Because of the purity of the oil and the wick it doesn’t burn dimly, as it were.*";
P_HTM[4243]="*evameva kho, āvuso kaccāna, idhekacco bhikkhu ‘parisuddhābhā’ti pharitvā adhimuccitvā viharati.**In the same way, take some mendicant who meditates determined on pervading ‘pure radiance’.*";
P_HTM[4244]="*Tassa kāyaduṭṭhullampi suppaṭippassaddhaṃ hoti, thinamiddhampi susamūhataṃ hoti, uddhaccakukkuccampi suppaṭivinītaṃ hoti.**Their physical discomfort is completely settled, their dullness and drowsiness is completely eradicated, and their restlessness and remorse is completely eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4245]="*So kāyaduṭṭhullassapi suppaṭippassaddhattā thinamiddhassapi susamūhatattā uddhaccakukkuccassapi suppaṭivinītattā na andhandhaṃ viya jhāyati.**Because of this they don’t practice absorption dimly, as it were.*";
P_HTM[4246]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parisuddhābhānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in the company of the gods of pure radiance.*";
P_HTM[4247]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso kaccāna, hetu ayaṃ paccayo yena tāsaṃ devatānaṃ ekaṃ devanikāyaṃ upapannānaṃ santettha ekaccā devatā saṃkiliṭṭhābhā, santi panettha ekaccā devatā parisuddhābhā”ti.**“This is the cause, Reverend Kaccāna, this is the reason why, when those deities have been reborn in a single order of gods, some deities there have corrupted radiance, while some have pure radiance.”*";
P_HTM[4248]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā sabhiyo kaccāno āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Venerable Abhiya Kaccāna said to Venerable Anuruddha,*";
P_HTM[4249]="*“sādhu, bhante anuruddha.**“Good, Venerable Anuruddha!*";
P_HTM[4250]="*Na, bhante, āyasmā anuruddho evamāha:**Venerable Anuruddha, you don’t say,*";
P_HTM[4251]="*‘evaṃ me sutan’ti vā ‘evaṃ arahati bhavitun’ti vā;**‘So I have heard’ or ‘It ought to be like this.’*";
P_HTM[4252]="*atha ca pana, bhante, āyasmā anuruddho ‘evampi tā devatā, itipi tā devatā’tveva bhāsati.**Rather, you say: ‘These deities are like this, those deities are like that.’*";
P_HTM[4253]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, evaṃ hoti:**Sir, it occurs to me,*";
P_HTM[4254]="*‘addhā āyasmatā anuruddhena tāhi devatāhi saddhiṃ sannivutthapubbañceva sallapitapubbañca sākacchā ca samāpajjitapubbā’”ti.**‘Clearly, Venerable Anuruddha has previously lived together with those deities, conversed, and engaged in discussion.’”*";
P_HTM[4255]="*“Addhā kho ayaṃ, āvuso kaccāna, āsajja upanīya vācā bhāsitā,**“Your words are clearly invasive and intrusive, Reverend Kaccāna.*";
P_HTM[4256]="*api ca te ahaṃ byākarissāmi:**Nevertheless, I will answer you.*";
P_HTM[4257]="*‘dīgharattaṃ kho me, āvuso kaccāna, tāhi devatāhi saddhiṃ sannivutthapubbañceva sallapitapubbañca sākacchā ca samāpajjitapubbā’”ti.**For a long time I have previously lived together with those deities, conversed, and engaged in discussion.”*";
P_HTM[4258]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā sabhiyo kaccāno pañcakaṅgaṃ thapatiṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Venerable Abhiya Kaccāna said to Pañcakaṅga the master builder,*";
P_HTM[4259]="*“lābhā te, gahapati, suladdhaṃ te, gahapati,**“You’re fortunate, householder, so very fortunate,*";
P_HTM[4260]="*yaṃ tvañceva taṃ kaṅkhādhammaṃ pahāsi, mayañcimaṃ dhammapariyāyaṃ alatthamhā savanāyā”ti.**to have given up your state of uncertainty, and to have got the chance to listen to this exposition of the teaching.”*";
P_HTM[4261]="*Anuruddhasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4262]="*128. Upakkilesasutta**Corruptions*";
P_HTM[4263]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[4264]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kosambiyaṃ viharati ghositārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Kosambi, in Ghosita’s Monastery.*";
P_HTM[4265]="*Tena kho pana samayena kosambiyaṃ bhikkhū bhaṇḍanajātā kalahajātā vivādāpannā aññamaññaṃ mukhasattīhi vitudantā viharanti.**Now at that time the mendicants of Kosambi were arguing, quarreling, and fighting, continually wounding each other with barbed words.*";
P_HTM[4266]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, bowed, stood to one side, and told him what was happening, adding:*";
P_HTM[4267]="*“idha, bhante, kosambiyaṃ bhikkhū bhaṇḍanajātā kalahajātā vivādāpannā aññamaññaṃ mukhasattīhi vitudantā viharanti.* **";
P_HTM[4268]="*Sādhu, bhante, bhagavā yena te bhikkhū tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**“Please, sir go to those mendicants out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[4269]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[4270]="*Atha kho bhagavā yena te bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā te bhikkhū etadavoca:**Then the Buddha went up to those mendicants and said,*";
P_HTM[4271]="*“alaṃ, bhikkhave, mā bhaṇḍanaṃ, mā kalahaṃ, mā viggahaṃ, mā vivādan”ti.**“Enough, mendicants! Stop arguing, quarreling, and fighting.”*";
P_HTM[4272]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, one of the mendicants said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[4273]="*“āgametu, bhante.**“Wait, sir!*";
P_HTM[4274]="*Bhagavā dhammassāmī;**Let the Buddha, the Lord of the Dhamma,*";
P_HTM[4275]="*appossukko, bhante, bhagavā diṭṭhadhammasukhavihāraṃ anuyutto viharatu;**remain passive, dwelling in blissful meditation in the present life.*";
P_HTM[4276]="*mayametena bhaṇḍanena kalahena viggahena vivādena paññāyissāmā”ti.**We will be known for this arguing, quarreling, and fighting.”*";
P_HTM[4277]="*Dutiyampi kho bhagavā te bhikkhū etadavoca:**For a second time …*";
P_HTM[4278]="*“alaṃ, bhikkhave, mā bhaṇḍanaṃ, mā kalahaṃ, mā viggahaṃ, mā vivādan”ti.* **";
P_HTM[4279]="*Dutiyampi kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[4280]="*“āgametu, bhante.* **";
P_HTM[4281]="*Bhagavā dhammassāmī;* **";
P_HTM[4282]="*appossukko, bhante, bhagavā diṭṭhadhammasukhavihāraṃ anuyutto viharatu;* **";
P_HTM[4283]="*mayametena bhaṇḍanena kalahena viggahena vivādena paññāyissāmā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[4284]="*Tatiyampi kho bhagavā te bhikkhū etadavoca:**and a third time the Buddha said to those mendicants,*";
P_HTM[4285]="*“alaṃ, bhikkhave, mā bhaṇḍanaṃ, mā kalahaṃ, mā viggahaṃ, mā vivādan”ti.**“Enough, mendicants! Stop arguing, quarreling, and fighting.”*";
P_HTM[4286]="*Tatiyampi kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**For a third time that mendicant said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[4287]="*“āgametu, bhante.**“Wait, sir!*";
P_HTM[4288]="*Bhagavā dhammassāmī;**Let the Buddha, the Lord of the Dhamma,*";
P_HTM[4289]="*appossukko, bhante, bhagavā diṭṭhadhammasukhavihāraṃ anuyutto viharatu;**remain passive, dwelling in blissful meditation in the present life.*";
P_HTM[4290]="*mayametena bhaṇḍanena kalahena viggahena vivādena paññāyissāmā”ti.**We will be known for this arguing, quarreling, and fighting.”*";
P_HTM[4291]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya kosambiṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Kosambi for alms.*";
P_HTM[4292]="*Kosambiyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto senāsanaṃ saṃsāmetvā pattacīvaramādāya ṭhitakova imā gāthā abhāsi:**After the meal, on his return from alms-round, he set his lodgings in order. Taking his bowl and robe, he recited these verses while standing right there:*";
P_HTM[4293]="*“Puthusaddo samajano,**“When many voices shout at once,*";
P_HTM[4294]="*na bālo koci maññatha;**no-one thinks that they’re a fool!*";
P_HTM[4295]="*Saṃghasmiṃ bhijjamānasmiṃ,**While the Saṅgha’s being split,*";
P_HTM[4296]="*nāññaṃ bhiyyo amaññaruṃ.**none thought another to be better.*";
P_HTM[4297]="*Parimuṭṭhā paṇḍitābhāsā,**Dolts pretending to be astute,*";
P_HTM[4298]="*vācāgocarabhāṇino;**they talk, their words right out of bounds.*";
P_HTM[4299]="*Yāvicchanti mukhāyāmaṃ,**They blab at will, their mouths agape,*";
P_HTM[4300]="*yena nītā na taṃ vidū.**and no-one knows what leads them on.*";
P_HTM[4301]="*Akkocchi maṃ avadhi maṃ,**‘He abused me, he hit me!*";
P_HTM[4302]="*ajini maṃ ahāsi me;**He beat me, he took from me!’*";
P_HTM[4303]="*Ye ca taṃ upanayhanti,**Those who cling to hate like this*";
P_HTM[4304]="*veraṃ tesaṃ na sammati.**never settle their enmity.*";
P_HTM[4305]="*Akkocchi maṃ avadhi maṃ,**‘He abused me, he hit me!*";
P_HTM[4306]="*ajini maṃ ahāsi me;**He beat me, he took from me!’*";
P_HTM[4307]="*Ye ca taṃ nupanayhanti,**Those who never cling to hate*";
P_HTM[4308]="*veraṃ tesūpasammati.**always settle their enmity.*";
P_HTM[4309]="*Na hi verena verāni,**For enmity in this world*";
P_HTM[4310]="*sammantīdha kudācanaṃ;**is never settled by enmity.*";
P_HTM[4311]="*Averena ca sammanti,**It’s only settled by love:*";
P_HTM[4312]="*esa dhammo sanantano.**this is an ancient principle.*";
P_HTM[4313]="*Pare ca na vijānanti,**Others don’t understand*";
P_HTM[4314]="*mayamettha yamāmase;**that our lives must have limits.*";
P_HTM[4315]="*Ye ca tattha vijānanti,**The clever ones who know this*";
P_HTM[4316]="*tato sammanti medhagā.**settle their quarrels right away.*";
P_HTM[4317]="*Aṭṭhicchinnā pāṇaharā,**Breakers of bones and takers of life,*";
P_HTM[4318]="*gavassadhanahārino;**thieves of cattle, horses, wealth,*";
P_HTM[4319]="*Raṭṭhaṃ vilumpamānānaṃ,**those who plunder the nation:*";
P_HTM[4320]="*tesampi hoti saṅgati;**even they can come together,*";
P_HTM[4321]="*Kasmā tumhākaṃ no siyā.**so why on earth can’t you?*";
P_HTM[4322]="*Sace labhetha nipakaṃ sahāyaṃ,**If you find an alert companion,*";
P_HTM[4323]="*Saddhiṃ caraṃ sādhuvihāri dhīraṃ;**a wise and virtuous friend,*";
P_HTM[4324]="*Abhibhuyya sabbāni parissayāni,**then, overcoming all challenges,*";
P_HTM[4325]="*Careyya tenattamano satīmā.**wander with them, joyful and mindful.*";
P_HTM[4326]="*No ce labhetha nipakaṃ sahāyaṃ,**If you find no alert companion,*";
P_HTM[4327]="*Saddhiṃ caraṃ sādhuvihāri dhīraṃ;**no wise and virtuous friend,*";
P_HTM[4328]="*Rājāva raṭṭhaṃ vijitaṃ pahāya,**then, like a king who flees his conquered realm,*";
P_HTM[4329]="*Eko care mātaṅgaraññeva nāgo.**wander alone like a tusker in the wilds.*";
P_HTM[4330]="*Ekassa caritaṃ seyyo,**It’s better to wander alone,*";
P_HTM[4331]="*Natthi bāle sahāyatā;**for a fool can never be a friend.*";
P_HTM[4332]="*Eko care na ca pāpāni kayirā,**Wander alone and do no wrong,*";
P_HTM[4333]="*Appossukko mātaṅgaraññeva nāgo”ti.**at ease like a tusker in the wilds.”*";
P_HTM[4334]="*Atha kho bhagavā ṭhitakova imā gāthā bhāsitvā yena bālakaloṇakāragāmo tenupasaṅkami.**After speaking these verses while standing, the Buddha went to the village of the child salt-miners,*";
P_HTM[4335]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā bhagu bālakaloṇakāragāme viharati.**where Venerable Bhagu was staying at the time.*";
P_HTM[4336]="*Addasā kho āyasmā bhagu bhagavantaṃ dūratova āgacchantaṃ.**Bhagu saw the Buddha coming off in the distance,*";
P_HTM[4337]="*Disvāna āsanaṃ paññapesi udakañca pādānaṃ dhovanaṃ.**so he spread out a seat and placed water for washing the feet.*";
P_HTM[4338]="*Nisīdi bhagavā paññatte āsane.**The Buddha sat on the seat spread out,*";
P_HTM[4339]="*Nisajja pāde pakkhālesi.**and washed his feet.*";
P_HTM[4340]="*Āyasmāpi kho bhagu bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**Bhagu bowed to the Buddha and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[4341]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ bhaguṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[4342]="*“kacci, bhikkhu, khamanīyaṃ, kacci yāpanīyaṃ, kacci piṇḍakena na kilamasī”ti?**“I hope you’re keeping well, mendicant; I hope you’re all right. And I hope you’re having no trouble getting alms-food.”*";
P_HTM[4343]="*“Khamanīyaṃ bhagavā, yāpanīyaṃ bhagavā, na cāhaṃ, bhante, piṇḍakena kilamāmī”ti.**“I’m keeping well, sir; I’m all right. And I’m having no trouble getting alms-food.”*";
P_HTM[4344]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ bhaguṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassetvā samādapetvā samuttejetvā sampahaṃsetvā uṭṭhāyāsanā yena pācīnavaṃsadāyo tenupasaṅkami.**Then the Buddha educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired Bhagu with a Dhamma talk, after which he got up from his seat and set out for the Eastern Bamboo Park.*";
P_HTM[4345]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā ca anuruddho āyasmā ca nandiyo āyasmā ca kimilo pācīnavaṃsadāye viharanti.**Now at that time the venerables Anuruddha, Nandiya, and Kimbila were staying in the Eastern Bamboo Park.*";
P_HTM[4346]="*Addasā kho dāyapālo bhagavantaṃ dūratova āgacchantaṃ.**The park keeper saw the Buddha coming off in the distance*";
P_HTM[4347]="*Disvāna bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[4348]="*“mā, mahāsamaṇa, etaṃ dāyaṃ pāvisi.**“Don’t come into this park, ascetic.*";
P_HTM[4349]="*Santettha tayo kulaputtā attakāmarūpā viharanti.**There are three gentlemen who love themselves staying here.*";
P_HTM[4350]="*Mā tesaṃ aphāsumakāsī”ti.**Don’t disturb them.”*";
P_HTM[4351]="*Assosi kho āyasmā anuruddho dāyapālassa bhagavatā saddhiṃ mantayamānassa.**Anuruddha heard the park keeper conversing with the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[4352]="*Sutvāna dāyapālaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him,*";
P_HTM[4353]="*“mā, āvuso dāyapāla, bhagavantaṃ vāresi.**“Don’t keep the Buddha out, good park keeper!*";
P_HTM[4354]="*Satthā no bhagavā anuppatto”ti.**Our Teacher, the Blessed One, has arrived.”*";
P_HTM[4355]="*Atha kho āyasmā anuruddho yenāyasmā ca nandiyo yenāyasmā ca kimilo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantañca nandiyaṃ āyasmantañca kimilaṃ etadavoca:**Then Anuruddha went to Nandiya and Kimbila, and said to them,*";
P_HTM[4356]="*“abhikkamathāyasmanto, abhikkamathāyasmanto, satthā no bhagavā anuppatto”ti.**“Come forth, venerables, come forth! Our Teacher, the Blessed One, has arrived!”*";
P_HTM[4357]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca anuruddho āyasmā ca nandiyo āyasmā ca kimilo bhagavantaṃ paccuggantvā**Then Anuruddha, Nandiya, and Kimbila came out to greet the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4358]="*eko bhagavato pattacīvaraṃ paṭiggahesi, eko āsanaṃ paññapesi, eko pādodakaṃ upaṭṭhapesi.**One received his bowl and robe, one spread out a seat, and one set out water for washing his feet.*";
P_HTM[4359]="*Nisīdi bhagavā paññatte āsane.**The Buddha sat on the seat spread out*";
P_HTM[4360]="*Nisajja pāde pakkhālesi.**and washed his feet.*";
P_HTM[4361]="*Tepi kho āyasmanto bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**Those venerables bowed and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[4362]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said to Anuruddha,*";
P_HTM[4363]="*“kacci vo, anuruddhā, khamanīyaṃ, kacci yāpanīyaṃ, kacci piṇḍakena na kilamathā”ti?**“I hope you’re keeping well, Anuruddha and friends; I hope you’re all right. And I hope you’re having no trouble getting alms-food.”*";
P_HTM[4364]="*“Khamanīyaṃ bhagavā, yāpanīyaṃ bhagavā, na ca mayaṃ, bhante, piṇḍakena kilamāmā”ti.**“We’re keeping well, sir; we’re all right. And we’re having no trouble getting alms-food.”*";
P_HTM[4365]="*“Kacci pana vo, anuruddhā, samaggā sammodamānā avivadamānā khīrodakībhūtā aññamaññaṃ piyacakkhūhi sampassantā viharathā”ti?**“I hope you’re living in harmony, appreciating each other, without quarreling, blending like milk and water, and regarding each other with kindly eyes?”*";
P_HTM[4366]="*“Taggha mayaṃ, bhante, samaggā sammodamānā avivadamānā khīrodakībhūtā aññamaññaṃ piyacakkhūhi sampassantā viharāmā”ti.**“Indeed, sir, we live in harmony as you say.”*";
P_HTM[4367]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana tumhe, anuruddhā, samaggā sammodamānā avivadamānā khīrodakībhūtā aññamaññaṃ piyacakkhūhi sampassantā viharathā”ti?**“But how do you live this way?”*";
P_HTM[4368]="*“Idha mayhaṃ, bhante, evaṃ hoti:**“In this case, sir, I think:*";
P_HTM[4369]="*‘lābhā vata me, suladdhaṃ vata me**‘I’m fortunate, so very fortunate,*";
P_HTM[4370]="*yohaṃ evarūpehi sabrahmacārīhi saddhiṃ viharāmī’ti.**to live together with spiritual companions such as these.’*";
P_HTM[4371]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, imesu āyasmantesu mettaṃ kāyakammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ āvi ceva raho ca,**I consistently treat these venerables with kindness by way of body, speech, and mind, both in public and in private.*";
P_HTM[4372]="*mettaṃ vacīkammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ āvi ceva raho ca,* **";
P_HTM[4373]="*mettaṃ manokammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ āvi ceva raho ca.* **";
P_HTM[4374]="*Tassa, mayhaṃ, bhante, evaṃ hoti:**I think:*";
P_HTM[4375]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ sakaṃ cittaṃ nikkhipitvā imesaṃyeva āyasmantānaṃ cittassa vasena vatteyyan’ti.**‘Why don’t I set aside my own ideas and just go along with these venerables’ ideas?’*";
P_HTM[4376]="*So kho ahaṃ, bhante, sakaṃ cittaṃ nikkhipitvā imesaṃyeva āyasmantānaṃ cittassa vasena vattāmi.**And that’s what I do.*";
P_HTM[4377]="*Nānā hi kho no, bhante, kāyā, ekañca pana maññe cittan”ti.**Though we’re different in body, sir, we’re one in mind, it seems to me.”*";
P_HTM[4378]="*Āyasmāpi kho nandiyo … pe …**And the venerables Nandiya and Kimbila spoke likewise, and they added:*";
P_HTM[4379]="*āyasmāpi kho kimilo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[4380]="*“mayhampi kho, bhante, evaṃ hoti:* **";
P_HTM[4381]="*‘lābhā vata me, suladdhaṃ vata me* **";
P_HTM[4382]="*yohaṃ evarūpehi sabrahmacārīhi saddhiṃ viharāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4383]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, imesu āyasmantesu mettaṃ kāyakammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ āvi ceva raho ca,* **";
P_HTM[4384]="*mettaṃ vacīkammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ āvi ceva raho ca,* **";
P_HTM[4385]="*mettaṃ manokammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ āvi ceva raho ca.* **";
P_HTM[4386]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, evaṃ hoti:* **";
P_HTM[4387]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ sakaṃ cittaṃ nikkhipitvā imesaṃyeva āyasmantānaṃ cittassa vasena vatteyyan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4388]="*So kho ahaṃ, bhante, sakaṃ cittaṃ nikkhipitvā imesaṃyeva āyasmantānaṃ cittassa vasena vattāmi.* **";
P_HTM[4389]="*Nānā hi kho no, bhante, kāyā, ekañca pana maññe cittanti.* **";
P_HTM[4390]="*Evaṃ kho mayaṃ, bhante, samaggā sammodamānā avivadamānā khīrodakībhūtā aññamaññaṃ piyacakkhūhi sampassantā viharāmā”ti.**“That’s how we live in harmony, appreciating each other, without quarreling, blending like milk and water, and regarding each other with kindly eyes.”*";
P_HTM[4391]="*“Sādhu sādhu, anuruddhā.**“Good, good, Anuruddha and friends!*";
P_HTM[4392]="*Kacci pana vo, anuruddhā, appamattā ātāpino pahitattā viharathā”ti?**But I hope you’re living diligently, keen, and resolute?”*";
P_HTM[4393]="*“Taggha mayaṃ, bhante, appamattā ātāpino pahitattā viharāmā”ti.**“Indeed, sir, we live diligently.”*";
P_HTM[4394]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana tumhe, anuruddhā, appamattā ātāpino pahitattā viharathā”ti?**“But how do you live this way?”*";
P_HTM[4395]="*“Idha, bhante, amhākaṃ yo paṭhamaṃ gāmato piṇḍāya paṭikkamati, so āsanāni paññapeti, pānīyaṃ paribhojanīyaṃ upaṭṭhāpeti, avakkārapātiṃ upaṭṭhāpeti.**“In this case, sir, whoever returns first from alms-round prepares the seats, and puts out the drinking water and the rubbish bin.*";
P_HTM[4396]="*Yo pacchā gāmato piṇḍāya paṭikkamati—sace hoti bhuttāvaseso, sace ākaṅkhati, bhuñjati; no ce ākaṅkhati, appaharite vā chaḍḍeti apāṇake vā udake opilāpeti—**If there’s anything left over, whoever returns last eats it if they like. Otherwise they throw it out where there is little that grows, or drop it into water that has no living creatures.*";
P_HTM[4397]="*so āsanāni paṭisāmeti, pānīyaṃ paribhojanīyaṃ paṭisāmeti, avakkārapātiṃ dhovitvā paṭisāmeti, bhattaggaṃ sammajjati.**Then they put away the seats, drinking water, and rubbish bin, and sweep the refectory.*";
P_HTM[4398]="*Yo passati pānīyaghaṭaṃ vā paribhojanīyaghaṭaṃ vā vaccaghaṭaṃ vā rittaṃ tucchaṃ so upaṭṭhāpeti.**If someone sees that the pot of water for washing, drinking, or the toilet is empty they set it up.*";
P_HTM[4399]="*Sacassa hoti avisayhaṃ, hatthavikārena dutiyaṃ āmantetvā hatthavilaṅghakena upaṭṭhāpema, na tveva mayaṃ, bhante, tappaccayā vācaṃ bhindāma.**If he can’t do it, he summons another with a wave of the hand, and they set it up by lifting it with their hands. But we don’t break into speech for that reason.*";
P_HTM[4400]="*Pañcāhikaṃ kho pana mayaṃ, bhante, sabbarattiṃ dhammiyā kathāya sannisīdāma.**And every five days we sit together for the whole night and discuss the teachings.*";
P_HTM[4401]="*Evaṃ kho mayaṃ, bhante, appamattā ātāpino pahitattā viharāmā”ti.**That’s how we live diligently, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[4402]="*“Sādhu sādhu, anuruddhā.**“Good, good, Anuruddha and friends!*";
P_HTM[4403]="*Atthi pana vo, anuruddhā, evaṃ appamattānaṃ ātāpīnaṃ pahitattānaṃ viharataṃ uttari manussadhammā alamariyañāṇadassanaviseso adhigato phāsuvihāro”ti?**But as you live diligently like this, have you achieved any superhuman distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones, a meditation at ease?”*";
P_HTM[4404]="*“Idha mayaṃ, bhante, appamattā ātāpino pahitattā viharantā obhāsañceva sañjānāma dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**“Well, sir, while meditating diligent, keen, and resolute, we perceive both light and vision of forms.*";
P_HTM[4405]="*So kho pana no obhāso nacirasseva antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ;**But before long the light and the vision of forms vanish.*";
P_HTM[4406]="*tañca nimittaṃ nappaṭivijjhāmā”ti.**We haven’t worked out the reason for that.”*";
P_HTM[4407]="*“Taṃ kho pana vo, anuruddhā, nimittaṃ paṭivijjhitabbaṃ.**“Well, you should work out the reason for that.*";
P_HTM[4408]="*Ahampi sudaṃ, anuruddhā, pubbeva sambodhā anabhisambuddho bodhisattova samāno obhāsañceva sañjānāmi dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**Before my awakening—when I was still unawakened but intent on awakening—I too perceived both light and vision of forms.*";
P_HTM[4409]="*So kho pana me obhāso nacirasseva antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**But before long my light and vision of forms vanished.*";
P_HTM[4410]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[4411]="*‘ko nu kho hetu ko paccayo yena me obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānan’ti?**‘What’s the cause, what’s the reason why my light and vision of forms vanish?’*";
P_HTM[4412]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[4413]="*‘vicikicchā kho me udapādi, vicikicchādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.**‘Doubt arose in me, and because of that my immersion fell away.*";
P_HTM[4414]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**When immersion falls away, the light and vision of forms vanish.*";
P_HTM[4415]="*Sohaṃ tathā karissāmi yathā me puna na vicikicchā uppajjissatī’ti. (1)**I’ll make sure that doubt will not arise in me again.’*";
P_HTM[4416]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā, appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto obhāsañceva sañjānāmi dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**While meditating diligent, keen, and resolute, I perceived both light and vision of forms.*";
P_HTM[4417]="*So kho pana me obhāso nacirasseva antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**But before long my light and vision of forms vanished.*";
P_HTM[4418]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[4419]="*‘ko nu kho hetu ko paccayo yena me obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānan’ti?**‘What’s the cause, what’s the reason why my light and vision of forms vanish?’*";
P_HTM[4420]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[4421]="*‘amanasikāro kho me udapādi, amanasikārādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.**‘Loss of focus arose in me, and because of that my immersion fell away.*";
P_HTM[4422]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**When immersion falls away, the light and vision of forms vanish.*";
P_HTM[4423]="*Sohaṃ tathā karissāmi yathā me puna na vicikicchā uppajjissati, na amanasikāro’ti. (2)**I’ll make sure that neither doubt nor loss of focus will arise in me again.’*";
P_HTM[4424]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā … pe …**While meditating …*";
P_HTM[4425]="*tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[4426]="*‘thinamiddhaṃ kho me udapādi, thinamiddhādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.**‘Dullness and drowsiness arose in me …*";
P_HTM[4427]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4428]="*Sohaṃ tathā karissāmi yathā me puna na vicikicchā uppajjissati, na amanasikāro, na thinamiddhan’ti. (3)**I’ll make sure that neither doubt nor loss of focus nor dullness and drowsiness will arise in me again.’*";
P_HTM[4429]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā … pe …**While meditating …*";
P_HTM[4430]="*tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[4431]="*‘chambhitattaṃ kho me udapādi, chambhitattādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.**‘Terror arose in me, and because of that my immersion fell away.*";
P_HTM[4432]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**When immersion falls away, the light and vision of forms vanish.*";
P_HTM[4433]="*Seyyathāpi, anuruddhā, puriso addhānamaggappaṭipanno, tassa ubhatopasse vaṭṭakā uppateyyuṃ, tassa tatonidānaṃ chambhitattaṃ uppajjeyya;**Suppose a person was traveling along a road, and killers were to spring out at them from both sides. They’d feel terrified because of that.*";
P_HTM[4434]="*evameva kho me, anuruddhā, chambhitattaṃ udapādi, chambhitattādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.**In the same way, terror arose in me …*";
P_HTM[4435]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4436]="*Sohaṃ tathā karissāmi yathā me puna na vicikicchā uppajjissati, na amanasikāro, na thinamiddhaṃ, na chambhitattan’ti. (4)**I’ll make sure that neither doubt nor loss of focus nor dullness and drowsiness nor terror will arise in me again.’*";
P_HTM[4437]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā … pe …**While meditating …*";
P_HTM[4438]="*tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[4439]="*‘uppilaṃ kho me udapādi, uppilādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.**‘Excitement arose in me, and because of that my immersion fell away.*";
P_HTM[4440]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**When immersion falls away, the light and vision of forms vanish.*";
P_HTM[4441]="*Seyyathāpi, anuruddhā, puriso ekaṃ nidhimukhaṃ gavesanto sakideva pañcanidhimukhāni adhigaccheyya, tassa tatonidānaṃ uppilaṃ uppajjeyya;**Suppose a person was looking for an entrance to a hidden treasure. And all at once they’d come across five entrances! They’d feel excited because of that.*";
P_HTM[4442]="*evameva kho me, anuruddhā, uppilaṃ udapādi, uppilādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.**In the same way, excitement arose in me …*";
P_HTM[4443]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4444]="*Sohaṃ tathā karissāmi yathā me puna na vicikicchā uppajjissati, na amanasikāro, na thinamiddhaṃ, na chambhitattaṃ, na uppilan’ti. (5)**I’ll make sure that neither doubt nor loss of focus nor dullness and drowsiness nor terror nor excitement will arise in me again.’*";
P_HTM[4445]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā … pe …**While meditating …*";
P_HTM[4446]="*tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[4447]="*‘duṭṭhullaṃ kho me udapādi, duṭṭhullādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.**‘Discomfort arose in me …*";
P_HTM[4448]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4449]="*Sohaṃ tathā karissāmi yathā me puna na vicikicchā uppajjissati, na amanasikāro, na thinamiddhaṃ, na chambhitattaṃ, na uppilaṃ, na duṭṭhullan’ti. (6)**I’ll make sure that neither doubt nor loss of focus nor dullness and drowsiness nor terror nor excitement nor discomfort will arise in me again.’*";
P_HTM[4450]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā … pe …**While meditating …*";
P_HTM[4451]="*tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[4452]="*‘accāraddhavīriyaṃ kho me udapādi, accāraddhavīriyādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.**‘Excessive energy arose in me, and because of that my immersion fell away.*";
P_HTM[4453]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**When immersion falls away, the light and vision of forms vanish.*";
P_HTM[4454]="*Seyyathāpi, anuruddhā, puriso ubhohi hatthehi vaṭṭakaṃ gāḷhaṃ gaṇheyya, so tattheva patameyya;**Suppose a person was to grip a quail too tightly in this hands—it would die right there.*";
P_HTM[4455]="*evameva kho me, anuruddhā, accāraddhavīriyaṃ udapādi, accāraddhavīriyādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.* **";
P_HTM[4456]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4457]="*Sohaṃ tathā karissāmi yathā me puna na vicikicchā uppajjissati, na amanasikāro, na thinamiddhaṃ, na chambhitattaṃ, na uppilaṃ, na duṭṭhullaṃ, na accāraddhavīriyan’ti. (7)**I’ll make sure that neither doubt nor loss of focus nor dullness and drowsiness nor terror nor excitement nor discomfort nor excessive energy will arise in me again.’*";
P_HTM[4458]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā … pe …**While meditating …*";
P_HTM[4459]="*tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[4460]="*‘atilīnavīriyaṃ kho me udapādi, atilīnavīriyādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.**‘Overly lax energy arose in me, and because of that my immersion fell away.*";
P_HTM[4461]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**When immersion falls away, the light and vision of forms vanish.*";
P_HTM[4462]="*Seyyathāpi, anuruddhā, puriso vaṭṭakaṃ sithilaṃ gaṇheyya, so tassa hatthato uppateyya;**Suppose a person was to grip a quail too loosely—it would fly out of their hands.*";
P_HTM[4463]="*evameva kho me, anuruddhā, atilīnavīriyaṃ udapādi, atilīnavīriyādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.* **";
P_HTM[4464]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4465]="*Sohaṃ tathā karissāmi yathā me puna na vicikicchā uppajjissati, na amanasikāro, na thinamiddhaṃ, na chambhitattaṃ, na uppilaṃ, na duṭṭhullaṃ, na accāraddhavīriyaṃ, na atilīnavīriyan’ti. (8)**I’ll make sure that neither doubt nor loss of focus nor dullness and drowsiness nor terror nor excitement nor discomfort nor excessive energy nor overly lax energy will arise in me again.’*";
P_HTM[4466]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā … pe …**While meditating …*";
P_HTM[4467]="*tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[4468]="*‘abhijappā kho me udapādi, abhijappādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.**‘Longing arose in me …*";
P_HTM[4469]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4470]="*Sohaṃ tathā karissāmi yathā me puna na vicikicchā uppajjissati, na amanasikāro, na thinamiddhaṃ, na chambhitattaṃ, na uppilaṃ, na duṭṭhullaṃ, na accāraddhavīriyaṃ, na atilīnavīriyaṃ, na abhijappā’ti. (9)**I’ll make sure that neither doubt nor loss of focus nor dullness and drowsiness nor terror nor excitement nor discomfort nor excessive energy nor overly lax energy nor longing will arise in me again.’*";
P_HTM[4471]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā … pe …**While meditating …*";
P_HTM[4472]="*tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[4473]="*‘nānattasaññā kho me udapādi, nānattasaññādhikaraṇañca pana me samādhi cavi.**‘Perceptions of diversity arose in me …*";
P_HTM[4474]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4475]="*Sohaṃ tathā karissāmi yathā me puna na vicikicchā uppajjissati, na amanasikāro, na thinamiddhaṃ, na chambhitattaṃ, na uppilaṃ, na duṭṭhullaṃ, na accāraddhavīriyaṃ, na atilīnavīriyaṃ, na abhijappā, na nānattasaññā’ti. (10)**I’ll make sure that neither doubt nor loss of focus nor dullness and drowsiness nor terror nor excitement nor discomfort nor excessive energy nor overly lax energy nor longing nor perception of diversity will arise in me again.’*";
P_HTM[4476]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā, appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto obhāsañceva sañjānāmi dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**While meditating diligent, keen, and resolute, I perceived both light and vision of forms.*";
P_HTM[4477]="*So kho pana me obhāso nacirasseva antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**But before long my light and vision of forms vanished.*";
P_HTM[4478]="*Tassa mayhaṃ anuruddhā etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[4479]="*‘ko nu kho hetu ko paccayo yena me obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānan’ti.**‘What’s the cause, what’s the reason why my light and vision of forms vanish?’*";
P_HTM[4480]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[4481]="*‘atinijjhāyitattaṃ kho me rūpānaṃ udapādi, atinijjhāyitattādhikaraṇañca pana me rūpānaṃ samādhi cavi.**‘Excessive concentration on forms arose in me, and because of that my immersion fell away.*";
P_HTM[4482]="*Samādhimhi cute obhāso antaradhāyati dassanañca rūpānaṃ.**When immersion falls away, the light and vision of forms vanish.*";
P_HTM[4483]="*Sohaṃ tathā karissāmi yathā me puna na vicikicchā uppajjissati, na amanasikāro, na thinamiddhaṃ, na chambhitattaṃ, na uppilaṃ, na duṭṭhullaṃ, na accāraddhavīriyaṃ, na atilīnavīriyaṃ, na abhijappā, na nānattasaññā, na atinijjhāyitattaṃ rūpānan’ti. (11)**I’ll make sure that neither doubt nor loss of focus nor dullness and drowsiness nor terror nor excitement nor discomfort nor excessive energy nor overly lax energy nor longing nor perception of diversity nor excessive concentration on forms will arise in me again.’*";
P_HTM[4484]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā, ‘vicikicchā cittassa upakkileso’ti—**When I understood that doubt is a corruption of the mind, I gave it up.*";
P_HTM[4485]="*iti viditvā vicikicchaṃ cittassa upakkilesaṃ pajahiṃ, ‘amanasikāro cittassa upakkileso’ti—**When I understood that loss of focus,*";
P_HTM[4486]="*iti viditvā amanasikāraṃ cittassa upakkilesaṃ pajahiṃ, ‘thinamiddhaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**dullness and drowsiness,*";
P_HTM[4487]="*iti viditvā thinamiddhaṃ cittassa upakkilesaṃ pajahiṃ, ‘chambhitattaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**terror,*";
P_HTM[4488]="*iti viditvā chambhitattaṃ cittassa upakkilesaṃ pajahiṃ, ‘uppilaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**excitement,*";
P_HTM[4489]="*iti viditvā uppilaṃ cittassa upakkilesaṃ pajahiṃ, ‘duṭṭhullaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**discomfort,*";
P_HTM[4490]="*iti viditvā duṭṭhullaṃ cittassa upakkilesaṃ pajahiṃ, ‘accāraddhavīriyaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**excessive energy,*";
P_HTM[4491]="*iti viditvā accāraddhavīriyaṃ cittassa upakkilesaṃ pajahiṃ, ‘atilīnavīriyaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**overly lax energy,*";
P_HTM[4492]="*iti viditvā atilīnavīriyaṃ cittassa upakkilesaṃ pajahiṃ, ‘abhijappā cittassa upakkileso’ti—**longing,*";
P_HTM[4493]="*iti viditvā abhijappaṃ cittassa upakkilesaṃ pajahiṃ, ‘nānattasaññā cittassa upakkileso’ti—**perception of diversity,*";
P_HTM[4494]="*iti viditvā nānattasaññaṃ cittassa upakkilesaṃ pajahiṃ, ‘atinijjhāyitattaṃ rūpānaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**and excessive concentration on forms are corruptions of the mind, I gave them up.*";
P_HTM[4495]="*iti viditvā atinijjhāyitattaṃ rūpānaṃ cittassa upakkilesaṃ pajahiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4496]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā, appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto obhāsañhi kho sañjānāmi, na ca rūpāni passāmi;**While meditating diligent, keen, and resolute, I perceived light but did not see forms,*";
P_HTM[4497]="*rūpāni hi kho passāmi, na ca obhāsaṃ sañjānāmi:**or I saw forms, but did not see light.*";
P_HTM[4498]="*‘kevalampi rattiṃ, kevalampi divaṃ, kevalampi rattindivaṃ’.**And this went on for a whole night, a whole day, even a whole night and day.*";
P_HTM[4499]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:**I thought:*";
P_HTM[4500]="*‘ko nu kho hetu ko paccayo yvāhaṃ obhāsañhi kho sañjānāmi na ca rūpāni passāmi;**‘What is the cause, what is the reason for this?’*";
P_HTM[4501]="*rūpāni hi kho passāmi na ca obhāsaṃ sañjānāmi—* **";
P_HTM[4502]="*kevalampi rattiṃ, kevalampi divaṃ, kevalampi rattindivan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4503]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[4504]="*‘yasmiñhi kho ahaṃ samaye rūpanimittaṃ amanasikaritvā obhāsanimittaṃ manasi karomi, obhāsañhi kho tasmiṃ samaye sañjānāmi, na ca rūpāni passāmi.**‘When I don’t focus on the foundation of the forms, but focus on the foundation of the light, then I perceive light and do not see forms.*";
P_HTM[4505]="*Yasmiṃ panāhaṃ samaye obhāsanimittaṃ amanasikaritvā rūpanimittaṃ manasi karomi, rūpāni hi kho tasmiṃ samaye passāmi na ca obhāsaṃ sañjānāmi—**But when I don’t focus on the foundation of the light, but focus on the foundation of the forms, then I see forms and do not perceive light.*";
P_HTM[4506]="*kevalampi rattiṃ, kevalampi divaṃ, kevalampi rattindivan’ti.**And this goes on for a whole night, a whole day, even a whole night and day.’*";
P_HTM[4507]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā, appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto parittañceva obhāsaṃ sañjānāmi, parittāni ca rūpāni passāmi;**While meditating diligent, keen, and resolute, I perceived limited light and saw limited forms,*";
P_HTM[4508]="*appamāṇañceva obhāsaṃ sañjānāmi, appamāṇāni ca rūpāni passāmi:**or I perceived limitless light and saw limitless forms.*";
P_HTM[4509]="*‘kevalampi rattiṃ, kevalampi divaṃ, kevalampi rattindivaṃ’.**And this went on for a whole night, a whole day, even a whole night and day.*";
P_HTM[4510]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:**I thought:*";
P_HTM[4511]="*‘ko nu kho hetu ko paccayo yvāhaṃ parittañceva obhāsaṃ sañjānāmi, parittāni ca rūpāni passāmi;**‘What is the cause, what is the reason for this?’*";
P_HTM[4512]="*appamāṇañceva obhāsaṃ sañjānāmi, appamāṇāni ca rūpāni passāmi—* **";
P_HTM[4513]="*kevalampi rattiṃ, kevalampi divaṃ, kevalampi rattindivan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4514]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[4515]="*‘yasmiṃ kho me samaye paritto samādhi hoti, parittaṃ me tasmiṃ samaye cakkhu hoti.**‘When my immersion is limited, then my vision is limited,*";
P_HTM[4516]="*Sohaṃ parittena cakkhunā parittañceva obhāsaṃ sañjānāmi, parittāni ca rūpāni passāmi.**and with limited vision I perceive limited light and see limited forms.*";
P_HTM[4517]="*Yasmiṃ pana me samaye appamāṇo samādhi hoti, appamāṇaṃ me tasmiṃ samaye cakkhu hoti.**But when my immersion is limitless, then my vision is limitless,*";
P_HTM[4518]="*Sohaṃ appamāṇena cakkhunā appamāṇañceva obhāsaṃ sañjānāmi, appamāṇāni ca rūpāni passāmi—**and with limitless vision I perceive limitless light and see limitless forms.*";
P_HTM[4519]="*kevalampi rattiṃ, kevalampi divaṃ, kevalampi rattindivan’ti.**And this goes on for a whole night, a whole day, even a whole night and day.’*";
P_HTM[4520]="*Yato kho me, anuruddhā, ‘vicikicchā cittassa upakkileso’ti—**When I understood that doubt,*";
P_HTM[4521]="*iti viditvā vicikicchā cittassa upakkileso pahīno ahosi, ‘amanasikāro cittassa upakkileso’ti—**loss of focus,*";
P_HTM[4522]="*iti viditvā amanasikāro cittassa upakkileso pahīno ahosi, ‘thinamiddhaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**dullness and drowsiness,*";
P_HTM[4523]="*iti viditvā thinamiddhaṃ cittassa upakkileso pahīno ahosi, ‘chambhitattaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**terror,*";
P_HTM[4524]="*iti viditvā chambhitattaṃ cittassa upakkileso pahīno ahosi, ‘uppilaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**excitement,*";
P_HTM[4525]="*iti viditvā uppilaṃ cittassa upakkileso pahīno ahosi, ‘duṭṭhullaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**discomfort,*";
P_HTM[4526]="*iti viditvā duṭṭhullaṃ cittassa upakkileso pahīno ahosi, ‘accāraddhavīriyaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**excessive energy,*";
P_HTM[4527]="*iti viditvā accāraddhavīriyaṃ cittassa upakkileso pahīno ahosi, ‘atilīnavīriyaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**overly lax energy,*";
P_HTM[4528]="*iti viditvā atilīnavīriyaṃ cittassa upakkileso pahīno ahosi, ‘abhijappā cittassa upakkileso’ti—**longing,*";
P_HTM[4529]="*iti viditvā abhijappā cittassa upakkileso pahīno ahosi, ‘nānattasaññā cittassa upakkileso’ti—**perception of diversity,*";
P_HTM[4530]="*iti viditvā nānattasaññā cittassa upakkileso pahīno ahosi, ‘atinijjhāyitattaṃ rūpānaṃ cittassa upakkileso’ti—**and excessive concentration on forms are corruptions of the mind, I gave them up.*";
P_HTM[4531]="*iti viditvā atinijjhāyitattaṃ rūpānaṃ cittassa upakkileso pahīno ahosi.* **";
P_HTM[4532]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, anuruddhā, etadahosi:**I thought:*";
P_HTM[4533]="*‘ye kho me cittassa upakkilesā te me pahīnā.**‘I’ve given up my mental corruptions.*";
P_HTM[4534]="*Handa dānāhaṃ tividhena samādhiṃ bhāvemī’ti.**Now let me develop immersion in three ways.’*";
P_HTM[4535]="*So kho ahaṃ, anuruddhā, savitakkampi savicāraṃ samādhiṃ bhāvesiṃ, avitakkampi vicāramattaṃ samādhiṃ bhāvesiṃ, avitakkampi avicāraṃ samādhiṃ bhāvesiṃ, sappītikampi samādhiṃ bhāvesiṃ, nippītikampi samādhiṃ bhāvesiṃ, sātasahagatampi samādhiṃ bhāvesiṃ, upekkhāsahagatampi samādhiṃ bhāvesiṃ.**I developed immersion while placing the mind and keeping it connected; without placing the mind, but just keeping it connected; without placing the mind or keeping it connected; with rapture; without rapture; with pleasure; with equanimity.*";
P_HTM[4536]="*Yato kho me, anuruddhā, savitakkopi savicāro samādhi bhāvito ahosi, avitakkopi vicāramatto samādhi bhāvito ahosi, avitakkopi avicāro samādhi bhāvito ahosi, sappītikopi samādhi bhāvito ahosi, nippītikopi samādhi bhāvito ahosi, sātasahagatopi samādhi bhāvito ahosi, upekkhāsahagatopi samādhi bhāvito ahosi.**When I had developed immersion in these ways,*";
P_HTM[4537]="*Ñāṇañca pana me dassanaṃ udapādi,**the knowledge and vision arose in me:*";
P_HTM[4538]="*akuppā me cetovimutti. Ayamantimā jāti, natthi dāni punabbhavo”ti.**‘My freedom is unshakable; this is my last rebirth; now there are no more future lives.’”*";
P_HTM[4539]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[4540]="*Attamano āyasmā anuruddho bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Anuruddha was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[4541]="*Upakkilesasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4542]="*129. Bālapaṇḍitasutta**The Foolish and the Astute*";
P_HTM[4543]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[4544]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[4545]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[4546]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[4547]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[4548]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[4549]="*“Tīṇimāni, bhikkhave, bālassa bālalakkhaṇāni bālanimittāni bālāpadānāni.**“These are the three characteristics, signs, and manifestations of a fool.*";
P_HTM[4550]="*Katamāni tīṇi?**What three?*";
P_HTM[4551]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bālo duccintitacintī ca hoti dubbhāsitabhāsī ca dukkaṭakammakārī ca.**A fool thinks poorly, speaks poorly, and acts poorly.*";
P_HTM[4552]="*No cetaṃ, bhikkhave, bālo duccintitacintī ca abhavissa dubbhāsitabhāsī ca dukkaṭakammakārī ca kena naṃ paṇḍitā jāneyyuṃ:**If a fool didn’t think poorly, speak poorly, and act poorly, then how would the astute know of them,*";
P_HTM[4553]="*‘bālo ayaṃ bhavaṃ asappuriso’ti?**‘This fellow is a fool, a bad person’?*";
P_HTM[4554]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, bālo duccintitacintī ca hoti dubbhāsitabhāsī ca dukkaṭakammakārī ca tasmā naṃ paṇḍitā jānanti:**But since a fool does think poorly, speak poorly, and act poorly, then the astute do know of them,*";
P_HTM[4555]="*‘bālo ayaṃ bhavaṃ asappuriso’ti.**‘This fellow is a fool, a bad person’.*";
P_HTM[4556]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, bālo tividhaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhaṃ domanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**A fool experiences three kinds of suffering and sadness in the present life.*";
P_HTM[4557]="*Sace, bhikkhave, bālo sabhāyaṃ vā nisinno hoti, rathikāya vā nisinno hoti, siṅghāṭake vā nisinno hoti;**Suppose a fool is sitting in a council hall, a street, or a crossroad,*";
P_HTM[4558]="*tatra ce jano tajjaṃ tassāruppaṃ kathaṃ manteti.**where people are discussing what is proper and fitting.*";
P_HTM[4559]="*Sace, bhikkhave, bālo pāṇātipātī hoti, adinnādāyī hoti, kāmesumicchācārī hoti, musāvādī hoti, surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhāyī hoti.**And suppose that fool is someone who kills living creatures, steals, commits sexual misconduct, lies, and uses alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.*";
P_HTM[4560]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, bālassa evaṃ hoti:**Then that fool thinks,*";
P_HTM[4561]="*‘yaṃ kho jano tajjaṃ tassāruppaṃ kathaṃ manteti,**‘These people are discussing what is proper and fitting.*";
P_HTM[4562]="*saṃvijjanteva te dhammā mayi, ahañca tesu dhammesu sandissāmī’ti.**But those things are found in me and I am seen in them!’*";
P_HTM[4563]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, bālo paṭhamaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhaṃ domanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**This is the first kind of suffering and sadness that a fool experiences in the present life.*";
P_HTM[4564]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bālo passati rājāno coraṃ āgucāriṃ gahetvā vividhā kammakāraṇā kārente—**Furthermore, a fool sees that the kings have arrested a bandit, a criminal, and subjected them to various punishments—*";
P_HTM[4565]="*kasāhipi tāḷente vettehipi tāḷente addhadaṇḍakehipi tāḷente hatthampi chindante pādampi chindante hatthapādampi chindante kaṇṇampi chindante nāsampi chindante kaṇṇanāsampi chindante bilaṅgathālikampi karonte saṅkhamuṇḍikampi karonte rāhumukhampi karonte jotimālikampi karonte hatthapajjotikampi karonte erakavattikampi karonte cīrakavāsikampi karonte eṇeyyakampi karonte baḷisamaṃsikampi karonte kahāpaṇikampi karonte khārāpatacchikampi karonte palighaparivattikampi karonte palālapīṭhakampi karonte tattenapi telena osiñcante sunakhehipi khādāpente jīvantampi sūle uttāsente asināpi sīsaṃ chindante.**whipping, caning, and clubbing; cutting off hands or feet, or both; cutting off ears or nose, or both; the ‘porridge pot’, the ‘shell-shave’, the ‘demon’s mouth’, the ‘garland of fire’, the ‘burning hand’, the ‘grass blades’, the ‘bark dress’, the ‘antelope’, the ‘meat hook’, the ‘coins’, the ‘acid pickle’, the ‘twisting bar’, the ‘straw mat’; being splashed with hot oil, being fed to the dogs, being impaled alive, and being beheaded.*";
P_HTM[4566]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, bālassa evaṃ hoti:**Then that fool thinks,*";
P_HTM[4567]="*‘yathārūpānaṃ kho pāpakānaṃ kammānaṃ hetu rājāno coraṃ āgucāriṃ gahetvā vividhā kammakāraṇā kārenti—**‘The kinds of deeds for which the kings inflict such punishments—*";
P_HTM[4568]="*kasāhipi tāḷenti … pe … asināpi sīsaṃ chindanti;* **";
P_HTM[4569]="*saṃvijjanteva te dhammā mayi, ahañca tesu dhammesu sandissāmi.**those things are found in me and I am seen in them!*";
P_HTM[4570]="*Mañcepi rājāno jāneyyuṃ, mampi rājāno gahetvā vividhā kammakāraṇā kāreyyuṃ—**If the kings find out about me, they will inflict the same kinds of punishments on me!’*";
P_HTM[4571]="*kasāhipi tāḷeyyuṃ … pe … jīvantampi sūle uttāseyyuṃ, asināpi sīsaṃ chindeyyun’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4572]="*Idampi, bhikkhave, bālo dutiyaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhaṃ domanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**This is the second kind of suffering and sadness that a fool experiences in the present life.*";
P_HTM[4573]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bālaṃ pīṭhasamārūḷhaṃ vā mañcasamārūḷhaṃ vā chamāyaṃ vā semānaṃ, yānissa pubbe pāpakāni kammāni katāni kāyena duccaritāni vācāya duccaritāni manasā duccaritāni tānissa tamhi samaye olambanti ajjholambanti abhippalambanti.**Furthermore, when a fool is resting on a chair or a bed or on the ground, their past bad deeds—misconduct of body, speech, and mind—settle down upon them, rest down upon them, and lay down upon them.*";
P_HTM[4574]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, mahataṃ pabbatakūṭānaṃ chāyā sāyanhasamayaṃ pathaviyā olambanti ajjholambanti abhippalambanti;**It is like the shadow of a great mountain peak in the evening as it settles down, rests down, and lays down upon the earth.*";
P_HTM[4575]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bālaṃ pīṭhasamārūḷhaṃ vā mañcasamārūḷhaṃ vā chamāyaṃ vā semānaṃ, yānissa pubbe pāpakāni kammāni katāni kāyena duccaritāni vācāya duccaritāni manasā duccaritāni tānissa tamhi samaye olambanti ajjholambanti abhippalambanti.**In the same way, when a fool is resting on a chair or a bed or on the ground, their past bad deeds—misconduct of body, speech, and mind—settle down upon them, rest down upon them, and lay down upon them.*";
P_HTM[4576]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, bālassa evaṃ hoti:**Then that fool thinks,*";
P_HTM[4577]="*‘akataṃ vata me kalyāṇaṃ, akataṃ kusalaṃ, akataṃ bhīruttāṇaṃ;**‘Well, I haven’t done good and skillful things that keep me safe.*";
P_HTM[4578]="*kataṃ pāpaṃ, kataṃ luddaṃ, kataṃ kibbisaṃ.**And I have done bad, violent, and corrupt things.*";
P_HTM[4579]="*Yāvatā, bho, akatakalyāṇānaṃ akatakusalānaṃ akatabhīruttāṇānaṃ katapāpānaṃ kataluddānaṃ katakibbisānaṃ gati taṃ gatiṃ pecca gacchāmī’ti.**When I depart, I’ll go to the place where people who’ve done such things go.’*";
P_HTM[4580]="*So socati kilamati paridevati urattāḷiṃ kandati sammohaṃ āpajjati.**They sorrow and pine and lament, beating their breasts and falling into confusion.*";
P_HTM[4581]="*Idampi, bhikkhave, bālo tatiyaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhaṃ domanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**This is the third kind of suffering and sadness that a fool experiences in the present life.*";
P_HTM[4582]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, bālo kāyena duccaritaṃ caritvā vācāya duccaritaṃ caritvā manasā duccaritaṃ caritvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**Having done bad things by way of body, speech, and mind, when their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[4583]="*Yaṃ kho taṃ, bhikkhave, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**And if there’s anything of which it may be rightly said that*";
P_HTM[4584]="*‘ekantaṃ aniṭṭhaṃ ekantaṃ akantaṃ ekantaṃ amanāpan’ti, nirayameva taṃ sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**it is utterly unlikable, undesirable, and disagreeable, it is of hell that this should be said.*";
P_HTM[4585]="*‘ekantaṃ aniṭṭhaṃ ekantaṃ akantaṃ ekantaṃ amanāpan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4586]="*Yāvañcidaṃ, bhikkhave, upamāpi na sukarā yāva dukkhā nirayā”ti.**So much so that it’s not easy to give a simile for how painful hell is.”*";
P_HTM[4587]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, one of the mendicants asked the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[4588]="*“sakkā pana, bhante, upamaṃ kātun”ti?**“But sir, is it possible to give a simile?”*";
P_HTM[4589]="*“Sakkā, bhikkhū”ti bhagavā avoca.**“It’s possible,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4590]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhu, coraṃ āgucāriṃ gahetvā rañño dasseyyuṃ:**“Suppose they arrest a bandit, a criminal and present him to the king, saying,*";
P_HTM[4591]="*‘ayaṃ kho, deva, coro āgucārī, imassa yaṃ icchasi taṃ daṇḍaṃ paṇehī’ti.**‘Your Majesty, this is a bandit, a criminal. Punish him as you will.’*";
P_HTM[4592]="*Tamenaṃ rājā evaṃ vadeyya:**The king would say,*";
P_HTM[4593]="*‘gacchatha, bho, imaṃ purisaṃ pubbaṇhasamayaṃ sattisatena hanathā’ti.**‘Go, my men, and strike this man in the morning with a hundred spears!’*";
P_HTM[4594]="*Tamenaṃ pubbaṇhasamayaṃ sattisatena haneyyuṃ.**The king’s men did as they were told.*";
P_HTM[4595]="*Atha rājā majjhanhikasamayaṃ evaṃ vadeyya:**Then at midday the king would say,*";
P_HTM[4596]="*‘ambho, kathaṃ so puriso’ti?**‘My men, how is that man?’*";
P_HTM[4597]="*‘Tatheva, deva, jīvatī’ti.**‘He’s still alive, Your Majesty.’*";
P_HTM[4598]="*Tamenaṃ rājā evaṃ vadeyya:**The king would say,*";
P_HTM[4599]="*‘gacchatha, bho, taṃ purisaṃ majjhanhikasamayaṃ sattisatena hanathā’ti.**‘Go, my men, and strike this man in the midday with a hundred spears!’*";
P_HTM[4600]="*Tamenaṃ majjhanhikasamayaṃ sattisatena haneyyuṃ.**The king’s men did as they were told.*";
P_HTM[4601]="*Atha rājā sāyanhasamayaṃ evaṃ vadeyya:**Then late in the afternoon the king would say,*";
P_HTM[4602]="*‘ambho, kathaṃ so puriso’ti?**‘My men, how is that man?’*";
P_HTM[4603]="*‘Tatheva, deva, jīvatī’ti.**‘He’s still alive, Your Majesty.’*";
P_HTM[4604]="*Tamenaṃ rājā evaṃ vadeyya:**The king would say,*";
P_HTM[4605]="*‘gacchatha, bho, taṃ purisaṃ sāyanhasamayaṃ sattisatena hanathā’ti.**‘Go, my men, and strike this man in the late afternoon with a hundred spears!’*";
P_HTM[4606]="*Tamenaṃ sāyanhasamayaṃ sattisatena haneyyuṃ.**The king’s men did as they were told.*";
P_HTM[4607]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[4608]="*api nu so puriso tīhi sattisatehi haññamāno tatonidānaṃ dukkhaṃ domanassaṃ paṭisaṃvediyethā”ti?**Would that man experience pain and distress from being struck with three hundred spears?”*";
P_HTM[4609]="*“Ekissāpi, bhante, sattiyā haññamāno so puriso tatonidānaṃ dukkhaṃ domanassaṃ paṭisaṃvediyetha, ko pana vādo tīhi sattisatehī”ti?**“Sir, that man would experience pain and distress from being struck with one spear, let alone three hundred spears!”*";
P_HTM[4610]="*Atha kho bhagavā parittaṃ pāṇimattaṃ pāsāṇaṃ gahetvā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha, picking up a stone the size of his palm, addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[4611]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**“What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[4612]="*katamo nu kho mahantataro—yo cāyaṃ mayā paritto pāṇimatto pāsāṇo gahito, yo ca himavā pabbatarājā”ti?**Which is bigger: the stone the size of my palm that I’ve picked up, or the Himalayas, the king of mountains?”*";
P_HTM[4613]="*“Appamattako ayaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā paritto pāṇimatto pāsāṇo gahito, himavantaṃ pabbatarājānaṃ upanidhāya saṅkhampi na upeti, kalabhāgampi na upeti, upanidhampi na upe”ti.**“Sir, the stone you’ve picked up is tiny. Compared to the Himalayas, it doesn’t even count, it’s not even a fraction, there’s no comparison.”*";
P_HTM[4614]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yaṃ so puriso tīhi sattisatehi haññamāno tatonidānaṃ dukkhaṃ domanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti taṃ nirayakassa dukkhassa upanidhāya saṅkhampi na upeti, kalabhāgampi na upeti, upanidhampi na upeti.**“In the same way, compared to the suffering in hell, the pain and distress experienced by that man due to being struck with three hundred spears doesn’t even count, it’s not even a fraction, there’s no comparison.*";
P_HTM[4615]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā pañcavidhabandhanaṃ nāma kammakāraṇaṃ karonti—**Then the wardens of hell punish them with the five-fold crucifixion.*";
P_HTM[4616]="*tattaṃ ayokhilaṃ hatthe gamenti, tattaṃ ayokhilaṃ dutiye hatthe gamenti, tattaṃ ayokhilaṃ pāde gamenti, tattaṃ ayokhilaṃ dutiye pāde gamenti, tattaṃ ayokhilaṃ majjhe urasmiṃ gamenti.**They drive red-hot stakes through the hands and feet, and another in the middle of the chest.*";
P_HTM[4617]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti.**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4618]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā saṃvesetvā kuṭhārīhi tacchanti.**Then the wardens of hell throw them down and hack them with axes. …*";
P_HTM[4619]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā … pe … byantīhoti.* **";
P_HTM[4620]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā uddhampādaṃ adhosiraṃ gahetvā vāsīhi tacchanti.**They hang them upside-down and hack them with hatchets. …*";
P_HTM[4621]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā … pe … byantīhoti.* **";
P_HTM[4622]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā rathe yojetvā ādittāya pathaviyā sampajjalitāya sajotibhūtāya sārentipi paccāsārentipi.**They harness them to a chariot, and drive them back and forth across burning ground, blazing and glowing. …*";
P_HTM[4623]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā … pe … byantīhoti.* **";
P_HTM[4624]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā mahantaṃ aṅgārapabbataṃ ādittaṃ sampajjalitaṃ sajotibhūtaṃ āropentipi oropentipi.**They make them climb up and down a huge mountain of burning coals, blazing and glowing. …*";
P_HTM[4625]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti.* **";
P_HTM[4626]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā uddhampādaṃ adhosiraṃ gahetvā tattāya lohakumbhiyā pakkhipanti ādittāya sampajjalitāya sajotibhūtāya.**Then the wardens of hell turn them upside down and throw them into a red-hot copper pot, burning, blazing, and glowing.*";
P_HTM[4627]="*So tattha pheṇuddehakaṃ paccati.* **";
P_HTM[4628]="*So tattha pheṇuddehakaṃ paccamāno sakimpi uddhaṃ gacchati, sakimpi adho gacchati, sakimpi tiriyaṃ gacchati.**There they’re seared in boiling scum, and they’re swept up and down and round and round.*";
P_HTM[4629]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti.**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4630]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā mahāniraye pakkhipanti.**Then the wardens of hell toss them in the Great Hell.*";
P_HTM[4631]="*So kho pana, bhikkhave, mahānirayo—**Now, about that Great Hell:*";
P_HTM[4632]="*Catukkaṇṇo catudvāro,**‘Four are its corners, four its doors,*";
P_HTM[4633]="*vibhatto bhāgaso mito;**divided into measured parts.*";
P_HTM[4634]="*Ayopākārapariyanto,**Surrounded by an iron wall,*";
P_HTM[4635]="*ayasā paṭikujjito.**of iron is its roof.*";
P_HTM[4636]="*Tassa ayomayā bhūmi,**The ground is even made of iron,*";
P_HTM[4637]="*jalitā tejasā yutā;**it burns with fierce fire.*";
P_HTM[4638]="*Samantā yojanasataṃ,**The heat forever radiates*";
P_HTM[4639]="*pharitvā tiṭṭhati sabbadā.**a hundred leagues around.’*";
P_HTM[4640]="*Anekapariyāyenapi kho ahaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayakathaṃ katheyyaṃ;**I could tell you many different things about hell.*";
P_HTM[4641]="*yāvañcidaṃ, bhikkhave, na sukarā akkhānena pāpuṇituṃ yāva dukkhā nirayā.**So much so that it’s not easy to completely describe the suffering in hell.*";
P_HTM[4642]="*Santi, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā tiṇabhakkhā.**There are, mendicants, animals that feed on grass.*";
P_HTM[4643]="*Te allānipi tiṇāni sukkhānipi tiṇāni dantullehakaṃ khādanti.**They eat by cropping fresh or dried grass with their teeth.*";
P_HTM[4644]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā tiṇabhakkhā?**And what animals feed on grass?*";
P_HTM[4645]="*Hatthī assā goṇā gadrabhā ajā migā, ye vā panaññepi keci tiracchānagatā pāṇā tiṇabhakkhā.**Elephants, horses, cattle, donkeys, goats, deer, and various others.*";
P_HTM[4646]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, bālo idha pubbe rasādo idha pāpāni kammāni karitvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā tesaṃ sattānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjati ye te sattā tiṇabhakkhā.**A fool who used to be a glutton here and did bad deeds here, when their body breaks up, after death, is reborn in the company of those sentient beings who feed on grass.*";
P_HTM[4647]="*Santi, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā gūthabhakkhā.**There are animals that feed on dung.*";
P_HTM[4648]="*Te dūratova gūthagandhaṃ ghāyitvā dhāvanti:**When they catch a whiff of dung they run to it, thinking,*";
P_HTM[4649]="*‘ettha bhuñjissāma, ettha bhuñjissāmā’ti.**‘There we’ll eat! There we’ll eat!’*";
P_HTM[4650]="*Seyyathāpi nāma brāhmaṇā āhutigandhena dhāvanti:**It’s like when brahmins smell a burnt offering, they run to it, thinking,*";
P_HTM[4651]="*‘ettha bhuñjissāma, ettha bhuñjissāmā’ti;**‘There we’ll eat! There we’ll eat!’*";
P_HTM[4652]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, santi tiracchānagatā pāṇā gūthabhakkhā,**In the same way, there are animals that feed on dung.*";
P_HTM[4653]="*te dūratova gūthagandhaṃ ghāyitvā dhāvanti:**When they catch a whiff of dung they run to it, thinking,*";
P_HTM[4654]="*‘ettha bhuñjissāma, ettha bhuñjissāmā’ti.**‘There we’ll eat! There we’ll eat!’*";
P_HTM[4655]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā gūthabhakkhā?**And what animals feed on dung?*";
P_HTM[4656]="*Kukkuṭā sūkarā soṇā siṅgālā, ye vā panaññepi keci tiracchānagatā pāṇā gūthabhakkhā.**Chickens, pigs, dogs, jackals, and various others.*";
P_HTM[4657]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, bālo idha pubbe rasādo idha pāpāni kammāni karitvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā tesaṃ sattānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjati ye te sattā gūthabhakkhā.**A fool who used to be a glutton here and did bad deeds here, after death is reborn in the company of those sentient beings who feed on dung.*";
P_HTM[4658]="*Santi, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā andhakāre jāyanti andhakāre jīyanti andhakāre mīyanti.**There are animals who are born, live, and die in darkness.*";
P_HTM[4659]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā andhakāre jāyanti andhakāre jīyanti andhakāre mīyanti?**And what animals are born, live, and die in darkness?*";
P_HTM[4660]="*Kīṭā puḷavā gaṇḍuppādā, ye vā panaññepi keci tiracchānagatā pāṇā andhakāre jāyanti andhakāre jīyanti andhakāre mīyanti.**Moths, maggots, earthworms, and various others.*";
P_HTM[4661]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, bālo idha pubbe rasādo, idha pāpāni kammāni karitvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā tesaṃ sattānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjati ye te sattā andhakāre jāyanti andhakāre jīyanti andhakāre mīyanti.**A fool who used to be a glutton here and did bad deeds here, after death is reborn in the company of those sentient beings who are born, live, and die in darkness.*";
P_HTM[4662]="*Santi, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā udakasmiṃ jāyanti udakasmiṃ jīyanti udakasmiṃ mīyanti.**There are animals who are born, live, and die in water.*";
P_HTM[4663]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā udakasmiṃ jāyanti udakasmiṃ jīyanti udakasmiṃ mīyanti?**And what animals are born, live, and die in water?*";
P_HTM[4664]="*Macchā kacchapā susumārā, ye vā panaññepi keci tiracchānagatā pāṇā udakasmiṃ jāyanti udakasmiṃ jīyanti udakasmiṃ mīyanti.**Fish, turtles, crocodiles, and various others.*";
P_HTM[4665]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, bālo idha pubbe rasādo idha pāpāni kammāni karitvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā tesaṃ sattānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjati ye te sattā udakasmiṃ jāyanti udakasmiṃ jīyanti udakasmiṃ mīyanti.**A fool who used to be a glutton here and did bad deeds here, after death is reborn in the company of those sentient beings who are born, live, and die in water.*";
P_HTM[4666]="*Santi, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā asucismiṃ jāyanti asucismiṃ jīyanti asucismiṃ mīyanti.**There are animals who are born, live, and die in filth.*";
P_HTM[4667]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā asucismiṃ jāyanti asucismiṃ jīyanti asucismiṃ mīyanti?**And what animals are born, live, and die in filth?*";
P_HTM[4668]="*Ye te, bhikkhave, sattā pūtimacche vā jāyanti pūtimacche vā jīyanti pūtimacche vā mīyanti pūtikuṇape vā … pe …**Those animals that are born, live, and die in a rotten fish, a rotten corpse,*";
P_HTM[4669]="*pūtikummāse vā …**rotten porridge,*";
P_HTM[4670]="*candanikāya vā …**or a sewer.*";
P_HTM[4671]="*oligalle vā jāyanti, ye vā panaññepi keci tiracchānagatā pāṇā asucismiṃ jāyanti asucismiṃ jīyanti asucismiṃ mīyanti.* **";
P_HTM[4672]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, bālo idha pubbe rasādo idha pāpāni kammāni karitvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā tesaṃ sattānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjati ye te sattā asucismiṃ jāyanti asucismiṃ jīyanti asucismiṃ mīyanti.**A fool who used to be a glutton here and did bad deeds here, after death is reborn in the company of those sentient beings who are born, live, and die in filth.*";
P_HTM[4673]="*Anekapariyāyenapi kho ahaṃ, bhikkhave, tiracchānayonikathaṃ katheyyaṃ;**I could tell you many different things about the animal realm.*";
P_HTM[4674]="*yāvañcidaṃ, bhikkhave, na sukaraṃ akkhānena pāpuṇituṃ yāva dukkhā tiracchānayoni.**So much so that it’s not easy to completely describe the suffering in the animal realm.*";
P_HTM[4675]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso ekacchiggalaṃ yugaṃ mahāsamudde pakkhipeyya.**Mendicants, suppose a person were to throw a yoke with a single hole into the ocean.*";
P_HTM[4676]="*Tamenaṃ puratthimo vāto pacchimena saṃhareyya, pacchimo vāto puratthimena saṃhareyya, uttaro vāto dakkhiṇena saṃhareyya, dakkhiṇo vāto uttarena saṃhareyya.**The east wind wafts it west; the west wind wafts it east; the north wind wafts it south; and the south wind wafts it north.*";
P_HTM[4677]="*Tatrāssa kāṇo kacchapo, so vassasatassa vassasatassa accayena sakiṃ ummujjeyya.**And there was a one-eyed turtle who popped up once every hundred years.*";
P_HTM[4678]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[4679]="*api nu so kāṇo kacchapo amusmiṃ ekacchiggale yuge gīvaṃ paveseyyā”ti?**Would that one-eyed turtle still poke its neck through the hole in that yoke?”*";
P_HTM[4680]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[4681]="*“Yadi pana, bhante, kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayenā”ti.**Only after a very long time, sir, if ever.”*";
P_HTM[4682]="*“Khippataraṃ kho so, bhikkhave, kāṇo kacchapo amusmiṃ ekacchiggale yuge gīvaṃ paveseyya, ato dullabhatarāhaṃ, bhikkhave, manussattaṃ vadāmi sakiṃ vinipātagatena bālena.**“That one-eyed turtle would poke its neck through the hole in that yoke sooner than a fool who has fallen to the underworld would be reborn as a human being, I say.*";
P_HTM[4683]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[4684]="*Na hettha, bhikkhave, atthi dhammacariyā samacariyā kusalakiriyā puññakiriyā.**Because there there’s no principled or moral conduct, and no doing what is good and skillful.*";
P_HTM[4685]="*Aññamaññakhādikā ettha, bhikkhave, vattati dubbalakhādikā.**There they just prey on each other, preying on the weak.*";
P_HTM[4686]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, bālo sace kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena manussattaṃ āgacchati, yāni tāni nīcakulāni—**And suppose that fool, after a very long time, returned to the human realm.*";
P_HTM[4687]="*caṇḍālakulaṃ vā nesādakulaṃ vā venakulaṃ vā rathakārakulaṃ vā pukkusakulaṃ vā.**They’d be reborn in a low class family—a family of outcastes, hunters, bamboo-workers, chariot-makers, or waste-collectors.*";
P_HTM[4688]="*Tathārūpe kule paccājāyati dalidde appannapānabhojane kasiravuttike, yattha kasirena ghāsacchādo labbhati.**Such families are poor, with little to eat or drink, where life is tough, and food and shelter are hard to find.*";
P_HTM[4689]="*So ca hoti dubbaṇṇo duddasiko okoṭimako bavhābādho kāṇo vā kuṇī vā khujjo vā pakkhahato vā na lābhī annassa pānassa vatthassa yānassa mālāgandhavilepanassa seyyāvasathapadīpeyyassa.**And they’d be ugly, unsightly, deformed, chronically ill—one-eyed, crippled, lame, or half-paralyzed. They don’t get to have food, drink, clothes, and vehicles; garlands, perfumes, and makeup; or bed, house, and lighting.*";
P_HTM[4690]="*So kāyena duccaritaṃ carati vācāya duccaritaṃ carati manasā duccaritaṃ carati.**And they do bad things by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4691]="*So kāyena duccaritaṃ caritvā vācāya duccaritaṃ caritvā manasā duccaritaṃ caritvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[4692]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, akkhadhutto paṭhameneva kaliggahena puttampi jīyetha, dārampi jīyetha, sabbaṃ sāpateyyampi jīyetha, uttaripi adhibandhaṃ nigaccheyya.**Suppose a gambler on the first unlucky throw were to lose his wife and child, all his property, and then get thrown in jail.*";
P_HTM[4693]="*Appamattako so, bhikkhave, kaliggaho yaṃ so akkhadhutto paṭhameneva kaliggahena puttampi jīyetha, dārampi jīyetha, sabbaṃ sāpateyyampi jīyetha, uttaripi adhibandhaṃ nigaccheyya.**But such an unlucky throw is trivial compared to*";
P_HTM[4694]="*Atha kho ayameva tato mahantataro kaliggaho yaṃ so bālo kāyena duccaritaṃ caritvā vācāya duccaritaṃ caritvā manasā duccaritaṃ caritvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**the unlucky throw whereby a fool, having done bad things by way of body, speech, and mind, when their body breaks up, after death, is reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[4695]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, kevalā paripūrā bālabhūmīti.**This is the total fulfillment of the fool’s level.*";
P_HTM[4696]="*Tīṇimāni, bhikkhave, paṇḍitassa paṇḍitalakkhaṇāni paṇḍitanimittāni paṇḍitāpadānāni.**There are these three characteristics, signs, and manifestations of an astute person.*";
P_HTM[4697]="*Katamāni tīṇi?**What three?*";
P_HTM[4698]="*Idha, bhikkhave, paṇḍito sucintitacintī ca hoti subhāsitabhāsī ca sukatakammakārī ca.**An astute person thinks well, speaks well, and acts well.*";
P_HTM[4699]="*No cetaṃ, bhikkhave, paṇḍito sucintitacintī ca abhavissa subhāsitabhāsī ca sukatakammakārī ca, kena naṃ paṇḍitā jāneyyuṃ:**If an astute person didn’t think well, speak well, and act well, then how would the astute know of them,*";
P_HTM[4700]="*‘paṇḍito ayaṃ bhavaṃ sappuriso’ti?**‘This fellow is astute, a good person’?*";
P_HTM[4701]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, paṇḍito sucintitacintī ca hoti subhāsitabhāsī ca sukatakammakārī ca tasmā naṃ paṇḍitā jānanti:**But since an astute person does think well, speak well, and act well, then the astute do know of them,*";
P_HTM[4702]="*‘paṇḍito ayaṃ bhavaṃ sappuriso’ti.**‘This fellow is astute, a good person’.*";
P_HTM[4703]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, paṇḍito tividhaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**An astute person experiences three kinds of pleasure and happiness in the present life.*";
P_HTM[4704]="*Sace, bhikkhave, paṇḍito sabhāyaṃ vā nisinno hoti, rathikāya vā nisinno hoti, siṅghāṭake vā nisinno hoti;**Suppose an astute person is sitting in a council hall, a street, or a crossroad,*";
P_HTM[4705]="*tatra ce jano tajjaṃ tassāruppaṃ kathaṃ manteti.**where people are discussing about what is proper and fitting.*";
P_HTM[4706]="*Sace, bhikkhave, paṇḍito pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti, adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti, kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato hoti, musāvādā paṭivirato hoti, surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā paṭivirato hoti;**And suppose that astute person is someone who refrains from killing living creatures, stealing, committing sexual misconduct, lying, and alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.*";
P_HTM[4707]="*tatra, bhikkhave, paṇḍitassa evaṃ hoti:**Then that astute person thinks,*";
P_HTM[4708]="*‘yaṃ kho jano tajjaṃ tassāruppaṃ kathaṃ manteti;**‘These people are discussing what is proper and fitting.*";
P_HTM[4709]="*saṃvijjanteva te dhammā mayi, ahañca tesu dhammesu sandissāmī’ti.**And those things are found in me and I am seen in them.’*";
P_HTM[4710]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṇḍito paṭhamaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**This is the first kind of pleasure and happiness that an astute person experiences in the present life.*";
P_HTM[4711]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, paṇḍito passati rājāno coraṃ āgucāriṃ gahetvā vividhā kammakāraṇā kārente—**Furthermore, an astute person sees that the kings have arrested a bandit, a criminal, and subjected them to various punishments—*";
P_HTM[4712]="*kasāhipi tāḷente vettehipi tāḷente addhadaṇḍakehipi tāḷente hatthampi chindante pādampi chindante hatthapādampi chindante kaṇṇampi chindante nāsampi chindante kaṇṇanāsampi chindante bilaṅgathālikampi karonte saṅkhamuṇḍikampi karonte rāhumukhampi karonte jotimālikampi karonte hatthapajjotikampi karonte erakavattikampi karonte cīrakavāsikampi karonte eṇeyyakampi karonte balisamaṃsikampi karonte kahāpaṇikampi karonte khārāpatacchikampi karonte palighaparivattikampi karonte palālapīṭhakampi karonte tattenapi telena osiñcante sunakhehipi khādāpente jīvantampi sūle uttāsente asināpi sīsaṃ chindante.**whipping, caning, and clubbing; cutting off hands or feet, or both; cutting off ears or nose, or both; the ‘porridge pot’, the ‘shell-shave’, the ‘demon’s mouth’, the ‘garland of fire’, the ‘burning hand’, the ‘grass blades’, the ‘bark dress’, the ‘antelope’, the ‘meat hook’, the ‘coins’, the ‘acid pickle’, the ‘twisting bar’, the ‘straw mat’; being splashed with hot oil, being fed to the dogs, being impaled alive, and being beheaded.*";
P_HTM[4713]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, paṇḍitassa evaṃ hoti:**Then that astute person thinks,*";
P_HTM[4714]="*‘yathārūpānaṃ kho pāpakānaṃ kammānaṃ hetu rājāno coraṃ āgucāriṃ gahetvā vividhā kammakāraṇā kārenti kasāhipi tāḷenti, vettehipi tāḷenti, addhadaṇḍakehipi tāḷenti, hatthampi chindanti, pādampi chindanti, hatthapādampi chindanti, kaṇṇampi chindanti, nāsampi chindanti, kaṇṇanāsampi chindanti, bilaṅgathālikampi karonti, saṅkhamuṇḍikampi karonti, rāhumukhampi karonti, jotimālikampi karonti, hatthapajjotikampi karonti, erakavattikampi karonti, cīrakavāsikampi karonti, eṇeyyakampi karonti, balisamaṃsikampi karonti, kahāpaṇikampi karonti, khārāpatacchikampi karonti, palighaparivattikampi karonti, palālapīṭhakampi karonti, tattenapi telena osiñcanti, sunakhehipi khādāpenti, jīvantampi sūle uttāsenti, asināpi sīsaṃ chindanti, na te dhammā mayi saṃvijjanti, ahañca na tesu dhammesu sandissāmī’ti.**‘The kinds of deeds for which the kings inflict such punishments—those things are not found in me and I am not seen in them!’*";
P_HTM[4715]="*Idampi, bhikkhave, paṇḍito dutiyaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**This is the second kind of pleasure and happiness that an astute person experiences in the present life.*";
P_HTM[4716]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, paṇḍitaṃ pīṭhasamārūḷhaṃ vā mañcasamārūḷhaṃ vā chamāyaṃ vā semānaṃ, yānissa pubbe kalyāṇāni kammāni katāni kāyena sucaritāni vācāya sucaritāni manasā sucaritāni tānissa tamhi samaye olambanti … pe …**Furthermore, when an astute person is resting on a chair or a bed or on the ground, their past good deeds—good conduct of body, speech, and mind—settle down upon them, rest down upon them, and lay down upon them.*";
P_HTM[4717]="*seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, mahataṃ pabbatakūṭānaṃ chāyā sāyanhasamayaṃ pathaviyā olambanti ajjholambanti abhippalambanti;**It is like the shadow of a great mountain peak in the evening as it settles down, rests down, and lays down upon the earth.*";
P_HTM[4718]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, paṇḍitaṃ pīṭhasamārūḷhaṃ vā mañcasamārūḷhaṃ vā chamāyaṃ vā semānaṃ yānissa pubbe kalyāṇāni kammāni katāni kāyena sucaritāni vācāya sucaritāni manasā sucaritāni tānissa tamhi samaye olambanti ajjholambanti abhippalambanti.**In the same way, when an astute person is resting on a chair or a bed or on the ground, their past good deeds—good conduct of body, speech, and mind—settle down upon them, rest down upon them, and lay down upon them.*";
P_HTM[4719]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, paṇḍitassa evaṃ hoti:**Then that astute person thinks,*";
P_HTM[4720]="*‘akataṃ vata me pāpaṃ, akataṃ luddaṃ, akataṃ kibbisaṃ;**‘Well, I haven’t done bad, violent, and corrupt things.*";
P_HTM[4721]="*kataṃ kalyāṇaṃ, kataṃ kusalaṃ, kataṃ bhīruttāṇaṃ.**And I have done good and skillful deeds that keep me safe.*";
P_HTM[4722]="*Yāvatā, bho, akatapāpānaṃ akataluddānaṃ akatakibbisānaṃ katakalyāṇānaṃ katakusalānaṃ katabhīruttāṇānaṃ gati taṃ gatiṃ pecca gacchāmī’ti.**When I pass away, I’ll go to the place where people who’ve done such things go.’*";
P_HTM[4723]="*So na socati, na kilamati, na paridevati, na urattāḷiṃ kandati, na sammohaṃ āpajjati.**So they don’t sorrow and pine and lament, beating their breast and falling into confusion.*";
P_HTM[4724]="*Idampi, bhikkhave, paṇḍito tatiyaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**This is the third kind of pleasure and happiness that an astute person experiences in the present life.*";
P_HTM[4725]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, paṇḍito kāyena sucaritaṃ caritvā vācāya sucaritaṃ caritvā manasā sucaritaṃ caritvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[4726]="*Yaṃ kho taṃ, bhikkhave, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**And if there’s anything of which it may be rightly said that*";
P_HTM[4727]="*‘ekantaṃ iṭṭhaṃ ekantaṃ kantaṃ ekantaṃ manāpan’ti, saggameva taṃ sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**it is utterly likable, desirable, and agreeable, it is of heaven that this should be said.*";
P_HTM[4728]="*‘ekantaṃ iṭṭhaṃ ekantaṃ kantaṃ ekantaṃ manāpan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4729]="*Yāvañcidaṃ, bhikkhave, upamāpi na sukarā yāva sukhā saggā”ti.**So much so that it’s not easy to give a simile for how pleasurable heaven is.”*";
P_HTM[4730]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, one of the mendicants asked the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[4731]="*“sakkā pana, bhante, upamaṃ kātun”ti?**“But sir, is it possible to give a simile?”*";
P_HTM[4732]="*“Sakkā, bhikkhū”ti bhagavā avoca.**“It’s possible,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4733]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī sattahi ratanehi samannāgato catūhi ca iddhīhi tatonidānaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**“Suppose there was a king, a wheel-turning monarch who possessed seven treasures and four blessings, and experienced pleasure and happiness because of them.*";
P_HTM[4734]="*Katamehi sattahi?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[4735]="*Idha, bhikkhave, rañño khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa tadahuposathe pannarase sīsaṃnhātassa uposathikassa uparipāsādavaragatassa dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ pātubhavati sahassāraṃ sanemikaṃ sanābhikaṃ sabbākāraparipūraṃ.**It’s when, on the fifteenth day sabbath, an anointed aristocratic king has bathed his head and gone upstairs in the stilt longhouse to observe the sabbath. And the heavenly wheel-treasure appears to him, with a thousand spokes, with rim and hub, complete in every detail.*";
P_HTM[4736]="*Taṃ disvāna rañño khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa evaṃ hoti:**Seeing this, the king thinks,*";
P_HTM[4737]="*‘sutaṃ kho pana metaṃ yassa rañño khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa tadahuposathe pannarase sīsaṃnhātassa uposathikassa uparipāsādavaragatassa dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ pātubhavati sahassāraṃ sanemikaṃ sanābhikaṃ sabbākāraparipūraṃ, so hoti rājā cakkavattīti.**‘I have heard that when the heavenly wheel-treasure appears to a king in this way, he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4738]="*Assaṃ nu kho ahaṃ rājā cakkavattī’ti?**Am I then a wheel-turning monarch?’*";
P_HTM[4739]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhāvasitto vāmena hatthena bhiṅkāraṃ gahetvā dakkhiṇena hatthena cakkaratanaṃ abbhukkirati:**Then the anointed king, taking a ceremonial vase in his left hand, besprinkled the wheel-treasure with his right hand, saying,*";
P_HTM[4740]="*‘pavattatu bhavaṃ cakkaratanaṃ, abhivijinātu bhavaṃ cakkaratanan’ti.**‘Roll forth, O wheel-treasure! Triumph, O wheel-treasure!’*";
P_HTM[4741]="*Atha kho taṃ, bhikkhave, cakkaratanaṃ puratthimaṃ disaṃ pavattati. Anvadeva rājā cakkavattī saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya. Yasmiṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, padese cakkaratanaṃ patiṭṭhāti tattha rājā cakkavattī vāsaṃ upeti saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya.**Then the wheel-treasure rolls towards the east. And the king follows it together with his army of four divisions. In whatever place the wheel-treasure stands still, there the king comes to stay together with his army.*";
P_HTM[4742]="*Ye kho pana, bhikkhave, puratthimāya disāya paṭirājāno te rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:**And any opposing rulers of the eastern quarter come to the wheel-turning monarch and say,*";
P_HTM[4743]="*‘ehi kho, mahārāja. Svāgataṃ te, mahārāja. Sakaṃ te, mahārāja. Anusāsa, mahārājā’ti.**‘Come, great king! Welcome, great king! We are yours, great king, instruct us.’*";
P_HTM[4744]="*Rājā cakkavattī evamāha:**The wheel-turning monarch says,*";
P_HTM[4745]="*‘pāṇo na hantabbo, adinnaṃ nādātabbaṃ, kāmesumicchā na caritabbā, musā na bhāsitabbā, majjaṃ na pātabbaṃ, yathābhuttañca bhuñjathā’ti.**‘Do not kill living creatures. Do not steal. Do not commit sexual misconduct. Do not lie. Do not drink alcohol. Maintain the current level of taxation.’*";
P_HTM[4746]="*Ye kho pana, bhikkhave, puratthimāya disāya paṭirājāno te rañño cakkavattissa anuyantā bhavanti.**And so the opposing rulers of the eastern quarter become his vassals.*";
P_HTM[4747]="*Atha kho taṃ, bhikkhave, cakkaratanaṃ puratthimaṃ samuddaṃ ajjhogāhetvā paccuttaritvā dakkhiṇaṃ disaṃ pavattati … pe …**Then the wheel-treasure, having plunged into the eastern ocean and emerged again, rolls towards the south. …*";
P_HTM[4748]="*dakkhiṇaṃ samuddaṃ ajjhogāhetvā paccuttaritvā pacchimaṃ disaṃ pavattati … pe …**Having plunged into the southern ocean and emerged again, it rolls towards the west. …*";
P_HTM[4749]="*pacchimaṃ samuddaṃ ajjhogāhetvā paccuttaritvā uttaraṃ disaṃ pavattati anvadeva rājā cakkavattī saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya. Yasmiṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, padese cakkaratanaṃ patiṭṭhāti tattha rājā cakkavattī vāsaṃ upeti saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya.**Having plunged into the western ocean and emerged again, it rolls towards the north, followed by the king together with his army of four divisions. In whatever place the wheel-treasure stands still, there the king comes to stay together with his army.*";
P_HTM[4750]="*Ye kho pana, bhikkhave, uttarāya disāya paṭirājāno te rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:**And any opposing rulers of the northern quarter come to the wheel-turning monarch and say,*";
P_HTM[4751]="*‘ehi kho, mahārāja. Svāgataṃ te, mahārāja. Sakaṃ te, mahārāja. Anusāsa, mahārājā’ti.**‘Come, great king! Welcome, great king! We are yours, great king, instruct us.’*";
P_HTM[4752]="*Rājā cakkavattī evamāha:**The wheel-turning monarch says,*";
P_HTM[4753]="*‘pāṇo na hantabbo, adinnaṃ nādātabbaṃ, kāmesumicchā na caritabbā, musā na bhāsitabbā, majjaṃ na pātabbaṃ; yathābhuttañca bhuñjathā’ti.**‘Do not kill living creatures. Do not steal. Do not commit sexual misconduct. Do not lie. Do not drink alcohol. Maintain the current level of taxation.’*";
P_HTM[4754]="*Ye kho pana, bhikkhave, uttarāya disāya paṭirājāno te rañño cakkavattissa anuyantā bhavanti.**And so the rulers of the northern quarter become his vassals.*";
P_HTM[4755]="*Atha kho taṃ, bhikkhave, cakkaratanaṃ samuddapariyantaṃ pathaviṃ abhivijinitvā tameva rājadhāniṃ paccāgantvā rañño cakkavattissa antepuradvāre akkhāhataṃ maññe tiṭṭhati rañño cakkavattissa antepuradvāraṃ upasobhayamānaṃ.**And then the wheel-treasure, having triumphed over this land surrounded by ocean, returns to the royal capital. There it stands still at the gate to the royal compound as if fixed to an axle, illuminating the royal compound.*";
P_HTM[4756]="*Rañño, bhikkhave, cakkavattissa evarūpaṃ cakkaratanaṃ pātubhavati. (1)**Such is the wheel-treasure that appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4757]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rañño cakkavattissa hatthiratanaṃ pātubhavati—**Next, the elephant-treasure appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4758]="*sabbaseto sattappatiṭṭho iddhimā vehāsaṅgamo uposatho nāma nāgarājā.**It was an all-white sky-walker with psychic power, touching the ground in seven places, a king of elephants named Sabbath.*";
P_HTM[4759]="*Taṃ disvāna rañño cakkavattissa cittaṃ pasīdati:**Seeing him, the king was impressed,*";
P_HTM[4760]="*‘bhaddakaṃ vata bho hatthiyānaṃ, sace damathaṃ upeyyā’ti.**‘This would truly be a fine elephant vehicle, if he would submit to taming.’*";
P_HTM[4761]="*Atha kho taṃ, bhikkhave, hatthiratanaṃ seyyathāpi nāma bhaddo hatthājānīyo dīgharattaṃ suparidanto evameva damathaṃ upeti.**Then the elephant-treasure submitted to taming, as if he were a fine thoroughbred elephant that had been tamed for a long time.*";
P_HTM[4762]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī tameva hatthiratanaṃ vīmaṃsamāno pubbaṇhasamayaṃ abhiruhitvā samuddapariyantaṃ pathaviṃ anusaṃyāyitvā tameva rājadhāniṃ paccāgantvā pātarāsamakāsi.**Once it so happened that the wheel-turning monarch, testing that same elephant-treasure, mounted him in the morning and traversed the land surrounded by ocean before returning to the royal capital in time for breakfast.*";
P_HTM[4763]="*Rañño, bhikkhave, cakkavattissa evarūpaṃ hatthiratanaṃ pātubhavati. (2)**Such is the elephant-treasure that appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4764]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rañño cakkavattissa assaratanaṃ pātubhavati—**Next, the horse-treasure appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4765]="*sabbaseto kāḷasīso muñjakeso iddhimā vehāsaṅgamo valāhako nāma assarājā.**It was an all-white sky-walker with psychic power, with head of black and mane like woven reeds, a royal steed named Thundercloud.*";
P_HTM[4766]="*Taṃ disvāna rañño cakkavattissa cittaṃ pasīdati:**Seeing him, the king was impressed,*";
P_HTM[4767]="*‘bhaddakaṃ vata bho assayānaṃ, sace damathaṃ upeyyā’ti.**‘This would truly be a fine horse vehicle, if he would submit to taming.’*";
P_HTM[4768]="*Atha kho taṃ, bhikkhave, assaratanaṃ seyyathāpi nāma bhaddo assājānīyo dīgharattaṃ suparidanto evameva damathaṃ upeti.**Then the horse-treasure submitted to taming, as if he were a fine thoroughbred horse that had been tamed for a long time.*";
P_HTM[4769]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī tameva assaratanaṃ vīmaṃsamāno pubbaṇhasamayaṃ abhiruhitvā samuddapariyantaṃ pathaviṃ anusaṃyāyitvā tameva rājadhāniṃ paccāgantvā pātarāsamakāsi.**Once it so happened that the wheel-turning monarch, testing that same horse-treasure, mounted him in the morning and traversed the land surrounded by ocean before returning to the royal capital in time for breakfast.*";
P_HTM[4770]="*Rañño, bhikkhave, cakkavattissa evarūpaṃ assaratanaṃ pātubhavati. (3)**Such is the horse-treasure that appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4771]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rañño cakkavattissa maṇiratanaṃ pātubhavati.**Next, the jewel-treasure appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4772]="*So hoti maṇi veḷuriyo subho jātimā aṭṭhaṃso suparikammakato.**It is a beryl gem that’s naturally beautiful, eight-faceted, well-worked.*";
P_HTM[4773]="*Tassa kho pana, bhikkhave, maṇiratanassa ābhā samantā yojanaṃ phuṭā hoti.**And the radiance of that jewel spreads all-round for a league.*";
P_HTM[4774]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī tameva maṇiratanaṃ vīmaṃsamāno caturaṅginiṃ senaṃ sannayhitvā maṇiṃ dhajaggaṃ āropetvā rattandhakāratimisāya pāyāsi.**Once it so happened that the wheel-turning monarch, testing that same jewel-treasure, mobilized his army of four divisions and, with the jewel hoisted on his banner, set out in the dark of the night.*";
P_HTM[4775]="*Ye kho pana, bhikkhave, samantā gāmā ahesuṃ te tenobhāsena kammante payojesuṃ ‘divā’ti maññamānā.**Then the villagers around them set off to work, thinking that it was day.*";
P_HTM[4776]="*Rañño, bhikkhave, cakkavattissa evarūpaṃ maṇiratanaṃ pātubhavati. (4)**Such is the jewel-treasure that appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4777]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rañño cakkavattissa itthiratanaṃ pātubhavati.**Next, the woman-treasure appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4778]="*Sā abhirūpā dassanīyā pāsādikā paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgatā nātidīghā nātirassā nātikisā nātithūlā nātikāḷikā nāccodātā, atikkantā mānusaṃ vaṇṇaṃ, appattā dibbaṃ vaṇṇaṃ.**She is attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty. She’s neither too tall nor too short; neither too thin nor too fat; neither too dark nor too light. She outdoes human beauty without reaching divine beauty.*";
P_HTM[4779]="*Tassa kho pana, bhikkhave, itthiratanassa evarūpo kāyasamphasso hoti, seyyathāpi nāma tūlapicuno vā kappāsapicuno vā.**And her touch is like a tuft of cotton-wool or kapok.*";
P_HTM[4780]="*Tassa kho pana, bhikkhave, itthiratanassa sīte uṇhāni gattāni honti, uṇhe sītāni gattāni honti.**When it’s cool her limbs are warm, and when it’s warm her limbs are cool.*";
P_HTM[4781]="*Tassa kho pana, bhikkhave, itthiratanassa kāyato candanagandho vāyati, mukhato uppalagandho vāyati.**The fragrance of sandal floats from her body, and lotus from her mouth.*";
P_HTM[4782]="*Taṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, itthiratanaṃ rañño cakkavattissa pubbuṭṭhāyinī hoti pacchānipātinī kiṃkārapaṭissāvinī manāpacārinī piyavādinī.**She gets up before the king and goes to bed after him, and is obliging, behaving nicely and speaking politely.*";
P_HTM[4783]="*Taṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, itthiratanaṃ rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ manasāpi no aticarati, kuto pana kāyena?**The woman-treasure does not betray the wheel-turning monarch even in thought, still less in deed.*";
P_HTM[4784]="*Rañño, bhikkhave, cakkavattissa evarūpaṃ itthiratanaṃ pātubhavati. (5)**Such is the woman-treasure who appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4785]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rañño cakkavattissa gahapatiratanaṃ pātubhavati.**Next, the householder-treasure appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4786]="*Tassa kammavipākajaṃ dibbacakkhu pātubhavati, yena nidhiṃ passati sassāmikampi assāmikampi.**The power of clairvoyance manifests in him as a result of past deeds, by which he sees hidden treasure, both owned and ownerless.*";
P_HTM[4787]="*So rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāha:**He approaches the wheel-turning monarch and says,*";
P_HTM[4788]="*‘appossukko tvaṃ, deva, hohi. Ahaṃ te dhanena dhanakaraṇīyaṃ karissāmī’ti.**‘Relax, sire. I will take care of the treasury.’*";
P_HTM[4789]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī tameva gahapatiratanaṃ vīmaṃsamāno nāvaṃ abhiruhitvā majjhe gaṅgāya nadiyā sotaṃ ogāhitvā gahapatiratanaṃ etadavoca:**Once it so happened that the wheel-turning monarch, testing that same householder-treasure, boarded a boat and sailed to the middle of the Ganges river. Then he said to the householder-treasure,*";
P_HTM[4790]="*‘attho me, gahapati, hiraññasuvaṇṇenā’ti.**‘Householder, I need gold coins and bullion.’*";
P_HTM[4791]="*‘Tena hi, mahārāja, ekaṃ tīraṃ nāvā upetū’ti.**‘Well then, great king, draw the boat up to one shore.’*";
P_HTM[4792]="*‘Idheva me, gahapati, attho hiraññasuvaṇṇenā’ti.**‘It’s right here, householder, that I need gold coins and bullion.’*";
P_HTM[4793]="*Atha kho taṃ, bhikkhave, gahapatiratanaṃ ubhohi hatthehi udake omasitvā pūraṃ hiraññasuvaṇṇassa kumbhiṃ uddharitvā rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ etadavoca:**Then that householder-treasure, immersing both hands in the water, pulled up a pot full of gold coin and bullion, and said to the king,*";
P_HTM[4794]="*‘alamettāvatā, mahārāja. Katamettāvatā, mahārāja. Pūjitamettāvatā, mahārājā’ti.**‘Is this sufficient, great king? Has enough been done, great king, enough offered?’*";
P_HTM[4795]="*Rājā cakkavattī evamāha:**The wheel-turning monarch said,*";
P_HTM[4796]="*‘alamettāvatā, gahapati. Katamettāvatā, gahapati. Pūjitamettāvatā, gahapatī’ti.**‘That is sufficient, householder. Enough has been done, enough offered.’*";
P_HTM[4797]="*Rañño, bhikkhave, cakkavattissa evarūpaṃ gahapatiratanaṃ pātubhavati. (6)**Such is the householder-treasure that appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4798]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rañño cakkavattissa pariṇāyakaratanaṃ pātubhavati—**Next, the counselor-treasure appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4799]="*paṇḍito byatto medhāvī paṭibalo rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ upayāpetabbaṃ upayāpetuṃ apayāpetabbaṃ apayāpetuṃ ṭhapetabbaṃ ṭhapetuṃ.**He is astute, competent, intelligent, and capable of getting the king to appoint who should be appointed, dismiss who should be dismissed, and retain who should be retained.*";
P_HTM[4800]="*So rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāha:**He approaches the wheel-turning monarch and says,*";
P_HTM[4801]="*‘appossukko tvaṃ, deva, hohi. Ahamanusāsissāmī’ti.**‘Relax, sire. I shall issue instructions.’*";
P_HTM[4802]="*Rañño, bhikkhave, cakkavattissa evarūpaṃ pariṇāyakaratanaṃ pātubhavati.**Such is the counselor-treasure that appears to the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4803]="*Rājā, bhikkhave, cakkavattī imehi sattahi ratanehi samannāgato hoti. (7)**These are the seven treasures possessed by a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4804]="*Katamāhi catūhi iddhīhi?**And what are the four blessings?*";
P_HTM[4805]="*Idha, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī abhirūpo hoti dassanīyo pāsādiko paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgato ativiya aññehi manussehi.**A wheel-turning monarch is attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty, more so than other people.*";
P_HTM[4806]="*Rājā, bhikkhave, cakkavattī imāya paṭhamāya iddhiyā samannāgato hoti.**This is the first blessing.*";
P_HTM[4807]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī dīghāyuko hoti ciraṭṭhitiko ativiya aññehi manussehi.**Furthermore, he is long-lived, more so than other people.*";
P_HTM[4808]="*Rājā, bhikkhave, cakkavattī imāya dutiyāya iddhiyā samannāgato hoti.**This is the second blessing.*";
P_HTM[4809]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī appābādho hoti appātaṅko samavepākiniyā gahaṇiyā samannāgato nātisītāya nāccuṇhāya ativiya aññehi manussehi.**Furthermore, he is rarely ill or unwell, and his stomach digests well, being neither too hot nor too cold, more so than other people.*";
P_HTM[4810]="*Rājā, bhikkhave, cakkavattī imāya tatiyāya iddhiyā samannāgato hoti.**This is the third blessing.*";
P_HTM[4811]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī brāhmaṇagahapatikānaṃ piyo hoti manāpo.**Furthermore, a wheel-turning monarch is as dear and beloved to the brahmins and householders*";
P_HTM[4812]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, pitā puttānaṃ piyo hoti manāpo;**as a father is to his children.*";
P_HTM[4813]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī brāhmaṇagahapatikānaṃ piyo hoti manāpo.* **";
P_HTM[4814]="*Raññopi, bhikkhave, cakkavattissa brāhmaṇagahapatikā piyā honti manāpā.**And the brahmins and householders are as dear to the wheel-turning monarch*";
P_HTM[4815]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, pitu puttā piyā honti manāpā;**as children are to their father.*";
P_HTM[4816]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, raññopi cakkavattissa brāhmaṇagahapatikā piyā honti manāpā.* **";
P_HTM[4817]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī caturaṅginiyā senāya uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyāsi.**Once it so happened that a wheel-turning monarch went with his army of four divisions to visit a park.*";
P_HTM[4818]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, brāhmaṇagahapatikā rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:**Then the brahmins and householders went up to him and said,*";
P_HTM[4819]="*‘ataramāno, deva, yāhi yathā taṃ mayaṃ cirataraṃ passeyyāmā’ti.**‘Slow down, Your Majesty, so we may see you longer!’*";
P_HTM[4820]="*Rājāpi, bhikkhave, cakkavattī sārathiṃ āmantesi:**And the king addressed his charioteer,*";
P_HTM[4821]="*‘ataramāno, sārathi, pesehi yathā maṃ brāhmaṇagahapatikā cirataraṃ passeyyun’ti.**‘Drive slowly, charioteer, so I can see the brahmins and householders longer!’*";
P_HTM[4822]="*Rājā, bhikkhave, cakkavattī imāya catutthāya iddhiyā samannāgato hoti.**This is the fourth blessing.*";
P_HTM[4823]="*Rājā, bhikkhave, cakkavattī imāhi catūhi iddhīhi samannāgato hoti.**These are the four blessings possessed by a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[4824]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[4825]="*api nu kho rājā cakkavattī imehi sattahi ratanehi samannāgato imāhi catūhi ca iddhīhi tatonidānaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvediyethā”ti?**Would a wheel-turning monarch who possessed these seven treasures and these four blessings experience pleasure and happiness because of them?”*";
P_HTM[4826]="*“Ekamekenapi, bhante, ratanena samannāgato rājā cakkavattī tatonidānaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvediyetha, ko pana vādo sattahi ratanehi catūhi ca iddhīhī”ti?**“Sir, a wheel-turning monarch who possessed even a single one of these treasures would experience pleasure and happiness because of that, let alone all seven treasures and four blessings!”*";
P_HTM[4827]="*Atha kho bhagavā parittaṃ pāṇimattaṃ pāsāṇaṃ gahetvā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha, picking up a stone the size of his palm, addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[4828]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**“What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[4829]="*katamo nu kho mahantataro—yo cāyaṃ mayā paritto pāṇimatto pāsāṇo gahito yo ca himavā pabbatarājā”ti?**Which is bigger: the stone the size of my palm that I’ve picked up, or the Himalayas, the king of mountains?”*";
P_HTM[4830]="*“Appamattako ayaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā paritto pāṇimatto pāsāṇo gahito; himavantaṃ pabbatarājānaṃ upanidhāya saṅkhampi na upeti; kalabhāgampi na upeti; upanidhampi na upetī”ti.**“Sir, the stone you’ve picked up is tiny. Compared to the Himalayas, it doesn’t even count, it’s not even a fraction, there’s no comparison.”*";
P_HTM[4831]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yaṃ rājā cakkavattī sattahi ratanehi samannāgato catūhi ca iddhīhi tatonidānaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti taṃ dibbassa sukhassa upanidhāya saṅkhampi na upeti; kalabhāgampi na upeti; upanidhampi na upeti.**“In the same way, compared to the happiness of heaven, the pleasure and happiness experienced by a wheel-turning monarch due to those seven treasures and those four blessings doesn’t even count, it’s not even a fraction, there’s no comparison.*";
P_HTM[4832]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, paṇḍito sace kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena manussattaṃ āgacchati, yāni tāni uccākulāni—**And suppose that astute person, after a very long time, returned to the human realm.*";
P_HTM[4833]="*khattiyamahāsālakulaṃ vā brāhmaṇamahāsālakulaṃ vā gahapatimahāsālakulaṃ vā tathārūpe kule paccājāyati aḍḍhe mahaddhane mahābhoge pahūtajātarūparajate pahūtavittūpakaraṇe pahūtadhanadhaññe.**They’d be reborn in a well-to-do family of aristocrats, brahmins, or householders—rich, affluent, and wealthy, with lots of gold and silver, lots of property and assets, and lots of money and grain.*";
P_HTM[4834]="*So ca hoti abhirūpo dassanīyo pāsādiko paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgato, lābhī annassa pānassa vatthassa yānassa mālāgandhavilepanassa seyyāvasathapadīpeyyassa.**And they’d be attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty. They’d get to have food, drink, clothes, and vehicles; garlands, perfumes, and makeup; and a bed, house, and lighting.*";
P_HTM[4835]="*So kāyena sucaritaṃ carati, vācāya sucaritaṃ carati, manasā sucaritaṃ carati.**And they do good things by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4836]="*So kāyena sucaritaṃ caritvā, vācāya sucaritaṃ caritvā, manasā sucaritaṃ caritvā, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[4837]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, akkhadhutto paṭhameneva kaṭaggahena mahantaṃ bhogakkhandhaṃ adhigaccheyya;**Suppose a gambler on the first lucky throw was to win a big pile of money.*";
P_HTM[4838]="*appamattako so, bhikkhave, kaṭaggaho yaṃ so akkhadhutto paṭhameneva kaṭaggahena mahantaṃ bhogakkhandhaṃ adhigaccheyya.**But such a lucky throw is trivial compared to*";
P_HTM[4839]="*Atha kho ayameva tato mahantataro kaṭaggaho yaṃ so paṇḍito kāyena sucaritaṃ caritvā, vācāya sucaritaṃ caritvā, manasā sucaritaṃ caritvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**the lucky throw whereby an astute person, when their body breaks up, after death, is reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[4840]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, kevalā paripūrā paṇḍitabhūmī”ti.**This is the total fulfillment of the astute person’s level.”*";
P_HTM[4841]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[4842]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[4843]="*Bālapaṇḍitasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4844]="*130. Devadūtasutta**Messengers of the Gods*";
P_HTM[4845]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[4846]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[4847]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[4848]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[4849]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[4850]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[4851]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, dve agārā sadvārā, tattha cakkhumā puriso majjhe ṭhito passeyya manusse gehaṃ pavisantepi nikkhamantepi anucaṅkamantepi anuvicarantepi;**“Mendicants, suppose there were two houses with doors. A person with good eyesight standing in between them would see people entering and leaving a house and wandering to and fro.*";
P_HTM[4852]="*evameva kho ahaṃ, bhikkhave, dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passāmi cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe, sugate duggate yathākammūpage satte pajānāmi: ‘ime vata bhonto sattā kāyasucaritena samannāgatā vacīsucaritena samannāgatā manosucaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ anupavādakā sammādiṭṭhikā sammādiṭṭhikammasamādānā; te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannā. Ime vā pana bhonto sattā kāyasucaritena samannāgatā vacīsucaritena samannāgatā manosucaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ anupavādakā sammādiṭṭhikā sammādiṭṭhikammasamādānā; te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā manussesu upapannā. Ime vata bhonto sattā kāyaduccaritena samannāgatā vacīduccaritena samannāgatā manoduccaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ upavādakā micchādiṭṭhikā micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānā; te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā pettivisayaṃ upapannā. Ime vā pana bhonto sattā kāyaduccaritena samannāgatā vacīduccaritena samannāgatā manoduccaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ upavādakā micchādiṭṭhikā micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānā; te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā tiracchānayoniṃ upapannā. Ime vā pana bhonto sattā kāyaduccaritena samannāgatā vacīduccaritena samannāgatā manoduccaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ upavādakā micchādiṭṭhikā micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānā; te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannā’ti.**In the same way, with clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, I see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. I understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds: ‘These dear beings did good things by way of body, speech, and mind. They never spoke ill of the noble ones; they had right view; and they chose to act out of that right view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm, or among humans. These dear beings did bad things by way of body, speech, and mind. They spoke ill of the noble ones; they had wrong view; and they chose to act out of that wrong view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in the ghost realm, the animal realm, or in a lower realm, a bad destination, a world of misery, hell.’*";
P_HTM[4853]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā nānābāhāsu gahetvā yamassa rañño dassenti:**Then the wardens of hell take them by the arms and present them to King Yama, saying,*";
P_HTM[4854]="*‘ayaṃ, deva, puriso amatteyyo apetteyyo asāmañño abrāhmañño, na kule jeṭṭhāpacāyī.**‘Your Majesty, this person did not pay due respect to their mother and father, ascetics and brahmins, or honor the elders in the family.*";
P_HTM[4855]="*Imassa devo daṇḍaṃ paṇetū’ti.**May Your Majesty punish them!’*";
P_HTM[4856]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā paṭhamaṃ devadūtaṃ samanuyuñjati samanugāhati samanubhāsati:**Then King Yama pursues, presses, and grills them about the first messenger of the gods.*";
P_HTM[4857]="*‘ambho purisa, na tvaṃ addasa manussesu paṭhamaṃ devadūtaṃ pātubhūtan’ti?**‘Mister, did you not see the first messenger of the gods that appeared among human beings?’*";
P_HTM[4858]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4859]="*‘nāddasaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I saw nothing, sir.’*";
P_HTM[4860]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4861]="*‘ambho purisa, na tvaṃ addasa manussesu daharaṃ kumāraṃ mandaṃ uttānaseyyakaṃ sake muttakarīse palipannaṃ semānan’ti?**‘Mister, did you not see among human beings a little baby collapsed in their own urine and feces?’*";
P_HTM[4862]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4863]="*‘addasaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I saw that, sir.’*";
P_HTM[4864]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4865]="*‘ambho purisa, tassa te viññussa sato mahallakassa na etadahosi—**‘Mister, did it not occur to you—being sensible and mature—*";
P_HTM[4866]="*ahampi khomhi jātidhammo, jātiṃ anatīto. Handāhaṃ kalyāṇaṃ karomi kāyena vācāya manasā’ti?**“I, too, am liable to be born. I’m not exempt from rebirth. I’d better do good by way of body, speech, and mind”?’*";
P_HTM[4867]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4868]="*‘nāsakkhissaṃ, bhante, pamādassaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I couldn’t, sir. I was negligent.’*";
P_HTM[4869]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4870]="*‘ambho purisa, pamādavatāya na kalyāṇamakāsi kāyena vācāya manasā.**‘Mister, because you were negligent, you didn’t do good by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4871]="*Taggha tvaṃ, ambho purisa, tathā karissanti yathā taṃ pamattaṃ.**Well, they’ll definitely punish you to fit your negligence.*";
P_HTM[4872]="*Taṃ kho pana te etaṃ pāpakammaṃ neva mātarā kataṃ na pitarā kataṃ na bhātarā kataṃ na bhaginiyā kataṃ na mittāmaccehi kataṃ na ñātisālohitehi kataṃ na samaṇabrāhmaṇehi kataṃ na devatāhi kataṃ, tayāvetaṃ pāpakammaṃ kataṃ, tvaññevetassa vipākaṃ paṭisaṃvedissasī’ti. (1)**That bad deed wasn’t done by your mother, father, brother, or sister. It wasn’t done by friends and colleagues, by relatives and kin, by ascetics and brahmins, or by the deities. That bad deed was done by you alone, and you alone will experience the result.’*";
P_HTM[4873]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā paṭhamaṃ devadūtaṃ samanuyuñjitvā samanugāhitvā samanubhāsitvā dutiyaṃ devadūtaṃ samanuyuñjati samanugāhati samanubhāsati:**Then King Yama grills them about the second messenger of the gods.*";
P_HTM[4874]="*‘ambho purisa, na tvaṃ addasa manussesu dutiyaṃ devadūtaṃ pātubhūtan’ti?**‘Mister, did you not see the second messenger of the gods that appeared among human beings?’*";
P_HTM[4875]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4876]="*‘nāddasaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I saw nothing, sir.’*";
P_HTM[4877]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4878]="*‘ambho purisa, na tvaṃ addasa manussesu itthiṃ vā purisaṃ vā () jiṇṇaṃ gopānasivaṅkaṃ bhoggaṃ daṇḍaparāyanaṃ pavedhamānaṃ gacchantaṃ āturaṃ gatayobbanaṃ khaṇḍadantaṃ palitakesaṃ vilūnaṃ khalitasiraṃ valinaṃ tilakāhatagattan’ti?**‘Mister, did you not see among human beings an elderly woman or a man—eighty, ninety, or a hundred years old—bent double, crooked, leaning on a staff, trembling as they walk, ailing, past their prime, with teeth broken, hair grey and scanty or bald, skin wrinkled, and limbs blotchy?’*";
P_HTM[4879]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4880]="*‘addasaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I saw that, sir.’*";
P_HTM[4881]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4882]="*‘ambho purisa, tassa te viññussa sato mahallakassa na etadahosi—**‘Mister, did it not occur to you—being sensible and mature—*";
P_HTM[4883]="*ahampi khomhi jarādhammo, jaraṃ anatīto. Handāhaṃ kalyāṇaṃ karomi kāyena vācāya manasā’ti?**“I, too, am liable to grow old. I’m not exempt from old age. I’d better do good by way of body, speech, and mind”?’*";
P_HTM[4884]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4885]="*‘nāsakkhissaṃ, bhante, pamādassaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I couldn’t, sir. I was negligent.’*";
P_HTM[4886]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4887]="*‘ambho purisa, pamādavatāya na kalyāṇamakāsi kāyena vācāya manasā.**‘Mister, because you were negligent, you didn’t do good by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4888]="*Taggha tvaṃ, ambho purisa, tathā karissanti yathā taṃ pamattaṃ.**Well, they’ll definitely punish you to fit your negligence.*";
P_HTM[4889]="*Taṃ kho pana te etaṃ pāpakammaṃ neva mātarā kataṃ na pitarā kataṃ na bhātarā kataṃ na bhaginiyā kataṃ na mittāmaccehi kataṃ na ñātisālohitehi kataṃ na samaṇabrāhmaṇehi kataṃ na devatāhi kataṃ, tayāvetaṃ pāpakammaṃ kataṃ, tvaññevetassa vipākaṃ paṭisaṃvedissasī’ti. (2)**That bad deed wasn’t done by your mother, father, brother, or sister. It wasn’t done by friends and colleagues, by relatives and kin, by ascetics and brahmins, or by the deities. That bad deed was done by you alone, and you alone will experience the result.’*";
P_HTM[4890]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā dutiyaṃ devadūtaṃ samanuyuñjitvā samanugāhitvā samanubhāsitvā tatiyaṃ devadūtaṃ samanuyuñjati samanugāhati samanubhāsati:**Then King Yama grills them about the third messenger of the gods.*";
P_HTM[4891]="*‘ambho purisa, na tvaṃ addasa manussesu tatiyaṃ devadūtaṃ pātubhūtan’ti?**‘Mister, did you not see the third messenger of the gods that appeared among human beings?’*";
P_HTM[4892]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4893]="*‘nāddasaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I saw nothing, sir.’*";
P_HTM[4894]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4895]="*‘ambho purisa, na tvaṃ addasa manussesu itthiṃ vā purisaṃ vā ābādhikaṃ dukkhitaṃ bāḷhagilānaṃ sake muttakarīse palipannaṃ semānaṃ aññehi vuṭṭhāpiyamānaṃ aññehi saṃvesiyamānan’ti?**‘Mister, did you not see among human beings a woman or a man, sick, suffering, gravely ill, collapsed in their own urine and feces, being picked up by some and put down by others?’*";
P_HTM[4896]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4897]="*‘addasaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I saw that, sir.’*";
P_HTM[4898]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4899]="*‘ambho purisa, tassa te viññussa sato mahallakassa na etadahosi—**‘Mister, did it not occur to you—being sensible and mature—*";
P_HTM[4900]="*ahampi khomhi byādhidhammo, byādhiṃ anatīto.**“I, too, am liable to become sick. I’m not exempt from sickness. I’d better do good by way of body, speech, and mind”?’*";
P_HTM[4901]="*Handāhaṃ kalyāṇaṃ karomi kāyena vācāya manasā’ti? So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4902]="*‘nāsakkhissaṃ, bhante, pamādassaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I couldn’t, sir. I was negligent.’*";
P_HTM[4903]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4904]="*‘ambho purisa, pamādavatāya na kalyāṇamakāsi kāyena vācāya manasā.**‘Mister, because you were negligent, you didn’t do good by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4905]="*Taggha tvaṃ, ambho purisa, tathā karissanti yathā taṃ pamattaṃ.**Well, they’ll definitely punish you to fit your negligence.*";
P_HTM[4906]="*Taṃ kho pana te etaṃ pāpakammaṃ neva mātarā kataṃ na pitarā kataṃ na bhātarā kataṃ na bhaginiyā kataṃ na mittāmaccehi kataṃ na ñātisālohitehi kataṃ na samaṇabrāhmaṇehi kataṃ na devatāhi kataṃ, tayāvetaṃ pāpakammaṃ kataṃ, tvaññevetassa vipākaṃ paṭisaṃvedissasī’ti. (3)**That bad deed wasn’t done by your mother, father, brother, or sister. It wasn’t done by friends and colleagues, by relatives and kin, by ascetics and brahmins, or by the deities. That bad deed was done by you alone, and you alone will experience the result.’*";
P_HTM[4907]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā tatiyaṃ devadūtaṃ samanuyuñjitvā samanugāhitvā samanubhāsitvā catutthaṃ devadūtaṃ samanuyuñjati samanugāhati samanubhāsati:**Then King Yama grills them about the fourth messenger of the gods.*";
P_HTM[4908]="*‘ambho purisa, na tvaṃ addasa manussesu catutthaṃ devadūtaṃ pātubhūtan’ti?**‘Mister, did you not see the fourth messenger of the gods that appeared among human beings?’*";
P_HTM[4909]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4910]="*‘nāddasaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I saw nothing, sir.’*";
P_HTM[4911]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4912]="*‘ambho purisa, na tvaṃ addasa manussesu rājāno coraṃ āgucāriṃ gahetvā vividhā kammakāraṇā kārente—**‘Mister, did you not see among human beings when the rulers arrested a bandit, a criminal, and subjected them to various punishments—*";
P_HTM[4913]="*kasāhipi tāḷente vettehipi tāḷente addhadaṇḍakehipi tāḷente hatthampi chindante pādampi chindante hatthapādampi chindante kaṇṇampi chindante nāsampi chindante kaṇṇanāsampi chindante bilaṅgathālikampi karonte saṅkhamuṇḍikampi karonte rāhumukhampi karonte jotimālikampi karonte hatthapajjotikampi karonte erakavattikampi karonte cīrakavāsikampi karonte eṇeyyakampi karonte baḷisamaṃsikampi karonte kahāpaṇikampi karonte khārāpatacchikampi karonte palighaparivattikampi karonte palālapīṭhakampi karonte tattenapi telena osiñcante sunakhehipi khādāpente jīvantampi sūle uttāsente asināpi sīsaṃ chindante’ti?**whipping, caning, and clubbing; cutting off hands or feet, or both; cutting off ears or nose, or both; the ‘porridge pot’, the ‘shell-shave’, the ‘demon’s mouth’, the ‘garland of fire’, the ‘burning hand’, the ‘grass blades’, the ‘bark dress’, the ‘antelope’, the ‘meat hook’, the ‘coins’, the ‘acid pickle’, the ‘twisting bar’, the ‘straw mat’; being splashed with hot oil, being fed to the dogs, being impaled alive, and being beheaded?’*";
P_HTM[4914]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4915]="*‘addasaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I saw that, sir.’*";
P_HTM[4916]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4917]="*‘ambho purisa, tassa te viññussa sato mahallakassa na etadahosi—**‘Mister, did it not occur to you—being sensible and mature—*";
P_HTM[4918]="*ye kira, bho, pāpakāni kammāni karonti te diṭṭheva dhamme evarūpā vividhā kammakāraṇā karīyanti, kimaṅgaṃ pana parattha. Handāhaṃ kalyāṇaṃ karomi kāyena vācāya manasā’ti?**that if someone who does bad deeds receives such punishment in the present life, what must happen to them in the next; I’d better do good by way of body, speech, and mind”?’*";
P_HTM[4919]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4920]="*‘nāsakkhissaṃ, bhante, pamādassaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I couldn’t, sir. I was negligent.’*";
P_HTM[4921]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4922]="*‘ambho purisa, pamādavatāya na kalyāṇamakāsi kāyena vācāya manasā.**‘Mister, because you were negligent, you didn’t do good by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4923]="*Taggha tvaṃ, ambho purisa, tathā karissanti yathā taṃ pamattaṃ.**Well, they’ll definitely punish you to fit your negligence.*";
P_HTM[4924]="*Taṃ kho pana te etaṃ pāpakammaṃ neva mātarā kataṃ na pitarā kataṃ na bhātarā kataṃ na bhaginiyā kataṃ na mittāmaccehi kataṃ na ñātisālohitehi kataṃ na samaṇabrāhmaṇehi kataṃ na devatāhi kataṃ, tayāvetaṃ pāpakammaṃ kataṃ, tvaññevetassa vipākaṃ paṭisaṃvedissasī’ti. (4)**That bad deed wasn’t done by your mother, father, brother, or sister. It wasn’t done by friends and colleagues, by relatives and kin, by ascetics and brahmins, or by the deities. That bad deed was done by you alone, and you alone will experience the result.’*";
P_HTM[4925]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā catutthaṃ devadūtaṃ samanuyuñjitvā samanugāhitvā samanubhāsitvā pañcamaṃ devadūtaṃ samanuyuñjati samanugāhati samanubhāsati:**Then King Yama grills them about the fifth messenger of the gods.*";
P_HTM[4926]="*‘ambho purisa, na tvaṃ addasa manussesu pañcamaṃ devadūtaṃ pātubhūtan’ti?**‘Mister, did you not see the fifth messenger of the gods that appeared among human beings?’*";
P_HTM[4927]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4928]="*‘nāddasaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I saw nothing, sir.’*";
P_HTM[4929]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4930]="*‘ambho purisa, na tvaṃ addasa manussesu itthiṃ vā purisaṃ vā ekāhamataṃ vā dvīhamataṃ vā tīhamataṃ vā uddhumātakaṃ vinīlakaṃ vipubbakajātan’ti?**‘Mister, did you not see among human beings a woman or a man, dead for one, two, or three days, bloated, livid, and festering?’*";
P_HTM[4931]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4932]="*‘addasaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I saw that, sir.’*";
P_HTM[4933]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4934]="*‘ambho purisa, tassa te viññussa sato mahallakassa na etadahosi—**‘Mister, did it not occur to you—being sensible and mature—*";
P_HTM[4935]="*ahampi khomhi maraṇadhammo, maraṇaṃ anatīto. Handāhaṃ kalyāṇaṃ karomi kāyena vācāya manasā’ti?**“I, too, am liable to die. I’m not exempt from death. I’d better do good by way of body, speech, and mind”?’*";
P_HTM[4936]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[4937]="*‘nāsakkhissaṃ, bhante, pamādassaṃ, bhante’ti.**‘I couldn’t, sir. I was negligent.’*";
P_HTM[4938]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā evamāha:**Then King Yama says,*";
P_HTM[4939]="*‘ambho purisa, pamādavatāya na kalyāṇamakāsi kāyena vācāya manasā.**‘Mister, because you were negligent, you didn’t do good by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4940]="*Taggha tvaṃ, ambho purisa, tathā karissanti yathā taṃ pamattaṃ.**Well, they’ll definitely punish you to fit your negligence.*";
P_HTM[4941]="*Taṃ kho pana te etaṃ pāpakammaṃ neva mātarā kataṃ na pitarā kataṃ na bhātarā kataṃ na bhaginiyā kataṃ na mittāmaccehi kataṃ na ñātisālohitehi kataṃ na samaṇabrāhmaṇehi kataṃ na devatāhi kataṃ, tayāvetaṃ pāpakammaṃ kataṃ, tvaññevetassa vipākaṃ paṭisaṃvedissasī’ti. (5)**That bad deed wasn’t done by your mother, father, brother, or sister. It wasn’t done by friends and colleagues, by relatives and kin, by ascetics and brahmins, or by the deities. That bad deed was done by you alone, and you alone will experience the result.’*";
P_HTM[4942]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, yamo rājā pañcamaṃ devadūtaṃ samanuyuñjitvā samanugāhitvā samanubhāsitvā tuṇhī hoti.**Then, after grilling them about the fifth messenger of the gods, King Yama falls silent.*";
P_HTM[4943]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā pañcavidhabandhanaṃ nāma kammakāraṇaṃ karonti—**Then the wardens of hell punish them with the five-fold crucifixion.*";
P_HTM[4944]="*tattaṃ ayokhilaṃ hatthe gamenti, tattaṃ ayokhilaṃ dutiye hatthe gamenti, tattaṃ ayokhilaṃ pāde gamenti, tattaṃ ayokhilaṃ dutiye pāde gamenti, tattaṃ ayokhilaṃ majjheurasmiṃ gamenti.**They drive red-hot stakes through the hands and feet, and another in the middle of the chest.*";
P_HTM[4945]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti.**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4946]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā saṃvesetvā kuṭhārīhi tacchanti … pe …**Then the wardens of hell throw them down and hack them with axes. …*";
P_HTM[4947]="*tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā uddhampādaṃ adhosiraṃ gahetvā vāsīhi tacchanti … pe …**They hang them upside-down and hack them with hatchets. …*";
P_HTM[4948]="*tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā rathe yojetvā ādittāya pathaviyā sampajjalitāya sajotibhūtāya sārentipi, paccāsārentipi … pe …**They harness them to a chariot, and drive them back and forth across burning ground, blazing and glowing. …*";
P_HTM[4949]="*tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā mahantaṃ aṅgārapabbataṃ ādittaṃ sampajjalitaṃ sajotibhūtaṃ āropentipi oropentipi … pe …**They make them climb up and down a huge mountain of burning coals, blazing and glowing. …*";
P_HTM[4950]="*tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā uddhampādaṃ adhosiraṃ gahetvā tattāya lohakumbhiyā pakkhipanti ādittāya sampajjalitāya sajotibhūtāya.**Then the wardens of hell turn them upside down and throw them in a red-hot copper pot, burning, blazing, and glowing.*";
P_HTM[4951]="*So tattha pheṇuddehakaṃ paccati.* **";
P_HTM[4952]="*So tattha pheṇuddehakaṃ paccamāno sakimpi uddhaṃ gacchati, sakimpi adho gacchati, sakimpi tiriyaṃ gacchati.**There they’re seared in boiling scum, and they’re swept up and down and round and round.*";
P_HTM[4953]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti.**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4954]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā mahāniraye pakkhipanti.**Then the wardens of hell toss them into the Great Hell.*";
P_HTM[4955]="*So kho pana, bhikkhave, mahānirayo—**Now, about that Great Hell:*";
P_HTM[4956]="*Catukkaṇṇo catudvāro,**‘Four are its corners, four its doors,*";
P_HTM[4957]="*vibhatto bhāgaso mito;**divided into measured parts.*";
P_HTM[4958]="*Ayopākārapariyanto,**Surrounded by an iron wall,*";
P_HTM[4959]="*ayasā paṭikujjito.**of iron is its roof.*";
P_HTM[4960]="*Tassa ayomayā bhūmi,**The ground is even made of iron,*";
P_HTM[4961]="*jalitā tejasāyutā;**it burns with fierce fire.*";
P_HTM[4962]="*Samantā yojanasataṃ,**The heat forever radiates*";
P_HTM[4963]="*pharitvā tiṭṭhati sabbadā.**a hundred leagues around.’*";
P_HTM[4964]="*Tassa kho pana, bhikkhave, mahānirayassa puratthimāya bhittiyā acci uṭṭhahitvā pacchimāya bhittiyā paṭihaññati, pacchimāya bhittiyā acci uṭṭhahitvā puratthimāya bhittiyā paṭihaññati, uttarāya bhittiyā acci uṭṭhahitvā dakkhiṇāya bhittiyā paṭihaññati, dakkhiṇāya bhittiyā acci uṭṭhahitvā uttarāya bhittiyā paṭihaññati, heṭṭhā acci uṭṭhahitvā upari paṭihaññati, uparito acci uṭṭhahitvā heṭṭhā paṭihaññati.**Now in the Great Hell, flames surge out of the walls and crash into the opposite wall: from east to west, from west to east, from north to south, from south to north, from bottom to top, from top to bottom.*";
P_HTM[4965]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti.**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4966]="*Hoti kho so, bhikkhave, samayo yaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena tassa mahānirayassa puratthimaṃ dvāraṃ apāpurīyati.**There comes a time when, after a very long period has passed, the eastern gate of the Great Hell is opened.*";
P_HTM[4967]="*So tattha sīghena javena dhāvati.**So they run there as fast as they can.*";
P_HTM[4968]="*Tassa sīghena javena dhāvato chavimpi ḍayhati, cammampi ḍayhati, maṃsampi ḍayhati, nhārumpi ḍayhati, aṭṭhīnipi sampadhūpāyanti, ubbhataṃ tādisameva hoti.**And as they run, their outer skin, inner skin, flesh, and sinews burn and even their bones smoke. Such is their escape;*";
P_HTM[4969]="*Yato ca kho so, bhikkhave, bahusampatto hoti, atha taṃ dvāraṃ pidhīyati.**but when they’ve managed to make it most of the way, the gate is slammed shut.*";
P_HTM[4970]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti.**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4971]="*Hoti kho so, bhikkhave, samayo yaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena tassa mahānirayassa pacchimaṃ dvāraṃ apāpurīyati … pe …**There comes a time when, after a very long period has passed, the western gate …*";
P_HTM[4972]="*uttaraṃ dvāraṃ apāpurīyati … pe …**northern gate …*";
P_HTM[4973]="*dakkhiṇaṃ dvāraṃ apāpurīyati.**southern gate of the Great hell is opened.*";
P_HTM[4974]="*So tattha sīghena javena dhāvati.**So they run there as fast as they can.*";
P_HTM[4975]="*Tassa sīghena javena dhāvato chavimpi ḍayhati, cammampi ḍayhati, maṃsampi ḍayhati, nhārumpi ḍayhati, aṭṭhīnipi sampadhūpāyanti, ubbhataṃ tādisameva hoti.**And as they run, their outer skin, inner skin, flesh, and sinews burn and even their bones smoke. Such is their escape;*";
P_HTM[4976]="*Yato ca kho so, bhikkhave, bahusampatto hoti, atha taṃ dvāraṃ pidhīyati.**but when they’ve managed to make it most of the way, the gate is slammed shut.*";
P_HTM[4977]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti.**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4978]="*Hoti kho so, bhikkhave, samayo yaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena tassa mahānirayassa puratthimaṃ dvāraṃ apāpurīyati.**There comes a time when, after a very long period has passed, the eastern gate of the Great Hell is opened.*";
P_HTM[4979]="*So tattha sīghena javena dhāvati.**So they run there as fast as they can.*";
P_HTM[4980]="*Tassa sīghena javena dhāvato chavimpi ḍayhati, cammampi ḍayhati, maṃsampi ḍayhati, nhārumpi ḍayhati, aṭṭhīnipi sampadhūpāyanti, ubbhataṃ tādisameva hoti.**And as they run, their outer skin, inner skin, flesh, and sinews burn and even their bones smoke. Such is their escape;*";
P_HTM[4981]="*So tena dvārena nikkhamati.**and they make it out that door.*";
P_HTM[4982]="*Tassa kho pana, bhikkhave, mahānirayassa samanantarā sahitameva mahanto gūthanirayo.**Immediately adjacent to the Great Hell is the vast Dung Hell.*";
P_HTM[4983]="*So tattha patati.**And that’s where they fall.*";
P_HTM[4984]="*Tasmiṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, gūthaniraye sūcimukhā pāṇā chaviṃ chindanti, chaviṃ chetvā cammaṃ chindanti, cammaṃ chetvā maṃsaṃ chindanti, maṃsaṃ chetvā nhāruṃ chindanti, nhāruṃ chetvā aṭṭhiṃ chindanti, aṭṭhiṃ chetvā aṭṭhimiñjaṃ khādanti.**In that Dung Hell there are needle-mouthed creatures that bore through the outer skin, the inner skin, the flesh, sinews, and bones, until they reach the marrow and devour it.*";
P_HTM[4985]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti. (1)**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4986]="*Tassa kho pana, bhikkhave, gūthanirayassa samanantarā sahitameva mahanto kukkulanirayo.**Immediately adjacent to the Dung Hell is the vast Hell of Hot Coals.*";
P_HTM[4987]="*So tattha patati.**And that’s where they fall.*";
P_HTM[4988]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti. (2)**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4989]="*Tassa kho pana, bhikkhave, kukkulanirayassa samanantarā sahitameva mahantaṃ simbalivanaṃ uddhaṃ yojanamuggataṃ soḷasaṅgulakaṇṭakaṃ ādittaṃ sampajjalitaṃ sajotibhūtaṃ.**Immediately adjacent to the Hell of Hot Coals is the vast Hell of the Red Silk-Cotton Wood. It’s a league high, full of sixteen-inch thorns, burning, blazing, and glowing.*";
P_HTM[4990]="*Tattha āropentipi oropentipi.**And there they make them climb up and down.*";
P_HTM[4991]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti. (3)**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4992]="*Tassa kho pana, bhikkhave, simbalivanassa samanantarā sahitameva mahantaṃ asipattavanaṃ.**Immediately adjacent to the Hell of the Red Silk-Cotton Wood is the vast Hell of the Sword-Leaf Trees.*";
P_HTM[4993]="*So tattha pavisati.**They enter that.*";
P_HTM[4994]="*Tassa vāteritāni pattāni patitāni hatthampi chindanti, pādampi chindanti, hatthapādampi chindanti, kaṇṇampi chindanti, nāsampi chindanti, kaṇṇanāsampi chindanti.**There the fallen leaves blown by the wind cut their hands, feet, both hands and feet; they cut their ears, nose, both ears and nose.*";
P_HTM[4995]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti. (4)**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[4996]="*Tassa kho pana, bhikkhave, asipattavanassa samanantarā sahitameva mahatī khārodakā nadī.**Immediately adjacent to the Hell of the Sword-Leaf Trees is the vast Acid Hell.*";
P_HTM[4997]="*So tattha patati.**And that’s where they fall.*";
P_HTM[4998]="*So tattha anusotampi vuyhati, paṭisotampi vuyhati, anusotapaṭisotampi vuyhati.**There they are swept upstream, swept downstream, and swept both up and down stream.*";
P_HTM[4999]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti. (5)**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[5000]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā balisena uddharitvā thale patiṭṭhāpetvā evamāhaṃsu:**Then the wardens of hell pull them out and place them on dry land, and say,*";
P_HTM[5001]="*‘ambho purisa, kiṃ icchasī’ti?**‘Mister, what do you want?’*";
P_HTM[5002]="*So evamāha:**They say,*";
P_HTM[5003]="*‘jighacchitosmi, bhante’ti.**‘I’m hungry, sir.’*";
P_HTM[5004]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā tattena ayosaṅkunā mukhaṃ vivaritvā ādittena sampajjalitena sajotibhūtena tattaṃ lohaguḷaṃ mukhe pakkhipanti ādittaṃ sampajjalitaṃ sajotibhūtaṃ.**The wardens of hell force open their mouth with a hot iron spike—burning, blazing, glowing—and shove in a red-hot copper ball, burning, blazing, and glowing.*";
P_HTM[5005]="*So tassa oṭṭhampi dahati, mukhampi dahati, kaṇṭhampi dahati, urampi dahati, antampi antaguṇampi ādāya adhobhāgā nikkhamati.**It burns their lips, mouth, tongue, throat, and stomach before coming out below dragging their entrails.*";
P_HTM[5006]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti.**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[5007]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā evamāhaṃsu:**Then the wardens of hell say,*";
P_HTM[5008]="*‘ambho purisa, kiṃ icchasī’ti?**‘Mister, what do you want?’*";
P_HTM[5009]="*So evamāha:**They say,*";
P_HTM[5010]="*‘pipāsitosmi, bhante’ti.**‘I’m thirsty, sir.’*";
P_HTM[5011]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā tattena ayosaṅkunā mukhaṃ vivaritvā ādittena sampajjalitena sajotibhūtena tattaṃ tambalohaṃ mukhe āsiñcanti ādittaṃ sampajjalitaṃ sajotibhūtaṃ.**The wardens of hell force open their mouth with a hot iron spike—burning, blazing, glowing—and pour in molten copper, burning, blazing, and glowing.*";
P_HTM[5012]="*Taṃ tassa oṭṭhampi dahati, mukhampi dahati, kaṇṭhampi dahati, urampi dahati, antampi antaguṇampi ādāya adhobhāgā nikkhamati.**It burns their lips, mouth, tongue, throat, and stomach before coming out below dragging their entrails.*";
P_HTM[5013]="*So tattha dukkhā tibbā kharā kaṭukā vedanā vedeti, na ca tāva kālaṃ karoti, yāva na taṃ pāpakammaṃ byantīhoti.**And there they feel painful, sharp, severe, acute feelings—but they don’t die until that bad deed is eliminated.*";
P_HTM[5014]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, nirayapālā puna mahāniraye pakkhipanti.**Then the wardens of hell toss them back in the Great Hell.*";
P_HTM[5015]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, yamassa rañño etadahosi:**Once upon a time, King Yama thought:*";
P_HTM[5016]="*‘ye kira, bho, loke pāpakāni akusalāni kammāni karonti te evarūpā vividhā kammakāraṇā karīyanti.**‘Those who do such bad deeds in the world receive these many different punishments.*";
P_HTM[5017]="*Aho vatāhaṃ manussattaṃ labheyyaṃ. Tathāgato ca loke uppajjeyya arahaṃ sammāsambuddho. Tañcāhaṃ bhagavantaṃ payirupāseyyaṃ.**Oh, I hope I may be reborn as a human being! And that a Realized One—a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha—arises in the world! And that I may pay homage to the Buddha!*";
P_HTM[5018]="*So ca me bhagavā dhammaṃ deseyya. Tassa cāhaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ ājāneyyan’ti.**Then the Buddha can teach me Dhamma, so that I may understand his teaching.’*";
P_HTM[5019]="*Taṃ kho panāhaṃ, bhikkhave, nāññassa samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā sutvā vadāmi, api ca yadeva sāmaṃ ñātaṃ sāmaṃ diṭṭhaṃ sāmaṃ viditaṃ tadevāhaṃ vadāmī”ti.**Now, I don’t say this because I’ve heard it from some other ascetic or brahmin. I only say it because I’ve known, seen, and realized it for myself.”*";
P_HTM[5020]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[5021]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[5022]="*“Coditā devadūtehi,**“Those people who are negligent,*";
P_HTM[5023]="*ye pamajjanti māṇavā;**when warned by the gods’ messengers:*";
P_HTM[5024]="*Te dīgharattaṃ socanti,**a long time they sorrow,*";
P_HTM[5025]="*hīnakāyūpagā narā.**when they go to that wretched place.*";
P_HTM[5026]="*Ye ca kho devadūtehi,**But those good and peaceful people,*";
P_HTM[5027]="*santo sappurisā idha;**when warned by the gods’ messengers,*";
P_HTM[5028]="*Coditā nappamajjanti,**never neglect*";
P_HTM[5029]="*ariyadhamme kudācanaṃ.**the teaching of the noble ones.*";
P_HTM[5030]="*Upādāne bhayaṃ disvā,**Seeing the danger in grasping,*";
P_HTM[5031]="*jātimaraṇasambhave;**the origin of birth and death,*";
P_HTM[5032]="*Anupādā vimuccanti,**they’re freed by not grasping,*";
P_HTM[5033]="*jātimaraṇasaṅkhaye.**with the ending of birth and death.*";
P_HTM[5034]="*Te khemappattā sukhino,**Happy, they’ve come to a safe place,*";
P_HTM[5035]="*diṭṭhadhammābhinibbutā;**extinguished in this very life.*";
P_HTM[5036]="*Sabbaverabhayātītā,**They’ve gone beyond all threats and perils,*";
P_HTM[5037]="*sabbadukkhaṃ upaccagun”ti.**and risen above all suffering.”*";
P_HTM[5038]="*Devadūtasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5039]="*Suññatavaggo niṭṭhito tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[5040]="*Dvidhāva suññatā hoti,* **";
P_HTM[5041]="*Abbhutadhammabākulaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5042]="*Aciravatabhūmijanāmo,* **";
P_HTM[5043]="*Anuruddhupakkilesaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5044]="*Bālapaṇḍito devadūtañca te dasāti.* **";
P_HTM[5045]="*131. Bhaddekarattasutta**One Fine Night*";
P_HTM[5046]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[5047]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[5048]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[5049]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[5050]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[5051]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[5052]="*“bhaddekarattassa vo, bhikkhave, uddesañca vibhaṅgañca desessāmi.**“I shall teach you the passage for recitation and the analysis of One Fine Night.*";
P_HTM[5053]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[5054]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[5055]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[5056]="*“Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,**“Don’t run back to the past,*";
P_HTM[5057]="*nappaṭikaṅkhe anāgataṃ;**don’t hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5058]="*Yadatītaṃ pahīnaṃ taṃ,**What’s past is left behind;*";
P_HTM[5059]="*appattañca anāgataṃ.**the future has not arrived;*";
P_HTM[5060]="*Paccuppannañca yo dhammaṃ,**and phenomena in the present*";
P_HTM[5061]="*Tattha tattha vipassati;**are clearly seen in every case.*";
P_HTM[5062]="*Asaṃhīraṃ asaṃkuppaṃ,**Knowing this, foster it—*";
P_HTM[5063]="*Taṃ vidvā manubrūhaye.**unfaltering, unshakable.*";
P_HTM[5064]="*Ajjeva kiccamātappaṃ,**Today’s the day to keenly work—*";
P_HTM[5065]="*ko jaññā maraṇaṃ suve;**who knows, tomorrow may bring death!*";
P_HTM[5066]="*Na hi no saṅgaraṃ tena,**For there is no bargain to be struck*";
P_HTM[5067]="*mahāsenena maccunā.**with Death and his mighty hordes.*";
P_HTM[5068]="*Evaṃvihāriṃ ātāpiṃ,**The peaceful sage explained it’s those*";
P_HTM[5069]="*ahorattamatanditaṃ;**who keenly meditate like this,*";
P_HTM[5070]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,**tireless all night and day,*";
P_HTM[5071]="*santo ācikkhate muni.**who truly have that one fine night.*";
P_HTM[5072]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, atītaṃ anvāgameti?**And how do you run back to the past?*";
P_HTM[5073]="*‘Evaṃrūpo ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti, ‘evaṃvedano ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti, ‘evaṃsañño ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti, ‘evaṃsaṅkhāro ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti, ‘evaṃviññāṇo ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti—**You muster delight there, thinking: ‘I had such form in the past.’ … ‘I had such feeling … perception … choice … consciousness in the past.’*";
P_HTM[5074]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, atītaṃ anvāgameti.**That’s how you run back to the past.*";
P_HTM[5075]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, atītaṃ nānvāgameti?**And how do you not run back to the past?*";
P_HTM[5076]="*‘Evaṃrūpo ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti, ‘evaṃvedano ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti, ‘evaṃsañño ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti, ‘evaṃsaṅkhāro ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti, ‘evaṃviññāṇo ahosiṃ atītamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti—**You don’t muster delight there, thinking: ‘I had such form in the past.’ … ‘I had such feeling … perception … choice … consciousness in the past.’*";
P_HTM[5077]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, atītaṃ nānvāgameti.**That’s how you don’t run back to the past.*";
P_HTM[5078]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, anāgataṃ paṭikaṅkhati?**And how do you hope for the future?*";
P_HTM[5079]="*‘Evaṃrūpo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti, evaṃvedano siyaṃ … pe … evaṃsañño siyaṃ … evaṃsaṅkhāro siyaṃ … evaṃviññāṇo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti—**You muster delight there, thinking: ‘May I have such form in the future.’ … ‘May I have such feeling … perception … choice … consciousness in the future.’*";
P_HTM[5080]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, anāgataṃ paṭikaṅkhati.**That’s how you hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5081]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, anāgataṃ nappaṭikaṅkhati?**And how do you not hope for the future?*";
P_HTM[5082]="*‘Evaṃrūpo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti, evaṃvedano siyaṃ … evaṃsañño siyaṃ … evaṃsaṅkhāro siyaṃ … ‘evaṃviññāṇo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānan’ti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti—**You don’t muster delight there, thinking: ‘May I have such form in the future.’ … ‘May I have such feeling … perception … choice … consciousness in the future.’*";
P_HTM[5083]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, anāgataṃ nappaṭikaṅkhati.**That’s how you don’t hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5084]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, paccuppannesu dhammesu saṃhīrati?**And how do you falter amid presently arisen phenomena?*";
P_HTM[5085]="*Idha, bhikkhave, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto**It’s when an uneducated ordinary person has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[5086]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ, attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ;**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[5087]="*vedanaṃ … pe …**They regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[5088]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[5089]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[5090]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ—**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5091]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, paccuppannesu dhammesu saṃhīrati.**That’s how you falter amid presently arisen phenomena.*";
P_HTM[5092]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, paccuppannesu dhammesu na saṃhīrati?**And how do you not falter amid presently arisen phenomena?*";
P_HTM[5093]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī ariyadhammassa kovido ariyadhamme suvinīto sappurisānaṃ dassāvī sappurisadhammassa kovido sappurisadhamme suvinīto**It’s when an educated noble disciple has seen the noble ones, and is skilled and trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve seen good persons, and are skilled and trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[5094]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ, na attani vā rūpaṃ, na rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ;**They don’t regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[5095]="*na vedanaṃ …**They don’t regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[5096]="*na saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[5097]="*na saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[5098]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, na viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ, na attani vā viññāṇaṃ, na viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ—**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5099]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, paccuppannesu dhammesu na saṃhīrati.**That’s how you don’t falter amid presently arisen phenomena.*";
P_HTM[5100]="*Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,**Don’t run back to the past,*";
P_HTM[5101]="*nappaṭikaṅkhe anāgataṃ;**don’t hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5102]="*Yadatītaṃ pahīnaṃ taṃ,**What’s past is left behind;*";
P_HTM[5103]="*appattañca anāgataṃ.**the future has not arrived;*";
P_HTM[5104]="*Paccuppannañca yo dhammaṃ,**and phenomena in the present*";
P_HTM[5105]="*tattha tattha vipassati;**are clearly seen in every case.*";
P_HTM[5106]="*Asaṃhīraṃ asaṅkuppaṃ,**Knowing this, foster it—*";
P_HTM[5107]="*taṃ vidvā manubrūhaye.**unfaltering, unshakable.*";
P_HTM[5108]="*Ajjeva kiccamātappaṃ,**Today’s the day to keenly work—*";
P_HTM[5109]="*ko jaññā maraṇaṃ suve;**who knows, tomorrow may bring death!*";
P_HTM[5110]="*Na hi no saṅgaraṃ tena,**For there is no bargain to be struck*";
P_HTM[5111]="*mahāsenena maccunā.**with Death and his mighty hordes.*";
P_HTM[5112]="*Evaṃvihāriṃ ātāpiṃ,**The peaceful sage explained it’s those*";
P_HTM[5113]="*ahorattamatanditaṃ;**who keenly meditate like this,*";
P_HTM[5114]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,**tireless all night and day,*";
P_HTM[5115]="*santo ācikkhate munīti.**who truly have that one fine night.*";
P_HTM[5116]="*‘Bhaddekarattassa vo, bhikkhave, uddesañca vibhaṅgañca desessāmī’ti—**And that’s what I meant when I said: ‘I shall teach you the passage for recitation and the analysis of One Fine Night.’”*";
P_HTM[5117]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttan”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5118]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[5119]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[5120]="*Bhaddekarattasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5121]="*132. Ānandabhaddekarattasutta**Ānanda and One Fine Night*";
P_HTM[5122]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[5123]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[5124]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā ānando upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandasseti samādapeti samuttejeti sampahaṃseti, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca bhāsati.**Now at that time Venerable Ānanda was educating, encouraging, firing up, and inspiring the mendicants in the assembly hall with a Dhamma talk on the topic of the recitation passage and analysis of One Fine Night.*";
P_HTM[5125]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenupaṭṭhānasālā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha came out of retreat, went to the assembly hall, where he sat on the seat spread out,*";
P_HTM[5126]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**and addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[5127]="*“ko nu kho, bhikkhave, upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca abhāsī”ti?**“Who was inspiring the mendicants with a talk on the recitation passage and analysis of One Fine Night?”*";
P_HTM[5128]="*“Āyasmā, bhante, ānando upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca abhāsī”ti.**“It was Venerable Ānanda, sir.”*";
P_HTM[5129]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[5130]="*“yathā kathaṃ pana tvaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca abhāsī”ti?**“But in what way were you inspiring the mendicants with a talk on the recitation passage and analysis of One Fine Night?”*";
P_HTM[5131]="*“Evaṃ kho ahaṃ, bhante, bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassesiṃ samādapesiṃ samuttejesiṃ sampahaṃsesiṃ, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca abhāsiṃ—**“I was doing so in this way, sir,” replied Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[5132]="*Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,* **";
P_HTM[5133]="*nappaṭikaṅkhe anāgataṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5134]="*Yadatītaṃ pahīnaṃ taṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5135]="*appattañca anāgataṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5136]="*Paccuppannañca yo dhammaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5137]="*tattha tattha vipassati;* **";
P_HTM[5138]="*Asaṃhīraṃ asaṅkuppaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5139]="*taṃ vidvā manubrūhaye.* **";
P_HTM[5140]="*Ajjeva kiccamātappaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5141]="*ko jaññā maraṇaṃ suve;* **";
P_HTM[5142]="*Na hi no saṅgaraṃ tena,* **";
P_HTM[5143]="*mahāsenena maccunā.* **";
P_HTM[5144]="*Evaṃvihāriṃ ātāpiṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5145]="*ahorattamatanditaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5146]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,* **";
P_HTM[5147]="*santo ācikkhate muni.* **";
P_HTM[5148]="*‘Kathañca, āvuso, atītaṃ anvāgameti?**(And he went on to repeat the verses and analysis as in the previous discourse, MN 131.)*";
P_HTM[5149]="*Evaṃrūpo ahosiṃ atītamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti, evaṃvedano ahosiṃ atītamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti, evaṃsañño ahosiṃ atītamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti, evaṃsaṅkhāro ahosiṃ atītamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti, evaṃviññāṇo ahosiṃ atītamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti—* **";
P_HTM[5150]="*evaṃ kho, āvuso, atītaṃ anvāgameti.* **";
P_HTM[5151]="*Kathañca, āvuso, atītaṃ nānvāgameti?* **";
P_HTM[5152]="*Evaṃrūpo ahosiṃ atītamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti, evaṃvedano ahosiṃ atītamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti, evaṃsañño ahosiṃ atītamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti, evaṃsaṅkhāro ahosiṃ atītamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti, evaṃviññāṇo ahosiṃ atītamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti—* **";
P_HTM[5153]="*evaṃ kho, āvuso, atītaṃ nānvāgameti.* **";
P_HTM[5154]="*Kathañca, āvuso, anāgataṃ paṭikaṅkhati?* **";
P_HTM[5155]="*Evaṃrūpo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti, evaṃvedano siyaṃ … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5156]="*evaṃsañño siyaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[5157]="*evaṃsaṅkhāro siyaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[5158]="*evaṃviññāṇo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ samanvāneti—* **";
P_HTM[5159]="*evaṃ kho, āvuso, anāgataṃ paṭikaṅkhati.* **";
P_HTM[5160]="*Kathañca, āvuso, anāgataṃ nappaṭikaṅkhati?* **";
P_HTM[5161]="*Evaṃrūpo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti, evaṃvedano siyaṃ … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5162]="*evaṃsañño siyaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[5163]="*evaṃsaṅkhāro siyaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[5164]="*evaṃviññāṇo siyaṃ anāgatamaddhānanti tattha nandiṃ na samanvāneti—* **";
P_HTM[5165]="*evaṃ kho, āvuso, anāgataṃ nappaṭikaṅkhati.* **";
P_HTM[5166]="*Kathañca, āvuso, paccuppannesu dhammesu saṃhīrati?* **";
P_HTM[5167]="*Idha, āvuso, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto* **";
P_HTM[5168]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ, attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5169]="*vedanaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[5170]="*saññaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[5171]="*saṅkhāre …* **";
P_HTM[5172]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ, attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5173]="*evaṃ kho, āvuso, paccuppannesu dhammesu saṃhīrati.* **";
P_HTM[5174]="*Kathañca, āvuso, paccuppannesu dhammesu na saṃhīrati?* **";
P_HTM[5175]="*Idha, āvuso, sutavā ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī ariyadhammassa kovido ariyadhamme suvinīto sappurisānaṃ dassāvī sappurisadhammassa kovido sappurisadhamme suvinīto* **";
P_HTM[5176]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ, na attani vā rūpaṃ, na rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5177]="*na vedanaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[5178]="*na saññaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[5179]="*na saṅkhāre …* **";
P_HTM[5180]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, na viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ, na attani vā viññāṇaṃ, na viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5181]="*evaṃ kho, āvuso, paccuppannesu dhammesu na saṃhīrati.* **";
P_HTM[5182]="*Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,* **";
P_HTM[5183]="*nappaṭikaṅkhe anāgataṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5184]="*Yadatītaṃ pahīnaṃ taṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5185]="*appattañca anāgataṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5186]="*Paccuppannañca yo dhammaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5187]="*tattha tattha vipassati;* **";
P_HTM[5188]="*Asaṃhīraṃ asaṅkuppaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5189]="*taṃ vidvā manubrūhaye.* **";
P_HTM[5190]="*Ajjeva kiccamātappaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5191]="*ko jaññā maraṇaṃ suve;* **";
P_HTM[5192]="*Na hi no saṅgaraṃ tena,* **";
P_HTM[5193]="*mahāsenena maccunā.* **";
P_HTM[5194]="*Evaṃvihāriṃ ātāpiṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5195]="*ahorattamatanditaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5196]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,* **";
P_HTM[5197]="*santo ācikkhate munī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5198]="*Evaṃ kho ahaṃ, bhante, bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassesiṃ samādapesiṃ samuttejesiṃ sampahaṃsesiṃ, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca abhāsin”ti.**“That’s how I was inspiring the mendicants with a talk on the recitation passage and analysis of One Fine Night.”*";
P_HTM[5199]="*“Sādhu sādhu, ānanda.**“Good, good, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[5200]="*Sādhu kho tvaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca abhāsi:**It’s good that you were inspiring the mendicants with a talk on the recitation passage and analysis of One Fine Night.”*";
P_HTM[5201]="*‘Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,* **";
P_HTM[5202]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[5203]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,* **";
P_HTM[5204]="*santo ācikkhate munī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5205]="*Kathañca, ānanda, atītaṃ anvāgameti … pe …**(And the Buddha repeated the verses and analysis once more.)*";
P_HTM[5206]="*evaṃ kho, ānanda, atītaṃ anvāgameti.* **";
P_HTM[5207]="*Kathañca, ānanda, atītaṃ nānvāgameti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5208]="*evaṃ kho, ānanda, atītaṃ nānvāgameti.* **";
P_HTM[5209]="*Kathañca, ānanda, anāgataṃ paṭikaṅkhati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5210]="*evaṃ kho, ānanda, anāgataṃ paṭikaṅkhati.* **";
P_HTM[5211]="*Kathañca, ānanda, anāgataṃ nappaṭikaṅkhati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5212]="*evaṃ kho, ānanda, anāgataṃ nappaṭikaṅkhati.* **";
P_HTM[5213]="*Kathañca, ānanda, paccuppannesu dhammesu saṃhīrati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5214]="*evaṃ kho, ānanda, paccuppannesu dhammesu saṃhīrati.* **";
P_HTM[5215]="*Kathañca, ānanda, paccuppannesu dhammesu na saṃhīrati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5216]="*evaṃ kho, ānanda, paccuppannesu dhammesu na saṃhīrati.* **";
P_HTM[5217]="*‘Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,* **";
P_HTM[5218]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[5219]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,* **";
P_HTM[5220]="*santo ācikkhate munī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5221]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[5222]="*Attamano āyasmā ānando bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Ānanda was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[5223]="*Ānandabhaddekarattasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5224]="*133. Mahākaccānabhaddekarattasutta**Mahākaccāna and One Fine Night*";
P_HTM[5225]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[5226]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati tapodārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha in the Hot Springs Monastery.*";
P_HTM[5227]="*Atha kho āyasmā samiddhi rattiyā paccūsasamayaṃ paccuṭṭhāya yena tapodo tenupasaṅkami gattāni parisiñcituṃ.**Then Venerable Samiddhi rose at the crack of dawn and went to the hot springs to bathe.*";
P_HTM[5228]="*Tapode gattāni parisiñcitvā paccuttaritvā ekacīvaro aṭṭhāsi gattāni pubbāpayamāno.**When he had bathed and emerged from the water he stood in one robe drying himself.*";
P_HTM[5229]="*Atha kho aññatarā devatā abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇā kevalakappaṃ tapodaṃ obhāsetvā yenāyasmā samiddhi tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho sā devatā āyasmantaṃ samiddhiṃ etadavoca:**Then, late at night, a glorious deity, lighting up the entire hot springs, went up to Samiddhi, stood to one side, and said to Samiddhi:*";
P_HTM[5230]="*“dhāresi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañcā”ti?**“Mendicant, do you remember the recitation passage and analysis of One Fine Night?”*";
P_HTM[5231]="*“Na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, dhāremi bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca.**“No, reverend, I do not.*";
P_HTM[5232]="*Tvaṃ panāvuso, dhāresi bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañcā”ti?**Do you?”*";
P_HTM[5233]="*“Ahampi kho, bhikkhu, na dhāremi bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca.**“I also do not.*";
P_HTM[5234]="*Dhāresi pana tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattiyo gāthā”ti?**But do you remember just the verses on One Fine Night?”*";
P_HTM[5235]="*“Na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, dhāremi bhaddekarattiyo gāthāti.**“I do not.*";
P_HTM[5236]="*Tvaṃ panāvuso, dhāresi bhaddekarattiyo gāthā”ti?**Do you?”*";
P_HTM[5237]="*“Ahampi kho, bhikkhu na dhāremi bhaddekarattiyo gāthāti.**“I also do not.*";
P_HTM[5238]="*Uggaṇhāhi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca;**Learn the recitation passage and analysis of One Fine Night, mendicant,*";
P_HTM[5239]="*pariyāpuṇāhi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca;**memorize it,*";
P_HTM[5240]="*dhārehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca.**and remember it.*";
P_HTM[5241]="*Atthasaṃhito, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddeso ca vibhaṅgo ca ādibrahmacariyako”ti.**It is beneficial and relates to the fundamentals of the spiritual life.”*";
P_HTM[5242]="*Idamavoca sā devatā.**That’s what that deity said,*";
P_HTM[5243]="*Idaṃ vatvā tatthevantaradhāyi.**before vanishing right there.*";
P_HTM[5244]="*Atha kho āyasmā samiddhi tassā rattiyā accayena yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā samiddhi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then, when the night had passed, Samiddhi went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened. Then he added:*";
P_HTM[5245]="*“Idhāhaṃ, bhante, rattiyā paccūsasamayaṃ paccuṭṭhāya yena tapodo tenupasaṅkamiṃ gattāni parisiñcituṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5246]="*Tapode gattāni parisiñcitvā paccuttaritvā ekacīvaro aṭṭhāsiṃ gattāni pubbāpayamāno.* **";
P_HTM[5247]="*Atha kho bhante, aññatarā devatā abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇā kevalakappaṃ tapodaṃ obhāsetvā yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho sā devatā maṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[5248]="*‘dhāresi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañcā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[5249]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, bhante, taṃ devataṃ etadavocaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[5250]="*‘na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, dhāremi bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca.* **";
P_HTM[5251]="*Tvaṃ panāvuso, dhāresi bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañcā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[5252]="*‘Ahampi kho, bhikkhu, na dhāremi bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca.* **";
P_HTM[5253]="*Dhāresi pana tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattiyo gāthā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[5254]="*‘Na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, dhāremi bhaddekarattiyo gāthāti.* **";
P_HTM[5255]="*Tvaṃ panāvuso, dhāresi bhaddekarattiyo gāthā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[5256]="*‘Ahampi kho, bhikkhu, na dhāremi bhaddekarattiyo gāthāti.* **";
P_HTM[5257]="*Uggaṇhāhi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca;* **";
P_HTM[5258]="*pariyāpuṇāhi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca;* **";
P_HTM[5259]="*dhārehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca.* **";
P_HTM[5260]="*Atthasaṃhito, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddeso ca vibhaṅgo ca ādibrahmacariyako’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5261]="*Idamavoca, bhante, sā devatā.* **";
P_HTM[5262]="*Idaṃ vatvā tatthevantaradhāyi.* **";
P_HTM[5263]="*Sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca desetū”ti.**“Sir, please teach me the recitation passage and analysis of One Fine night.”*";
P_HTM[5264]="*“Tena hi, bhikkhu, suṇāhi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, mendicant, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[5265]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā samiddhi bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Samiddhi replied.*";
P_HTM[5266]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[5267]="*“Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,**“Don’t run back to the past,*";
P_HTM[5268]="*nappaṭikaṅkhe anāgataṃ;**don’t hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5269]="*Yadatītaṃ pahīnaṃ taṃ,**What’s past is left behind;*";
P_HTM[5270]="*appattañca anāgataṃ.**the future has not arrived;*";
P_HTM[5271]="*Paccuppannañca yo dhammaṃ,**and phenomena in the present*";
P_HTM[5272]="*tattha tattha vipassati;**are clearly seen in every case.*";
P_HTM[5273]="*Asaṃhīraṃ asaṅkuppaṃ,**Knowing this, foster it—*";
P_HTM[5274]="*taṃ vidvā manubrūhaye.**unfaltering, unshakable.*";
P_HTM[5275]="*Ajjeva kiccamātappaṃ,**Today’s the day to keenly work—*";
P_HTM[5276]="*ko jaññā maraṇaṃ suve;**who knows, tomorrow may bring death!*";
P_HTM[5277]="*Na hi no saṅgaraṃ tena,**For there is no bargain to be struck*";
P_HTM[5278]="*mahāsenena maccunā.**with Death and his mighty hordes.*";
P_HTM[5279]="*Evaṃvihāriṃ ātāpiṃ,**The peaceful sage explained it’s those*";
P_HTM[5280]="*ahorattamatanditaṃ;**who keenly meditate like this,*";
P_HTM[5281]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,**tireless all night and day,*";
P_HTM[5282]="*santo ācikkhate munī”ti.**who truly have that one fine night.”*";
P_HTM[5283]="*Idamavoca bhagavā;**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[5284]="*idaṃ vatvāna sugato uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ pāvisi.**When he had spoken, the Holy One got up from his seat and entered his dwelling.*";
P_HTM[5285]="*Atha kho tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ, acirapakkantassa bhagavato, etadahosi:**Soon after the Buddha left, those mendicants considered,*";
P_HTM[5286]="*“idaṃ kho no, āvuso, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:**“The Buddha gave this brief passage for recitation, then entered his dwelling without explaining the meaning in detail. …*";
P_HTM[5287]="*‘Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,* **";
P_HTM[5288]="*nappaṭikaṅkhe anāgataṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5289]="*Yadatītaṃ pahīnaṃ taṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5290]="*appattañca anāgataṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5291]="*Paccuppannañca yo dhammaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5292]="*tattha tattha vipassati;* **";
P_HTM[5293]="*Asaṃhīraṃ asaṅkuppaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5294]="*taṃ vidvā manubrūhaye.* **";
P_HTM[5295]="*Ajjeva kiccamātappaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5296]="*ko jaññā maraṇaṃ suve;* **";
P_HTM[5297]="*Na hi no saṅgaraṃ tena,* **";
P_HTM[5298]="*mahāsenena maccunā.* **";
P_HTM[5299]="*Evaṃvihāriṃ ātāpiṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5300]="*ahorattamatanditaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5301]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,* **";
P_HTM[5302]="*santo ācikkhate munī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5303]="*Ko nu kho imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajeyyā”ti?**Who can explain in detail the meaning of this brief summary given by the Buddha?”*";
P_HTM[5304]="*Atha kho tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ etadahosi:**Then those mendicants thought:*";
P_HTM[5305]="*“ayaṃ kho āyasmā mahākaccāno satthu ceva saṃvaṇṇito sambhāvito ca viññūnaṃ sabrahmacārīnaṃ;**“This Venerable Mahākaccāna is praised by the Buddha and esteemed by his sensible spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[5306]="*pahoti cāyasmā mahākaccāno imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajituṃ.**He is capable of explaining in detail the meaning of this brief passage for recitation given by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[5307]="*Yannūna mayaṃ yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkameyyāma; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyāmā”ti.**Let’s go to him, and ask him about this matter.”*";
P_HTM[5308]="*Atha kho te bhikkhū yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā mahākaccānena saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**Then those mendicants went to Mahākaccāna, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[5309]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side. They told him what had happened, and said:*";
P_HTM[5310]="*“idaṃ kho no, āvuso kaccāna, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:* **";
P_HTM[5311]="*‘Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,* **";
P_HTM[5312]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[5313]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,* **";
P_HTM[5314]="*santo ācikkhate munī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5315]="*Tesaṃ no, āvuso kaccāna, amhākaṃ, acirapakkantassa bhagavato, etadahosi—* **";
P_HTM[5316]="*idaṃ kho no, āvuso, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:* **";
P_HTM[5317]="*‘Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,* **";
P_HTM[5318]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[5319]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,* **";
P_HTM[5320]="*santo ācikkhate munī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5321]="*Ko nu kho imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajeyyāti?* **";
P_HTM[5322]="*Tesaṃ no, āvuso kaccāna, amhākaṃ etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[5323]="*‘ayaṃ kho āyasmā mahākaccāno satthu ceva saṃvaṇṇito sambhāvito ca viññūnaṃ sabrahmacārīnaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5324]="*Pahoti cāyasmā mahākaccāno imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajituṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5325]="*Yannūna mayaṃ yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkameyyāma; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyāmā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5326]="*Vibhajatāyasmā mahākaccāno”ti.**“May Venerable Mahākaccāna please explain this.”*";
P_HTM[5327]="*“Seyyathāpi, āvuso, puriso sāratthiko sāragavesī sārapariyesanaṃ caramāno mahato rukkhassa tiṭṭhato sāravato atikkammeva mūlaṃ atikkamma khandhaṃ sākhāpalāse sāraṃ pariyesitabbaṃ maññeyya;**“Reverends, suppose there was a person in need of heartwood. And while wandering in search of heartwood he’d come across a large tree standing with heartwood. But he’d pass over the roots and trunk, imagining that the heartwood should be sought in the branches and leaves.*";
P_HTM[5328]="*evaṃsampadamidaṃ āyasmantānaṃ satthari sammukhībhūte taṃ bhagavantaṃ atisitvā amhe etamatthaṃ paṭipucchitabbaṃ maññatha.**Such is the consequence for the venerables. Though you were face to face with the Buddha, you passed him by, imagining that you should ask me about this matter.*";
P_HTM[5329]="*So hāvuso, bhagavā jānaṃ jānāti, passaṃ passati, cakkhubhūto ñāṇabhūto dhammabhūto brahmabhūto vattā pavattā atthassa ninnetā amatassa dātā dhammassāmī tathāgato.**For he is the Buddha, who knows and sees. He is vision, he is knowledge, he is the truth, he is supreme. He is the teacher, the proclaimer, the elucidator of meaning, the bestower of the deathless, the lord of truth, the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[5330]="*So ceva panetassa kālo ahosi yaṃ bhagavantaṃyeva etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyātha, yathā vo bhagavā byākareyya tathā naṃ dhāreyyāthā”ti.**That was the time to approach the Buddha and ask about this matter. You should have remembered it in line with the Buddha’s answer.”*";
P_HTM[5331]="*“Addhāvuso kaccāna, bhagavā jānaṃ jānāti, passaṃ passati, cakkhubhūto ñāṇabhūto dhammabhūto brahmabhūto vattā pavattā atthassa ninnetā amatassa dātā dhammassāmī tathāgato.**“Certainly he is the Buddha, who knows and sees. He is vision, he is knowledge, he is the truth, he is supreme. He is the teacher, the proclaimer, the elucidator of meaning, the bestower of the deathless, the lord of truth, the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[5332]="*So ceva panetassa kālo ahosi yaṃ bhagavantaṃyeva etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyāma;**That was the time to approach the Buddha and ask about this matter.*";
P_HTM[5333]="*yathā no bhagavā byākareyya tathā naṃ dhāreyyāma.**We should have remembered it in line with the Buddha’s answer.*";
P_HTM[5334]="*Api cāyasmā mahākaccāno satthu ceva saṃvaṇṇito sambhāvito ca viññūnaṃ sabrahmacārīnaṃ;**Still, Venerable Mahākaccāna is praised by the Buddha and esteemed by his sensible spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[5335]="*pahoti cāyasmā mahākaccāno imassa bhagavatā saṃkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajituṃ.**He is capable of explaining in detail the meaning of this brief passage for recitation given by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[5336]="*Vibhajatāyasmā mahākaccāno agaruṃ karitvā”ti.**Please explain this, if it’s no trouble.”*";
P_HTM[5337]="*“Tena hāvuso, suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, reverends, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[5338]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato mahākaccānassa paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[5339]="*Āyasmā mahākaccāno etadavoca:**Venerable Mahākaccāna said this:*";
P_HTM[5340]="*“Yaṃ kho no, āvuso, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:**“Reverends, the Buddha gave this brief passage for recitation, then entered his dwelling without explaining the meaning in detail:*";
P_HTM[5341]="*‘Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,**‘Don’t run back to the past …*";
P_HTM[5342]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[5343]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,**not slacking off by night or day,*";
P_HTM[5344]="*santo ācikkhate munī’ti.**who truly have that one fine night.’*";
P_HTM[5345]="*Imassa kho ahaṃ, āvuso, bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmi—**And this is how I understand the detailed meaning of this passage for recitation.*";
P_HTM[5346]="*Kathañca, āvuso, atītaṃ anvāgameti?**And how do you run back to the past?*";
P_HTM[5347]="*Iti me cakkhu ahosi atītamaddhānaṃ iti rūpāti—**Consciousness gets tied up there with desire and lust, thinking: ‘In the past I had such eyes and such sights.’*";
P_HTM[5348]="*tattha chandarāgappaṭibaddhaṃ hoti viññāṇaṃ, chandarāgappaṭibaddhattā viññāṇassa tadabhinandati, tadabhinandanto atītaṃ anvāgameti.**So you take pleasure in that, and that’s when you run back to the past.*";
P_HTM[5349]="*Iti me sotaṃ ahosi atītamaddhānaṃ iti saddāti … pe …**Consciousness gets tied up there with desire and lust, thinking: ‘In the past I had such ears and such sounds …*";
P_HTM[5350]="*iti me ghānaṃ ahosi atītamaddhānaṃ iti gandhāti …**such a nose and such smells …*";
P_HTM[5351]="*iti me jivhā ahosi atītamaddhānaṃ iti rasāti …**such a tongue and such tastes …*";
P_HTM[5352]="*iti me kāyo ahosi atītamaddhānaṃ iti phoṭṭhabbāti …**such a body and such touches …*";
P_HTM[5353]="*iti me mano ahosi atītamaddhānaṃ iti dhammāti—**such a mind and such thoughts.’*";
P_HTM[5354]="*tattha chandarāgappaṭibaddhaṃ hoti viññāṇaṃ, chandarāgappaṭibaddhattā viññāṇassa tadabhinandati, tadabhinandanto atītaṃ anvāgameti—**So you take pleasure in that, and that’s when you run back to the past.*";
P_HTM[5355]="*evaṃ kho, āvuso, atītaṃ anvāgameti.**That’s how you run back to the past.*";
P_HTM[5356]="*Kathañca, āvuso, atītaṃ nānvāgameti?**And how do you not run back to the past?*";
P_HTM[5357]="*Iti me cakkhu ahosi atītamaddhānaṃ iti rūpāti—**Consciousness doesn’t get tied up there with desire and lust, thinking: ‘In the past I had such eyes and such sights.’*";
P_HTM[5358]="*tattha na chandarāgappaṭibaddhaṃ hoti viññāṇaṃ, na chandarāgappaṭibaddhattā viññāṇassa na tadabhinandati, na tadabhinandanto atītaṃ nānvāgameti.**So you don’t take pleasure in that, and that’s when you no longer run back to the past.*";
P_HTM[5359]="*Iti me sotaṃ ahosi atītamaddhānaṃ iti saddāti … pe …**Consciousness doesn’t get tied up there with desire and lust, thinking: ‘In the past I had such ears and such sounds …*";
P_HTM[5360]="*iti me ghānaṃ ahosi atītamaddhānaṃ iti gandhāti …**such a nose and such smells …*";
P_HTM[5361]="*iti me jivhā ahosi atītamaddhānaṃ iti rasāti …**such a tongue and such tastes …*";
P_HTM[5362]="*iti me kāyo ahosi atītamaddhānaṃ iti phoṭṭhabbāti …**such a body and such touches …*";
P_HTM[5363]="*iti me mano ahosi atītamaddhānaṃ iti dhammāti—**such a mind and such thoughts.’*";
P_HTM[5364]="*tattha na chandarāgappaṭibaddhaṃ hoti viññāṇaṃ, na chandarāgappaṭibaddhattā viññāṇassa, na tadabhinandati, na tadabhinandanto atītaṃ nānvāgameti—**So you don’t take pleasure in that, and that’s when you no longer run back to the past.*";
P_HTM[5365]="*evaṃ kho, āvuso, atītaṃ nānvāgameti.**That’s how you don’t run back to the past.*";
P_HTM[5366]="*Kathañca, āvuso, anāgataṃ paṭikaṅkhati?**And how do you hope for the future?*";
P_HTM[5367]="*Iti me cakkhu siyā anāgatamaddhānaṃ iti rūpāti—**The heart is set on getting what it does not have, thinking: ‘May I have such eyes and such sights in the future.’*";
P_HTM[5368]="*appaṭiladdhassa paṭilābhāya cittaṃ paṇidahati, cetaso paṇidhānapaccayā tadabhinandati, tadabhinandanto anāgataṃ paṭikaṅkhati.**So you take pleasure in that, and that’s when you hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5369]="*Iti me sotaṃ siyā anāgatamaddhānaṃ iti saddāti … pe …**The heart is set on getting what it does not have, thinking: ‘May I have such ears and such sounds …*";
P_HTM[5370]="*iti me ghānaṃ siyā anāgatamaddhānaṃ iti gandhāti …**such a nose and such smells …*";
P_HTM[5371]="*iti me jivhā siyā anāgatamaddhānaṃ iti rasāti …**such a tongue and such tastes …*";
P_HTM[5372]="*iti me kāyo siyā anāgatamaddhānaṃ iti phoṭṭhabbāti …**such a body and such touches …*";
P_HTM[5373]="*iti me mano siyā anāgatamaddhānaṃ iti dhammāti—**such a mind and such thoughts in the future.’*";
P_HTM[5374]="*appaṭiladdhassa paṭilābhāya cittaṃ paṇidahati, cetaso paṇidhānapaccayā tadabhinandati, tadabhinandanto anāgataṃ paṭikaṅkhati—**So you take pleasure in that, and that’s when you hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5375]="*evaṃ kho, āvuso, anāgataṃ paṭikaṅkhati.**That’s how you hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5376]="*Kathañca, āvuso, anāgataṃ nappaṭikaṅkhati?**And how do you not hope for the future?*";
P_HTM[5377]="*Iti me cakkhu siyā anāgatamaddhānaṃ iti rūpāti—**The heart is not set on getting what it does not have, thinking: ‘May I have such eyes and such sights in the future.’*";
P_HTM[5378]="*appaṭiladdhassa paṭilābhāya cittaṃ nappaṇidahati, cetaso appaṇidhānapaccayā na tadabhinandati, na tadabhinandanto anāgataṃ nappaṭikaṅkhati.**So you don’t take pleasure in that, and that’s when you no longer hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5379]="*Iti me sotaṃ siyā anāgatamaddhānaṃ iti saddāti … pe …**The heart is not set on getting what it does not have, thinking: ‘May I have such ears and such sounds …*";
P_HTM[5380]="*iti me ghānaṃ siyā anāgatamaddhānaṃ iti gandhāti …**such a nose and such smells …*";
P_HTM[5381]="*iti me jivhā siyā anāgatamaddhānaṃ iti rasāti …**such a tongue and such tastes …*";
P_HTM[5382]="*iti me kāyo siyā anāgatamaddhānaṃ iti phoṭṭhabbāti …**such a body and such touches …*";
P_HTM[5383]="*iti me mano siyā anāgatamaddhānaṃ iti dhammāti—**such a mind and such thoughts in the future.’*";
P_HTM[5384]="*appaṭiladdhassa paṭilābhāya cittaṃ nappaṇidahati, cetaso appaṇidhānapaccayā na tadabhinandati, na tadabhinandanto anāgataṃ nappaṭikaṅkhati—**So you don’t take pleasure in that, and that’s when you no longer hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5385]="*evaṃ kho, āvuso, anāgataṃ nappaṭikaṅkhati.**That’s how you don’t hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5386]="*Kathañca, āvuso, paccuppannesu dhammesu saṃhīrati?**And how do you falter amid presently arisen phenomena?*";
P_HTM[5387]="*Yañcāvuso, cakkhu ye ca rūpā—**Both the eye and sights*";
P_HTM[5388]="*ubhayametaṃ paccuppannaṃ.**are presently arisen.*";
P_HTM[5389]="*Tasmiñce paccuppanne chandarāgappaṭibaddhaṃ hoti viññāṇaṃ, chandarāgappaṭibaddhattā viññāṇassa tadabhinandati, tadabhinandanto paccuppannesu dhammesu saṃhīrati.**If consciousness gets tied up there in the present with desire and lust, you take pleasure in that, and that’s when you falter amid presently arisen phenomena.*";
P_HTM[5390]="*Yañcāvuso, sotaṃ ye ca saddā … pe …**Both the ear and sounds …*";
P_HTM[5391]="*yañcāvuso, ghānaṃ ye ca gandhā …**nose and smells …*";
P_HTM[5392]="*yā cāvuso, jivhā ye ca rasā …**tongue and tastes …*";
P_HTM[5393]="*yo cāvuso, kāyo ye ca phoṭṭhabbā …**body and touches …*";
P_HTM[5394]="*yo cāvuso, mano ye ca dhammā—**mind and thoughts*";
P_HTM[5395]="*ubhayametaṃ paccuppannaṃ.**are presently arisen.*";
P_HTM[5396]="*Tasmiñce paccuppanne chandarāgappaṭibaddhaṃ hoti viññāṇaṃ, chandarāgappaṭibaddhattā viññāṇassa tadabhinandati, tadabhinandanto paccuppannesu dhammesu saṃhīrati—**If consciousness gets tied up there in the present with desire and lust, you take pleasure in that, and that’s when you falter amid presently arisen phenomena.*";
P_HTM[5397]="*evaṃ kho, āvuso, paccuppannesu dhammesu saṃhīrati.**That’s how you falter amid presently arisen phenomena.*";
P_HTM[5398]="*Kathañca, āvuso, paccuppannesu dhammesu na saṃhīrati?**And how do you not falter amid presently arisen phenomena?*";
P_HTM[5399]="*Yañcāvuso, cakkhu ye ca rūpā—**Both the eye and sights*";
P_HTM[5400]="*ubhayametaṃ paccuppannaṃ.**are presently arisen.*";
P_HTM[5401]="*Tasmiñce paccuppanne na chandarāgappaṭibaddhaṃ hoti viññāṇaṃ, na chandarāgappaṭibaddhattā viññāṇassa na tadabhinandati, na tadabhinandanto paccuppannesu dhammesu na saṃhīrati.**If consciousness doesn’t get tied up there in the present with desire and lust, you don’t take pleasure in that, and that’s when you no longer falter amid presently arisen phenomena.*";
P_HTM[5402]="*Yañcāvuso, sotaṃ ye ca saddā … pe …**Both the ear and sounds …*";
P_HTM[5403]="*yañcāvuso, ghānaṃ ye ca gandhā …**nose and smells …*";
P_HTM[5404]="*yā cāvuso, jivhā ye ca rasā …**tongue and tastes …*";
P_HTM[5405]="*yo cāvuso, kāyo ye ca phoṭṭhabbā …**body and touches …*";
P_HTM[5406]="*yo cāvuso, mano ye ca dhammā—**mind and thoughts*";
P_HTM[5407]="*ubhayametaṃ paccuppannaṃ.**are presently arisen.*";
P_HTM[5408]="*Tasmiñce paccuppanne na chandarāgappaṭibaddhaṃ hoti viññāṇaṃ, na chandarāgappaṭibaddhattā viññāṇassa na tadabhinandati, na tadabhinandanto paccuppannesu dhammesu na saṃhīrati—**If consciousness doesn’t get tied up there in the present with desire and lust, you don’t take pleasure in that, and that’s when you no longer falter amid presently arisen phenomena.*";
P_HTM[5409]="*evaṃ kho, āvuso, paccuppannesu dhammesu na saṃhīrati.**That’s how you don’t falter amid presently arisen phenomena.*";
P_HTM[5410]="*Yaṃ kho no, āvuso, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:**This is how I understand the detailed meaning of that brief passage for recitation given by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[5411]="*‘Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,* **";
P_HTM[5412]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[5413]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,* **";
P_HTM[5414]="*santo ācikkhate munī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5415]="*Imassa kho ahaṃ, āvuso, bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmi.* **";
P_HTM[5416]="*Ākaṅkhamānā ca pana tumhe āyasmanto bhagavantaṃyeva upasaṅkamitvā etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyātha,**If you wish, you may go to the Buddha and ask him about this.*";
P_HTM[5417]="*yathā vo bhagavā byākaroti tathā naṃ dhāreyyāthā”ti.**You should remember it in line with the Buddha’s answer.”*";
P_HTM[5418]="*Atha kho te bhikkhū āyasmato mahākaccānassa bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**“Yes, reverend,” said those mendicants, approving and agreeing with what Mahākaccāna said. Then they rose from their seats and went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened, adding:*";
P_HTM[5419]="*“yaṃ kho no, bhante, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:* **";
P_HTM[5420]="*‘Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,* **";
P_HTM[5421]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[5422]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,* **";
P_HTM[5423]="*santo ācikkhate munī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5424]="*Tesaṃ no, bhante, amhākaṃ, acirapakkantassa bhagavato, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[5425]="*‘idaṃ kho no, āvuso, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:* **";
P_HTM[5426]="*“Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,* **";
P_HTM[5427]="*nappaṭikaṅkhe anāgataṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5428]="*Yadatītaṃ pahīnaṃ taṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5429]="*appattañca anāgataṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5430]="*Paccuppannañca yo dhammaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5431]="*tattha tattha vipassati;* **";
P_HTM[5432]="*Asaṃhīraṃ asaṅkuppaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5433]="*taṃ vidvā manubrūhaye.* **";
P_HTM[5434]="*Ajjeva kiccamātappaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5435]="*ko jaññā maraṇaṃ suve;* **";
P_HTM[5436]="*Na hi no saṅgaraṃ tena,* **";
P_HTM[5437]="*mahāsenena maccunā.* **";
P_HTM[5438]="*Evaṃvihāriṃ ātāpiṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5439]="*ahorattamatanditaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5440]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,* **";
P_HTM[5441]="*santo ācikkhate munī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5442]="*Ko nu kho imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajeyyā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[5443]="*Tesaṃ no, bhante, amhākaṃ etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[5444]="*‘ayaṃ kho āyasmā mahākaccāno satthu ceva saṃvaṇṇito sambhāvito ca viññūnaṃ sabrahmacārīnaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5445]="*Pahoti cāyasmā mahākaccāno imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajituṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5446]="*Yannūna mayaṃ yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkameyyāma; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyāmā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5447]="*Atha kho mayaṃ, bhante, yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkamimha; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etamatthaṃ paṭipucchimha.* **";
P_HTM[5448]="*Tesaṃ no, bhante, āyasmatā mahākaccānena imehi ākārehi imehi padehi imehi byañjanehi attho vibhatto”ti.**“Mahākaccāna clearly explained the meaning to us in this manner, with these words and phrases.”*";
P_HTM[5449]="*“Paṇḍito, bhikkhave, mahākaccāno; mahāpañño, bhikkhave mahākaccāno.**“Mahākaccāna is astute, mendicants, he has great wisdom.*";
P_HTM[5450]="*Mañcepi tumhe, bhikkhave, etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyātha, ahampi taṃ evamevaṃ byākareyyaṃ yathā taṃ mahākaccānena byākataṃ.**If you came to me and asked this question, I would answer it in exactly the same way as Mahākaccāna.*";
P_HTM[5451]="*Eso cevetassa attho. Evañca naṃ dhārethā”ti.**That is what it means, and that’s how you should remember it.”*";
P_HTM[5452]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[5453]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[5454]="*Mahākaccānabhaddekarattasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5455]="*134. Lomasakaṅgiyabhaddekarattasutta**Lomasakaṅgiya and One Fine Night*";
P_HTM[5456]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[5457]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[5458]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā lomasakaṅgiyo sakkesu viharati kapilavatthusmiṃ nigrodhārāme.**Now at that time Venerable Lomasakaṅgiya was staying in the Sakyan country at Kapilavatthu in the Banyan Tree Monastery.*";
P_HTM[5459]="*Atha kho candano devaputto abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇo kevalakappaṃ nigrodhārāmaṃ obhāsetvā yenāyasmā lomasakaṅgiyo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho candano devaputto āyasmantaṃ lomasakaṅgiyaṃ etadavoca:**Then, late at night, the glorious god Candana, lighting up the entire Banyan Tree Monastery, went up to the Venerable Lomasakaṅgiya, and stood to one side. Standing to one side, he said to Lomasakaṅgiya:*";
P_HTM[5460]="*“dhāresi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañcā”ti?**“Mendicant, do you remember the recitation passage and analysis of One Fine Night?”*";
P_HTM[5461]="*“Na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, dhāremi bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca.**“No, reverend, I do not.*";
P_HTM[5462]="*Tvaṃ panāvuso, dhāresi bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañcā”ti?**Do you?”*";
P_HTM[5463]="*“Ahampi kho, bhikkhu, na dhāremi bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca.**“I also do not.*";
P_HTM[5464]="*Dhāresi pana tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattiyo gāthā”ti?**But do you remember just the verses on One Fine Night?”*";
P_HTM[5465]="*“Na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, dhāremi bhaddekarattiyo gāthā.**“I do not.*";
P_HTM[5466]="*Tvaṃ panāvuso, dhāresi bhaddekarattiyo gāthā”ti?**Do you?”*";
P_HTM[5467]="*“Dhāremi kho ahaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattiyo gāthā”ti.**“I do.”*";
P_HTM[5468]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana tvaṃ, āvuso, dhāresi bhaddekarattiyo gāthā”ti?**“How do you remember the verses on One Fine Night?”*";
P_HTM[5469]="*“Ekamidaṃ, bhikkhu, samayaṃ bhagavā devesu tāvatiṃsesu viharati pāricchattakamūle paṇḍukambalasilāyaṃ.**“This one time, the Buddha was staying among the gods of the Thirty-Three at the root of the Shady Orchard Tree on the stone spread with a cream rug.*";
P_HTM[5470]="*Tatra bhagavā devānaṃ tāvatiṃsānaṃ bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca abhāsi:**There he taught the recitation passage and analysis of One Fine Night to the gods of the Thirty-Three:*";
P_HTM[5471]="*‘Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,**‘Don’t run back to the past,*";
P_HTM[5472]="*nappaṭikaṅkhe anāgataṃ;**don’t hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5473]="*Yadatītaṃ pahīnaṃ taṃ,**What’s past is left behind;*";
P_HTM[5474]="*appattañca anāgataṃ.**the future has not arrived;*";
P_HTM[5475]="*Paccuppannañca yo dhammaṃ,**and phenomena in the present*";
P_HTM[5476]="*tattha tattha vipassati;**are clearly seen in every case.*";
P_HTM[5477]="*Asaṃhīraṃ asaṅkuppaṃ,**Knowing this, foster it—*";
P_HTM[5478]="*taṃ vidvā manubrūhaye.**unfaltering, unshakable.*";
P_HTM[5479]="*Ajjeva kiccamātappaṃ,**Today’s the day to keenly work—*";
P_HTM[5480]="*ko jaññā maraṇaṃ suve;**who knows, tomorrow may bring death!*";
P_HTM[5481]="*Na hi no saṅgaraṃ tena,**For there is no bargain to be struck*";
P_HTM[5482]="*mahāsenena maccunā.**with Death and his mighty hordes.*";
P_HTM[5483]="*Evaṃvihāriṃ ātāpiṃ,**The peaceful sage explained it’s those*";
P_HTM[5484]="*ahorattamatanditaṃ;**who keenly meditate like this,*";
P_HTM[5485]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,**tireless all night and day,*";
P_HTM[5486]="*santo ācikkhate munī’ti.**who truly have that one fine night.’*";
P_HTM[5487]="*Evaṃ kho ahaṃ, bhikkhu, dhāremi bhaddekarattiyo gāthā.**That’s how I remember the verses of One Fine Night.*";
P_HTM[5488]="*Uggaṇhāhi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca;**Learn the recitation passage and analysis of One Fine Night, mendicant,*";
P_HTM[5489]="*pariyāpuṇāhi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca;**memorize it,*";
P_HTM[5490]="*dhārehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca.**and remember it.*";
P_HTM[5491]="*Atthasaṃhito, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddeso ca vibhaṅgo ca ādibrahmacariyako”ti.**It is beneficial and relates to the fundamentals of the spiritual life.”*";
P_HTM[5492]="*Idamavoca candano devaputto.**That’s what the god Candana said*";
P_HTM[5493]="*Idaṃ vatvā tatthevantaradhāyi.**before vanishing right there.*";
P_HTM[5494]="*Atha kho āyasmā lomasakaṅgiyo tassā rattiyā accayena senāsanaṃ saṃsāmetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena sāvatthi tena cārikaṃ pakkāmi.**Then Lomasakaṅgiya set his lodgings in order and, taking his bowl and robe, set out for Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[5495]="*Anupubbena cārikaṃ caramāno yena sāvatthi jetavanaṃ anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāmo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā lomasakaṅgiyo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Eventually he came to Sāvatthī and Jeta’s Grove. He went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened. Then he added:*";
P_HTM[5496]="*“Ekamidāhaṃ, bhante, samayaṃ sakkesu viharāmi kapilavatthusmiṃ nigrodhārāme.* **";
P_HTM[5497]="*Atha kho, bhante, aññataro devaputto abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇo kevalakappaṃ nigrodhārāmaṃ obhāsetvā yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho, bhante, so devaputto maṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[5498]="*‘dhāresi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañcā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[5499]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, bhante, taṃ devaputtaṃ etadavocaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[5500]="*‘na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, dhāremi bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca.* **";
P_HTM[5501]="*Tvaṃ panāvuso, dhāresi bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañcā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[5502]="*‘Ahampi kho, bhikkhu, na dhāremi bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca.* **";
P_HTM[5503]="*Dhāresi pana tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattiyo gāthā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[5504]="*‘Na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, dhāremi bhaddekarattiyo gāthā.* **";
P_HTM[5505]="*Tvaṃ panāvuso, dhāresi bhaddekarattiyo gāthā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[5506]="*‘Dhāremi kho ahaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattiyo gāthā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5507]="*‘Yathā kathaṃ pana tvaṃ, āvuso, dhāresi bhaddekarattiyo gāthā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[5508]="*‘Ekamidaṃ, bhikkhu, samayaṃ bhagavā devesu tāvatiṃsesu viharati pāricchattakamūle paṇḍukambalasilāyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5509]="*Tatra kho bhagavā devānaṃ tāvatiṃsānaṃ bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca abhāsi:* **";
P_HTM[5510]="*“Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,* **";
P_HTM[5511]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[5512]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,* **";
P_HTM[5513]="*santo ācikkhate munī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5514]="*Evaṃ kho ahaṃ, bhikkhu, dhāremi bhaddekarattiyo gāthā.* **";
P_HTM[5515]="*Uggaṇhāhi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca;* **";
P_HTM[5516]="*pariyāpuṇāhi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca;* **";
P_HTM[5517]="*dhārehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca.* **";
P_HTM[5518]="*Atthasaṃhito, bhikkhu, bhaddekarattassa uddeso ca vibhaṅgo ca ādibrahmacariyako’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5519]="*Idamavoca, bhante, so devaputto.* **";
P_HTM[5520]="*Idaṃ vatvā tatthevantaradhāyi.* **";
P_HTM[5521]="*Sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā bhaddekarattassa uddesañca vibhaṅgañca desetū”ti.**“Sir, please teach me the recitation passage and analysis of One Fine night.”*";
P_HTM[5522]="*“Jānāsi pana tvaṃ, bhikkhu, taṃ devaputtan”ti?**“But mendicant, do you know that god?”*";
P_HTM[5523]="*“Na kho ahaṃ, bhante, jānāmi taṃ devaputtan”ti.**“I do not, sir.”*";
P_HTM[5524]="*“Candano nāma so, bhikkhu, devaputto.**“That god was named Candana.*";
P_HTM[5525]="*Candano, bhikkhu, devaputto aṭṭhiṃ katvā manasikatvā sabbacetasā samannāharitvā ohitasoto dhammaṃ suṇāti.**Candana pays heed, pays attention, engages wholeheartedly, and lends an ear to the teaching.*";
P_HTM[5526]="*Tena hi, bhikkhu, suṇāhi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**Well then, mendicant, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[5527]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā lomasakaṅgiyo bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Lomasakaṅgiya replied.*";
P_HTM[5528]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[5529]="*“Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,**“Don’t run back to the past,*";
P_HTM[5530]="*nappaṭikaṅkhe anāgataṃ;**don’t hope for the future.*";
P_HTM[5531]="*Yadatītaṃ pahīnaṃ taṃ,**What’s past is left behind;*";
P_HTM[5532]="*appattañca anāgataṃ.**the future has not arrived;*";
P_HTM[5533]="*Paccuppannañca yo dhammaṃ,**and phenomena in the present*";
P_HTM[5534]="*tattha tattha vipassati;**are clearly seen in every case.*";
P_HTM[5535]="*Asaṃhīraṃ asaṅkuppaṃ,**Knowing this, foster it—*";
P_HTM[5536]="*taṃ vidvā manubrūhaye.**unfaltering, unshakable.*";
P_HTM[5537]="*Ajjeva kiccamātappaṃ,**Today’s the day to keenly work—*";
P_HTM[5538]="*ko jaññā maraṇaṃ suve;**who knows, tomorrow may bring death!*";
P_HTM[5539]="*Na hi no saṅgaraṃ tena,**For there is no bargain to be struck*";
P_HTM[5540]="*mahāsenena maccunā.**with Death and his mighty hordes.*";
P_HTM[5541]="*Evaṃvihāriṃ ātāpiṃ,**The peaceful sage explained it’s those*";
P_HTM[5542]="*ahorattamatanditaṃ;**who keenly meditate like this,*";
P_HTM[5543]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,**tireless all night and day,*";
P_HTM[5544]="*santo ācikkhate muni.**who truly have that one fine night.*";
P_HTM[5545]="*Kathañca, bhikkhu, atītaṃ anvāgameti …**And how do you run back to the past? …”*";
P_HTM[5546]="*pe …**(And the Buddha repeated the analysis as in MN 131.)*";
P_HTM[5547]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, atītaṃ anvāgameti.* **";
P_HTM[5548]="*Kathañca, bhikkhu, atītaṃ nānvāgameti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5549]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, atītaṃ nānvāgameti.* **";
P_HTM[5550]="*Kathañca, bhikkhu, anāgataṃ paṭikaṅkhati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5551]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, anāgataṃ paṭikaṅkhati.* **";
P_HTM[5552]="*Kathañca, bhikkhu, anāgataṃ nappaṭikaṅkhati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5553]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, anāgataṃ nappaṭikaṅkhati.* **";
P_HTM[5554]="*Kathañca, bhikkhu, paccuppannesu dhammesu saṃhīrati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5555]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, paccuppannesu dhammesu saṃhīrati.* **";
P_HTM[5556]="*Kathañca, bhikkhu, paccuppannesu dhammesu na saṃhīrati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5557]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, paccuppannesu dhammesu na saṃhīrati.* **";
P_HTM[5558]="*Atītaṃ nānvāgameyya,* **";
P_HTM[5559]="*nappaṭikaṅkhe anāgataṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5560]="*Yadatītaṃ pahīnaṃ taṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5561]="*appattañca anāgataṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5562]="*Paccuppannañca yo dhammaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5563]="*tattha tattha vipassati;* **";
P_HTM[5564]="*Asaṃhīraṃ asaṅkuppaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5565]="*taṃ vidvā manubrūhaye.* **";
P_HTM[5566]="*Ajjeva kiccamātappaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5567]="*ko jaññā maraṇaṃ suve;* **";
P_HTM[5568]="*Na hi no saṅgaraṃ tena,* **";
P_HTM[5569]="*mahāsenena maccunā.* **";
P_HTM[5570]="*Evaṃvihāriṃ ātāpiṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5571]="*ahorattamatanditaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5572]="*Taṃ ve bhaddekarattoti,* **";
P_HTM[5573]="*santo ācikkhate munī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5574]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[5575]="*Attamano āyasmā lomasakaṅgiyo bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Lomasakaṅgiya was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[5576]="*Lomasakaṅgiyabhaddekarattasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5577]="*135. Cūḷakammavibhaṅgasutta**The Shorter Analysis of Deeds*";
P_HTM[5578]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[5579]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane, anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[5580]="*Atha kho subho māṇavo todeyyaputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then the brahmin student Subha, Todeyya’s son, approached the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[5581]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho subho māṇavo todeyyaputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[5582]="*“Ko nu kho, bho gotama, hetu ko paccayo yena manussānaṃyeva sataṃ manussabhūtānaṃ dissanti hīnappaṇītatā?**“What is the cause, Master Gotama, what is the reason why even among those who are human beings some are seen to be inferior and superior?*";
P_HTM[5583]="*Dissanti hi, bho gotama, manussā appāyukā, dissanti dīghāyukā;**For people are seen who are short-lived and long-lived,*";
P_HTM[5584]="*dissanti bavhābādhā, dissanti appābādhā;**sickly and healthy,*";
P_HTM[5585]="*dissanti dubbaṇṇā, dissanti vaṇṇavanto;**ugly and beautiful,*";
P_HTM[5586]="*dissanti appesakkhā, dissanti mahesakkhā;**insignificant and illustrious,*";
P_HTM[5587]="*dissanti appabhogā, dissanti mahābhogā;**poor and rich,*";
P_HTM[5588]="*dissanti nīcakulīnā, dissanti uccākulīnā;**from low and eminent families,*";
P_HTM[5589]="*dissanti duppaññā, dissanti paññavanto.**witless and wise.*";
P_HTM[5590]="*Ko nu kho, bho gotama, hetu ko paccayo yena manussānaṃyeva sataṃ manussabhūtānaṃ dissanti hīnappaṇītatā”ti?**What is the reason why even among those who are human beings some are seen to be inferior and superior?”*";
P_HTM[5591]="*“Kammassakā, māṇava, sattā kammadāyādā kammayonī kammabandhū kammappaṭisaraṇā.**“Student, sentient beings are the owners of their deeds and heir to their deeds. Deeds are their womb, their relative, and their refuge.*";
P_HTM[5592]="*Kammaṃ satte vibhajati yadidaṃ—**It is deeds that divide beings into*";
P_HTM[5593]="*hīnappaṇītatāyā”ti.**inferior and superior.”*";
P_HTM[5594]="*“Na kho ahaṃ imassa bhoto gotamassa saṃkhittena bhāsitassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmi.**“I don’t understand the meaning of what Master Gotama has said in brief, without explaining the details.*";
P_HTM[5595]="*Sādhu me bhavaṃ gotamo tathā dhammaṃ desetu yathā ahaṃ imassa bhoto gotamassa saṃkhittena bhāsitassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ ājāneyyan”ti.**Master Gotama, please teach me this matter in detail so I can understand the meaning.”*";
P_HTM[5596]="*“Tena hi, māṇava, suṇāhi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, student, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[5597]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho subho māṇavo todeyyaputto bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Subha.*";
P_HTM[5598]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[5599]="*“Idha, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā pāṇātipātī hoti luddo lohitapāṇi hatapahate niviṭṭho adayāpanno pāṇabhūtesu.**“Take some woman or man who kills living creatures. They’re violent, bloody-handed, a hardened killer, merciless to living beings.*";
P_HTM[5600]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, when their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[5601]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati appāyuko hoti.**If they’re not reborn in a place of loss, but return to the human realm, then wherever they’re reborn they’re short-lived.*";
P_HTM[5602]="*Appāyukasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—**For killing living creatures is the path leading to a short lifespan.*";
P_HTM[5603]="*pāṇātipātī hoti luddo lohitapāṇi hatapahate niviṭṭho adayāpanno pāṇabhūtesu. (1)* **";
P_HTM[5604]="*Idha pana, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti nihitadaṇḍo nihitasattho, lajjī dayāpanno sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī viharati.**But take some woman or man who gives up killing living creatures. They renounce the rod and the sword. They’re scrupulous and kind, living full of compassion for all living beings.*";
P_HTM[5605]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, when their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5606]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati dīghāyuko hoti.**If they’re not reborn in a heavenly realm, but return to the human realm, then wherever they’re reborn they’re long-lived.*";
P_HTM[5607]="*Dīghāyukasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—**For not killing living creatures is the path leading to a long lifespan.*";
P_HTM[5608]="*pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti nihitadaṇḍo nihitasattho, lajjī dayāpanno sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī viharati. (1)* **";
P_HTM[5609]="*Idha, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā sattānaṃ viheṭhakajātiko hoti, pāṇinā vā leḍḍunā vā daṇḍena vā satthena vā.**Take some woman or man who habitually hurts living creatures with a fist, stone, rod, or sword.*";
P_HTM[5610]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, after death they’re reborn in a place of loss …*";
P_HTM[5611]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati bavhābādho hoti.**or if they return to the human realm, they’re sickly …*";
P_HTM[5612]="*Bavhābādhasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5613]="*sattānaṃ viheṭhakajātiko hoti pāṇinā vā leḍḍunā vā daṇḍena vā satthena vā. (2)* **";
P_HTM[5614]="*Idha pana, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā sattānaṃ aviheṭhakajātiko hoti pāṇinā vā leḍḍunā vā daṇḍena vā satthena vā.**But take some woman or man who does not habitually hurt living creatures with a fist, stone, rod, or sword.*";
P_HTM[5615]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, after death they’re reborn in a heavenly realm …*";
P_HTM[5616]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati appābādho hoti.**or if they return to the human realm, they’re healthy …*";
P_HTM[5617]="*Appābādhasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5618]="*sattānaṃ aviheṭhakajātiko hoti pāṇinā vā leḍḍunā vā daṇḍena vā satthena vā. (2)* **";
P_HTM[5619]="*Idha, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā kodhano hoti upāyāsabahulo.**Take some woman or man who is irritable and bad-tempered.*";
P_HTM[5620]="*Appampi vutto samāno abhisajjati kuppati byāpajjati patiṭṭhīyati kopañca dosañca appaccayañca pātukaroti.**Even when lightly criticized they lose their temper, becoming annoyed, hostile, and hard-hearted, and displaying annoyance, hate, and bitterness.*";
P_HTM[5621]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, after death they’re reborn in a place of loss …*";
P_HTM[5622]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati dubbaṇṇo hoti.**or if they return to the human realm, they’re ugly …*";
P_HTM[5623]="*Dubbaṇṇasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5624]="*kodhano hoti upāyāsabahulo;* **";
P_HTM[5625]="*appampi vutto samāno abhisajjati kuppati byāpajjati patiṭṭhīyati kopañca dosañca appaccayañca pātukaroti. (3)* **";
P_HTM[5626]="*Idha pana, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā akkodhano hoti anupāyāsabahulo;**But take some woman or man who isn’t irritable and bad-tempered.*";
P_HTM[5627]="*bahumpi vutto samāno nābhisajjati na kuppati na byāpajjati na patiṭṭhīyati na kopañca dosañca appaccayañca pātukaroti.**Even when heavily criticized, they don’t lose their temper, become annoyed, hostile, and hard-hearted, or display annoyance, hate, and bitterness.*";
P_HTM[5628]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, after death they’re reborn in a heavenly realm …*";
P_HTM[5629]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati pāsādiko hoti.**or if they return to the human realm, they’re lovely …*";
P_HTM[5630]="*Pāsādikasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5631]="*akkodhano hoti anupāyāsabahulo;* **";
P_HTM[5632]="*bahumpi vutto samāno nābhisajjati na kuppati na byāpajjati na patiṭṭhīyati na kopañca dosañca appaccayañca pātukaroti. (3)* **";
P_HTM[5633]="*Idha, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā issāmanako hoti;**Take some woman or man who is jealous.*";
P_HTM[5634]="*paralābhasakkāragarukāramānanavandanapūjanāsu issati upadussati issaṃ bandhati.**They envy, resent, and begrudge the possessions, honor, respect, reverence, homage, and veneration given to others.*";
P_HTM[5635]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, after death they’re reborn in a place of loss …*";
P_HTM[5636]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati appesakkho hoti.**or if they return to the human realm, they’re insignificant …*";
P_HTM[5637]="*Appesakkhasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5638]="*issāmanako hoti;* **";
P_HTM[5639]="*paralābhasakkāragarukāramānanavandanapūjanāsu issati upadussati issaṃ bandhati. (4)* **";
P_HTM[5640]="*Idha pana, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā anissāmanako hoti;**But take some woman or man who is not jealous …*";
P_HTM[5641]="*paralābhasakkāragarukāramānanavandanapūjanāsu na issati na upadussati na issaṃ bandhati.* **";
P_HTM[5642]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, after death they’re reborn in a heavenly realm …*";
P_HTM[5643]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati mahesakkho hoti.**or if they return to the human realm, they’re illustrious …*";
P_HTM[5644]="*Mahesakkhasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5645]="*anissāmanako hoti;* **";
P_HTM[5646]="*paralābhasakkāragarukāramānanavandanapūjanāsu na issati na upadussati na issaṃ bandhati. (4)* **";
P_HTM[5647]="*Idha, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā na dātā hoti samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā annaṃ pānaṃ vatthaṃ yānaṃ mālāgandhavilepanaṃ seyyāvasathapadīpeyyaṃ.**Take some woman or man who doesn’t give to ascetics or brahmins such things as food, drink, clothing, vehicles; garlands, perfumes, and makeup; and bed, house, and lighting.*";
P_HTM[5648]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, after death they’re reborn in a place of loss …*";
P_HTM[5649]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati appabhogo hoti.**or if they return to the human realm, they’re poor …*";
P_HTM[5650]="*Appabhogasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5651]="*na dātā hoti samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā annaṃ pānaṃ vatthaṃ yānaṃ mālāgandhavilepanaṃ seyyāvasathapadīpeyyaṃ. (5)* **";
P_HTM[5652]="*Idha pana, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā dātā hoti samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā annaṃ pānaṃ vatthaṃ yānaṃ mālāgandhavilepanaṃ seyyāvasathapadīpeyyaṃ.**But take some woman or man who does give to ascetics or brahmins …*";
P_HTM[5653]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, after death they’re reborn in a heavenly realm …*";
P_HTM[5654]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati mahābhogo hoti.**or if they return to the human realm, they’re rich …*";
P_HTM[5655]="*Mahābhogasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5656]="*dātā hoti samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā annaṃ pānaṃ vatthaṃ yānaṃ mālāgandhavilepanaṃ seyyāvasathapadīpeyyaṃ. (5)* **";
P_HTM[5657]="*Idha, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā thaddho hoti atimānī—**Take some woman or man who is obstinate and vain.*";
P_HTM[5658]="*abhivādetabbaṃ na abhivādeti, paccuṭṭhātabbaṃ na paccuṭṭheti, āsanārahassa na āsanaṃ deti, maggārahassa na maggaṃ deti, sakkātabbaṃ na sakkaroti, garukātabbaṃ na garukaroti, mānetabbaṃ na māneti, pūjetabbaṃ na pūjeti.**They don’t bow to those they should bow to. They don’t rise up for them, offer them a seat, make way for them, or honor, respect, esteem, or venerate those who are worthy of such.*";
P_HTM[5659]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, after death they’re reborn in a place of loss …*";
P_HTM[5660]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati nīcakulīno hoti.**or if they return to the human realm, they’re reborn in a low class family …*";
P_HTM[5661]="*Nīcakulīnasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5662]="*thaddho hoti atimānī;* **";
P_HTM[5663]="*abhivādetabbaṃ na abhivādeti, paccuṭṭhātabbaṃ na paccuṭṭheti, āsanārahassa na āsanaṃ deti, maggārahassa na maggaṃ deti, sakkātabbaṃ na sakkaroti, garukātabbaṃ na garukaroti, mānetabbaṃ na māneti, pūjetabbaṃ na pūjeti. (6)* **";
P_HTM[5664]="*Idha pana, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā atthaddho hoti anatimānī;**But take some woman or man who is not obstinate and vain …*";
P_HTM[5665]="*abhivādetabbaṃ abhivādeti, paccuṭṭhātabbaṃ paccuṭṭheti, āsanārahassa āsanaṃ deti, maggārahassa maggaṃ deti, sakkātabbaṃ sakkaroti, garukātabbaṃ garukaroti, mānetabbaṃ māneti, pūjetabbaṃ pūjeti.* **";
P_HTM[5666]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, after death they’re reborn in a heavenly realm …*";
P_HTM[5667]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati uccākulīno hoti.**or if they return to the human realm, they’re reborn in an eminent family …*";
P_HTM[5668]="*Uccākulīnasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5669]="*atthaddho hoti anatimānī;* **";
P_HTM[5670]="*abhivādetabbaṃ abhivādeti, paccuṭṭhātabbaṃ paccuṭṭheti, āsanārahassa āsanaṃ deti, maggārahassa maggaṃ deti, sakkātabbaṃ sakkaroti, garukātabbaṃ garukaroti, mānetabbaṃ māneti, pūjetabbaṃ pūjeti. (6)* **";
P_HTM[5671]="*Idha, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā upasaṅkamitvā na paripucchitā hoti:**Take some woman or man who doesn’t approach an ascetic or brahmin to ask:*";
P_HTM[5672]="*‘kiṃ, bhante, kusalaṃ, kiṃ akusalaṃ;**‘Sir, what is skillful and what is unskillful?*";
P_HTM[5673]="*kiṃ sāvajjaṃ, kiṃ anavajjaṃ;**What is blameworthy and what is blameless?*";
P_HTM[5674]="*kiṃ sevitabbaṃ, kiṃ na sevitabbaṃ;**What should be cultivated and what should not be cultivated?*";
P_HTM[5675]="*kiṃ me karīyamānaṃ dīgharattaṃ ahitāya dukkhāya hoti, kiṃ vā pana me karīyamānaṃ dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāya hotī’ti?**What kind of action will lead to my lasting harm and suffering? Or what kind of action will lead to my lasting welfare and happiness?’*";
P_HTM[5676]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, after death they’re reborn in a place of loss …*";
P_HTM[5677]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati duppañño hoti.**or if they return to the human realm, they’re witless …*";
P_HTM[5678]="*Duppaññasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[5679]="*samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā upasaṅkamitvā na paripucchitā hoti:* **";
P_HTM[5680]="*‘kiṃ, bhante, kusalaṃ, kiṃ akusalaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5681]="*kiṃ sāvajjaṃ, kiṃ anavajjaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5682]="*kiṃ sevitabbaṃ, kiṃ na sevitabbaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5683]="*kiṃ me karīyamānaṃ dīgharattaṃ ahitāya dukkhāya hoti, kiṃ vā pana me karīyamānaṃ dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāya hotī’ti? (7)* **";
P_HTM[5684]="*Idha pana, māṇava, ekacco itthī vā puriso vā samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā upasaṅkamitvā paripucchitā hoti:**But take some woman or man who does approach an ascetic or brahmin to ask:*";
P_HTM[5685]="*‘kiṃ, bhante, kusalaṃ, kiṃ akusalaṃ;**‘Sir, what is skillful and what is unskillful?*";
P_HTM[5686]="*kiṃ sāvajjaṃ, kiṃ anavajjaṃ;**What is blameworthy and what is blameless?*";
P_HTM[5687]="*kiṃ sevitabbaṃ, kiṃ na sevitabbaṃ;**What should be cultivated and what should not be cultivated?*";
P_HTM[5688]="*kiṃ me karīyamānaṃ dīgharattaṃ ahitāya dukkhāya hoti, kiṃ vā pana me karīyamānaṃ dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāya hotī’ti?**What kind of action will lead to my lasting harm and suffering? Or what kind of action will lead to my lasting welfare and happiness?’*";
P_HTM[5689]="*So tena kammena evaṃ samattena evaṃ samādinnena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**Because of undertaking such deeds, when their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5690]="*No ce kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati, sace manussattaṃ āgacchati yattha yattha paccājāyati mahāpañño hoti.**If they’re not reborn in a heavenly realm, but return to the human realm, then wherever they’re reborn they’re very wise.*";
P_HTM[5691]="*Mahāpaññasaṃvattanikā esā, māṇava, paṭipadā yadidaṃ—**For asking questions of ascetics or brahmins is the path leading to wisdom.*";
P_HTM[5692]="*samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā upasaṅkamitvā paripucchitā hoti:* **";
P_HTM[5693]="*‘kiṃ, bhante, kusalaṃ, kiṃ akusalaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5694]="*kiṃ sāvajjaṃ, kiṃ anavajjaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5695]="*kiṃ sevitabbaṃ, kiṃ na sevitabbaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5696]="*kiṃ me karīyamānaṃ dīgharattaṃ ahitāya dukkhāya hoti, kiṃ vā pana me karīyamānaṃ dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāya hotī’ti? (7)* **";
P_HTM[5697]="*Iti kho, māṇava, appāyukasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā appāyukattaṃ upaneti, dīghāyukasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā dīghāyukattaṃ upaneti;**So it is the way people live that makes them how they are, whether short-lived or long lived,*";
P_HTM[5698]="*bavhābādhasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā bavhābādhattaṃ upaneti, appābādhasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā appābādhattaṃ upaneti;**sickly or healthy,*";
P_HTM[5699]="*dubbaṇṇasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā dubbaṇṇattaṃ upaneti, pāsādikasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā pāsādikattaṃ upaneti;**ugly or lovely,*";
P_HTM[5700]="*appesakkhasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā appesakkhattaṃ upaneti, mahesakkhasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā mahesakkhattaṃ upaneti;**insignificant or illustrious,*";
P_HTM[5701]="*appabhogasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā appabhogattaṃ upaneti, mahābhogasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā mahābhogattaṃ upaneti;**poor or rich,*";
P_HTM[5702]="*nīcakulīnasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā nīcakulīnattaṃ upaneti, uccākulīnasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā uccākulīnattaṃ upaneti;**in a low class or eminent family,*";
P_HTM[5703]="*duppaññasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā duppaññattaṃ upaneti, mahāpaññasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā mahāpaññattaṃ upaneti.**or witless or wise.*";
P_HTM[5704]="*Kammassakā, māṇava, sattā kammadāyādā kammayonī kammabandhū kammappaṭisaraṇā.**Sentient beings are the owners of their deeds and heir to their deeds. Deeds are their womb, their relative, and their refuge.*";
P_HTM[5705]="*Kammaṃ satte vibhajati yadidaṃ—**It is deeds that divide beings into*";
P_HTM[5706]="*hīnappaṇītatāyā”ti.**inferior and superior.”*";
P_HTM[5707]="*Evaṃ vutte, subho māṇavo todeyyaputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Subha said to him,*";
P_HTM[5708]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama, abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama.**“Excellent, Master Gotama! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[5709]="*Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhotā gotamena anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, Master Gotama has made the Teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[5710]="*Esāhaṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[5711]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[5712]="*Cūḷakammavibhaṅgasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5713]="*136. Mahākammavibhaṅgasutta**The Longer Analysis of Deeds*";
P_HTM[5714]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[5715]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[5716]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā samiddhi araññakuṭikāyaṃ viharati.**Now at that time Venerable Samiddhi was staying in a wilderness hut.*";
P_HTM[5717]="*Atha kho potaliputto paribbājako jaṅghāvihāraṃ anucaṅkamamāno anuvicaramāno yenāyasmā samiddhi tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā samiddhinā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then as the wanderer Potaliputta was going for a walk he came up to Venerable Samiddhi and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[5718]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho potaliputto paribbājako āyasmantaṃ samiddhiṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to him:*";
P_HTM[5719]="*“sammukhā metaṃ, āvuso samiddhi, samaṇassa gotamassa sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**“Reverend Samiddhi, I have heard and learned this in the presence of the ascetic Gotama:*";
P_HTM[5720]="*‘moghaṃ kāyakammaṃ moghaṃ vacīkammaṃ, manokammameva saccan’ti.**‘Deeds by way of body and speech are done in vain. Only mental deeds are real.’*";
P_HTM[5721]="*Atthi ca sā samāpatti yaṃ samāpattiṃ samāpanno na kiñci vediyatī”ti?**And: ‘There is such an attainment where the one who enters it does not feel anything at all.’”*";
P_HTM[5722]="*“Mā hevaṃ, āvuso potaliputta, avaca; mā hevaṃ, āvuso potaliputta, avaca; mā bhagavantaṃ abbhācikkhi. Na hi sādhu bhagavato abbhakkhānaṃ. Na hi bhagavā evaṃ vadeyya:**“Don’t say that, Reverend Potaliputta, don’t say that! Don’t misrepresent the Buddha, for misrepresentation of the Buddha is not good. And the Buddha would not say this.*";
P_HTM[5723]="*‘moghaṃ kāyakammaṃ moghaṃ vacīkammaṃ, manokammameva saccan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5724]="*‘Atthi ca kho sā, āvuso, samāpatti yaṃ samāpattiṃ samāpanno na kiñci vediyatī’”ti.**But, reverend, there is such an attainment where the one who enters it does not feel anything at all.”*";
P_HTM[5725]="*“Kīvaciraṃ pabbajitosi, āvuso samiddhī”ti?**“Reverend Samiddhi, how long has it been since you went forth?”*";
P_HTM[5726]="*“Na ciraṃ, āvuso, tīṇi vassānī”ti.**“Not long, reverend: three years.”*";
P_HTM[5727]="*“Ettha dāni mayaṃ there bhikkhū kiṃ vakkhāma, yatra hi nāma evaṃnavo bhikkhu satthāraṃ parirakkhitabbaṃ maññissati.**“Well now, what are we to say to the senior mendicants, when even such a junior mendicant imagines their Teacher needs defending?*";
P_HTM[5728]="*Sañcetanikaṃ, āvuso samiddhi, kammaṃ katvā kāyena vācāya manasā kiṃ so vediyatī”ti?**After doing an intentional deed by way of body, speech, or mind, reverend, what does one feel?”*";
P_HTM[5729]="*“Sañcetanikaṃ, āvuso potaliputta, kammaṃ katvā kāyena vācāya manasā dukkhaṃ so vediyatī”ti.**“After doing an intentional deed by way of body, speech, or mind, reverend, one feels suffering.”*";
P_HTM[5730]="*Atha kho potaliputto paribbājako āyasmato samiddhissa bhāsitaṃ neva abhinandi nappaṭikkosi;**Then, neither approving nor dismissing Samiddhi’s statement, Potaliputta*";
P_HTM[5731]="*anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmi.**got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[5732]="*Atha kho āyasmā samiddhi acirapakkante potaliputte paribbājake yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā ānandena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Soon after he had left, Venerable Samiddhi went to Venerable Ānanda, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[5733]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side,*";
P_HTM[5734]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā samiddhi yāvatako ahosi potaliputtena paribbājakena saddhiṃ kathāsallāpo taṃ sabbaṃ āyasmato ānandassa ārocesi.**and informed Ānanda of all they had discussed.*";
P_HTM[5735]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando āyasmantaṃ samiddhiṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Ānanda said to him,*";
P_HTM[5736]="*“atthi kho idaṃ, āvuso samiddhi, kathāpābhataṃ bhagavantaṃ dassanāya.**“Reverend Samiddhi, we should see the Buddha about this matter.*";
P_HTM[5737]="*Āyāmāvuso samiddhi, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamissāma; upasaṅkamitvā etamatthaṃ bhagavato ārocessāma.**Come, let’s go to the Buddha and inform him about this.*";
P_HTM[5738]="*Yathā no bhagavā byākarissati tathā naṃ dhāressāmā”ti.**As he answers, so we’ll remember it.”*";
P_HTM[5739]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho āyasmā samiddhi āyasmato ānandassa paccassosi.**“Yes, reverend,” Samiddhi replied.*";
P_HTM[5740]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca ānando āyasmā ca samiddhi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**Then Ānanda and Samiddhi went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side,*";
P_HTM[5741]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando yāvatako ahosi āyasmato samiddhissa potaliputtena paribbājakena saddhiṃ kathāsallāpo taṃ sabbaṃ bhagavato ārocesi.**and told him what had happened.*";
P_HTM[5742]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**When they had spoken, the Buddha said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[5743]="*“dassanampi kho ahaṃ, ānanda, potaliputtassa paribbājakassa nābhijānāmi, kuto panevarūpaṃ kathāsallāpaṃ?**“I don’t recall even seeing the wanderer Potaliputta, Ānanda, so how could we have had such a discussion?*";
P_HTM[5744]="*Iminā ca, ānanda, samiddhinā moghapurisena potaliputtassa paribbājakassa vibhajjabyākaraṇīyo pañho ekaṃsena byākato”ti.**The wanderer Potaliputta’s question should have been answered after analyzing it, but this foolish person answered with a generalization.”*";
P_HTM[5745]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā udāyī bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Udāyī said to him,*";
P_HTM[5746]="*“sace pana, bhante, āyasmatā samiddhinā idaṃ sandhāya bhāsitaṃ—**“But perhaps, sir, Venerable Samiddhi spoke in reference to the statement:*";
P_HTM[5747]="*yaṃ kiñci vedayitaṃ taṃ dukkhasmin”ti.**‘Suffering includes whatever is felt.’”*";
P_HTM[5748]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**But the Buddha said to Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[5749]="*“passasi no tvaṃ, ānanda, imassa udāyissa moghapurisassa ummaṅgaṃ?**“See how this foolish person Udāyī comes up with an idea?*";
P_HTM[5750]="*Aññāsiṃ kho ahaṃ, ānanda:**I knew that*";
P_HTM[5751]="*‘idānevāyaṃ udāyī moghapuriso ummujjamāno ayoniso ummujjissatī’ti.**he was going to come up with such an irrational idea.*";
P_HTM[5752]="*Ādiṃyeva, ānanda, potaliputtena paribbājakena tisso vedanā pucchitā.**Right from the start Potaliputta asked about the three feelings.*";
P_HTM[5753]="*Sacāyaṃ, ānanda, samiddhi moghapuriso potaliputtassa paribbājakassa evaṃ puṭṭho evaṃ byākareyya:**Suppose the foolish person Samiddhi had answered the wanderer Potaliputta’s question like this:*";
P_HTM[5754]="*‘sañcetanikaṃ, āvuso potaliputta, kammaṃ katvā kāyena vācāya manasā sukhavedanīyaṃ sukhaṃ so vedayati;**‘After doing an intentional deed to be experienced as pleasant by way of body, speech, or mind, one feels pleasure.*";
P_HTM[5755]="*sañcetanikaṃ, āvuso potaliputta, kammaṃ katvā kāyena vācāya manasā dukkhavedanīyaṃ dukkhaṃ so vedayati;**After doing an intentional deed to be experienced as painful by way of body, speech, or mind, one feels pain.*";
P_HTM[5756]="*sañcetanikaṃ, āvuso potaliputta, kammaṃ katvā kāyena vācāya manasā adukkhamasukhavedanīyaṃ adukkhamasukhaṃ so vedayatī’ti.**After doing an intentional deed to be experienced as neutral by way of body, speech, or mind, one feels neutral.’*";
P_HTM[5757]="*Evaṃ byākaramāno kho, ānanda, samiddhi moghapuriso potaliputtassa paribbājakassa sammā byākaramāno byākareyya.**Answering in this way, Samiddhi would have rightly answered Potaliputta.*";
P_HTM[5758]="*Api ca, ānanda, ke ca aññatitthiyā paribbājakā bālā abyattā ke ca tathāgatassa mahākammavibhaṅgaṃ jānissanti?**Still, who are those foolish and incompetent wanderers who follow other paths to understand the Realized One’s great analysis of deeds?*";
P_HTM[5759]="*Sace tumhe, ānanda, suṇeyyātha tathāgatassa mahākammavibhaṅgaṃ vibhajantassā”ti.**Ānanda, if only you would all listen to the Realized One’s explanation of the great analysis of deeds.”*";
P_HTM[5760]="*“Etassa, bhagavā, kālo, etassa, sugata, kālo**“Now is the time, Blessed One! Now is the time, Holy One!*";
P_HTM[5761]="*yaṃ bhagavā mahākammavibhaṅgaṃ vibhajeyya. Bhagavato sutvā bhikkhū dhāressantī”ti.**Let the Buddha explain the great analysis of deeds. The mendicants will listen and remember it.”*";
P_HTM[5762]="*“Tena hānanda, suṇāhi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, Ānanda, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[5763]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[5764]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[5765]="*“Cattārome, ānanda, puggalā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasmiṃ.**“Ānanda, these four people are found in the world.*";
P_HTM[5766]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[5767]="*Idhānanda, ekacco puggalo idha pāṇātipātī hoti, adinnādāyī hoti, kāmesumicchācārī hoti, musāvādī hoti, pisuṇavāco hoti, pharusavāco hoti, samphappalāpī hoti, abhijjhālu hoti, byāpannacitto hoti, micchādiṭṭhi hoti.**Some person here kills living creatures, steals, and commits sexual misconduct. They use speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical. And they’re covetous, malicious, and have wrong view.*";
P_HTM[5768]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati. (1)**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[5769]="*Idha panānanda, ekacco puggalo idha pāṇātipātī hoti, adinnādāyī hoti, kāmesumicchācārī hoti, musāvādī hoti, pisuṇavāco hoti, pharusavāco hoti, samphappalāpī hoti, abhijjhālu hoti, byāpannacitto hoti, micchādiṭṭhi hoti.**But some other person here kills living creatures, steals, and commits sexual misconduct. They use speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical. And they’re covetous, malicious, and have wrong view.*";
P_HTM[5770]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati. (2)**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5771]="*Idhānanda, ekacco puggalo idha pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti, adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti, kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato hoti, musāvādā paṭivirato hoti, pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti, pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti, samphappalāpā paṭivirato hoti, anabhijjhālu hoti, abyāpannacitto hoti, sammādiṭṭhi hoti.**But some other person here refrains from killing living creatures, stealing, committing sexual misconduct, or using speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical. And they’re contented, kind-hearted, and have right view.*";
P_HTM[5772]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati. (3)**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5773]="*Idha panānanda, ekacco puggalo idha pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti, adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti, kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato hoti, musāvādā paṭivirato hoti, pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti, pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti, samphappalāpā paṭivirato hoti, anabhijjhālu hoti, abyāpannacitto hoti, sammādiṭṭhi hoti.**But some other person here refrains from killing living creatures, stealing, committing sexual misconduct, or using speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical. And they’re contented, kind-hearted, and have right view.*";
P_HTM[5774]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati. (4)**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[5775]="*Idhānanda, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati yathāsamāhite citte dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena amuṃ puggalaṃ passati—**Now, some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that it gives rise to clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman. With that clairvoyance they see that person*";
P_HTM[5776]="*idha pāṇātipātiṃ adinnādāyiṃ kāmesumicchācāriṃ musāvādiṃ pisuṇavācaṃ pharusavācaṃ samphappalāpiṃ abhijjhāluṃ byāpannacittaṃ micchādiṭṭhiṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā passati apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannaṃ.**here who killed living creatures, stole, and committed sexual misconduct; who used speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical; and who was covetous, malicious, and had wrong view. And they see that, when their body breaks up, after death, that person is reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[5777]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[5778]="*‘atthi kira, bho, pāpakāni kammāni, atthi duccaritassa vipāko.**‘It seems that there is such a thing as bad deeds, and the result of bad conduct.*";
P_HTM[5779]="*Amāhaṃ puggalaṃ addasaṃ idha pāṇātipātiṃ adinnādāyiṃ … pe … micchādiṭṭhiṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā passāmi apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannan’ti.**For I saw a person here who killed living creatures … and had wrong view. And when their body broke up, after death, they were reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.’*";
P_HTM[5780]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[5781]="*‘yo kira, bho, pāṇātipātī adinnādāyī … pe … micchādiṭṭhi, sabbo so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**‘It seems that everyone who kills living creatures … and has wrong view is reborn in hell.*";
P_HTM[5782]="*Ye evaṃ jānanti, te sammā jānanti; ye aññathā jānanti, micchā tesaṃ ñāṇan’ti.**Those who know this are right. Those who know something else are wrong.’*";
P_HTM[5783]="*Iti so yadeva tassa sāmaṃ ñātaṃ sāmaṃ diṭṭhaṃ sāmaṃ viditaṃ tadeva tattha thāmasā parāmāsā abhinivissa voharati: ‘idameva saccaṃ, moghamaññan’ti. (1)**And so they obstinately stick to what they have known, seen, and understood for themselves, insisting that: ‘This is the only truth, other ideas are silly.’*";
P_HTM[5784]="*Idha panānanda, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati yathāsamāhite citte dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena amuṃ puggalaṃ passati—**But some other ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that it gives rise to clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman. With that clairvoyance they see that person*";
P_HTM[5785]="*idha pāṇātipātiṃ adinnādāyiṃ … pe … micchādiṭṭhiṃ, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā passati sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannaṃ.**here who killed living creatures … and had wrong view. And they see that that person is reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5786]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[5787]="*‘natthi kira, bho, pāpakāni kammāni, natthi duccaritassa vipāko.**‘It seems that there is no such thing as bad deeds, and the result of bad conduct.*";
P_HTM[5788]="*Amāhaṃ puggalaṃ addasaṃ—idha pāṇātipātiṃ adinnādāyiṃ … pe … micchādiṭṭhiṃ, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā passāmi sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannan’ti.**For I have seen a person here who killed living creatures … and had wrong view. And I saw that that person was reborn in a heavenly realm.’*";
P_HTM[5789]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[5790]="*‘yo kira, bho, pāṇātipātī adinnādāyī … pe … micchādiṭṭhi, sabbo so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**‘It seems that everyone who kills living creatures … and has wrong view is reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5791]="*Ye evaṃ jānanti te sammā jānanti; ye aññathā jānanti, micchā tesaṃ ñāṇan’ti.**Those who know this are right. Those who know something else are wrong.’*";
P_HTM[5792]="*Iti so yadeva tassa sāmaṃ ñātaṃ sāmaṃ diṭṭhaṃ sāmaṃ viditaṃ tadeva tattha thāmasā parāmāsā abhinivissa voharati: ‘idameva saccaṃ, moghamaññan’ti. (2)**And so they obstinately stick to what they have known, seen, and understood for themselves, insisting that: ‘This is the only truth, other ideas are silly.’*";
P_HTM[5793]="*Idhānanda, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati yathāsamāhite citte dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena amuṃ puggalaṃ passati—**Take some ascetic or brahmin who with clairvoyance sees a person*";
P_HTM[5794]="*idha pāṇātipātā paṭivirataṃ adinnādānā paṭivirataṃ kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirataṃ musāvādā paṭivirataṃ pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirataṃ pharusāya vācāya paṭivirataṃ samphappalāpā paṭivirataṃ anabhijjhāluṃ abyāpannacittaṃ sammādiṭṭhiṃ, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā passati sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannaṃ.**here who refrained from killing living creatures … and had right view. And they see that that person is reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5795]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[5796]="*‘atthi kira, bho, kalyāṇāni kammāni, atthi sucaritassa vipāko.**‘It seems that there is such a thing as good deeds, and the result of good conduct.*";
P_HTM[5797]="*Amāhaṃ puggalaṃ addasaṃ—idha pāṇātipātā paṭivirataṃ adinnādānā paṭivirataṃ … pe … sammādiṭṭhiṃ, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā passāmi sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannan’ti.**For I have seen a person here who refrained from killing living creatures … and had right view. And I saw that that person was reborn in a heavenly realm.’*";
P_HTM[5798]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[5799]="*‘yo kira, bho, pāṇātipātā paṭivirato adinnādānā paṭivirato … pe … sammādiṭṭhi sabbo so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**‘It seems that everyone who refrains from killing living creatures … and has right view is reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5800]="*Ye evaṃ jānanti te sammā jānanti; ye aññathā jānanti, micchā tesaṃ ñāṇan’ti.**Those who know this are right. Those who know something else are wrong.’*";
P_HTM[5801]="*Iti so yadeva tassa sāmaṃ ñātaṃ sāmaṃ diṭṭhaṃ sāmaṃ viditaṃ tadeva tattha thāmasā parāmāsā abhinivissa voharati: ‘idameva saccaṃ, moghamaññan’ti. (3)**And so they obstinately stick to what they have known, seen, and understood for themselves, insisting that: ‘This is the only truth, other ideas are silly.’*";
P_HTM[5802]="*Idha panānanda, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati yathāsamāhite citte dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena amuṃ puggalaṃ passati—idha pāṇātipātā paṭivirataṃ … pe … sammādiṭṭhiṃ, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā passati apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannaṃ.**Take some ascetic or brahmin who with clairvoyance sees a person here who refrained from killing living creatures … and had right view. And they see that that person is reborn in hell.*";
P_HTM[5803]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[5804]="*‘natthi kira, bho, kalyāṇāni kammāni, natthi sucaritassa vipāko. Amāhaṃ puggalaṃ addasaṃ—**‘It seems that there is no such thing as good deeds, and the result of good conduct. For I have seen a person*";
P_HTM[5805]="*idha pāṇātipātā paṭivirataṃ adinnādānā paṭivirataṃ … pe … sammādiṭṭhiṃ, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā passāmi apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannan’ti.**here who refrained from killing living creatures … and had right view. And I saw that that person was reborn in hell.’*";
P_HTM[5806]="*So evamāha: ‘yo kira, bho, pāṇātipātā paṭivirato adinnādānā paṭivirato … pe … sammādiṭṭhi, sabbo so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**They say: ‘It seems that everyone who refrains from killing living creatures … and has right view is reborn in hell.*";
P_HTM[5807]="*Ye evaṃ jānanti te sammā jānanti; ye aññathā jānanti, micchā tesaṃ ñāṇan’ti.**Those who know this are right. Those who know something else are wrong.’*";
P_HTM[5808]="*Iti so yadeva tassa sāmaṃ ñātaṃ sāmaṃ diṭṭhaṃ sāmaṃ viditaṃ tadeva tattha thāmasā parāmāsā abhinivissa voharati: ‘idameva saccaṃ, moghamaññan’ti. (4)**And so they obstinately stick to what they have known, seen, and understood for themselves, insisting that: ‘This is the only truth, other ideas are silly.’*";
P_HTM[5809]="*Tatrānanda, yvāyaṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā evamāha:**In this case, when an ascetic or brahmin says this:*";
P_HTM[5810]="*‘atthi kira, bho, pāpakāni kammāni, atthi duccaritassa vipāko’ti idamassa anujānāmi;**‘It seems that there is such a thing as bad deeds, and the result of bad conduct,’ I grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5811]="*yampi so evamāha:**And when they say:*";
P_HTM[5812]="*‘amāhaṃ puggalaṃ addasaṃ—idha pāṇātipātiṃ adinnādāyiṃ … pe … micchādiṭṭhiṃ, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā passāmi apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannan’ti idampissa anujānāmi;**‘I have seen a person here who killed living creatures … and had wrong view. And after death, they were reborn in hell,’ I also grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5813]="*yañca kho so evamāha:**But when they say:*";
P_HTM[5814]="*‘yo kira, bho, pāṇātipātī adinnādāyī … pe … micchādiṭṭhi, sabbo so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjatī’ti idamassa nānujānāmi;**‘It seems that everyone who kills living creatures … and has wrong view is reborn in hell,’ I don’t grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5815]="*yampi so evamāha:**And when they say:*";
P_HTM[5816]="*‘ye evaṃ jānanti te sammā jānanti; ye aññathā jānanti, micchā tesaṃ ñāṇan’ti idampissa nānujānāmi;**‘Those who know this are right. Those who know something else are wrong,’ I also don’t grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5817]="*yampi so yadeva tassa sāmaṃ ñātaṃ sāmaṃ diṭṭhaṃ sāmaṃ viditaṃ tadeva tattha thāmasā parāmāsā abhinivissa voharati: ‘idameva saccaṃ, moghamaññan’ti idampissa nānujānāmi.**And when they obstinately stick to what they have known, seen, and understood for themselves, insisting that: ‘This is the only truth, other ideas are silly,’ I also don’t grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5818]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[5819]="*Aññathā hi, ānanda, tathāgatassa mahākammavibhaṅge ñāṇaṃ hoti. (1)**Because the Realized One’s knowledge of the great analysis of deeds is otherwise.*";
P_HTM[5820]="*Tatrānanda, yvāyaṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā evamāha:**In this case, when an ascetic or brahmin says this:*";
P_HTM[5821]="*‘natthi kira, bho, pāpakāni kammāni, natthi duccaritassa vipāko’ti idamassa nānujānāmi;**‘It seems that there is no such thing as bad deeds, and the result of bad conduct,’ I don’t grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5822]="*yañca kho so evamāha:**But when they say:*";
P_HTM[5823]="*‘amāhaṃ puggalaṃ addasaṃ—idha pāṇātipātiṃ adinnādāyiṃ … pe … micchādiṭṭhiṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā passāmi sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannan’ti idamassa anujānāmi;**‘I have seen a person here who killed living creatures … and had wrong view. And I saw that that person was reborn in a heavenly realm,’ I grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5824]="*yañca kho so evamāha:**But when they say:*";
P_HTM[5825]="*‘yo kira, bho, pāṇātipātī adinnādāyī … pe … micchādiṭṭhi, sabbo so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjatī’ti idamassa nānujānāmi;**‘It seems that everyone who kills living creatures … and has wrong view is reborn in a heavenly realm,’ I don’t grant them that. …*";
P_HTM[5826]="*yampi so evamāha:* **";
P_HTM[5827]="*‘ye evaṃ jānanti te sammā jānanti; ye aññathā jānanti, micchā tesaṃ ñāṇan’ti idampissa nānujānāmi;* **";
P_HTM[5828]="*yampi so yadeva tassa sāmaṃ ñātaṃ sāmaṃ diṭṭhaṃ sāmaṃ viditaṃ tadeva tattha thāmasā parāmāsā abhinivissa voharati: ‘idameva saccaṃ, moghamaññan’ti idampissa nānujānāmi.* **";
P_HTM[5829]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[5830]="*Aññathā hi, ānanda, tathāgatassa mahākammavibhaṅge ñāṇaṃ hoti. (2)**Because the Realized One’s knowledge of the great analysis of deeds is otherwise.*";
P_HTM[5831]="*Tatrānanda, yvāyaṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā evamāha:**In this case, when an ascetic or brahmin says this:*";
P_HTM[5832]="*‘atthi kira, bho, kalyāṇāni kammāni, atthi sucaritassa vipāko’ti idamassa anujānāmi;**‘It seems that there is such a thing as good deeds, and the result of good conduct,’ I grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5833]="*yampi so evamāha:**And when they say:*";
P_HTM[5834]="*‘amāhaṃ puggalaṃ addasaṃ—idha pāṇātipātā paṭivirataṃ adinnādānā paṭivirataṃ … pe … sammādiṭṭhiṃ, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā passāmi sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannan’ti idampissa anujānāmi;**‘I have seen a person here who refrained from killing living creatures … and had right view. And I saw that that person was reborn in a heavenly realm,’ I grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5835]="*yañca kho so evamāha:**But when they say:*";
P_HTM[5836]="*‘yo kira, bho, pāṇātipātā paṭivirato adinnādānā paṭivirato … pe … sammādiṭṭhi, sabbo so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjatī’ti idamassa nānujānāmi;**‘It seems that everyone who refrains from killing living creatures … and has right view is reborn in a heavenly realm,’ I don’t grant them that. …*";
P_HTM[5837]="*yampi so evamāha:* **";
P_HTM[5838]="*‘ye evaṃ jānanti te sammā jānanti; ye aññathā jānanti, micchā tesaṃ ñāṇan’ti idampissa nānujānāmi;* **";
P_HTM[5839]="*yampi so yadeva tassa sāmaṃ ñātaṃ sāmaṃ diṭṭhaṃ sāmaṃ viditaṃ tadeva tattha thāmasā parāmāsā abhinivissa voharati: ‘idameva saccaṃ, moghamaññan’ti idampissa nānujānāmi.* **";
P_HTM[5840]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[5841]="*Aññathā hi, ānanda, tathāgatassa mahākammavibhaṅge ñāṇaṃ hoti. (3)**Because the Realized One’s knowledge of the great analysis of deeds is otherwise.*";
P_HTM[5842]="*Tatrānanda, yvāyaṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā evamāha:**In this case, when an ascetic or brahmin says this:*";
P_HTM[5843]="*‘natthi kira, bho, kalyāṇāni kammāni, natthi sucaritassa vipāko’ti idamassa nānujānāmi;**‘It seems that there is no such thing as good deeds, and the result of good conduct,’ I don’t grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5844]="*yañca kho so evamāha:**But when they say:*";
P_HTM[5845]="*‘amāhaṃ puggalaṃ addasaṃ—idha pāṇātipātā paṭivirataṃ adinnādānā paṭivirataṃ … pe … sammādiṭṭhiṃ, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā passāmi apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannan’ti idamassa anujānāmi;**‘I have seen a person here who refrained from killing living creatures … and had right view. And after death, they were reborn in hell,’ I grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5846]="*yañca kho so evamāha:**But when they say:*";
P_HTM[5847]="*‘yo kira, bho, pāṇātipātā paṭivirato adinnādānā paṭivirato … pe … sammādiṭṭhi, sabbo so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjatī’ti idamassa nānujānāmi;**‘It seems that everyone who refrains from killing living creatures … and has right view is reborn in hell,’ I don’t grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5848]="*yañca kho so evamāha: ‘ye evaṃ jānanti te sammā jānanti;**But when they say: ‘Those who know this are right.*";
P_HTM[5849]="*ye aññathā jānanti, micchā tesaṃ ñāṇan’ti idampissa nānujānāmi;**Those who know something else are wrong,’ I also don’t grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5850]="*yampi so yadeva tassa sāmaṃ ñātaṃ sāmaṃ diṭṭhaṃ sāmaṃ viditaṃ tadeva tattha thāmasā parāmāsā abhinivissa voharati: ‘idameva saccaṃ, moghamaññan’ti idampissa nānujānāmi.**And when they obstinately stick to what they have known, seen, and understood for themselves, insisting that: ‘This is the only truth, other ideas are silly,’ I also don’t grant them that.*";
P_HTM[5851]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[5852]="*Aññathā hi, ānanda, tathāgatassa mahākammavibhaṅge ñāṇaṃ hoti. (4)**Because the Realized One’s knowledge of the great analysis of deeds is otherwise.*";
P_HTM[5853]="*Tatrānanda, yvāyaṃ puggalo idha pāṇātipātī adinnādāyī … pe … micchādiṭṭhi, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati,**Now, Ānanda, take the case of the person here who killed living creatures … and had wrong view, and who, when their body breaks up, after death, is reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[5854]="*pubbe vāssa taṃ kataṃ hoti pāpakammaṃ dukkhavedanīyaṃ, pacchā vāssa taṃ kataṃ hoti pāpakammaṃ dukkhavedanīyaṃ, maraṇakāle vāssa hoti micchādiṭṭhi samattā samādinnā.**They must have done a bad deed to be experienced as painful either previously or later, or else at the time of death they undertook wrong view.*";
P_HTM[5855]="*Tena so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**And that’s why, when their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[5856]="*Yañca kho so idha pāṇātipātī hoti adinnādāyī hoti … pe … micchādiṭṭhi hoti tassa diṭṭheva dhamme vipākaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti upapajja vā apare vā pariyāye. (1)**But anyone here who kills living creatures … and has wrong view experiences the result of that in the present life, or in the next life, or in some subsequent period.*";
P_HTM[5857]="*Tatrānanda, yvāyaṃ puggalo idha pāṇātipātī adinnādāyī … pe … micchādiṭṭhi kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati,**Now, Ānanda, take the case of the person here who killed living creatures … and had wrong view, and who is reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5858]="*pubbe vāssa taṃ kataṃ hoti kalyāṇakammaṃ sukhavedanīyaṃ, pacchā vāssa taṃ kataṃ hoti kalyāṇakammaṃ sukhavedanīyaṃ, maraṇakāle vāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi samattā samādinnā.**They must have done a good deed to be experienced as pleasant either previously or later, or else at the time of death they undertook right view.*";
P_HTM[5859]="*Tena so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**And that’s why, when their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5860]="*Yañca kho so idha pāṇātipātī hoti adinnādāyī hoti … pe … micchādiṭṭhi hoti tassa diṭṭheva dhamme vipākaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti upapajja vā apare vā pariyāye. (2)**But anyone here who kills living creatures … and has wrong view experiences the result of that in the present life, or in the next life, or in some subsequent period.*";
P_HTM[5861]="*Tatrānanda, yvāyaṃ puggalo idha pāṇātipātā paṭivirato adinnādānā paṭivirato … pe … sammādiṭṭhi, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati,**Now, Ānanda, take the case of the person here who refrained from killing living creatures … and had right view, and who is reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5862]="*pubbe vāssa taṃ kataṃ hoti kalyāṇakammaṃ sukhavedanīyaṃ, pacchā vāssa taṃ kataṃ hoti kalyāṇakammaṃ sukhavedanīyaṃ, maraṇakāle vāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi samattā samādinnā.**They must have done a good deed to be experienced as pleasant either previously or later, or else at the time of death they undertook right view.*";
P_HTM[5863]="*Tena so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**And that’s why, when their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5864]="*Yañca kho so idha pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti … pe … sammādiṭṭhi hoti, tassa diṭṭheva dhamme vipākaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti upapajja vā apare vā pariyāye. (3)**But anyone here who refrains from killing living creatures … and has right view experiences the result of that in the present life, or in the next life, or in some subsequent period.*";
P_HTM[5865]="*Tatrānanda, yvāyaṃ puggalo idha pāṇātipātā paṭivirato adinnādānā paṭivirato … pe … sammādiṭṭhi, kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati,**Now, Ānanda, take the case of the person here who refrained from killing living creatures … and had right view, and who is reborn in hell.*";
P_HTM[5866]="*pubbe vāssa taṃ kataṃ hoti pāpakammaṃ dukkhavedanīyaṃ, pacchā vāssa taṃ kataṃ hoti pāpakammaṃ dukkhavedanīyaṃ, maraṇakāle vāssa hoti micchādiṭṭhi samattā samādinnā.**They must have done a bad deed to be experienced as painful either previously or later, or else at the time of death they undertook wrong view.*";
P_HTM[5867]="*Tena so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**And that’s why, when their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[5868]="*Yañca kho so idha pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti, adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti … pe … sammādiṭṭhi hoti, tassa diṭṭheva dhamme vipākaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti upapajja vā apare vā pariyāye. (4)**But anyone here who refrains from killing living creatures … and has right view experiences the result of that in the present life, or in the next life, or in some subsequent period.*";
P_HTM[5869]="*Iti kho, ānanda, atthi kammaṃ abhabbaṃ abhabbābhāsaṃ, atthi kammaṃ abhabbaṃ bhabbābhāsaṃ, atthi kammaṃ bhabbañceva bhabbābhāsañca, atthi kammaṃ bhabbaṃ abhabbābhāsan”ti.**So, Ānanda, there are deeds that are ineffective and appear ineffective. There are deeds that are ineffective but appear effective. There are deeds that are effective and appear effective. And there are deeds that are effective but appear ineffective.”*";
P_HTM[5870]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[5871]="*Attamano āyasmā ānando bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Ānanda was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[5872]="*Mahākammavibhaṅgasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5873]="*137. Saḷāyatanavibhaṅgasutta**The Analysis of the Six Sense Fields*";
P_HTM[5874]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[5875]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[5876]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[5877]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[5878]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[5879]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[5880]="*“saḷāyatanavibhaṅgaṃ vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I shall teach you the analysis of the six sense fields.*";
P_HTM[5881]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[5882]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[5883]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[5884]="*“‘Cha ajjhattikāni āyatanāni veditabbāni, cha bāhirāni āyatanāni veditabbāni, cha viññāṇakāyā veditabbā, cha phassakāyā veditabbā, aṭṭhārasa manopavicārā veditabbā, chattiṃsa sattapadā veditabbā, tatra idaṃ nissāya idaṃ pajahatha, tayo satipaṭṭhānā yadariyo sevati yadariyo sevamāno satthā gaṇamanusāsitumarahati, so vuccati yoggācariyānaṃ anuttaro purisadammasārathī’ti—**“‘The six interior sense fields should be understood. The six exterior sense fields should be understood. The six classes of consciousness should be understood. The six classes of contact should be understood. The eighteen mental preoccupations should be understood. The thirty-six positions of sentient beings should be understood. Therein, relying on this, give up that. The Noble One cultivates the establishment of mindfulness in three cases, by virtue of which they are a Teacher worthy to instruct a group. Of all meditation teachers, it is he that is called the supreme guide for those who wish to train.’*";
P_HTM[5885]="*ayamuddeso saḷāyatanavibhaṅgassa.**This is the recitation passage for the analysis of the six sense fields.*";
P_HTM[5886]="*‘Cha ajjhattikāni āyatanāni veditabbānī’ti—**‘The six interior sense fields should be understood.’*";
P_HTM[5887]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[5888]="*‘Cakkhāyatanaṃ sotāyatanaṃ ghānāyatanaṃ jivhāyatanaṃ kāyāyatanaṃ manāyatanaṃ—**There are the sense fields of the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[5889]="*cha ajjhattikāni āyatanāni veditabbānī’ti—**‘The six interior sense fields should be understood.’*";
P_HTM[5890]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (1)**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[5891]="*‘Cha bāhirāni āyatanāni veditabbānī’ti—**‘The six exterior sense fields should be understood.’*";
P_HTM[5892]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[5893]="*‘Rūpāyatanaṃ saddāyatanaṃ gandhāyatanaṃ rasāyatanaṃ phoṭṭhabbāyatanaṃ dhammāyatanaṃ—**There are the sense fields of sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[5894]="*cha bāhirāni āyatanāni veditabbānī’ti—**‘The six exterior sense fields should be understood.’*";
P_HTM[5895]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (2)**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[5896]="*‘Cha viññāṇakāyā veditabbā’ti—**‘The six classes of consciousness should be understood.’*";
P_HTM[5897]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[5898]="*‘Cakkhuviññāṇaṃ sotaviññāṇaṃ ghānaviññāṇaṃ jivhāviññāṇaṃ kāyaviññāṇaṃ manoviññāṇaṃ—**There are eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5899]="*cha viññāṇakāyā veditabbā’ti—**‘The six classes of consciousness should be understood.’*";
P_HTM[5900]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (3)**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[5901]="*‘Cha phassakāyā veditabbā’ti—**‘The six classes of contact should be understood.’*";
P_HTM[5902]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[5903]="*‘Cakkhusamphasso sotasamphasso ghānasamphasso jivhāsamphasso kāyasamphasso manosamphasso—**There is contact through the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[5904]="*cha phassakāyā veditabbā’ti—**‘The six classes of contact should be understood.’*";
P_HTM[5905]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (4)**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[5906]="*‘Aṭṭhārasa manopavicārā veditabbā’ti—**‘The eighteen mental preoccupations should be understood.’*";
P_HTM[5907]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[5908]="*‘Cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā somanassaṭṭhānīyaṃ rūpaṃ upavicarati, domanassaṭṭhānīyaṃ rūpaṃ upavicarati, upekkhāṭṭhānīyaṃ rūpaṃ upavicarati.**Seeing a sight with the eye, one is preoccupied with a sight that’s a basis for happiness or sadness or equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5909]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**Hearing a sound with the ear …*";
P_HTM[5910]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā …**Smelling an odor with the nose …*";
P_HTM[5911]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā …**Tasting a flavor with the tongue …*";
P_HTM[5912]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā …**Feeling a touch with the body …*";
P_HTM[5913]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya somanassaṭṭhānīyaṃ dhammaṃ upavicarati, domanassaṭṭhānīyaṃ dhammaṃ upavicarati, upekkhāṭṭhānīyaṃ dhammaṃ upavicarati.**Becoming conscious of a thought with the mind, one is preoccupied with a thought that’s a basis for happiness or sadness or equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5914]="*Iti cha somanassūpavicārā, cha domanassūpavicārā, cha upekkhūpavicārā, aṭṭhārasa manopavicārā veditabbā’ti—**So there are six preoccupations with happiness, six preoccupations with sadness, and six preoccupations with equanimity. ‘The eighteen mental preoccupations should be understood.’*";
P_HTM[5915]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (5)**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[5916]="*‘Chattiṃsa sattapadā veditabbā’ti—**‘The thirty-six positions of sentient beings should be understood.’*";
P_HTM[5917]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[5918]="*Cha gehasitāni somanassāni, cha nekkhammasitāni somanassāni, cha gehasitāni domanassāni, cha nekkhammasitāni domanassāni, cha gehasitā upekkhā, cha nekkhammasitā upekkhā.**There are six kinds of lay happiness and six kinds of renunciate happiness. There are six kinds of lay sadness and six kinds of renunciate sadness. There are six kinds of lay equanimity and six kinds of renunciate equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5919]="*Tattha katamāni cha gehasitāni somanassāni?**And in this context what are the six kinds of lay happiness?*";
P_HTM[5920]="*Cakkhuviññeyyānaṃ rūpānaṃ iṭṭhānaṃ kantānaṃ manāpānaṃ manoramānaṃ lokāmisapaṭisaṃyuttānaṃ paṭilābhaṃ vā paṭilābhato samanupassato pubbe vā paṭiladdhapubbaṃ atītaṃ niruddhaṃ vipariṇataṃ samanussarato uppajjati somanassaṃ.**There are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasing, connected with the world’s material delights. Happiness arises when you regard it as a gain to obtain such sights, or when you recollect sights you formerly obtained that have passed, ceased, and perished.*";
P_HTM[5921]="*Yaṃ evarūpaṃ somanassaṃ idaṃ vuccati gehasitaṃ somanassaṃ.**Such happiness is called lay happiness.*";
P_HTM[5922]="*Sotaviññeyyānaṃ saddānaṃ …**There are sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[5923]="*ghānaviññeyyānaṃ gandhānaṃ …**Smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[5924]="*jivhāviññeyyānaṃ rasānaṃ …**Tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[5925]="*kāyaviññeyyānaṃ phoṭṭhabbānaṃ …**Touches known by the body …*";
P_HTM[5926]="*manoviññeyyānaṃ dhammānaṃ iṭṭhānaṃ kantānaṃ manāpānaṃ … pe … somanassaṃ.**Thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasing, connected with the world’s material delights. Happiness arises when you regard it as a gain to obtain such thoughts, or when you recollect thoughts you formerly obtained that have passed, ceased, and perished.*";
P_HTM[5927]="*Yaṃ evarūpaṃ somanassaṃ idaṃ vuccati gehasitaṃ somanassaṃ.**Such happiness is called lay happiness.*";
P_HTM[5928]="*Imāni cha gehasitāni somanassāni.**These are the six kinds of lay happiness.*";
P_HTM[5929]="*Tattha katamāni cha nekkhammasitāni somanassāni?**And in this context what are the six kinds of renunciate happiness?*";
P_HTM[5930]="*Rūpānaṃ tveva aniccataṃ viditvā vipariṇāmavirāganirodhaṃ, ‘pubbe ceva rūpā etarahi ca sabbe te rūpā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato uppajjati somanassaṃ.**When you’ve understood the impermanence of sights—their perishing, fading away, and cessation—happiness arises as you truly understand through right understanding that both formerly and now all those sights are impermanent, suffering, and perishable.*";
P_HTM[5931]="*Yaṃ evarūpaṃ somanassaṃ idaṃ vuccati nekkhammasitaṃ somanassaṃ.**Such happiness is called renunciate happiness.*";
P_HTM[5932]="*Saddānaṃ tveva …**When you’ve understood the impermanence of sounds …*";
P_HTM[5933]="*gandhānaṃ tveva …**smells …*";
P_HTM[5934]="*rasānaṃ tveva …**tastes …*";
P_HTM[5935]="*phoṭṭhabbānaṃ tveva …**touches …*";
P_HTM[5936]="*dhammānaṃ tveva aniccataṃ viditvā vipariṇāmavirāganirodhaṃ, ‘pubbe ceva dhammā etarahi ca sabbe te dhammā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato uppajjati somanassaṃ.**thoughts—their perishing, fading away, and cessation—happiness arises as you truly understand through right understanding that both formerly and now all those thoughts are impermanent, suffering, and perishable.*";
P_HTM[5937]="*Yaṃ evarūpaṃ somanassaṃ idaṃ vuccati nekkhammasitaṃ somanassaṃ.**Such happiness is called renunciate happiness.*";
P_HTM[5938]="*Imāni cha nekkhammasitāni somanassāni.**These are the six kinds of renunciate happiness.*";
P_HTM[5939]="*Tattha katamāni cha gehasitāni domanassāni?**And in this context what are the six kinds of lay sadness?*";
P_HTM[5940]="*Cakkhuviññeyyānaṃ rūpānaṃ …**There are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasing, connected with the world’s material delights. Sadness arises when you regard it as a loss to lose such sights, or when you recollect sights you formerly lost that have passed, ceased, and perished.*";
P_HTM[5941]="*pe …**Such sadness is called lay sadness.*";
P_HTM[5942]="*sotaviññeyyānaṃ saddānaṃ …**There are sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[5943]="*ghānaviññeyyānaṃ gandhānaṃ …**There are smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[5944]="*jivhāviññeyyānaṃ rasānaṃ …**There are tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[5945]="*kāyaviññeyyānaṃ phoṭṭhabbānaṃ …**There are touches known by the body …*";
P_HTM[5946]="*manoviññeyyānaṃ dhammānaṃ iṭṭhānaṃ kantānaṃ manāpānaṃ manoramānaṃ lokāmisapaṭisaṃyuttānaṃ appaṭilābhaṃ vā appaṭilābhato samanupassato pubbe vā appaṭiladdhapubbaṃ atītaṃ niruddhaṃ vipariṇataṃ samanussarato uppajjati domanassaṃ.**There are thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasing, connected with the world’s material delights. Sadness arises when you regard it as a loss to lose such thoughts, or when you recollect thoughts you formerly lost that have passed, ceased, and perished.*";
P_HTM[5947]="*Yaṃ evarūpaṃ domanassaṃ idaṃ vuccati gehasitaṃ domanassaṃ.**Such sadness is called lay sadness.*";
P_HTM[5948]="*Imāni cha gehasitāni domanassāni.**These are the six kinds of lay sadness.*";
P_HTM[5949]="*“Tattha katamāni cha nekkhammasitāni domanassāni?**And in this context what are the six kinds of renunciate sadness?*";
P_HTM[5950]="*Rūpānaṃ tveva aniccataṃ viditvā vipariṇāmavirāganirodhaṃ, ‘pubbe ceva rūpā etarahi ca sabbe te rūpā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya disvā anuttaresu vimokkhesu pihaṃ upaṭṭhāpeti:**When you’ve understood the impermanence of sights—their perishing, fading away, and cessation—you truly understand through right understanding that both formerly and now all those sights are impermanent, suffering, and perishable. Upon seeing this, you give rise to yearning for the supreme liberations:*";
P_HTM[5951]="*‘kudāssu nāmāhaṃ tadāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharissāmi yadariyā etarahi āyatanaṃ upasampajja viharantī’ti iti anuttaresu vimokkhesu pihaṃ upaṭṭhāpayato uppajjati pihapaccayā domanassaṃ.**‘Oh, when will I enter and remain in the same dimension that the noble ones enter and remain in today?’ When you give rise to yearning for the supreme liberations like this, sadness arises because of the yearning.*";
P_HTM[5952]="*Yaṃ evarūpaṃ domanassaṃ idaṃ vuccati nekkhammasitaṃ domanassaṃ.**Such sadness is called renunciate sadness.*";
P_HTM[5953]="*Saddānaṃ tveva … pe …**When you’ve understood the impermanence of sounds …*";
P_HTM[5954]="*gandhānaṃ tveva …**smells …*";
P_HTM[5955]="*rasānaṃ tveva …**tastes …*";
P_HTM[5956]="*phoṭṭhabbānaṃ tveva …**touches …*";
P_HTM[5957]="*dhammānaṃ tveva aniccataṃ viditvā vipariṇāmavirāganirodhaṃ, ‘pubbe ceva dhammā etarahi ca sabbe te dhammā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya disvā anuttaresu vimokkhesu pihaṃ upaṭṭhāpeti:**thoughts—their perishing, fading away, and cessation—you truly understand through right understanding that both formerly and now all those thoughts are impermanent, suffering, and perishable. Upon seeing this, you give rise to yearning for the supreme liberations:*";
P_HTM[5958]="*‘kudāssu nāmāhaṃ tadāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharissāmi yadariyā etarahi āyatanaṃ upasampajja viharantī’ti iti anuttaresu vimokkhesu pihaṃ upaṭṭhāpayato uppajjati pihapaccayā domanassaṃ.**‘Oh, when will I enter and remain in the same dimension that the noble ones enter and remain in today?’ When you give rise to yearning for the supreme liberations like this, sadness arises because of the yearning.*";
P_HTM[5959]="*Yaṃ evarūpaṃ domanassaṃ idaṃ vuccati nekkhammasitaṃ domanassaṃ.**Such sadness is called renunciate sadness.*";
P_HTM[5960]="*Imāni cha nekkhammasitāni domanassāni.**These are the six kinds of renunciate sadness.*";
P_HTM[5961]="*Tattha katamā cha gehasitā upekkhā?**And in this context what are the six kinds of lay equanimity?*";
P_HTM[5962]="*Cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā uppajjati upekkhā bālassa mūḷhassa puthujjanassa anodhijinassa avipākajinassa anādīnavadassāvino assutavato puthujjanassa.**When seeing a sight with the eye, equanimity arises for the uneducated ordinary person—a foolish ordinary person who has not overcome their limitations and the results of deeds, and is blind to the drawbacks.*";
P_HTM[5963]="*Yā evarūpā upekkhā, rūpaṃ sā nātivattati.**Such equanimity does not transcend the sight.*";
P_HTM[5964]="*Tasmā sā upekkhā ‘gehasitā’ti vuccati.**That’s why it’s called lay equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5965]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā …**When hearing a sound with the ear …*";
P_HTM[5966]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā …**When smelling an odor with the nose …*";
P_HTM[5967]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā …**When tasting a flavor with the tongue …*";
P_HTM[5968]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā …**When feeling a touch with the body …*";
P_HTM[5969]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya uppajjati upekkhā bālassa mūḷhassa puthujjanassa anodhijinassa avipākajinassa anādīnavadassāvino assutavato puthujjanassa.**When knowing a thought with the mind, equanimity arises for the uneducated ordinary person—a foolish ordinary person who has not overcome their limitations and the results of deeds, and is blind to the drawbacks.*";
P_HTM[5970]="*Yā evarūpā upekkhā, dhammaṃ sā nātivattati.**Such equanimity does not transcend the thought.*";
P_HTM[5971]="*Tasmā sā upekkhā ‘gehasitā’ti vuccati.**That’s why it’s called lay equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5972]="*Imā cha gehasitā upekkhā.**These are the six kinds of lay equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5973]="*Tattha katamā cha nekkhammasitā upekkhā?**And in this context what are the six kinds of renunciate equanimity?*";
P_HTM[5974]="*Rūpānaṃ tveva aniccataṃ viditvā vipariṇāmavirāganirodhaṃ, ‘pubbe ceva rūpā etarahi ca sabbe te rūpā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato uppajjati upekkhā.**When you’ve understood the impermanence of sights—their perishing, fading away, and cessation—equanimity arises as you truly understand through right understanding that both formerly and now all those sights are impermanent, suffering, and perishable.*";
P_HTM[5975]="*Yā evarūpā upekkhā, rūpaṃ sā ativattati.**Such equanimity transcends the sight.*";
P_HTM[5976]="*Tasmā sā upekkhā ‘nekkhammasitā’ti vuccati.**That’s why it’s called renunciate equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5977]="*Saddānaṃ tveva …**When you’ve understood the impermanence of sounds …*";
P_HTM[5978]="*gandhānaṃ tveva …**smells …*";
P_HTM[5979]="*rasānaṃ tveva …**tastes …*";
P_HTM[5980]="*phoṭṭhabbānaṃ tveva …**touches …*";
P_HTM[5981]="*dhammānaṃ tveva aniccataṃ viditvā vipariṇāmavirāganirodhaṃ, ‘pubbe ceva dhammā etarahi ca sabbe te dhammā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato uppajjati upekkhā.**thoughts—their perishing, fading away, and cessation—equanimity arises as you truly understand through right understanding that both formerly and now all those thoughts are impermanent, suffering, and perishable.*";
P_HTM[5982]="*Yā evarūpā upekkhā, dhammaṃ sā ativattati.**Such equanimity transcends the thought.*";
P_HTM[5983]="*Tasmā sā upekkhā ‘nekkhammasitā’ti vuccati.**That’s why it’s called renunciate equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5984]="*Imā cha nekkhammasitā upekkhā.**These are the six kinds of renunciate equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5985]="*‘Chattiṃsa sattapadā veditabbā’ti—**‘The thirty-six positions of sentient beings should be understood.’*";
P_HTM[5986]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[5987]="*‘Tatra idaṃ nissāya idaṃ pajahathā’ti—**‘Therein, relying on this, give up that.’*";
P_HTM[5988]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ; Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[5989]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yāni cha nekkhammasitāni somanassāni tāni nissāya tāni āgamma yāni cha gehasitāni somanassāni tāni pajahatha, tāni samatikkamatha.**Therein, by relying and depending on the six kinds of renunciate happiness, give up and go beyond the six kinds of lay happiness.*";
P_HTM[5990]="*Evametesaṃ pahānaṃ hoti, evametesaṃ samatikkamo hoti.**That’s how they are given up.*";
P_HTM[5991]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yāni cha nekkhammasitāni domanassāni tāni nissāya tāni āgamma yāni cha gehasitāni domanassāni tāni pajahatha, tāni samatikkamatha.**Therein, by relying on the six kinds of renunciate sadness, give up the six kinds of lay sadness.*";
P_HTM[5992]="*Evametesaṃ pahānaṃ hoti, evametesaṃ samatikkamo hoti.**That’s how they are given up.*";
P_HTM[5993]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yā cha nekkhammasitā upekkhā tā nissāya tā āgamma, yā cha gehasitā upekkhā tā pajahatha tā samatikkamatha.**Therein, by relying on the six kinds of renunciate equanimity, give up the six kinds of lay equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5994]="*Evametāsaṃ pahānaṃ hoti, evametāsaṃ samatikkamo hoti.**That’s how they are given up.*";
P_HTM[5995]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yāni cha nekkhammasitāni somanassāni tāni nissāya tāni āgamma yāni cha nekkhammasitāni domanassāni tāni pajahatha, tāni samatikkamatha.**Therein, by relying on the six kinds of renunciate happiness, give up the six kinds of renunciate sadness.*";
P_HTM[5996]="*Evametesaṃ pahānaṃ hoti, evametesaṃ samatikkamo hoti.**That’s how they are given up.*";
P_HTM[5997]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yā cha nekkhammasitā upekkhā tā nissāya tā āgamma yāni cha nekkhammasitāni somanassāni tāni pajahatha, tāni samatikkamatha.**Therein, by relying on the six kinds of renunciate equanimity, give up the six kinds of renunciate happiness.*";
P_HTM[5998]="*Evametesaṃ pahānaṃ hoti, evametesaṃ samatikkamo hoti.**That’s how they are given up.*";
P_HTM[5999]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, upekkhā nānattā nānattasitā, atthi upekkhā ekattā ekattasitā.**There is equanimity that is diversified, based on diversity, and equanimity that is unified, based on unity.*";
P_HTM[6000]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, upekkhā nānattā nānattasitā?**And what is equanimity based on diversity?*";
P_HTM[6001]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, upekkhā rūpesu, atthi saddesu, atthi gandhesu, atthi rasesu, atthi phoṭṭhabbesu—**There is equanimity towards sights, sounds, smells, tastes, and touches.*";
P_HTM[6002]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, upekkhā nānattā nānattasitā.**This is equanimity based on diversity.*";
P_HTM[6003]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, upekkhā ekattā ekattasitā?**And what is equanimity based on unity?*";
P_HTM[6004]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, upekkhā ākāsānañcāyatananissitā, atthi viññāṇañcāyatananissitā, atthi ākiñcaññāyatananissitā, atthi nevasaññānāsaññāyatananissitā—**There is equanimity based on the dimensions of infinite space, infinite consciousness, nothingness, and neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[6005]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, upekkhā ekattā ekattasitā.**This is equanimity based on unity.*";
P_HTM[6006]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yāyaṃ upekkhā ekattā ekattasitā taṃ nissāya taṃ āgamma yāyaṃ upekkhā nānattā nānattasitā taṃ pajahatha, taṃ samatikkamatha.**Therein, relying on equanimity based on unity, give up equanimity based on diversity.*";
P_HTM[6007]="*Evametissā pahānaṃ hoti, evametissā samatikkamo hoti.**That’s how it is given up.*";
P_HTM[6008]="*Atammayataṃ, bhikkhave, nissāya atammayataṃ āgamma yāyaṃ upekkhā ekattā ekattasitā taṃ pajahatha, taṃ samatikkamatha.**Relying on non-identification, give up equanimity based on unity.*";
P_HTM[6009]="*Evametissā pahānaṃ hoti, evametissā samatikkamo hoti.**That’s how it is given up.*";
P_HTM[6010]="*‘Tatra idaṃ nissāya idaṃ pajahathā’ti—**‘Therein, relying on this, give up that.’*";
P_HTM[6011]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6012]="*‘Tayo satipaṭṭhānā yadariyo sevati, yadariyo sevamāno satthā gaṇamanusāsitumarahatī’ti—**‘The Noble One cultivates the establishment of mindfulness in three cases, by virtue of which they are a Teacher worthy to instruct a group.’*";
P_HTM[6013]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ;**That’s what I said,*";
P_HTM[6014]="*kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6015]="*Idha, bhikkhave, satthā sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ deseti anukampako hitesī anukampaṃ upādāya:**The first case is when the Teacher teaches the Dhamma out of kindness and compassion:*";
P_HTM[6016]="*‘idaṃ vo hitāya, idaṃ vo sukhāyā’ti.**‘This is for your welfare. This is for your happiness.’*";
P_HTM[6017]="*Tassa sāvakā na sussūsanti, na sotaṃ odahanti, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, vokkamma ca satthusāsanā vattanti.**But their disciples don’t want to listen. They don’t pay attention or apply their minds to understand. They proceed having turned away from the Teacher’s instruction.*";
P_HTM[6018]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, tathāgato na ceva anattamano hoti, na ca anattamanataṃ paṭisaṃvedeti, anavassuto ca viharati sato sampajāno.**In this case the Realized One is not displeased, he does not feel displeasure. He remains unaffected, mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[6019]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ satipaṭṭhānaṃ yadariyo sevati, yadariyo sevamāno satthā gaṇamanusāsitumarahati.**This is the first case in which the Noble One cultivates the establishment of mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[6020]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, satthā sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ deseti anukampako hitesī anukampaṃ upādāya:**The next case is when the Teacher teaches the Dhamma out of kindness and compassion:*";
P_HTM[6021]="*‘idaṃ vo hitāya, idaṃ vo sukhāyā’ti.**‘This is for your welfare. This is for your happiness.’*";
P_HTM[6022]="*Tassa ekacce sāvakā na sussūsanti, na sotaṃ odahanti, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, vokkamma ca satthusāsanā vattanti;**And some of their disciples don’t want to listen. They don’t pay attention or apply their minds to understand. They proceed having turned away from the Teacher’s instruction.*";
P_HTM[6023]="*ekacce sāvakā sussūsanti, sotaṃ odahanti, aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, na ca vokkamma satthusāsanā vattanti.**But some of their disciples do want to listen. They pay attention and apply their minds to understand. They don’t proceed having turned away from the Teacher’s instruction.*";
P_HTM[6024]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, tathāgato na ceva anattamano hoti, na ca anattamanataṃ paṭisaṃvedeti;**In this case the Realized One is not displeased,*";
P_HTM[6025]="*na ca attamano hoti, na ca attamanataṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**nor is he pleased.*";
P_HTM[6026]="*Anattamanatā ca attamanatā ca—* **";
P_HTM[6027]="*tadubhayaṃ abhinivajjetvā upekkhako viharati sato sampajāno.**Rejecting both displeasure and pleasure, he remains equanimous, mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[6028]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ satipaṭṭhānaṃ yadariyo sevati, yadariyo sevamāno satthā gaṇamanusāsitumarahati.**This is the second case in which the Noble One cultivates the establishment of mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[6029]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, satthā sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ deseti anukampako hitesī anukampaṃ upādāya:**The next case is when the Teacher teaches the Dhamma out of kindness and compassion:*";
P_HTM[6030]="*‘idaṃ vo hitāya, idaṃ vo sukhāyā’ti.**‘This is for your welfare. This is for your happiness.’*";
P_HTM[6031]="*Tassa sāvakā sussūsanti, sotaṃ odahanti, aññācittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, na ca vokkamma satthusāsanā vattanti.**And their disciples want to listen. They pay attention and apply their minds to understand. They don’t proceed having turned away from the Teacher’s instruction.*";
P_HTM[6032]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, tathāgato attamano ceva hoti, attamanatañca paṭisaṃvedeti, anavassuto ca viharati sato sampajāno.**In this case the Realized One is not pleased, he does not feel pleasure. He remains unaffected, mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[6033]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ satipaṭṭhānaṃ yadariyo sevati, yadariyo sevamāno satthā gaṇamanusāsitumarahati.**This is the third case in which the Noble One cultivates the establishment of mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[6034]="*‘Tayo satipaṭṭhānā yadariyo sevati, yadariyo sevamāno satthā gaṇamanusāsitumarahatī’ti—**‘The Noble One cultivates the establishment of mindfulness in three cases, by virtue of which they are a Teacher worthy to instruct a group.’*";
P_HTM[6035]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6036]="*‘So vuccati yoggācariyānaṃ anuttaro purisadammasārathī’ti—**‘Of all meditation teachers, it is he that is called the supreme guide for those who wish to train.’*";
P_HTM[6037]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6038]="*Hatthidamakena, bhikkhave, hatthidammo sārito ekaṃyeva disaṃ dhāvati—**Driven by an elephant trainer, an elephant in training proceeds in just one direction:*";
P_HTM[6039]="*puratthimaṃ vā pacchimaṃ vā uttaraṃ vā dakkhiṇaṃ vā.**east, west, north, or south.*";
P_HTM[6040]="*Assadamakena, bhikkhave, assadammo sārito ekaññeva disaṃ dhāvati—**Driven by a horse trainer, a horse in training proceeds in just one direction:*";
P_HTM[6041]="*puratthimaṃ vā pacchimaṃ vā uttaraṃ vā dakkhiṇaṃ vā.**east, west, north, or south.*";
P_HTM[6042]="*Godamakena, bhikkhave, godammo sārito ekaññeva disaṃ dhāvati—**Driven by an ox trainer, an ox in training proceeds in just one direction:*";
P_HTM[6043]="*puratthimaṃ vā pacchimaṃ vā uttaraṃ vā dakkhiṇaṃ vā.**east, west, north, or south.*";
P_HTM[6044]="*Tathāgatena hi, bhikkhave, arahatā sammāsambuddhena purisadammo sārito aṭṭha disā vidhāvati.**But driven by the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, a person in training proceeds in eight directions:*";
P_HTM[6045]="*Rūpī rūpāni passati—**Having physical form, they see visions.*";
P_HTM[6046]="*ayaṃ ekā disā;**This is the first direction.*";
P_HTM[6047]="*ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī bahiddhā rūpāni passati—**Not perceiving physical form internally, they see visions externally.*";
P_HTM[6048]="*ayaṃ dutiyā disā;**This is the second direction.*";
P_HTM[6049]="*subhantveva adhimutto hoti—**They’re focused only on beauty.*";
P_HTM[6050]="*ayaṃ tatiyā disā;**This is the third direction.*";
P_HTM[6051]="*sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati—**Going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[6052]="*ayaṃ catutthī disā;**This is the fourth direction.*";
P_HTM[6053]="*sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati—**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6054]="*ayaṃ pañcamī disā;**This is the fifth direction.*";
P_HTM[6055]="*sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati—**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they enter and remain in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[6056]="*ayaṃ chaṭṭhī disā;**This is the sixth direction.*";
P_HTM[6057]="*sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati—**Going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, they enter and remain in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[6058]="*ayaṃ sattamī disā;**This is the seventh direction.*";
P_HTM[6059]="*sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati—**Going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, they enter and remain in the cessation of perception and feeling.*";
P_HTM[6060]="*ayaṃ aṭṭhamī disā.**This is the eighth direction.*";
P_HTM[6061]="*Tathāgatena, bhikkhave, arahatā sammāsambuddhena purisadammo sārito imā aṭṭha disā vidhāvati.**Driven by the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, a person in training proceeds in these eight directions.*";
P_HTM[6062]="*So vuccati: ‘yoggācariyānaṃ anuttaro purisadammasārathī’ti—**‘Of all meditation teachers, it is he that is called the supreme guide for those who wish to train.’*";
P_HTM[6063]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttan”ti.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.”*";
P_HTM[6064]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[6065]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[6066]="*Saḷāyatanavibhaṅgasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6067]="*138. Uddesavibhaṅgasutta**The Analysis of a Recitation Passage*";
P_HTM[6068]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[6069]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[6070]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[6071]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[6072]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[6073]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[6074]="*“uddesavibhaṅgaṃ vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I shall teach you the analysis of a recitation passage.*";
P_HTM[6075]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[6076]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[6077]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[6078]="*“Tathā tathā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu upaparikkheyya yathā yathā upaparikkhato bahiddhā cassa viññāṇaṃ avikkhittaṃ avisaṭaṃ, ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhitaṃ anupādāya na paritasseyya.**“A mendicant should examine in any such a way that their consciousness is neither scattered and diffused externally nor stuck internally, and they are not anxious because of grasping.*";
P_HTM[6079]="*Bahiddhā, bhikkhave, viññāṇe avikkhitte avisaṭe sati ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhite anupādāya aparitassato āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇadukkhasamudayasambhavo na hotī”ti.**When this is the case and they are no longer anxious, there is for them no coming to be of the origin of suffering—of rebirth, old age, and death in the future.”*";
P_HTM[6080]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[6081]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ pāvisi.**When he had spoken, the Holy One got up from his seat and entered his dwelling.*";
P_HTM[6082]="*Atha kho tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ, acirapakkantassa bhagavato, etadahosi:**Soon after the Buddha left, those mendicants considered,*";
P_HTM[6083]="*“idaṃ kho no, āvuso, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:**“The Buddha gave this brief passage for recitation, then entered his dwelling without explaining the meaning in detail.*";
P_HTM[6084]="*‘tathā tathā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu upaparikkheyya yathā yathā upaparikkhato bahiddhā cassa viññāṇaṃ avikkhittaṃ avisaṭaṃ, ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhitaṃ anupādāya na paritasseyya.* **";
P_HTM[6085]="*Bahiddhā, bhikkhave, viññāṇe avikkhitte avisaṭe sati ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhite anupādāya aparitassato āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇadukkhasamudayasambhavo na hotī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[6086]="*Ko nu kho imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajeyyā”ti?**Who can explain in detail the meaning of this brief passage for recitation given by the Buddha?”*";
P_HTM[6087]="*Atha kho tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ etadahosi:**Then those mendicants thought,*";
P_HTM[6088]="*“ayaṃ kho āyasmā mahākaccāno satthu ceva saṃvaṇṇito sambhāvito ca viññūnaṃ sabrahmacārīnaṃ;**“This Venerable Mahākaccāna is praised by the Buddha and esteemed by his sensible spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[6089]="*pahoti cāyasmā mahākaccāno imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajituṃ.**He is capable of explaining in detail the meaning of this brief passage for recitation given by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[6090]="*Yannūna mayaṃ yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkameyyāma; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyāmā”ti.**Let’s go to him, and ask him about this matter.”*";
P_HTM[6091]="*Atha kho te bhikkhū yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā mahākaccānena saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**Then those mendicants went to Mahākaccāna, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[6092]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side. They told him what had happened, and said,*";
P_HTM[6093]="*“Idaṃ kho no, āvuso kaccāna, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:* **";
P_HTM[6094]="*‘tathā tathā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu upaparikkheyya yathā yathā upaparikkhato bahiddhā cassa viññāṇaṃ avikkhittaṃ avisaṭaṃ, ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhitaṃ anupādāya na paritasseyya.* **";
P_HTM[6095]="*Bahiddhā, bhikkhave, viññāṇe avikkhitte avisaṭe sati ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhite anupādāya aparitassato āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇadukkhasamudayasambhavo na hotī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[6096]="*Tesaṃ no, āvuso kaccāna, amhākaṃ, acirapakkantassa bhagavato, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[6097]="*‘idaṃ kho no, āvuso, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:* **";
P_HTM[6098]="*“tathā tathā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu upaparikkheyya, yathā yathā upaparikkhato bahiddhā cassa viññāṇaṃ avikkhittaṃ avisaṭaṃ ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhitaṃ anupādāya na paritasseyya.* **";
P_HTM[6099]="*Bahiddhā, bhikkhave, viññāṇe avikkhitte avisaṭe sati ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhite anupādāya aparitassato āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇadukkhasamudayasambhavo na hotī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6100]="*Ko nu kho imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajeyyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[6101]="*Tesaṃ no, āvuso kaccāna, amhākaṃ etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[6102]="*‘ayaṃ kho āyasmā mahākaccāno satthu ceva saṃvaṇṇito, sambhāvito ca viññūnaṃ sabrahmacārīnaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6103]="*Pahoti cāyasmā mahākaccāno imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajituṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6104]="*Yannūna mayaṃ yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkameyyāma; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyāmā’ti—* **";
P_HTM[6105]="*vibhajatāyasmā mahākaccāno”ti.**“May Venerable Mahākaccāna please explain this.”*";
P_HTM[6106]="*“Seyyathāpi, āvuso, puriso sāratthiko sāragavesī sārapariyesanaṃ caramāno mahato rukkhassa tiṭṭhato sāravato atikkammeva mūlaṃ atikkamma khandhaṃ sākhāpalāse sāraṃ pariyesitabbaṃ maññeyya,**“Reverends, suppose there was a person in need of heartwood. And while wandering in search of heartwood he’d come across a large tree standing with heartwood. But he’d pass over the roots and trunk, imagining that the heartwood should be sought in the branches and leaves.*";
P_HTM[6107]="*evaṃ sampadamidaṃ āyasmantānaṃ satthari sammukhībhūte taṃ bhagavantaṃ atisitvā amhe etamatthaṃ paṭipucchitabbaṃ maññatha.**Such is the consequence for the venerables. Though you were face to face with the Buddha, you passed him by, imagining that you should ask me about this matter.*";
P_HTM[6108]="*So hāvuso, bhagavā jānaṃ jānāti, passaṃ passati, cakkhubhūto ñāṇabhūto dhammabhūto brahmabhūto vattā pavattā atthassa ninnetā amatassa dātā dhammassāmī tathāgato.**For he is the Buddha, who knows and sees. He is vision, he is knowledge, he is the truth, he is supreme. He is the teacher, the proclaimer, the elucidator of meaning, the bestower of the deathless, the lord of truth, the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[6109]="*So ceva panetassa kālo ahosi yaṃ bhagavantaṃyeva etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyātha;**That was the time to approach the Buddha and ask about this matter.*";
P_HTM[6110]="*yathā vo bhagavā byākareyya tathā naṃ dhāreyyāthā”ti.**You should have remembered it in line with the Buddha’s answer.”*";
P_HTM[6111]="*“Addhāvuso kaccāna, bhagavā jānaṃ jānāti, passaṃ passati, cakkhubhūto ñāṇabhūto dhammabhūto brahmabhūto vattā pavattā atthassa ninnetā amatassa dātā dhammassāmī tathāgato.**“Certainly he is the Buddha, who knows and sees. He is vision, he is knowledge, he is the truth, he is supreme. He is the teacher, the proclaimer, the elucidator of meaning, the bestower of the deathless, the lord of truth, the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[6112]="*So ceva panetassa kālo ahosi yaṃ bhagavantaṃyeva etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyāma;**That was the time to approach the Buddha and ask about this matter.*";
P_HTM[6113]="*yathā no bhagavā byākareyya tathā naṃ dhāreyyāma.**We should have remembered it in line with the Buddha’s answer.*";
P_HTM[6114]="*Api cāyasmā mahākaccāno satthu ceva saṃvaṇṇito sambhāvito ca viññūnaṃ sabrahmacārīnaṃ.**Still, Venerable Mahākaccāna is praised by the Buddha and esteemed by his sensible spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[6115]="*Pahoti cāyasmā mahākaccāno imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajituṃ.**He is capable of explaining in detail the meaning of this brief passage for recitation given by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[6116]="*Vibhajatāyasmā mahākaccāno agaruṃ karitvā”ti.**Please explain this, if it’s no trouble.”*";
P_HTM[6117]="*“Tena hāvuso, suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, reverends, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[6118]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato mahākaccānassa paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[6119]="*Āyasmā mahākaccāno etadavoca:**Venerable Mahākaccāna said this:*";
P_HTM[6120]="*“Yaṃ kho no, āvuso, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:**“Reverends, the Buddha gave this brief passage for recitation, then entered his dwelling without explaining the meaning in detail:*";
P_HTM[6121]="*‘tathā tathā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu upaparikkheyya, yathā yathā upaparikkhato bahiddhā cassa viññāṇaṃ avikkhittaṃ avisaṭaṃ ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhitaṃ anupādāya na paritasseyya, bahiddhā, bhikkhave, viññāṇe avikkhitte avisaṭe sati ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhite anupādāya aparitassato āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇadukkhasamudayasambhavo na hotī’ti.**‘A mendicant should examine in any such a way that their consciousness is neither scattered and diffused externally nor stuck internally, and they are not anxious because of grasping. When this is the case and they are no longer anxious, there is for them no coming to be of the origin of suffering—of rebirth, old age, and death in the future.’*";
P_HTM[6122]="*Imassa kho ahaṃ, āvuso, bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmi.**And this is how I understand the detailed meaning of this passage for recitation.*";
P_HTM[6123]="*Kathañcāvuso, bahiddhā viññāṇaṃ vikkhittaṃ visaṭanti vuccati?**And how is consciousness scattered and diffused externally?*";
P_HTM[6124]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā rūpanimittānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti rūpanimittassādagadhitaṃ rūpanimittassādavinibandhaṃ rūpanimittassādasaṃyojanasaṃyuttaṃ bahiddhā viññāṇaṃ vikkhittaṃ visaṭanti vuccati.**Take a mendicant who sees a sight with their eyes. Their consciousness follows after the features of that sight, tied, attached, and fettered to gratification in its features. So their consciousness is said to be scattered and diffused externally.*";
P_HTM[6125]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**When they hear a sound with their ears …*";
P_HTM[6126]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā …**When they smell an odor with their nose …*";
P_HTM[6127]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā …**When they taste a flavor with their tongue …*";
P_HTM[6128]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā …**When they feel a touch with their body …*";
P_HTM[6129]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya dhammanimittānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti; dhammanimittassādagadhitaṃ dhammanimittassādavinibandhaṃ dhammanimittassādasaṃyojanasaṃyuttaṃ bahiddhā viññāṇaṃ vikkhittaṃ visaṭanti vuccati.**When they know a thought with their mind, their consciousness follows after the features of that thought, tied, attached, and fettered to gratification in its features. So their consciousness is said to be scattered and diffused externally.*";
P_HTM[6130]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bahiddhā viññāṇaṃ vikkhittaṃ visaṭanti vuccati.**That’s how consciousness is scattered and diffused externally.*";
P_HTM[6131]="*Kathañcāvuso, bahiddhā viññāṇaṃ avikkhittaṃ avisaṭanti vuccati?**And how is consciousness not scattered and diffused externally?*";
P_HTM[6132]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā na rūpanimittānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti, na rūpanimittassādagadhitaṃ na rūpanimittassādavinibandhaṃ na rūpanimittassādasaṃyojanasaṃyuttaṃ bahiddhā viññāṇaṃ avikkhittaṃ avisaṭanti vuccati.**Take a mendicant who sees a sight with their eyes. Their consciousness doesn’t follow after the features of that sight, and is not tied, attached, and fettered to gratification in its features. So their consciousness is said to be not scattered and diffused externally.*";
P_HTM[6133]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**When they hear a sound with their ears …*";
P_HTM[6134]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā …**When they smell an odor with their nose …*";
P_HTM[6135]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā …**When they taste a flavor with their tongue …*";
P_HTM[6136]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā …**When they feel a touch with their body …*";
P_HTM[6137]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya na dhammanimittānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti na dhammanimittassādagadhitaṃ na dhammanimittassādavinibandhaṃ na dhammanimittassādasaṃyojanasaṃyuttaṃ bahiddhā viññāṇaṃ avikkhittaṃ avisaṭanti vuccati.**When they know a thought with their mind, their consciousness doesn’t follow after the features of that thought, and is not tied, attached, and fettered to gratification in its features. So their consciousness is said to be not scattered and diffused externally.*";
P_HTM[6138]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bahiddhā viññāṇaṃ avikkhittaṃ avisaṭanti vuccati.**That’s how consciousness is not scattered and diffused externally.*";
P_HTM[6139]="*Kathañcāvuso, ajjhattaṃ saṇṭhitanti vuccati?**And how is their consciousness stuck internally?*";
P_HTM[6140]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Take a mendicant who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[6141]="*Tassa vivekajapītisukhānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti vivekajapītisukhassādagadhitaṃ vivekajapītisukhassādavinibandhaṃ vivekajapītisukhassādasaṃyojanasaṃyuttaṃ ajjhattaṃ cittaṃ saṇṭhitanti vuccati.**Their consciousness follows after that rapture and bliss born of seclusion, tied, attached, and fettered to gratification in that rapture and bliss born of seclusion. So their mind is said to be stuck internally.*";
P_HTM[6142]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, a mendicant enters and remains in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[6143]="*Tassa samādhijapītisukhānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti samādhijapītisukhassādagadhitaṃ samādhijapītisukhassādavinibandhaṃ samādhijapītisukhassādasaṃyojanasaṃyuttaṃ ajjhattaṃ cittaṃ saṇṭhitanti vuccati.**Their consciousness follows after that rapture and bliss born of immersion, tied, attached, and fettered to gratification in that rapture and bliss born of immersion. So their mind is said to be stuck internally.*";
P_HTM[6144]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato ca sampajāno sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, with the fading away of rapture, a mendicant enters and remains in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[6145]="*Tassa upekkhānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti upekkhāsukhassādagadhitaṃ upekkhāsukhassādavinibandhaṃ upekkhāsukhassādasaṃyojanasaṃyuttaṃ ajjhattaṃ cittaṃ saṇṭhitanti vuccati.**Their consciousness follows after that equanimity, tied, attached, and fettered to gratification in that equanimous bliss. So their mind is said to be stuck internally.*";
P_HTM[6146]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, a mendicant enters and remains in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[6147]="*Tassa adukkhamasukhānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti adukkhamasukhassādagadhitaṃ adukkhamasukhassādavinibandhaṃ adukkhamasukhassādasaṃyojanasaṃyuttaṃ ajjhattaṃ cittaṃ asaṇṭhitanti vuccati.**Their consciousness follows after that neutral feeling, tied, attached, and fettered to gratification in that neutral feeling. So their mind is said to be stuck internally.*";
P_HTM[6148]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, ajjhattaṃ saṇṭhitanti vuccati.**That’s how their consciousness is stuck internally.*";
P_HTM[6149]="*Kathañcāvuso, ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhitanti vuccati?**And how is their consciousness not stuck internally?*";
P_HTM[6150]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[6151]="*Tassa na vivekajapītisukhānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti na vivekajapītisukhassādagadhitaṃ na vivekajapītisukhassādavinibandhaṃ na vivekajapītisukhassādasaṃyojanasaṃyuttaṃ ajjhattaṃ cittaṃ asaṇṭhitanti vuccati.**Their consciousness doesn’t follow after that rapture and bliss born of seclusion, and is not tied, attached, and fettered to gratification in that rapture and bliss born of seclusion. So their mind is said to be not stuck internally.*";
P_HTM[6152]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā … pe … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, they enter the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[6153]="*Tassa na samādhijapītisukhānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti na samādhijapītisukhassādagadhitaṃ na samādhijapītisukhassādavinibandhaṃ na samādhijapītisukhassādasaṃyojanasaṃyuttaṃ ajjhattaṃ cittaṃ asaṇṭhitanti vuccati.**Their consciousness doesn’t follow after that rapture and bliss born of immersion …*";
P_HTM[6154]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā … pe … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, they enter and remain in the third absorption …*";
P_HTM[6155]="*Tassa na upekkhānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti na upekkhāsukhassādagadhitaṃ na upekkhāsukhassādavinibandhaṃ na upekkhāsukhassādasaṃyojanasaṃyuttaṃ ajjhattaṃ cittaṃ asaṇṭhitanti vuccati.**Their consciousness doesn’t follow after that equanimity, and is not tied, attached, and fettered to gratification in that equanimous bliss. So their mind is said to be not stuck internally.*";
P_HTM[6156]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption …*";
P_HTM[6157]="*Tassa na adukkhamasukhānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti na adukkhamasukhassādagadhitaṃ na adukkhamasukhassādavinibandhaṃ na adukkhamasukhassādasaṃyojanasaṃyuttaṃ ajjhattaṃ cittaṃ asaṇṭhitanti vuccati.**Their consciousness doesn’t follow after that neutral feeling, and is not tied, attached, and fettered to gratification in that neutral feeling. So their mind is said to be not stuck internally.*";
P_HTM[6158]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhitanti vuccati.**That’s how their consciousness is not stuck internally.*";
P_HTM[6159]="*Kathañcāvuso, anupādā paritassanā hoti?**And how are they anxious because of grasping?*";
P_HTM[6160]="*Idhāvuso, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto**It’s when an uneducated ordinary person has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[6161]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ attani vā rūpaṃ rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[6162]="*Tassa taṃ rūpaṃ vipariṇamati, aññathā hoti.**But that form of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[6163]="*Tassa rūpavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā rūpavipariṇāmānuparivatti viññāṇaṃ hoti.**and consciousness latches on to the perishing of form.*";
P_HTM[6164]="*Tassa rūpavipariṇāmānuparivattajā paritassanā dhammasamuppādā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti.**Anxieties occupy their mind, born of latching on to the perishing of form, and originating in accordance with natural principles.*";
P_HTM[6165]="*Cetaso pariyādānā uttāsavā ca hoti vighātavā ca apekkhavā ca anupādāya ca paritassati.**So they become frightened, worried, concerned, and anxious because of grasping.*";
P_HTM[6166]="*Vedanaṃ … pe …**They regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[6167]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[6168]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[6169]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ attani vā viññāṇaṃ viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6170]="*Tassa taṃ viññāṇaṃ vipariṇamati, aññathā hoti.**But that consciousness of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[6171]="*Tassa viññāṇavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā viññāṇavipariṇāmānuparivatti viññāṇaṃ hoti.**and consciousness latches on to the perishing of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6172]="*Tassa viññāṇavipariṇāmānuparivattajā paritassanā dhammasamuppādā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti.**Anxieties occupy their mind, born of latching on to the perishing of consciousness, and originating in accordance with natural principles.*";
P_HTM[6173]="*Cetaso pariyādānā uttāsavā ca hoti vighātavā ca apekkhavā ca anupādāya ca paritassati.**So they become frightened, worried, concerned, and anxious because of grasping.*";
P_HTM[6174]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, anupādā paritassanā hoti.**That’s how they are anxious because of grasping.*";
P_HTM[6175]="*Kathañcāvuso, anupādānā aparitassanā hoti?**And how are they not anxious because of grasping?*";
P_HTM[6176]="*Idhāvuso, sutavā ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī ariyadhammassa kovido ariyadhamme suvinīto sappurisānaṃ dassāvī sappurisadhammassa kovido sappurisadhamme suvinīto**It’s when an educated noble disciple has seen the noble ones, and is skilled and trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve seen good persons, and are skilled and trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[6177]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati na rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ na attani vā rūpaṃ na rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**They don’t regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[6178]="*Tassa taṃ rūpaṃ vipariṇamati, aññathā hoti.**When that form of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[6179]="*Tassa rūpavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā na ca rūpavipariṇāmānuparivatti viññāṇaṃ hoti.**consciousness doesn’t latch on to the perishing of form.*";
P_HTM[6180]="*Tassa na rūpavipariṇāmānuparivattajā paritassanā dhammasamuppādā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti.**Anxieties—born of latching on to the perishing of form and originating in accordance with natural principles—don’t occupy their mind.*";
P_HTM[6181]="*Cetaso pariyādānā na cevuttāsavā hoti na ca vighātavā na ca apekkhavā anupādāya ca na paritassati.**So they don’t become frightened, worried, concerned, or anxious because of grasping.*";
P_HTM[6182]="*Na vedanaṃ …**They don’t regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[6183]="*na saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[6184]="*na saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[6185]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati na viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ na attani vā viññāṇaṃ na viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6186]="*Tassa taṃ viññāṇaṃ vipariṇamati, aññathā hoti.**When that consciousness of theirs decays and perishes,*";
P_HTM[6187]="*Tassa viññāṇavipariṇāmaññathābhāvā na ca viññāṇavipariṇāmānuparivatti viññāṇaṃ hoti.**consciousness doesn’t latch on to the perishing of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6188]="*Tassa na viññāṇavipariṇāmānuparivattajā paritassanā dhammasamuppādā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti.**Anxieties—born of latching on to the perishing of consciousness and originating in accordance with natural principles—don’t occupy their mind.*";
P_HTM[6189]="*Cetaso pariyādānā na cevuttāsavā hoti na ca vighātavā na ca apekkhavā, anupādāya ca na paritassati.**So they don’t become frightened, worried, concerned, or anxious because of grasping.*";
P_HTM[6190]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, anupādā aparitassanā hoti.**That’s how they are not anxious because of grasping.*";
P_HTM[6191]="*Yaṃ kho no, āvuso, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:**The Buddha gave this brief passage for recitation, then entered his dwelling without explaining the meaning in detail:*";
P_HTM[6192]="*‘tathā tathā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu upaparikkheyya yathā yathā upaparikkhato bahiddhā cassa viññāṇaṃ avikkhittaṃ avisaṭaṃ, ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhitaṃ anupādāya na paritasseyya.**‘A mendicant should examine in any such a way that their consciousness is neither scattered and diffused externally nor stuck internally, and they are not anxious because of grasping.*";
P_HTM[6193]="*Bahiddhā, bhikkhave, viññāṇe avikkhitte avisaṭe sati ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhite anupādāya aparitassato āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇadukkhasamudayasambhavo na hotī’ti.**When this is the case and they are no longer anxious, there is for them no coming to be of the origin of suffering—of rebirth, old age, and death in the future.’*";
P_HTM[6194]="*Imassa kho ahaṃ, āvuso, bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmi.**And this is how I understand the detailed meaning of this passage for recitation.*";
P_HTM[6195]="*Ākaṅkhamānā ca pana tumhe āyasmanto bhagavantaṃyeva upasaṅkamitvā etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyātha;**If you wish, you may go to the Buddha and ask him about this.*";
P_HTM[6196]="*yathā vo bhagavā byākaroti tathā naṃ dhāreyyāthā”ti.**You should remember it in line with the Buddha’s answer.”*";
P_HTM[6197]="*Atha kho te bhikkhū āyasmato mahākaccānassa bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**“Yes, reverend,” said those mendicants, approving and agreeing with what Mahākaccāna said. Then they rose from their seats and went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened, saying:*";
P_HTM[6198]="*“Yaṃ kho no, bhante, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho:* **";
P_HTM[6199]="*‘tathā tathā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu upaparikkheyya yathā yathā upaparikkhato bahiddhā cassa viññāṇaṃ avikkhittaṃ avisaṭaṃ, ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhitaṃ anupādāya na paritasseyya.* **";
P_HTM[6200]="*Bahiddhā, bhikkhave, viññāṇe avikkhitte avisaṭe sati ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhite anupādāya aparitassato āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇadukkhasamudayasambhavo na hotī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[6201]="*Tesaṃ no, bhante, amhākaṃ, acirapakkantassa bhagavato, etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[6202]="*‘idaṃ kho no, āvuso, bhagavā saṅkhittena uddesaṃ uddisitvā vitthārena atthaṃ avibhajitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ paviṭṭho—* **";
P_HTM[6203]="*tathā tathā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu upaparikkheyya, yathā yathā upaparikkhato bahiddhā cassa viññāṇaṃ avikkhittaṃ avisaṭaṃ, ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhitaṃ anupādāya na paritasseyya.* **";
P_HTM[6204]="*Bahiddhā, bhikkhave, viññāṇe avikkhitte avisaṭe sati ajjhattaṃ asaṇṭhite anupādāya aparitassato āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇadukkhasamudayasambhavo na hotīti.* **";
P_HTM[6205]="*Ko nu kho imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajeyyā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[6206]="*Tesaṃ no, bhante, amhākaṃ etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[6207]="*‘ayaṃ kho āyasmā mahākaccāno satthu ceva saṃvaṇṇito sambhāvito ca viññūnaṃ sabrahmacārīnaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6208]="*Pahoti cāyasmā mahākaccāno imassa bhagavatā saṅkhittena uddesassa uddiṭṭhassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ vibhajituṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6209]="*Yannūna mayaṃ yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkameyyāma; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyāmā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[6210]="*Atha kho mayaṃ, bhante, yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkamimha; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etamatthaṃ paṭipucchimha.* **";
P_HTM[6211]="*Tesaṃ no, bhante, āyasmatā mahākaccānena imehi ākārehi imehi padehi imehi byañjanehi attho vibhatto”ti.**“Mahākaccāna clearly explained the meaning to us in this manner, with these words and phrases.”*";
P_HTM[6212]="*“Paṇḍito, bhikkhave, mahākaccāno; mahāpañño, bhikkhave, mahākaccāno.**“Mahākaccāna is astute, mendicants, he has great wisdom.*";
P_HTM[6213]="*Mañcepi tumhe, bhikkhave, etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyātha, ahampi evamevaṃ byākareyyaṃ yathā taṃ mahākaccānena byākataṃ.**If you came to me and asked this question, I would answer it in exactly the same way as Mahākaccāna.*";
P_HTM[6214]="*Eso cevetassa attho. Evañca naṃ dhāreyyāthā”ti.**That is what it means, and that’s how you should remember it.”*";
P_HTM[6215]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[6216]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[6217]="*Uddesavibhaṅgasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6218]="*139. Araṇavibhaṅgasutta**The Analysis of Non-Conflict*";
P_HTM[6219]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[6220]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[6221]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[6222]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[6223]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[6224]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[6225]="*“araṇavibhaṅgaṃ vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I shall teach you the analysis of non-conflict.*";
P_HTM[6226]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[6227]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[6228]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[6229]="*“Na kāmasukhamanuyuñjeyya hīnaṃ gammaṃ pothujjanikaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, na ca attakilamathānuyogamanuyuñjeyya dukkhaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ.**“Don’t indulge in sensual pleasures, which are low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. And don’t indulge in self-mortification, which is painful, ignoble, and pointless.*";
P_HTM[6230]="*Ete kho, bhikkhave, ubho ante anupagamma majjhimā paṭipadā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā, cakkhukaraṇī ñāṇakaraṇī upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati.**Avoiding these two extremes, the Realized One woke up by understanding the middle way, which gives vision and knowledge, and leads to peace, direct knowledge, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[6231]="*Ussādanañca jaññā, apasādanañca jaññā;**Know what it means to flatter and to rebuke.*";
P_HTM[6232]="*ussādanañca ñatvā apasādanañca ñatvā nevussādeyya, na apasādeyya, dhammameva deseyya.**Knowing these, avoid them, and just teach Dhamma.*";
P_HTM[6233]="*Sukhavinicchayaṃ jaññā;**Know how to assess different kinds of pleasure.*";
P_HTM[6234]="*sukhavinicchayaṃ ñatvā ajjhattaṃ sukhamanuyuñjeyya.**Knowing this, pursue inner bliss.*";
P_HTM[6235]="*Rahovādaṃ na bhāseyya, sammukhā na khīṇaṃ bhaṇe.**Don’t talk behind people’s backs, and don’t speak sharply in their presence.*";
P_HTM[6236]="*Ataramānova bhāseyya, no taramāno.**Don’t speak hurriedly.*";
P_HTM[6237]="*Janapadaniruttiṃ nābhiniveseyya, samaññaṃ nātidhāveyyāti—**Don’t insist on local terminology and don’t override normal usage.*";
P_HTM[6238]="*ayamuddeso araṇavibhaṅgassa.**This is the recitation passage for the analysis of non-conflict.*";
P_HTM[6239]="*‘Na kāmasukhamanuyuñjeyya hīnaṃ gammaṃ pothujjanikaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, na ca attakilamathānuyogamanuyuñjeyya dukkhaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitan’ti—**‘Don’t indulge in sensual pleasures, which are low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. And don’t indulge in self-mortification, which is painful, ignoble, and pointless.’*";
P_HTM[6240]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ; Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6241]="*Yo kāmapaṭisandhisukhino somanassānuyogo hīno gammo pothujjaniko anariyo anatthasaṃhito, sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho; micchāpaṭipadā.**Pleasure linked to sensuality is low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. Indulging in such happiness is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[6242]="*Yo kāmapaṭisandhisukhino somanassānuyogaṃ ananuyogo hīnaṃ gammaṃ pothujjanikaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho; sammāpaṭipadā.**Breaking off such indulgence is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.*";
P_HTM[6243]="*Yo attakilamathānuyogo dukkho anariyo anatthasaṃhito, sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho; micchāpaṭipadā.**Indulging in self-mortification is painful, ignoble, and pointless. It is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[6244]="*Yo attakilamathānuyogaṃ ananuyogo dukkhaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho; sammāpaṭipadā.**Breaking off such indulgence is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.*";
P_HTM[6245]="*‘Na kāmasukhamanuyuñjeyya hīnaṃ gammaṃ pothujjanikaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, na ca attakilamathānuyogaṃ anuyuñjeyya dukkhaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitan’ti—**‘Don’t indulge in sensual pleasures, which are low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. And don’t indulge in self-mortification, which is painful, ignoble, and pointless.’*";
P_HTM[6246]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6247]="*‘Ete kho ubho ante anupagamma majjhimā paṭipadā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā, cakkhukaraṇī ñāṇakaraṇī upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattatī’ti—**‘Avoiding these two extremes, the Realized One woke up by understanding the middle way, which gives vision and knowledge, and leads to peace, direct knowledge, awakening, and extinguishment.’*";
P_HTM[6248]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6249]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, seyyathidaṃ—**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[6250]="*sammādiṭṭhi, sammāsaṅkappo, sammāvācā, sammākammanto, sammāājīvo, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati, sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[6251]="*‘Ete kho ubho ante anupagamma majjhimā paṭipadā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā, cakkhukaraṇī ñāṇakaraṇī upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattatī’ti—**‘Avoiding these two extremes, the Realized One woke up by understanding the middle way, which gives vision and knowledge, and leads to peace, direct knowledge, awakening, and extinguishment.’*";
P_HTM[6252]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6253]="*‘Ussādanañca jaññā, apasādanañca jaññā;**‘Know what it means to flatter and to rebuke.*";
P_HTM[6254]="*ussādanañca ñatvā apasādanañca ñatvā nevussādeyya, na apasādeyya, dhammameva deseyyā’ti—**Knowing these, avoid them, and just teach Dhamma.’*";
P_HTM[6255]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6256]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, ussādanā ca hoti apasādanā ca, no ca dhammadesanā?**And how is there flattering and rebuking without teaching Dhamma?*";
P_HTM[6257]="*‘Ye kāmapaṭisandhisukhino somanassānuyogaṃ anuyuttā hīnaṃ gammaṃ pothujjanikaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, sabbe te sadukkhā saupaghātā saupāyāsā sapariḷāhā micchāpaṭipannā’ti—**In speaking like this, some are rebuked: ‘Pleasure linked to sensuality is low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. All those who indulge in such happiness are beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and they are practicing the wrong way.’*";
P_HTM[6258]="*iti vadaṃ ittheke apasādeti.* **";
P_HTM[6259]="*‘Ye kāmapaṭisandhisukhino somanassānuyogaṃ ananuyuttā hīnaṃ gammaṃ pothujjanikaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, sabbe te adukkhā anupaghātā anupāyāsā apariḷāhā sammāpaṭipannā’ti—**In speaking like this, some are flattered: ‘Pleasure linked to sensuality is low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. All those who have broken off such indulgence are free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and they are practicing the right way.’*";
P_HTM[6260]="*iti vadaṃ ittheke ussādeti.* **";
P_HTM[6261]="*‘Ye attakilamathānuyogaṃ anuyuttā dukkhaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, sabbe te sadukkhā saupaghātā saupāyāsā sapariḷāhā micchāpaṭipannā’ti—**In speaking like this, some are rebuked: ‘Indulging in self-mortification is painful, ignoble, and pointless. All those who indulge in it are beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and they are practicing the wrong way.’*";
P_HTM[6262]="*iti vadaṃ ittheke apasādeti.* **";
P_HTM[6263]="*‘Ye attakilamathānuyogaṃ ananuyuttā dukkhaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, sabbe te adukkhā anupaghātā anupāyāsā apariḷāhā sammāpaṭipannā’ti—**In speaking like this, some are flattered: ‘Indulging in self-mortification is painful, ignoble, and pointless. All those who have broken off such indulgence are free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and they are practicing the right way.’*";
P_HTM[6264]="*iti vadaṃ ittheke ussādeti.* **";
P_HTM[6265]="*‘Yesaṃ kesañci bhavasaṃyojanaṃ appahīnaṃ, sabbe te sadukkhā saupaghātā saupāyāsā sapariḷāhā micchāpaṭipannā’ti—**In speaking like this, some are rebuked: ‘All those who have not given up the fetters of rebirth are beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and they are practicing the wrong way.’*";
P_HTM[6266]="*iti vadaṃ ittheke apasādeti.* **";
P_HTM[6267]="*‘Yesaṃ kesañci bhavasaṃyojanaṃ pahīnaṃ, sabbe te adukkhā anupaghātā anupāyāsā apariḷāhā sammāpaṭipannā’ti—**In speaking like this, some are flattered: ‘All those who have given up the fetters of rebirth are free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and they are practicing the right way.’*";
P_HTM[6268]="*iti vadaṃ ittheke ussādeti.* **";
P_HTM[6269]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, ussādanā ca hoti apasādanā ca, no ca dhammadesanā.**That’s how there is flattering and rebuking without teaching Dhamma.*";
P_HTM[6270]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, nevussādanā hoti na apasādanā, dhammadesanā ca?**And how is there neither flattering nor rebuking, and just teaching Dhamma?*";
P_HTM[6271]="*‘Ye kāmapaṭisandhisukhino somanassānuyogaṃ anuyuttā hīnaṃ gammaṃ pothujjanikaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, sabbe te sadukkhā saupaghātā saupāyāsā sapariḷāhā micchāpaṭipannā’ti—**You don’t say: ‘Pleasure linked to sensuality is low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. All those who indulge in such happiness are beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and they are practicing the wrong way.’*";
P_HTM[6272]="*na evamāha.**Rather, by saying this you just teach Dhamma:*";
P_HTM[6273]="*‘Anuyogo ca kho sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho;**‘The indulgence is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.’*";
P_HTM[6274]="*micchāpaṭipadā’ti—* **";
P_HTM[6275]="*iti vadaṃ dhammameva deseti.* **";
P_HTM[6276]="*‘Ye kāmapaṭisandhisukhino somanassānuyogaṃ ananuyuttā hīnaṃ gammaṃ pothujjanikaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, sabbe te adukkhā anupaghātā anupāyāsā apariḷāhā sammāpaṭipannā’ti—**You don’t say: ‘Pleasure linked to sensuality is low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. All those who have broken off such indulgence are free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and they are practicing the right way.’*";
P_HTM[6277]="*na evamāha.**Rather, by saying this you just teach Dhamma:*";
P_HTM[6278]="*‘Ananuyogo ca kho adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho;**‘Breaking off the indulgence is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.’*";
P_HTM[6279]="*sammāpaṭipadā’ti—* **";
P_HTM[6280]="*iti vadaṃ dhammameva deseti.* **";
P_HTM[6281]="*‘Ye attakilamathānuyogaṃ anuyuttā dukkhaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, sabbe te sadukkhā saupaghātā saupāyāsā sapariḷāhā micchāpaṭipannā’ti—**You don’t say: ‘Indulging in self-mortification is painful, ignoble, and pointless. All those who indulge in it are beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and they are practicing the wrong way.’*";
P_HTM[6282]="*na evamāha.**Rather, by saying this you just teach Dhamma:*";
P_HTM[6283]="*‘Anuyogo ca kho sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho;**‘The indulgence is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.’*";
P_HTM[6284]="*micchāpaṭipadā’ti—* **";
P_HTM[6285]="*iti vadaṃ dhammameva deseti.* **";
P_HTM[6286]="*‘Ye attakilamathānuyogaṃ ananuyuttā dukkhaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, sabbe te adukkhā anupaghātā anupāyāsā apariḷāhā sammāpaṭipannā’ti—**You don’t say: ‘Indulging in self-mortification is painful, ignoble, and pointless. All those who have broken off such indulgence are free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and they are practicing the right way.’*";
P_HTM[6287]="*na evamāha.**Rather, by saying this you just teach Dhamma:*";
P_HTM[6288]="*‘Ananuyogo ca kho adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho;**‘Breaking off the indulgence is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.’*";
P_HTM[6289]="*sammāpaṭipadā’ti—* **";
P_HTM[6290]="*iti vadaṃ dhammameva deseti.* **";
P_HTM[6291]="*‘Yesaṃ kesañci bhavasaṃyojanaṃ appahīnaṃ, sabbe te sadukkhā saupaghātā saupāyāsā sapariḷāhā micchāpaṭipannā’ti—**You don’t say: ‘All those who have not given up the fetters of rebirth are beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and they are practicing the wrong way.’*";
P_HTM[6292]="*na evamāha.**Rather, by saying this you just teach Dhamma:*";
P_HTM[6293]="*‘Bhavasaṃyojane ca kho appahīne bhavopi appahīno hotī’ti—**‘When the fetter of rebirth is not given up, rebirth is also not given up.’*";
P_HTM[6294]="*iti vadaṃ dhammameva deseti.* **";
P_HTM[6295]="*‘Yesaṃ kesañci bhavasaṃyojanaṃ pahīnaṃ, sabbe te adukkhā anupaghātā anupāyāsā apariḷāhā sammāpaṭipannā’ti—**You don’t say: ‘All those who have given up the fetters of rebirth are free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and they are practicing the right way.’*";
P_HTM[6296]="*na evamāha.**Rather, by saying this you just teach Dhamma:*";
P_HTM[6297]="*‘Bhavasaṃyojane ca kho pahīne bhavopi pahīno hotī’ti—**‘When the fetter of rebirth is given up, rebirth is also given up.’*";
P_HTM[6298]="*iti vadaṃ dhammameva deseti.* **";
P_HTM[6299]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, nevussādanā hoti na apasādanā, dhammadesanā ca.**That’s how there is neither flattering nor rebuking, and just teaching Dhamma.*";
P_HTM[6300]="*‘Ussādanañca jaññā, apasādanañca jaññā;**‘Know what it means to flatter and to rebuke.*";
P_HTM[6301]="*ussādanañca ñatvā apasādanañca ñatvā nevussādeyya, na apasādeyya, dhammameva deseyyā’ti—**Knowing these, avoid them, and just teach Dhamma.’*";
P_HTM[6302]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6303]="*‘Sukhavinicchayaṃ jaññā;**‘Know how to assess different kinds of pleasure.*";
P_HTM[6304]="*sukhavinicchayaṃ ñatvā ajjhattaṃ sukhamanuyuñjeyyā’ti—**Knowing this, pursue inner bliss.’*";
P_HTM[6305]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6306]="*Pañcime, bhikkhave, kāmaguṇā.**There are these five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[6307]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[6308]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā,**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[6309]="*sotaviññeyyā saddā …**Sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[6310]="*ghānaviññeyyā gandhā …**Smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[6311]="*jivhāviññeyyā rasā …**Tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[6312]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā—**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[6313]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca kāmaguṇā.**These are the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[6314]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhave, ime pañca kāmaguṇe paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ idaṃ vuccati kāmasukhaṃ mīḷhasukhaṃ puthujjanasukhaṃ anariyasukhaṃ.**The pleasure and happiness that arise from these five kinds of sensual stimulation is called sensual pleasure—a filthy, common, ignoble pleasure.*";
P_HTM[6315]="*‘Na āsevitabbaṃ, na bhāvetabbaṃ, na bahulīkātabbaṃ, bhāyitabbaṃ etassa sukhassā’ti—vadāmi.**Such pleasure should not be cultivated or developed, but should be feared, I say.*";
P_HTM[6316]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Now, take a mendicant who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[6317]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[6318]="*Pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati … pe … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ … pe …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[6319]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[6320]="*Idaṃ vuccati nekkhammasukhaṃ pavivekasukhaṃ upasamasukhaṃ sambodhisukhaṃ.**This is called the pleasure of renunciation, the pleasure of seclusion, the pleasure of peace, the pleasure of awakening.*";
P_HTM[6321]="*‘Āsevitabbaṃ, bhāvetabbaṃ, bahulīkātabbaṃ, na bhāyitabbaṃ etassa sukhassā’ti—vadāmi.**Such pleasure should be cultivated and developed, and should not be feared, I say.*";
P_HTM[6322]="*‘Sukhavinicchayaṃ jaññā;**‘Know how to assess different kinds of pleasure.*";
P_HTM[6323]="*sukhavinicchayaṃ ñatvā ajjhattaṃ sukhamanuyuñjeyyā’ti—**Knowing this, pursue inner bliss.’*";
P_HTM[6324]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6325]="*‘Rahovādaṃ na bhāseyya, sammukhā na khīṇaṃ bhaṇe’ti—**‘Don’t talk behind people’s backs, and don’t speak sharply in their presence.’*";
P_HTM[6326]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said,*";
P_HTM[6327]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6328]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yaṃ jaññā rahovādaṃ abhūtaṃ atacchaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ sasakkaṃ taṃ rahovādaṃ na bhāseyya.**When you know that what you say behind someone’s back is untrue, false, and harmful, then if at all possible you should not speak.*";
P_HTM[6329]="*Yampi jaññā rahovādaṃ bhūtaṃ tacchaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ tassapi sikkheyya avacanāya.**When you know that what you say behind someone’s back is true and correct, but harmful, then you should train yourself not to speak.*";
P_HTM[6330]="*Yañca kho jaññā rahovādaṃ bhūtaṃ tacchaṃ atthasaṃhitaṃ tatra kālaññū assa tassa rahovādassa vacanāya.**When you know that what you say behind someone’s back is true, correct, and beneficial, then you should know the right time to speak.*";
P_HTM[6331]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yaṃ jaññā sammukhā khīṇavādaṃ abhūtaṃ atacchaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ sasakkaṃ taṃ sammukhā khīṇavādaṃ na bhāseyya.**When you know that your sharp words in someone’s presence are untrue, false, and harmful, then if at all possible you should not speak.*";
P_HTM[6332]="*Yampi jaññā sammukhā khīṇavādaṃ bhūtaṃ tacchaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ tassapi sikkheyya avacanāya.**When you know that your sharp words in someone’s presence are true and correct, but harmful, then you should train yourself not to speak.*";
P_HTM[6333]="*Yañca kho jaññā sammukhā khīṇavādaṃ bhūtaṃ tacchaṃ atthasaṃhitaṃ tatra kālaññū assa tassa sammukhā khīṇavādassa vacanāya.**When you know that your sharp words in someone’s presence are true, correct, and beneficial, then you should know the right time to speak.*";
P_HTM[6334]="*‘Rahovādaṃ na bhāseyya, sammukhā na khīṇaṃ bhaṇe’ti—**‘Don’t talk behind people’s backs, and don’t speak sharply in their presence.’*";
P_HTM[6335]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6336]="*‘Ataramānova bhāseyya no taramāno’ti—**‘Don’t speak hurriedly.’*";
P_HTM[6337]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6338]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, taramānassa bhāsato kāyopi kilamati, cittampi upahaññati, saropi upahaññati, kaṇṭhopi āturīyati, avisaṭṭhampi hoti aviññeyyaṃ taramānassa bhāsitaṃ.**When speaking hurriedly, your body gets tired, your mind gets stressed, your voice gets stressed, your throat gets sore, and your words become unclear and hard to understand.*";
P_HTM[6339]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ataramānassa bhāsato kāyopi na kilamati, cittampi na upahaññati, saropi na upahaññati, kaṇṭhopi na āturīyati, visaṭṭhampi hoti viññeyyaṃ ataramānassa bhāsitaṃ.**When not speaking hurriedly, your body doesn’t get tired, your mind doesn’t get stressed, your voice doesn’t get stressed, your throat doesn’t get sore, and your words are clear and easy to understand.*";
P_HTM[6340]="*‘Ataramānova bhāseyya, no taramāno’ti—**‘Don’t speak hurriedly.’*";
P_HTM[6341]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6342]="*‘Janapadaniruttiṃ nābhiniveseyya, samaññaṃ nātidhāveyyā’ti—**‘Don’t insist on local terminology and don’t override normal usage.’*";
P_HTM[6343]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6344]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, janapadaniruttiyā ca abhiniveso hoti samaññāya ca atisāro?**And how do you insist on local terminology and override normal usage?*";
P_HTM[6345]="*Idha, bhikkhave, tadevekaccesu janapadesu ‘pātī’ti sañjānanti, ‘pattan’ti sañjānanti, ‘vittan’ti sañjānanti, ‘sarāvan’ti sañjānanti ‘dhāropan’ti sañjānanti, ‘poṇan’ti sañjānanti, ‘pisīlavan’ti sañjānanti.**It’s when in different localities the same thing is known as a ‘plate’, a ‘bowl’, a ‘cup’, a ‘dish’, a ‘basin’, a ‘tureen’, or a ‘porringer’.*";
P_HTM[6346]="*Iti yathā yathā naṃ tesu tesu janapadesu sañjānanti tathā tathā thāmasā parāmāsā abhinivissa voharati:**And however it is known in those various localities, you speak accordingly, obstinately sticking to that and insisting:*";
P_HTM[6347]="*‘idameva saccaṃ, moghamaññan’ti.**‘This is the only truth, other ideas are silly.’*";
P_HTM[6348]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, janapadaniruttiyā ca abhiniveso hoti samaññāya ca atisāro.**That’s how you insist on local terminology and override normal usage.*";
P_HTM[6349]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, janapadaniruttiyā ca anabhiniveso hoti samaññāya ca anatisāro?**And how do you not insist on local terminology and not override normal usage?*";
P_HTM[6350]="*Idha, bhikkhave, tadevekaccesu janapadesu ‘pātī’ti sañjānanti, ‘pattan’ti sañjānanti, ‘vittan’ti sañjānanti, ‘sarāvan’ti sañjānanti, ‘dhāropan’ti sañjānanti, ‘poṇan’ti sañjānanti, ‘pisīlavan’ti sañjānanti.**It’s when in different localities the same thing is known as a ‘plate’, a ‘bowl’, a ‘cup’, a ‘dish’, a ‘basin’, a ‘tureen’, or a ‘porringer’.*";
P_HTM[6351]="*Iti yathā yathā naṃ tesu tesu janapadesu sañjānanti ‘idaṃ kira me āyasmanto sandhāya voharantī’ti tathā tathā voharati aparāmasaṃ.**And however it is known in those various localities, you speak accordingly, thinking: ‘It seems that the venerables are referring to this.’*";
P_HTM[6352]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, janapadaniruttiyā ca anabhiniveso hoti, samaññāya ca anatisāro.**That’s how you don’t insist on local terminology and don’t override normal usage.*";
P_HTM[6353]="*‘Janapadaniruttiṃ nābhiniveseyya samaññaṃ nātidhāveyyā’ti—**‘Don’t insist on local terminology and don’t override normal usage.’*";
P_HTM[6354]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6355]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yo kāmapaṭisandhisukhino somanassānuyogo hīno gammo pothujjaniko anariyo anatthasaṃhito, sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho;**Now, mendicants, pleasure linked to sensuality is low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. Indulging in such happiness is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[6356]="*micchāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6357]="*Tasmā eso dhammo saraṇo.**That’s why this is a principle beset by conflict.*";
P_HTM[6358]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yo kāmapaṭisandhisukhino somanassānuyogaṃ ananuyogo hīnaṃ gammaṃ pothujjanikaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho;**Breaking off such indulgence is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.*";
P_HTM[6359]="*sammāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6360]="*Tasmā eso dhammo araṇo.**That’s why this is a principle free of conflict.*";
P_HTM[6361]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yo attakilamathānuyogo dukkho anariyo anatthasaṃhito, sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho;**Indulging in self-mortification is painful, ignoble, and pointless. It is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[6362]="*micchāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6363]="*Tasmā eso dhammo saraṇo.**That’s why this is a principle beset by conflict.*";
P_HTM[6364]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yo attakilamathānuyogaṃ ananuyogo dukkhaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho;**Breaking off such indulgence is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.*";
P_HTM[6365]="*sammāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6366]="*Tasmā eso dhammo araṇo.**That’s why this is a principle free of conflict.*";
P_HTM[6367]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yāyaṃ majjhimā paṭipadā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā, cakkhukaraṇī ñāṇakaraṇī upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati, adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho;**The middle way by which the Realized One was awakened gives vision and knowledge, and leads to peace, direct knowledge, awakening, and extinguishment. It is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.*";
P_HTM[6368]="*sammāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6369]="*Tasmā eso dhammo araṇo.**That’s why this is a principle free of conflict.*";
P_HTM[6370]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yāyaṃ ussādanā ca apasādanā ca no ca dhammadesanā, sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho;**Flattering and rebuking without teaching Dhamma is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[6371]="*micchāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6372]="*Tasmā eso dhammo saraṇo.**That’s why this is a principle beset by conflict.*";
P_HTM[6373]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yāyaṃ nevussādanā ca na apasādanā ca dhammadesanā ca, adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho;**Neither flattering nor rebuking, and just teaching Dhamma is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.*";
P_HTM[6374]="*sammāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6375]="*Tasmā eso dhammo araṇo.**That’s why this is a principle free of conflict.*";
P_HTM[6376]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yamidaṃ kāmasukhaṃ mīḷhasukhaṃ pothujjanasukhaṃ anariyasukhaṃ, sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho;**Sensual pleasure—a filthy, common, ignoble pleasure—is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[6377]="*micchāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6378]="*Tasmā eso dhammo saraṇo.**That’s why this is a principle beset by conflict.*";
P_HTM[6379]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yamidaṃ nekkhammasukhaṃ pavivekasukhaṃ upasamasukhaṃ sambodhisukhaṃ, adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho;**The pleasure of renunciation, the pleasure of seclusion, the pleasure of peace, the pleasure of awakening is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.*";
P_HTM[6380]="*sammāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6381]="*Tasmā eso dhammo araṇo.**That’s why this is a principle free of conflict.*";
P_HTM[6382]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yvāyaṃ rahovādo abhūto ataccho anatthasaṃhito, sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho;**Saying untrue, false, and harmful things behind someone’s back is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[6383]="*micchāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6384]="*Tasmā eso dhammo saraṇo.**That’s why this is a principle beset by conflict.*";
P_HTM[6385]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yvāyaṃ rahovādo bhūto taccho anatthasaṃhito, sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho;**Saying true and correct, but harmful things behind someone’s back is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[6386]="*micchāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6387]="*Tasmā eso dhammo saraṇo.**That’s why this is a principle beset by conflict.*";
P_HTM[6388]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yvāyaṃ rahovādo bhūto taccho atthasaṃhito, adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho;**Saying true, correct, and beneficial things behind someone’s back is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.*";
P_HTM[6389]="*sammāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6390]="*Tasmā eso dhammo araṇo.**That’s why this is a principle free of conflict.*";
P_HTM[6391]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yvāyaṃ sammukhā khīṇavādo abhūto ataccho anatthasaṃhito, sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho;**Saying untrue, false, and harmful things in someone’s presence is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[6392]="*micchāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6393]="*Tasmā eso dhammo saraṇo.**That’s why this is a principle beset by conflict.*";
P_HTM[6394]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yvāyaṃ sammukhā khīṇavādo bhūto taccho anatthasaṃhito, sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho;**Saying true and correct, but harmful things in someone’s presence is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[6395]="*micchāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6396]="*Tasmā eso dhammo saraṇo.**That’s why this is a principle beset by conflict.*";
P_HTM[6397]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yvāyaṃ sammukhā khīṇavādo bhūto taccho atthasaṃhito, adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho;**Saying true, correct, and beneficial things in someone’s presence is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.*";
P_HTM[6398]="*sammāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6399]="*Tasmā eso dhammo araṇo.**That’s why this is a principle free of conflict.*";
P_HTM[6400]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yamidaṃ taramānassa bhāsitaṃ, sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho;**Speaking hurriedly is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[6401]="*micchāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6402]="*Tasmā eso dhammo saraṇo.**That’s why this is a principle beset by conflict.*";
P_HTM[6403]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yamidaṃ ataramānassa bhāsitaṃ, adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho;**Speaking unhurriedly is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.*";
P_HTM[6404]="*sammāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6405]="*Tasmā eso dhammo araṇo.**That’s why this is a principle free of conflict.*";
P_HTM[6406]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yvāyaṃ janapadaniruttiyā ca abhiniveso samaññāya ca atisāro, sadukkho eso dhammo saupaghāto saupāyāso sapariḷāho;**Insisting on local terminology and overriding normal usage is a principle beset by pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[6407]="*micchāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6408]="*Tasmā eso dhammo saraṇo.**That’s why this is a principle beset by conflict.*";
P_HTM[6409]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yvāyaṃ janapadaniruttiyā ca anabhiniveso samaññāya ca anatisāro, adukkho eso dhammo anupaghāto anupāyāso apariḷāho;**Not insisting on local terminology and not overriding normal usage is a principle free of pain, harm, stress, and fever, and it is the right way.*";
P_HTM[6410]="*sammāpaṭipadā.* **";
P_HTM[6411]="*Tasmā eso dhammo araṇo.**That’s why this is a principle free of conflict.*";
P_HTM[6412]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘saraṇañca dhammaṃ jānissāma, araṇañca dhammaṃ jānissāma;**So you should train like this: ‘We shall know the principles beset by conflict and the principles free of conflict.*";
P_HTM[6413]="*saraṇañca dhammaṃ ñatvā araṇañca dhammaṃ ñatvā araṇapaṭipadaṃ paṭipajjissāmā’ti evañhi vo, bhikkhave, sikkhitabbaṃ.**Knowing this, we will practice the way free of conflict.’*";
P_HTM[6414]="*Subhūti ca pana, bhikkhave, kulaputto araṇapaṭipadaṃ paṭipanno”ti.**And, mendicants, Subhūti, the gentleman, practices the way of non-conflict.”*";
P_HTM[6415]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[6416]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[6417]="*Araṇavibhaṅgasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6418]="*140. Dhātuvibhaṅgasutta**The Analysis of the Elements*";
P_HTM[6419]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[6420]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā magadhesu cārikaṃ caramāno yena rājagahaṃ tadavasari;**At one time the Buddha was wandering in the Magadhan lands when he arrived at Rājagaha.*";
P_HTM[6421]="*yena bhaggavo kumbhakāro tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhaggavaṃ kumbhakāraṃ etadavoca:**He went to see Bhaggava the potter, and said,*";
P_HTM[6422]="*“sace te, bhaggava, agaru viharemu āvesane ekarattan”ti.**“Bhaggava, if it is no trouble, I’d like to spend a single night in your workshop.”*";
P_HTM[6423]="*“Na kho me, bhante, garu.**“It’s no trouble, sir.*";
P_HTM[6424]="*Atthi cettha pabbajito paṭhamaṃ vāsūpagato.**But there’s a renunciate already staying there.*";
P_HTM[6425]="*Sace so anujānāti, viharatha, bhante, yathāsukhan”ti.**If he allows it, sir, you may stay as long as you like.”*";
P_HTM[6426]="*Tena kho pana samayena pukkusāti nāma kulaputto bhagavantaṃ uddissa saddhāya agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito.**Now at that time a gentleman named Pukkusāti had gone forth from the lay life to homelessness out of faith in the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[6427]="*So tasmiṃ kumbhakārāvesane paṭhamaṃ vāsūpagato hoti.**And it was he who had first taken up residence in the workshop.*";
P_HTM[6428]="*Atha kho bhagavā yenāyasmā pukkusāti tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ pukkusātiṃ etadavoca:**Then the Buddha approached Venerable Pukkusāti and said,*";
P_HTM[6429]="*“sace te, bhikkhu, agaru viharemu āvesane ekarattan”ti.**“Mendicant, if it is no trouble, I’d like to spend a single night in the workshop.”*";
P_HTM[6430]="*“Urundaṃ, āvuso, kumbhakārāvesanaṃ.**“The potter’s workshop is spacious, reverend.*";
P_HTM[6431]="*Viharatāyasmā yathāsukhan”ti.**Please stay as long as you like.”*";
P_HTM[6432]="*Atha kho bhagavā kumbhakārāvesanaṃ pavisitvā ekamantaṃ tiṇasanthārakaṃ paññāpetvā nisīdi pallaṅkaṃ ābhujitvā ujuṃ kāyaṃ paṇidhāya parimukhaṃ satiṃ upaṭṭhapetvā.**Then the Buddha entered the workshop and spread out a grass mat to one side. He sat down cross-legged, with his body straight, and established mindfulness right there.*";
P_HTM[6433]="*Atha kho bhagavā bahudeva rattiṃ nisajjāya vītināmesi.**He spent most of the night sitting meditation,*";
P_HTM[6434]="*Āyasmāpi kho pukkusāti bahudeva rattiṃ nisajjāya vītināmesi.**and so did Pukkusāti.*";
P_HTM[6435]="*Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:**Then it occurred to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[6436]="*“pāsādikaṃ kho ayaṃ kulaputto iriyati.**“This gentleman’s conduct is impressive.*";
P_HTM[6437]="*Yannūnāhaṃ puccheyyan”ti.**Why don’t I question him?”*";
P_HTM[6438]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ pukkusātiṃ etadavoca:**So the Buddha said to Pukkusāti,*";
P_HTM[6439]="*“kaṃsi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, uddissa pabbajito? Ko vā te satthā? Kassa vā tvaṃ dhammaṃ rocesī”ti?**“In whose name have you gone forth, reverend? Who is your Teacher? Whose teaching do you believe in?”*";
P_HTM[6440]="*“Atthāvuso, samaṇo gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito.**“Reverend, there is the ascetic Gotama—a Sakyan, gone forth from a Sakyan family.*";
P_HTM[6441]="*Taṃ kho pana bhagavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[6442]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[6443]="*Tāhaṃ bhagavantaṃ uddissa pabbajito.**I’ve gone forth in his name.*";
P_HTM[6444]="*So ca me bhagavā satthā.**That Blessed One is my Teacher,*";
P_HTM[6445]="*Tassa cāhaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ rocemī”ti.**and I believe in his teaching.”*";
P_HTM[6446]="*“Kahaṃ pana, bhikkhu, etarahi so bhagavā viharati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho”ti.**“But mendicant, where is the Blessed One at present, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha?”*";
P_HTM[6447]="*“Atthāvuso, uttaresu janapadesu sāvatthi nāma nagaraṃ.**“In the northern lands there is a city called Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[6448]="*Tattha so bhagavā etarahi viharati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho”ti.**There the Blessed One is now staying, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[6449]="*“Diṭṭhapubbo pana te, bhikkhu, so bhagavā;**“But have you ever seen that Buddha?*";
P_HTM[6450]="*disvā ca pana jāneyyāsī”ti?**Would you recognize him if you saw him?”*";
P_HTM[6451]="*“Na kho me, āvuso, diṭṭhapubbo so bhagavā;**“No, I’ve never seen him,*";
P_HTM[6452]="*disvā cāhaṃ na jāneyyan”ti.**and I wouldn’t recognize him if I did.”*";
P_HTM[6453]="*Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:**Then it occurred to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[6454]="*“mamañca khvāyaṃ kulaputto uddissa pabbajito.**“This gentleman has gone forth in my name.*";
P_HTM[6455]="*Yannūnassāhaṃ dhammaṃ deseyyan”ti.**Why don’t I teach him the Dhamma?”*";
P_HTM[6456]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ pukkusātiṃ āmantesi:**So the Buddha said to Pukkusāti,*";
P_HTM[6457]="*“dhammaṃ te, bhikkhu, desessāmi.**“Mendicant, I shall teach you the Dhamma.*";
P_HTM[6458]="*Taṃ suṇāhi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[6459]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho āyasmā pukkusāti bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, reverend,” replied Pukkusāti.*";
P_HTM[6460]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[6461]="*“‘Cha dhāturo ayaṃ, bhikkhu, puriso cha phassāyatano aṭṭhārasa manopavicāro caturādhiṭṭhāno;**“‘This person has six elements, six fields of contact, and eighteen mental preoccupations.*";
P_HTM[6462]="*yattha ṭhitaṃ maññassavā nappavattanti, maññassave kho pana nappavattamāne muni santoti vuccati.**They have four foundations, standing on which the streams of identification don’t flow. And when the streams of identification don’t flow, they’re called a sage at peace.*";
P_HTM[6463]="*Paññaṃ nappamajjeyya, saccamanurakkheyya, cāgamanubrūheyya, santimeva so sikkheyyā’ti—**Don’t neglect wisdom, preserve truth, foster generosity, and train only for peace.’*";
P_HTM[6464]="*ayamuddeso dhātuvibhaṅgassa.**This is the recitation passage for the analysis of the elements.*";
P_HTM[6465]="*‘Cha dhāturo ayaṃ, bhikkhu, puriso’ti—**‘This person has six elements.’*";
P_HTM[6466]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6467]="*Chayimā, bhikkhu, dhātuyo—**There are these six elements:*";
P_HTM[6468]="*pathavīdhātu, āpodhātu, tejodhātu, vāyodhātu, ākāsadhātu, viññāṇadhātu.**the elements of earth, water, fire, air, space, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6469]="*‘Cha dhāturo ayaṃ, bhikkhu, puriso’ti—**‘This person has six elements.’*";
P_HTM[6470]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6471]="*‘Cha phassāyatano ayaṃ, bhikkhu, puriso’ti—**‘This person has six fields of contact.’*";
P_HTM[6472]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6473]="*Cakkhusamphassāyatanaṃ, sotasamphassāyatanaṃ, ghānasamphassāyatanaṃ, jivhāsamphassāyatanaṃ, kāyasamphassāyatanaṃ, manosamphassāyatanaṃ.**The fields of contact of the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[6474]="*‘Cha phassāyatano ayaṃ, bhikkhu, puriso’ti—**‘This person has six fields of contact.’*";
P_HTM[6475]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6476]="*‘Aṭṭhārasa manopavicāro ayaṃ, bhikkhu, puriso’ti—**‘This person has eighteen mental preoccupations.’*";
P_HTM[6477]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6478]="*Cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā somanassaṭṭhāniyaṃ rūpaṃ upavicarati, domanassaṭṭhāniyaṃ rūpaṃ upavicarati, upekkhāṭṭhāniyaṃ rūpaṃ upavicarati;**Seeing a sight with the eye, one is preoccupied with a sight that’s a basis for happiness or sadness or equanimity.*";
P_HTM[6479]="*sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**Hearing a sound with the ear …*";
P_HTM[6480]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā …**Smelling an odor with the nose …*";
P_HTM[6481]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā …**Tasting a flavor with the tongue …*";
P_HTM[6482]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā …**Feeling a touch with the body …*";
P_HTM[6483]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya somanassaṭṭhāniyaṃ dhammaṃ upavicarati, domanassaṭṭhāniyaṃ dhammaṃ upavicarati, upekkhāṭṭhāniyaṃ dhammaṃ upavicarati—**Becoming conscious of a thought with the mind, one is preoccupied with a thought that’s a basis for happiness or sadness or equanimity.*";
P_HTM[6484]="*iti cha somanassupavicārā, cha domanassupavicārā, cha upekkhupavicārā.**So there are six preoccupations with happiness, six preoccupations with sadness, and six preoccupations with equanimity.*";
P_HTM[6485]="*‘Aṭṭhārasa manopavicāro ayaṃ, bhikkhu, puriso’ti—**‘This person has eighteen mental preoccupations.’*";
P_HTM[6486]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6487]="*‘Caturādhiṭṭhāno ayaṃ, bhikkhu, puriso’ti—**‘This person has four foundations.’*";
P_HTM[6488]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6489]="*Paññādhiṭṭhāno, saccādhiṭṭhāno, cāgādhiṭṭhāno, upasamādhiṭṭhāno.**The foundations of wisdom, truth, generosity, and peace.*";
P_HTM[6490]="*‘Caturādhiṭṭhāno ayaṃ, bhikkhu, puriso’ti—**‘This person has four foundations.’*";
P_HTM[6491]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6492]="*‘Paññaṃ nappamajjeyya, saccamanurakkheyya, cāgamanubrūheyya, santimeva so sikkheyyā’ti—**‘Don’t neglect wisdom, preserve truth, foster generosity, and train only for peace.’*";
P_HTM[6493]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6494]="*Kathañca, bhikkhu, paññaṃ nappamajjati?**And how does one not neglect wisdom?*";
P_HTM[6495]="*Chayimā, bhikkhu, dhātuyo—**There are these six elements:*";
P_HTM[6496]="*pathavīdhātu, āpodhātu, tejodhātu, vāyodhātu, ākāsadhātu, viññāṇadhātu.**the elements of earth, water, fire, air, space, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6497]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhu, pathavīdhātu?**And what is the earth element?*";
P_HTM[6498]="*Pathavīdhātu siyā ajjhattikā siyā bāhirā.**The earth element may be interior or exterior.*";
P_HTM[6499]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhu, ajjhattikā pathavīdhātu?**And what is the interior earth element?*";
P_HTM[6500]="*Yaṃ ajjhattaṃ paccattaṃ kakkhaḷaṃ kharigataṃ upādinnaṃ, seyyathidaṃ—**Anything hard, solid, and organic that’s internal, pertaining to an individual. This includes*";
P_HTM[6501]="*kesā lomā nakhā dantā taco maṃsaṃ nhāru aṭṭhi aṭṭhimiñjaṃ vakkaṃ hadayaṃ yakanaṃ kilomakaṃ pihakaṃ papphāsaṃ antaṃ antaguṇaṃ udariyaṃ karīsaṃ, yaṃ vā panaññampi kiñci ajjhattaṃ paccattaṃ kakkhaḷaṃ kharigataṃ upādinnaṃ—**head hair, body hair, nails, teeth, skin, flesh, sinews, bones, bone marrow, kidneys, heart, liver, diaphragm, spleen, lungs, intestines, mesentery, undigested food, feces, or anything else hard, solid, and organic that’s internal, pertaining to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6502]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu, ajjhattikā pathavīdhātu.**This is called the interior earth element.*";
P_HTM[6503]="*Yā ceva kho pana ajjhattikā pathavīdhātu yā ca bāhirā pathavīdhātu pathavīdhāturevesā.**The interior earth element and the exterior earth element are just the earth element.*";
P_HTM[6504]="*‘Taṃ netaṃ mama nesohamasmi na meso attā’ti—evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**This should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[6505]="*Evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya disvā pathavīdhātuyā nibbindati, pathavīdhātuyā cittaṃ virājeti.**When you truly see with right understanding, you reject the earth element, detaching the mind from the earth element.*";
P_HTM[6506]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhu, āpodhātu?**And what is the water element?*";
P_HTM[6507]="*Āpodhātu siyā ajjhattikā siyā bāhirā.**The water element may be interior or exterior.*";
P_HTM[6508]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhu, ajjhattikā āpodhātu?**And what is the interior water element?*";
P_HTM[6509]="*Yaṃ ajjhattaṃ paccattaṃ āpo āpogataṃ upādinnaṃ seyyathidaṃ—**Anything that’s water, watery, and organic that’s internal, pertaining to an individual. This includes*";
P_HTM[6510]="*pittaṃ semhaṃ pubbo lohitaṃ sedo medo assu vasā kheḷo siṅghāṇikā lasikā muttaṃ, yaṃ vā panaññampi kiñci ajjhattaṃ paccattaṃ āpo āpogataṃ upādinnaṃ—**bile, phlegm, pus, blood, sweat, fat, tears, grease, saliva, snot, synovial fluid, urine, or anything else that’s water, watery, and organic that’s internal, pertaining to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6511]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu, ajjhattikā āpodhātu.**This is called the interior water element.*";
P_HTM[6512]="*Yā ceva kho pana ajjhattikā āpodhātu yā ca bāhirā āpodhātu āpodhāturevesā.**The interior water element and the exterior water element are just the water element.*";
P_HTM[6513]="*‘Taṃ netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti—evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**This should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[6514]="*Evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya disvā āpodhātuyā nibbindati, āpodhātuyā cittaṃ virājeti.**When you truly see with right understanding, you reject the water element, detaching the mind from the water element.*";
P_HTM[6515]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhu, tejodhātu?**And what is the fire element?*";
P_HTM[6516]="*Tejodhātu siyā ajjhattikā siyā bāhirā.**The fire element may be interior or exterior.*";
P_HTM[6517]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhu, ajjhattikā tejodhātu?**And what is the interior fire element?*";
P_HTM[6518]="*Yaṃ ajjhattaṃ paccattaṃ tejo tejogataṃ upādinnaṃ, seyyathidaṃ—**Anything that’s fire, fiery, and organic that’s internal, pertaining to an individual. This includes*";
P_HTM[6519]="*yena ca santappati, yena ca jīrīyati, yena ca pariḍayhati, yena ca asitapītakhāyitasāyitaṃ sammā pariṇāmaṃ gacchati, yaṃ vā panaññampi kiñci ajjhattaṃ paccattaṃ tejo tejogataṃ upādinnaṃ—**that which warms, that which ages, that which heats you up when feverish, that which properly digests food and drink, or anything else that’s fire, fiery, and organic that’s internal, pertaining to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6520]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu, ajjhattikā tejodhātu.**This is called the interior fire element.*";
P_HTM[6521]="*Yā ceva kho pana ajjhattikā tejodhātu yā ca bāhirā tejodhātu tejodhāturevesā.**The interior fire element and the exterior fire element are just the fire element.*";
P_HTM[6522]="*‘Taṃ netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti—evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**This should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[6523]="*Evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya disvā tejodhātuyā nibbindati, tejodhātuyā cittaṃ virājeti.**When you truly see with right understanding, you reject the fire element, detaching the mind from the fire element.*";
P_HTM[6524]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhu, vāyodhātu?**And what is the air element?*";
P_HTM[6525]="*Vāyodhātu siyā ajjhattikā siyā bāhirā.**The air element may be interior or exterior.*";
P_HTM[6526]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhu, ajjhattikā vāyodhātu?**And what is the interior air element?*";
P_HTM[6527]="*Yaṃ ajjhattaṃ paccattaṃ vāyo vāyogataṃ upādinnaṃ, seyyathidaṃ—**Anything that’s air, airy, and organic that’s internal, pertaining to an individual. This includes*";
P_HTM[6528]="*uddhaṅgamā vātā adhogamā vātā kucchisayā vātā koṭṭhāsayā vātā aṅgamaṅgānusārino vātā assāso passāso iti, yaṃ vā panaññampi kiñci ajjhattaṃ paccattaṃ vāyo vāyogataṃ upādinnaṃ—**winds that go up or down, winds in the belly or the bowels, winds that flow through the limbs, in-breaths and out-breaths, or anything else that’s air, airy, and organic that’s internal, pertaining to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6529]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu, ajjhattikā vāyodhātu.**This is called the interior air element.*";
P_HTM[6530]="*Yā ceva kho pana ajjhattikā vāyodhātu yā ca bāhirā vāyodhātu vāyodhāturevesā.**The interior air element and the exterior air element are just the air element.*";
P_HTM[6531]="*‘Taṃ netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti—evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**This should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[6532]="*Evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya disvā vāyodhātuyā nibbindati, vāyodhātuyā cittaṃ virājeti.**When you truly see with right understanding, you reject the air element, detaching the mind from the air element.*";
P_HTM[6533]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhu, ākāsadhātu?**And what is the space element?*";
P_HTM[6534]="*Ākāsadhātu siyā ajjhattikā siyā bāhirā.**The space element may be interior or exterior.*";
P_HTM[6535]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhu, ajjhattikā ākāsadhātu?**And what is the interior space element?*";
P_HTM[6536]="*Yaṃ ajjhattaṃ paccattaṃ ākāsaṃ ākāsagataṃ upādinnaṃ, seyyathidaṃ—**Anything that’s space, spacious, and organic that’s internal, pertaining to an individual. This includes*";
P_HTM[6537]="*kaṇṇacchiddaṃ nāsacchiddaṃ mukhadvāraṃ yena ca asitapītakhāyitasāyitaṃ ajjhoharati, yattha ca asitapītakhāyitasāyitaṃ santiṭṭhati, yena ca asitapītakhāyitasāyitaṃ adhobhāgaṃ nikkhamati, yaṃ vā panaññampi kiñci ajjhattaṃ paccattaṃ ākāsaṃ ākāsagataṃ aghaṃ aghagataṃ vivaraṃ vivaragataṃ asamphuṭṭhaṃ maṃsalohitehi upādinnaṃ—**the ear canals, nostrils, and mouth; and the space for swallowing what is eaten and drunk, the space where it stays, and the space for excreting it from the nether regions.*";
P_HTM[6538]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu, ajjhattikā ākāsadhātu.**This is called the interior space element.*";
P_HTM[6539]="*Yā ceva kho pana ajjhattikā ākāsadhātu yā ca bāhirā ākāsadhātu ākāsadhāturevesā.**The interior space element and the exterior space element are just the space element.*";
P_HTM[6540]="*‘Taṃ netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti—evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya daṭṭhabbaṃ.**This should be truly seen with right understanding like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[6541]="*Evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya disvā ākāsadhātuyā nibbindati, ākāsadhātuyā cittaṃ virājeti.**When you truly see with right understanding, you reject the space element, detaching the mind from the space element.*";
P_HTM[6542]="*Athāparaṃ viññāṇaṃyeva avasissati parisuddhaṃ pariyodātaṃ.**There remains only consciousness, pure and bright.*";
P_HTM[6543]="*Tena ca viññāṇena kiṃ vijānāti?**And what does that consciousness know?*";
P_HTM[6544]="*‘Sukhan’tipi vijānāti, ‘dukkhan’tipi vijānāti, ‘adukkhamasukhan’tipi vijānāti.**It knows ‘pleasure’ and ‘pain’ and ‘neutral’.*";
P_HTM[6545]="*Sukhavedaniyaṃ, bhikkhu, phassaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhā vedanā.**Pleasant feeling arises dependent on a contact to be experienced as pleasant.*";
P_HTM[6546]="*So sukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘sukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti.**When they feel a pleasant feeling, they know: ‘I feel a pleasant feeling.’*";
P_HTM[6547]="*‘Tasseva sukhavedaniyassa phassassa nirodhā yaṃ tajjaṃ vedayitaṃ sukhavedaniyaṃ phassaṃ paṭicca uppannā sukhā vedanā sā nirujjhati, sā vūpasammatī’ti pajānāti.**They know: ‘With the cessation of that contact to be experienced as pleasant, the corresponding pleasant feeling ceases and stops.’*";
P_HTM[6548]="*Dukkhavedaniyaṃ, bhikkhu, phassaṃ paṭicca uppajjati dukkhā vedanā.**Painful feeling arises dependent on a contact to be experienced as painful.*";
P_HTM[6549]="*So dukkhaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘dukkhaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti.**When they feel a painful feeling, they know: ‘I feel a painful feeling.’*";
P_HTM[6550]="*‘Tasseva dukkhavedaniyassa phassassa nirodhā yaṃ tajjaṃ vedayitaṃ dukkhavedaniyaṃ phassaṃ paṭicca uppannā dukkhā vedanā sā nirujjhati, sā vūpasammatī’ti pajānāti.**They know: ‘With the cessation of that contact to be experienced as painful, the corresponding painful feeling ceases and stops.’*";
P_HTM[6551]="*Adukkhamasukhavedaniyaṃ, bhikkhu, phassaṃ paṭicca uppajjati adukkhamasukhā vedanā.**Neutral feeling arises dependent on a contact to be experienced as neutral.*";
P_HTM[6552]="*So adukkhamasukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘adukkhamasukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti.**When they feel a neutral feeling, they know: ‘I feel a neutral feeling.’*";
P_HTM[6553]="*‘Tasseva adukkhamasukhavedaniyassa phassassa nirodhā yaṃ tajjaṃ vedayitaṃ adukkhamasukhavedaniyaṃ phassaṃ paṭicca uppannā adukkhamasukhā vedanā sā nirujjhati, sā vūpasammatī’ti pajānāti.**They know: ‘With the cessation of that contact to be experienced as neutral, the corresponding neutral feeling ceases and stops.’*";
P_HTM[6554]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhu, dvinnaṃ kaṭṭhānaṃ saṅghaṭṭā samodhānā usmā jāyati, tejo abhinibbattati, tesaṃyeva dvinnaṃ kaṭṭhānaṃ nānābhāvā vinikkhepā yā tajjā usmā sā nirujjhati, sā vūpasammati;**When you rub two sticks together, heat is generated and fire is produced. But when you part the sticks and lay them aside, any corresponding heat ceases and stops.*";
P_HTM[6555]="*evameva kho, bhikkhu, sukhavedaniyaṃ phassaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhā vedanā.**In the same way, pleasant feeling arises dependent on a contact to be experienced as pleasant. …*";
P_HTM[6556]="*So sukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘sukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[6557]="*‘Tasseva sukhavedaniyassa phassassa nirodhā yaṃ tajjaṃ vedayitaṃ sukhavedaniyaṃ phassaṃ paṭicca uppannā sukhā vedanā sā nirujjhati, sā vūpasammatī’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[6558]="*Dukkhavedaniyaṃ, bhikkhu, phassaṃ paṭicca uppajjati dukkhā vedanā.* **";
P_HTM[6559]="*So dukkhaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘dukkhaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[6560]="*‘Tasseva dukkhavedaniyassa phassassa nirodhā yaṃ tajjaṃ vedayitaṃ dukkhavedaniyaṃ phassaṃ paṭicca uppannā dukkhā vedanā sā nirujjhati, sā vūpasammatī’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[6561]="*Adukkhamasukhavedaniyaṃ, bhikkhu, phassaṃ paṭicca uppajjati adukkhamasukhā vedanā.* **";
P_HTM[6562]="*So adukkhamasukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘adukkhamasukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[6563]="*‘Tasseva adukkhamasukhavedaniyassa phassassa nirodhā yaṃ tajjaṃ vedayitaṃ adukkhamasukhavedaniyaṃ phassaṃ paṭicca uppannā adukkhamasukhā vedanā sā nirujjhati, sā vūpasammatī’ti pajānāti.**They know: ‘With the cessation of that contact to be experienced as neutral, the corresponding neutral feeling ceases and stops.’*";
P_HTM[6564]="*Athāparaṃ upekkhāyeva avasissati parisuddhā pariyodātā mudu ca kammaññā ca pabhassarā ca.**There remains only equanimity, pure, bright, pliable, workable, and radiant.*";
P_HTM[6565]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhu, dakkho suvaṇṇakāro vā suvaṇṇakārantevāsī vā ukkaṃ bandheyya, ukkaṃ bandhitvā ukkāmukhaṃ ālimpeyya, ukkāmukhaṃ ālimpetvā saṇḍāsena jātarūpaṃ gahetvā ukkāmukhe pakkhipeyya, tamenaṃ kālena kālaṃ abhidhameyya, kālena kālaṃ udakena paripphoseyya, kālena kālaṃ ajjhupekkheyya, taṃ hoti jātarūpaṃ sudhantaṃ niddhantaṃ nīhaṭaṃ ninnītakasāvaṃ mudu ca kammaññañca pabhassarañca, yassā yassā ca piḷandhanavikatiyā ākaṅkhati—yadi paṭṭikāya yadi kuṇḍalāya yadi gīveyyakāya yadi suvaṇṇamālāya tañcassa atthaṃ anubhoti;**It’s like when a goldsmith or a goldsmith’s apprentice prepares a forge, fires the crucible, picks up some gold with tongs and puts it in the crucible. From time to time they fan it, from time to time they sprinkle water on it, and from time to time they just watch over it. That gold becomes pliable, workable, and radiant, not brittle, and is ready to be worked. Then the goldsmith can successfully create any kind of ornament they want, whether a bracelet, earrings, a necklace, or a golden garland.*";
P_HTM[6566]="*evameva kho, bhikkhu, athāparaṃ upekkhāyeva avasissati parisuddhā pariyodātā mudu ca kammaññā ca pabhassarā ca.**In the same way, there remains only equanimity, pure, bright, pliable, workable, and radiant.*";
P_HTM[6567]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[6568]="*‘imañce ahaṃ upekkhaṃ evaṃ parisuddhaṃ evaṃ pariyodātaṃ ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasaṃhareyyaṃ, tadanudhammañca cittaṃ bhāveyyaṃ.**‘If I were to apply this equanimity, so pure and bright, to the dimension of infinite space, my mind would develop accordingly.*";
P_HTM[6569]="*Evaṃ me ayaṃ upekkhā tannissitā tadupādānā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭheyya.**And this equanimity of mine, relying on that and grasping it, would remain for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[6570]="*Imañce ahaṃ upekkhaṃ evaṃ parisuddhaṃ evaṃ pariyodātaṃ viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasaṃhareyyaṃ, tadanudhammañca cittaṃ bhāveyyaṃ.**If I were to apply this equanimity, so pure and bright, to the dimension of infinite consciousness, my mind would develop accordingly.*";
P_HTM[6571]="*Evaṃ me ayaṃ upekkhā tannissitā tadupādānā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭheyya.**And this equanimity of mine, relying on that and grasping it, would remain for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[6572]="*Imañce ahaṃ upekkhaṃ evaṃ parisuddhaṃ evaṃ pariyodātaṃ ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasaṃhareyyaṃ, tadanudhammañca cittaṃ bhāveyyaṃ.**If I were to apply this equanimity, so pure and bright, to the dimension of nothingness, my mind would develop accordingly.*";
P_HTM[6573]="*Evaṃ me ayaṃ upekkhā tannissitā tadupādānā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭheyya.**And this equanimity of mine, relying on that and grasping it, would remain for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[6574]="*Imañce ahaṃ upekkhaṃ evaṃ parisuddhaṃ evaṃ pariyodātaṃ nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasaṃhareyyaṃ, tadanudhammañca cittaṃ bhāveyyaṃ.**If I were to apply this equanimity, so pure and bright, to the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, my mind would develop accordingly.*";
P_HTM[6575]="*Evaṃ me ayaṃ upekkhā tannissitā tadupādānā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭheyyā’ti.**And this equanimity of mine, relying on that and grasping it, would remain for a very long time.’*";
P_HTM[6576]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[6577]="*‘imañce ahaṃ upekkhaṃ evaṃ parisuddhaṃ evaṃ pariyodātaṃ ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasaṃhareyyaṃ, tadanudhammañca cittaṃ bhāveyyaṃ;**‘If I were to apply this equanimity, so pure and bright, to the dimension of infinite space, my mind would develop accordingly.*";
P_HTM[6578]="*saṅkhatametaṃ.**But that is conditioned.*";
P_HTM[6579]="*Imañce ahaṃ upekkhaṃ evaṃ parisuddhaṃ evaṃ pariyodātaṃ viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasaṃhareyyaṃ, tadanudhammañca cittaṃ bhāveyyaṃ;**If I were to apply this equanimity, so pure and bright, to the dimension of infinite consciousness …*";
P_HTM[6580]="*saṅkhatametaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6581]="*Imañce ahaṃ upekkhaṃ evaṃ parisuddhaṃ evaṃ pariyodātaṃ ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasaṃhareyyaṃ, tadanudhammañca cittaṃ bhāveyyaṃ;**nothingness …*";
P_HTM[6582]="*saṅkhatametaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6583]="*Imañce ahaṃ upekkhaṃ evaṃ parisuddhaṃ evaṃ pariyodātaṃ nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasaṃhareyyaṃ, tadanudhammañca cittaṃ bhāveyyaṃ;**neither perception nor non-perception, my mind would develop accordingly.*";
P_HTM[6584]="*saṅkhatametan’ti.**But that is conditioned.’*";
P_HTM[6585]="*So neva taṃ abhisaṅkharoti, na abhisañcetayati bhavāya vā vibhavāya vā.**They neither make a choice nor form an intention to continue existence or to end existence.*";
P_HTM[6586]="*So anabhisaṅkharonto anabhisañcetayanto bhavāya vā vibhavāya vā na kiñci loke upādiyati,**Because of this, they don’t grasp at anything in the world.*";
P_HTM[6587]="*anupādiyaṃ na paritassati, aparitassaṃ paccattaṃyeva parinibbāyati.**Not grasping, they’re not anxious. Not being anxious, they personally become extinguished.*";
P_HTM[6588]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[6589]="*So sukhañce vedanaṃ vedeti, ‘sā aniccā’ti pajānāti, ‘anajjhositā’ti pajānāti, ‘anabhinanditā’ti pajānāti.**If they feel a pleasant feeling, they understand that it’s impermanent, that they’re not attached to it, and that they don’t take pleasure in it.*";
P_HTM[6590]="*Dukkhañce vedanaṃ vedeti, ‘sā aniccā’ti pajānāti, ‘anajjhositā’ti pajānāti, ‘anabhinanditā’ti pajānāti.**If they feel a painful feeling, they understand that it’s impermanent, that they’re not attached to it, and that they don’t take pleasure in it.*";
P_HTM[6591]="*Adukkhamasukhañce vedanaṃ vedeti, ‘sā aniccā’ti pajānāti, ‘anajjhositā’ti pajānāti, ‘anabhinanditā’ti pajānāti.**If they feel a neutral feeling, they understand that it’s impermanent, that they’re not attached to it, and that they don’t take pleasure in it.*";
P_HTM[6592]="*So sukhañce vedanaṃ vedeti, visaṃyutto naṃ vedeti;**If they feel a pleasant feeling, they feel it detached.*";
P_HTM[6593]="*dukkhañce vedanaṃ vedeti, visaṃyutto naṃ vedeti;**If they feel a painful feeling, they feel it detached.*";
P_HTM[6594]="*adukkhamasukhañce vedanaṃ vedeti, visaṃyutto naṃ vedeti.**If they feel a neutral feeling, they feel it detached.*";
P_HTM[6595]="*So kāyapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘kāyapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti, jīvitapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘jīvitapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti,**Feeling the end of the body approaching, they understand: ‘I feel the end of the body approaching.’ Feeling the end of life approaching, they understand: ‘I feel the end of life approaching.’*";
P_HTM[6596]="*‘kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā uddhaṃ jīvitapariyādānā idheva sabbavedayitāni anabhinanditāni sītībhavissantī’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘When my body breaks up and my life has come to an end, everything that’s felt, since I no longer take pleasure in it, will become cool right here.’*";
P_HTM[6597]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhu, telañca paṭicca vaṭṭiñca paṭicca telappadīpo jhāyati;**Suppose an oil lamp depended on oil and a wick to burn.*";
P_HTM[6598]="*tasseva telassa ca vaṭṭiyā ca pariyādānā aññassa ca anupahārā anāhāro nibbāyati;**As the oil and the wick are used up, it would be extinguished due to lack of fuel.*";
P_HTM[6599]="*evameva kho, bhikkhu, kāyapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘kāyapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti, jīvitapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘jīvitapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti,**In the same way, feeling the end of the body approaching, they understand: ‘I feel the end of the body approaching.’ Feeling the end of life approaching, they understand: ‘I feel the end of life approaching.’*";
P_HTM[6600]="*‘kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā uddhaṃ jīvitapariyādānā idheva sabbavedayitāni anabhinanditāni sītībhavissantī’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘When my body breaks up and my life has come to an end, everything that’s felt, since I no longer take pleasure in it, will become cool right here.’*";
P_HTM[6601]="*Tasmā evaṃ samannāgato bhikkhu iminā paramena paññādhiṭṭhānena samannāgato hoti.**Therefore a mendicant thus endowed is endowed with the ultimate foundation of wisdom.*";
P_HTM[6602]="*Esā hi, bhikkhu, paramā ariyā paññā yadidaṃ—**For this is the ultimate noble wisdom, namely,*";
P_HTM[6603]="*sabbadukkhakkhaye ñāṇaṃ.**the knowledge of the ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[6604]="*Tassa sā vimutti sacce ṭhitā akuppā hoti.**Their freedom, being founded on truth, is unshakable.*";
P_HTM[6605]="*Tañhi, bhikkhu, musā yaṃ mosadhammaṃ, taṃ saccaṃ yaṃ amosadhammaṃ nibbānaṃ.**For that which is false has a deceptive nature, while that which is true has an undeceptive nature—extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[6606]="*Tasmā evaṃ samannāgato bhikkhu iminā paramena saccādhiṭṭhānena samannāgato hoti.**Therefore a mendicant thus endowed is endowed with the ultimate foundation of truth.*";
P_HTM[6607]="*Etañhi, bhikkhu, paramaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yadidaṃ—**For this is the ultimate noble truth, namely,*";
P_HTM[6608]="*amosadhammaṃ nibbānaṃ.**that which has an undeceptive nature—extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[6609]="*Tasseva kho pana pubbe aviddasuno upadhī honti samattā samādinnā.**In their ignorance, they used to acquire attachments.*";
P_HTM[6610]="*Tyāssa pahīnā honti ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**Those have been cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, obliterated so they are unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[6611]="*Tasmā evaṃ samannāgato bhikkhu iminā paramena cāgādhiṭṭhānena samannāgato hoti.**Therefore a mendicant thus endowed is endowed with the ultimate foundation of generosity.*";
P_HTM[6612]="*Eso hi, bhikkhu, paramo ariyo cāgo yadidaṃ—**For this is the ultimate noble generosity, namely,*";
P_HTM[6613]="*sabbūpadhipaṭinissaggo.**letting go of all attachments.*";
P_HTM[6614]="*Tasseva kho pana pubbe aviddasuno abhijjhā hoti chando sārāgo.**In their ignorance, they used to be covetous, full of desire and lust.*";
P_HTM[6615]="*Svāssa pahīno hoti ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo.**That has been cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, obliterated so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[6616]="*Tasseva kho pana pubbe aviddasuno āghāto hoti byāpādo sampadoso.**In their ignorance, they used to be contemptuous, full of ill will and malevolence.*";
P_HTM[6617]="*Svāssa pahīno hoti ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo.**That has been cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, obliterated so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[6618]="*Tasseva kho pana pubbe aviddasuno avijjā hoti sammoho.**In their ignorance, they used to be ignorant, full of delusion.*";
P_HTM[6619]="*Svāssa pahīno hoti ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo.**That has been cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, obliterated so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[6620]="*Tasmā evaṃ samannāgato bhikkhu iminā paramena upasamādhiṭṭhānena samannāgato hoti.**Therefore a mendicant thus endowed is endowed with the ultimate foundation of peace.*";
P_HTM[6621]="*Eso hi, bhikkhu, paramo ariyo upasamo yadidaṃ—**For this is the ultimate noble peace, namely,*";
P_HTM[6622]="*rāgadosamohānaṃ upasamo.**the pacification of greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[6623]="*‘Paññaṃ nappamajjeyya, saccamanurakkheyya, cāgamanubrūheyya, santimeva so sikkheyyā’ti—**‘Don’t neglect wisdom, preserve truth, foster generosity, and train only for peace.’*";
P_HTM[6624]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6625]="*‘Yattha ṭhitaṃ maññassavā nappavattanti, maññassave kho pana nappavattamāne muni santoti vuccatī’ti—**‘They have four foundations, standing on which the streams of identification don’t flow. And when the streams of identification don’t flow, they’re called a sage at peace.’*";
P_HTM[6626]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[6627]="*‘Asmī’ti, bhikkhu, maññitametaṃ, ‘ayamahamasmī’ti maññitametaṃ, ‘bhavissan’ti maññitametaṃ, ‘na bhavissan’ti maññitametaṃ, ‘rūpī bhavissan’ti maññitametaṃ, ‘arūpī bhavissan’ti maññitametaṃ, ‘saññī bhavissan’ti maññitametaṃ, ‘asaññī bhavissan’ti maññitametaṃ, ‘nevasaññīnāsaññī bhavissan’ti maññitametaṃ.**These are all forms of identifying: ‘I am’, ‘I am this’, ‘I will be’, ‘I will not be’, ‘I will have form’, ‘I will be formless’, ‘I will be percipient’, ‘I will be non-percipient’, ‘I will be neither percipient nor non-percipient.’*";
P_HTM[6628]="*Maññitaṃ, bhikkhu, rogo maññitaṃ gaṇḍo maññitaṃ sallaṃ.**Identification is a disease, a boil, a dart.*";
P_HTM[6629]="*Sabbamaññitānaṃ tveva, bhikkhu, samatikkamā muni santoti vuccati.**Having gone beyond all identification, one is called a sage at peace.*";
P_HTM[6630]="*Muni kho pana, bhikkhu, santo na jāyati, na jīyati, na mīyati, na kuppati, na piheti.**The sage at peace is not reborn, does not grow old, and does not die. They are not shaken, and do not yearn.*";
P_HTM[6631]="*Tañhissa, bhikkhu, natthi yena jāyetha, ajāyamāno kiṃ jīyissati, ajīyamāno kiṃ mīyissati, amīyamāno kiṃ kuppissati, akuppamāno kissa pihessati?**For they have nothing which would cause them to be reborn. Not being reborn, how could they grow old? Not growing old, how could they die? Not dying, how could they be shaken? Not shaking, for what could they yearn?*";
P_HTM[6632]="*‘Yattha ṭhitaṃ maññassavā nappavattanti, maññassave kho pana nappavattamāne muni santoti vuccatī’ti—**‘They have four foundations, standing on which the streams of identification don’t flow. And when the streams of identification don’t flow, they’re called a sage at peace.’*";
P_HTM[6633]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[6634]="*Imaṃ kho me tvaṃ, bhikkhu, saṃkhittena chadhātuvibhaṅgaṃ dhārehī”ti.**Mendicant, you should remember this brief analysis of the six elements.”*";
P_HTM[6635]="*Atha kho āyasmā pukkusāti:**Then Venerable Pukkusāti thought,*";
P_HTM[6636]="*“satthā kira me anuppatto, sugato kira me anuppatto, sammāsambuddho kira me anuppatto”ti uṭṭhāyāsanā ekaṃsaṃ cīvaraṃ katvā bhagavato pādesu sirasā nipatitvā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**“It seems the Teacher has come to me! The Holy One has come to me! The fully awakened Buddha has come to me!” He got up from his seat, arranged his robe over one shoulder, bowed with his head to the Buddha’s feet, and said,*";
P_HTM[6637]="*“accayo maṃ, bhante, accagamā yathābālaṃ yathāmūḷhaṃ yathāakusalaṃ, yohaṃ bhagavantaṃ āvusovādena samudācaritabbaṃ amaññissaṃ.**“I have made a mistake, sir. It was foolish, stupid, and unskillful of me to presume to address the Buddha as ‘reverend’.*";
P_HTM[6638]="*Tassa me, bhante, bhagavā accayaṃ accayato paṭiggaṇhātu āyatiṃ saṃvarāyā”ti.**Please, sir, accept my mistake for what it is, so I will restrain myself in future.”*";
P_HTM[6639]="*“Taggha tvaṃ, bhikkhu, accayo accagamā yathābālaṃ yathāmūḷhaṃ yathāakusalaṃ, yaṃ maṃ tvaṃ āvusovādena samudācaritabbaṃ amaññittha.**“Indeed, mendicant, you made a mistake. It was foolish, stupid, and unskillful of you to act in that way.*";
P_HTM[6640]="*Yato ca kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, accayaṃ accayato disvā yathādhammaṃ paṭikarosi, taṃ te mayaṃ paṭiggaṇhāma.**But since you have recognized your mistake for what it is, and have dealt with it properly, I accept it.*";
P_HTM[6641]="*Vuddhihesā, bhikkhu, ariyassa vinaye yo accayaṃ accayato disvā yathādhammaṃ paṭikaroti, āyatiṃ saṃvaraṃ āpajjatī”ti.**For it is growth in the training of the noble one to recognize a mistake for what it is, deal with it properly, and commit to restraint in the future.”*";
P_HTM[6642]="*“Labheyyāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato santike upasampadan”ti.**“Sir, may I receive the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha’s presence?”*";
P_HTM[6643]="*“Paripuṇṇaṃ pana te, bhikkhu, pattacīvaran”ti?**“But mendicant, are your bowl and robes complete?”*";
P_HTM[6644]="*“Na kho me, bhante, paripuṇṇaṃ pattacīvaran”ti.**“No, sir, they are not.”*";
P_HTM[6645]="*“Na kho, bhikkhu, tathāgatā aparipuṇṇapattacīvaraṃ upasampādentī”ti.**“The Realized Ones do not ordain those whose bowl and robes are incomplete.”*";
P_HTM[6646]="*Atha kho āyasmā pukkusāti bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pattacīvarapariyesanaṃ pakkāmi.**And then Venerable Pukkusāti approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[6647]="*Atha kho āyasmantaṃ pukkusātiṃ pattacīvarapariyesanaṃ carantaṃ vibbhantā gāvī jīvitā voropesi.**But while he was wandering in search of a bowl and robes, a stray cow took his life.*";
P_HTM[6648]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several mendicants went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[6649]="*“yo so, bhante, pukkusāti nāma kulaputto bhagavatā saṃkhittena ovādena ovadito so kālaṅkato.**“Sir, the gentleman named Pukkusāti, who was advised in brief by the Buddha, has passed away.*";
P_HTM[6650]="*Tassa kā gati, ko abhisamparāyo”ti?**Where has he been reborn in his next life?”*";
P_HTM[6651]="*“Paṇḍito, bhikkhave, pukkusāti kulaputto paccapādi dhammassānudhammaṃ, na ca maṃ dhammādhikaraṇaṃ vihesesi.**“Mendicants, Pukkusāti was astute. He practiced in line with the teachings, and did not trouble me about the teachings.*";
P_HTM[6652]="*Pukkusāti, bhikkhave, kulaputto pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātiko tattha parinibbāyī anāvattidhammo tasmā lokā”ti.**With the ending of the five lower fetters, he’s been reborn spontaneously and will become extinguished there, not liable to return from that world.”*";
P_HTM[6653]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[6654]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[6655]="*Dhātuvibhaṅgasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6656]="*141. Saccavibhaṅgasutta**The Analysis of the Truths*";
P_HTM[6657]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[6658]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā bārāṇasiyaṃ viharati isipatane migadāye.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana.*";
P_HTM[6659]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[6660]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[6661]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[6662]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[6663]="*“Tathāgatena, bhikkhave, arahatā sammāsambuddhena bārāṇasiyaṃ isipatane migadāye anuttaraṃ dhammacakkaṃ pavattitaṃ appaṭivattiyaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ, yadidaṃ—**“Near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana, the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha rolled forth the supreme Wheel of Dhamma. And that wheel cannot be rolled back by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[6664]="*catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ ācikkhanā desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ.**It is the teaching, advocating, establishing, clarifying, analyzing, and revealing of the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[6665]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[6666]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa ācikkhanā desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ, dukkhasamudayassa ariyasaccassa ācikkhanā desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ, dukkhanirodhassa ariyasaccassa ācikkhanā desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa ācikkhanā desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ.**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[6667]="*Tathāgatena, bhikkhave, arahatā sammāsambuddhena bārāṇasiyaṃ isipatane migadāye anuttaraṃ dhammacakkaṃ pavattitaṃ appaṭivattiyaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ, yadidaṃ—**Near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana, the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha rolled forth the supreme Wheel of Dhamma. And that wheel cannot be rolled back by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[6668]="*imesaṃ catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ ācikkhanā desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ.**It is the teaching, advocating, establishing, clarifying, analyzing, and revealing of the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[6669]="*Sevatha, bhikkhave, sāriputtamoggallāne;**Mendicants, you should cultivate friendship with Sāriputta and Moggallāna.*";
P_HTM[6670]="*bhajatha, bhikkhave, sāriputtamoggallāne.**You should associate with Sāriputta and Moggallāna.*";
P_HTM[6671]="*Paṇḍitā bhikkhū anuggāhakā sabrahmacārīnaṃ.**They’re astute, and they support their spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[6672]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, janetā, evaṃ sāriputto;**Sāriputta is just like the mother who gives birth,*";
P_HTM[6673]="*seyyathāpi jātassa āpādetā, evaṃ moggallāno.**while Moggallāna is like the one who raises the child.*";
P_HTM[6674]="*Sāriputto, bhikkhave, sotāpattiphale vineti, moggallāno uttamatthe.**Sāriputta guides people to the fruit of stream-entry, Moggallāna to the highest goal.*";
P_HTM[6675]="*Sāriputto, bhikkhave, pahoti cattāri ariyasaccāni vitthārena ācikkhituṃ desetuṃ paññāpetuṃ paṭṭhapetuṃ vivarituṃ vibhajituṃ uttānīkātun”ti.**Sāriputta is able to teach, assert, establish, clarify, analyze, and reveal the four noble truths.”*";
P_HTM[6676]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[6677]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ pāvisi.**When he had spoken, the Holy One got up from his seat and entered his dwelling.*";
P_HTM[6678]="*Tatra kho āyasmā sāriputto acirapakkantassa bhagavato bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then soon after the Buddha left, Venerable Sāriputta said to the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[6679]="*“āvuso bhikkhave”ti.**“Reverends, mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[6680]="*“Āvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosuṃ.**“Reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[6681]="*Āyasmā sāriputto etadavoca:**Sāriputta said this:*";
P_HTM[6682]="*“Tathāgatena, āvuso, arahatā sammāsambuddhena bārāṇasiyaṃ isipatane migadāye anuttaraṃ dhammacakkaṃ pavattitaṃ appaṭivattiyaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ, yadidaṃ—**“Near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana, the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha rolled forth the supreme Wheel of Dhamma. And that wheel cannot be rolled back by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[6683]="*catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ ācikkhanā desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ.**It is the teaching, advocating, establishing, clarifying, analyzing, and revealing of the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[6684]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[6685]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa ācikkhanā desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ, dukkhasamudayassa ariyasaccassa ācikkhanā desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ, dukkhanirodhassa ariyasaccassa ācikkhanā desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa ācikkhanā desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ.**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[6686]="*Katamañcāvuso, dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ?**And what is the noble truth of suffering?*";
P_HTM[6687]="*Jātipi dukkhā, jarāpi dukkhā, maraṇampi dukkhaṃ, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsāpi dukkhā, yampicchaṃ na labhati tampi dukkhaṃ; saṅkhittena pañcupādānakkhandhā dukkhā.**Rebirth is suffering; old age is suffering; death is suffering; sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress are suffering; not getting what you wish for is suffering. In brief, the five grasping aggregates are suffering.*";
P_HTM[6688]="*Katamā cāvuso, jāti?**And what is rebirth?*";
P_HTM[6689]="*Yā tesaṃ tesaṃ sattānaṃ tamhi tamhi sattanikāye jāti sañjāti okkanti abhinibbatti khandhānaṃ pātubhāvo āyatanānaṃ paṭilābho,**The rebirth, inception, conception, reincarnation, manifestation of the aggregates, and acquisition of the sense fields of the various sentient beings in the various orders of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[6690]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘jāti’.**This is called rebirth.*";
P_HTM[6691]="*Katamā cāvuso, jarā?**And what is old age?*";
P_HTM[6692]="*Yā tesaṃ tesaṃ sattānaṃ tamhi tamhi sattanikāye jarā jīraṇatā khaṇḍiccaṃ pāliccaṃ valittacatā āyuno saṃhāni indriyānaṃ paripāko,**The old age, decrepitude, broken teeth, grey hair, wrinkly skin, diminished vitality, and failing faculties of the various sentient beings in the various orders of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[6693]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘jarā’.**This is called old age.*";
P_HTM[6694]="*Katamañcāvuso, maraṇaṃ?**And what is death?*";
P_HTM[6695]="*Yā tesaṃ tesaṃ sattānaṃ tamhā tamhā sattanikāyā cuti cavanatā bhedo antaradhānaṃ maccu maraṇaṃ kālaṅkiriyā khandhānaṃ bhedo kaḷevarassa nikkhepo jīvitindriyassupacchedo,**The passing away, perishing, disintegration, demise, mortality, death, decease, breaking up of the aggregates, laying to rest of the corpse, and cutting off of the life faculty of the various sentient beings in the various orders of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[6696]="*idaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘maraṇaṃ’.**This is called death.*";
P_HTM[6697]="*Katamo cāvuso, soko?**And what is sorrow?*";
P_HTM[6698]="*Yo kho, āvuso, aññataraññatarena byasanena samannāgatassa aññataraññatarena dukkhadhammena phuṭṭhassa soko socanā socitattaṃ antosoko antoparisoko,**The sorrow, sorrowing, state of sorrow, inner sorrow, inner deep sorrow in someone who has undergone misfortune, who has experienced suffering.*";
P_HTM[6699]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘soko’.**This is called sorrow.*";
P_HTM[6700]="*Katamo cāvuso, paridevo?**And what is lamentation?*";
P_HTM[6701]="*Yo kho, āvuso, aññataraññatarena byasanena samannāgatassa aññataraññatarena dukkhadhammena phuṭṭhassa ādevo paridevo ādevanā paridevanā ādevitattaṃ paridevitattaṃ,**The wail, lament, wailing, lamenting, state of wailing and lamentation in someone who has undergone misfortune, who has experienced suffering.*";
P_HTM[6702]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘paridevo’.**This is called lamentation.*";
P_HTM[6703]="*Katamañcāvuso, dukkhaṃ?**And what is pain?*";
P_HTM[6704]="*Yaṃ kho, āvuso, kāyikaṃ dukkhaṃ kāyikaṃ asātaṃ kāyasamphassajaṃ dukkhaṃ asātaṃ vedayitaṃ,**Physical pain, physical displeasure, the painful, unpleasant feeling that’s born from physical contact.*";
P_HTM[6705]="*idaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘dukkhaṃ’.**This is called pain.*";
P_HTM[6706]="*Katamañcāvuso, domanassaṃ?**And what is sadness?*";
P_HTM[6707]="*Yaṃ kho, āvuso, cetasikaṃ dukkhaṃ cetasikaṃ asātaṃ manosamphassajaṃ dukkhaṃ asātaṃ vedayitaṃ,**Mental pain, mental displeasure, the painful, unpleasant feeling that’s born from mind contact.*";
P_HTM[6708]="*idaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘domanassaṃ’.**This is called sadness.*";
P_HTM[6709]="*Katamo cāvuso, upāyāso?**And what is distress?*";
P_HTM[6710]="*Yo kho, āvuso, aññataraññatarena byasanena samannāgatassa aññataraññatarena dukkhadhammena phuṭṭhassa āyāso upāyāso āyāsitattaṃ upāyāsitattaṃ,**The stress, distress, state of stress and distress in someone who has undergone misfortune, who has experienced suffering.*";
P_HTM[6711]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘upāyāso’.**This is called distress.*";
P_HTM[6712]="*Katamañcāvuso, yampicchaṃ na labhati tampi dukkhaṃ?**And what is ‘not getting what you wish for is suffering’?*";
P_HTM[6713]="*Jātidhammānaṃ, āvuso, sattānaṃ evaṃ icchā uppajjati:**In sentient beings who are liable to be reborn, such a wish arises:*";
P_HTM[6714]="*‘aho vata mayaṃ na jātidhammā assāma; na ca vata no jāti āgaccheyyā’ti.**‘Oh, if only we were not liable to be reborn! If only rebirth would not come to us!’*";
P_HTM[6715]="*Na kho panetaṃ icchāya pattabbaṃ.**But you can’t get that by wishing.*";
P_HTM[6716]="*Idampi: ‘yampicchaṃ na labhati tampi dukkhaṃ’.**This is: ‘not getting what you wish for is suffering.’*";
P_HTM[6717]="*Jarādhammānaṃ, āvuso, sattānaṃ … pe …**In sentient beings who are liable to grow old …*";
P_HTM[6718]="*byādhidhammānaṃ, āvuso, sattānaṃ …**fall ill …*";
P_HTM[6719]="*maraṇadhammānaṃ, āvuso, sattānaṃ …**die …*";
P_HTM[6720]="*sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsadhammānaṃ, āvuso, sattānaṃ evaṃ icchā uppajjati:**experience sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress, such a wish arises:*";
P_HTM[6721]="*‘aho vata mayaṃ na sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsadhammā assāma; na ca vata no sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā āgaccheyyun’ti.**‘Oh, if only we were not liable to experience sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress! If only sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress would not come to us!’*";
P_HTM[6722]="*Na kho panetaṃ icchāya pattabbaṃ.**But you can’t get that by wishing.*";
P_HTM[6723]="*Idampi: ‘yampicchaṃ na labhati tampi dukkhaṃ’.**This is: ‘not getting what you wish for is suffering.’*";
P_HTM[6724]="*Katame cāvuso, saṅkhittena pañcupādānakkhandhā dukkhā?**And what is ‘in brief, the five grasping aggregates are suffering’?*";
P_HTM[6725]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**They are the grasping aggregates that consist of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6726]="*Ime vuccantāvuso: ‘saṅkhittena pañcupādānakkhandhā dukkhā’.**This is called ‘in brief, the five grasping aggregates are suffering.’*";
P_HTM[6727]="*Idaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ’.**This is called the noble truth of suffering.*";
P_HTM[6728]="*Katamañcāvuso, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ?**And what is the noble truth of the origin of suffering?*";
P_HTM[6729]="*Yāyaṃ taṇhā ponobbhavikā nandīrāgasahagatā tatratatrābhinandinī, seyyathidaṃ—**It’s the craving that leads to future rebirth, mixed up with relishing and greed, looking for enjoyment in various different realms. That is,*";
P_HTM[6730]="*kāmataṇhā bhavataṇhā vibhavataṇhā,**craving for sensual pleasures, craving to continue existence, and craving to end existence.*";
P_HTM[6731]="*idaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ’.**This is called the noble truth of the origin of suffering.*";
P_HTM[6732]="*Katamañcāvuso, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ?**And what is the noble truth of the cessation of suffering?*";
P_HTM[6733]="*Yo tassāyeva taṇhāya asesavirāganirodho cāgo paṭinissaggo mutti anālayo,**It’s the fading away and cessation of that very same craving with nothing left over; giving it away, letting it go, releasing it, and not adhering to it.*";
P_HTM[6734]="*idaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ’.**This is called the noble truth of the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[6735]="*Katamañcāvuso, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ?**And what is the noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering?*";
P_HTM[6736]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, seyyathidaṃ—**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[6737]="*sammādiṭṭhi, sammāsaṅkappo, sammāvācā, sammākammanto, sammāājīvo, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati, sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[6738]="*Katamā cāvuso, sammādiṭṭhi?**And what is right view?*";
P_HTM[6739]="*Yaṃ kho, āvuso, dukkhe ñāṇaṃ, dukkhasamudaye ñāṇaṃ, dukkhanirodhe ñāṇaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ñāṇaṃ,**Knowing about suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[6740]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘sammādiṭṭhi’.**This is called right view.*";
P_HTM[6741]="*Katamo cāvuso, sammāsaṅkappo?**And what is right thought?*";
P_HTM[6742]="*Nekkhammasaṅkappo, abyāpādasaṅkappo, avihiṃsāsaṅkappo,**Thoughts of renunciation, good will, and harmlessness.*";
P_HTM[6743]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘sammāsaṅkappo’.**This is called right thought.*";
P_HTM[6744]="*Katamā cāvuso, sammāvācā?**And what is right speech?*";
P_HTM[6745]="*Musāvādā veramaṇī, pisuṇāya vācāya veramaṇī, pharusāya vācāya veramaṇī, samphappalāpā veramaṇī,**Refraining from lying, divisive speech, harsh speech, and talking nonsense.*";
P_HTM[6746]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘sammāvācā’.**This is called right speech.*";
P_HTM[6747]="*Katamo cāvuso, sammākammanto?**And what is right action?*";
P_HTM[6748]="*Pāṇātipātā veramaṇī, adinnādānā veramaṇī, kāmesumicchācārā veramaṇī,**Refraining from killing living creatures, stealing, and sexual misconduct.*";
P_HTM[6749]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘sammākammanto’.**This is called right action.*";
P_HTM[6750]="*Katamo cāvuso, sammāājīvo?**And what is right livelihood?*";
P_HTM[6751]="*Idhāvuso, ariyasāvako micchāājīvaṃ pahāya sammāājīvena jīvikaṃ kappeti,**It’s when a noble disciple gives up wrong livelihood and earns a living by right livelihood.*";
P_HTM[6752]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘sammāājīvo’.**This is called right livelihood.*";
P_HTM[6753]="*Katamo cāvuso, sammāvāyāmo?**And what is right effort?*";
P_HTM[6754]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu anuppannānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ anuppādāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati,**It’s when a mendicant generates enthusiasm, tries, makes an effort, exerts the mind, and strives so that bad, unskillful qualities don’t arise.*";
P_HTM[6755]="*uppannānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati,**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that bad, unskillful qualities that have arisen are given up.*";
P_HTM[6756]="*anuppannānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ uppādāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati,**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that skillful qualities arise.*";
P_HTM[6757]="*uppannānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ ṭhitiyā asammosāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati,**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that skillful qualities that have arisen remain, are not lost, but increase, mature, and are completed by development.*";
P_HTM[6758]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘sammāvāyāmo’.**This is called right effort.*";
P_HTM[6759]="*Katamā cāvuso, sammāsati?**And what is right mindfulness?*";
P_HTM[6760]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[6761]="*Vedanāsu vedanānupassī viharati … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[6762]="*citte cittānupassī viharati …**mind …*";
P_HTM[6763]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ,**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[6764]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘sammāsati’.**This is called right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[6765]="*Katamo cāvuso, sammāsamādhi?**And what is right immersion?*";
P_HTM[6766]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati,**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[6767]="*vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati,**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[6768]="*pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati … pe … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ … pe …**And with the fading away of rapture, they enter and remain in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[6769]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati,**Giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[6770]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘sammāsamādhi’.**This is called right immersion.*";
P_HTM[6771]="*Idaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ’.**This is called the noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[6772]="*Tathāgatenāvuso, arahatā sammāsambuddhena bārāṇasiyaṃ isipatane migadāye anuttaraṃ dhammacakkaṃ pavattitaṃ appaṭivattiyaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ, yadidaṃ—**Near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana, the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha rolled forth the supreme Wheel of Dhamma. And that wheel cannot be rolled back by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[6773]="*imesaṃ catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ ācikkhanā desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkamman”ti.**It is the teaching, advocating, establishing, clarifying, analyzing, and revealing of the four noble truths.”*";
P_HTM[6774]="*Idamavoca āyasmā sāriputto.**That’s what Venerable Sāriputta said.*";
P_HTM[6775]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what Sāriputta said.*";
P_HTM[6776]="*Saccavibhaṅgasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6777]="*142. Dakkhiṇāvibhaṅgasutta**The Analysis of Religious Donations*";
P_HTM[6778]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[6779]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati kapilavatthusmiṃ nigrodhārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans, near Kapilavatthu in the Banyan Tree Monastery.*";
P_HTM[6780]="*Atha kho mahāpajāpati gotamī navaṃ dussayugaṃ ādāya yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho mahāpajāpati gotamī bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Mahāpajāpati Gotamī approached the Buddha bringing a new pair of garments. She bowed, sat down to one side, and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[6781]="*“idaṃ me, bhante, navaṃ dussayugaṃ bhagavantaṃ uddissa sāmaṃ kantaṃ sāmaṃ vāyitaṃ.**“Sir, I have spun and woven this new pair of garments specially for the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[6782]="*Taṃ me, bhante, bhagavā paṭiggaṇhātu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**May the Buddha please accept this from me out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[6783]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhagavā mahāpajāpatiṃ gotamiṃ etadavoca:**When she said this, the Buddha said to her,*";
P_HTM[6784]="*“saṃghe, gotami, dehi.**“Give it to the Saṅgha, Gotamī.*";
P_HTM[6785]="*Saṃghe te dinne ahañceva pūjito bhavissāmi saṃgho cā”ti.**When you give to the Saṅgha, both the Saṅgha and I will be honored.”*";
P_HTM[6786]="*Dutiyampi kho mahāpajāpati gotamī bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**For a second time …*";
P_HTM[6787]="*“idaṃ me, bhante, navaṃ dussayugaṃ bhagavantaṃ uddissa sāmaṃ kantaṃ sāmaṃ vāyitaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6788]="*Taṃ me, bhante, bhagavā paṭiggaṇhātu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6789]="*Dutiyampi kho bhagavā mahāpajāpatiṃ gotamiṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[6790]="*“saṅghe, gotami, dehi.* **";
P_HTM[6791]="*Saṅghe te dinne ahañceva pūjito bhavissāmi saṅgho cā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6792]="*Tatiyampi kho mahāpajāpati gotamī bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**For a third time, Mahāpajāpatī Gotamī said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[6793]="*“idaṃ me, bhante, navaṃ dussayugaṃ bhagavantaṃ uddissa sāmaṃ kantaṃ sāmaṃ vāyitaṃ.**“Sir, I have spun and woven this new pair of garments specially for the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[6794]="*Taṃ me, bhante, bhagavā paṭiggaṇhātu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**May the Buddha please accept this from me out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[6795]="*Tatiyampi kho bhagavā mahāpajāpatiṃ gotamiṃ etadavoca:**And for a third time, the Buddha said to her,*";
P_HTM[6796]="*“saṅghe, gotami, dehi.**“Give it to the Saṅgha, Gotamī.*";
P_HTM[6797]="*Saṅghe te dinne ahañceva pūjito bhavissāmi saṅgho cā”ti.**When you give to the Saṅgha, both the Saṅgha and I will be honored.”*";
P_HTM[6798]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Ānanda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[6799]="*“paṭiggaṇhātu, bhante, bhagavā mahāpajāpatiyā gotamiyā navaṃ dussayugaṃ.**“Sir, please accept the new pair of garments from Mahāpajāpatī Gotamī.*";
P_HTM[6800]="*Bahūpakārā, bhante, mahāpajāpati gotamī bhagavato mātucchā āpādikā posikā khīrassa dāyikā;**Sir, Mahāpajāpatī was very helpful to the Buddha. As his aunt, she raised him, nurtured him, and gave him her milk.*";
P_HTM[6801]="*bhagavantaṃ janettiyā kālaṅkatāya thaññaṃ pāyesi.**When the Buddha’s birth mother passed away, she nurtured him at her own breast.*";
P_HTM[6802]="*Bhagavāpi, bhante, bahūpakāro mahāpajāpatiyā gotamiyā.**And the Buddha has been very helpful to Mahāpajāpatī.*";
P_HTM[6803]="*Bhagavantaṃ, bhante, āgamma mahāpajāpati gotamī buddhaṃ saraṇaṃ gatā, dhammaṃ saraṇaṃ gatā, saṃghaṃ saraṇaṃ gatā.**It is owing to the Buddha that Mahāpajāpatī has gone for refuge to the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6804]="*Bhagavantaṃ, bhante, āgamma mahāpajāpati gotamī pāṇātipātā paṭiviratā adinnādānā paṭiviratā kāmesumicchācārā paṭiviratā musāvādā paṭiviratā surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhānā paṭiviratā.**It’s owing to the Buddha that she refrains from killing living creatures, stealing, committing sexual misconduct, lying, and taking alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.*";
P_HTM[6805]="*Bhagavantaṃ, bhante, āgamma mahāpajāpati gotamī buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgatā, dhamme aveccappasādena samannāgatā, saṃghe aveccappasādena samannāgatā ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgatā.**It’s owing to the Buddha that she has experiential confidence in the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, and has the ethics loved by the noble ones.*";
P_HTM[6806]="*Bhagavantaṃ, bhante, āgamma mahāpajāpati gotamī dukkhe nikkaṅkhā, dukkhasamudaye nikkaṅkhā, dukkhanirodhe nikkaṅkhā, dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya nikkaṅkhā.**It’s owing to the Buddha that she is free of doubt regarding suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[6807]="*Bhagavāpi, bhante, bahūpakāro mahāpajāpatiyā gotamiyā”ti.**The Buddha has been very helpful to Mahāpajāpatī.”*";
P_HTM[6808]="*“Evametaṃ, ānanda.**“That’s so true, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[6809]="*Yaṃ hānanda, puggalo puggalaṃ āgamma buddhaṃ saraṇaṃ gato hoti, dhammaṃ saraṇaṃ gato hoti, saṅghaṃ saraṇaṃ gato hoti, imassānanda, puggalassa iminā puggalena na suppatikāraṃ vadāmi, yadidaṃ—**When someone has enabled you to go for refuge, it’s not easy to repay them*";
P_HTM[6810]="*abhivādanapaccuṭṭhānaañjalikammasāmīcikammacīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārānuppadānena.**by bowing down to them, rising up for them, greeting them with joined palms, and observing proper etiquette for them; or by providing them with robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick.*";
P_HTM[6811]="*Yaṃ hānanda, puggalo puggalaṃ āgamma pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti, adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti, kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato hoti, musāvādā paṭivirato hoti, surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhānā paṭivirato hoti, imassānanda, puggalassa iminā puggalena na suppatikāraṃ vadāmi, yadidaṃ—**When someone has enabled you to refrain from killing, stealing, sexual misconduct, lying, and alcoholic drinks that cause negligence, it’s not easy to repay them …*";
P_HTM[6812]="*abhivādanapaccuṭṭhānaañjalikammasāmīcikammacīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārānuppadānena.* **";
P_HTM[6813]="*Yaṃ hānanda, puggalo puggalaṃ āgamma buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti, dhamme … saṅghe … ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti, imassānanda, puggalassa iminā puggalena na suppatikāraṃ vadāmi, yadidaṃ—**When someone has enabled you to have experiential confidence in the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, and the ethics loved by the noble ones, it’s not easy to repay them …*";
P_HTM[6814]="*abhivādanapaccuṭṭhānaañjalikammasāmīcikammacīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārānuppadānena.* **";
P_HTM[6815]="*Yaṃ hānanda, puggalo puggalaṃ āgamma dukkhe nikkaṅkho hoti, dukkhasamudaye nikkaṅkho hoti, dukkhanirodhe nikkaṅkho hoti, dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya nikkaṅkho hoti, imassānanda, puggalassa iminā puggalena na suppatikāraṃ vadāmi, yadidaṃ—**When someone has enabled you to be free of doubt regarding suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation, it’s not easy to repay them*";
P_HTM[6816]="*abhivādanapaccuṭṭhānaañjalikammasāmīcikammacīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārānuppadānena.**by bowing down to them, rising up for them, greeting them with joined palms, and observing proper etiquette for them; or by providing them with robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick.*";
P_HTM[6817]="*Cuddasa kho panimānanda, pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**Ānanda, there are these fourteen religious donations to individuals.*";
P_HTM[6818]="*Katamā cuddasa?**What fourteen?*";
P_HTM[6819]="*Tathāgate arahante sammāsambuddhe dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[6820]="*ayaṃ paṭhamā pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the first religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6821]="*Paccekasambuddhe dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to a Buddha awakened for themselves.*";
P_HTM[6822]="*ayaṃ dutiyā pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the second religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6823]="*Tathāgatasāvake arahante dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to a perfected one.*";
P_HTM[6824]="*ayaṃ tatiyā pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the third religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6825]="*Arahattaphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanne dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to a someone practicing to realize the fruit of perfection.*";
P_HTM[6826]="*ayaṃ catutthī pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the fourth religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6827]="*Anāgāmissa dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to a non-returner.*";
P_HTM[6828]="*ayaṃ pañcamī pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the fifth religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6829]="*Anāgāmiphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanne dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to someone practicing to realize the fruit of non-return.*";
P_HTM[6830]="*ayaṃ chaṭṭhī pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the sixth religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6831]="*Sakadāgāmissa dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to a once-returner.*";
P_HTM[6832]="*ayaṃ sattamī pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the seventh religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6833]="*Sakadāgāmiphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanne dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to someone practicing to realize the fruit of once-return.*";
P_HTM[6834]="*ayaṃ aṭṭhamī pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the eighth religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6835]="*Sotāpanne dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to a stream-enterer.*";
P_HTM[6836]="*ayaṃ navamī pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the ninth religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6837]="*Sotāpattiphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanne dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to someone practicing to realize the fruit of stream-entry.*";
P_HTM[6838]="*ayaṃ dasamī pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the tenth religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6839]="*Bāhirake kāmesu vītarāge dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to someone outside of Buddhism who is free of sensual desire.*";
P_HTM[6840]="*ayaṃ ekādasamī pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the eleventh religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6841]="*Puthujjanasīlavante dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to an ordinary person who has good ethical conduct.*";
P_HTM[6842]="*ayaṃ dvādasamī pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the twelfth religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6843]="*Puthujjanadussīle dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to an ordinary person who has bad ethical conduct.*";
P_HTM[6844]="*ayaṃ terasamī pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇā.**This is the thirteenth religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6845]="*Tiracchānagate dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to an animal.*";
P_HTM[6846]="*ayaṃ cuddasamī pāṭipuggalikā dakkhiṇāti.**This is the fourteenth religious donation to an individual.*";
P_HTM[6847]="*Tatrānanda, tiracchānagate dānaṃ datvā sataguṇā dakkhiṇā pāṭikaṅkhitabbā, puthujjanadussīle dānaṃ datvā sahassaguṇā dakkhiṇā pāṭikaṅkhitabbā, puthujjanasīlavante dānaṃ datvā satasahassaguṇā dakkhiṇā pāṭikaṅkhitabbā, bāhirake kāmesu vītarāge dānaṃ datvā koṭisatasahassaguṇā dakkhiṇā pāṭikaṅkhitabbā, sotāpattiphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanne dānaṃ datvā asaṅkheyyā appameyyā dakkhiṇā pāṭikaṅkhitabbā, ko pana vādo sotāpanne, ko pana vādo sakadāgāmiphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanne, ko pana vādo sakadāgāmissa, ko pana vādo anāgāmiphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanne, ko pana vādo anāgāmissa, ko pana vādo arahattaphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanne, ko pana vādo arahante, ko pana vādo paccekasambuddhe, ko pana vādo tathāgate arahante sammāsambuddhe.**Now, Ānanda, gifts to the following persons may be expected to yield the following returns. To an animal, a hundred times. To an unethical ordinary person, a thousand. To an ethical ordinary person, a hundred thousand. To an outsider free of sensual desire, 10,000,000,000. But a gift to someone practicing to realize the fruit of stream-entry may be expected to yield incalculable, immeasurable returns. How much more so a gift to a stream-enterer, someone practicing to realize the fruit of once-return, a once-returner, someone practicing to realize the fruit of non-return, a non-returner, someone practicing to realize the fruit of perfection, a perfected one, or a Buddha awakened for themselves? How much more so a Realized One, a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha?*";
P_HTM[6848]="*Satta kho panimānanda, saṅghagatā dakkhiṇā.**But there are, Ānanda, seven religious donations bestowed on a Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6849]="*Katamā satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[6850]="*Buddhappamukhe ubhatosaṅghe dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to the communities of both monks and nuns headed by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[6851]="*ayaṃ paṭhamā saṅghagatā dakkhiṇā.**This is the first religious donation bestowed on a Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6852]="*Tathāgate parinibbute ubhatosaṅghe dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to the communities of both monks and nuns after the Buddha has finally become extinguished.*";
P_HTM[6853]="*ayaṃ dutiyā saṅghagatā dakkhiṇā.**This is the second religious donation bestowed on a Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6854]="*Bhikkhusaṅghe dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to the Saṅgha of monks.*";
P_HTM[6855]="*ayaṃ tatiyā saṅghagatā dakkhiṇā.**This is the third religious donation bestowed on a Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6856]="*Bhikkhunisaṅghe dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift to the Saṅgha of nuns.*";
P_HTM[6857]="*ayaṃ catutthī saṅghagatā dakkhiṇā.**This is the fourth religious donation bestowed on a Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6858]="*‘Ettakā me bhikkhū ca bhikkhuniyo ca saṅghato uddissathā’ti dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift, thinking: ‘Appoint this many monks and nuns for me from the Saṅgha.’*";
P_HTM[6859]="*ayaṃ pañcamī saṅghagatā dakkhiṇā.**This is the fifth religious donation bestowed on a Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6860]="*‘Ettakā me bhikkhū saṅghato uddissathā’ti dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift, thinking: ‘Appoint this many monks for me from the Saṅgha.’*";
P_HTM[6861]="*ayaṃ chaṭṭhī saṅghagatā dakkhiṇā.**This is the sixth religious donation bestowed on a Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6862]="*‘Ettakā me bhikkhuniyo saṅghato uddissathā’ti dānaṃ deti—**One gives a gift, thinking: ‘Appoint this many nuns for me from the Saṅgha.’*";
P_HTM[6863]="*ayaṃ sattamī saṅghagatā dakkhiṇā.**This is the seventh religious donation bestowed on a Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6864]="*Bhavissanti kho panānanda, anāgatamaddhānaṃ gotrabhuno kāsāvakaṇṭhā dussīlā pāpadhammā.**In times to come there will be members of the spiritual family merely by virtue of wearing ocher cloth around their necks; but they are unethical and of bad character.*";
P_HTM[6865]="*Tesu dussīlesu saṅghaṃ uddissa dānaṃ dassanti.**People will give gifts to those unethical people in the name of the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6866]="*Tadāpāhaṃ, ānanda, saṅghagataṃ dakkhiṇaṃ asaṅkheyyaṃ appameyyaṃ vadāmi.**Even then, I say, a religious donation bestowed on the Saṅgha is incalculable and immeasurable.*";
P_HTM[6867]="*Na tvevāhaṃ, ānanda, kenaci pariyāyena saṅghagatāya dakkhiṇāya pāṭipuggalikaṃ dānaṃ mahapphalataraṃ vadāmi.**But I say that there is no way a personal offering can be more fruitful than one bestowed on a Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6868]="*Catasso kho imā, ānanda, dakkhiṇā visuddhiyo.**Ānanda, there are these four ways of purifying a religious donation.*";
P_HTM[6869]="*Katamā catasso?**What four?*";
P_HTM[6870]="*Atthānanda, dakkhiṇā dāyakato visujjhati no paṭiggāhakato.**There’s a religious donation that’s purified by the giver, not the recipient.*";
P_HTM[6871]="*Atthānanda, dakkhiṇā paṭiggāhakato visujjhati no dāyakato.**There’s a religious donation that’s purified by the recipient, not the giver.*";
P_HTM[6872]="*Atthānanda, dakkhiṇā neva dāyakato visujjhati no paṭiggāhakato.**There’s a religious donation that’s purified by neither the giver nor the recipient.*";
P_HTM[6873]="*Atthānanda, dakkhiṇā dāyakato ceva visujjhati paṭiggāhakato ca.**There’s a religious donation that’s purified by both the giver and the recipient.*";
P_HTM[6874]="*Kathañcānanda, dakkhiṇā dāyakato visujjhati no paṭiggāhakato?**And how is a religious donation purified by the giver, not the recipient?*";
P_HTM[6875]="*Idhānanda, dāyako hoti sīlavā kalyāṇadhammo, paṭiggāhakā honti dussīlā pāpadhammā—**It’s when the giver is ethical, of good character, but the recipient is unethical, of bad character.*";
P_HTM[6876]="*evaṃ kho, ānanda, dakkhiṇā dāyakato visujjhati no paṭiggāhakato.* **";
P_HTM[6877]="*Kathañcānanda, dakkhiṇā paṭiggāhakato visujjhati no dāyakato?**And how is a religious donation purified by the recipient, not the giver?*";
P_HTM[6878]="*Idhānanda, dāyako hoti dussīlo pāpadhammo, paṭiggāhakā honti sīlavanto kalyāṇadhammā—**It’s when the giver is unethical, of bad character, but the recipient is ethical, of good character.*";
P_HTM[6879]="*evaṃ kho, ānanda, dakkhiṇā paṭiggāhakato visujjhati no dāyakato.* **";
P_HTM[6880]="*Kathañcānanda, dakkhiṇā neva dāyakato visujjhati no paṭiggāhakato?**And how is a religious donation purified by neither the giver nor the recipient?*";
P_HTM[6881]="*Idhānanda, dāyako ca hoti dussīlo pāpadhammo, paṭiggāhakā ca honti dussīlā pāpadhammā—**It’s when both the giver and the recipient are unethical, of bad character.*";
P_HTM[6882]="*evaṃ kho, ānanda, dakkhiṇā neva dāyakato visujjhati no paṭiggāhakato.* **";
P_HTM[6883]="*Kathañcānanda, dakkhiṇā dāyakato ceva visujjhati paṭiggāhakato ca?**And how is a religious donation purified by both the giver and the recipient?*";
P_HTM[6884]="*Idhānanda, dāyako ca hoti sīlavā kalyāṇadhammo, paṭiggāhakā ca honti sīlavanto kalyāṇadhammā—**It’s when both the giver and the recipient are ethical, of good character.*";
P_HTM[6885]="*evaṃ kho, ānanda, dakkhiṇā dāyakato ceva visujjhati paṭiggāhakato ca.* **";
P_HTM[6886]="*Imā kho, ānanda, catasso dakkhiṇā visuddhiyo”ti.**These are the four ways of purifying a religious donation.”*";
P_HTM[6887]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[6888]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[6889]="*“Yo sīlavā dussīlesu dadāti dānaṃ,**“When an ethical person with trusting heart*";
P_HTM[6890]="*Dhammena laddhaṃ supasannacitto;**gives a proper gift to unethical persons,*";
P_HTM[6891]="*Abhisaddahaṃ kammaphalaṃ uḷāraṃ,**trusting in the ample fruit of deeds,*";
P_HTM[6892]="*Sā dakkhiṇā dāyakato visujjhati.**that offering is purified by the giver.*";
P_HTM[6893]="*Yo dussīlo sīlavantesu dadāti dānaṃ,**When an unethical and untrusting person,*";
P_HTM[6894]="*Adhammena laddhaṃ appasannacitto;**gives an improper gift to ethical persons,*";
P_HTM[6895]="*Anabhisaddahaṃ kammaphalaṃ uḷāraṃ,**not trusting in the ample fruit of deeds,*";
P_HTM[6896]="*Sā dakkhiṇā paṭiggāhakato visujjhati.**that offering is purified by the receivers.*";
P_HTM[6897]="*Yo dussīlo dussīlesu dadāti dānaṃ,**When an unethical and untrusting person,*";
P_HTM[6898]="*Adhammena laddhaṃ appasannacitto;**gives an improper gift to unethical persons,*";
P_HTM[6899]="*Anabhisaddahaṃ kammaphalaṃ uḷāraṃ,**not trusting in the ample fruit of deeds,*";
P_HTM[6900]="*Na taṃ dānaṃ vipulapphalanti brūmi.**I declare that gift is not very fruitful.*";
P_HTM[6901]="*Yo sīlavā sīlavantesu dadāti dānaṃ,**When an ethical person with trusting heart*";
P_HTM[6902]="*Dhammena laddhaṃ supasannacitto;**gives a proper gift to ethical persons,*";
P_HTM[6903]="*Abhisaddahaṃ kammaphalaṃ uḷāraṃ,**trusting in the ample fruit of deeds,*";
P_HTM[6904]="*Taṃ ve dānaṃ vipulapphalanti brūmi.**I declare that gift is abundantly fruitful.*";
P_HTM[6905]="*Yo vītarāgo vītarāgesu dadāti dānaṃ,**But when a passionless one gives to the passionless*";
P_HTM[6906]="*Dhammena laddhaṃ supasannacitto;**a proper gift with trusting heart,*";
P_HTM[6907]="*Abhisaddahaṃ kammaphalaṃ uḷāraṃ,**trusting in the ample fruit of deeds,*";
P_HTM[6908]="*Taṃ ve dānaṃ āmisadānānamaggan”ti.**that’s truly the best of material gifts.”*";
P_HTM[6909]="*Dakkhiṇāvibhaṅgasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dvādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6910]="*Vibhaṅgavaggo niṭṭhito catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[6911]="*Bhaddekānandakaccāna,* **";
P_HTM[6912]="*Lomasakaṅgiyāsubho;* **";
P_HTM[6913]="*Mahākammasaḷāyatanavibhaṅgā,* **";
P_HTM[6914]="*Uddesaaraṇā dhātu saccaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6915]="*Dakkhiṇāvibhaṅgasuttanti.* **";
P_HTM[6916]="*143. Anāthapiṇḍikovādasutta**Advice to Anāthapiṇḍika*";
P_HTM[6917]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[6918]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[6919]="*Tena kho pana samayena anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati ābādhiko hoti dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time the householder Anāthapiṇḍika was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[6920]="*Atha kho anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati aññataraṃ purisaṃ āmantesi:**Then he addressed a man,*";
P_HTM[6921]="*“ehi tvaṃ, ambho purisa, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā mama vacanena bhagavato pāde sirasā vandāhi:**“Please, mister, go to the Buddha, and in my name bow with your head to his feet. Say to him:*";
P_HTM[6922]="*‘anāthapiṇḍiko, bhante, gahapati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**‘Sir, the householder Anāthapiṇḍika is sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[6923]="*So bhagavato pāde sirasā vandatī’ti.**He bows with his head to your feet.’*";
P_HTM[6924]="*Yena cāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā mama vacanena āyasmato sāriputtassa pāde sirasā vandāhi:**Then go to Venerable Sāriputta, and in my name bow with your head to his feet. Say to him:*";
P_HTM[6925]="*‘anāthapiṇḍiko, bhante, gahapati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**‘Sir, the householder Anāthapiṇḍika is sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[6926]="*So āyasmato sāriputtassa pāde sirasā vandatī’ti.**He bows with his head to your feet.’*";
P_HTM[6927]="*Evañca vadehi:**And then say:*";
P_HTM[6928]="*‘sādhu kira, bhante, āyasmā sāriputto yena anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.**‘Sir, please visit him at his home out of compassion.’”*";
P_HTM[6929]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho so puriso anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa paṭissutvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so puriso bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” that man replied. He did as Anāthapiṇḍika asked.*";
P_HTM[6930]="*“anāthapiṇḍiko, bhante, gahapati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.* **";
P_HTM[6931]="*So bhagavato pāde sirasā vandatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6932]="*Yena cāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so puriso āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[6933]="*“anāthapiṇḍiko, bhante, gahapati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.* **";
P_HTM[6934]="*So āyasmato sāriputtassa pāde sirasā vandati;* **";
P_HTM[6935]="*evañca vadeti:* **";
P_HTM[6936]="*‘sādhu kira, bhante, āyasmā sāriputto yena anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6937]="*Adhivāsesi kho āyasmā sāriputto tuṇhībhāvena.**Sāriputta consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[6938]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya āyasmatā ānandena pacchāsamaṇena yena anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi. Nisajja kho āyasmā sāriputto anāthapiṇḍikaṃ gahapatiṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Sāriputta robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went with Venerable Ānanda as his second monk to Anāthapiṇḍika’s home. He sat down on the seat spread out, and said to Anāthapiṇḍika,*";
P_HTM[6939]="*“kacci te, gahapati, khamanīyaṃ, kacci yāpanīyaṃ? Kacci te dukkhā vedanā paṭikkamanti, no abhikkamanti; paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no abhikkamo”ti?**“Householder, I hope you’re keeping well; I hope you’re alright. And I hope the pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.”*";
P_HTM[6940]="*“Na me, bhante sāriputta, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo.**“I’m not keeping well, Master Sāriputta, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading, its growing, not its fading, is evident.*";
P_HTM[6941]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante sāriputta, balavā puriso tiṇhena sikharena muddhani abhimattheyya; evameva kho me, bhante sāriputta, adhimattā vātā muddhani ūhananti.**The winds piercing my head are so severe, it feels like a strong man drilling into my head with a sharp point.*";
P_HTM[6942]="*Na me, bhante sāriputta, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo.* **";
P_HTM[6943]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante sāriputta, balavā puriso daḷhena varattakhaṇḍena sīse sīsaveṭhaṃ dadeyya; evameva kho me, bhante sāriputta, adhimattā sīse sīsavedanā.**The pain in my head is so severe, it feels like a strong man tightening a tough leather strap around my head.*";
P_HTM[6944]="*Na me, bhante sāriputta, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo.* **";
P_HTM[6945]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante sāriputta, dakkho goghātako vā goghātakantevāsī vā tiṇhena govikantanena kucchiṃ parikanteyya; evameva kho me, bhante sāriputta, adhimattā vātā kucchiṃ parikantanti.**The winds piercing my belly are so severe, it feels like a deft butcher or their apprentice is slicing my belly open with a meat cleaver.*";
P_HTM[6946]="*Na me, bhante sāriputta, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo.* **";
P_HTM[6947]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante sāriputta, dve balavanto purisā dubbalataraṃ purisaṃ nānābāhāsu gahetvā aṅgārakāsuyā santāpeyyuṃ, samparitāpeyyuṃ; evameva kho me, bhante sāriputta, adhimatto kāyasmiṃ ḍāho.**The burning in my body is so severe, it feels like two strong men grabbing a weaker man by the arms to burn and scorch him on a pit of glowing coals. That’s how severe the burning is in my body.*";
P_HTM[6948]="*Na me, bhante sāriputta, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo”ti.**I’m not keeping well, Master Sāriputta, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading, its growing, not its fading, is evident.”*";
P_HTM[6949]="*“Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**“That’s why, householder, you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[6950]="*‘na cakkhuṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me cakkhunissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp the eye, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on the eye.’*";
P_HTM[6951]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[6952]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**You should train like this:*";
P_HTM[6953]="*‘na sotaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me sotanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp the ear, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on the ear.’ …*";
P_HTM[6954]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6955]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[6956]="*‘na ghānaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me ghānanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp the nose, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on the nose.’ …*";
P_HTM[6957]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6958]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[6959]="*‘na jivhaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me jivhānissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp the tongue, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on the tongue.’ …*";
P_HTM[6960]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6961]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[6962]="*‘na kāyaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me kāyanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp the body, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on the body.’ …*";
P_HTM[6963]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6964]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[6965]="*‘na manaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me manonissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp the mind, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on the mind.’*";
P_HTM[6966]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ. (1)**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[6967]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**You should train like this:*";
P_HTM[6968]="*‘na rūpaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me rūpanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp sight, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on sight.’ …*";
P_HTM[6969]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6970]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[6971]="*‘na saddaṃ upādiyissāmi … pe …**‘I shall not grasp sound …*";
P_HTM[6972]="*na gandhaṃ upādiyissāmi …**smell …*";
P_HTM[6973]="*na rasaṃ upādiyissāmi …**taste …*";
P_HTM[6974]="*na phoṭṭhabbaṃ upādiyissāmi …**touch …*";
P_HTM[6975]="*na dhammaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me dhammanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**thought, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on thought.’*";
P_HTM[6976]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ. (2)**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[6977]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**You should train like this:*";
P_HTM[6978]="*‘na cakkhuviññāṇaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me cakkhuviññāṇanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp eye consciousness, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on eye consciousness.’ …*";
P_HTM[6979]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6980]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[6981]="*‘na sotaviññāṇaṃ upādiyissāmi …**‘I shall not grasp ear consciousness …*";
P_HTM[6982]="*na ghānaviññāṇaṃ upādiyissāmi …**nose consciousness …*";
P_HTM[6983]="*na jivhāviññāṇaṃ upādiyissāmi …**tongue consciousness …*";
P_HTM[6984]="*na kāyaviññāṇaṃ upādiyissāmi …**body consciousness …*";
P_HTM[6985]="*na manoviññāṇaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me manoviññāṇanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**mind consciousness, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on mind consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[6986]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ. (3)**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[6987]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**You should train like this:*";
P_HTM[6988]="*‘na cakkhusamphassaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me cakkhusamphassanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp eye contact …*";
P_HTM[6989]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6990]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[6991]="*‘na sotasamphassaṃ upādiyissāmi …**ear contact …*";
P_HTM[6992]="*na ghānasamphassaṃ upādiyissāmi …**nose contact …*";
P_HTM[6993]="*na jivhāsamphassaṃ upādiyissāmi …**tongue contact …*";
P_HTM[6994]="*na kāyasamphassaṃ upādiyissāmi …**body contact …*";
P_HTM[6995]="*na manosamphassaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me manosamphassanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**mind contact, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on mind contact.’*";
P_HTM[6996]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ. (4)**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[6997]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**You should train like this:*";
P_HTM[6998]="*‘na cakkhusamphassajaṃ vedanaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me cakkhusamphassajāvedanānissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp feeling born of eye contact …*";
P_HTM[6999]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7000]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7001]="*‘na sotasamphassajaṃ vedanaṃ upādiyissāmi …**feeling born of ear contact …*";
P_HTM[7002]="*na ghānasamphassajaṃ vedanaṃ upādiyissāmi …**feeling born of nose contact …*";
P_HTM[7003]="*na jivhāsamphassajaṃ vedanaṃ upādiyissāmi …**feeling born of tongue contact …*";
P_HTM[7004]="*na kāyasamphassajaṃ vedanaṃ upādiyissāmi …**feeling born of body contact …*";
P_HTM[7005]="*na manosamphassajaṃ vedanaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me manosamphassajāvedanānissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**feeling born of mind contact, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on the feeling born of mind contact.’*";
P_HTM[7006]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ. (5)**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[7007]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**You should train like this:*";
P_HTM[7008]="*‘na pathavīdhātuṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me pathavīdhātunissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp the earth element …*";
P_HTM[7009]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7010]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7011]="*‘na āpodhātuṃ upādiyissāmi …**water element …*";
P_HTM[7012]="*na tejodhātuṃ upādiyissāmi …**fire element …*";
P_HTM[7013]="*na vāyodhātuṃ upādiyissāmi …**air element …*";
P_HTM[7014]="*na ākāsadhātuṃ upādiyissāmi …**space element …*";
P_HTM[7015]="*na viññāṇadhātuṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me viññāṇadhātunissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**consciousness element, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on the consciousness element.’*";
P_HTM[7016]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ. (6)**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[7017]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**You should train like this:*";
P_HTM[7018]="*‘na rūpaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me rūpanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp form …*";
P_HTM[7019]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7020]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7021]="*‘na vedanaṃ upādiyissāmi …**feeling …*";
P_HTM[7022]="*na saññaṃ upādiyissāmi …**perception …*";
P_HTM[7023]="*na saṅkhāre upādiyissāmi …**choices …*";
P_HTM[7024]="*na viññāṇaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me viññāṇanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**consciousness, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[7025]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ. (7)**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[7026]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**You should train like this:*";
P_HTM[7027]="*‘na ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me ākāsānañcāyatananissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp the dimension of infinite space …*";
P_HTM[7028]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7029]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7030]="*‘na viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upādiyissāmi …**the dimension of infinite consciousness …*";
P_HTM[7031]="*na ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upādiyissāmi …**the dimension of nothingness …*";
P_HTM[7032]="*na nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me nevasaññānāsaññāyatananissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.’*";
P_HTM[7033]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ. (8)**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[7034]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**You should train like this:*";
P_HTM[7035]="*‘na idhalokaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me idhalokanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp this world, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on this world.’*";
P_HTM[7036]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[7037]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**You should train like this:*";
P_HTM[7038]="*‘na paralokaṃ upādiyissāmi, na ca me paralokanissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp the other world, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on the other world.’*";
P_HTM[7039]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabbaṃ.**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[7040]="*Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**You should train like this:*";
P_HTM[7041]="*‘yampi me diṭṭhaṃ sutaṃ mutaṃ viññātaṃ pattaṃ pariyesitaṃ anupariyesitaṃ anucaritaṃ manasā tampi na upādiyissāmi, na ca me tannissitaṃ viññāṇaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘I shall not grasp whatever is seen, heard, thought, known, sought, and explored by my mind, and there shall be no consciousness of mine dependent on that.’*";
P_HTM[7042]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabban”ti. (9)**That’s how you should train.”*";
P_HTM[7043]="*Evaṃ vutte, anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati parodi, assūni pavattesi.**When he said this, Anāthapiṇḍika cried and burst out in tears.*";
P_HTM[7044]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando anāthapiṇḍikaṃ gahapatiṃ etadavoca:**Venerable Ānanda said to him,*";
P_HTM[7045]="*“olīyasi kho tvaṃ, gahapati, saṃsīdasi kho tvaṃ, gahapatī”ti?**“Are you failing, householder? Are you fading, householder?”*";
P_HTM[7046]="*“Nāhaṃ, bhante ānanda, olīyāmi, napi saṃsīdāmi;**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[7047]="*api ca me dīgharattaṃ satthā payirupāsito manobhāvanīyā ca bhikkhū;**But for a long time I have paid homage to the Buddha and the esteemed mendicants.*";
P_HTM[7048]="*na ca me evarūpī dhammī kathā sutapubbā”ti.**Yet I have never before heard such a Dhamma talk.”*";
P_HTM[7049]="*“Na kho, gahapati, gihīnaṃ odātavasanānaṃ evarūpī dhammī kathā paṭibhāti;**“Householder, it does not occur to us to teach such a Dhamma talk to white-clothed laypeople.*";
P_HTM[7050]="*pabbajitānaṃ kho, gahapati, evarūpī dhammī kathā paṭibhātī”ti.**Rather, we teach like this to those gone forth.”*";
P_HTM[7051]="*“Tena hi, bhante sāriputta, gihīnampi odātavasanānaṃ evarūpī dhammī kathā paṭibhātu.**“Well then, Master Sāriputta, let it occur to you to teach such a Dhamma talk to white-clothed laypeople as well!*";
P_HTM[7052]="*Santi hi, bhante, kulaputtā apparajakkhajātikā, assavanatā dhammassa parihāyanti;**There are gentlemen with little dust in their eyes. They’re in decline because they haven’t heard the teaching.*";
P_HTM[7053]="*bhavissanti dhammassa aññātāro”ti.**There will be those who understand the teaching!”*";
P_HTM[7054]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca ānando anāthapiṇḍikaṃ gahapatiṃ iminā ovādena ovaditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃsu.**And when the venerables Sāriputta and Ānanda had given the householder Anāthapiṇḍika this advice they got up from their seat and left.*";
P_HTM[7055]="*Atha kho anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati, acirapakkante āyasmante ca sāriputte āyasmante ca ānande, kālamakāsi tusitaṃ kāyaṃ upapajji.**Not long after they had left, Anāthapiṇḍika passed away and was reborn in the host of Joyful Gods.*";
P_HTM[7056]="*Atha kho anāthapiṇḍiko devaputto abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇo kevalakappaṃ jetavanaṃ obhāsetvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi.**Then, late at night, the glorious god Anāthapiṇḍika, lighting up the entire Jeta’s Grove, went up to the Buddha, bowed, stood to one side,*";
P_HTM[7057]="*Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho anāthapiṇḍiko devaputto bhagavantaṃ gāthāhi ajjhabhāsi:**and addressed the Buddha in verse:*";
P_HTM[7058]="*“Idañhi taṃ jetavanaṃ,**“This is indeed that Jeta’s Grove,*";
P_HTM[7059]="*isisaṅghanisevitaṃ;**frequented by the Saṅgha of hermits,*";
P_HTM[7060]="*Āvutthaṃ dhammarājena,**where the King of Dhamma stayed:*";
P_HTM[7061]="*pītisañjananaṃ mama.**it brings me joy!*";
P_HTM[7062]="*Kammaṃ vijjā ca dhammo ca,**Deeds, knowledge, and principle;*";
P_HTM[7063]="*sīlaṃ jīvitamuttamaṃ;**ethical conduct, an excellent livelihood;*";
P_HTM[7064]="*Etena maccā sujjhanti,**by these are mortals purified,*";
P_HTM[7065]="*na gottena dhanena vā.**not by clan or wealth.*";
P_HTM[7066]="*Tasmā hi paṇḍito poso,**That’s why an astute person,*";
P_HTM[7067]="*sampassaṃ atthamattano;**seeing what’s good for themselves,*";
P_HTM[7068]="*Yoniso vicine dhammaṃ,**would examine the teaching rationally,*";
P_HTM[7069]="*evaṃ tattha visujjhati.**and thus be purified in it.*";
P_HTM[7070]="*Sāriputtova paññāya,**Sāriputta has true wisdom,*";
P_HTM[7071]="*sīlena upasamena ca;**ethics, and also peace.*";
P_HTM[7072]="*Yopi pāraṅgato bhikkhu,**Any mendicant who has crossed over*";
P_HTM[7073]="*etāvaparamo siyā”ti.**can at best equal him.”*";
P_HTM[7074]="*Idamavoca anāthapiṇḍiko devaputto.**This is what the god Anāthapiṇḍika said,*";
P_HTM[7075]="*Samanuñño satthā ahosi.**and the teacher approved.*";
P_HTM[7076]="*Atha kho anāthapiṇḍiko devaputto:**Then the god Anāthapiṇḍika,*";
P_HTM[7077]="*“samanuñño me satthā”ti bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā tatthevantaradhāyi.**knowing that the teacher approved, bowed and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before vanishing right there.*";
P_HTM[7078]="*Atha kho bhagavā tassā rattiyā accayena bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then, when the night had passed, the Buddha told the mendicants all that had happened.*";
P_HTM[7079]="*“imaṃ, bhikkhave, rattiṃ aññataro devaputto abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇo kevalakappaṃ jetavanaṃ obhāsetvā yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi.* **";
P_HTM[7080]="*Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho so devaputto maṃ gāthāhi ajjhabhāsi:* **";
P_HTM[7081]="*‘Idañhi taṃ jetavanaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[7082]="*isisaṅghanisevitaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[7083]="*Āvutthaṃ dhammarājena,* **";
P_HTM[7084]="*pītisañjananaṃ mama.* **";
P_HTM[7085]="*Kammaṃ vijjā ca dhammo ca,* **";
P_HTM[7086]="*sīlaṃ jīvitamuttamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[7087]="*Etena maccā sujjhanti,* **";
P_HTM[7088]="*na gottena dhanena vā.* **";
P_HTM[7089]="*Tasmā hi paṇḍito poso,* **";
P_HTM[7090]="*sampassaṃ atthamattano;* **";
P_HTM[7091]="*Yoniso vicine dhammaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[7092]="*evaṃ tattha visujjhati.* **";
P_HTM[7093]="*Sāriputtova paññāya,* **";
P_HTM[7094]="*sīlena upasamena ca;* **";
P_HTM[7095]="*Yopi pāraṅgato bhikkhu,* **";
P_HTM[7096]="*etāvaparamo siyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7097]="*Idamavoca, bhikkhave, so devaputto.* **";
P_HTM[7098]="*‘Samanuñño me satthā’ti maṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā tatthevantaradhāyī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7099]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Venerable Ānanda said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[7100]="*“so hi nūna so, bhante, anāthapiṇḍiko devaputto bhavissati.**“Sir, that god must surely have been Anāthapiṇḍika.*";
P_HTM[7101]="*Anāthapiṇḍiko, bhante, gahapati āyasmante sāriputte abhippasanno ahosī”ti.**For the householder Anāthapiṇḍika was devoted to Venerable Sāriputta.”*";
P_HTM[7102]="*“Sādhu sādhu, ānanda.**“Good, good, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[7103]="*Yāvatakaṃ kho, ānanda, takkāya pattabbaṃ, anuppattaṃ taṃ tayā.**You’ve reached the logical conclusion, as far as logic goes.*";
P_HTM[7104]="*Anāthapiṇḍiko so, ānanda, devaputto”ti.**For that was indeed the god Anāthapiṇḍika.”*";
P_HTM[7105]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[7106]="*Attamano āyasmā ānando bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Ānanda was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[7107]="*Anāthapiṇḍikovādasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7108]="*144. Channovādasutta**Advice to Channa*";
P_HTM[7109]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[7110]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[7111]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahācundo āyasmā ca channo gijjhakūṭe pabbate viharanti.**Now at that time the venerables Sāriputta, Mahācunda, and Channa were staying on the Vulture’s Peak Mountain.*";
P_HTM[7112]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā channo ābādhiko hoti dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time Venerable Channa was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[7113]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenāyasmā mahācundo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahācundaṃ etadavoca:**Then in the late afternoon, Venerable Sāriputta came out of retreat, went to Venerable Mahācunda and said to him,*";
P_HTM[7114]="*“āyāmāvuso cunda, yenāyasmā channo tenupasaṅkamissāma gilānapucchakā”ti.**“Come, Reverend Cunda, let’s go to see Venerable Channa and ask about his illness.”*";
P_HTM[7115]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho āyasmā mahācundo āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosi.**“Yes, reverend,” replied Mahācunda.*";
P_HTM[7116]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahācundo yenāyasmā channo tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā channena saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**And then Sāriputta and Mahācunda went to see Channa and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[7117]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto āyasmantaṃ channaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side. Then Sāriputta said to Channa,*";
P_HTM[7118]="*“kacci te, āvuso channa, khamanīyaṃ, kacci yāpanīyaṃ? Kacci te dukkhā vedanā paṭikkamanti, no abhikkamanti; paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no abhikkamo”ti?**“I hope you’re keeping well, Reverend Channa; I hope you’re alright. I hope that your pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.”*";
P_HTM[7119]="*“Na me, āvuso sāriputta, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo.**“Reverend Sāriputta, I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is evident, not its fading.*";
P_HTM[7120]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso sāriputta, balavā puriso tiṇhena sikharena muddhani abhimattheyya; evameva kho me, āvuso sāriputta, adhimattā vātā muddhani ūhananti.**The winds piercing my head are so severe, it feels like a strong man drilling into my head with a sharp point.*";
P_HTM[7121]="*Na me, āvuso sāriputta, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati no paṭikkamo.* **";
P_HTM[7122]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso sāriputta, balavā puriso daḷhena varattakkhaṇḍena sīse sīsaveṭhaṃ dadeyya; evameva kho me, āvuso sāriputta, adhimattā sīse sīsavedanā.**The pain in my head is so severe, it feels like a strong man tightening a tough leather strap around my head.*";
P_HTM[7123]="*Na me, āvuso sāriputta, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo.* **";
P_HTM[7124]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso sāriputta, dakkho goghātako vā goghātakantevāsī vā tiṇhena govikantanena kucchiṃ parikanteyya; evameva kho me, āvuso sāriputta, adhimattā vātā kucchiṃ parikantanti.**The winds piercing my belly are so severe, it feels like a deft butcher or their apprentice is slicing my belly open with a meat cleaver.*";
P_HTM[7125]="*Na me, āvuso sāriputta, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo.* **";
P_HTM[7126]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso sāriputta, dve balavanto purisā dubbalataraṃ purisaṃ nānābāhāsu gahetvā aṅgārakāsuyā santāpeyyuṃ samparitāpeyyuṃ; evameva kho me, āvuso sāriputta, adhimatto kāyasmiṃ ḍāho.**The burning in my body is so severe, it feels like two strong men grabbing a weaker man by the arms to burn and scorch him on a pit of glowing coals.*";
P_HTM[7127]="*Na me, āvuso sāriputta, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo.**I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is evident, not its fading.*";
P_HTM[7128]="*Satthaṃ, āvuso sāriputta, āharissāmi, nāvakaṅkhāmi jīvitan”ti.**Reverend Sāriputta, I will slit my wrists. I don’t wish to live.”*";
P_HTM[7129]="*“Māyasmā channo satthaṃ āharesi.**“Please don’t slit your wrists!*";
P_HTM[7130]="*Yāpetāyasmā channo. Yāpentaṃ mayaṃ āyasmantaṃ channaṃ icchāma.**Venerable Channa, keep going! We want you to keep going.*";
P_HTM[7131]="*Sace āyasmato channassa natthi sappāyāni bhojanāni, ahaṃ āyasmato channassa sappāyāni bhojanāni pariyesissāmi.**If you don’t have any suitable food, we’ll find it for you.*";
P_HTM[7132]="*Sace āyasmato channassa natthi sappāyāni bhesajjāni, ahaṃ āyasmato channassa sappāyāni bhesajjāni pariyesissāmi.**If you don’t have suitable medicine, we’ll find it for you.*";
P_HTM[7133]="*Sace āyasmato channassa natthi patirūpā upaṭṭhākā, ahaṃ āyasmantaṃ channaṃ upaṭṭhahissāmi.**If you don’t have a capable carer, we’ll find one for you.*";
P_HTM[7134]="*Māyasmā channo satthaṃ āharesi.**Please don’t slit your wrists!*";
P_HTM[7135]="*Yāpetāyasmā channo. Yāpentaṃ mayaṃ āyasmantaṃ channaṃ icchāmā”ti.**Venerable Channa, keep going! We want you to keep going.”*";
P_HTM[7136]="*“Napi me, āvuso sāriputta, natthi sappāyāni bhojanāni;**“Reverend Sāriputta, it’s not that I don’t have suitable food,*";
P_HTM[7137]="*napi me natthi sappāyāni bhesajjāni;**or suitable medicine,*";
P_HTM[7138]="*napi me natthi patirūpā upaṭṭhākā;**or a capable carer.*";
P_HTM[7139]="*api cāvuso sāriputta, pariciṇṇo me satthā dīgharattaṃ manāpeneva no amanāpena.**Moreover, for a long time now I have served the Teacher with love, not without love.*";
P_HTM[7140]="*Etañhi, āvuso sāriputta, sāvakassa patirūpaṃ yaṃ satthāraṃ paricareyya manāpeneva no amanāpena.**For it is proper for a disciple to serve the Teacher with love, not without love.*";
P_HTM[7141]="*‘Anupavajjaṃ channo bhikkhu satthaṃ āharissatī’ti evametaṃ, āvuso sāriputta, dhārehī”ti.**You should remember this: ‘The mendicant Channa slit his wrists blamelessly.’”*";
P_HTM[7142]="*“Puccheyyāma mayaṃ āyasmantaṃ channaṃ kañcideva desaṃ, sace āyasmā channo okāsaṃ karoti pañhassa veyyākaraṇāyā”ti.**“I’d like to ask you about a certain point, if you’d take the time to answer.”*";
P_HTM[7143]="*“Pucchāvuso sāriputta, sutvā vedissāmī”ti.**“Ask, Reverend Sāriputta. When I’ve heard it I’ll know.”*";
P_HTM[7144]="*“Cakkhuṃ, āvuso channa, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassasi?**“Reverend Channa, do you regard the eye, eye consciousness, and things knowable by eye consciousness in this way: ‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?*";
P_HTM[7145]="*Sotaṃ, āvuso channa, sotaviññāṇaṃ … pe …**Do you regard the ear …*";
P_HTM[7146]="*ghānaṃ, āvuso channa, ghānaviññāṇaṃ …**nose …*";
P_HTM[7147]="*jivhaṃ, āvuso channa, jivhāviññāṇaṃ …**tongue …*";
P_HTM[7148]="*kāyaṃ, āvuso channa, kāyaviññāṇaṃ …**body …*";
P_HTM[7149]="*manaṃ, āvuso channa, manoviññāṇaṃ manoviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassasī”ti?**mind, mind consciousness, and things knowable by mind consciousness in this way: ‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[7150]="*“Cakkhuṃ, āvuso sāriputta, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassāmi.**“Reverend Sāriputta, I regard the eye, eye consciousness, and things knowable by eye consciousness in this way: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[7151]="*Sotaṃ, āvuso sāriputta … pe …**I regard the ear …*";
P_HTM[7152]="*ghānaṃ, āvuso sāriputta …**nose …*";
P_HTM[7153]="*jivhaṃ, āvuso sāriputta …**tongue …*";
P_HTM[7154]="*kāyaṃ, āvuso sāriputta …**body …*";
P_HTM[7155]="*manaṃ, āvuso sāriputta, manoviññāṇaṃ manoviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassāmī”ti.**mind, mind consciousness, and things knowable by mind consciousness in this way: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self’.”*";
P_HTM[7156]="*“Cakkhusmiṃ, āvuso channa, cakkhuviññāṇe cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbesu dhammesu kiṃ disvā kiṃ abhiññāya cakkhuṃ cakkhuviññāṇaṃ cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassasi?**“Reverend Channa, what have you seen, what have you directly known in these things that you regard them in this way: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self’?”*";
P_HTM[7157]="*Sotasmiṃ, āvuso channa, sotaviññāṇe …* **";
P_HTM[7158]="*ghānasmiṃ, āvuso channa, ghānaviññāṇe …* **";
P_HTM[7159]="*jivhāya, āvuso channa, jivhāviññāṇe …* **";
P_HTM[7160]="*kāyasmiṃ, āvuso channa, kāyaviññāṇe …* **";
P_HTM[7161]="*manasmiṃ, āvuso channa, manoviññāṇe manoviññāṇaviññātabbesu dhammesu kiṃ disvā kiṃ abhiññāya manaṃ manoviññāṇaṃ manoviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassasī”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7162]="*“Cakkhusmiṃ, āvuso sāriputta, cakkhuviññāṇe cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbesu dhammesu nirodhaṃ disvā nirodhaṃ abhiññāya cakkhuṃ cakkhuviññāṇaṃ cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassāmi.**“Reverend Sāriputta, after seeing cessation, after directly knowing cessation in these things I regard them in this way: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self’.”*";
P_HTM[7163]="*Sotasmiṃ, āvuso sāriputta, sotaviññāṇe …* **";
P_HTM[7164]="*ghānasmiṃ, āvuso sāriputta, ghānaviññāṇe …* **";
P_HTM[7165]="*jivhāya, āvuso sāriputta, jivhāviññāṇe …* **";
P_HTM[7166]="*kāyasmiṃ, āvuso sāriputta, kāyaviññāṇe …* **";
P_HTM[7167]="*manasmiṃ, āvuso sāriputta, manoviññāṇe manoviññāṇaviññātabbesu dhammesu nirodhaṃ disvā nirodhaṃ abhiññāya manaṃ manoviññāṇaṃ manoviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassāmī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7168]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā mahācundo āyasmantaṃ channaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Mahācunda said to Venerable Channa:*";
P_HTM[7169]="*“tasmātiha, āvuso channa, idampi tassa bhagavato sāsanaṃ, niccakappaṃ manasi kātabbaṃ:**“So, Reverend Channa, you should pay close attention to this instruction of the Buddha whenever you can:*";
P_HTM[7170]="*‘nissitassa calitaṃ, anissitassa calitaṃ natthi.**‘For the dependent there is agitation. For the independent there’s no agitation.*";
P_HTM[7171]="*Calite asati passaddhi,**When there’s no agitation there is tranquility.*";
P_HTM[7172]="*passaddhiyā sati nati na hoti.**When there is tranquility there’s no inclination.*";
P_HTM[7173]="*Natiyā asati āgatigati na hoti.**When there’s no inclination there’s no coming and going.*";
P_HTM[7174]="*Āgatigatiyā asati cutūpapāto na hoti.**When there’s no coming and going there’s no passing away and reappearing.*";
P_HTM[7175]="*Cutūpapāte asati nevidha na huraṃ na ubhayamantarena.**When there’s no passing away and reappearing there’s no this world or world beyond or between the two.*";
P_HTM[7176]="*Esevanto dukkhassā’”ti.**Just this is the end of suffering.’”*";
P_HTM[7177]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahācundo āyasmantaṃ channaṃ iminā ovādena ovaditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃsu.**And when the venerables Sāriputta and Mahācunda had given Venerable Channa this advice they got up from their seat and left.*";
P_HTM[7178]="*Atha kho āyasmā channo acirapakkante āyasmante ca sāriputte āyasmante ca mahācunde satthaṃ āharesi.**Not long after those venerables had left, Venerable Channa slit his wrists.*";
P_HTM[7179]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Sāriputta went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[7180]="*“āyasmatā, bhante, channena satthaṃ āharitaṃ.**“Sir, Venerable Channa has slit his wrists.*";
P_HTM[7181]="*Tassa kā gati, ko abhisamparāyo”ti?**Where has he been reborn in his next life?”*";
P_HTM[7182]="*“Nanu te, sāriputta, channena bhikkhunā sammukhāyeva anupavajjatā byākatā”ti?**“Sāriputta, didn’t the mendicant Channa declare his blamelessness to you personally?”*";
P_HTM[7183]="*“Atthi, bhante, pubbajiraṃ nāma vajjigāmo.**“Sir, there is a Vajjian village named Pubbavijjhana*";
P_HTM[7184]="*Tatthāyasmato channassa mittakulāni suhajjakulāni upavajjakulānī”ti.**where Channa had families with whom he was friendly, intimate, and familiar.”*";
P_HTM[7185]="*“Honti hete, sāriputta, channassa bhikkhuno mittakulāni suhajjakulāni upavajjakulāni.**“The mendicant Channa did indeed have such families.*";
P_HTM[7186]="*Nāhaṃ, sāriputta, ettāvatā ‘saupavajjo’ti vadāmi.**But this is not enough for me to call someone ‘blameworthy’.*";
P_HTM[7187]="*Yo kho, sāriputta, imañca kāyaṃ nikkhipati aññañca kāyaṃ upādiyati tamahaṃ ‘saupavajjo’ti vadāmi.**When someone lays down this body and takes up another body, I call them ‘blameworthy’.*";
P_HTM[7188]="*Taṃ channassa bhikkhuno natthi.**But the mendicant Channa did no such thing.*";
P_HTM[7189]="*‘Anupavajjo channo bhikkhu satthaṃ āharesī’ti evametaṃ, sāriputta, dhārehī”ti.**You should remember this: ‘The mendicant Channa slit his wrists blamelessly.’”*";
P_HTM[7190]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[7191]="*Attamano āyasmā sāriputto bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Sāriputta was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[7192]="*Channovādasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7193]="*145. Puṇṇovādasutta**Advice to Puṇṇa*";
P_HTM[7194]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[7195]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[7196]="*Atha kho āyasmā puṇṇo sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā puṇṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then in the late afternoon, Venerable Puṇṇa came out of retreat and went to the Buddha. He bowed, sat down to one side, and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[7197]="*“sādhu maṃ, bhante, bhagavā saṃkhittena ovādena ovadatu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[7198]="*“Tena hi, puṇṇa, suṇāhi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, Puṇṇa, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[7199]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā puṇṇo bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Puṇṇa.*";
P_HTM[7200]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[7201]="*“Santi kho, puṇṇa, cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**“Puṇṇa, there are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[7202]="*Tañce bhikkhu abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**If a mendicant approves, welcomes, and keeps clinging to them,*";
P_HTM[7203]="*Tassa taṃ abhinandato abhivadato ajjhosāya tiṭṭhato uppajjati nandī.**this gives rise to relishing.*";
P_HTM[7204]="*‘Nandīsamudayā dukkhasamudayo, puṇṇā’ti vadāmi.**Relishing is the origin of suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[7205]="*Santi kho, puṇṇa, sotaviññeyyā saddā …**There are sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[7206]="*ghānaviññeyyā gandhā …**smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[7207]="*jivhāviññeyyā rasā …**tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[7208]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā …**touches known by the body …*";
P_HTM[7209]="*manoviññeyyā dhammā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[7210]="*Tañce bhikkhu abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**If a mendicant approves, welcomes, and keeps clinging to them,*";
P_HTM[7211]="*Tassa taṃ abhinandato abhivadato ajjhosāya tiṭṭhato uppajjati nandī.**this gives rise to relishing.*";
P_HTM[7212]="*‘Nandīsamudayā dukkhasamudayo, puṇṇā’ti vadāmi.**Relishing is the origin of suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[7213]="*Santi ca kho, puṇṇa, cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**There are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[7214]="*Tañce bhikkhu nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**If a mendicant doesn’t approve, welcome, and keep clinging to them,*";
P_HTM[7215]="*Tassa taṃ anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato nandī nirujjhati.**relishing ceases.*";
P_HTM[7216]="*‘Nandīnirodhā dukkhanirodho, puṇṇā’ti vadāmi.**When relishing ceases, suffering ceases, I say.*";
P_HTM[7217]="*Santi ca kho, puṇṇa, sotaviññeyyā saddā …**There are sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[7218]="*ghānaviññeyyā gandhā …**smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[7219]="*jivhāviññeyyā rasā …**tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[7220]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā …**touches known by the body …*";
P_HTM[7221]="*manoviññeyyā dhammā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[7222]="*Tañce bhikkhu nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**If a mendicant doesn’t approve, welcome, and keep clinging to them,*";
P_HTM[7223]="*Tassa taṃ anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato nandī nirujjhati.**relishing ceases.*";
P_HTM[7224]="*‘Nandīnirodhā dukkhanirodho, puṇṇā’ti vadāmi.**When relishing ceases, suffering ceases, I say.*";
P_HTM[7225]="*Iminā ca tvaṃ, puṇṇa, mayā saṅkhittena ovādena ovadito katarasmiṃ janapade viharissasī”ti?**Puṇṇa, now that I’ve given you this brief advice, what country will you live in?”*";
P_HTM[7226]="*“Imināhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena ovādena ovadito, atthi sunāparanto nāma janapado, tatthāhaṃ viharissāmī”ti.**“Sir, there’s a country named Sunāparanta. I shall live there.”*";
P_HTM[7227]="*“Caṇḍā kho, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā;**“The people of Sunāparanta are wild and rough, Puṇṇa.*";
P_HTM[7228]="*pharusā kho, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā.* **";
P_HTM[7229]="*Sace taṃ, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā akkosissanti paribhāsissanti, tattha te, puṇṇa, kinti bhavissatī”ti?**If they abuse and insult you, what will you think of them?”*";
P_HTM[7230]="*“Sace maṃ, bhante, sunāparantakā manussā akkosissanti paribhāsissanti, tattha me evaṃ bhavissati:**“If they abuse and insult me, I will think:*";
P_HTM[7231]="*‘bhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, subhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, yaṃ me nayime pāṇinā pahāraṃ dentī’ti.**‘These people of Sunāparanta are gracious, truly gracious, since they don’t hit me with their fists.’*";
P_HTM[7232]="*Evamettha, bhagavā, bhavissati;**That’s what I’ll think, Blessed One.*";
P_HTM[7233]="*evamettha, sugata, bhavissatī”ti.**That’s what I’ll think, Holy One.”*";
P_HTM[7234]="*“Sace pana te, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā pāṇinā pahāraṃ dassanti, tattha pana te, puṇṇa, kinti bhavissatī”ti?**“But if they do hit you with their fists, what will you think of them then?”*";
P_HTM[7235]="*“Sace me, bhante, sunāparantakā manussā pāṇinā pahāraṃ dassanti, tattha me evaṃ bhavissati:**“If they hit me with their fists, I’ll think:*";
P_HTM[7236]="*‘bhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, subhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, yaṃ me nayime leḍḍunā pahāraṃ dentī’ti.**‘These people of Sunāparanta are gracious, truly gracious, since they don’t throw stones at me.’*";
P_HTM[7237]="*Evamettha, bhagavā, bhavissati;**That’s what I’ll think, Blessed One.*";
P_HTM[7238]="*evamettha, sugata, bhavissatī”ti.**That’s what I’ll think, Holy One.”*";
P_HTM[7239]="*“Sace pana te, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā leḍḍunā pahāraṃ dassanti, tattha pana te, puṇṇa, kinti bhavissatī”ti?**“But if they do throw stones at you, what will you think of them then?”*";
P_HTM[7240]="*“Sace me, bhante, sunāparantakā manussā leḍḍunā pahāraṃ dassanti, tattha me evaṃ bhavissati:**“If they throw stones at me, I’ll think:*";
P_HTM[7241]="*‘bhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, subhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, yaṃ me nayime daṇḍena pahāraṃ dentī’ti.**‘These people of Sunāparanta are gracious, truly gracious, since they don’t beat me with a club.’*";
P_HTM[7242]="*Evamettha, bhagavā, bhavissati;**That’s what I’ll think, Blessed One.*";
P_HTM[7243]="*evamettha, sugata, bhavissatī”ti.**That’s what I’ll think, Holy One.”*";
P_HTM[7244]="*“Sace pana te, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā daṇḍena pahāraṃ dassanti, tattha pana te, puṇṇa, kinti bhavissatī”ti?**“But if they do beat you with a club, what will you think of them then?”*";
P_HTM[7245]="*“Sace me, bhante, sunāparantakā manussā daṇḍena pahāraṃ dassanti, tattha me evaṃ bhavissati:**“If they beat me with a club, I’ll think:*";
P_HTM[7246]="*‘bhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, subhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, yaṃ me nayime satthena pahāraṃ dentī’ti.**‘These people of Sunāparanta are gracious, truly gracious, since they don’t stab me with a knife.’*";
P_HTM[7247]="*Evamettha, bhagavā, bhavissati;**That’s what I’ll think, Blessed One.*";
P_HTM[7248]="*evamettha, sugata, bhavissatī”ti.**That’s what I’ll think, Holy One.”*";
P_HTM[7249]="*“Sace pana te, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā satthena pahāraṃ dassanti, tattha pana te, puṇṇa, kinti bhavissatī”ti?**“But if they do stab you with a knife, what will you think of them then?”*";
P_HTM[7250]="*“Sace me, bhante, sunāparantakā manussā satthena pahāraṃ dassanti, tattha me evaṃ bhavissati:**“If they stab me with a knife, I’ll think:*";
P_HTM[7251]="*‘bhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, subhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, yaṃ maṃ nayime tiṇhena satthena jīvitā voropentī’ti.**‘These people of Sunāparanta are gracious, truly gracious, since they don’t take my life with a sharp knife.’*";
P_HTM[7252]="*Evamettha, bhagavā, bhavissati;**That’s what I’ll think, Blessed One.*";
P_HTM[7253]="*evamettha, sugata, bhavissatī”ti.**That’s what I’ll think, Holy One.”*";
P_HTM[7254]="*“Sace pana taṃ, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā tiṇhena satthena jīvitā voropessanti, tattha pana te, puṇṇa, kinti bhavissatī”ti?**“But if they do take your life with a sharp knife, what will you think of them then?”*";
P_HTM[7255]="*“Sace maṃ, bhante, sunāparantakā manussā tiṇhena satthena jīvitā voropessanti, tattha me evaṃ bhavissati:**“If they take my life with a sharp knife, I’ll think:*";
P_HTM[7256]="*‘santi kho bhagavato sāvakā kāye ca jīvite ca aṭṭīyamānā harāyamānā jigucchamānā satthahārakaṃ pariyesanti. Taṃ me idaṃ apariyiṭṭhaṃyeva satthahārakaṃ laddhan’ti.**‘There are disciples of the Buddha who looked for someone to assist with slitting their wrists because they were horrified, repelled, and disgusted with the body and with life. And I have found this without looking!’*";
P_HTM[7257]="*Evamettha, bhagavā, bhavissati;**That’s what I’ll think, Blessed One.*";
P_HTM[7258]="*evamettha, sugata, bhavissatī”ti.**That’s what I’ll think, Holy One.”*";
P_HTM[7259]="*“Sādhu sādhu, puṇṇa.**“Good, good Puṇṇa!*";
P_HTM[7260]="*Sakkhissasi kho tvaṃ, puṇṇa, iminā damūpasamena samannāgato sunāparantasmiṃ janapade viharituṃ.**Having such self-control and peacefulness, you will be quite capable of living in Sunāparanta.*";
P_HTM[7261]="*Yassadāni tvaṃ, puṇṇa, kālaṃ maññasī”ti.**Now, Puṇṇa, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[7262]="*Atha kho āyasmā puṇṇo bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā senāsanaṃ saṃsāmetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena sunāparanto janapado tena cārikaṃ pakkāmi.**And then Puṇṇa welcomed and agreed with the Buddha’s words. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right. Then he set his lodgings in order and, taking his bowl and robe, set out for Sunāparanta.*";
P_HTM[7263]="*Anupubbena cārikaṃ caramāno yena sunāparanto janapado tadavasari.**Traveling stage by stage, he arrived at Sunāparanta,*";
P_HTM[7264]="*Tatra sudaṃ āyasmā puṇṇo sunāparantasmiṃ janapade viharati.**and stayed there.*";
P_HTM[7265]="*Atha kho āyasmā puṇṇo tenevantaravassena pañcamattāni upāsakasatāni paṭivedesi, tenevantaravassena pañcamattāni upāsikasatāni paṭivedesi, tenevantaravassena tisso vijjā sacchākāsi.**Within that rainy season he confirmed around five hundred male and five hundred female lay followers. And within that same rainy season he realized the three knowledges.*";
P_HTM[7266]="*Atha kho āyasmā puṇṇo aparena samayena parinibbāyi.**Some time later he became fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[7267]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several mendicants went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[7268]="*“yo so, bhante, puṇṇo nāma kulaputto bhagavatā saṃkhittena ovādena ovadito so kālaṅkato.**“Sir, the gentleman named Puṇṇa, who was advised in brief by the Buddha, has passed away.*";
P_HTM[7269]="*Tassa kā gati, ko abhisamparāyo”ti?**Where has he been reborn in his next life?”*";
P_HTM[7270]="*“Paṇḍito, bhikkhave, puṇṇo kulaputto paccapādi dhammassānudhammaṃ, na ca maṃ dhammādhikaraṇaṃ viheṭhesi.**“Mendicants, Puṇṇa was astute. He practiced in line with the teachings, and did not trouble me about the teachings.*";
P_HTM[7271]="*Parinibbuto, bhikkhave, puṇṇo kulaputto”ti.**Puṇṇa has become completely extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[7272]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[7273]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[7274]="*Puṇṇovādasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7275]="*146. Nandakovādasutta**Advice from Nandaka*";
P_HTM[7276]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[7277]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[7278]="*Atha kho mahāpajāpatigotamī pañcamattehi bhikkhunisatehi saddhiṃ yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho mahāpajāpatigotamī bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Mahāpajāpatī Gotamī together with around five hundred nuns approached the Buddha, bowed, stood to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[7279]="*“ovadatu, bhante, bhagavā bhikkhuniyo;**“Sir, may the Buddha please advise*";
P_HTM[7280]="*anusāsatu, bhante, bhagavā bhikkhuniyo;**and instruct the nuns.*";
P_HTM[7281]="*karotu, bhante, bhagavā bhikkhunīnaṃ dhammiṃ kathan”ti.**Please give the nuns a Dhamma talk.”*";
P_HTM[7282]="*Tena kho pana samayena therā bhikkhū bhikkhuniyo ovadanti pariyāyena.**Now at that time the senior monks were taking turns to advise the nuns.*";
P_HTM[7283]="*Āyasmā nandako na icchati bhikkhuniyo ovadituṃ pariyāyena.**But Venerable Nandaka didn’t want to take his turn.*";
P_HTM[7284]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[7285]="*“kassa nu kho, ānanda, ajja pariyāyo bhikkhuniyo ovadituṃ pariyāyenā”ti?**“Ānanda, whose turn is it to advise the nuns today?”*";
P_HTM[7286]="*“Sabbeheva, bhante, kato pariyāyo bhikkhuniyo ovadituṃ pariyāyena.**“It’s Nandaka’s turn, sir,*";
P_HTM[7287]="*Ayaṃ, bhante, āyasmā nandako na icchati bhikkhuniyo ovadituṃ pariyāyenā”ti.**but he doesn’t want to do it.”*";
P_HTM[7288]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ nandakaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to Nandaka,*";
P_HTM[7289]="*“ovada, nandaka, bhikkhuniyo;**“Nandaka, please advise*";
P_HTM[7290]="*anusāsa, nandaka, bhikkhuniyo;**and instruct the nuns.*";
P_HTM[7291]="*karohi tvaṃ, brāhmaṇa, bhikkhunīnaṃ dhammiṃ kathan”ti.**Please, brahmin, give the nuns a Dhamma talk.”*";
P_HTM[7292]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā nandako bhagavato paṭissutvā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya sāvatthiṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Nandaka. Then, in the morning, he robed up and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Sāvatthī for alms.*";
P_HTM[7293]="*Sāvatthiyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto attadutiyo yena rājakārāmo tenupasaṅkami.**He wandered for alms in Sāvatthī. After the meal, on his return from alms-round, he went to the Royal Monastery with a companion.*";
P_HTM[7294]="*Addasaṃsu kho tā bhikkhuniyo āyasmantaṃ nandakaṃ dūratova āgacchantaṃ.**Those nuns saw him coming off in the distance,*";
P_HTM[7295]="*Disvāna āsanaṃ paññāpesuṃ, udakañca pādānaṃ upaṭṭhapesuṃ.**so they spread out a seat and placed water for washing the feet.*";
P_HTM[7296]="*Nisīdi kho āyasmā nandako paññatte āsane.**Nandaka sat down on the seat spread out,*";
P_HTM[7297]="*Nisajja pāde pakkhālesi.**and washed his feet.*";
P_HTM[7298]="*Tāpi kho bhikkhuniyo āyasmantaṃ nandakaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**Those nuns bowed, and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[7299]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho tā bhikkhuniyo āyasmā nandako etadavoca:**Nandaka said to them,*";
P_HTM[7300]="*“paṭipucchakathā kho, bhaginiyo, bhavissati.**“Sisters, this talk shall be in the form of questions.*";
P_HTM[7301]="*Tattha ājānantīhi: ‘ājānāmā’ tissa vacanīyaṃ, na ājānantīhi: ‘na ājānāmā’ tissa vacanīyaṃ.**When you understand, say so. When you don’t understand, say so.*";
P_HTM[7302]="*Yassā vā panassa kaṅkhā vā vimati vā ahameva tattha paṭipucchitabbo:**If anyone has a doubt or uncertainty, ask me about it:*";
P_HTM[7303]="*‘idaṃ, bhante, kathaṃ; imassa kvattho’”ti?**‘Why, sir, does it say this? What does that mean?’”*";
P_HTM[7304]="*“Ettakenapi mayaṃ, bhante, ayyassa nandakassa attamanā abhiraddhā yaṃ no ayyo nandako pavāretī”ti.**“We’re already delighted and satisfied with Venerable Nandaka, since he invites us like this.”*";
P_HTM[7305]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhaginiyo,**“What do you think, sisters?*";
P_HTM[7306]="*cakkhu niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is the eye permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[7307]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7308]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[7309]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7310]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[7311]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[7312]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7313]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhaginiyo,**“What do you think, sisters?*";
P_HTM[7314]="*sotaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is the ear …*";
P_HTM[7315]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante … pe …* **";
P_HTM[7316]="*ghānaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**nose …*";
P_HTM[7317]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante” …* **";
P_HTM[7318]="*“jivhā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**tongue …*";
P_HTM[7319]="*“Aniccā, bhante” …* **";
P_HTM[7320]="*“kāyo nicco vā anicco vā”ti?**body …*";
P_HTM[7321]="*“Anicco, bhante” …* **";
P_HTM[7322]="*“mano nicco vā anicco vā”ti?**mind permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[7323]="*“Anicco, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7324]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[7325]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7326]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[7327]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[7328]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[7329]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7330]="*“Pubbeva no etaṃ, bhante, yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhaṃ:**Because we have already truly seen this with right wisdom:*";
P_HTM[7331]="*‘itipime cha ajjhattikā āyatanā aniccā’”ti.**‘So these six interior sense fields are impermanent.’”*";
P_HTM[7332]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhaginiyo.**“Good, good, sisters!*";
P_HTM[7333]="*Evañhetaṃ, bhaginiyo, hoti ariyasāvakassa yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato.**That’s how it is for a noble disciple who truly sees with right wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7334]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhaginiyo,**What do you think, sisters?*";
P_HTM[7335]="*rūpā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**Are sights permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[7336]="*“Aniccā, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7337]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if they're impermanent, are they suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[7338]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7339]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if they're impermanent, suffering, and perishable, are they fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[7340]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[7341]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7342]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhaginiyo,**“What do you think, sisters?*";
P_HTM[7343]="*saddā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**Are sounds …*";
P_HTM[7344]="*“Aniccā, bhante … pe …* **";
P_HTM[7345]="*gandhā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**smells …*";
P_HTM[7346]="*“Aniccā, bhante” …* **";
P_HTM[7347]="*“rasā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**tastes …*";
P_HTM[7348]="*“Aniccā, bhante” …* **";
P_HTM[7349]="*“phoṭṭhabbā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**touches …*";
P_HTM[7350]="*“Aniccā, bhante” …* **";
P_HTM[7351]="*“dhammā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**thoughts permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[7352]="*“Aniccā, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7353]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if they're impermanent, are they suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[7354]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7355]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if they're impermanent, suffering, and perishable, are they fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[7356]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[7357]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[7358]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7359]="*“Pubbeva no etaṃ, bhante, yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhaṃ:**Because we have already truly seen this with right wisdom:*";
P_HTM[7360]="*‘itipime cha bāhirā āyatanā aniccā’”ti.**‘So these six exterior sense fields are impermanent.’”*";
P_HTM[7361]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhaginiyo.**“Good, good, sisters!*";
P_HTM[7362]="*Evañhetaṃ, bhaginiyo, hoti ariyasāvakassa yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato.**That’s how it is for a noble disciple who truly sees with right wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7363]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhaginiyo,**What do you think, sisters?*";
P_HTM[7364]="*cakkhuviññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is eye consciousness …*";
P_HTM[7365]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7366]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7367]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7368]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7369]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7370]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7371]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhaginiyo, sotaviññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**ear consciousness …*";
P_HTM[7372]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante … pe …* **";
P_HTM[7373]="*ghānaviññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**nose consciousness …*";
P_HTM[7374]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante” …* **";
P_HTM[7375]="*“jivhāviññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**tongue consciousness …*";
P_HTM[7376]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante” …* **";
P_HTM[7377]="*“kāyaviññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**body consciousness …*";
P_HTM[7378]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante” …* **";
P_HTM[7379]="*“manoviññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**mind consciousness permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[7380]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7381]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vāti”?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[7382]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7383]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[7384]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[7385]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[7386]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7387]="*“Pubbeva no etaṃ, bhante, yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhaṃ:**Because we have already truly seen this with right wisdom:*";
P_HTM[7388]="*‘itipime cha viññāṇakāyā aniccā’”ti.**‘So these six classes of consciousness are impermanent.’”*";
P_HTM[7389]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhaginiyo.**“Good, good, sisters!*";
P_HTM[7390]="*Evañhetaṃ, bhaginiyo, hoti ariyasāvakassa yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato.**That’s how it is for a noble disciple who truly sees with right wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7391]="*Seyyathāpi, bhaginiyo, telappadīpassa jhāyato telampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, vaṭṭipi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā, accipi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā, ābhāpi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā.**Suppose there was an oil lamp burning. The oil, wick, flame, and light were all impermanent and perishable.*";
P_HTM[7392]="*Yo nu kho, bhaginiyo, evaṃ vadeyya:**Now, suppose someone was to say:*";
P_HTM[7393]="*‘amussa telappadīpassa jhāyato telampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, vaṭṭipi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā, accipi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā;**‘While this oil lamp is burning, the oil, the wick, and the flame are all impermanent and perishable.*";
P_HTM[7394]="*yā ca khvāssa ābhā sā niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā’ti;**But the light is permanent, lasting, eternal, and imperishable.’*";
P_HTM[7395]="*sammā nu kho so, bhaginiyo, vadamāno vadeyyā”ti?**Would they be speaking rightly?”*";
P_HTM[7396]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[7397]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7398]="*“Amussa hi, bhante, telappadīpassa jhāyato telampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, vaṭṭipi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā, accipi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā;**Because that oil lamp’s oil, wick, and flame are all impermanent and perishable,*";
P_HTM[7399]="*pagevassa ābhā aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā”ti.**let alone the light.”*";
P_HTM[7400]="*“Evameva kho, bhaginiyo, yo nu kho evaṃ vadeyya:**“In the same way, suppose someone was to say:*";
P_HTM[7401]="*‘cha khome ajjhattikā āyatanā aniccā;**‘These six interior sense fields are impermanent.*";
P_HTM[7402]="*yañca kho cha ajjhattike āyatane paṭicca paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā taṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhamman’ti;**But the feeling—whether pleasant, painful, or neutral—that I experience due to these six interior sense fields is permanent, lasting, eternal, and imperishable.’*";
P_HTM[7403]="*sammā nu kho so, bhaginiyo, vadamāno vadeyyā”ti?**Would they be speaking rightly?”*";
P_HTM[7404]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[7405]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7406]="*“Tajjaṃ tajjaṃ, bhante, paccayaṃ paṭicca tajjā tajjā vedanā uppajjanti.**Because each kind of feeling arises dependent on the corresponding condition.*";
P_HTM[7407]="*Tajjassa tajjassa paccayassa nirodhā tajjā tajjā vedanā nirujjhantī”ti.**When the corresponding condition ceases, the appropriate feeling ceases.”*";
P_HTM[7408]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhaginiyo.**“Good, good, sisters!*";
P_HTM[7409]="*Evañhetaṃ, bhaginiyo, hoti ariyasāvakassa yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato.**That’s how it is for a noble disciple who truly sees with right wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7410]="*Seyyathāpi, bhaginiyo, mahato rukkhassa tiṭṭhato sāravato mūlampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, khandhopi anicco vipariṇāmadhammo, sākhāpalāsampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, chāyāpi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā.**Suppose there was a large tree standing with heartwood. The roots, trunk, branches and leaves, and shadow were all impermanent and perishable.*";
P_HTM[7411]="*Yo nu kho, bhaginiyo, evaṃ vadeyya:**Now, suppose someone was to say:*";
P_HTM[7412]="*‘amussa mahato rukkhassa tiṭṭhato sāravato mūlampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, khandhopi anicco vipariṇāmadhammo, sākhāpalāsampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, yā ca khvāssa chāyā sā niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā’ti;**‘There’s a large tree standing with heartwood. The roots, trunk, and branches and leaves are all impermanent and perishable. But the shadow is permanent, lasting, eternal, and imperishable.’*";
P_HTM[7413]="*sammā nu kho so, bhaginiyo, vadamāno vadeyyā”ti?**Would they be speaking rightly?”*";
P_HTM[7414]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[7415]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7416]="*“Amussa hi, bhante, mahato rukkhassa tiṭṭhato sāravato mūlampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, khandhopi anicco vipariṇāmadhammo, sākhāpalāsampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ;**Because that large tree’s roots, trunk, and branches and leaves are all impermanent and perishable,*";
P_HTM[7417]="*pagevassa chāyā aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā”ti.**let alone the shadow.”*";
P_HTM[7418]="*“Evameva kho, bhaginiyo, yo nu kho evaṃ vadeyya:**“In the same way, suppose someone was to say:*";
P_HTM[7419]="*‘cha khome bāhirā āyatanā aniccā.**‘These six exterior sense fields are impermanent.*";
P_HTM[7420]="*Yañca kho cha bāhire āyatane paṭicca paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā taṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhamman’ti;**But the feeling—whether pleasant, painful, or neutral—that I experience due to these six exterior sense fields is permanent, lasting, eternal, and imperishable.’*";
P_HTM[7421]="*sammā nu kho so, bhaginiyo, vadamāno vadeyyā”ti?**Would they be speaking rightly?”*";
P_HTM[7422]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[7423]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7424]="*“Tajjaṃ tajjaṃ, bhante, paccayaṃ paṭicca tajjā tajjā vedanā uppajjanti.**Because each kind of feeling arises dependent on the corresponding condition.*";
P_HTM[7425]="*Tajjassa tajjassa paccayassa nirodhā tajjā tajjā vedanā nirujjhantī”ti.**When the corresponding condition ceases, the appropriate feeling ceases.”*";
P_HTM[7426]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhaginiyo.**“Good, good, sisters!*";
P_HTM[7427]="*Evañhetaṃ, bhaginiyo, hoti ariyasāvakassa yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato.**That’s how it is for a noble disciple who truly sees with right wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7428]="*Seyyathāpi, bhaginiyo, dakkho goghātako vā goghātakantevāsī vā gāviṃ vadhitvā tiṇhena govikantanena gāviṃ saṅkanteyya anupahacca antaraṃ maṃsakāyaṃ anupahacca bāhiraṃ cammakāyaṃ.**Suppose a deft butcher or their apprentice was to kill a cow and carve it with a sharp meat cleaver. Without damaging the flesh inside or the hide outside,*";
P_HTM[7429]="*Yaṃ yadeva tattha antarā vilimaṃsaṃ antarā nhāru antarā bandhanaṃ taṃ tadeva tiṇhena govikantanena sañchindeyya saṅkanteyya sampakanteyya samparikanteyya.**they’d cut, carve, sever, and slice through the connecting tendons, sinews, and ligaments,*";
P_HTM[7430]="*Sañchinditvā saṅkantitvā sampakantitvā samparikantitvā vidhunitvā bāhiraṃ cammakāyaṃ teneva cammena taṃ gāviṃ paṭicchādetvā evaṃ vadeyya:**and then peel off the outer hide. Then they’d wrap that cow up in that very same hide and say:*";
P_HTM[7431]="*‘tathevāyaṃ gāvī saṃyuttā imināva cammenā’ti;**‘This cow is joined to its hide just like before.’*";
P_HTM[7432]="*sammā nu kho so, bhaginiyo, vadamāno vadeyyā”ti?**Would they be speaking rightly?”*";
P_HTM[7433]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[7434]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7435]="*“Amu hi, bhante, dakkho goghātako vā goghātakantevāsī vā gāviṃ vadhitvā tiṇhena govikantanena gāviṃ saṅkanteyya anupahacca antaraṃ maṃsakāyaṃ anupahacca bāhiraṃ cammakāyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7436]="*Yaṃ yadeva tattha antarā vilimaṃsaṃ antarā nhāru antarā bandhanaṃ taṃ tadeva tiṇhena govikantanena sañchindeyya saṅkanteyya sampakanteyya samparikanteyya.* **";
P_HTM[7437]="*Sañchinditvā saṅkantitvā sampakantitvā samparikantitvā vidhunitvā bāhiraṃ cammakāyaṃ teneva cammena taṃ gāviṃ paṭicchādetvā kiñcāpi so evaṃ vadeyya:**Because even if they wrap that cow up in that very same hide and say:*";
P_HTM[7438]="*‘tathevāyaṃ gāvī saṃyuttā imināva cammenā’ti;**‘This cow is joined to its hide just like before,’*";
P_HTM[7439]="*atha kho sā gāvī visaṃyuttā teneva cammenā”ti.**still that cow is not joined to that hide.”*";
P_HTM[7440]="*“Upamā kho me ayaṃ, bhaginiyo, katā atthassa viññāpanāya.**“I’ve made up this simile to make a point.*";
P_HTM[7441]="*Ayamevettha attho;**And this is the point.*";
P_HTM[7442]="*‘antarā maṃsakāyo’ti kho, bhaginiyo, channetaṃ ajjhattikānaṃ āyatanānaṃ adhivacanaṃ;**‘The inner flesh’ is a term for the six interior sense fields.*";
P_HTM[7443]="*‘bāhiro cammakāyo’ti kho, bhaginiyo, channetaṃ bāhirānaṃ āyatanānaṃ adhivacanaṃ;**‘The outer hide’ is a term for the six exterior sense fields.*";
P_HTM[7444]="*‘antarā vilimaṃsaṃ, antarā nhāru, antarā bandhanan’ti kho, bhaginiyo, nandīrāgassetaṃ adhivacanaṃ;**‘The connecting tendons, sinews, and ligaments’ is a term for desire with relishing.*";
P_HTM[7445]="*‘tiṇhaṃ govikantanan’ti kho, bhaginiyo, ariyāyetaṃ paññāya adhivacanaṃ;**‘A sharp meat cleaver’ is a term for noble wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7446]="*yāyaṃ ariyā paññā antarā kilesaṃ antarā saṃyojanaṃ antarā bandhanaṃ sañchindati saṅkantati sampakantati samparikantati.**And it is that noble wisdom which cuts, carves, severs, and slices the connecting corruption, fetter, and bond.*";
P_HTM[7447]="*Satta kho panime, bhaginiyo, bojjhaṅgā, yesaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**Sisters, by developing and cultivating these seven awakening factors, a mendicant realizes the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[7448]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[7449]="*Idha, bhaginiyo, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pe … vīriyasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pītisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … passaddhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … samādhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[7450]="*Ime kho, bhaginiyo, satta bojjhaṅgā, yesaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharatī”ti.**It is by developing and cultivating these seven awakening factors that a mendicant realizes the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.”*";
P_HTM[7451]="*Atha kho āyasmā nandako tā bhikkhuniyo iminā ovādena ovaditvā uyyojesi:**Then after giving this advice to the nuns, Nandaka dismissed them, saying,*";
P_HTM[7452]="*“gacchatha, bhaginiyo; kālo”ti.**“Go, sisters, it is time.”*";
P_HTM[7453]="*Atha kho tā bhikkhuniyo āyasmato nandakassa bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā āyasmantaṃ nandakaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho tā bhikkhuniyo bhagavā etadavoca:**And then those nuns approved and agreed with what Nandaka had said. They got up from their seat, bowed, and respectfully circled him, keeping him on their right. Then they went up to the Buddha, bowed, and stood to one side. The Buddha said to them,*";
P_HTM[7454]="*“gacchatha, bhikkhuniyo; kālo”ti.**“Go, nuns, it is time.”*";
P_HTM[7455]="*Atha kho tā bhikkhuniyo bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkamiṃsu.**Then those nuns bowed to the Buddha respectfully circled him, keeping him on their right, before departing.*";
P_HTM[7456]="*Atha kho bhagavā acirapakkantīsu tāsu bhikkhunīsu bhikkhū āmantesi:**Soon after those nuns had left, the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[7457]="*“seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, tadahuposathe cātuddase na hoti bahuno janassa kaṅkhā vā vimati vā:**“Suppose, mendicants, it was the sabbath of the fourteenth day. You wouldn’t get lots of people*";
P_HTM[7458]="*‘ūno nu kho cando, puṇṇo nu kho cando’ti, atha kho ūno cando tveva hoti.**wondering whether the moon is full or not, since it is obviously not full.*";
P_HTM[7459]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, tā bhikkhuniyo nandakassa dhammadesanāya attamanā honti no ca kho paripuṇṇasaṅkappā”ti.**In the same way, those nuns were uplifted by Nandaka’s Dhamma teaching, but they still haven’t found what they’re looking for.”*";
P_HTM[7460]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ nandakaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to Nandaka,*";
P_HTM[7461]="*“tena hi tvaṃ, nandaka, svepi tā bhikkhuniyo tenevovādena ovadeyyāsī”ti.**“Well then, Nandaka, tomorrow you should give those nuns the same advice again.”*";
P_HTM[7462]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā nandako bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Nandaka replied.*";
P_HTM[7463]="*Atha kho āyasmā nandako tassā rattiyā accayena pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya sāvatthiṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**And the next day he went to those nuns, and all unfolded just like the previous day.*";
P_HTM[7464]="*Sāvatthiyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto attadutiyo yena rājakārāmo tenupasaṅkami.* **";
P_HTM[7465]="*Addasaṃsu kho tā bhikkhuniyo āyasmantaṃ nandakaṃ dūratova āgacchantaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7466]="*Disvāna āsanaṃ paññāpesuṃ, udakañca pādānaṃ upaṭṭhapesuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7467]="*Nisīdi kho āyasmā nandako paññatte āsane.* **";
P_HTM[7468]="*Nisajja pāde pakkhālesi.* **";
P_HTM[7469]="*Tāpi kho bhikkhuniyo āyasmantaṃ nandakaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[7470]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho tā bhikkhuniyo āyasmā nandako etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[7471]="*“paṭipucchakathā kho, bhaginiyo, bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[7472]="*Tattha ājānantīhi ‘ājānāmā’ tissa vacanīyaṃ, na ājānantīhi ‘na ājānāmā’ tissa vacanīyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7473]="*Yassā vā panassa kaṅkhā vā vimati vā, ahameva tattha paṭipucchitabbo:* **";
P_HTM[7474]="*‘idaṃ, bhante, kathaṃ; imassa kvattho’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7475]="*“Ettakenapi mayaṃ, bhante, ayyassa nandakassa attamanā abhiraddhā yaṃ no ayyo nandako pavāretī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7476]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhaginiyo, cakkhu niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7477]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7478]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7479]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7480]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7481]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7482]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7483]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhaginiyo, sotaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7484]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante … pe …* **";
P_HTM[7485]="*ghānaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7486]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante …* **";
P_HTM[7487]="*jivhā …* **";
P_HTM[7488]="*kāyo …* **";
P_HTM[7489]="*mano nicco vā anicco vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7490]="*“Anicco, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7491]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7492]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7493]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7494]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7495]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7496]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?* **";
P_HTM[7497]="*“Pubbeva no etaṃ, bhante, yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7498]="*‘itipime cha ajjhattikā āyatanā aniccā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7499]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhaginiyo.* **";
P_HTM[7500]="*Evañhetaṃ, bhaginiyo, hoti ariyasāvakassa yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato.* **";
P_HTM[7501]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhaginiyo, rūpā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7502]="*“Aniccā, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7503]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7504]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7505]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7506]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7507]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7508]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhaginiyo, saddā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7509]="*“Aniccā, bhante … pe …* **";
P_HTM[7510]="*gandhā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7511]="*“Aniccā, bhante …* **";
P_HTM[7512]="*rasā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7513]="*“Aniccā, bhante …* **";
P_HTM[7514]="*phoṭṭhabbā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7515]="*“Aniccā, bhante …* **";
P_HTM[7516]="*dhammā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7517]="*“Aniccā, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7518]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7519]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7520]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7521]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7522]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7523]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?* **";
P_HTM[7524]="*“Pubbeva no etaṃ, bhante, yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7525]="*‘itipime cha bāhirā āyatanā aniccā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7526]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhaginiyo.* **";
P_HTM[7527]="*Evañhetaṃ, bhaginiyo, hoti ariyasāvakassa yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato.* **";
P_HTM[7528]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhaginiyo, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7529]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante … pe …* **";
P_HTM[7530]="*sotaviññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7531]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante …* **";
P_HTM[7532]="*ghānaviññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7533]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante …* **";
P_HTM[7534]="*jivhāviññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7535]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante …* **";
P_HTM[7536]="*kāyaviññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7537]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante …* **";
P_HTM[7538]="*manoviññāṇaṃ niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7539]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7540]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7541]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7542]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7543]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7544]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7545]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?* **";
P_HTM[7546]="*“Pubbeva no etaṃ, bhante, yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7547]="*‘itipime cha viññāṇakāyā aniccā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7548]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhaginiyo.* **";
P_HTM[7549]="*Evañhetaṃ, bhaginiyo, hoti ariyasāvakassa yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato.* **";
P_HTM[7550]="*Seyyathāpi, bhaginiyo, telappadīpassa jhāyato telampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, vaṭṭipi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā, accipi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā, ābhāpi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā.* **";
P_HTM[7551]="*Yo nu kho, bhaginiyo, evaṃ vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[7552]="*‘amussa telappadīpassa jhāyato telampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, vaṭṭipi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā, accipi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā;* **";
P_HTM[7553]="*yā ca khvāssa ābhā sā niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā’ti;* **";
P_HTM[7554]="*sammā nu kho so, bhaginiyo, vadamāno vadeyyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7555]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7556]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?* **";
P_HTM[7557]="*“Amussa hi, bhante, telappadīpassa jhāyato telampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, vaṭṭipi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā, accipi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā;* **";
P_HTM[7558]="*pagevassa ābhā aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7559]="*“Evameva kho, bhaginiyo, yo nu kho evaṃ vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[7560]="*‘cha khome ajjhattikā āyatanā aniccā.* **";
P_HTM[7561]="*Yañca kho cha ajjhattike āyatane paṭicca paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā taṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhamman’ti;* **";
P_HTM[7562]="*sammā nu kho so, bhaginiyo, vadamāno vadeyyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7563]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7564]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?* **";
P_HTM[7565]="*“Tajjaṃ tajjaṃ, bhante, paccayaṃ paṭicca tajjā tajjā vedanā uppajjanti.* **";
P_HTM[7566]="*Tajjassa tajjassa paccayassa nirodhā tajjā tajjā vedanā nirujjhantī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7567]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhaginiyo.* **";
P_HTM[7568]="*Evañhetaṃ, bhaginiyo, hoti ariyasāvakassa yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato.* **";
P_HTM[7569]="*Seyyathāpi, bhaginiyo, mahato rukkhassa tiṭṭhato sāravato mūlampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, khandhopi anicco vipariṇāmadhammo, sākhāpalāsampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, chāyāpi aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā.* **";
P_HTM[7570]="*Yo nu kho, bhaginiyo, evaṃ vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[7571]="*‘amussa mahato rukkhassa tiṭṭhato sāravato mūlampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, khandhopi anicco vipariṇāmadhammo, sākhāpalāsampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[7572]="*yā ca khvāssa chāyā sā niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā’ti;* **";
P_HTM[7573]="*sammā nu kho so bhaginiyo, vadamāno vadeyyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7574]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7575]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?* **";
P_HTM[7576]="*“Amussa hi, bhante, mahato rukkhassa tiṭṭhato sāravato mūlampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, khandhopi anicco vipariṇāmadhammo, sākhāpalāsampi aniccaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[7577]="*pagevassa chāyā aniccā vipariṇāmadhammā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7578]="*“Evameva kho, bhaginiyo, yo nu kho evaṃ vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[7579]="*‘cha khome bāhirā āyatanā aniccā.* **";
P_HTM[7580]="*Yañca kho bāhire āyatane paṭicca paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā taṃ niccaṃ dhuvaṃ sassataṃ avipariṇāmadhamman’ti;* **";
P_HTM[7581]="*sammā nu kho so, bhaginiyo, vadamāno vadeyyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7582]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7583]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?* **";
P_HTM[7584]="*“Tajjaṃ tajjaṃ, bhante, paccayaṃ paṭicca tajjā tajjā vedanā uppajjanti.* **";
P_HTM[7585]="*Tajjassa tajjassa paccayassa nirodhā tajjā tajjā vedanā nirujjhantī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7586]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhaginiyo.* **";
P_HTM[7587]="*Evañhetaṃ, bhaginiyo, hoti ariyasāvakassa yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya passato.* **";
P_HTM[7588]="*Seyyathāpi, bhaginiyo, dakkho goghātako vā goghātakantevāsī vā gāviṃ vadhitvā tiṇhena govikantanena gāviṃ saṅkanteyya anupahacca antaraṃ maṃsakāyaṃ anupahacca bāhiraṃ cammakāyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7589]="*Yaṃ yadeva tattha antarā vilimaṃsaṃ antarā nhāru antarā bandhanaṃ taṃ tadeva tiṇhena govikantanena sañchindeyya saṅkanteyya sampakanteyya samparikanteyya.* **";
P_HTM[7590]="*Sañchinditvā saṅkantitvā sampakantitvā samparikantitvā vidhunitvā bāhiraṃ cammakāyaṃ teneva cammena taṃ gāviṃ paṭicchādetvā evaṃ vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[7591]="*‘tathevāyaṃ gāvī saṃyuttā imināva cammenā’ti;* **";
P_HTM[7592]="*sammā nu kho so, bhaginiyo, vadamāno vadeyyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7593]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[7594]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?* **";
P_HTM[7595]="*“Amu hi, bhante, dakkho goghātako vā goghātakantevāsī vā gāviṃ vadhitvā tiṇhena govikantanena gāviṃ saṅkanteyya anupahacca antaraṃ maṃsakāyaṃ anupahacca bāhiraṃ cammakāyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7596]="*Yaṃ yadeva tattha antarā vilimaṃsaṃ antarā nhāru antarā bandhanaṃ taṃ tadeva tiṇhena govikantanena sañchindeyya saṅkanteyya sampakanteyya samparikanteyya.* **";
P_HTM[7597]="*Sañchinditvā saṅkantitvā sampakantitvā samparikantitvā vidhunitvā bāhiraṃ cammakāyaṃ teneva cammena taṃ gāviṃ paṭicchādetvā kiñcāpi so evaṃ vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[7598]="*‘tathevāyaṃ gāvī saṃyuttā imināva cammenā’ti;* **";
P_HTM[7599]="*atha kho sā gāvī visaṃyuttā teneva cammenā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7600]="*“Upamā kho me ayaṃ, bhaginiyo, katā atthassa viññāpanāya ayamevettha attho.* **";
P_HTM[7601]="*‘Antarā maṃsakāyo’ti kho, bhaginiyo, channetaṃ ajjhattikānaṃ āyatanānaṃ adhivacanaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[7602]="*‘bāhiro cammakāyo’ti kho, bhaginiyo, channetaṃ bāhirānaṃ āyatanānaṃ adhivacanaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[7603]="*‘antarā vilimaṃsaṃ antarā nhāru antarā bandhanan’ti kho, bhaginiyo, nandīrāgassetaṃ adhivacanaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[7604]="*‘tiṇhaṃ govikantanan’ti kho, bhaginiyo, ariyāyetaṃ paññāya adhivacanaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[7605]="*yāyaṃ ariyā paññā antarā kilesaṃ antarā saṃyojanaṃ antarā bandhanaṃ sañchindati saṅkantati sampakantati samparikantati.* **";
P_HTM[7606]="*Satta kho panime, bhaginiyo, bojjhaṅgā, yesaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.* **";
P_HTM[7607]="*Katame satta?* **";
P_HTM[7608]="*Idha, bhaginiyo, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ. Dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pe … vīriyasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pītisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … passaddhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … samādhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7609]="*Ime kho, bhaginiyo, satta bojjhaṅgā yesaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7610]="*Atha kho āyasmā nandako tā bhikkhuniyo iminā ovādena ovaditvā uyyojesi:* **";
P_HTM[7611]="*“gacchatha, bhaginiyo; kālo”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7612]="*Atha kho tā bhikkhuniyo āyasmato nandakassa bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā āyasmantaṃ nandakaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho tā bhikkhuniyo bhagavā etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[7613]="*“gacchatha, bhikkhuniyo; kālo”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7614]="*Atha kho tā bhikkhuniyo bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkamiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[7615]="*Atha kho bhagavā acirapakkantīsu tāsu bhikkhunīsu bhikkhū āmantesi:**Soon after those nuns had left, the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[7616]="*“seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, tadahuposathe pannarase na hoti bahuno janassa kaṅkhā vā vimati vā:**“Suppose, mendicants, it was the sabbath of the fifteenth day. You wouldn’t get lots of people*";
P_HTM[7617]="*‘ūno nu kho cando, puṇṇo nu kho cando’ti, atha kho puṇṇo cando tveva hoti;**wondering whether the moon is full or not, since it is obviously full.*";
P_HTM[7618]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, tā bhikkhuniyo nandakassa dhammadesanāya attamanā ceva paripuṇṇasaṅkappā ca.**In the same way, those nuns were uplifted by Nandaka’s Dhamma teaching, and they found what they’re looking for.*";
P_HTM[7619]="*Tāsaṃ, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ bhikkhunisatānaṃ yā pacchimikā bhikkhunī sā sotāpannā avinipātadhammā niyatā sambodhiparāyanā”ti.**Even the last of these five hundred nuns is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.”*";
P_HTM[7620]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[7621]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[7622]="*Nandakovādasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7623]="*147. Cūḷarāhulovādasutta**The Shorter Advice to Rāhula*";
P_HTM[7624]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[7625]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[7626]="*Atha kho bhagavato rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Then as he was in private retreat this thought came to his mind,*";
P_HTM[7627]="*“paripakkā kho rāhulassa vimuttiparipācanīyā dhammā.**“The qualities that ripen in freedom have ripened in Rāhula.*";
P_HTM[7628]="*Yannūnāhaṃ rāhulaṃ uttariṃ āsavānaṃ khaye vineyyan”ti.**Why don’t I lead him further to the ending of defilements?”*";
P_HTM[7629]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya sāvatthiṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Sāvatthī for alms.*";
P_HTM[7630]="*Sāvatthiyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto āyasmantaṃ rāhulaṃ āmantesi:**Then, after the meal, on his return from alms-round, he addressed Venerable Rāhula,*";
P_HTM[7631]="*“gaṇhāhi, rāhula, nisīdanaṃ;**“Rāhula, get your sitting cloth.*";
P_HTM[7632]="*yena andhavanaṃ tenupasaṅkamissāma divāvihārāyā”ti.**Let’s go to the Dark Forest for the day’s meditation.”*";
P_HTM[7633]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā rāhulo bhagavato paṭissutvā nisīdanaṃ ādāya bhagavantaṃ piṭṭhito piṭṭhito anubandhi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Rāhula. Taking his sitting cloth he followed behind the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[7634]="*Tena kho pana samayena anekāni devatāsahassāni bhagavantaṃ anubandhāni honti:**Now at that time many thousands of deities followed the Buddha, thinking,*";
P_HTM[7635]="*“ajja bhagavā āyasmantaṃ rāhulaṃ uttariṃ āsavānaṃ khaye vinessatī”ti.**“Today the Buddha will lead Rāhula further to the ending of defilements!”*";
P_HTM[7636]="*Atha kho bhagavā andhavanaṃ ajjhogāhetvā aññatarasmiṃ rukkhamūle paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha plunged deep into the Dark Forest and sat at the root of a tree on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[7637]="*Āyasmāpi kho rāhulo bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**Rāhula bowed to the Buddha and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[7638]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ rāhulaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[7639]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, rāhula,**“What do you think, Rāhula?*";
P_HTM[7640]="*cakkhu niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is the eye permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[7641]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7642]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[7643]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7644]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[7645]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[7646]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7647]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, rāhula,**“What do you think, Rāhula?*";
P_HTM[7648]="*rūpā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**Are sights permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[7649]="*“Aniccā, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7650]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if they're impermanent, are they suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[7651]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7652]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if they're impermanent, suffering, and perishable, are they fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[7653]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[7654]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
